<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIRECTOR MAY SHAKE UP MEETING OF MATTEL'S BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the embattled board of Mattel Inc. meets Thursday, its
agenda is likely to include the company's depressed stock price,
the so-far unsuccessful search for a new chief executive and any
further problems that might be lurking at the Learning Co.,
Mattel's troubled computer software subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting in El Segundo, Calif., will also have a couple
of new elements. One is Ralph V. Whitworth, managing member of
Relational Investors, a private investment fund that owns 4.2
million Mattel shares. Whitworth, known as a straight talker who is
often brought in to clean up management messes, may shake up the
sleepy Mattel board. He will be making his first appearance at a
board meeting since being appointed a director on March 2.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is the reappearance of an old court case. A civil
lawsuit filed in 1995 by Michelle Greenwald, a former Mattel
executive who contended she was wrongfully terminated, has been
given new life by the California appeals court. Mattel, which has
said the suit is baseless, will now have to battle in court.
</P>
<P>
   In her case, Greenwald says Mattel fired her because she blew
the whistle on what she considered accounting irregularities at the
company. As a result, what emerges in the court battle could prove
interesting to unhappy shareholders who have recently brought their
own suit against Mattel citing mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Feb. 3 resignation of Jill E. Barad, Mattel's chief
executive, the company has been rudderless. It is being run by
William D. Rollnick, a board member who is acting chairman, and
Ronald M. Loeb, also a board member who is acting chief executive.
Ned Mansour, president of Mattel, resigned March 24. The company's
shares have barely budged since Barad's departure and closed
yesterday at $10.375.
</P>
<P>
   Whitworth's ascension to the Mattel board could stir up the
close-knit directors. In a speech Tuesday at a conference sponsored
by the Council of Institutional Investors in Washington, Whitworth
said that Mattel needed fresh blood and that the dynamics on the
board were not healthy. In an interview Wednesday, Whitworth
declined to say more about what he has found at Mattel. But he is
an involved investor who considered a proxy fight to try to get
Mattel back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The March 27 decision in the California Court of Appeal in the
Greenwald matter may also have long-term ramifications for Mattel.
Greenwald, who was hired as a senior vice president in 1992,
contends that Mattel fired her in July 1995 because she alerted her
superior, James Eskridge, then Mattel's president, of her concern
that the company might not have accounted properly for a royalty
payment it had persuaded the Walt Disney Co. to defer from 1994
into 1995. Greenwald had primary responsibility for Disney-licensed
products.
</P>
<P>
   The case, filed in 1995, was dismissed on summary judgment in
December 1997. The judge in the case said Greenwald had not
objected vigorously enough.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 review of Greenwald's accusations by the law firm Davis
Polk &AMP; Wardwell and the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young concluded
that there was no evidence that the company's accounting was
``inconsistent with generally accepted accounting principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in its 1998 annual report, Mattel stated that
during 1996, the company received comments from the Securities and
Exchange Commission regarding ``its accounting for certain
royalties and participation fees in prior periods.'' Therefore, the
company ``recognized a catch-up adjustment in the amount of $21.8
million before taxes in the fourth quarter of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Mildred Lillie, Earl Johnson Jr. and Norvell
Frederick Woods Jr. unanimously reversed the dismissal. Stuart B.
Esner, who argued the case for Greenwald, said: ``This opinion
demonstrates in fact that her lawsuit is not baseless. It is also
worth noting that this decision does not blaze new trails expanding
liability for corporations or employers. The court really has ruled
based on settled principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattel declined to comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
