<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-PETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT WAS LIKE A TOTO MOMENT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF PRINCE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Some pets had close calls, a few were still
missing, and at least one was found dead after Tuesday's tornado,
but most survived unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only had a few calls for lost dogs; it's kind of
surprising,'' said Mike Pugliese, kennel manager at the Arlington
Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents in southeast Arlington said they put their dogs
inside their houses or garages before the tornado hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people were aware because there was an eerie feeling
just prior to the storm,'' said Don Brandon, 45. ``We took
precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   Precautions didn't help a teen-ager who took his dog inside a
house on Sandalwood Lane. The tornado hit the house hard. The boy
survived unharmed, but a police canine sniffed out the dog dead
under debris, Arlington police said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents were away from home, leaving the pets to fend for
themselves. Most pets did fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised they survived,'' Marcus Brown, 33, said of his
two mixed-breed dogs, Budweiser and Butch.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his family were in Dallas when the storm hit
Arlington. By the time they returned to their house on Waxwing
Drive, the roof was missing and the privacy fence around their back
yard was gone. Worried about his dogs, Brown ran around to the back
yard. He saw a thick tree broken in two and noticed that his
trampoline had blown away.
</P>
<P>
   He called out for his dogs, and they scampered out of a nearby
lightweight doghouse that had somehow been spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out wagging their tails,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Diamond, 45, was eating dinner with his family on Glenwillow
Drive, unaware that a tornado was about to touch down. When the
wind suddenly picked up, the family looked out a window and saw
their dachshund's doghouse spinning four feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dog was spinning around inside the doghouse,'' Diamond
said. ``It was like a Toto moment. My wife started hollering at me,
like it was my fault we had a tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   She told Diamond and the couple's son, Chris, 14, to save the
dog, Max. But they took a look at the doghouse in the air, a
lawnmower flying by and a crumbling fence and decided to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get out there, but we couldn't because it was like
a wind tunnel,'' the teen-ager said.
</P>
<P>
   When the doghouse hit the ground, Max took off. He returned home
an hour later, shaken but uninjured.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Carrillo and his family were out of town when the storm
hit. When they returned home at 1 a.m. Wednesday, their fence was
scattered and their German shepherd, Rusty, was missing. Carrillo's
daughter, Alex, 5, was distraught.
</P>
<P>
   A wee-hour search for Rusty was fruitless. When the sun came up,
Alex refused to get ready for school, saying they had to search
again for Rusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sad and scared because he was gone,'' she said. ``I love
my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor eventually found the dog, called the number on his
dog tag and took him home.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 0022EST &QL; 
