<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ENTERS DEBATE ON NEW YORK POLICE SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton waded ever so gently into the
raging battle over police shootings in New York City by suggesting
Wednesday that better training of recruits might reduce such
shootings without sacrificing public safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now ample evidence that the crime rate can go down
and the tenor of community-police relations can go up,'' Clinton
said in a news conference at the White House on Wednesday in
response to a question about whether the New York Police Department
has a racial problem. ``It's largely a matter of the right sort of
training, the right sort of policies and consistent effort there.''
</P>
<P>
   Four unarmed men have been shot and killed by New York City
police officers in the last 13 months, with the most recent
shooting, of Patrick Dorismond, igniting angry protests and calls
for federal oversight of the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who is an adviser to the Dorismond family,
and a group of Haitian community leaders from New York met
Wednesday with about 20 House Democrats, most of them members of
the Congressional Black Caucus, to ask for help in pressuring the
Department of Justice to investigate Dorismond's death.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's group said it also wanted the Justice Department to
bring federal civil rights charges against the police officers
recently acquitted of criminal charges in the shooting of Amadou
Diallo and to petition a federal judge to appoint a monitor to
oversee the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Their requests were warmly received by the members of Congress,
many of whom used the event to lash out at Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
``The mayor is really polarizing the community against the
police,'' said Rep. Charles B. Rangel, a Manhattan Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at City Hall on Wednesday, the mayor, who
is running for the Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton, suggested
that such criticisms were politically motivated. He defended the
Police Department as ``one of the most restrained'' in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sharpton filed a lawsuit in U.S. District
Court in Washington accusing Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the
Republican National Committee, of defamation, libel and slander for
remarks he made in a letter to The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, Nicholson asserted that Sharpton had incited
riots that led to deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Nicholson refused to back down. ``Al Sharpton is no
civil rights leader,'' he said. ``He is a hate-monger, an
anti-Semite and a racist.'' He called on Clinton and Vice President
Al Gore to repudiate Sharpton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
