<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MIAMIBEACH-MOB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI BEACH NIGHTCLUB OWNER FREED ON BAIL IN N.Y. MOB CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A wealthy Miami Beach nightclub impresario, who has
been charged with murder and accused of being part of a vicious
Brooklyn Mafia crew, was released from federal custody Wednesday on
$15 million bail.
</P>
<P>
   But as the suspect, Chris Paciello, walked out of U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn, he nearly got away from the private security
guards who had been hired by the government to watch him. There
were two identical black Lincoln Town Cars waiting at the curb, and
Paciello got into one as the guards accidentally got into the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris, wrong car!'' said a security guard, Jim Woods, who
realized his prisoner was not in the correct back seat and plucked
Paciello from the wrong Lincoln just as he was closing the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said a black car,'' Paciello responded, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors contend that Paciello, who owns a string of
South Beach night spots in Miami Beach, took part in the murder of
a Staten Island woman in 1993. The government said that he was then
a member of what was called the Bath Avenue Crew, a group of street
toughs who reported to the Bonanno crime family. He has also been
charged with robbing a Staten Island bank in 1992. Since his arrest
Dec. 1, he has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bail agreement, Paciello will be under house arrest at
his mother's home on Staten Island near the Fresh Kills landfill
and guarded round the clock by two $25-an-hour security guards, who
work for Lawn, Mullen &AMP; Good, a private security consulting firm.
Their fees are to be paid by Paciello.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Freeman, a partner in the security firm and one of the men
who escorted Paciello from the courthouse Wednesday, said the
guards would follow their prisoner around the house and sometimes
do errands for him. .
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he develops a taste for chili dogs,'' Freeman said,
adding that the guards might occasionally have to cook for their
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Town Car mix-up Wednesday was perhaps a result of the
half-dozen or so reporters who swarmed around Paciello as he was
walking out of court.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was unlikely Paciello could have used the Lincoln
as a getaway car. It had already been hired to pick up another man
accused of being a mobster _ Joseph Burger, who was arrested
earlier this month on charges of using extortion to attract
customers to a scrap metal empire run by Carmine Agnello, the
son-in-law of John J. Gotti, the former Gambino boss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
