<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SYRIAN-SETBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFTER THE SYRIAN SETBACK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago there seemed a good chance that Israel and Syria
might soon resume negotiations and move rapidly toward a formal
peace treaty. Instead the two countries remain deadlocked, and
there is even a danger that they could drift into armed conflict
after Israel withdraws its troops from Lebanon in July.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of this impasse is Syria's president, Hafez Assad, who
refused to show any flexibility when he met with President Clinton
in Geneva last Sunday. He continues to insist, unreasonably, that
Israel withdraw from the entire Golan Heights down to the shoreline
of the Sea of Galilee before he will even discuss issues vital to
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea of Galilee is Israel's main source of fresh water.
Israel fears that the Syrians might deliberately or accidentally
contaminate the sea or claim a portion of the Galilee for their own
use. The Israelis are reportedly willing to offer Syria additional
territory elsewhere in exchange for a shoreline buffer strip, but
Damascus has shown no interest in such a swap.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis fear that if there is no negotiating breakthrough
with Syria by the time of Israel's planned withdrawal from southern
Lebanon, Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas, with the approval of
Damascus, will move their rocket launchers to the border and shell
northern Israeli villages. Israel would probably retaliate with
airstrikes against Lebanese power stations and other targets. If
the rocket attacks persisted, Israel might consider airstrikes
against Syria itself. Even the remote possibility of such a
development underscores the danger of continued stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the negotiating breakdown with Syria has not
infected Israel's talks with the Palestinians, which are moving
ahead slowly. Both sides show a growing willingness to compromise,
and the outlines of a possible agreement are visible. It would
involve Israel handing over much of the West Bank and accepting
some form of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Formulas are being explored that would expand the territory of
greater Jerusalem so that some area outside the present city limits
might become a Palestinian administrative capital. In return, the
Palestinians would accept continued Israeli authority over most
existing West Bank settlements, Israeli military control over the
Jordan River Valley and an agreement on refugees that would settle
most of them in the areas where they now reside. Refining these
broad formulas will be difficult. But with good will on both sides
it may be possible by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential that neither Prime Minister Ehud Barak nor the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, be distracted by Assad's
intransigence. The next building block of a durable Middle East
peace is a permanent settlement between Israel and the
Palestinians. For now, peace with Syria may not be possible, but
Assad and Barak must guard against escalating tensions over
Lebanon. Syria in recent years has restrained Lebanese guerrillas
from attacking Israeli territory. That must continue after Israel's
July withdrawal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
