<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROPBB-AUDIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSITION BB MANAGEMENT FEES OUT OF CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By DAVID R. BAKER AND GREG GITTRICH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Unified School District wasted as
much as $51.3 million on management fees that could have gone to
school repairs or construction, the district's inspector general
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A two-month investigation by Inspector General Don Mullinax
found that fees paid to manage school repairs under the $2.4
billion Proposition BB bond issue far outstripped those paid by
other districts nationwide. The management fees consumed between
18.5 percent and 20.7 percent of all the money spent, more than
twice the percentage recommended by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not reasonable,'' said Mullinax. ``What we're paying
here in Los Angeles is definitely higher than elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   His report placed the blame for the excessive costs on the
company hired to manage the overall program, the proposition's
oversight committee and the district itself. He urged all three to
stop their recent squabbling and work out ways to lower the
program's management costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On all of these contracts, they need to get in there and scrub
the numbers closely and see why the numbers are so high,'' Mullinax
said.
</P>
<P>
   District officials said the excessive management costs were one
reason why the program, which had spent about $632 million by the
end of 1999, faces a projected $316.4 million deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly shows that Proposition BB money has been wasted
in the past,'' board member Caprice Young said. ``Because we know
this now, we can take corrective actions before we move forward
with major expenditures like building new schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The hefty, 142-page report capped months of feuding among the
district, the Proposition BB oversight committee and
3D/International-O'Brien Kreitzberg, the firm responsible for
managing the immense repair and construction project, approved by
voters in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax's audit was ordered by the new reform school board
after the oversight committee and management firm disputed Chief
Operating Officer Howard Miller's assertion that fees were running
out of control and demanded the replacement of several company
employees working on the project.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute effort Wednesday by 3D/I-OBK to block release of
the audit was rejected by a Superior Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   The firm threatened to sue for defamation if Mullinax went
forward but its rhetoric cooled considerably after the report's
release.
</P>
<P>
   Company representatives withdrew a separate court action seeking
damages for business 3D/I-OBK claimed to have lost due to the
district's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral candidate Steven Soboroff, who had defended 3D/I-OBK's
performance as head of the Proposition BB oversight committee,
criticized Mullinax's methodology and some of his figures, but
agreed with many of the report's basic points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand by Mullinax on this,'' Soboroff said. ``Communication
has got to get better. We need honesty, integrity, and everything
has to see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for 3D/I-OBK disputed some of the findings, but
said the report's final version was a vast improvement over a draft
they had seen earlier. The company would not have gone to court if
it had seen the final version first, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a chance to take a preliminary look at it and
frankly we are considerably relieved,'' said Tom Bishop, executive
vice president of O'Brien Kreitzberg.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the conciliatory talk, the report could still lead to
further conflict between the company and the school district.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mullinax specifically avoided recommending punitive
action against 3D/I-OBK or that any of the 10 project managers
working on Proposition BB be fired, Miller left open that
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly one of the options we have an obligation to
look at,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that 3D/I-OBK's current job might be cut as part of a
massive reorganization at the school district. The district could
use its own staff to manage the overall Proposition BB program
while hiring private companies to oversee projects in different
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The report states that:
</P>
<P>
   Determining the exact amount spent was complicated by the
district's lack of a single, unified financial records system.
</P>
<P>
   The district repeatedly changed the Proposition BB project's
administration, sometimes assigning more work to the project
management companies, at other times assigning more to district
staffers. The changes wasted money and effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Proposition BB oversight committee and 3D/I-OBK warned the
district about cost overruns on Proposition BB projects, to little
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The oversight committee tracked the amount spent on projects,
but neither the committee nor the district checked the
cost-effectiveness of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Had Los Angeles Unified spent 4 percent on management - the
least spent by other large, urban districts - it would have saved
as much as $51.3 million. Had it spent 11 percent on management -
the most other districts paid - it would have saved $25.9 million.
The different numbers come from two different estimates Mullinax
provided on the total construction costs for projects under the
program manager's control.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Proposition BB committee argued that their
volunteer group operates without overhead or staff and is therefore
limited in the work it can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters did not give us the resources to do anything other
than authorize audits and be a watchdog,'' Soboroff said. ``If the
district doesn't give us information, hides things, red-lines
reports and doesn't follow our recommendations, it makes our job
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said the report released Wednesday differed substantially
from the draft his company reviewed last week. After reviewing the
draft, a lawyer for the joint venture sent an 83-page rebuttal of
many of the draft's findings, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the project manager argued in its March 23
correspondence that the LAUSD's former facilities administrators
``repeatedly ignored recommendations from the program manager that
would have resulted in a more cost-effective and efficient
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the former LAUSD administrators authorized projects
that exceeded the scope of work authorized under the bond and
awarded projects that exceeded the bond budget, wrote attorney John
W. Rakow.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
