<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE RELEASED, CLEMENTE ACQUIRED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Anaheim Angels traded two-minor leaguers _
outfielder Norm Hutchins and catcher Jason Dewey _ for Colorado
Rockies outfielder Edgard Clemente on Wednesday, and made room for
Clemente on the roster by releasing catcher/DH Todd Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Clemente, the nephew of Roberto Clemente, gives
the Angels five outfielders on their roster. Some believe the trade
will trigger yet another trade involving an outfielder, and rumors
of a deal for Minnesota Twins ace Brad Radke already are surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   A move to Minnesota would put left fielder Darin Erstad close to
his winter home in Fargo, N.D. Center fielder Garret Anderson, like
Radke, is a free agent after the 2000 season. Erstad's contract is
up after 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, 24, split last season between Triple-A Colorado
Springs (.304, 16 homers, 59 RBI in 75 games) and the Rockies
(.253, eight homers, 25 RBI in 57 games).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tools,'' Angels general manager Bill Stoneman said.
``He's a good outfielder with speed. He can play all three outfield
positions well.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Stoneman said, was that the club will have more
use for a reserve outfielder than a third-string catcher/part-time
DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no denying Greenie's bat,'' Stoneman said. ``He's got
a power bat. Somebody's going to be happy to have him. He's going
to have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, like Jim Edmonds a week ago, was in tears as he left the
clubhouse Wednesday. Greene had spent his entire career in the
Angels organization since being drafted in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hard part,'' Greene said of saying goodbye to his
former teammates. ''I'm sad I'm leaving these players. But it's
part of the game. Todd Greene doesn't change. He's still the same,
he still can play. Just not with those guys and that's the hard
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Any team can claim Greene off waivers for 48 hours following his
release but would be responsible for his $650,000 salary. If Greene
is not claimed, he is free to sign with any team. He also is
considering playing in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rotation set: Scioscia announced his starting rotation to
start the season _ joining Ken Hill, Kent Bottenfield, Jason
Dickson and Ramon Ortiz will be Scott Schoeneweis, who won the
final spot over Kent Mercker. Mercker will begin the season in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker admitted to being disappointed, especially considering
his spring numbers (3-0, 3.78 ERA) compared to Schoeneweis' numbers
(2-2, 7.54 ERA). It came down to Mercker being better suited to
pitch out of the bullpen. Schoeneweis pitched in the bullpen last
season, but the Angels told him at the beginning of camp he would
be a starter only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just too good, too versatile,'' Mercker joked. ''I know in
Atlanta they kept me in the pen. I was not good enough for the
rotation and too good to trade. But I got to three World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
