<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HOOP-STAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA BARS BASKETBALL STAR FROM U.S. EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (duplication notice: also sent with `s' code) 
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China has barred a young basketball star from
taking part this weekend in the Nike Hoop Summit in Indianapolis,
an exhibition event meant to showcase the world's best young
players and introduce them to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The player, Yao Ming, 19, is a 7-foot-6 center for the Shanghai
Sharks, a professional team, and has long been viewed as a possible
future player in the NBA, which has had very few players his size.
He had hoped to display his skills at the Nike games, which fall
during the NCAA's Final Four playoffs and are closely watched by
agents and coaches looking to recruit international talent.
</P>
<P>
   But China's basketball bureaucrats have decided that Yao should
stay home. ``Yao Ming has been chosen for China's national Olympic
team and must start intensive training in Beijing on April 1,''
said Xu Minfeng, director of the Chinese Basketball Association's
general office.
</P>
<P>
   Xu said the ``second reason'' that Yao was not allowed to leave
is that he ``has played a lot of games in the past year, feels very
tired and needs time to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Yao apparently does not have any choice. The basketball
association, a government agency, said Yao ``must abide by the
decision.'' Questions were referred to the State Sports General
Administration's propaganda department, which could not be reached.
Yao left Shanghai for Beijing on Wednesday and was unavailable for
comment. His father, reached by telephone, declined to discuss the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   China's decision is a stark reminder that despite advances in
the country's economy, its people are not necessarily free to
travel abroad at will and remain subject to the whims of the
central government bureaucracy. The ban is reminiscent of the Cold
War era, when many Soviet athletes were prevented from traveling
abroad or, when they did, defected to freer societies in the West.
</P>
<P>
   It also darkens Yao's NBA dreams, which would bring him millions
of dollars if realized, compared with the $8,000 a year his team
managers say he earns now.
</P>
<P>
   The Jinan Times, the newspaper in Shandong province that
reported the travel ban, said Yao had hoped that this weekend's
games would have shown that he ranked among the top international
players. Basketball executives say the games were to have been
Yao's ``coming-out party,'' and would have helped him decide
whether to put himself into the NBA draft this year. Players under
22 must declare their desire to participate in the draft to the
NBA, in writing, by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a shame!'' the Shandong newspaper quoted Yao as saying.
``What a big shame! This is my last chance.'' He will not be
eligible for the games next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Jinan Times report was picked up by several Chinese-language
Web sites and word of the government's decision spread quickly
through the sporting community.
</P>
<P>
   China is counting on Yao and another player, Wang Zhizhi, for a
chance at winning a gold medal at this summer's Olympics, a hugely
prestigious prize for a country obsessed with its standing in
international forums. Wang was prevented from going to the United
States last year after he was drafted by the Dallas Mavericks, and
many people believe his value as an Olympic player was a primary
reason.
</P>
<P>
   China remains sensitive to what it considers a history of
foreign exploitation, and that extends to sports. The country's
fledgling basketball league is also reluctant to let the United
States begin poaching its best players, even though a Chinese
player in the NBA would undoubtedly increase interest in the sport
at home. ``We need Yao Ming here,'' said the Shanghai Sharks'
general manager, Li Yaomin, in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, provided that Yao is not injured, he will remain an
attractive NBA. candidate for years, giving him time to wait for
China to change its attitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
