<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLA-FORECAST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE'S ECONOMIC GROWTH TO CONTINUE TILL AT LEAST '02
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By   CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Propelled by strong job growth and increased
exports to Asia, California's robust economy will continue
expanding through 2002 but at a slightly more moderate pace,
according to a UCLA survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly forecast by the Anderson School at the University
of California, Los Angeles, said neither a volatile stock market
nor higher interest rates on business and personal loans could slow
the state's growth. It predicts nonfarm jobs will increase 3.5
percent this year, up from 3.1 percent in 1999. It'll slow to 2.6
percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers show the California economy is still very
promising ... and is one of the fastest-growing states in the
nation,'' said Lynn Reaser, chief economist with Bank of America
Asset Management Group in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The strong export gains of last year should continue through
2002, according to Tom K. Lieser, executive director of the
Anderson Business Forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Exports grew by 7.7 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999,
compared with the same period in 1998. According to the survey,
Mexico remains the leading destination for California exports. For
the year, export sales to Mexico increased 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japan was the second-largest destination for California exports,
while Canada was third, followed by South Korea and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Trade with Asia should continue to grow as Japan's economy
continues its recovery and tensions between Taiwan and China begin
to subside following Taiwan's elections earlier this month, said
Reaser.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's economic growth was led by Riverside and
San Bernardino counties, which increased 5.8 percent last year,
compared with 4.8 percent in 1998, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County grew by 4.2 percent, Orange County by 3.5 percent
and Los Angeles County by 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the forecast noted some gray clouds on the horizon. The
region's economy is being slowed by ``widespread shortages of
labor,'' Lieser said, and quickly spiraling home prices are
threatening to scare away new workers.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates will also put some limits on borrowing of
both households and businesses, he said. Which, of course, is what
the Federal Reserve intended when it ratcheted up the rate charged
to banks by the Fed in an attempt to cool the economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will higher interest rates and gas prices work in tandem to
slow the economy? That would definitely please the Federal
Reserve,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles
County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of higher gas prices and interest rates ``is
going to take some of the bloom off the spending rose,'' said
Kyser.
</P>
<P>
   Although new residential construction in California has
increased considerably, further gains may be hindered because of
existing obstacles to large-scale development combined with
less-favorable financing conditions this year and next, Lieser
said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey forecasts new residential permits of 150,000 units
this year, decreasing to 143,000 in 2001, before rising to 157,000
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are still insufficient to meet the demand (for
housing) we have in California,'' said Kathy Fairbanks, vice
president of the California Chamber of Commerce in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nonresidential construction was the highest ever in
the fourth quarter, increasing by 21.5 percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   With limited new housing coming to market, prices continue to
increase. In Los Angeles County, the average price of a home should
increase by 3.5 percent this year, down from 6.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, home prices were expected to increase 3.4 percent
followed by a 3.8 percent increase in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The high price and lack of housing could be a ``significant
barrier to job growth and California's continued economic
prosperity,'' said Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   While home prices continue to outpace construction, the survey
also found that consumer confidence, recently at record levels in
California, has driven consumer spending to the strongest gains in
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lieser said California will enjoy a 7.1 percent increase in
taxable sales this year, followed by slower gains of 6.4 percent in
2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot predict when the bull market and its associated
wealth effects will recede,'' wrote Lieser, ``but the higher
interest rates in this forecast should take at least a small bite
from this source later this year and in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also predicts that total immigration will average
240,000 people annually through 2002 and the overall population
should grow by 1.6 percent per year for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is still very promising, which should make
California one of the nation's fastest-growing states this year,
said Reaser.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent estimates for the jobless rate show an economy
in California that is approaching full employment.
</P>
<P>
   February's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 4.6
percent, the lowest since 1959. The rate was only 0.5 percent
higher than the national jobless rate of 4.1 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   The main drag on the state's rate is the agriculture-driven
Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have the Central Valley, our unemployment rate
would be below the national rate,'' Reaser said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
