<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGATE-BUYOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGATE TECHNOLOGY TO BE TAKEN PRIVATE IN INTRICATE BUYOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a complex $19 billion deal, Seagate
Technology, the world's largest disk drive company, will be taken
private by an investor group led by Silver Lake Partners, Seagate
executives and the Texas Pacific Group.
</P>
<P>
   The nonoperating assets of Seagate, primarily a one-third stake
in Veritas Software, would be acquired by Veritas and redistributed
to Seagate's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which was managed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
Veritas would acquire all of its shares that are currently held by
Seagate, as well as cash and Seagate's smaller equity stakes in
several other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The investor group would acquire Seagate's disk drive business
for $2 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate shareholders would get about $77.50 a share for each
share of Seagate common stock, consisting of 0.467 Veritas share
and approximately $5 in cash based on closing prices Tuesday. The
price represents about a 24 percent premium to Wednesday's closing
price for Seagate of $62.75. Seagate shares have traded as low as
$25.125 the last 52 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Veritas shares, which closed down $12.4375, at $142.50 on the
Nasdaq on Wednesday, traded as high as $160.375 after hours.
Seagate, off $4.50 at the close of trading, moved as high as $76
after hours.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reflects the divergent fortunes of Seagate and Veritas,
which became intertwined in October 1998, when Seagate sold its
software unit to Veritas and in return received about 35 percent of
the company. Despite being the dominant supplier of disk drives,
Seagate struggled to maintain profits in a competitive market.
Veritas, on the other hand, flourished as the growth of the
Internet bolstered demand for its software, which manages data
storage and backup tasks across networks.
</P>
<P>
   With Veritas' market valuation at about $55 billion and
Seagate's at $13 billion, Seagate was valued at less than its stake
in Veritas was worth. Seagate management had been seeking a way to
realize the value of its assets but was unable to distribute the
Veritas stake to its own shareholders without setting off a
substantial tax liability for them.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Seagate's market leadership in disk drives, no buyer
had emerged for that business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the speculation in the past 30 days, the stock traded
at a huge discount to the underlying assets,'' said Steve Luczo,
Seagate's president and chief executive, in a telephone interview.
The disk drive business is ``probably the most disliked business in
technology by public investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, you have a kind of pressure that is short term in
nature. We now align ourselves with an investor group that has a
long-term perspective and a belief in the importance of storage
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   A key to making the deal tax free was the involvement of
Veritas. Because Seagate's Veritas shares were the same class of
stock as Veritas' freely trading shares, Veritas could retire them
to its treasury and distribute new shares tax free. Because of the
spread between the Veritas and Seagate market capitalizations,
Veritas could actually distribute fewer shares than it had
acquired, so the deal would immediately increase earnings per
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fulcrum of the transaction, the thing that makes it
possible, is we own the same shares,'' said Mark Leslie, Veritas'
chairman and chief executive. He noted that his company's float, or
the percentage of shares available to trade, increases from 67
percent to 99 percent, and Veritas gains almost $3 billion in cash.
But Veritas did not want to own a disk drive company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Silver Lake Partners, a buyout firm formed last year to
invest in technology companies. Although recognizing the volatility
and competitiveness of the disk drive business, Silver Lake's
investors liked Seagate for its market leadership, said Roger
McNamee, Silver Lake's co-founder and managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true growth investment,'' McNamee said. ``Seagate,
properly capitalized, has a chance to really break away from the
pack.''
</P>
<P>
   After the buyout, Silver Lake would be the largest shareholder
in Seagate, followed by Texas Pacific. Luczo said Seagate
management and employees would own about a third of the new
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
