<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX, GEORGE GET CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ The Lakers arrived in Canada without their
third-leading scorer, but coach Phil Jackson viewed Glen Rice's
illness as an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   With Rice at home in L.A. nursing a stomach virus Wednesday, the
Lakers were forced to start Rick Fox and lean more on rookie Devean
George _ the former fighting through a shooting slump, the latter
fighting just to get some minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the team and for us to have some different
personnel in,'' Jackson said. ``Even though I don't want it to
happen, it's OK with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such situations have been rare for the Lakers, who haven't
needed to change the starting lineup or fiddle much with the
rotation in months. No starter had missed a game since Dec. 12, the
last time Rice was ill.
</P>
<P>
   With the playoffs just a few weeks away, Jackson figured Fox
could benefit from the extended minutes against Vancouver. In the
prior nine games, Fox made just 8 of 33 shots (24.2 percent) from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it creates a return to some more opportunities to get a
rhythm, that will only help us down the road,'' said Fox, who got
his first start of the season, in his native country. ``The most
important thing is we get a win some way without (Rice), and if out
of that comes an opportunity to get into a rhythm that carries
over, that would be nice too.''
</P>
<P>
   With Fox focusing on his role as a defensive stopper and a setup
man for Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, his shooting has been a
secondary concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing Shaquille score 40 points on a consistent basis,
our emphasis is then getting him the ball, and he's obviously been
doing the job that's been unstoppable of late,'' Fox said. ``So the
focus hasn't been on a lot of perimeter play, other than Kobe
creating opportunities, which he always does, and Glen feeding off
of those guys. So if I can go in and be an asset defensively and
not turn the ball over and still take the shots that are there, I
honestly have the confidence that they'll start to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also used Bryant at small forward some but said he
prefers not to play him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lusts after playing that position,'' Jackson said. ``(But)
it's really a scorer's position and he's a playmaker now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Oh, Canada: Selections are not official yet, but Fox figures
to be playing for the Canadian national team in this summer's
Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of when to get in there with enough time to
prepare ourselves as a whole team,'' he said. ``Hopefully, the goal
is to stretch this (the Lakers' season) out until June, and there
needs to be a period where I spend some time with the family, rest
a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Slow down: Jackson wants to start cutting back on starters'
minutes, especially O'Neal's, to prepare for the playoffs, but
won't do so right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts when we clinch (No. 1 seed in the West) really. If
we have an opportunity to clinch in the next few games, that would
be a pattern I'd like to see,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
