<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUDE-DANCING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NUDE DANCING AND FREE EXPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   A case concerning nude dancing at an Erie, Pa., night spot
occasioned a disappointing 6-3 Supreme Court opinion Wednesday that
unduly broadened the government's authority to regulate expressive
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was an Erie ordinance banning public nudity and
requiring dancers in adult clubs to don at least pasties and a
G-string before appearing on stage. Two years ago Pennsylvania's
top court struck down the ordinance, rejecting the city's argument
that the nude-dancing ban was justified to combat crime.
</P>
<P>
   In reversing that decision Wednesday, the court endorsed a
perilous change in legal doctrine. In the past the court has
allowed localities to regulate the location of X-rated
establishments in an effort to reduce crime and other adverse
``secondary effects'' on neighborhoods. Indeed, New York City
relied on those precedents to justify its recent rezoning of adult
establishments. But Wednesday Justice Sandra Day O'Connor's main
opinion used the ``secondary effects'' rationale to justify a total
ban on one type of erotic message that even the majority concedes
falls within the ambit of the First Amendment, albeit ``the outer
ambit.'' Dancing in the nude, like other forms of dance, is an
expressive activity that conveys a distinct artistic message
warranting free-speech protection.
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed dissent, Justice John Paul Stevens, joined by
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, rightly criticized the majority for
blindly accepting the law's crime-fighting rationale. ``To believe
that the mandatory addition of pasties and a G-string will have any
kind of noticeable impact on secondary effects requires nothing
short of a titanic surrender to the implausible,'' Stevens wrote.
The court upheld a similar nude dancing ban in 1991 in a badly
splintered decision that left the grounds for a ban murky.
Wednesday it made matters worse by giving localities more leeway
than necessary to protect neighborhoods and inflicting damage on
First Amendment principles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0019 </DOCNO>
