<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BRITAIN-PRIME-PR     03-30 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRITAIN-PRIME-PRIME-MINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PRIME MINISTER'S LABOR PAINS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   With the birth of his fourth child due in May, Prime Minister
Tony Blair of Britain has been presented with a perfect chance to
lend new authority to his support for paternity leave. He should
take some time off and help his wife with the wee one. It would
make a point politically and score a point or two at home. Or, as
the Mirror tabloid aptly advised recently in billboard-size type,
``Show new dads the way, Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some wage-earning fathers, Blair cannot argue the
disadvantages of helping with child care. The Blairs' living
quarters are conveniently attached to Blair's working quarters. The
help situation is fairly accommodating, ranging from household
staff to an assortment of Cabinet ministers. For a thoroughly
modern prime minister, this would seem to be an easy call.
</P>
<P>
   Under new regulations in the European Union, parents are
entitled to 13 weeks of unpaid time off during the first five years
of a child's life. Many working fathers have apparently resisted
taking parental time off, protesting that they are too busy or
worrying that if they change too many diapers they might also be
forced to change jobs.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, Blair has said he is worried about
making sure the country is ``properly run.'' But the idea of the
head man staying with a new tot is understandably popular with
women, an important voting bloc for Blair and his Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   One particular working mum, however, may have a more substantial
sway in this matter _ the prime minister's wife, Cherie. A
high-powered barrister who practices law under the name Cherie
Booth, Blair last week praised the prime minister of Finland, Paavo
Lipponen, who has taken time off for the birth of his children.
Blair's advisers are suggesting that he could take a week or so on
his holiday schedule, meaning that he would work only four hours a
day. That way he would be easily within reach for any emergencies
in the government as well as any mishaps at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
