<HEADLINE>
EXPECT PALFFY FOR FIRST ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ziggy Palffy's sprained right shoulder continues
to improve and he should be back in two weeks for the first round
of the playoffs. The news on winger Nelson Emerson isn't so
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who suffered a badly broken left index finger just 11
days after he was acquired from Atlanta at the March 14 trade
deadline, probably will not be ready for the opening round of the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson was injured on a slash by Philadelphia's Daymond Langkow
that broke the finger just above the left knuckle. His left arm was
placed in a cast up to the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson is spending this week in Atlanta to put his house on the
market. He will be reexamined Monday and the team orthopedist might
have to insert a pin surgically to stabilize the finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors say we could be looking at a lengthy time frame,''
general manager Dave Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The range of motion in Palffy's shoulder has improved and he
could be back in a week to 10 days. Right, now, Palffy is
undergoing hot and cold treatment and electronic stimulation to the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings would like to have Palffy play the final
regular-season games to prepare for the first round.
</P>
<P>
   __ Line shifts: Emerson originally replaced Palffy on the Kings'
first unit, but now the line is composed of Jozef Stumpel, Glen
Murray and Craig Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who had two goals and four assists on the Kings'
three-game East Coast trip, assisted on both goals by Murray on
Saturday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The two broke in the same season (1991-92) with the Bruins and
played in Boston together for four seasons. Murray was traded to
Pittsburgh in 1995 then onto the Kings two years later. Stumpel was
traded to the Kings in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stumpy and I go back a long way,'' said Murray, who has played
most of the season with Bryan Smolinski's second line. ``We know
each other very well. We've picked it up pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings actually have several former Bruins on their roster.
Smolinski broke in with Boston fulltime in 1993-94 and scored a
career-high 31 goals his rookie year. Defenseman Garry Galley
played 3 seasons in Boston from 1988-91.
</P>
</TEXT>
