<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PANTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LOSE ZUBOV, CLAIM PACIFIC TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ The Pacific Division became the official
property of the Stars last night.
</P>
<P>
   They, of course, celebrated with their seasonlong sidekicks: ice
bags, black eyes and an another injury _ this one to the only Stars
player who hadn't missed a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   With 13:30 remaining in the Stars' 4-1 victory against the
Florida Panthers, defenseman Sergei Zubov went down after taking a
hit from Panthers defenseman Bret Hedican. He lay on the ice for a
couple of minutes before being helped off. He has a strained right
knee and is scheduled to be evaluated tomorrow to determine whether
he'll play in any of the Stars' five remaining regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ACL tear, so he's certainly going to be back for
the playoffs,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, putting on his best
happy face.
</P>
<P>
   He, like his team, has been here before.
</P>
<P>
   Rare has the game been in which the Stars haven't seen one of
their best players with his arms draped over two teammates
shoulders, being helped off the ice. They're almost used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just play,'' Hitchcock said. ``You just go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   They've done it all year. They'll, no doubt, do it again. But
they were starting to play so well. Just ask Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The second line that Hitchcock has been so worried about? Scored
three goals.
</P>
<P>
   The toughness that the Stars supposedly lacked? Got in four
fights.
</P>
<P>
   The strain that playing in three games in four nights might have
on goalie Ed Belfour? Stopped 36 of 37 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to do my job, and that's what I have to do,
come up with those saves,'' said Belfour, who has played in every
game since a weeklong hiatus following his March 8 arrest. He's
4-1-1 with an overtime loss, allowing 11 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers winger Pavel Bure prevented Belfour from getting his
50th shutout, scoring his NHL-leading 55th goal of the season at
8:46 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pavel Bure show was upstaged by the Scott Thornton
comeback tour.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in his first game back after a three-game suspension for
a high stick to San Jose's Marco Sturm, Thornton scored two goals,
had four shots and got into a fight while playing on the second
line with Joe Nieuwendyk and Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nieuwendyk's line really stepped up big-time. They were really
good,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think Thornton helped a lot, but I
think the other two guys were very good players tonight. They were
involved physically. Both guys really looked like workers out
there, and they had scoring chances because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock has been pleading from production from his second line
ever since Nieuwendyk returned from a separated shoulder three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored at 2:42 of the first period on a pretty wrist
shot from the bottom of the circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I still have to get playing a little bit better
here,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Mentally, it has been more tough than
physically. Physically, I am starting to come around. Mentally, it
has been difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   After a goal by Stars center Guy Carbonneau at 12:34 of the
second period, his second goal in as many nights, the Thornton show
started. For a guy not brought in to score goals, he's sure scoring
them.
</P>
<P>
   He scored at 13:23 of the second period on a pass from Hull, one
of Hull's three assists on the night. The other came at 4:32 of the
third, when he punched in a rebound of a Hull shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying. Like I've been saying, I thought we were playing
pretty well together before I got suspended,'' Thornton said of the
line. ``I was a little surprised with how good I felt with this
time off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars don't usually have that many in a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had heard before game these guys wanted to use us as a
measuring stick,'' Thornton said. ``So, for us, that was a little
bit of a challenge so we came out and answered the bell.'' ] All in
all not a bad night, if it weren't for the whole losing Zubov
thing. Zubov has been one of the Stars' best, most-consistent and
most-versatile players. When Stars captain Derian Hatcher missed
nine weeks with a lacerated calf earlier this season, Zubov filled
in as part of the shutdown pair with Richard Matvichuk. In addition
to quarterbacking the power play, he's also No. 3 on the team in
scoring with nine goals and 33 assists. In his four seasons with
the Stars, Zubov has missed 14 games. If he doesn't play Sunday, it
will be 15. ``Well, you know, what can you say,'' Belfour said.
``Zubie, he's a great player. Anytime you lose a player like that
out of your lineup you are going to miss him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
