<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     03-30 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE newspaper, yellowing with age, is still thumbtacked to the
cluttered wall of greater Kissimmee's most beloved watering hole,
which is mentioned in a column as the site of a wee-hours
conversation between a ballplayer-turned-sportscaster and a couple
of sportswriters regarding the finest young pitching phenom the
former had seen come along in ages.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Larry Dierker knew something about young pitching
phenoms, having been one himself a generation earlier. When you
have struck out Willie Mays in your first big-league start at the
age of 18, as Dierker had, you are fully qualified to pass judgment
on the likes of Dwight Gooden, who was about to embark on the most
precocious Cy Young Award-winning season ever.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was barely 20, but it hadn't required the consumption of
a single Big Bamboo cocktail _ the near-lethal house specialty _
for any of the parties in this long-ago, beer-fueled bull session
to conclude that Baby Doc was fast-tracking his way to a place in
Cooperstown. It was Dierker's contention that Gooden had all the
requisite tools to become the reference standard for power pitchers
in the modern age.
</P>
<P>
   And for an all-too-brief time, he lived up to Dierk's
expectations. Gooden's first three seasons, through the Mets'
world-championship year of 1986, stack up nicely against anybody's
in the latter half of the 20th century. His next four weren't
shabby either, although the demons that would nearly destroy him
had begun to dog his every celebrated step.
</P>
<P>
   As we now know, Gooden wouldn't handle fame and fortune in the
New York fishbowl well. Drugs became his crutch, his escape from
the pressures of his high profile. He took to living as fast as he
threw a baseball _ way north of 90 mph back then _ and that's how
he wound up where he is today at 35, determined, perhaps desperate
even, to script an end to his career remotely worthy of its
original boundless promise.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden won't go to the Hall of Fame. He won't win 300 games or
strike out 3,000 hitters. But as an Astro, pitching for Dierker, he
can make peace with himself. And in the process, he gets to claim a
small piece of Houston baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   In Enron Field's inaugural game tonight, shortly after 7:05
p.m., Gooden will throw the first pitch of baseball's new era in
Houston to native son Chuck Knoblauch of the world champion
Yankees, the team that gave Doc his first second chance after the
cross-town Mets had had their fill of him.
</P>
<P>
   And even in these pitching-depleted times, the Astros may
represent his last second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to it,'' Doc said of the Enron
opener. ``I've had a lot of things happen to me in my career, but
this will be a new experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final Florida start Saturday, he was supposed to work six
innings against the Expos. But he lasted only three after
experiencing numbness in the tip of a finger when Hideki Irabu
clipped him as he squared up to bunt on a squeeze play. He stayed
in the game after being examined by trainer Dave Labossiere and
went one more inning before catcher Paul Bako warned the Astros'
brain trust that he believed Doc was altering his mechanics
slightly to compensate for his diminished feel for the ball. Still,
the abbreviated outing would be his third in the Grapefruit League
in which he didn't surrender a run.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's ERA is a sparkling 2.37 after 19 exhibition innings. He
has given up 10 hits and walked six while striking out 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very encouraged,'' he said afterward. ``The Astros offered
me a chance to prove myself, and I think I have. It's been a good
situation for me, being here, just being back in the National
League. I like the National League game better, and I like to hit
except for maybe today.''
</P>
<P>
   He should like it. His eight home runs rank first among active
major-league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   As for his forte, though, Gooden is only 31-22 since he was
suspended for the entire 1995 season for repeatedly violating the
provisions of his drug-rehab program. And battling a shoulder
strain much of the season, he went 3-4 with a 6.26 ERA for
Cleveland a year ago, in what many felt would surely be his last
major-league gasp.
</P>
<P>
   But Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker was with the Mets
when Gooden was Doctor K, and he deemed him worthy of a look-see _
certainly since Houston had a sudden crying need for a stopgap
starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton was gone, ironically, to the Mets, and Scott
Elarton was coming off rotator-cuff surgery. If Gooden could bring
anything at all, he would have a spot, at least short-term.
</P>
<P>
   Well?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything that discourages me,'' Dierker said,
speaking cautiously so as to not overburden Gooden with fan
expectations. ``I've seen what I'd hoped I'd see, a veteran who
can't overpower hitters anymore but who can get them out because he
knows how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consideration was given to inserting Gooden in the rotation
behind Shane Reynolds, Jose Lima and Chris Holt, but Dierker
decided not to subject him to the pressure of having to pitch the
Astros' regular-season Enron opener a week from Friday night
against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid that might be asking a little too much of him,''
the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros _ more irony _ will instead ask it of Octavio Dotel,
the 24-year-old ascendant star acquired from the Mets as part of
the Hampton trade. Dotel, who was touted in New York as a possible
second coming of the Doc, showed Gooden-esque flashes as a
flame-throwing Mets rookie in 1999, although at 8-3 with a 5.38
ERA, his numbers were hardly ballpark with the teen-age Gooden's
remarkable 17-6, 2.60 and 276 K's in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   No, Dotel is not the Doc. But all things considered, maybe
that's for the best.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
