<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-HNS &LR;      03-30 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
When the Astros pursued Roger Clemens prior to last season, they
envisioned the five-time Cy Young Award winner on the mound for the
first game at their new downtown ballpark.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They'll get their wish _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will be wearing pinstripes when he walks to the mound
tonight in the inaugural game at Enron Field, but it has nothing to
do with the Astros' change of uniform. He'll be pitching for the
defending World Series champion New York Yankees, who also helped
the Astros open the Astrodome 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited for Houston, as someone who lives there,'' said
Clemens, a product of Spring Woods. ``I hope it does for our
downtown what it's done for some of these other downtowns, like
Cleveland and Baltimore. You see the effect these stadiums have on
the cities that build them. I just hope Houston has the same thing
happen. That downtown is starting to come together, and this could
be just what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   During his Hall of Fame career _ which includes 247 victories
and 3,316 strikeouts in 15 major-league seasons _ Clemens has
pitched in his hometown just once. He was the American League's
starting pitcher in the 1986 All-Star Game, played at the
Astrodome, and threw three perfect innings.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, also known as ``the Rocket,'' came close to returning
home when he demanded a trade from the Toronto Blue Jays after the
1998 season. The Astros expressed their desire to acquire Clemens,
but when his Houston-based representatives, Alan and Randy
Hendricks, requested a $27 million contract extension, general
manager Gerry Hunsicker publicly criticized the agents. Clemens
vowed never to play for the Astros, and a few months later he was
dealt to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Clemens lives with his wife, Deb, and
their four sons _ Koby, 13; Kory, 11; Kacy, 5; and Kody, 3 _ 20
minutes from downtown. He has purchased 200 tickets to tonight's
game for family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the name he has, I think it's going to be real neat for
the city to see him pitch,'' said Yankees lefthander Andy Pettitte,
who played at Deer Park. ``That's going to be special. It's special
for the town. I know it'll be special for Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   It will also be special for the Houston-area contingent on the
Yankees' roster, which includes Clemens, Pettitte, second baseman
Chuck Knoblauch (Bellaire) and relievers Mike Stanton (Alvin
Community College) and Jason Grimsley (Cleveland).
</P>
<P>
   ``Revitalization isn't the right word. It would be a
vitalization,'' Stanton said. ``Downtown has never been a big place
for Houston. You see other places like Cleveland, Baltimore, places
like that. In those cities, business is pretty much concentrated
and done downtown. In Houston, business is done everywhere.
Downtown's got an OK skyline, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
