<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1977 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ENRON-HNS &LR;      03-30 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ENRON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
After hearing about it for months, the newest tenants at the
6.5-acre property at the corner of Texas Avenue and Crawford Street
finally walked around their new home Wednesday afternoon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging by the wide-eyed, awe-struck look on the faces of Astros
players, coaches and personnel, the two-year construction of Enron
Field was worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw pictures of the stadium, so we had an idea. But you
never really get the full effect until you see it for yourself,''
infielder Bill Spiers said. ``I think everybody is like a young kid
in a candy store walking around this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon their midday arrival at Bush Intercontinental Airport, the
Astros were given a police escort for the 30-minute drive downtown.
The Astros left their spring-training site in Kissimmee, Fla., a
day early to allow players a glimpse of their new home before
tonight's Enron-opening exhibition with the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all excited to be here and be a part of it,'' Spiers
said. ``This is definitely worth the wait. You could see the
excitement in the guys when we landed, got on the bus and had a
police escort for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Once at the ballpark, players went on a tour of the clubhouse
before walking through the dugout tunnels and onto the grassy
playing field, a view of Union Station and part of the Houston
skyline directly in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bogar, looking like a tourist with a camera in his hand,
immediately began taking pictures. Billy Wagner and Jay Powell
walked to the home team's bullpen area in right-center field. Craig
Biggio checked out the infield dirt and chatted briefly with head
groundskeeper Luke Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima pointed to the short 315-foot line in left field. ``I
may even go deep this season,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around at the 42,000 seats that will be filled for
tonight's game against the defending World Series champions, most
of the Astros were speechless, calling the picturesque setting
``breathtaking and unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said.
``It's hard to believe. You knew it was coming; you watched it go
up. But until you really come out and see the finished product,
it's just like it's almost surreal. I find myself asking the
questions, `Is this really happening? Is this really ours?' This is
going to be very special for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a fan walking around, step by step, admiring every
section of this new ballpark. You're not going to forget the first
time you walked into this place.''
</P>
<P>
   So what part of the ballpark drew the most attention?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the 1850s-era locomotive beyond left field or the
three-section retractable roof that cast a partial shadow in the
outfield Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it the cozy yet spacious clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   How about the gigantic scoreboard in the upper reaches of right
field?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' Biggio said. ``It's a beautiful facility. It's a
beautiful ballpark. They did an excellent job. After playing 12
years in an old building, to open a new house is exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lima was mesmerized with the left-field porch, outfielder
Roger Cedeno was busy inspecting center field, which includes a
30-degree slope up to the wall and a flagpole in fair territory.
Standing 435 feet from home plate, the center-field wall is the
deepest in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three days to figure it out and make adjustments,''
Cedeno said. ``It's a long way. I don't think a lot of balls are
going to be hit there. That's why I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best reviews were saved for the Bermuda grass _ a
welcome replacement for the Astrodome's turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the greenest grass I've seen in a long time,'' Bogar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden, a former Yankee, made his first career start in
the Astrodome while with the New York Mets, and he'll pitch the
first game at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've been in the right place at the right time,'' said
Gooden, who briefly threw with reliever Mike Maddux in left field
after most of his teammates were long gone. ``I couldn't be in a
better situation, especially going against the Yankees in a new
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Hometown icon Roger Clemens, winner of five Cy Young Awards,
will start for New York. The Yankees played in the first game in
the Astrodome in 1965, a 2-1 Astros exhibition victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won't take batting practice or test the field until
prior to today's exhibition. But after Wednesday's visit, they felt
a new chapter had officially begun in Houston baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``After playing in the Dome and all the tradition there, coming
here and starting your own tradition and your new brand of baseball
is exciting,'' Wagner said. ``I think the fans are in for a real
treat.''
</P>
<P>
   The most eager person in the organization to officially open
Enron Field, Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr., was still deciding
how he would spend the eve of the grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not go to bed,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
