<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     03-30 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FOR the second time in 35 years, the Houston Astros will open a
magnificent new stadium against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   What? Again?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these are not your father's Yankees who will provide
the opposition when the Astros dedicate Enron Field, the downtown
jewel of what was once Houston's dreary east end. In 1965, the
Yankees still had Mickey Mantle, Tony Kubek and Whitey Ford, but
they were not the defending world champions, as these Bronx Bombers
are.
</P>
<P>
   They finished second to the St. Louis Cardinals in the '64 World
Series, a loss that cost Yogi Berra his job as manager. He was
replaced by Johnny Keane, who made his home in Houston. A proud
man, Keane resigned his job as Cardinals manager after the Series.
He had led them to a comeback so remarkable that it embarrassed the
ownership. St. Louis won the pennant on the last day of the season,
after the club had negotiated with Leo Durocher to be the next
year's field leader.
</P>
<P>
   You got all that?
</P>
<P>
   No such intrigue, no blood on the ground, surrounds the teams as
they plunge into this year's pageantry. In the Year of the
Astrodome, the Astros were destined to finish ninth, still seeking
their first winning season, a mere seven years away.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Yankees have a clue that their great run was over
and that hard times were coming. They were as awe-struck as the
Astros by the grandeur of the world's first indoor ballpark. Mantle
and Joe Pepitone boasted proudly of their achievements in the Dome,
Mick blasting the first home run and Pepitone making the first
error by an Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, it was only a preseason game, but, oh, what it
seemed to be. You can expect the same blizzard of first recorded
moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros inspected Enron Field for the first time Wednesday,
shortly after their arrival from the sun-soaked shores of Florida.
They loved what they saw, being careful not to step too hard on the
newly planted grass or muck up the smoothly brushed red clay of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing smug about the way they conducted this visit,
none of that ``the Astros are here and checking it out'' attitude.
They were looking at the angles of the field and testing the
pattern of the wind and whether the fences are friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have to paint those bricks out there,'' said
Craig Biggio, pointing to a light beige patch on the wall beneath
the terrace in center field. This is the kind of detail that can
cause a hitter to lose the ball in that background as it leaves the
pitcher's hand. You sense that by 7:05 tonight, the bricks will be
green, matching the rest of the backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was asked jokingly what he thought of the ambience.
``Nice,'' he said. ``It looks like a ballpark.'' He was standing in
the outfield, about 10 feet behind second base, his work station.
Owner Drayton McLane Jr. was beside him, and slightly beside
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever think,'' he asked a reporter, ``that you would
see the Astros in a stadium with real grass and the sun shining on
your face?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly,'' said the reporter, ``I was pretty content with old
Colt Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Drayton pointed to his corner offices on the top floor of Union
Station, overlooking left field. ``It's about 422 feet from home
plate to my window,'' he said, turning to Biggio. ``Would you hit a
home run for me through there?''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran grinned and said, ``If you let me hit it from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the distance, the ball would have to achieve a
height of around 40 feet. It was remarked offhand that the glass
must be of the non-breakable variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' Drayton replied. ``I insisted on breakable glass. I
want to hear the glass shatter. I want to hear a lot of noise.
We'll just keep buying new windows.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Astros won't need sound effects to recreate the
clatter once associated with Rosie Roswell, an old-time broadcaster
with the Pirates. ``He would recreate the games using Western
Union,'' recalled Milo Hamilton. ``When a Pirate hit one out,
they'd cue up the record of breaking glass and Rosie would say,
`Watch out, Aunt Minnie, another one is coming through.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Vern Ruhle pointed to the fence in right-center,
just short of the power alley. ``How far is it to there?'' he
asked. He was given an estimate of 355 feet. ``Man, that looks
close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large the Houston pitchers, accustomed to the luxury
of the wide-open spaces in the Astrodome, were encouraged by what
their eyes told them. The Enron roof was open, and the day was warm
and muggy. ``The ball might not carry as much as we thought,''
decided Ruhle.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner, the bullpen ace whose fastball has been known to
cause powder burns, stopped by to share the latest inside
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to two of the construction workers,'' he
reported, ``and they said the wind usually blows in from right
field and then moves in circles.''
</P>
<P>
   So much to learn, so many to please, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
