<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-FLORIDA-DONOVAN-H     03-30 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLORIDA-DONOVAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Joan Donovan remembers a night in 1980 when she couldn't sleep and
got up to go to the kitchen at 2 a.m. She walked by the bedroom of
her son, Billy, but he wasn't there. The bed was empty.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She woke up her husband, William, frantic that their 14-year-old
son was gone. William Donovan was much calmer about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' he said. ``I'm sure you will find him up at the
gym.''
</P>
<P>
   William Donovan was right. His son was shooting baskets at St.
Agnes High School while the rest of the Long Island community of
Rockville Centre, N.Y., was under the covers.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Billy Donovan continues to make the extra
effort to get to where he wants to be. That relentless
determination and drive to be the best has his Florida Gators two
games away from a national championship, making Donovan one of the
youngest coaches ever to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I get too caught up in it sometimes, but I've always
been passionate about basketball,'' Donovan said. ``I always tried
to learn and get better as a player, and now I'm trying to learn
and get better as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   They call him ``Billy the Kid,'' a moniker pinned on him by his
mentor Rick Pitino when Donovan's quick shot release at Providence
almost was fast enough to keep up with the speed of his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, 34, can rattle off sentences in his New York accent
faster than most people can process what he's saying. And he has a
lot to say these days about his young team, which has reached the
promised land of college basketball faster than virtually anyone
believed it could.
</P>
<P>
   The running Gators have four freshmen and three sophomores among
the 10-man rotation, which employs a full-court press that leaves
most opponents gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told all our freshmen when they got here that they needed
to be humble,'' Donovan said. ``They needed to understand that they
don't have all the answers. Guys had to understand their role. We
have strength in numbers, which is why our depth is so important.
We can't have guys play 33 or 34 minutes a game in our style of
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't going to tell them that we weren't that good yet,
that we were too young or were probably a year away. I wanted our
players to dream of going to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth season at Florida, Donovan has helped his players
make that dream come true after inheriting a team that won only 12
games the year before Donovan arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But Donovan has done more than win games. He has made basketball
a happening on the Florida campus, where football always has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 23 years at Florida, everybody told me we never would be
a basketball school,'' Florida athletic director Jeremy Foley said.
``I've heard that a thousand times. But Billy has changed all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida had basketball success under former coach Lon Kruger,
reaching the Final Four in 1994. But the Gators never captured the
heart of the fans the way they have since Donovan arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth is these Gators are fun to watch. They run,
they gun, and they have the talent to make highlight reel plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that sent me to Florida more than anything
else,'' sophomore center Udonis Haslem said. ``I wanted to get up
and down the floor. That's the only thing that was promised to me,
that we would press and run the floor, and that appealed to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of basketball Donovan believes in and one of the
reasons he was hired to coach the team when he was only 30, after
two years as head coach at Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of following the pattern we always had followed of
hiring a coach with a proven record, we wanted to find an
up-and-comer,'' Foley said. ``I wanted someone who was looking to
make his mark. I wanted someone with a lot of energy, passion and
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also were looking for a style of play that would bring fans
to the arena. Billy's style of play was important, and his pedigree
was important. But once I met him, I knew he was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's pedigree includes a trip to the Final Four as a player
for Pitino at Providence and as an assistant coach under Pitino at
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino took the job at Providence before Donovan's junior year.
Donovan rode the bench his first two seasons, but Pitino gave him a
chance to start.
</P>
<P>
   He told Donovan to lose 15 pounds over the summer and come back
ready to play. Donovan averaged 15 points a game as a junior and 21
points a game as senior point guard and team captain for Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   After one year in the NBA with the New York Knicks and one year
as a stockbroker on Wall Street, Donovan joined Pitino at Kentucky
as a graduate assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk a lot, but the biggest thing I learned from Rick was to
listen,'' Donovan said. ``A lot of times as a head coach you can
think you have all the answers, but your assistants may view things
differently than you. You may think you have a pulse on things, but
you don't always.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick wants feedback constantly. He squashes egos and gets guys
to buy into the team and the system. He also is extremely
innovative and not afraid to take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan adopted the pressing defense from Pitino, and he has
stuck with it when people said he should be more conservative. He
proved his point when Florida defeated top-ranked Duke 77-65 in the
East Regional semifinals last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said we shouldn't press Duke,'' Donovan said. ``They
said Duke would eat us alive if we did, but we wouldn't have won
the game without pressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said it is Donovan's boundless energy more than his style
of play that has made him successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy always has kept the boy alive in him,'' Pitino said.
``He refuses to grow up. That type of enthusiasm is difficult to
find, but he has it and it's infectious. And no one will outwork
him in recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's recruiting success at Florida has landed him four
McDonald's All-Americans in the last two years _ guards Teddy Dupay
and Brett Nelson and forwards Mike Miller and Donnell Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the court, (Donovan) is energetic and crazy because of his
youth,'' Miller said. ``But on the court, he has the wisdom of a
guy who has been around the game a long time. It surprised me when
I got here how much he knew about the game. In every situation, he
knows what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Dupay are sophomores; Nelson and Harvey are freshmen.
No school in history ever had signed multiple McDonald's
All-Americans in back-to-back years.
</P>
<P>
   It raised some eyebrows and brought accusations of impropriety
from other coaches, including Roy Williams of Kansas and Eddie
Fogler of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was furious when Miller, a South Dakota product, turned
down the Jayhawks to sign with Florida. Williams publicly
questioned Donovan's tactics, but an NCAA investigation showed no
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy and I have talked, and we've agreed to disagree,'' Donovan
said. ``I have tremendous respect for him as a coach, but I did not
like the way he handled that situation. People don't understand how
much work we put in on recruiting. We spent 24 straight days with
Mike Miller. We're aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are coaches who don't want to spend as much time on this
as we do. They don't want to work as hard. Some coaches think a
two-hour home visit is enough, but don't criticize me for taking
advantage of every single minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan has been taking advantage of every minute since his days
back on Long Island, shooting baskets at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the doors to the school gym were locked, but Donovan
cured that problem. He took a bolt cutter and cut off the key lock,
then put on his own combination lock and told the custodian the
necessary numbers. At that point, the custodian just gave Donovan a
key to reach his destination.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan still is working overtime and hoping he has a key to
another destination _ a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
