<HEADLINE>
CSUN BACK IN THE SWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will this be the year Cal State Northridge finally
returns to the NCAA golf tournament?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Bracken thinks it might be, even if he's had to limit
his optimism to baby steps with the most talented team he has
fielded since the former Division II-powerhouse Matadors jumped to
Division I in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just a field-filler anymore,'' said Bracken, whose
team has often finished in the upper half of collegiate tournaments
this year, topped by a second-place finish at San Diego and a fifth
at UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat a lot of good teams at Santa Barbara,'' he said. ``We
played so-so at Irvine (16th of 21 teams Tuesday, 30 strokes behind
winner Washington) but we've been starting to play better. We've
just had a little inconsistency.''
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency, which he says has infected the entire team in
varying degrees, has sometimes produced dramatic consecutive-round
swings _ and not only toward a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bashian, the Matadors' talented freshman from Birmingham
High _ a state amateur finalist last summer _ soared to an 87 in a
Northridge tournament bid at difficult La Purisima, then shot
1-over-par 73 in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of players like Bashian, who has alternated at No. 5
with Lance Dombroski, Chuck Ruiz and Carlos Robledo, and of the
Northridge top four of Anthony Marciano, Paul D'Ambra, Manny Hayes
and Tim Wren (another former State Amateur finalist) keeps Bracken
confident his alma mater will break through to get back to the
playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made it to the Division I regionals yet, and we
were there every year in Division II,'' said Bracken, whose Div. I
recruiting efforts were made difficult for much of the 1990s by
constant rumors that the golf program would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But Bracken, who has been associated as a player or coach with
almost every top player or team the Matadors have produced in golf,
got a recruiting boost two years ago with the school's decision to
retain the golf program.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits could show this season. The Matadors _ last in the
Big Sky Conference last year _ are considered one of the teams to
beat for the Big Sky tournament title, which is accompanied by an
automatic berth to the NCAA West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think we might be favored,'' said Bracken, whose team
has split in four meetings with defending conference champion
Sacramento State and will have at least a traveling advantage for
the Big Sky tournament, since that May 1-3 event will be played at
River Ridge in Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, he'll try to help coax a little more consistency out
of a Northridge team that has had some moments of brilliance,
including top-10 tournament finishes by D'Ambra and Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a lot of talent,'' Bracken said. ``I keep
telling them, `The difference between you guys and some of the
nation's ranked teams is just a little inconsistency.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sometimes, when they're going bad. You just try to
keep them calm and stop the bleeding, tell them to just not make
the mental mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bracken is looking forward to the end-of-the-season Division
I playoff push by the latest edition of a program that produced
Division II team and individual champions and sent Bob Burns on to
the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get together in conference and get to regionals and
play to our ability there, we could surprise some teams.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fore the record: UCLA coach Brad Sherfy of Camarillo is
listed by the Southern California Golf Association as record-holder
at two courses _ De Bell in Burbank (61) and Spanish Hills in
Camarillo (a share at 65).
</P>
<P>
   The SCGA, in its March/April edition of Fore Magazine, includes
a list of record-holders at most Southern California courses, and
many area golfers were named.
</P>
<P>
   Former CSUN players Gary Finneran (his 64 shares the mark at El
Cariso), Patrick Boyd (62 for a share at Porter Valley and 65 at
Steele Canyon), Vic Wilk (61 at Balboa) and Jeff Sanday (62 at SCGA
Members Club, 65 at Primm Valley Desert course and 64 for a share
at Coyote Hills) made the list.
</P>
<P>
   So did former Alemany High standout David Berganio (a share of
the 62 at Porter Valley) and former Granada Hills star Darren Angel
(63 for a share at Knollwood). Agoura Hills resident Matthew Lane
(61 at Braemar East and 63 at Calabasas) and longtime area
instructor Paul Holtby (62 at Braemar West) were among the many
other area golfers on a list that continues to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   __ Drive, putt and chip: The Golf Channel's Drive, Putt and Chip
competition for kids ages 7-12 will be held Wednesday at David L.
Baker Memorial GC in Fountain Valley. The event is open to the
first 120 players who register at the course (10410 Edinger Ave.,
Fountain Valley) on or before Friday. Competition will be in age
groups 7-8, 9-10 and 11-12. Winners have the opportunity to advance
to regional and national events. Information: (714) 418-2152.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Former Westlake High star Brandon DiTullio
won this week's Spaulding/Anteater Invitational at Coto de Caza,
shooting 67-76-70 _ 213 for the only subpar total (3 under) of the
tournament to help the Bruins finish third. UCLA freshman J.T.
Kohut, another former Westlake standout, was the Bruins' No. 4
scorer at Coto de Caza.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Contreras, teaching pro at Verdugo Hills GC (where Kohut
holds the course record with the 11-under-par 43 he shot as an
11-year-old), is coaching the Village Christian high school team
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Former Alemany High star Matt Heyn is averaging 76.8 for the
third-best stroke average at Loyola Marymount. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
