r a BC-CRIME-STATISTICS-LADN     03-30 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-STATISTICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR CRIMES DOWN 50% SINCE 1994
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writers Greg Botonis, Cecilia Chan, Joseph Giordono and
Orith Goldberg contributed to this story) 
By   LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Serious crime plunged across Los Angeles County
and the Greater San Fernando Valley in 1999, continuing a six-year
trend that has yielded a 50 percent drop in crime since 1994,
according to figures released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dramatic decreases overall, violent crime was up in
Burbank, the Van Nuys Division had more homicides, and the Van Nuys
and Devonshire divisions logged more rapes, according to statistics
compiled by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide, crime including homicide, assault and rape was down
8.8 percent, with an even more dramatic decline of 10.5 percent in
the Valley, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Police cited tougher gun laws, a strong economy and particularly
the cooperation of residents as a key to the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley has a very strong Neighborhood Watch, and the
involvement in the community has led to numerous arrests. They're
taking back their streets,'' said LAPD Cmdr. Val Paniccia of the
Valley Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics, covering cities with populations of at least
100,000, show a 13.2 percent decline in crime statewide. Some of
the numbers have been reported previously, including the rise in
homicides in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must continue to fight for more and better prevention plans
that work and that can steer our young people away from delinquency
and crime careers,'' said Attorney General Bill Lockyer.
</P>
<P>
   In Burbank, aggravated assaults rose 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank police spokesman Lt. Robert Giles said he is not alarmed
by the rise. ``I saw the increase in the numbers last month,
dismissed it and filed the paperwork appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles said crime has declined steadily in the city, but it's
just a matter of time before ``the pendulum swings the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show property crimes declined in Burbank by 11
percent and larceny and thefts were down 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley's Devonshire Division, rapes were up 21 percent,
with 93 reports last year, vs. 77 in 1998. In Van Nuys, rapes
increased 20 percent, with 84 in 1999 and 70 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Police attribute the increase largely to their efforts to
encourage people to report rapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing acquaintance-type rapes that we hadn't seen
previously,'' said Lt. Joe Eddy, in charge of detectives at the
Devonshire Division.
</P>
<P>
   Devonshire's figures might also be skewed because the division
acquired a 1.4-square-mile area of Panorama City in 1999 that Van
Nuys previously handled.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Jim Rahm, in charge of the sex crimes section at Van
Nuys, said that recently he has taken more rape reports from women
who accepted rides with men they don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what your mother told you when you were a child: You
don't get into a stranger's car. The same thing applies to adults.
This is a big city and not everybody is a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, people report being raped by their spouses, Rahm
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Van Nuys, the number of homicides increased - with 11 in
1999, compared with seven in 1998, said Lt. Ann Young, in charge of
detectives at Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them were acquaintance homicides where the victims
knew their attackers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Foothill Division in the northeast San Fernando Valley
showed the most significant decrease in crime at 19 percent, with
reported rapes decreasing 30percent, burglaries by 29 percent and
homicides by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other large decreases were Devonshire's homicides,
with 11 in 1999 vs. 17 the year before - a 35 percent decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide, violent crimes, which includes homicides, rapes,
robberies and aggravated assaults, decreased 4.8 percent in 1999
over 1998. Authorities attribute the decline to tough sentencing
laws, more LAPD officers in the past six years, the booming economy
and record low unemployment and innovative crime prevention
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, all crimes are down, with motor vehicle thefts
taking the biggest plunge at 14.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale police spokesman Chahe Keuroghelian attributes the
decrease, in part, to programs such as Community Police
PartnerShip, in which officers broadcast safety tips and inform the
public via local access cable channels. Officers advise residents
on preventive measures, such as buying car alarms, parking on
well-lit streets and locking their garages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage residents to be our eyes and ears and, through
Neighborhood Watch groups or Business Watch groups, whenever they
see suspicious activity, to report it immediately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of crimes reported in Simi Valley dropped nearly 6
percent, with the largest decrease - more than 28 percent - coming
in the category of aggravated assaults, according to figures
released by the Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Oaks reported an 8.1 percent drop in overall crime,
with statistics reflecting a 17.8 percent decline in burglaries,
the report shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very encouraged by the numbers,'' Simi Valley Police
Chief Randy Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   While arson and robberies increased in the Santa Clarita Valley,
serious crimes have gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities linked the arson increase to a surge in car thefts
regionwide - with the thieves dumping cars in remote areas of Santa
Clarita and torching them to destroy evidence. An increase in the
number of small arson incidents by minors in the Canyon Country
area also played a role in the jump, said Los Angeles County
sheriff's Lt. Tim Peters.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in robberies has been a little more baffling, with
a 13 percent rise in the Santa Clarita Valley and a 33 percent rise
within city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Serious crimes in Lancaster dropped from 5,405 in 1998 to 4,155
in 1999, down 23.1 percent, and from 4,836 to 3,906 in Palmdale,
down 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
