r a BC-RABBIS-MARRIAGE-SFCHR     03-30 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBIS-MARRIAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATTIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 JEWISH REFORM RABBIS VOTE IN FAVOR OF SAME-SEX CEREMONIES  By DON &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Backers of gay and lesbian marriage won a major moral victory
Wednesday when the rabbis of the Jewish Reform movement
overwhelmingly voted to support same-sex ceremonies in their
synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in Greensboro, N.C., the Central Conference of American
Rabbis adopted a resolution stating that ``a Jewish same gender
couple is worthy of affirmation through appropriate Jewish
ritual.'' The statement directs the conference to produce
educational materials and a new liturgy for same-sex ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Individual rabbis and congregations in the 1.5 million-member
Reform movement are free to perform the ceremonies or not,
depending on their individual conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The vote makes the Reform movement the third major religious
denomination to adopt a national policy allowing same-sex
ceremonies, following the Unitarian Universalist Association and
the United Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, many Reform rabbis are already conducting
same-sex ceremonies in their synagogues. Nevertheless, Wednesday's
vote puts the nation's largest _ and most liberal _ rabbinic
organization on record as supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Eric Weiss, one of three national coordinators of the Gay
and Lesbian Rabbinic Network, said Wednesday's vote was a welcome
relief after the passage of Proposition 22, the California ballot
measure that limits civil marriage rights to heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an undercurrent in that campaign of people in the
religious community saying our unions were not worthy of
sanctification,'' said Weiss, the executive director of the Bay
Area Jewish Healing Center in San Francisco. ``This vote is a
prophetic call for other religious denominations to follow as a
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Other religious denominations will soon have that chance.
Between May and July, national policy-making conventions of
Methodists, Episcopalians and Presbyterians will address the
hot-button issue of homosexual marriage. Gay and lesbian activists
are expected to face much tougher opposition in those Christian
venues.
</P>
<P>
   While the gay marriage proposal was overwhelmingly approved by
the Reform rabbis, more conservative Jewish leaders were dismayed
by the vote, saying it would further isolate the Reform movement
from Orthodox Judaism in Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of RABBIS30 (80351 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I'm saddened by it,'' said Rabbi Jacob Traub of Adath Israel,
an Orthodox synagogue in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Traub said he did not believe the Jewish marriage ceremony
should be ``lightly adopted'' to conform to ever-changing moral
views.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Jewish marriage to homosexuals, Traub said, will
certainly not help the Reform rabbis in Israel, where they have
been struggling to establish themselves in a religious world
dominated by Orthodox Judaism. ``They're shooting themselves in the
foot,'' Traub said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Stephen Pearce of Congregation Emanu-El, the largest
Reform movement synagogue in San Francisco, said the American
Jewish clergy shouldn't worry about how their actions will play in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned with what they think,'' Pearce said.
``Nothing short of donning black hats and observing Orthodox
rituals day in and day out will satisfy them.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, the Reform movement has charted its own
Jewish course, allowing the ordination of women in 1973 and voting
in 1990 to open their rabbinic ranks to gay and lesbian clergy.
They have also separated themselves from Orthodox Jews by
proclaiming that Jewishness is passed on by either the mother and
the father. Orthodox Judaism believes only in matrilineal descent.
</P>
<P>
   Women rabbis led the campaign for same-sex ceremonies in Reform
movement synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Shira Stern, co-president of the Women's Rabbinic Network,
which first proposed the resolution two years ago, said Wednesday's
vote is ``as much a civil rights issue as it is a religious
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will strengthen Jewish families by recognizing the sacred
relationship between two Jews,'' she said, ``whether they be
homosexual or heterosexual.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christians opposed to gay marriage in their
churches often cite the Old Testament's condemnation of homosexual
intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Allen Bennett of Temple Israel, a Reform synagogue in
Alameda, said his colleagues do not believe the Hebrew Bible
condemns homosexuality as it is understood in modern society.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many other things we have decided are no longer
applicable in Scripture,'' said Bennett, who is gay. ``There's a
passage in the Bible that says a child who disobeys should be
stoned to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said he has conducted at least three dozen gay marriage
ceremonies over the past 10 years, but none at his Alameda
synagogue, where he has served for 31/2 years. ``I haven't been
asked to do one at the synagogue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Congregational Emanu-El, Pearce estimates that he performs
five or six homosexual marriages a year. He said he'd probably do
more, but many gays and lesbians in San Francisco go to
Congregation Sha'ar Zahav, a Reform movement synagogue with a
special outreach to gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgendered Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GAY-FINGERS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-FINGERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINGER LENGTH POINTS TO SEXUAL ORIENTATION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ In a study sure to provoke a lot of
self-examination, a University of California at Berkeley team has
found that differences in the lengths of one's fingers may yield
clues about sexual orientation.
<P>
   Lesbians on average turned out to have more ``masculine'' hands
than heterosexual women _ with the index finger significantly
shorter than the ring finger. There was no such difference in the
hands of gay and straight men, however.
</P>
<P>
   A brief summary of the study, led by Berkeley psychologist S.
Marc Breedlove and undergraduates Terrance J. Williams and Michelle
E. Pepitone, appeared Wednesday in the science journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Although the results may seem a bit puzzling, experts said it's
only the latest of several studies that suggest hormones in the
womb have a powerful affect on sexual orientation and behavior
throughout life.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research has found certain differences in brain
structures as well as other anatomical distinctions between gays
and straights.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is mixed, however, and nobody claimed the latest
findings will settle the debate over how sexual orientation is
shaped by biology versus environmental factors.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can finger lengths be used as a reliable guide to very much
of anything, although it's long been known that men tend to have
longer fingers than women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences are subtle,'' said Raymond Blanchard, a
pioneer in gender and sexuality studies at the University of
Toronto's Center for Addiction and Mental Health. ``There's no way
anybody could use this to screen a date.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest study was based on the fact, which was already
apparent to scientists, that males tend to have a different pattern
of finger lengths than females.
</P>
<P>
   In men, the index finger tends to be a bit shorter than the ring
finger. These same two fingers on women are typically about the
same length. The male-female difference tends to be more pronounced
on the right hand, for reasons experts cannot explain, regardless
of whether the person is left- or right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   These gender differences can be picked up in very young
children, strongly suggesting they arise because of prenatal
influences. Based on a host of animal studies and other research,
it's almost certainly a product of androgen levels _ testosterone
and other male hormones _ in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists now suspect that finger lengths may be a marker of
how much a fetus was exposed to these masculinizing sex hormones.
The same prenatal influences may affect behavior and sexual
identity throughout life.
</P>
<P>
   Breedlove and his Berkeley colleagues appear to be the first
academic researchers to bother checking whether there is any
appreciable difference in finger-length ratios linked to sexual
orientation in adults.
</P>
<P>
   They set up booths last summer at a gay pride event in Oakland,
the annual Solano Stroll in Berkeley and at the Castro Street Fair
in San Francisco. Fairgoers were offered a free $1 lottery ticket
in exchange for having their hands photocopied and filling out a
detailed questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the hands of 720 adults, Breedlove's team
discovered that the average finger-length pattern for lesbians
closely resembled that of males. That is, the index fingers on
lesbians who were surveyed was judged to be significantly shorter
than the ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers concluded that ``at least some homosexual women were
exposed to greater levels of fetal androgen than heterosexual
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand patterns between gay men and heterosexual men revealed no
such difference. But the surveys yielded other intriguing clues.
</P>
<P>
   It was already known that men with more than one older brother
are slightly more apt to grow up to be homosexual than are
firstborn males.
</P>
<P>
   The new study suggested that males with older brothers are
subjected to higher levels of androgens in the womb than are eldest
sons.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the study says, men with more than one older
brother have a significantly more masculine right hand than men
without older brothers. That is, the right index finger is more
often shorter than the ring finger on the same hand.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such effect in men with older sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Breedlove said it's a complete mystery as to how a mother's body
could ``remember'' how many male children she had borne, where this
signal was kept and how it could influence hormone levels of a
later-born child.
</P>
<P>
   He also cautioned against making too much of the differences in
the hands of gay and straight women, noting it's an extremely
subtle distinction that holds true only when large numbers of hands
are averaged and compared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't use this to classify people,'' he said. ``If it were
that obvious, it probably would have been written about by
Aristotle a long time ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
