<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SMOG-FEE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-FEE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS WANTS TO SIGN SMOG-FEE REFUND CHECKS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis proposed spending millions more
than is necessary to give refunds to motorists who paid illegal
smog impact fees so that his administration _ and not the state
controller's office _ can mail the checks, sources have told The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The action is the latest jab by Davis in his long-running feud
with Controller Kathleen Connell, a fellow Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   At Davis' request, the two bills authorizing the refund for 1.7
million Californians who paid the $300 fee since 1990 would give
the Department of Motor Vehicles nearly $11 million to administer
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bustamante, Davis' press secretary, said the chance for
gubernatorial publicity never even played into Davis' decision to
transfer the check-cutting task to the DMV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most cost-effective way to get it done. There's
less hands involved. That means less costs,'' Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft breakdown of the department's estimated
costs, that $11 million includes 77 employees at a cost of $5.2
million over two years and operating costs of $5.6 million _
$976,519 of which is postage.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative budget writers say the task of mailing out refund
checks is better handled _ at far less cost _ by the state
controller's office, whose primary job is mailing out state checks.
</P>
<P>
   According to controller's office records, it costs that office
about 40 cents to process a claim check. That includes labor,
printing, stuffing, mailing and postage.
</P>
<P>
   Mailing checks to the potential smog-fee refund recipients who
registered out-of-state cars with the DMV after moving to
California would cost the controller $680,000.
</P>
<P>
   The independent legislative analyst's office believes the checks
should be sent out by the controller's office, ``given that
office's expertise in reviewing claims and disbursing revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   The DMV counters that much of its expense is finding the people
eligible for a refund and that operating costs will probably be
lower than estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (cost estimates) are very preliminary. We've already cut
those by more than $750,000 in one area alone,'' said Evan Nossoff,
a DMV spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis decided in November to refund the money, plus interest,
and has allocated $665 million in his proposed budget to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The move came a few weeks after an appeals court ruled
unconstitutional the $300 fee that must be paid by people who move
to California and register their out-of-state automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The bill containing the funds, AB809, is scheduled to be heard
by the Senate Appropriations Committee Thursday. The two bills that
implement the return of the fee are expected to be on Davis' desk
by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping the job of refunding the fees within his
administration, Davis would be able to sign the checks, a
responsibility usually reserved for the controller.
</P>
<P>
   Among the department's proposed expenditures is a $223,106 media
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may have sold the car. They may have changed addresses.
We need to get the word out to these people,'' Nossoff said.
</P>
<P>
   A new database will also have to be created, at a cost of
$499,999, the department estimates. Paper costs for the computers
is pegged at $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Connell have been at odds since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A performance audit Connell commissioned when she became
controller found that her predecessor, Davis, had committed some
questionable acts, including one on his last day on the job _
allowing a major developer to postpone making a lease payment to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on the final night of the legislative session, Davis
tried to win passage of bill that would strip Connell of her seat
on the Franchise Tax Board. The bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   After a ``60 Minutes'' segment on fraud within Medi-Cal, the
state's health program for the poor, featured extensive footage of
Connell, Davis proposed in January a major increase in his
administration's Medi-Cal fraud investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Connell had sought more personnel to do the same thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
