<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SETTLE FOR TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The sellout crowd Wednesday wasn't sold.
</P>
<P>
   They came to see the Los Angeles Kings move closer to just their
second playoff appearance in seven years and did get a listless 1-1
tie against the San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, the Kings would have beaten the Sharks, then
clinched the postseason Saturday against the Mighty Ducks. Instead,
the Staples Center crowd of 18,118 was quiet and so were the Kings
(36-30-11).
</P>
<P>
   The tie gave them 87 points and did move them closer to the
playoffs. If the season ended today, they would finish fifth in the
Western Conference and open the first round against the Detroit Red
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   But what was more surprising was the way the Sharks, who are
clinging to the eighth and final spot, didn't show more fire.
Captain Owen Nolan, who has five goals this season against the
Kings, had just one shot the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, who entered the game third in the league with 85 points
and second in goals (44), was struck in the mouth two games ago
against Vancouver. He has continued to play, he just hasn't scored,
going without a goal for the third straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings went 2-0-1 on their recent East Coast
trip, they rarely played inspired after last Thursday's 3-2
overtime victory in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   They came back two days later in Boston and needed three
third-period goals to tie the Bruins. They closed out the trip with
a 4-1 victory against the expansion Atlanta Thrashers, who were
winless in their previous 16 home games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings are playing without Ziggy Palffy and Nelson
Emerson, two of their better offensive threats who could be
sidelined for the final two weeks of the regular season with
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy (sprained right shoulder) could be back next week for a
playoff tuneup, but Emerson, who scored one goal in four games
since coming over from Atlanta, might miss the first round with a
broken left index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Without them, the Kings didn't have much offense. Leading scorer
Luc Robitaille, who has 36 goals for the season and three in his
last three games, had just one shot in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake had the Kings' best scoring chance in
overtime when he skated in on Sharks goaltender Steve Shields and
took a slap shot from in close.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose (32-35-10) had the better of OT, getting five of its 25
shots in the extra session. The best chance was a breakaway by
Vincent Damphousse with 2:30 left.
</P>
<P>
   He intercepted a pass from Bryan Smolinski intended for Blake,
but his shot on Stephane Fiset sailed wide.
</P>
<P>
   A listless first period ended with a flurry when Kelly
Buchberger scored his first goal as a King at 19:18.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sean O'Donnell set up behind the San Jose net and
pushed a pass in front, where Buchberger beat Shields.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks tied the game midway though the second period on a
goal by Niklas Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   With Steve McKenna off for hooking, San Jose pressured Fiset.
Mike Ricci fired from the point and Sundstrom poked in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had a chance to take the lead in the final minute of
the second period. Glen Murray, who had two goals in the comeback
against Boston, made a slick cross-ice pass. Jozef Stumpel was
waiting and fired, but Shields made the stop.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel was at the center of another scoring opportunity early
in the third. Craig Johnson, who has joined Murray on the
reconfigured first line, took a shot that was stopped by the
sprawling Shields.
</P>
<P>
   The puck popped to Stumpel, who was looking at nothing but net.
Shields' only defense was his stick across the goalmouth and he
somehow managed to stop Stumpel's shot on goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
