<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CRITICIZE HILLARY FOR VISIT TO WOMEN'S EVENT IN S.F.
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton came to San
Francisco Wednesday for a women's high-tech event _ but took sharp
criticism from Republicans who charged that her California visits
disguise a glut of taxpayer-funded political fund raising for her
U.S. Senate bid.
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to appear in her official function as
first lady at an event for the San Francisco Women's Technology
Cluster, a high-tech ``incubator'' for female entrepreneurs. But
her three-day California trip was top-heavy with eight political
fund-raisers to benefit her Senate campaign _ all of them out of
the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area alone, she was the guest of honor at two
fund-raisers in private homes Wednesday _ one at the home of Apple
Computer founder Steve Jobs _ both off-limits to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong and unfair of her to use taxpayer money to go
around the country raising funds for her campaign,'' said Clifford
May, spokesman for the Republican National Committee, who called
the practice ``unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Senate campaign staff was decidedly reluctant to
discuss her fund-raising activities this week. It did not return
numerous phone calls from The Chronicle requesting information on
Clinton's campaign events in California.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Dunn, a campaign spokeswoman reached Wednesday, insisted
her office had no idea how many fund raisers Clinton had attended
here _ or what they expected to raise.
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady's own White House schedule listed a nonstop
schedule of such events in such tony California communities as
Beverly Hills and La Jolla after her arrival late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York Senate race heating up _ and Clinton appearing
to catch up in the polls with GOP challenger Rudolph Guiliani _ the
apparent reluctance to be forthcoming about her fund-raising
activities could present a thorny problem for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore, still under fire for
past fund-raising activities, has attempted to seize the campaign
finance reform issue from Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the California trip underscored the often fuzzy line between
Clinton's official role as first lady and her status as a
candidate. And it illustrated how _ like her husband, President
Clinton _ she has found the nation's most populous state to be a
gold mine of campaign donation checks.
</P>
<P>
   Federal elections records show that the first lady has raised
more than $316,000 from California donors during the current
election cycle. That is almost half as much as U.S. Rep. Tom
Campbell, the South Bay Republican campaigning to unseat California
Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who has picked up $674,450 from
individual donors in California.
</P>
<P>
   Guiliani has also turned to California as a source of
contributions, raising more than $380,000 from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour roundtable session Wednesday, Clinton met with
top female CEOS to discuss issues of women and technology
Wednesday, among them, Lavonne Luquis of Latino.com, Tiffany Bass
Bukow of Ms.Money.com and Cate Muther of the Women's Technology
Cluster.
</P>
<P>
   As first lady, Clinton dutifully asked about the problems of
business startups, financial challenges and the biases they
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also assured the women she would take their feedback
and ideas ``back to Silicon Alley'' _ a reference to the New York
high-tech industry. And she got a laugh when she asked Kim Fisher,
the CEO of AudioBasket, how to use her product if ``I'm interested
in New York state politics, just to pick a topic.''
</P>
<P>
   Some attendees were even more aggressive in using the
opportunity to push her campaign. ``I'm looking forward to all of
us ensuring her a seat in the Senate as soon as November 2000,''
Mayor Willie Brown told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say such events keenly illustrate how Clinton has
used her first lady status to unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason in the world why she couldn't charter a
campaign plane like other candidates do and pay for it by funds
contributed by willing donors _ rather than taxpayers who have no
choice,'' said May of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in San Francisco Wednesday on an Air Force
plane, but ``she flies on that for security reasons everywhere she
goes,'' said a White House spokeswoman Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's longtime friends and supporters say the GOP criticism
is just the latest example of unfair singling out of the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be ashamed of themselves. If nothing else, they
should afford respect to the first lady of the United States. She's
doing what she ought to be doing, according to the Secret Service,
to protect her security,'' said Martha Whetstone, a longtime
Democratic activist and family friend of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Chairwa, associate counsel for the president, said that on
a trip that involves campaign activity, the law requires
reimbursement by the campaign at a first-class rate for the first
lady as well as for her staff. She said that would include a trip,
such as the one to San Francisco, which involved both fund raising
and official first lady events.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are being increasingly vocal on the issue,
dubbing her junkets ``Air Hillary,'' and releasing a recent RNC
noting that _ according to the Air Force's own estimates _ it costs
taxpayers as much as $3,705 an hour for the trips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
