<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS' THEME: ESCAPE FROM THE 8-HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As the regular season, like the fan base, dwindles, it
is still possible to find something upon which the rare Sonics fan
can hang a hat.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only a gerbil hat. But take the rewards as they are
found. Beats ducking a TV remote control.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics reach 45 wins, they will have the best record in
the 17-year history of eighth seeds in the NBA postseason
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Yee. Hah.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's not the sort of thing that shuts down Fifth Avenue
for ticker tape (although we could throw a spectacular
concrete-dust parade).
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible that 45 wins would get them the No. 7 spot,
and thus avoid wasting an otherwise lovely spring week banging
around in the armpits of Shaquille O'Neal, a hell whose foulness
defies even Dante and his inferno.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics coach Paul Westphal, normally a man of reticence when it
comes to even harmless candor, owned up to the obvious wretched
fate awaiting a first-round match-up against the top-seeded Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make the playoffs, so we're fighting for
positioning,'' Westphal said after Monday's loss to San Antonio.
``We're like everybody else. We'd rather not play the Lakers.
That's a tall order.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing as No. 8 already is free of gratuitous prestige _ only
nine of the previous 32 eighth seeds have had winning records, the
best being the 44 mark of the 1997 Washington Bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Then to draw what might be the most formidable Western team
since the late-'80s Lakers of Magic Johnson, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
and James Worthy, well, the question of pointlessness is hard to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Westphal and president Wally Walker guaranteed in the
preseason the Sonics would return to the playoffs, and they will
(cue up concrete-dust parade, again). Even if Vernon Maxwell hits
Horace Grant with a sofa, there's no way the Sonics fall to No. 9,
their finish last year.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Other than a single home playoff game's ticket
revenues, how much difference is there between missing the playoffs
and going 0-3 in the first round?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Sonics owe it to whomever cares that they claw
their way out of the 8-hole as if it were a pit of vipers and they
are Indiana Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Already visible at nearly every KeyArena home game is the
vacant-seat damage attributable at least in part to a single season
without a playoff win. Two consecutive years of no postseason
victories after six seasons as a Western power represents a decay
beyond the reach of the nation's dentists.
</P>
<P>
   By getting to the seventh or sixth seed, the Sonics draw one
among Utah, San Antonio and suddenly vulnerable Portland. The
Sonics split the four-game season series with the Jazz and Spurs,
and although they are 0-3 against the Blazers, they are still the
Blazers, with the rich tradition of postseason evaporation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, forecasting a No. 7 or No. 6 berth would appear to be a
clutch at straws, given recent evidence. Prior to Wednesday night's
blowout loss to the Knicks, in the last four games against
playoff-bound San Antonio, Utah, Detroit and Portland, the Sonics
led in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They blew all the leads, and the games. At home.
</P>
<P>
   As Westphal put it after the Monday loss, ``We ran out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Acute NBA observers will suggest this is not a good sign,
especially within three weeks of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a lack of depth and previous injuries, Grant, 34, the
Sonics' only forceful big man, is worn down. Gary Payton (aka the
Boxing Glove) is wearing down. The standard opponent defensive
trick is to double-team Payton, the league leader in minutes
played, in the late stages and dare someone else to win the game.
No one has lately.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Spurs, Payton was shut down late, the Sonics missed
14 of 20 field goal attempts in the final period and finished with
a season-low five free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Grant had not been injured playing the referee's
role in Sonic Smackdown Sunday, the result might have been
different. And if the Sonics miss the No. 7 spot by a game, your
search for the single most unnecessary loss of the season might
start with that contest.
</P>
<P>
   The spin out of the Sonic camp is that the Payton-Maxwell dustup
may well have some perversely tonic effect from here on out. The
problem with that theory is if true, by mid-April, Sonics practices
will graduate to dope-slapping sessions broken up by turnbuckle
smashes and airborne TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the final 11 games, starting with current No. 7
seed Sacramento Friday, the Sonics have to find a more functional
way out of the 8-hole, and get to a playoff series where they have
a chance to salvage a little something.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, local hoops fans face an entire off-season of stories
explaining, defending and apologizing for Payton's, ahem,
eccentrism.
</P>
<P>
   I'd prefer a concrete-dust parade.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
