<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME ACHE CONTINUES FOR LISTLESS SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONADL TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Hanging over Horace Grant's locker was a yellow piece
of paper with big, bold type.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' veteran center had been preaching all week about the
team's sagging disposition. Wednesday, he borrowed a quote by
Charles Swindoll to amplify his point with a sign that partly read:
``Attitude ... is more than the past, more than money, more than
circumstances. ... Life is 10 percent what happens to me and 90
percent how I react.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing to adapt,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   As profound and somewhat effective as the message was, it was no
antidote for the Sonics, who looked jury-rigged in a 110-95 loss to
the New York Knicks Wednesday night at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' reconditioned posture lasted about four minutes at
the start of the game. New York used the next 44 minutes to hammer
the Sonics into their fifth consecutive loss _ all at home. This is
the first time the Sonics have staggered on such a skid since the
1984-85 season when they dropped six in a row at home.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest back-breakers was the discrepancy in
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   New York grabbed 57. The Sonics collected just 30 _ one shy of
their season low. In essence, the Sonics, who have been beaten
every way imaginable lately, found another way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   This loss prompted Sonics coach Paul Westphal to tell his team,
``If you're not going to put forth a better effort than that, stay
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Absentee players would only decrease the team's sagging and
increasingly unsympatheic crowd. This was the sixth time in the
past seven games the Sonics fell at KeyArena. Half the crowd
cheered the Knicks, which added to the list of disheartening facts
about the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Sonics brace themselves for the Sacramento Kings, who
visit KeyArena Friday. The Sonics already have lost twice to the
Kings and are 1{ games behind them in eighth place of the Western
Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we gave up. It was effort. There was no
effort,'' Grant said. ``We've got to stop being selfish. Early in
the season when we were moving the ball, we were winning. Now, it's
me, me, me. And that's not going to work around here. If you put
yourself before the team, the team's going to lose. So if we stop
doing that, we might be OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, the team in Orlando is not talented. We're a more
talented team. But that team has more heart and determination. Even
when they're down, they play hard. I haven't seen this (lack of
energy) in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup guard Vernon Maxwell, who went 3-for-8 in 15 minutes,
admitted he needed an attitude adjustment and the onus doesn't stop
at his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs to look in the mirror,'' Maxwell said. ``The
effort level could be a lot better than the way we've been playing.
We need to channel our energy in another direction instead of
worrying about shots and minutes. I'm pointing the finger at
myself. I've got to get myself right.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Sonics started the game with fire a day after what
was described as the most spirited practice of the season. They
jumped on the Knicks with a 15-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   However, the early blaze burned out like a match. New York
doused the Sonics' fast start with a 12-0 offensive spurt, and the
first quarter ended in a 30-30 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks slowly overpowered the Sonics from there.
</P>
<P>
   New York held a 28-18 rebounding edge by halftime and dominated
the offensive glass. Overall, the Knicks had 18 offensive rebounds.
They shot 43 of 82 (52 percent), and essentially recovered almost
half their misses.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby provided spark off the Knicks' bench with 18 points
and a career-high 19 boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' starting frontline amassed just 11 rebounds. Grant
and Vin Baker each had four. Ruben Patterson finished with three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do our job,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 59-49 at halftime, the Sonics seemed
anxious.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took an 84-71 advantage into the final frame. A pair
of Rashard Lewis 3-pointers got the Sonics within 85-79. But New
York never lost control and eventually led 102-82 with 4:18 left in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we can win games,'' said Westphal, referring to
the Sonics' 40-31 record. ``We've just got to find a formula to
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of a couch.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
