<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEWKING-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIE PUTS KINGS ONE STEP CLOSER
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Success is measured this time of year by cut lips
and missing teeth. Ties bring smiles. So does a good forecheck.
</P>
<P>
   Fans shouldn't feel let down by the Kings' 1-1 tie with the San
Jose Sharks on Wednesday night at Staples Center. If they do it
again Saturday afternoon against the Mighty Ducks, the Kings will
be in the playoffs for just the second time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Kings have two losses and two ties against the
Ducks and were 1-5 a year ago. But this time, a repeat of
Wednesday's game will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the way it is at this point in the season,''
defenseman Mattias Norstrom said. ``Nothing fancy. Nobody wants to
be the one that messes up with so much at stake. We feel we are
getting close, but we are taking nothing for granted. The little
things will get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The little things Wednesday were strong defense and a first-
period goal by newcomer Kelly Buchberger, brought here from Atlanta
to direct traffic in heavy-handed games like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why we got him,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said. ``And
tonight we had 19 other Buchbergers playing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And just as important was the close watch the Kings put on
Sharks captain Owen Nolan, who had five goals against them this
season. Nolan, second in the league with 44 goals, had just one
shot before leaving in the second period with an injured left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the kind of game played in the middle of the ice,''
Buchberger's linemate, Bob Corkum, said. ``It was a very
tight-checking game. There are five games left and that is the way
it is going to be the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings went 2-0-1 on their recent East Coast
trip, it has become clear that offense is at a premium, especially
without Ziggy Palffy and the other Kings newcomer, Nelson Emerson,
both out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy (sprained right shoulder) could be back next week for a
playoff tuneup, but Emerson, who scored one goal in four games
since coming over from Atlanta, might miss the first round with a
broken left index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Without them, the Kings don't have much firepower. Leading
scorer Luc Robitaille, who has 36 goals for the season and three in
his last three games, had just two shots in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake had the Kings' best scoring chance in
overtime when he skated in on Sharks goaltender Steve Shields just
20 seconds in and took a slap shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose (32-35-10), which has the eighth and final playoff spot
in the West, had the better of OT, getting five of its 25 shots in
the extra session. The Sharks' best chance was a breakaway by
Vincent Damphousse with 2:30 left. He intercepted a pass from Bryan
Smolinski intended for Blake, but his shot on Stephane Fiset sailed
wide.
</P>
<P>
   A listless first period ended with a flurry when Buchberger
scored his first goal as a King at 19:18.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sean O'Donnell set up behind the San Jose net and
pushed a pass in front, where Buchberger beat Shields.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks tied the game midway though the second period on a
goal by Niklas Sundstrom. With Steve McKenna off for hooking, San
Jose pressured Fiset. Mike Ricci fired from the point and Sundstrom
poked in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had a chance to take the lead in the final minute of
the second period. Glen Murray, who had two goals in Saturday's
comeback against Boston, made a slick cross-ice pass. Jozef Stumpel
was waiting and fired, but Shields made the stop.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel was at the center of another scoring opportunity early
in the third. Craig Johnson, who has joined Murray on the
reconfigured first line, took a shot that was stopped by the
sprawling Shields.
</P>
<P>
   The puck popped to Stumpel, who was looking at nothing but net.
Shields' only defense was his stick across the goalmouth and he
somehow managed to stop Stumpel's shot on goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
