<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DEMAND-PUBLISHING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY ALTERS LITERARY LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or
888-603-1036.) 
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Bronski watched sales of his first book wither to 75
copies a year, kept alive only by a few protective editors who
refused to let the bottom line overtake the written word.
</P>
<P>
   But just as ``Culture Clash'' was poised to go out of print
anyway, a new technology, called Publishing On Demand, came along
and offered the Cambridge, Mass. author every writer's dream:
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   In its incarnation, ``Culture Clash,'' which first appeared in
1984, now has no cover, no pages, and appears in no bookshops. In
fact, it's just a series of ones and zeroes in a computer that sits
in a warehouse outside Nashville. Today, the book is available
solely through Internet bookstores, and reenters the physical world
only when a customer orders it, at which time the computer prints
it, binds it, and ships it out.
</P>
<P>
   Bronski calls the new ``POD'' technology a ``godsend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When on-demand publishing came along, it was wonderful,''
Bronski said. ``It created a middle ground where books that are
perceived to have some worth and some faint hope of future selling
power can remain available.''
</P>
<P>
   Megabestseller Stephen King made headlines this month by
publishing his latest work in electronic form, with computer and
Palm Pilot users gobbling it up. But for the majority of authors,
the foot soldiers of publishing, POD is blunting the edge of one of
capitalism's most cutthroat industries, even as some critics
express concern that it will flood the market with lousy books.
</P>
<P>
   Half literary cryogenics and half editorial life-support, POD is
being called ``revolutionary'' by everyone from bookstore
executives to editors, unknown authors to bibliophiles because it
allows publishers to store and print books for a fraction of what
it once cost.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, POD has opened a promising new route for
aspiring authors to gain fame, by allowing them to self-publish
quickly and cheaply, then sell their volumes at popular Internet
bookstores such as Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   But if POD is changing the literary landscape, it is doing so in
wildly unpredictable fashion. Some publishers and authors _ never
the best of friends to begin with _ now accuse one another of
taking unfair advantage of the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Others complain that POD books are substandard. Still others
complain that POD will subvert a useful process in which critics
and publishers weeded out substandard works and guided readers to
works of quality.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many are debating whether the brave new future will
be as rosy as the good old days of sell or die.
</P>
<P>
   For Bronski, there's no debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to overstate my case, but there is nothing more
thrilling than knowing my book will be available for readers
throughout the foreseeable future,'' Bronski said. ``That's not how
things go in publishing. Only Agatha Christie and Stephen King got
that treatment before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronski was not exaggerating the dire odds most authors face. Of
the 61,000 new titles published in the United States annually,
50,000 of them, both paperbacks and tomes, end up in the literary
graveyard, victims of weak sales, a lack of promotion, and
sometimes, bad writing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the estimated 10,000 books that have gone POD in recent
years _ with another 1,500 being added monthly _ several are works
by ``important'' authors. Victor Navasky's ``Kennedy Justice,'' a
profile of Robert F. Kennedy's years as US attorney general and a
National Book Award nominee, is one of them. Others include volumes
by Mary McCarthy and Thornton Wilder, as well as bestsellers by
one-hit wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Still more POD books are the forgotten novels and textbooks that
sociologists, historians, and anthropologists rely on, works that
open a window into the era from which they emerged. Another trend
in POD: university presses are embracing the technology en masse,
saying it allows them to continue producing works of limited
interest that otherwise would have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear about what POD can do, it's thrilling,'' says
Paul Aiken, executive director of the Authors Guild, which
represents more than 8,000 writers.
</P>
<P>
   The Authors Guild has been at the forefront of the POD
revolution. In the next few weeks, 100 books that had gone out of
print will come back to life, thanks to the guild's
Backinprint.com, which is helping authors or their estates revive
forgotten works. Another 300 titles will follow shortly afterward,
Aiken said.
</P>
<P>
   But if many books in the burgeoning POD library make a good
argument for the technology, others do the opposite. In the past
few months, hundreds of unknown authors, with questionable writing
talent, have gone to fledgling POD publishers such as iuniverse.com
and 1stbooks.com, handed them several hundred dollars, and created
``books.'' Unlike the so-called vanity presses of old, the POD
publishers offer unknown authors something never before available:
a spot on the virtual shelves of Internet bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Azzolina, a former bank executive who lives in
Charlestown, recently published a mystery novel called ``Suicide
Inc.'' with 1stbooks, one of the most popular POD houses. Although
``Suicide Inc.'' ranks 1,784,179th on Amazon.com's list, the fact
that his book is available at all shows POD is a sure thing,
Azzolina said. Readers will judge for themselves if the book is a
good one, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had three agents and been close to sales with Putnam,
Viking, and Mysterious Press; I've paid my dues with the big
boys,'' Azzolina said. ``This is not an industry willing to take
chances and bring new authors along. If we as authors are going to
make things happen, we have to do it ourselves. POD, if done
properly, is the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   How readers will ever find ``Suicide Inc.'' in the sea of
available reading, no one knows. Book critics still regard
self-published books with skepticism, if not contempt, and the new
POD phenomenon has done little to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional publishing route seems like a good
gatekeeper,'' said Charles McGrath, editor of the New York Times
Book Review. McGrath said the Times, as well as most major sources
of reviews, avoid self-published books for two reasons: lack of
quality and lack of availability.
</P>
<P>
   The latter reason, McGrath said, may no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't known this was going on,'' McGrath said of the
partnerships between Internet booksellers and POD publishers. ``It
seems one of our rationales is eroding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say POD may erode the power structure of publishing as
well. Traditionally, the rights to a book have reverted back to
authors when a book went out of print. Thanks to POD, however,
several publishers are now creating digital versions of books, and
refusing to return them.
</P>
<P>
   While many publishers are now rewriting contracts to
specifically address the POD issue, thousands of authors who signed
contracts in the past several years are now finding that they may
never regain the rights to their books.
</P>
<P>
   That has authors crying foul. Recently, the National Writers
Union warned its members that POD poses ``a serious threat to the
rights of authors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-edged sword,'' said Frank Romano, a professor of
digital printing at the Rochester Institute of Technology.
``On-demand publishing makes it easier for publishers to not give
up books. But at the same time, it makes it easier for authors to
avoid publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins the power struggle, few argue that POD
books have a long way to go before they resemble those created by
more traditional printing methods. Right now, POD books come only
in soft-cover, and photos can only be reproduced in black and
white. Cover art, too, seems to have lost its cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give my POD copies to business acquaintances,'' Brodski
says.
</P>
<P>
   As the technology gets better, though, there's a good chance
that the peculiar social dilemma Brodski now endures will be a
thing of the past. Steve Riggio, vice chairman of
BarnesandNoble.com, says he foresees a day when every bookshop in
America will have a small, POD machine, so customers will never
have to leave the store empty-handed because their favorite book
was out of stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is the democratization of publishing,'' Riggio
said. ``When something is that important, the quality follows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-22-00 1340EST &QL;
</P>
