u a BC-CPT-EPOCRATES-SFCHRON     03-30 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EPOCRATES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Medical Data in a Doctor's Palm  
 By Benny Evangelista   
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week, a young patient came to Dr. Charles
Shaefer with a miserable cold and heavy congestion. Shaefer was
about to prescribe an antibiotic but then remembered the young
man's dermatologist had prescribed acne medicine that might not
react well with the antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
   So to check, the veteran Georgia physician reached into his
pocket for a Palm loaded with a prescription drug reference program
made by ePocrates Inc. of San Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lo and behold, the drug I was going to give him could have
caused increased pressure on the brain, not the kind of thing you
want when you're trying to treat a cold,'' Shaefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaefer, like many physicians, is not easily won over by new
gadgets. But in the past three months, Shaefer says he has come to
think of ePocrates and his stethoscope as his two most
indispensable medical tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to two or three times a day, I feel like I have made better
decisions because I have consulted the ePocrates program,'' said
Shaefer, an internal and critical care medicine specialist for
University Hospital in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old ePocrates Inc. has spent only about $3,000 for
marketing so far. But an estimated 34,000 people, about 70 percent
of whom are doctors, have downloaded the free program since
ePocrates made it available on its Internet site in October. The
firm is gaining about 2,000 new users a week by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've recommended it to 10 other physicians,'' said Dr. Joshua
Rassen, co-founder of Brown and Toland Medical Group in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a delegate at a California Medical Association meeting
and I showed it to three of the other delegates, and the reaction
was pretty much the same: `That's cool, where'd you get it?'''
</P>
<P>
   EPocrates is one of more than a dozen companies trying to
develop and market wireless technology that gives doctors access to
prescription drug data and electronic prescription writing using
devices like a Palm, handheld PC, notebook or smart pager.
</P>
<P>
   Public pressure is building to reduce the number of prescription
errors. The national Institute of Medicine released a study last
year that said there were 7,000 deaths annually from medication
errors. The institute and the Clinton administration have called on
the health care industry to slash the number of errors.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like iScribe Inc. of San Mateo, ePhysicians Inc. in
Mountain View and Allscripts Inc. of Libertyville, Ill., are making
handheld prescription drug reference and writing systems. They have
become ``a hot area within the health care industry,'' said analyst
Richard Lee, managing director for Wit Soundview in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But none so far has the number of users claimed by ePocrates in
such a short time. For example, Allscripts says it has about 10,000
physicians at 3,000 sites in the United States using its system,
which works on a Hewlett-Packard Journada or Windows CE device. And
ePhysician said the 120 physicians using its system have written
12,000 electronic prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said ePocrates seems to be gaining acceptance
because it has taken a different tack by not trying to convince
doctors to scrap their centuries-old practice of writing
prescriptions on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are a notoriously tough bunch to get to switch
their work (habits),'' said Claudine Singer, a senior analyst with
the Internet research firm Jupiter Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ePocrates is trying to build a large network of doctors
by luring them with an easy Palm program that provides background
information, dosage levels and potential problems for 1,500
commonly prescribed drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The program is downloaded from the Internet and transferred into
a standard Palm. The data can be updated daily with new information
about existing drugs or about new drugs that are constantly coming
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors like Shaefer and Rassen say the program allows them to
spend more time with patients and less time leafing through the
small type in a standard drug reference book like the Physicians'
Desk Reference. The 1999 edition of the book is 3,477 pages and
about 4 inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a fairly high volume, about four patients an hour,''
said Rassen. ``Anything that saves one or two or three minutes is
enormously valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 26 years as a physician, Rassen resisted using gadgets
like a Palm until he learned about ePocrates from his son in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I can't quite see doing without it,'' Rassen said. ``It's
become something of a necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, doctors who are using ePocrates are reporting
to the company that they are making fewer prescription errors and
providing better patient care, said Dr. Thomas Lee, a co-founder of
ePocrates who edits the drug database.
</P>
<P>
   The 130 doctors surveyed by the company said they were each
making about 1.2 fewer errors in dosage per week and slightly under
one error per week for side effects and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who has all but given up a medical practice to devote his
time to ePocrates, admits those numbers are unscientific and that
there has yet to be a formal study of ePocrates' effectiveness. But
he found it significant that the doctors were admitting they were
avoiding any errors at all.
</P>
<P>
   Co-founder Dr. Richard Fiedotin, who also switched from medicine
to business, said the company hopes to build a network of loyal
users and then gradually introduce them to other services, such as
electronic prescription writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take them up the technology ladder one rung at a time,''
Fiedotin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiedotin said the company hopes to make money through partners
who will sponsor distribution of hardware and software, but did not
want to reveal what kinds of new services the firm plans to roll
out in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the competition is just starting to heat up. About
30,000 doctors have registered their interest in subscribing to
ePhysician's Palm-based services, which the company began selling
last week after eight months of tests, said company founder Dr.
Stuart Weisman.
</P>
<P>
   For $20 a month, doctors can, for example, use a Palm to check
drug doses and patient information. The doctor can then send an
electronic prescription through a standard Internet browser to the
patient's pharmacy with a couple of taps on his Palm, eliminating
the age-old problem of bad physician handwriting skills.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said interest in ePhysician is strong. For example,
Weisman said he signed up 268 doctors in five hours last week at a
cardiologists' convention where surveys showed 98 percent of the
attendees already owned Palms.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jupiter's Singer called ePocrates' early success
impressive, she said it is too early to proclaim anyone a leader in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so nascent, the landscape is so unformed that I'm not
entirely convinced any player you list won't be blown out of the
water by another player that has yet to show its hand,'' Singer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said it is only a matter of time before the majority of
the nation's 600,000 physicians start using drug prescription
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The movement may be fed by the current crop of medical students
who are downloading programs like ePocrates into their Palm units.
</P>
<P>
   Shaefer, also an associate professor at the Medical College of
Georgia in Augusta, learned of ePocrates from one of his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had several other Palm-based medical programs that purported
to do a variety of things, from math calculations to keeping track
of patient records and so forth,'' Shaefer said. ``All of those
things were interesting, but they really didn't do anything that I
didn't already do in some other way.''
</P>
<P>
   But now his pocket-size drug reference is ``prodding me to
practice a higher standard of care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennyesfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;
