<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO TRADE IN TIRED EXPLORER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: The small lettering on my Web pages displayed
with Internet Explorer is very hard to read. The same pages with
Netscape are easy to read. I noticed with Netscape that you can
adjust the lettering size, but no size is listed with Internet
Explorer. _ Going Blind
</P>
<P>
   Dear Going: Either you've got an ancient version of IE or you're
just not looking in the right place. I'm guessing your browser is
showing its age.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's OK with some kinds of software. I've used the same
word-processing program for 17 years because all I need it to do is
save my work as a simple text file, and it does that nicely without
trying to rearrange my paragraphs or criticize my spelling and
grammar. After all, that's what copy editors are for. Yes, I
purposely ended that sentence with a preposition.
</P>
<P>
   Browser technology and Web design, on the other hand, change
daily. As soon as some new feature is included in a browser, you
can bet 10 million Poindexters are staying up late at night, trying
to take advantage of it on their sites. And, if your browser lacks
the capability to display the newest stuff, you're never going to
be treated to all those dancing, singing hamsters or whatever it is
some nerd thought would be totally cool.
</P>
<P>
   There's an added incentive to upgrading IE: Microsoft includes
improvements to the Windows operating system with each release of
Explorer. Nobody's forcing you to use IE _ at least, Bill Gates
hasn't worked out a totally reliable way to do that yet _ but you
miss out on some nifty stuff like easier-to-use dial-up networking
if you never upgrade. Don't worry. You can still use Netscape.
Nobody will tell Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've installed IE 5.01, go to the View menu and select
Text Size, where you'll have five font sizes to choose from. If
you've got a mouse that has that little wheel between the two
buttons, you can hold down the Control key and roll it up or down
to change text size. Let's see Netscape do that.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing: Stop using the default text size when you
design a Web page. It's too small for us old-timers to read. Have
some pity and throw a plus-1 or plus-2 into your FONT commands.
That ratchets the viewing size up.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Many greetings. I am from Greece, and I want to
start hacking. I want you to tell me how it could be. _ Wannabe
</P>
<P>
   Dear Wannabe: I've always said there aren't enough hackers in
the world. First, abandon all personal hygiene. Drop all interests
but computing. Don't even try to interact with other people, or you
won't be able to let your sense of values warp beyond all
recognition. Now, develop an unreasonable hatred for society.
Remember: It's not your fault you're a total loser with no friends,
marketable skills or future. Those multinational corporations and
government agencies are the ones to blame. Target them with the
only weapon you have in your pitiful arsenal: not your vote, not
your ideas, not your faith, not your inspiration, but your childish
belief that jamming somebody's Web page for a couple of hours will
make the world finally recognize how truly awesome you are. Trust
me: We'll all be really impressed. Oh, and you should have a really
cool nickname, too. Your cellmate will like that.
</P>
<P>
   (Call him old-fashioned, but Dr. Emilio Bombay misses the days
when kids wanted to grow up to be cowboys or ballerinas instead of
cyberterrorists. Reach him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-24-00 1822EST &QL;
</P>
