u a BC-CPT-HOMEBREW-COMPUTER     03-30 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-HOMEBREW-COMPUTER-CLUB-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFITS VS. SHARING: ROOTS OF A SILICON VALLEY SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of 
number of PCs in use in the U.S. has moved as NYT31-33 to NYT
graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ In June 1975, a solitary computer hacker
slipped quietly into a van in the parking lot of a local hotel,
Rickey's Hyatt House, and ``borrowed'' a copy of Microsoft BASIC,
the first commercial program from a tiny Albuquerque, N.M., company
started by two other young hackers, William H. Gates and Paul G.
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The van was on a nationwide tour to show off the MITS Altair
8800, one of the world's first personal computers. The program _
stored as a set of punched holes in a long paper tape _ was
``liberated'' to be shared by a rag-tag group of Silicon Valley
computer hobbyists who had banded together only four months earlier
as the Homebrew Computer Club.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was handed to Dan Sokol, then 31, a semiconductor
engineering manager who did what he thought was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made convenient copies for the members of the Homebrew Club,
because I was the only one who had easy access to a paper tape
reader,'' Sokol recalled recently.
</P>
<P>
   The act outraged Gates, of the company then spelled as
Micro-Soft, who saw nothing but outright theft in the stunt. He
wrote an angry letter to the computer hobbyists. ``As the majority
of hobbyists must be aware, most of you steal your software,'' the
letter said. ``Hardware must be paid for, but software is something
to share. Who cares if the people who worked on it get paid?''
</P>
<P>
   This initial confrontation between Gates, then 20, who was to
become the most powerful figure in the computer industry and the
world's richest man, and an anarchic cadre of programmers and
hardware tinkerers was the forge of a basic tension that is still
shaping the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of the PC as the ubiquitous tool of the
information age had its roots in the Homebrew Club. A central value
of its founders _ the free sharing of information _ has until
recently been submerged in the Silicon Valley gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the argument has returned as a battle cry in a range
of confrontations, from the challenge of the free Linux operating
system to the patent protection and copyright issues facing the
music industry and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the valley has long been motivated by what the
author Michael S. Malone called ``The Big Score'' _ or more simply
put, greed. Indeed, it was not long after the Homebrew Club's first
meeting in Menlo Park that it began spawning companies _ with names
like Apple, Osborne, Cromemco and Northstar _ owing their roots,
directly or indirectly, to the enthusiasm that was captured in the
initial club meetings.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the valley also continues to be driven by a
more ethereal and in many ways purer motive _ what the author has
called ``the hacker ethic,'' a reference to the values of
passionate programmers (and not, in the more modern definition of
``hacker,'' to an outlaw subculture).
</P>
<P>
   The ethos, which finds its clearest expression today in Linux
software and in the commitment of the so-called open source
movement to the shared ownership and development of computing
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Linux, which now has about a 25 percent share of the computer
server market and the backing of big companies like IBM, is a
freely available operating system that has been developed and
supported by volunteer programmers.
</P>
<P>
   The PC industry ``began with people who had a passion for
computers,'' said Paul Freiberger, co-author of ``Fire in the
Valley: The Making of the Personal Computer'' (McGraw Hill, 1999)
``They were followed by people who had a passion for money. It's
the mixture of those passions that defines Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy night 25 years ago, it was the original hacker spirit
that captivated a small group of young men who were drawn early on
to the potential of powerful personal computers. One of them, a
Hewlett-Packard technician named Stephen Wozniak, has long
maintained that he had no intention of creating a company when he
built his first computer, but that he rather was intent on building
a machine he could show off to the members of the Homebrew Club.
</P>
<P>
   By happenstance, Sokol sat next to Wozniak at an early club
meeting. ``He bemoaned the fact that he couldn't get any parts to
make his computer from H-P,'' Sokol remembered. ``So I told him to
come by my company and I found a shoe box full of parts that became
the components used in the first Apple I computer.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no initial-public-offering gleam in either man's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were interested in playing with toys,'' Sokol said.
``People looked at our hand-wired computers and laughed at us and
asked, `What are you going to do with it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two people showed up at the first meeting after a peace
activist named Frederick Moore Jr. rode his bicycle around Palo
Alto and Menlo Park, tacking up small 3-by-5-inch notices on
bulletin boards and telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slipped Fred $5 and he went to the copy store and printed up
a bunch of fliers,'' recalled Gordon French, an engineer who along
with Moore is considered a co-founder of the group and who held the
first club meetings in his Palo Alto garage.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny flier read in part: ``Are you building your own
computer? Terminal? TV Typewriter? I/O device? or some other
digital black magic box? Or are you buying time on a time-sharing
service? If so, you might like to come to a gather of people with
like-minded interests. Exchange information, swap ideas, help work
on a project, whatever ...''
</P>
<P>
   One person who saw the flier on a telephone pole was Alan Baum,
who became an early employee of Apple Computer. He called his
friend Wozniak, and the two agreed to attend.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wozniak had already heard about the meeting from
another friend, John Draper, even then a legendary figure in the
Bay Area. Draper had been nicknamed ``Cap'n Crunch'' after he
discovered that the whistle prize in the cereal box would unlock
the AT&AMP;T long-distance system by generating a specific tone; he was
considered a pioneer ``phone phreak,'' part of a subculture of
hobbyists who explored the inner workings of the telephone network
in the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Wozniak and his friend Steven P. Jobs had met Draper several
years earlier, in Wozniak's dormitory room at the University of
California at Berkeley. From him, they learned about devices called
blue boxes that could be used to gain free telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, Wozniak and Jobs sold blue boxes. But after Jobs
realized from the Homebrew Club meetings that there might be an
enthusiastic market for PCs, the two men founded Apple Computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
