<SLUG> BC-CPT-POLAROID-DIGITAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID GIRDS FOR NEW ERA IN INSTANT PHOTOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a paradox here somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Polaroid not only outsold its competitors in the
digital camera field, it even turned a slim profit on those sales.
Since analysts say that no one else is making money on digital
cameras, it was a coup.
</P>
<P>
   But talk to Polaroid executives and they shrug off digital
cameras as simply Polaroid's way of marking time. They expect that
a few years down the road, people will be snapping pictures with
cell phones, Palm Pilots and the like _ and, they hope, printing
them out on wireless Polaroid printers. ``The cameras are just
another way of capturing images, many of which we hope people will
want to print,'' said Gary T. DiCamillo, Polaroid's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of this forecast could determine Polaroid's chances
for survival in a digital world.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid has always sold cameras pretty much at cost, and made
its money from chemical-and-paper film that develops itself in a
minute or two. Since digital photography is essentially an
electronic form of instant pictures, Polaroid is either in a unique
position to move into this field _ or uniquely suited to be
rendered obsolete by it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Polaroid executives stress the opportunities. ``I
laugh when people are surprised we're doing well in digital
cameras,'' said Brian D. Poggi, senior vice president for North
America. ``After all, they're really the same as instant cameras:
They provide an affordable and immediate picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry experts wonder whether the similarity will
translate to sales. Many note that, even as film sales shrink,
companies like Fuji and Kodak can still do a thriving business in
sales of coated papers, which can be used to make high-quality
prints of digital photos. But a Polaroid customer who switches to
digital photography is lost to the market for the company's
self-developing film _ unless those customers use Polaroid printers
or hybrid digital/instant cameras to make prints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not clear to me what long-term digital strategy can
really replace what they are generating from film-based instant
prints,'' said Steve Hoffenberg, a digital photography market
analyst with Lyra Research Inc. in Newtonville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has similar concerns. Eastman Kodak and Polaroid
have both had earnings problems that have driven their stock prices
down in recent years. Kodak's stock remains mired in the $50s _
well below the nearly $70 it traded at a year ago. But many
analysts say the company has cleaned up its digital portfolio and
brought its costs under control, making its stock a good buy right
now. Few are as upbeat about Polaroid, even though that company's
stock closed at $25.1875 on Friday _ nowhere near the price of
$60.25 it reached in July 1997, but a nice rebound from its low of
$17.25 in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital cameras, scanners, picture CDs, Web sites, they are
all geared toward one thing _ driving output,'' said Jonathan
Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``And the
competitive picture for Polaroid in a digital world is a lot less
clear than it is for Kodak.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as the only instant photography company in the
country, competition is not something Polaroid is used to. (Fuji
Photo Film Co. sells instant cameras and film overseas, but when
Kodak tried to do so here, the courts upheld Polaroid's patents.)
But as the digital revolution is wooing many people from the 35-mm
film camp, Polaroid could grab customers long loyal either to Fuji
or Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be the only show in town for people who wanted
instant gratification on their pictures, and yes, we've lost
that,'' said Paul E. Lambert, Polaroid's senior vice president for
research and development. ``But for the first time, we can really
tap into the conventional photography market.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to capture a high-end digital market _ the
strategy that Fuji and Kodak have pursued _ Polaroid has farmed its
production out to overseas manufacturers, which make
Polaroid-branded cameras that sell for as little as $99 and rarely
top $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital cameras are just their mechanism for building shelf
space,'' said Michael Ellmann, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   True to its mass-market roots, Polaroid already is spewing forth
products to fill those shelves. There is a portable scanner that
can upload images to the Web. There is a digital camera with a
built-in modem that can send pictures via the Web to Polaroid for
transfer to prints, T-shirts or other items.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Polaroid announced an alliance with PictureWorks
Technology, a software company, to develop more Internet-related
products. One on the drawing boards is a product to help
dermatologists keep a digital-image record of a patient's progress
during treatments for skin disorders and plug the pictures into
insurance claims forms.
</P>
<P>
   On the wireless front, Polaroid recently demonstrated a wireless
printer that can receive images transmitted by radio waves from up
to 50 feet away. ``This makes the process truly portable, because
digital cameras are no longer tethered to PCs,'' said Ulysses
Yannas, an analyst with Buckman, Buckman &AMP; Reid.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of Polaroid's planned digital cameras will double
as makeshift printers. The company already sells a combination
instant-print and digital camera, aimed at teen-agers, that is
little more than two cameras glued together; the user cannot
instantly print an image captured digitally. Within a year, though,
Polaroid intends to introduce a hybrid camera that will collect
images electronically, but will also generate an instant print with
the press of a button.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's chemists are working on a new type of paper
for printing pictures that they claim will yield the same quality
as the silver halide films that Fuji, Kodak and Polaroid now use,
but at a much lower cost. By now, many inkjet printers can yield
high-resolution 8{-by-11-inch prints on photo-quality paper for
less than a dollar each. Although conventional Polaroid instant
film could be modified for use in a desktop printer, prints would
cost several dollars apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Polaroid's attempts to reduce costs were hamstrung
by the need for a chemically treated paper that can both capture an
image and print it; now, digital cameras take care of that first
step. ``If we don't have to worry about capturing the image, we can
optimize how we print it out,'' Lambert said.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid is divulging few details about its research, and its
new paper is at least two years from market. Still, what has leaked
out excites analysts. ``They're talking a few cents per print,''
Yannas said, ``so they could capture a big share of the home print
market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That market promises to be huge. Indeed, photo processors
already say that digital cameras have increased, not decimated,
their business. ``Digital photography has created a whole new
customer base for us,'' said Mitchell B. Goldstone, who owns 30
Minute Photo in Irvine, Calif. ``People use less film, but they
make more prints and enlargements.''
</P>
<P>
   But the conventional photography companies will not give up
market share without a fight. Kodak is also researching
non-silver-halide media for making prints. Last week, Kodak said it
would soon begin selling lower-priced digital cameras. And it
recently introduced a digital camera that can snap onto a Palm
Pilot and transfer images to the device's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak also has a prototype digital camera that can e-mail images
via a mobile phone. ``The person receiving that e-mail image is
likely to print it out, or send it to Kodak via the Internet to get
prints,'' said Willy C. Shih, president of Kodak's digital imaging
business.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji, meanwhile, has been selling to photo processing labs a
printing method that uses lasers and heat, rather than a wet
process, to transfer images to paper. The company is now
introducing a similar, scaled-down, dry-process photographic
printer for home use. Unlike Polaroid and Kodak, Fuji is
manufacturing its own digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital imaging is an industry unto itself, and we want to
provide a cradle-to-grave solution in that space,'' said Manny
Almeida, general manager of digital imaging at Fuji Photo Film USA.
</P>
<P>
   There are still opportunities that no photography company has
yet nailed down. B. Alexander Henderson, who covers the
photographic industry for Prudential Securities, contends that all
the photography companies should be touting their corporate Web
sites as places where customers can store their electronic
photographs, with an eye toward making prints in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuji, Kodak, Polaroid _ they could all generate repeat
business in prints, and enough traffic to generate advertising
revenue on their Web sites,'' he said. ``The holy grail of the
Internet is controlling content, yet none of them are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, all of the companies do have breathing space to get
their digital acts together. Conventional photography is still
growing fast in emerging economies like China. And the Photo
Marketing Association says that amateur photography is a $15
billion annual market in the United States. Polaroid's own research
shows that 90 percent of American households own cameras, but only
6 percent own digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional cameras may get squeezed out within our
lifetime,'' Almeida of Fuji said. ``But in the next few years? No
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid, too, says that sales of its conventional instant
cameras and film are at an all-time high. Last year, the company
sold 9.7 million instant cameras, topping its 1978 record of 9.4
million. Its total sales hit $1.98 billion in 1999, up from $1.85
billion the prior year. And its net earnings were $9 million, a
nice improvement from 1998, when weak demand in emerging markets
combined with smaller orders from mass marketers in the United
States to cause a net loss of $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid has been concentrating its marketing efforts on the
youth market _ it just signed a sponsorship agreement with Britney
Spears, the popular singer _and its cameras have become hot sellers
among teen-agers. The company's I-Zone camera, a $25 item that
yields postage-stamp-sized pictures, was the best-selling camera in
the country last Christmas season. ``There's no question,
Polaroid's instant cameras are going gangbusters,'' said Hoffenberg
of Lyra Research.
</P>
<P>
   But the excitement is clearly in digital products. ``Instant
photography will represent the majority of our business in the next
five years,'' DiCamillo said, ``but digital will be the
fastest-growing area.''
</P>
<P>
   That will probably be true in Polaroid's troubled commercial
business as well. In contrast to its robust consumer sales,
Polaroid's commercial sales, which in the past represented half its
revenues, have been flat, and profit margins razor-thin.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid is banking that its mass market products will be used
for commercial ends. A hospital in Canada, for example, uses
Polaroid I-Zone cameras that yield sticky-backed prints to affix
pictures to admissions records. ``Half of our products are used in
business, even if they're bought at Wal-Mart,'' said Stephen
Golden, director of marketing for consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Polaroid does have strictly commercial products as
well. Its digital microscopy camera, which captures what is seen
through a microscope, is selling well to research labs, despite
price tags that start at $6,000. Polaroid already is the world's
largest supplier of photo ID cards, and it has its sights on
becoming the dominant company for digitally produced
identification.
</P>
<P>
   It is ready to introduce a system, particularly intended for the
passport photo market, that would take and store photos digitally,
but print them out on Polaroid film. Polaroid already produces the
driver's licenses for 37 states, and it is testing a program in
West Virginia for snapping and storing digital photos of children
that police can use to help locate a missing child.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has new technologies for incorporating
fingerprints and facial recognition into ID cards. One system
enables states to check whether someone has a driver's license in
another name. And Polaroid just introduced a product, for sale to
computer keyboard manufacturers, that would let people use their
fingerprints in lieu of passwords and log-ons, by pressing their
index fingers against a little window.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid also is using the Internet to expand its base of
customers. It has begun accepting ID information and images via the
Web, mailing back ID cards within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``This now makes us accessible to small businesses that don't
want to spend thousands for an ID system,'' DiCamillo said. ``I
appreciate technology, but I'm a market-driven manager. And our
strategy, now and in the future, will be driven by understanding
what customers want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-26-00 1742EST &QL;
</P>
