<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GREETS ONLINE ENTREPRENEURS AT DOT-COM FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Ground zero at the Yahoo Internet Life Online Film
Festival last week was the coffee shop at the ostentatiously retro
Standard Hotel on Sunset Strip. Black-clad, steely eyed hipsters
with cell phones circled one another like prizefighters, feigning
indifference. Others huddled in the diner's booths while fresh
deals were announced with almost every tick of the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a madhouse,'' said Mika Salmi, chairman of
Seattle-based Atomfilms, one of the Internet's leading exhibitors,
producers and distributors of digital movies. ``It's very fast here
in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival is far from being the first or the only event
dedicated to the world of online film _ that is, the making and
distributing of digital movies on the Internet, an explosively
growing field some think is the vanguard of entertainment for the
future. But the two-day event that ended on Thursday night turned
into a kind of coming-out party, a faltering first date, for the
worlds of mainstream Hollywood and online entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 companies that offer some form of online films took
part in the festival along with all the names that have become
familiar in recent months in the field. Besides Atomfilms there
were Ifilm, Shockwave, Pop.com, Filmbazaar, Sputnik 7, EVEO and
others. Also at the festival, though, were some representatives of
mainstream Hollywood, from Peter Guber, the former studio chief,
and his Mandalay Films, announcing a new Internet initiative, to
Propaganda Films, announcing a new partnership to produce movies
for Atomfilms.
</P>
<P>
   The impression was that a load of fresh chum had been tossed
into the water and there was a great roiling on the surface. But it
was difficult to tell exactly who was eating whom down below.
</P>
<P>
   ``All revolutions are great unless they kill you,'' Guber said.
``This is a potentially lethal time. But daring times require bold
actions. Blazing a trail to the future is hazardous duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most emblematic festival event came early, on
Wednesday morning, when 17 companies had five minutes each to stand
up before reporters and announce any new partnership or
acquisition. No time for questions, though. Too many deals to be
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Shockwave announced that the director David Lynch would join
Trey Parker and Matt Stone, the creators of ``South Park,'' and the
filmmakers Tim Burton and James L. Brooks in creating films
exclusively for its site. Lynch said that his animated efforts
would be self-consciously dumb and poorly drawn, but he promised
they would be ``sophisticatedly crude.'' Pop.com announced that it
was joining with John Sloss, an entertainment lawyer and veteran
deal maker from the independent film world, to create Popfest, a
companion Web site that would compete with Atomfilms and others in
exhibiting the works of fledgling online filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Movie Database said it would join with Amazon.com
to create a special independent film area on its Web site that
would strategically link with Amazon's Advantage site to highlight
the works of independent filmmakers and even help them sell their
films. Universal Pictures, part of the Seagram Co., announced that
it would invest in Reelshort.com in hopes of ``providing an online
exhibition platform for cutting-edge creative work.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,800 people signed up for the online festival before
it was overwhelmed and registration had to be suspended on March
18. Along with seminars on how the worlds of Hollywood and dot-com
could get along, profitably, with one another, there were
screenings of online films, keynote speeches from Guber, the
journalist Kurt Andersen (who recently defected to the dot-com
world by founding Powerful Media) and the critic Roger Ebert, and
the world premiere of Mike Figgis' latest movie, ``Time Code,'' an
ambitious shot-on-digital comedy starring Stellan Skarsgard, Salma
Hayek and Jeanne Tripplehorn.
</P>
<P>
   A hostile scene outside the premiere of the Figgis film _ when
many times more people showed up than could be accommodated in the
theater, especially as three-quarters of its seats were reserved
for those affiliated with the film or the festival's sponsors _ was
defused when festival organizers added late-night screenings for
the overflow crowd. Hollywood luminaries Dustin Hoffman, Nicolas
Cage and Jodie Foster also showed up for the event.
</P>
<P>
   For two sunny days, the festival spread along the twisting
stretch of Sunset between the Standard Hotel and the Chateau
Marmont, about 200 yards apart, with the biggest events, like the
``Time Code'' premiere and the keynote speeches, held a few blocks
farther east in the auditorium of the Directors Guild of America.
The pool and the warren of walkways between the Marmont's bungalows
were festooned with balloons, plush chairs and banners advertising
the dot-coms that had their festival headquarters there.
Filmmakers, agents, production company scouts and dot-com aspirants
made the rounds there and in the hospitality suites at the
Standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event has turned out to be kind of the key event of the
year for combining the Internet with the world of independent
film,'' said Diane Zoi, director of Amazon.com Advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-26-00 1738EST &QL;
</P>
