<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GAMER28-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Syphon Filter returns 
c. 2000 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Syphon Filter is back. The
counter-terrorism game (which was meant to be a more action-packed
``Metal Gear Solid'') wowed us with its shooter-type gameplay. It
also had a pretty compelling storyline. 989 Studios's Syphon Filter
2 ($55, Playstation; www.989studios.com) surpasses the old Syphon
Filter in plot, and it offers a slew of new game functions. Your
task is to stop the Syphon Filter virus from being spread to
terrorists. To do this, you need to use brute force and an arsenal
that would make any action hero shout with joy (night vision
rifles, grenade launchers, crossbow, etc.). The game also offers an
addictive, two-player side-by-side mode. In this mode, you can play
the unsinkable Gabriel Logan while your partner in crime plays Lian
Xing. Blast your way to glory and save the world for us all.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   As many video games as have been made using the Star Wars
license, you'd think a game that took three years to develop would
blow us out of our collective seats. Unfortunately, LucasArts' new
Star Wars game, Force Commander ($40 for the PC, www.lucasarts.com)
does that, but in the wrong way: the game makes you want to get out
of your chair and take a walk just to get away from your computer.
Commander, a real-time-strategy game with 3D units and movement, is
nice to look at on first glance, but several problems emerge. The
game interface is clunky and needlessly complex. The background and
character graphics aren't as detailed or breathtaking as they
should be. And the control of the game's point of view is dodgy at
best. All of it combines to make an experience that is more
frustrating than fun. Star Wars fans deserve a great, awe-inspiring
strategy game along the lines of last year's stunning Homeworld,
but unfortunately, this is not the game they're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-27-00 1105EST &QL;
</P>
