<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-CO     03-30 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Why would Elian want to leave all this fun?
 &HT;    (For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ So, Diane Sawyer quotes little Elian as saying he
doesn't want to go back to Cuba. And Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, the
nun who hosted the bizarre reunion of Elian and his grandmothers in
which, allegedly, they bit his tongue and checked his penis, feels
the child would do better here _ because of something either Elian
or the grandmothers implied to her.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the convenient introduction of aberrations of the
Virgin Mary in nearby Miami locales, and we've got a situation that
begs rationality.
</P>
<P>
   I do not doubt that Elian told Sawyer he did not want to go
home, or that he told it to her several times in response to
modified questions. That ABC did not air Elian actually saying it,
instead left Sawyer to tell us he said it, is not flawless
documentation, but I'll accept it.
</P>
<P>
   But put yourself in Elian's shoes. You're 6 years old. In Cuba,
you've lived a moderate life (despite what strident Cuban exiles
insist is one of poverty). Videotape of your fifth birthday party
shows a bunch of kids and family in your Cardenas home, wearing
party hats, bringing gifts. There's a birthday cake. Everyone seems
fairly well dressed, no one looks starved _ and someone can afford
a video camera to record it!
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing, however, to what you have received in Miami. The
gifts just don't stop pouring in. You've got every toy imaginable,
toys I'm certain you never would have received in Cuba. You are
driven to school every day, and picked up.
</P>
<P>
   You are a celebrity. Every time you come out of your Miami home,
there are people there to cheer you, to photograph you. You are on
TV just about every day, everyone in radio is talking about you,
all those Cuban flags are waving for you out in the street. Great
Uncle Lazaro Gonzalez keeps raising you atop his shoulders so that
you may wave to the cameras and people.
</P>
<P>
   Even Diane Sawyer comes down from New York to roll around the
classroom floor with you.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's fun, isn't it, Elian?
</P>
<P>
   Would any 6-year-old want to give this up? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the things your Miami relatives are telling
you, things about Cuba, about your father. So what if they coach
you on what to do or say? They're nice people, have your best
interests at heart; right?
</P>
<P>
   Remember that second day with the relatives back in December,
when you flashed that V-for-Victory sign from the car window after
coming home from a hearing? You learned that in Cuba, didn't you?
Oh, you didn't? One of the relatives here taught you that? Oh, how
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't fathom yet, Elian _ and it's because you are too
young _ is that you are, simply, a political instrument. It's not
really about you, it's about Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not for you to worry about _ yet. You're only 6. If
you go home, maybe when you grow up, you can wrestle Cuba away from
Castro's communism. But if you stay here, then you'll just
eventually melt into the population. Soon the flags and TV cameras
will go away. Oh, you'll still be held high as a symbol, but the
luster will fade.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, everything's great! Why go home? Tell
Ms. Sawyer you want to stay, tell her you don't even want your
father coming here because he may take you home _ and the attention
at home was never like it is here.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine, Elian: nearly 100,000 (Cuban) flag-waving
protesters filled Miami's streets Wednesday night in favor of
keeping you here, shouting your name.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the Virgin Mary, too.
</P>
<P>
   No, I would have said the same thing to the TV lady.
</P>
<P>
   Go home? Leave this? No way, Jose!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
