<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX     03-30 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Double-barreled double-talk from the NRA
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association's phony cry-babying over the
Clinton administration's supposed failure to enforce existing gun
laws bids fair to make ``crocodile indignation'' a companion cliche
to ``crocodile tears.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's lament is thick and oily with insincerity. Going
beyond mere gall, the NRA is showing more cheek than a strip club
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Except for locking up criminals after the fact, the lobby has
consistently opposed firearms legislation and has politically
harassed federal enforcement of many of the very laws it now
pretends to wish were being more vigorously enforced.
</P>
<P>
   It was the NRA, remember, that notoriously equated agents of the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms with Nazi storm
troopers. It has portrayed federal law enforcement officers as
booted thugs kicking in the doors of innocent citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in good part to NRA lobbying, we have laws that let
convicted felons regain their legal right to buy firearms. NRA
pressure led Congress in 1986 to enact the Firearms Owners'
Protection Act, which, along with legislating other hobbles on
enforcement, limits unannounced ATF inspections of gun dealers to
one a year.
</P>
<P>
   More? Well, although it fought the Brady Act requiring
background checks for gun buyers, the lobby now declares and
denounces a federal failure to charge all felons who try to buy
guns they have no legal right to. But many of those supposed lapses
come under state, not federal, supervision of the law.
</P>
<P>
   And the law, as the NRA knows, limits such prosecutions to
persons who knowingly attempt to buy guns contrary to law. Even
then, more might be called to legal account if the short-handed ATF
didn't have to settle for cherry-picking the most dangerous
violators.
</P>
<P>
   Where the ATF had 2,448 agents and inspectors in 1973, currently
it is budgeted for 2,648 _ an increase of just 200 for very
different times. The NRA regularly lobbies against increases.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA pushed for the huge loophole that leaves private gun
sales unregulated, a means by which firearms are slipped to
criminals by legal but unscrupulous buyers who resell, no questions
asked. It is fighting a Clinton administration proposal to close
another big loophole that allows gun-show sales without background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the administration isn't doing all it could to prosecute
gun violators. It would take a complicated audit to find out. (Not
a bad idea, by the way.) But many violations can be prosecuted
either under federal or state laws. It is apparently one of the
NRA's tricks to count referrals to state prosecution as federal
defaults.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional group is working up legislation that would add
1,000 new state, local and federal prosecutors for gun crimes and
500 ATF agents and inspectors, would increase dealer inspections
and would improve record-keeping for domestic-violence offenders
who are ineligible to buy firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's enthusiasm for this beefed-up enforcement is more
hoped for than counted on.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
