<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UNIONCARBIDE-FUGITIVE     03-30 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIONCARBIDE-FUGITIVE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bhopal disaster catches up with ex-Union Carbide CEO
 &HT;    By Molly Hennessy-Fiske
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH _ For 14 years, Warren Anderson has lived in quiet
retirement, relaxing with his wife, taking walks on the beach and
traveling between his seaside homes here and on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   But as of January, the former head of Union Carbide was an
international fugitive, sought by private detectives, Interpol and
the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? He was CEO of Union Carbide in 1984 when a gas leak
at a Carbide-owned plant killed thousands of Indians in the city of
Bhopal.
</P>
<P>
   Private detectives were searching for him to serve him a summons
stemming from a class-action suit filed in New York City. The
Indian government has a criminal warrant for his arrest and alerted
Interpol.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney in the class action said last week that the search
has ended.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson could be at home in Bridgehampton on New York's Long
Island or in the Seaforest development on State Road A1A near Vero
Beach. In the gated Seaforest community, the Andersons' home stands
among about 40 other brick and stucco houses. Its windows are open
and a car is visible in the garage when the door rises now and
then. The silver 1992 Chevy Caprice belongs to Anderson's wife,
Lillian. Those who rang the bell earlier this month, including a
repairman, were greeted by an older man who stands about 6-foot-2,
thin, with glasses and a head of white hair. A man not unlike
Warren Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Anderson said last week that her husband is in Vero
Beach but would not answer questions about the new case.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said they have seen activity at the house but would
not comment on whether they spotted Anderson himself. After being
inundated with calls from servers, reporters (including The New
York Times and several magazines) and the generally curious, many
felt protective of a neighbor who moved in seeking peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That issue was decided 15 years ago,'' said neighbor John
Jandzen. ``There's nothing any of his good friends can do.''
Jandzen said he had not heard of the new suit, although he has been
``besieged'' by calls.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, neighbor Eleanor Harpring said she would
usually run into Lillian Anderson while walking but that the
``quiet, unassuming'' couple often kept to themselves. Theirs was
not a house that hosted cocktail parties, and in the neighborhood
of $300,000 to $700,000 homes, many protect their privacy. Even
backyard patios have walls that are 6 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want to see a soul, you don't have to,'' Harpring
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth McCallion, a Manhattan attorney, wants to see Anderson.
McCallion's firm filed the civil suit against Anderson. McCallion
said private investigators spent months trying to find Anderson at
his homes here and in New York.
</P>
<P>
   According to a March 5 New York Times article, the Indian
government contacted Interpol in an effort to locate Anderson. Last
week, U.S. Interpol officials said they had begun to ask other
Interpol agencies about the search for Anderson after receiving
calls from Florida authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Union Carbide, based in Danbury, Conn., previously refused the
summons service, contending the 1989 settlement prevented
subsequent claims against Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Replied McCallion, the Manhattan attorney who filed the suit:
``He should tell it to the judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The search ended March 9 when Union Carbide attorneys finally
accepted a summons on Anderson's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Satinath Sarangi, a member of Bhopal Group for Information and
Action that is a plaintiff in the suit, said he has been searching
for Anderson since the Indian government issued a warrant for his
arrest in April 1992 on charges that include manslaughter, assault
and the killing and poisoning of animals. The warrant was issued
after Union Carbide and Anderson settled an initial suit in 1989
and left the country just as the Indian government began a criminal
trial against Union Carbide's Indian subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something had gone wrong,'' Sarangi said. Union Carbide and
Anderson ``had said they would submit themselves to the (Indian)
courts, and when they didn't, the court didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Union Carbide spokesmen said all charges against the U.S.
company and Anderson were severed from those of the Indian
subsidiary. The company later sold its interest in the subsidiary
and contributed more than $70 million to build and operate a new
Bhopal hospital. Sarangi, who works at a free clinic in Bhopal,
said the hospital has yet to open.
</P>
<P>
   The new suit alleges that Union Carbide officials, even after
agreeing to the settlement, failed to accept fault for the
disaster. Union Carbide spokesmen don't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   In statements put forth at the time of the leak and today on the
company Web site, executives blame the toxic gas leak on an outside
saboteur, at one point indicating the culprit may have belonged to
a Sikh terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an act of a disgruntled employee,'' spokesman Tom
Sprick said. ``Our investigation and that of an independent firm,
A.D. Little, confirmed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Company attorneys filed a motion Jan. 27 to dismiss the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a settlement in place that includes all employees,
including Warren Anderson,'' spokesman Sean Clancey said. Clancey
said Union Carbide ``fulfilled our moral responsibility'' to the
victims of the Bhopal disaster through relief efforts, for which
Anderson himself flew to India. But advocacy groups now say the
company stopped far short of what was needed to heal the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Company estimates peg the number of dead at 3,800 and those
permanently disabled at 2,680.
</P>
<P>
   Sarangi said that when he arrived to treat the wounded in
December 1984, many thousands had already died from the effects of
the leaking pesticide gas. He contends that between 16,000 and
20,000 death claims have been filed, and another 120,000 suffer
chronic illnesses, including vision and breathing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to accept and take care of people,'' Sarangi said of
the company. ``They can't just write it off like a balance sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarangi said the plaintiffs filed the new suit under the Alien
Torts Claims Act, granting the U.S. court jurisdiction, and hope to
win enough money to support comprehensive medical care for victims.
Although 16 years have passed since the accident, any statute of
limitations on the suit would have to take into account years spent
negotiating where the initial civil case would be tried _ New York
or India _ and attempting to subpoena defendants, including
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Hennessy-Fiske writes for the Palm Beach Post. Staff
researchers Sammy Alzofon, Monica Martinez and Geni Guseila
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
