<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MUSIC-VH1-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      03-30 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VH1-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING BEHIND `BEHIND THE MUSIC' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TIMOTHY FINN  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  VH1 will air three ``Behind the
Music'' premieres in April: Oasis on April 2, the Police on April
16 and, as part of a ``BTM Music Marathon,'' No Doubt on April 23.
Show times are 8 p.m. central time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question was trivial; the response was, in the music world
anyway, profound. Sometime in spring 1997, Jeff Gaspin, an
executive producer at the cable-TV music channel VH1, idly
wondered: What ever happened to Milli Vanilli?
</P>
<P>
   That led to a few conversations and phone calls with colleagues
and then some earnest research. A few months later, in August 1997,
VH1 had produced the first two ``Behind the Music'' documentaries:
one on MC Hammer, the defunct//bankrupt '90s pop-rapper; the other
on Milli Vanilli, the fraudulent, lip-syncing Grammy-winning duo.
</P>
<P>
   The show was an instant success: 5 million people combined tuned
into the two episodes, making it at that time the most-watched
original series in the network's 12-year history.
</P>
<P>
   This month VH1 aired its 100th episode of ``Behind the Music,''
focusing, appropriately, on Tina Turner, a woman whose life story
is filled with the kind of pathos, mayhem and personal triumph that
has made ``BTM'' famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series has become a cultural phenomenon,'' said George
Moll, VH1's vice president of West Coast production and one of the
series' executive producers. ``I've been involved in lots of TV
shows in my career, but not in one that generates the kind of
reaction this one does.''
</P>
<P>
   The network gets some of its highest ratings from ``BTM,'' but
most artists profiled on the series benefit from an immediate spike
in record sales.
</P>
<P>
   Take Def Leppard, whose wild and tragic ``BTM'' episode first
ran on June 21, 1998. According to figures from SoundScan, sales of
the band's ``Greatest Hits'' record jumped 75 percent in two weeks.
Combined sales of the band's three studio records jumped 41 percent
in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   One year after his ``BTM'' episode ran, Tony Orlando wrote a
thank-you letter to Moll that flatly stated: ``There has been a
professional reaction where my audiences have quadrupled.''
</P>
<P>
   Such displays of gratitude have made it easier for VH1 to
convince artists that a ``BTM'' episode might be a good career
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first six months, getting artists to agree to do one was
like pulling teeth,'' Moll said from his Los Angeles office. ``But
after that ... let's just say it didn't take the industry long to
see that compelling TV can be an important marketing force.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex, drugs, mayhem
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 people work for ``Behind the Music,'' including
technical and legal advisers, but a team of three or four _
producer, associate producer and a researcher or two _ does most of
the work on each episode, which takes about four months to produce.
</P>
<P>
   The show is narrated by Jim Forbes, a veteran TV news producer
and correspondent who has become a popular fixture in the series.
Forbes wrote and produced ``Selena: Behind the Music,'' which won
an American Latino Media Arts Award in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Each ``BTM'' episode costs an average of $200,000 or so, much of
which is spent getting legal clearance to use music clips and video
footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What separates us from the other biography shows,'' Moll said,
``is we make the commitment to get the artists or the artists'
estates involved. The viewer gets the story from the artists and
hears the original music with it, which is very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, we've earned the trust of the artistic
community. We handle sensitive topics in a dignified manner.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the music adds vital flavor, but those ``sensitive
topics'' are what viewers sink their teeth into: drug and alcohol
jags; car, van and plane wrecks; bankruptcies; prison time and
backstage orgies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said the show works because people like to see
their stars knocked down to size,'' Gaspin told the Los Angeles
Times last year, ``but I think it's more that they like to see that
their heroes are human ... They have problems with sex and money,
and that's something the viewer can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all problems about sex and money are the same, though. The
most infamous ``BTM'' episodes tend to be those that cover the
swashbuckling heavy metal bands who party as hard as they rock.
</P>
<P>
   One of the series' most memorable moments came from Nikki Sixx,
the Crue's bass player, who impassively recalled a near-death
experience. He overdosed on heroin, turned blue and died, was
revived in the ambulance, skipped out of the emergency room, went
back home, shot up again, passed out and woke up the next day, the
needle still in his arm and his hand caked in his own blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have it on tape,'' Moll said, ``artists saying, `I just
don't want to come off as Spinal Tap when I'm telling my story.' So
we are careful. As tempting as it may have been with some artists,
we have never mocked anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen idol
</P>
<P>
   The most popular ``BTM'' episode _ and the second most-watched
program in VH1 history _ was the premiere of ``Shania Twain: Behind
the Music.'' Nearly 6.5 million viewers watched the show, which
first aired April 14, 1988. Since then Twain's episode has been
rerun more than any other ``BTM'' episode: 73 times. (Madonna's is
second with 63 reruns.)
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary stars may draw the most viewers, but the most
indelible shows tend to be about the artists who haven't seen a ray
of limelight in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boy George show remains one of my favorites,'' Moll said.
``And the Leif Garrett episode is certainly one of the most
memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Garrett ``BTM'' starts typically: Teen idol gets famous,
overindulges in fortune and stardom and falls out of fashion.
Toward the end, though, the show takes a twist: Garrett is reunited
with Roland Winkler, a friend he hadn't seen in more than 20 years
_ since the day Winkler was crippled in a car accident in which
Garrett was driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things we do when we start working on a show
is run a Nexus search of newspaper articles,'' said Paul Gallagher,
an associate producer of the Garrett episode. ``Our search turned
up this $7 million settlement against Leif. Needles to say, I was
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   During standard preliminary interviews with Garrett, Gallagher
asked him about the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly a very sensitive issue with him,'' Gallagher
said. ``He told me, `I don't know where to find him.'...
</P>
<P>
   ``It took about 10 minutes (on the Internet) to find Roland. I
barely got the question out _ `Would you like to meet with Leif
Garrett' _ when he said yes...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extremely emotionally charged moment, watching these
two people who had been very close come together after a tragic
accident and after so much time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaspin told The Times: ``It was definitely an uncomfortable
moment ... (but) it struck a nerve and really got people talking
about the show.''
</P>
<P>
   They did more than talk. Two weeks after the episode's premiere,
fans bought 152 copies of ``The Leif Garrett Collection'' _ 152
more than they bought the week before the show was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   VH1 has dozens of ``BTM'' episodes in production (AC//DC, Ricky
Martin, the Monkees), dozens more in development (Pearl Jam, Tupac
Shakur, the Eagles) and a ``hot list'' of artists it is considering
(Public Enemy, Keith Richards, Jerry Garcia).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have embarked on some projects that have been shelved
because the artists have tried to be too controlling,'' Moll said.
(One of those, Gaspin told Entertainment Weekly, is Chaka Khan.)
</P>
<P>
   ``And then,'' Moll said, ``there are projects we really want to
do, but the artists are reluctant to agree, like Peter Frampton.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaspin told The Times last year that he figured ``Behind the
Music'' could do about 150 shows before the material started
thinning appreciably, but that threshold seems a bit low.
</P>
<P>
   Five or 10 years from now, everyone from Britney Spears to Kid
Rock will have stories to tell and dormant records to sell. And
styles of music may come and go, but gossip never falls out of
fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
