<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2138 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-HUMOR-APRILFOOL'S-KAN     03-30 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMOR-APRILFOOL'S-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLEASHING YOUR INNER COMEDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GUTIERREZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know people whose faces would crack if they ever smiled,
people who sniff at April Fools' jokes, people who make you want to
yell: Aw, lighten up!
</P>
<P>
   It's not nice to yell.
</P>
<P>
   But you have science on your side when the boss writes you up
for slipping a whoopee cushion onto your colleague's ergonomic
office chair.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, from cancer patients and nurses to employees
at Fortune 500 companies, people are lightening up. In workshops
and summer camps, they're learning to be playful and silly, to
appreciate irony, to be the butt of their own jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Research of humor used as therapy shows that it speeds recovery
times, increases creativity and productivity on the job and reduces
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been ongoing recognition that humor and laughter and a
sense of play is good for us, physically, psychologically and
spiritually,'' says psychologist Ed Dunkelblau, immediate past
president of the American Association for Therapeutic Humor, based
in St. Louis. ``This is not a new concept.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, he says, it's right there in the Bible's Book of
Proverbs: ``A cheerful heart is good medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   We're no doctors, so we consulted with ``professionals'' _
comedians at Stanford &AMP; Sons Comedy Club in Westport _ to prescribe
a six-step program to unstarch your shorts and loosen that stiff
upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragedy's gonna happen every day. Planes are going to crash.
People are going to starve. In order to accept it all you have to
make some sense of it, and that sense is humor,'' counsels Bryan
``Comedy King'' Burgess, Stanford's booking agent.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to want to change. Like an alcoholic, you must
first acknowledge that you have a problem because ``there are
people you can't fix,'' says Jim Fite, a man with a rowdy tenor
laugh who directs the International Center for Humor and Health in
Edmond, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who join Weight Watchers 10, 20 times and
never lose weight. And the reason they never lose weight is that
they still perceive themselves as fat people.''
</P>
<P>
   So repeat after us: Hi, my name is (fill in the blank). And I am
a killjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you're ready.
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Laugh at yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if people are looking to find humor in life, the first
place you need to look is in the mirror. I'm the butt of 70 percent
of my jokes,'' says Joe Caronia, who's been working the crowds at
Stanford's for a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   The day comedian John Candy died, Caronia, always joking about
his own weight, called one of his heavyweight comic brethren and
crowed: ``We just moved up one!''
</P>
<P>
   When you look in the mirror and ``have big ears, realize you
have big ears. And that it's funny,'' says newcomer comic Justin
Leon, whose ears aren't particularly large.
</P>
<P>
   Leon makes a lot of jokes based on being black, like the time
when the old woman in the beat-up car locked her doors when she saw
him in the next lane on the highway. ``We were going 65 miles an
hour! What did she think I was going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The choice is this: Joke or get ticked off. ``If I lived
miserable, I'd be a miserable man,'' Leon says. ``I'd be my
father!''
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Avoid joy-suckers.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to surround yourself with people who make you
feel happy and make you laugh. ``Being around funny people makes
you funny,'' Leon promises.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Chris Porter, a dead ringer for the cartoon character
Doug, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get around people who make you laugh if you
spend all day with some (bleep, bleep) in the next cubicle,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: Learn to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Laughter reduces stress and stimulates the body's endorphins.
Laughter is an outlet, like singing out loud in the shower, Burgess
of Stanford's says.
</P>
<P>
   Can't get a good belly laugh rolling? Practice, practice,
practice. Stand in front of the mirror, ``take off whatever you
need, and just start laughing,'' Fite at the Center for Humor and
Health says.
</P>
<P>
   Step 4: Keep humorous stimuli around.
</P>
<P>
   Create a humor file _ a stash of written jokes or other things
that make you laugh _ that you can pull out when the need arises.
Keep a humorous calendar on your desk at work.
</P>
<P>
   Or ``mirth'' the Net, says Dunkelblau, the psychologist who
keeps an ``emergency tape'' of comedian Emo Philips in his car.
``The Net has hundreds of thousands of laughter resources. There
are tons and tons of joke sites, humorous prose. It's everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's even easier than that, say the comedians, who cull
their best material from things that go on around them every day.
Just open your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Step 5: Relax.
</P>
<P>
   Try a technique called ``freeze frame.'' Unless you're driving,
close your eyes and call to mind a pleasant, restful image. ``It
works almost immediately,'' says psychologist Dunkelblau, whose
freeze-frame snapshot is of a shady spot on a beach, with good food
and someone interesting to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Step 6: Cock your head to one side and look at life with fresh
eyes. It's like when you get stumped playing Scrabble. You walk
away from the board and when you come back, ``boom, you find a
25-point word,'' Leon says.  &LR; tag1:To reach Lisa Gutierrez, features
reporter for The Star, call (816) 234-4987 or send e-mail to
lgutierrez &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-C     03-30 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE DECLINE OF CIVIL VIRTUE
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (p) political categories.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Apr. 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You hear lots of talk these days among the winners
of the Cold War about how the Russians still can't get their act
together. A decade after the collapse of communism, it's
fashionable to kick around a nation led by an ex-KGB spy with a
knack for stirring up a patriotic fever over rebellious Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Brand the Russian voters as dysfunctional dupes if you want. But
they sure do know how to reach their polling places to perform
their civic duty.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 percent of eligible voters turned out in the recent
Russian presidential election. Even in bombed-out Chechnya, two of
every three adults managed to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The overall turnout was almost the same as in the 1996
presidential race, which Boris Yeltsin won handily. I saw ballots
being cast in a Moscow prison, where inmates awaiting sentence
retain their voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, we've been honing democratic values for
nearly two and a quarter centuries. But for all of that, in our
last presidential election voter turnout for the first time dipped
below the halfway mark. There's scant reason to believe we'll do
any better this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at what's happening with the census, the
once-a-decade head count mandated by the Constitution. Some three
weeks ago, the U.S. Census Bureau mailed out 115 million
questionnaires, backed by a $168 million ad drive.
</P>
<P>
   The national goal: a 70 percent mail-in response by April 11,
when census takers are due to begin knocking on doors. The response
at the halfway mark: a low 46 percent. The percentage of
``entities'' that have met their target, as reported on the
bureau's official Web site: less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national response rate of 70 percent would signal that the
country has reversed a decades-long decline in civic
participation,'' says census director Kenneth Prewitt. The final
response rate was 78 percent in 1970, 75 percent in 1980 and 65
percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a decline in what the ancient Greeks once called
civic virtue is occurring at a time when the rapid convergence of
satellite, computer, television, radio, telephone, and print
services make it easier than ever for all comers to join in the new
digital democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Gutenberg made it possible for anyone to read. The Xerox machine
made it possible for anyone to publish. The Internet makes it
possible for everybody to experience just about anything and
everything.
</P>
<P>
   But can the Internet rekindle that old-time civic spirit, that
proud sense of community when folks turned out for political
picnics? About the most we can hope for: Our ever-present political
polls will detect a nostalgia gap, prompting the presidential
campaigns to respond by staging more made-for-TV election rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, our political ways are much better than Russia's. But just
what is it that we've managed to empower?
</P>
<P>
   It should be more than merely an enhanced ability to retreat
into like-minded communities -- places we fear leaving to cast
ballots, lest by doing so we're placed on jury rosters, places
where census takers are halted by intercoms at security gates.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
