<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2172 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN31-COX     03-30 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP's Krusee predicts a redistricting romp
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Republicans are going to control
redistricting in 2001 and make huge gains in the Texas House,
Senate and congressional delegation after the 2002 elections. And
there's not a thing the Democrats can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the spin, at least, from state Rep. Mike Krusee (R-Round
Rock). House GOP Caucus leader Ken Marchant of Coppell has made
Krusee the Republicans' point man on redistricting. He also chairs
Texans for Fair Redistricting, an unincorporated political
association.
</P>
<P>
   If you think there aren't many Democrats in Texans for Fair
Redistricting, you're right. Krusee, a hard-charging Republican who
got his seat by knocking off a Democrat in 1992 in rapidly
Republicanizing Williamson County, has the look of someone who is
thoroughly enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
   So here, without filtration, is why Krusee thinks the
Republicans' time has finally come:
</P>
<P>
   In past redistricting, Krusee said, Democrats completely
gerrymandered the lines to protect their incumbents by mounting a
house-to-house search for Democratic voters and cramming as many
Republicans as possible into as few districts as possible. (The
Democrats don't dispute this, though they note they protected
Republican incumbents, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Krusee said the Democrats also took advantage of the 5 percent
population deviation allowed between House districts to favor
Democrats in rural districts at the expense of Republicans in
rapidly growing suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been that districts such as Republican state Rep.
Terry Keel's in Travis County have tens of thousands more people
than some rural districts that are losing population, Krusee said.
</P>
<P>
   What that means, Krusee said, is that Republicans will make huge
gains by reconfiguring the districts to make them compact and
roughly equal in population.
</P>
<P>
   Krusee said the Republicans ``can protect every incumbent we
have'' without gerrymandering. ``There's no Republican incumbent
that has to worry about numbers within the next decade _ so we
don't have to go through those contortions,'' he said. ``We don't
have to cheat. We don't have to split communities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are not going to start with the premise that the
lines that are there are valid,'' Krusee said. ``We're starting
with the premise that they're invalid. It's going to be a new map _
fair to Texans, not fair to politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Texas Legislature should draw redistricting maps for
the Texas House or Senate that the Republicans don't like, their
Republican governor _ be it George W. Bush or current Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry _ can veto it.
</P>
<P>
   And then, under Texas law, the plan would go to the Legislative
Redistricting Board. For the first time ever, the five-member board
will include a Republican _ and not just one, but probably four.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Krusee contends, will give the Republicans more than
90 members of the 150-member House, contrasted with the 72 they
have now. In the Senate, they'll up their number from 16 of the 31
members to perhaps 20.
</P>
<P>
   If either of the plans winds up in court _ and that isn't
unlikely, given redistricting history _ the Texas Supreme Court is
completely Republican, and the federal bench and the U.S. Supreme
Court are now more Republican then Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The lines for the Texas congressional districts are also drawn
by the Legislature _ although if that map is vetoed or there is an
impasse, it either goes back to the Legislature or to the courts,
rather than to the redistricting board.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Republicans plan to pick up at least eight seats
from the current 17-13 deficit, Krusee said. Texas should get at
least two and perhaps three new districts because of population
growth. And with the threat of a Republican gubernatorial veto, the
Republicans expect to get 21 to 23 of the 32 or 33 seats, Krusee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ``have a choice,'' Krusee said. ``They can be for a
Republican plan for Congress, or no plan. It's either Republican or
the courts'' _ which still tilt Republican, even after seven years
of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Krusee is completely mindful that the Democrats are doing
everything they can to hold on to their 78-72 edge in the House and
to take back the Senate. But frankly, Krusee maintains, it doesn't
matter: Republicans will rule on redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a year, we'll have some sense of how
successful Republicans were in controlling redistricting. And on
Nov. 6, 2002 _ the day after the general election following
redistricting _ we'll find out if Krusee's dreams of GOP gains came
true.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the American-Statesman.
You may contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
