<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As obviously as ominously, our nation is resegregating
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Every half-price historian knows about Brown vs.
Board of Education, the ruling that launched school desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently with almost no fanfare, the Supreme Court may have put
history's lid on school desegregation _ a formaldehyde cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   The issue wasn't forced busing. That's already in the jar. What
happened in Montgomery County (Md.) Public Schools vs. Eisenberg
was that the Supreme Court refused to act on a lower court's ruling
that schools could not consider race in apportioning students.
</P>
<P>
   A Maryland man sued when his son couldn't enroll in a magnet
school because it would harm the racial diversity of his
neighborhood school. The 4th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court could surprise everyone by ruling in
schools' favor in a similar Virginia case about whether a magnet
school could consider racial balance. Unless that happens, said the
National School Board Association, the court has thrown out Brown
vs. Board of Education and reinstituted ``separate but equal'' as
the American way.
</P>
<P>
   This would fit quite neatly into a political trend: the
elevation of institutional race-blindness to a virtue, rather than
the disability it is.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we all want to be race-blind in how we as individuals
apportion kindness. But knowing that inequity exists, we are fools
to have policies blind to how race still plays a factor in aligning
wealth and power. We also are fools to think that race-blindness
yet can produce public institutions that serve diverse communities.
</P>
<P>
   A truly race-blind police department, for instance, would see no
reason to recruit minority officers, crucial though they may be in
giving a department a feel for its community and conveying to all
that the department reflects the city.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action at its origins in the Lyndon Johnson White
House was nothing more than such an acknowledgement _ that public
institutions should act affirmatively (though not necessarily
arithmetically) to give minorities and women chances on which white
males had a historic lock.
</P>
<P>
   Now in a backlash against quotas and racial preferences, we risk
hampering public institutions from acknowledging or acting to end
continuing racial stratification, even without quotas.
</P>
<P>
   As to racial separatism and drift, no more stark example exists
than some of the neighborhood schools that have come from busing's
end. There's no question that major benefits come from poor
children and their parents being able to walk to grade school. But
obvious social drawbacks, and challenges for other institutions,
are inherent in this ``separate equality,'' with desegregation no
longer schools' cross to bear.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of magnet schools, school districts know full well
that if one becomes racially identifiable, it loses its pull.
Typically, as in Waco, magnet student bodies were sculpted to
reflect the district's racial breakdown. This would make for a
setting that can attract from every corner of town.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to court cases like the one in Maryland, school
districts across the country put on hold the use of race in filling
out magnet schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco Independent School District stopped it two years ago
and has been filling magnet slots based on a race-blind lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, fortunately, is that Waco's four magnets continue
to reflect the district's general racial enrollment, which is 40
percent African-American, 40 percent Hispanic and 20 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how a blind draw influences the
racial identities of these campuses over time.
</P>
<P>
   If luck holds, we'll still have some racially balanced schools
in our community, without the Supreme Court's help.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
