<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-PULITZER31-COX     03-30 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PULITZER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: Story is written by a free-lancer; not for use by NYTNS
clients.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Woman sees America change by reading 80 years of Pulitzer
Prize-winning novels
 &HT;    By Renate Frydman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDALIA, Ohio _ When Carol Ann Brown sets a goal for herself,
she doesn't rest until it is accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   So no one who knows her was surprised when she said she was
going to read all the works that have won the Pulitzer Prize for
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Brown has not only reached her goal, but has
made annotated comments about each of the 80 books. Her comments
make fascinating reading in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   She would have finished the Pulitzer winners in one year, she
says, if she, ``hadn't stopped to read other books in between that
everyone is talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Born 70-plus years ago in Fort Thomas, Ky., across the Ohio
River from Cincinnati, Brown admits that she has a lifelong passion
for reading. A favorite story of her childhood involves her total
engrossment with books.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 12, my mother put a pot of potatoes on the stove.
She asked me to watch them while she was gone. In 20 minutes, I was
to turn them off as she was going to make potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat alongside the stove reading a book. By the time my
mother came home, there were clouds of black smoke and a terrible
stink. I never even noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   The reading was one outlet. Art was another. She showed an early
aptitude for art and won her first scholarship at the age of 10.
Later, she studied at the Studio School of Fashion Illustration in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Brown came to Dayton in 1947 after landing a job at Leakes
Furriers as a fashion illustrator for two years. She free-lanced
for another year and many of her illustrations appeared in the
Dayton Daily News and The Journal Herald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marveled at being paid to do what I had done with my paper
dolls,'' she says now.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed at the YWCA and the woman who lived directly above
her introduced her to her brother, Leonard Brown, a printer at NCR.
They were married in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Like many women of that time, she stopped working outside the
home to raise her children. In 1967, she returned to work at
Capitol Cleaners and became a problem-solver at many of their
stores. In 1982, both she and her husband retired and he died in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Like many avid readers, Brown does not like to be disturbed when
reading a really good book.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer list came about because she couldn't locate all of
the books on a Wright State University list of ``outstanding
books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something I could complete _ a project,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And what a project it was. Each book is briefly reviewed and
critiqued in her own special way. Yet she is quick to assert that,
``the comments are only my own perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What really impressed me was the contrast of our culture
during the years of the Pulitzer, from 1918 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``From `The Age of Innocence' by Edith Wharton written in 1921
to `The Hours' by Michael Cunningham in 1999, the Pulitzer Prize
winners often reflect the life and times. At the time of
`Innocence,' society forbade divorces. It had the proper social
code for the late 1800s. The hero and heroine had to part because
they couldn't divorce their spouses. The more recent `The Hours'
features bisexual stories.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a wonder that Brown finds the time, with many volunteer
activities, to read 100 books a year. Most people can barely fit
one book into their tight schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read everywhere and watch very little TV,'' Brown says. ``I
read mostly at night and go to bed with a book around 9 p.m. I have
public radio for background music.''
</P>
<P>
   She usually reads until the books falls to the floor. ``If it is
a really good book, I go until 1 a.m. or until it is finished. Like
`Snow Falling on Cedars' by David Guterson. I read all night. It
was wonderful. It gave a feeling of dread, yet at the end, a most
beautiful thing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading is not all Brown does. She volunteers at Aullwood
Audubon Center and at the information desk of the Dayton Art
Institute. One day a week, she studies the ``History of Religion''
with a Sinclair Community College professor at the Vandalia Senior
Citizens Center.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is very important in her life and she is secretary of
the education committee of the Vandalia United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   She attends a Book Lovers Club with a friend at the Dayton
Women's Club, where people talk about and trade books. Another day
each week, she teaches English idioms to a Japanese woman and she
also belongs to the Dayton Chamber Music Society.
</P>
<P>
   Brown satisfies her love of music by frequenting concerts at the
DAI and her love of getting to know people of other cultures
through travel to Europe, China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And Carol Brown has some more lists to tackle. One is a list of
``things I have never done that I want to do.'' Riding on a
motorcycle has already been crossed off that list.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the project of another 100 books, a list that
includes Shakespeare, Homer, and Chaucer's ``The Canterbury
Tales.'' She wants to enjoy these old favorites once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like a good book,'' says Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
