r e BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS31-COX     03-30 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ross' books sure to be talk of the town
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A recent conversation with Lillian Ross,
the great New Yorker writer who began on the magazine just after
World War II, revealed that she's working on two books. One is an
anthology of pieces from the Talk of the Town section of the
magazine for Random House; the other is a book about reporting that
Ross said she hopes will be ``like Strunk and White, but more
readable.''
</P>
<P>
   All this in addition to her projects for the magazine. Long may
her banner wave.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYTHING OLD IS NEW AGAIN ...
</P>
<P>
   James Agee and Walker Evans' ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men'' is
being issued yet again as an accompaniment for a traveling show of
Evans' photographs being sent on the road by the Metropolitan
Museum in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The book took years to sell out its first printing _ it was
initially published in 1941 _ but began to gather momentum in the
'60s and has gone through numerous editions and formats since.
Houghton Mifflin's new edition costs $30; if you can deal with the
Faulknerian rumblings of Agee's prose, it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   SOME THINGS TO LOOK FORWARD TO ...
</P>
<P>
   Dial will be publishing ``Driving Mr. Albert,'' a book by
Michael Paterniti that tells the story of his drive across country
with Einstein's brain and Thomas Harvey, the pathologist who did
the autopsy when the great scientist died in 1955 and took the
brain home for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   The trip began in New Jersey and ended in California, where they
showed the brain to Einstein's granddaughter. We'll have to wait
for publication in June to discover whether said granddaughter was
thrilled or appalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bad translations are a reliable source of hilarity, as proved by
``Free Drinks for Ladies With Nuts,'' a collection to be published
by Dutton. Jane O'Boyle's book encompasses everything from
incompetent menus (``Pork with Fresh Garbage''), to ragged syntax
in butcher shops (``Recent Veal''), to bad subtitles in movies
(``As the crow flies, so shall you die tonight.'')
</P>
<P>
   My favorite comes from an instruction manual for a Japanese-made
food processor: ``Not to be used for the other use.''
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``Books are the curse of the human race. Nine-tenths of existing
books are nonsense, and the clever books are the refutation of that
nonsense. The greatest misfortune that ever befell man was the
invention of printing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Benjamin Disraeli
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
