r e BC-PULITZER-REVIEWS31-CO     03-30 0195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-REVIEWS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brown's Pulitzer reviews
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Carol Ann Brown provided this review of some of
the Pulitzer Prize-winning novels. Her verdicts are brief and
highly personal.
</P>
<P>
   1956: ``Andersonville'' by MacKinlay Kantor. Saddest book.
</P>
<P>
   1959: ``Travels of Jamie McPheeters'' by Lewis Taylor. Fun
reading.
</P>
<P>
   1955: ``A Fable'' by William Faulkner. Least comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   (but in contrast...)
</P>
<P>
   1963: ``The Reivers'' by William Faulkner. Totally different.
Very funny.
</P>
<P>
   1961: ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' by Harper Lee. An almost perfect
book.
</P>
<P>
   1972: ``Angle of Repose'' by Wallace Stenger. Very good.
</P>
<P>
   1976: ``Humboldt's Gift'' by Saul Bellow. Great quotes.
</P>
<P>
   1983: ``The Color Purple'' by Alice Walker. Excellent book.
</P>
<P>
   1986: ``Lonesome Dove'' by Larry McMurtry. Best Western.
</P>
<P>
   1984: ``Ironweed'' by William Kennedy. Ugliest book.
</P>
<P>
   1989: ``Breathing Lessons'' by Anne Taylor. Worst woman ever.
</P>
<P>
   1990: ``Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love'' by Oscar Hijuelos.
Pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
