<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BAHAMAS31-COX     03-30 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHAMAS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vacationing in the Bahamas _ your way
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Bahamas are so mystifying for most
of us. There are 30 or so inhabited islands. Which one should you
choose? We've made it easy _ just take a spin around the islands
and see where you land.
</P>
<P>
   HARBOUR ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Pastel, clapboard houses built during and just after the
American Revolu- tion, make Harbour Island one of the prettiest in
the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   If you have loads of money and dress in designer resort wear,
drive a Mercedes 500 series sedan or Porsche Boxster and like to
hang out with celebrities such as Martha Stewart, Christie
Brinkley, Diane von Furstenberg, Tim Robbins and Susan Sarandon: Go
to Harbour Island, a colonial city of pastel clapboard houses and
white picket fences. Stay at Pink Sands (800-OUTPOST), a collection
of fashionable cottages starting at $475 per night for garden view,
next to a 3-mile-long pink sand beach. Pink Sands is owned by
Island Records CEO Chris Blackwell, and there's the occasional
music celeb such as Keith Richards and his family.
</P>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR
</P>
<P>
   Want to make some European friends? This is the place,
especially at Club Med, which draws plenty of French topless
sunbathers.
</P>
<P>
   If you are European or have European sensibilities and an
appreciation for French food, like to sunbathe topless, and drive a
Saab convertible or BMW Z3: Go straight to San Salvador, which some
say was Christopher Columbus' first landfall and was later the
destination of French sunbathers. Stay at the Club Med
(800-CLUBMED), one of the company's more upscale resorts, which has
diving, sailing, kayaking and sunbathing on incredible white-sand
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   PARADISE ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Towers with its bridge suite, where Michael Jackson
stays, is part of Atlantis, a mega-resort that has a huge casino, a
half-dozen high-rise hotels, and the world's largest outdoor
aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a gamblin' man or woman and wear lots of gold jewelry,
drive a caddie or Lincoln and like to see celebrities such as
Michael Jackson, Oprah, Ivana and various Bee Gees: Go to Paradise
Island, a lushly landscaped island of high-rise hotels only a
causeway away from the colonial capital of Nassau. Stay at
theme-park-like Atlantis (800-ATLANTIS), which has the world's
largest open-air aquarium, humongous casino, a quarter-mile,
man-made river and a white sand beach.
</P>
<P>
   BIMINI
</P>
<P>
   Here, islanders remember Ernest Hemingway shooting sharks with a
submachine gun.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a sailor, fisherman and/or heavy beer drinker; drive a
Jeep Wrangler or Toyota Tacoma and you like to hang out where
Ernest Hemingway, Howard Hughes and Bing Crosby once stayed: Go to
Bimini, only 50 miles across the Gulf Stream from Miami. Stay in
the hilltop cottage (part of Blue Waters Resort, 242-347-3166)
where Ernest Hemingway lived, or next door at the modest but
extremely lively Compleat Angler Hotel (242-347-3122), or the
modern Big Game Resort (800-737-1007).
</P>
<P>
   GRAND BAHAMA
</P>
<P>
   If you like to shop at hundreds of duty-free stores and you wear
real rubies and eat off real English china but enjoy a bargain,
drive a Toyota Avalon or Mazda Millennia and like to see
celebrities such as Robin Williams, who took his family to Club
Fortuna: Go to Freeport, Grand Bahama, which has hundreds of
duty-free stores and miles of uncrowded, white-sand beaches. Stay
at the Lucayan Reef Village (800-582-2926), a seaside resort with a
fabulous renovation that includes a series of pools, high-style
public rooms and guest rooms offering a view of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU
</P>
<P>
   Kids can march with trained flamingos at Ardastra Gardens and
Zoo, where they can also handle snakes and feed ducks. Cable Beach,
home to big resorts including the Radisson, is nearby.
</P>
<P>
   If you are parents who like to vacation with your kids, drive a
Dodge Caravan or an SUV made for soccer moms, not construction
workers (Honda CRV, Toyota Rav4) and don't care about hanging out
with celebrities: Go to Nassau, New Providence Island, which has
resorts with kids' camps, beaches, forts and a kid-sized zoo. Stay
at the Radisson Cable Beach Casino and Golf Resort (800-333-3333),
where kids will enjoy Camp Junkanoo, which has counselors and
plenty of activities for kids while the parents can gamble,
water-ski, parasail, kayak and more.
</P>
<P>
   EXUMA
</P>
<P>
   If you enjoy playing sports as well as watching ESPN, drive an
SUV or truck made for real men (Dodge Ram, Humvee) and like to hang
out with celebrities such as Toronto Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi,
Giants manager Dusty Baker (who hosts a bonefishing tournament
every January), Jack Nicklaus, Lee Iacocca and Jimmy Buffett, who
amuses islanders by fishing out of his seaplane: Go to Exuma, a
bucolic island, which offers all the sport fishing and bonefishing
you can pay for. Stay at the historic Peace &AMP; Plenty Inn
(800-525-2210), where you can hire bonefish guides such as J.J.
Dames, who is a guide for Iacocca and Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
