<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-THEHOOK31-COX     03-30 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-THEHOOK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Implausibility keeps `Hook' from grabbing you
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bryce Proctorr has two massive problems:
</P>
<P>
   1. His wife is threatening to clean him out in a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   2. For the first time in his career as a best-selling novelist,
he's hopelessly blocked. His deadline is past due, he needs the
money _ $500,000 _ that he gets on delivery of the manuscript, and
there's not a coherent page to be found.
</P>
<P>
   So it's fortuitous that Proctor meets his old friend Wayne
Prentice, who had a promising start as a writer years ago but has
gradually lost momentum. In an effort to jump-start his career,
Prentice desperately adopted the pseudonym of Tim Fleet. It hasn't
helped; Tim Fleet, like his creator, has declined from midlist to
no-list.
</P>
<P>
   Even Prentice's agent insults him. ``You know I'm a fan of your
stuff,'' he says, ``I just wish there were more of us out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryce makes his old friend an offer. If Wayne will give him his
new book so he can pass it off as his own, Proctorr will split the
money with him.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice says yes.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one other thing, says Proctorr. You have to kill my
wife, too.
</P>
<P>
   And Donald Westlake, among the most reliable pros in the writing
game _ everything people say about Elmore Leonard could more
justifably be said about Westlake _ is off on what seems to have
been meant as a followup to his superb ``The Ax'' (for my money,
his best book).
</P>
<P>
   There have been other riffs on the basic theme of ``The Hook'' _
remember Ira Levin's play ``Deathtrap''? _ and they all seem to run
into trouble in the third act. Westlake's stumble comes earlier. It
begins with the slightly stiff, implausible names _ Bryce Proctorr
sounds like something out of Danielle Steel _ and continues with
equally implausible behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Wayne be so willing to kill a perfect stranger? His
ego may be starving, but he's not; his wife has a good job and
makes a comfortable living. Or is Westlake saying that a pseudonym
is as invariable a step towards homicide as, say, incivility?
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Prentice keeps up his end of the bargain and, in a
scene that seems to owe a little to Hitchcock's ``Torn Curtain,''
dispatches the deeply unpleasant Mrs. Proctorr. He delivers his
manuscript to Proctorr, who does a light polish to make it sound
like him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, things get interesting. Despite the thriller premise,
Westlake steers his book in an unexpected direction. ``The Hook''
turns out not to be about the spiraling complications of deceit _
Westlake brings in a policeman for a few brief scenes, but we're
closer to Inspector Lestrade than Inspector Porfiry _ but rather
about the slow dissolution of a human personality.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of its problems, for much of its length, ``The Hook''
is entertaining, especially for publishing insiders: ``The big
chain bookstores, they've each got the computer,'' Wayne complains,
``and the computer says, we took five thousand of his last book,
but we only sold thirty-one hundred, so don't order more than
thirty five hundred. So there's a thinner distribution, and you
sell twenty-seven hundred, so the next time they order three
thousand ...''
</P>
<P>
   And Westlake explains the very real modern economic reasons
behind a pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the sales staff. If they know Tim Fleet is Wayne
Prentice, even though it's supposed to be a secret outside the
publishing house, it has that stink of failure on it already. But
if they think Tim Fleet is Tim Fleet, really think that, and he's
brand-new, and he's never failed because he's never been tested
before, they can get excited. They can do wonders, when they're
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Westlake's characters are types, but he does them well,
and he does desperation really well.
</P>
<P>
   But the book doesn't grab and squeeze the way ``The Ax'' and
some of his other books do _ the characters are unsympathetic,
which is all right, but they lack charm, and that's not all right.
</P>
<P>
   The book winds up with a chilly little farewell that would have
made a dandy wind-up for an ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents,'' but it
seems slightly off-key for a writer who's always specialized in
unblinking, cold-blooded moral relativity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
