   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-RECORDS (Edwardsville, Ill.) _ Some law enforcement
agencies in Illinois are prohibiting public access to police
records, citing a recent Supreme Court ruling limiting what defense
lawyers and prosecutors can say to ensure that criminal defendants
get a fair trial. Illinois Press Association officials have
attacked the ruling and say they will fight it. ``There is now an
atmosphere of fear on the part of police and prosecutors to make
any statement about anything,'' says David Bennett, the press
group's executive director. By GARY SCHNEIDER.
</P>
<P>
   FEMINIST-PARLEY (San Francisco) _ The largest U.S. gathering of
women in 23 years brings the warriors of the old millennium _
Smeal, Steinem, Friedan _ together with the up-and-comers of the
new one to kick-start the feminist movement. The occasion is this
weekend's Feminist Expo 2000 in Baltimore. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING ATHEIST (Austin, Texas) _ Making his first appearance in
a Texas courtroom, Gary Paul Karr, the only person facing charges
in the disappearance of atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair, got a
court-appointed lawyer and had his arraignment set for next week.
By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POW (San Antonio) _ Army Spc. Steven M. Gonzales fell
from the exposed turret of his Humvee into its protective cocoon,
suddenly realizing it was being hit by bullets. As a boy, he'd
loved GI Joe toys and played soldier near his home in Temple,
firing at friends with a water rifle. Now he was being hunted by
soldiers armed with assault rifles and rocket-propelled grenades. A
year ago Friday, Gonzales and Staff Sgts. Christopher J. Stone and
Andrew A. Ramirez became the first and only American POWs of the
78-day Kosovo air campaign. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Voters in Upstate New York may be the
deciding factor in the ever-tightening U.S. Senate race between
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani, according to a new
poll. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The Hearst Corp. said four
government agencies had not objected to its imminent plan to sell
the San Francisco Examiner and buy the San Francisco Chronicle, the
company's lawyers said in court papers. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ California's robust economy will
continue to grow apace in 2000, but tightening credit concerns and
a crippling housing crunch will help cool off the Golden State in
coming years, according to the latest quarterly predictions
released by UCLA's Anderson School of Management. By ALAN T.
SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Jack Black was a professional
criminal who wrote the 1926 best-seller ``You Can't Win,'' which
recounted his life on the road, on the lam, in prison straitjackets
and under the lash, and his eventual rehabilitation by the great
San Francisco Bulletin Editor Fremont Older. ``You Can't Win,'' an
underground classic and William Burroughs' favorite book, has been
reprinted by San Francisco's AK Press. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A new Gold Rush is sweeping San
Francisco. And it is easily as potent (and mixed a blessing) as the
19th century version that transformed a pastoral Spanish mission
town into an overnight metropolis. The driving force: legions of
new technology companies, or dot-coms. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
