<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONVICT-KEYNOTE31-COX     03-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICT-KEYNOTE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cop By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Outraged law enforcement organizations from
across the nation are mobilizing to persuade Antioch College to
cancel a planned audiotape commencement address by a Pennsylvania
death-row inmate convicted of killing a Philadelphia police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   One national group promised a dignified but ``very large''
protest demonstration at the April 29 graduation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stomach turned in knots when I saw that your commencement
committee voted to have Mumia Abu-Jamal deliver the keynote
address,'' Kevin Temple, Dayton police detective and president of
the Dayton Fraternal Order of Police, said in a letter to Antioch
College President Bob Devine.
</P>
<P>
   Temple pointed to the slayings in Costa Rica this month of
Antioch College student Emily Howell and former Antioch student
Emily Eagen. He said their killers, after their conviction, will
also ``have a cause of their own. I have the feeling your college
will not invite them to speak in an effort to raise greater public
awareness of their cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Antioch College, in Yellow Springs, Ohio, gave no
sign of bowing to the pressure. Some of the hundreds of e-mail
messages that the college has received represent ``hate mail'' that
is intended to ``intimidate and harass us,'' Antioch Dean of
Students Scott Warren said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Antioch has a long tradition of democratic self-governance, and
the graduating seniors selected their commencement speaker by vote,
Warren said. The college ``does not take a position on the merits
of (Abu-Jamal's) case'' but does support his First Amendment right
of free speech, Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can learn from all voices,'' the dean said.
</P>
<P>
   Suzie Sawyer, executive director of the national organization
Concerns of Police Survivors Inc. (COPS), said the invitation to
Abu-Jamal represents ``a slap in the face of the memory of
Antioch's own students'' killed in Central America. ``It's a
disgrace,'' Sawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Camdenton, Mo.-based organization says it has membership of
more than 10,000 families. Sawyer promised a vigorous mail, fax and
e-mail campaign to campus officials. If the college does not
reconsider, Sawyer promised a significant demonstration of support
for police survivors and their advocates when Antioch awards
diplomas to its 110 graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, Yellow Springs will be a very busy place on April
29,'' Sawyer said. ``It will be a very dignified protest, but it
will be a very large one.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Fischer, Xenia police officer and president of the Greene
County FOP, said his organization will send a letter asking Antioch
officials to reconsider. Mike Taylor, secretary of the statewide
FOP, said his group will do the same, and noted the topic ``will be
on the agenda'' of a national FOP board meeting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said students requested that Abu-Jamal speak not about
his court case, but on the topics of how one individual can affect
the world and on the true meaning of revolution, Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was ``horribly inappropriate, insensitive and totally
unfair'' to compare the Costa Rica murders with the Abu-Jamal case.
There is little in dispute about the motives and circumstances
involving the Costa Rica slayings, while the Philadelphia case has
been on appeal for almost two decades and has spawned significant
support for both the prosecution and defense arguments, Warren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal, 45, a radio journalist and former Black Panther
activist, was convicted of fatally shooting Philadelphia police
Officer Daniel Faulkner after the officer stopped Abu-Jamal's
brother for driving the wrong way down a city street. Abu-Jamal's
cause has drawn international support from death penalty opponents
and from supporters who claim Abu-Jamal was targeted for political
reasons and framed in the killing. Amnesty International last month
called for a new trial for Abu-Jamal, citing what it called
judicial bias, irregularities in the police investigation and
possible coercion of key witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the evidence against Abu-Jamal is overwhelming.
He and Faulkner were found lying a few feet from each other;
Abu-Jamal's gun, with five empty shell casings, was found nearby;
and two witnesses testified that Abu-Jamal confessed at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court in October refused to hear Abu-Jamal's
last appeal from state courts. His appeal is now in federal court
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
