   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet LIFESTYLES page for
the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0330: SOFT SKIN -- There are three secrets to
glowing, healthy complexion, say skin-care experts _ moisturize,
moisturize, moisturize. And after months of cold air with low
humidity and superheated dry indoor air, your skin is ready for a
spring break and the need for moisture treatment. In an informal
test of drugstore vs. department store moisturizers, our four
testers split evenly with two preferring the less expensive brands
and two the pricey ones. (Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Art includes four 2-column color photos of women who tested the
lotions and four 2-column photos of the different brands of
lotions.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CHEAP CHIC -- It's hard to miss the design revolution
taking place in the aisles of the nation's mass merchandisers.
Designer looks are coming to discount retailers. (Brooks, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 1-column color photo of a
chair, a 1-column color photo of a teakettle, a 1-column color
photo of a can opener and a 1-column color photo of a wall clock.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CONSUMER Q&AMP;A -- How to get crayon marks off a freshly
painted wall and other answers to consumer-related questions.
(Greig, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week.) COXNET TRAVEL 0328 -- In 1889, New York World
reporter Nellie Bly circled the globe. In 2000, a modern-day Nellie
chronicles her own around-the-world adventure. It was a marathon
trip, eight countries in four weeks and sometimes several cities in
one country. But of course, the real joy of the trip was the people
encountered along the way. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) Art
includes a 2-column color illustration of her route, a 3-column
color photo of the Eiffel Tower, a 1-column color photo of a woman
selling fruit in Fengdu, China, a 2-column color photo of the
Parthenon in Athens, a 18-pica color photo of the changing of the
guard at Buckingham Palace, and a 2-column color photo of the lobby
of Raffles Hotel in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GLOBAL NOTEBOOK -- Some odds and ends observations from a
trip around the world. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- San Francisco is stretching its streetcar
tun to the Fisherman's Wharf. (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The following is a special Canada section from the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CANADA-FUNDY _ NEW BRUNSWICK, Canada _ Visiting the Bay
of Fundy, the yawning inlet between New Brunswick and Nova Scotia
that is home to some of the world's highest tides. (Hamilton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FUNDY-COVE _ ST. JOHN, New Brunswick _ A warming stay at the Inn
on the Cove, a bed-and-breakfast inm that's situated in an
appealingly quirky melange of Victorian and 1950s-style
architecture. The inn sits on a 3-acre climb above Sand Cove, a
tranquil inlet on the Bay of Fundy west of downtown Saint John, New
Brunswick.(Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDY-STJOHN _ ST. JOHN, New Brunswick _ The first thing a
visitor to St. John notices, undeniably, are the smokestacks.
Towering exhaust shafts atop area pulp mills and refineries loom
over this working-class city on the Bay of Fundy _ population,
125,000 _ like noxious shrines to the gods of commerce. But, to
borrow the movie poster come-on from ``American Beauty,'' look
closer: Behind the mask of industry is a charming, history-rich
town that reflects a world of influences. (Hamilton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO-GARDENS _ TORONTO _ Touring the public gardens of
Toronto: The narrow sandy streets wander past funky little gardens
ablaze with towering sunflowers, rampant petunias and perky
dahlias, all with heads held so high you'd swear you could see them
nod hello. It's a neighborhood so eclectic, so earthy, you'd expect
to find it in the villages of the English countryside or the rural
hamlets of the Deep South. But a sudden breeze off the water jolts
you to another locale _ the gleaming modern skyline of Toronto,
just 15 minutes by ferry across Lake Ontario. There, along the
banks of Canada's largest city, are small public parks that double
as pristine gardens celebrating music and the arts with giant
contemporary metal sculpture. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GARDENTOUR _ A tour of eight Toronto garden spots. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-EVENTS _ A calendar of warm-weather events and
celebrations across Canada. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS _ The bahamas are so near _ Grand Bahama Island is only
60 miles from West Palm Beach _ yet so mystifying for most of us.
There are 30 or so inhabited islands. Which one should you choose?
We've made it easy _ just take a spin around the island and see
where you land. (Palm Beach Post, Blackerby) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Getaway feature from Wednesday paper. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-CONTENT _ WASHINGTON _ The Parents Television Council
releases a report comparing four weeks of prime-time TV programming
from the falls of 1989 and 1999. (Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week.) COXNET BOOKS 0328 -- Physicist, author Brian Greene
aspires to solve the mysteries of the universe. Greene has been
acclaimed as a popularizer of physics in the style of the late Carl
Sagan. When his book ``The Elegant Universe'' became a best-seller
last year, the media all but canonized the telegenic Greene as the
new physicist who can communicate the wonder and mysteries of the
cosmos.(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a
2-column color photo of author Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AUTHOR PROFILE -- Author Nora Roberts says writing is the
easy part, it's all the other stuff that's a drag. (Marton, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of the
author.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BIOGRAPHY -- Tom King's extensive bio of entertainment
mogel David Geffen stirs up some controversy, but little else.
(Salamon, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes a 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NONFICTION -- A sad story of author Hesper Anderson's
childhood renders a great career. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) Art
includes a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES -- A new biography of screen star Lillian
Gish lovingly renders a great career. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Sportswriter Red Smith's magical prose
comes to life in a new collection of his writings. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 1-column color photo of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ A recent conversation with Lillian Ross, the
great New Yorker writer who began on the magazine just after World
War II, revealed that she's working on two books. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-THEHOOK _ Review of the book ``The Hook,'' by Donald W.
Westlake. Despite problems, the book is entertaining, especially
for publishing insiders. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Review and comment on ``How We Got Here: The
70's _ The Decade that Brought You Modern Life _ For Better or
Worse.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundup of the latest children's books. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Kent Haruf should have called his National Book
Award-nominated novel ``Eyes Wide Shut'' instead of ``Plainsong.''
In order to ``feel'' the story, he wrote the first draft with a
stocking cap over his face. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-HIGH _ Dave Larsen's review of ``High Fidelity,'' which he
gives a B+. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-ROAD _ Dave Larsen's review of ``The Road to El Dorado,''
which he gives a B-. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-LESS _ Review of ``Not One Less.'' (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GLORY _ Movie review: ``Price of Glory.'' Grade: C-.
(Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SKULLS _ Movie review: ``The Skulls.'' Grade: C+. (Murray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TOONS _ Hollywood is enjoying a 'toon boom. Not the sort
of explosion that occurs when one of Wile E. Coyote's ACME products
goes awry, but an animation renaissance. Ten animated films are to
be released this year. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
