<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MFUME DOESN'T NEED TO YANK ON REBEL FLAG IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush doesn't need the help of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People to win Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, it is well that NAACP President/CEO Kweisi Mfume has
exhibited the industrial-strength good sense to decline to dilute
the national organization's resources by taking an active role in
the effort by the state chapter to persuade Bush to take a stand
against the Confederate battle flag _ henceforth, the CBF.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Texas chapter has urged the governor to order
the removal of a plaque containing a replica of the Rebel flag from
the entrance to the building in which the Texas Supreme Court and
the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals are located.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has demurred. He lobbed out the idea of attaching some kind
of historical footnote to the plaque to explain why it is
appropriate for it to be where it is. When Gary Bledsoe, president
of the Texas NAACP, wouldn't buy that compromise, the governor said
he'd take the matter under study.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe insists that the Rebel flag symbolizes ``hate, division
and racism'' to African-Americans. He might have added that most of
those who insist on waving that flag in the faces of
African-Americans know this and that their intent is to hurt and
insult.
</P>
<P>
   The CBF that adorns the dome of the state Capitol in Columbia,
S.C., does that insulting and hurting in grand style. And that's
why the national NAACP is waging a full-tilt-boogie
African-American tourist boycott against the Palmetto State.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume has prophesied that the CBF atop the South Carolina
Capitol ``will come down.'' And he's most likely right. The boycott
has picked up steam since it started in January. The governor of
the state already has cried his ``uncle.'' But the Legislature
won't budge.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heritage thing, say many white South Carolinians. And
many of them are serious about that. But for others, perhaps the
majority, it's just a race thing, a resentment thing at the social,
political and economic advances that African-Americans have made
since the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, South Carolina will not be able to endure the
pangs of tourist dollar withdrawal indefinitely, and it will remove
the CBF from its inappropriate perch. When that happens, other
states that assign too much prominence to the CBF will let prudence
be their guide.
</P>
<P>
   So said Mfume at a news conference in Fort Worth last week. And
maybe that was his only reason for declining to enlist the national
organization in Bledsoe's effort to remove the CBF plaque from the
entryway to Texas' highest courts.
</P>
<P>
   But if Mfume is as politically astute as he is reputed to be,
there is another reason. He knows that such a push in Texas could
backfire against the NAACP and give Bush a boost. After all, the
Texas CBF is located in a place that is not visited frequently by a
lot of people. African-Americans have to go out of their way to
find it and get insulted by it.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Bush could portray himself as the victim of a
blatant NAACP plot to embarrass him. That would play well with the
white, Republican majority that will most likely deliver the
state's Electoral College votes to Bush. So he can, with political
impunity, stand in the Supreme Court door and proclaim: ``CBF
today, CBF tomorrow, CBF forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that wouldn't go over very well with Texas
African-Americans. But so what? Bush has never done anything
significant in his political life to indicate that he gives a
flying flip about the African-American vote.
</P>
<P>
   His only nod toward minorities in the state is his cosmetic
courtship of Hispanics. And that is a transparent bid to divide
that voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush relented and pushed the right buttons to get the
plaque moved, he could still claim to have done so out of duress.
And that would accomplish the same political purpose. The NAACP
would come out looking like the heavy.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that Bledsoe is wrong. His cause is just.
Mfume has given the national organization's blessing to the Texas
chapter's effort. It's just not going to waste any time, money and
effort on a Texas boycott.
</P>
<P>
   And that's smart. If the Texas chapter can use gentle persuasion
to change the governor's mind, so be it. But neither the national
organization nor the state chapter needs to go to great lengths to
provide Bush with an issue that could guarantee that he would win
Texas and help in some other states.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
