<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE GOLD RUSH WITHOUT BOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new Gold Rush is sweeping San Francisco. And
it is easily as potent (and mixed a blessing) as the 19th-century
version that transformed a pastoral Spanish mission town into an
overnight metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force: legions of new technology companies, or
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, along with residential real estate, which hasn't
been a bargain here since landfill made North Beach a geographical
misnomer, commercial real estate prices are now heading to the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-widening invasion of dot-com enterprises, most with a
Monopoly Game relationship to money, have ``become the latest focus
in the war over growth in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-business folks are inclined to make life super easy for
dot-coms, especially with regard to relaxing the annual development
limit of 950,000 square feet on downtown office space mandated by
14-year-old Proposition M.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-growthers, who have watched the practical boundaries of
``downtown'' spread like an oil slick across the city, see
longtime, low-rent-paying businesses as threatened, goo-covered
wildlife. To them, Proposition M's controls are all that stand
between the survival of these enterprises and extinction (or
Oakland).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe scariest of all, the city's official planners admit they
don't even know how big the dot-com space demand is, let alone how
to solve it in as fair and timely a manner as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1986 when voters enacted Proposition M, the threat was
proliferation of dense, high-rise concrete boxes that promised to
bring lots more automobiles downtown and South of Market while
blocking out air and light to the edge of the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-commerce was but a futuristic dream in the brains of a
handful of cyber geeks who worked in still-affordable Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they knew that a panoply of Internet companies _ each
needing vasts amounts of space, electricity and a ``hip'' San
Francisco address _ would one day be the focal point of the war
over growth in this city. But who else did?
</P>
<P>
   Planning commissions being what they are _ political appointees
who rarely have a strong background in urban complexities _ San
Francisco's could hardly be counted on to provide vision. Nor, as
the current commission has demonstrated, could it be expected to
swiftly recognize a growing crisis or to boldly react.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, here in 2000, the allegedly sophisticated city of
San Francisco is operating on a ``downtown'' land-use policy that
hasn't been updated since 1986. And, boy, is the age starting to
show.
</P>
<P>
   The only real control on dot-com development seems so far to be
the most libertine mechanism known to humankind: what the market
will bear.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years alone, commercial rents have more than
doubled South of Market and edged way up in surrounding areas like
Potrero Hill, the Mission District and Jackson Square.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the only casualties from dot-com takeovers are
rats, cockroaches, bad plumbing and a building's potential collapse
in an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, big-spending companies have elbowed out small
industries, crafts and blue-collar trades that traditionally
populated the peripheries of downtown. Also shut out are bare-bones
nonprofit organizations and genuine (not faked for a live-work loft
lease) artists.
</P>
<P>
   Before we find ourselves reading about how sad it is that
money-eating San Francisco General Hospital or the War Memorial
Veterans Building (in need of $80 million in seismic retrofitting)
have been taken over by a consortium of successful dot-coms,
mightn't we ask the Planning Commission one teensy little favor?
</P>
<P>
   Wake up, will ya?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
