<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-DAVID-DUCHOVNY-D     03-30 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-DAVID-DUCHOVNY-DIRECTS-THE-X-FILES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ACCORDING TO DAVID DUCHOVNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of David
Duchovny directing a scene from ``The X-Files.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The truth is this: David Duchovny is tired of playing Fox
Mulder. But writing and directing ``The X-Files'' are terrific
perks, and the bucks _ lawsuit notwithstanding _ thrill his
accountant.
 &HT;    The original ``X'' man is almost scarily into his
double-barreled task as writer/director of ``Hollywood, A.D.,'' a
jaunty comic installment in the popular series that's set to air on
April 30.
 &HT;    Over on Stage 8 at Twentieth Century Fox Studios in Hollywood,
Duchovny sits ensconced in a director's chair, dutifully studying a
monitor and soaking in his surroundings. And well he should, since
much of the cavernous stage has been transformed into an
ultra-Gothic cemetery, replete with trees and plants, creepy
tombstones and machine-gun-toting zombies.
 &HT;    Several crewmen are helping Duchovny stage an intricate crane
shot, during which the camera will pan across the whole cemetery
from high above, then dip down until it locates Mulder (Duchovny)
and Scully (Gillian Anderson). Meanwhile, other crewmembers assume
such vital tasks as creating smoke, touching up zombies and
ensuring that guest stars Tea Leoni and Garry Shandling stand in
the right spots.
 &HT;    Duchovny and company rehearse the camera move several times,
then the fledgeling director calls for the camera to roll _ and
watches, slack-jawed, as everything comes together.
 &HT;    ``This is incredible,'' a second assistant director comments.
 &HT;    Duchovny grins and seconds the motion.
 &HT;    ``It's moviemaking magic,'' he says, shaking his head.
 &HT;    A day later, Duchovny settles onto a couch at Los Angeles' Four
Seasons hotel, surrounded by videotapes of dailies that he's been
watching between interviews. The actor/writer/director seems to be
on a natural high. Critics and audiences alike are giving thumbs up
to his latest film, the feel-good weepie ``Return to Me,'' and
Duchovny feels good about ``Hollywood, A.D.'' as well.
 &HT;    ``I have a friend who has a friend who is an FBI agent, and he
comes to Los Angeles to pitch ideas,'' Duchovny says. ``I thought,
`What if that was Skinner (Mitch Pileggi)?' What if Skinner was
talking to Hollywood guys about making a movie, and what if he was
ripping off Mulder? What if he was using Mulder's life and selling
it to Hollywood _ and what would Hollywood do with it? How would
they change it?''
 &HT;    Thus the episode finds Mulder and Scully killing time during a
forced vacation by visiting the set of an ``X-Files'' feature,
where Leoni _ Duchovny's real-life wife _ is playing a buxom Scully
and Shandling a deadpan Mulder.
 &HT;    Needless to say, the real Mulder and Scully wind up deep in an
X-File with potentially explosive religious ramifications.
 &HT;    ``We've been having a lot of fun filming it,'' Duchovny says.
``I think it will be pretty entertaining. That's the goal.''
 &HT;    Despite the air of good will, Duchovny appears ready to bid
farewell to both ``The X-Files'' and his alter-ego of seven years.
However, negotiations are ongoing in a bid to bring him back into
the fold for one last season.
 &HT;    ``There would be things I'd like to know about Mulder if we were
to take the show in a different direction,'' he says. ``But I don't
think that's wise, and I know it's never going to happen.
 &HT;    ``So, for the Mulder that I play week after week, there's
nothing left.''
 &HT;    If, bottom line, Duchovny prefers not to return for an eighth
year, why would he even entertain the possibility? Other than
money, what's the incentive?
 &HT;    ``There is no incentive,'' says Duchovny, who would rather
continue playing Mulder on the big screen. ``The only incentive
would be writing and directing, which is what I'm doing now. I'm
allowed to have a really nice budget, a great crew, great cameras
and all the film I want.
 &HT;    ``More than money, the reason that I would come back would be to
write and direct,'' he says. ``In fact, it's not for the money at
all _ the money is always good, but in the end it's not worth
anything. It's really a chance to teach myself other things I want
to do.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The X-Files,'' consult the
official Web site at www.thex-files.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
