<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV07-N     03-30 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 TWO GROWN MEN TAKE SIBLING RIVALRY TO EXTREMES  
 FOR USE FRIDAY, APRIL 7, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRJOY-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call (888)-269-8796. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 c.2000 Dr. Joy Browne. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: My 38-year-old brother (who has never liked me)
recently decided that he dislikes me so much that he has requested
that our mother hold separate holiday celebrations so that he
doesn't have to see me. Our troubled relationship really came to a
head when he read a private e-mail I sent to our mother complaining
about how he has tried to exclude me from family events and how he
has forced our mother to be with us separately at meals or other
activities.
</P>
<P>
   While my brother's actions sadden me a great deal, I am more
upset that my mother has allowed him to manipulate the time that I
spend with her. My mother seems to feel that there is nothing wrong
and that I am overreacting. Please advise how I can best handle
these family conflicts. _ S.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The two of you are taking sibling rivalry to a rather
ridiculous extreme, if you'll pardon me for saying so. It is not
unusual for kids to be competitive for mom's attention, but the two
of your are taking this to such an extreme that you'll both be
wrinkled as prunes before it ends.
</P>
<P>
   Let your mother deal with your brother any way she wants. You
deal with him in whatever way works best for you. This may mean the
two of you will be estranged for a while. I do agree with you that
your mother is probably allowing this to go on longer than it
should because she allows him to dictate separate family
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   But for right now, this is your mother's problem. I would stop
sending e-mails that are nasty. Don't ever put anything in writing
_ especially in e-mails _ that you don't want to defend in court.
</P>
<P>
   Go out of your way to be charming to your brother. Let your
mother do whatever she wants to do. Try and understand that if both
you and your brother are willing to let go of this nonsense, it
probably will stop. As long as you are both willing to keep it
going, it will continue.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: I have a 15-year-old son who has driven a wedge so
big between me and my husband of seven years (he's not my son's
father) that we have separated. My husband wants a divorce, and he
and my son refuse to spend time in the same house.
</P>
<P>
   I want my marriage to last. I have learned since our separation
that my son had been causing conflicts. At the time I couldn't
believe he could do such a thing. I was probably feeling guilty
because when my first marriage ended, I gave custody of my son to
his father. I didn't plan to get remarried and believed he needed a
father in his life. I maintained a long distance visitation
schedule. Then my son told me a few years ago that he was being
mistreated by his stepfamily, so I went to court and regained
custody in Oct. 1998.
</P>
<P>
   I hope you can offer some information or suggest a book that can
help me to find ways to deal with the conflict between my husband
and my son. I feel I'm being forced to make a choice between the
two of them and I don't like that position. Is it true that parents
should always side with their children in such situations? _ D.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I don't think the issue is whether or not parents
should always side with children. It sounds like something else has
gone wrong here, given that things were relatively stable for a
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   It's true: Both the men in your life have legitimate claims on
you. Your son needs you because you haven't been his mom for the
past couple of years. You weren't involved with him so you owe him.
Your husband also has some reasonable expectations that you will be
a good wife to him since the two of you have been married for this
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than feeling that you have to choose between your husband
and your son, I would choose a good family counselor. A 15-year-old
child is not the easiest person to live with, but your son has a
legitimate claim. He feels you abandoned him. Consequently, his
wish to have you to himself may be more profound than an ordinary
teen-ager's demand. This doesn't necessarily mean his claim is
valid. You can't be anything more than his mother _ you certainly
can't be his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Find a good marriage counselor and figure out how you can do the
best by both the men in your life. It's clear you love them both
very much.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168, or
to drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered
in this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
