<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-30 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CRIME OF PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The speech began: ``I am classified as an
habitual criminal. The habitual criminal is a person who habitually
retains stupid lawyers. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   After the light opening, the speaker continued: ``I saw a man
hanged when I was a boy about 17 years old in the San Francisco
Jail. If I remember right, he was the last man hanged in the old
county jail of San Francisco _ a young man who had killed his
sweetheart. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him when they marched him up the steps to the scaffold.
He looked directly at me and I looked at him, and the clear light
of reason was not in that man's eyes. He was mentally dead, and so
far as punishment was concerned, they should have punished his
insane relatives. If he was punished at all, it was long before he
got to the scaffold.''
</P>
<P>
   Did some bleeding heart liberal, some radical agitator, some
Mumia give this speech? No, Jack Black gave this speech to the New
York state Assembly in 1930, and who was Jack Black?
</P>
<P>
   Black was a professional criminal who wrote the 1926 best-seller
``You Can't Win,'' which recounted his life on the road, on the
lam, in prison straitjackets and under the lash, and his eventual
rehabilitation by the great San Francisco Bulletin Editor Fremont
Older.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Can't Win,'' an underground classic and William Burroughs'
favorite book, has been reprinted by San Francisco's AK Press as
the first of a series of resurrected books by great American
``misfits and rebels,'' as Ramsey Kanaan of AK Press put it.
</P>
<P>
   The book provides a large bottom slice of early 20th-century San
Francisco life, a complete guide to riding the rails, living in bum
encampments, hanging out in Barbary Coast ``hop joints,'' as well
as a how-to (and why not-to) of house-breaking, jewel theft and
armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides this shock. Seventy years ago, a former
criminal with a long record could crusade for prison reform and
give that anti-death penalty speech before applauding state
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   No more Jack Blacks. This is the age of Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Black called for an end to capital punishment. Davis, the
Democratic governor of California, refuses to even recognize mercy.
Black argued for the value of work over prisons. Davis will have
new prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Black pointed out the benefits of humane probation and parole
policies for young offenders. Davis has appointed right-wing
Republicans to his parole boards.
</P>
<P>
   This week Davis appointed former Assemblyman Tom J. Bondonaro
Jr. to the state parole board. This is a man who once sponsored a
bill to make public the names of AIDS patients, fought gay rights
and was called ``extreme right-wing'' by former President Gerald
Ford, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   This is where we are 70 years after Black spoke against capital
punishment to New York legislators. California's governor, a
so-called ``moderate'' or ``centrist,'' is as hard-shelled
conservative as anyone in the country when it comes to matters of
crime and punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Shoring up political defenses on the right with prison walls and
prisoners' bodies is standard centrist strategy. When Bill Clinton
was governor of Arkansas he left the presidential campaign to go
home and witness the execution of a brain-damaged prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has more reason to be draconian. He lives with the memory
of the disaster brought on his former boss, Jerry Brown, by
appointing the late liberal Rose Bird to the California Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   These are craven times, and we have given up on the hope that
men and women can be rehabilitated, a hope Black once instilled
with the powerful story of his life and times at the bottom of
society.
</P>
<P>
   In ``You Can't Win,'' you meet honorable low lifes like Salt
Chunk Mary, so named because of the pot of salt pork and beans she
kept on the stove of her bordello and fencing operation.
</P>
<P>
   You learn truths like ``The best way to get misinformed is to
ask a lot of questions,'' and you get handy bits of firearm advice
like not to use ``off calibers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to shoot anybody,'' said one of Black's criminal
acquaintances, ``but if I do they won't dig a forty-one caliber
slug out of him and find a forty-one caliber slug on me.''
</P>
<P>
   You learn argot like ``stir steerer'' (shyster lawyer), ``box
man'' (safe cracker), ``four-bit mickey of Dr. Hall'' (50-cent
bottle of alcohol), ``gump'' (chicken), ``bindle'' (bedroll) and
``the poultice route'' (the rails through the land of milk and
honey of southern Utah).
</P>
<P>
   Black was a born storyteller and a criminal by training and
habit. The story ends with him turned around by the faith of
Fremont Older, and the mercy of a San Francisco judge named Frank
H. Dunne.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy, remember that?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a boy in prison at the age I was, as prisons were
then, he will become a criminal as sure as the day follows the
night or the night follows the day,'' Black told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   As prisons were then, so they are again. And boys are put in
them.
</P>
<P>
   The book ends with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no money, no wife, no auto. I have no dog. I have
neither a radio set nor a rubber plant _ I have no troubles. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could wish for anything else it would be a little more
moderation, a little more tolerance, and a little more of the
trustful innocence of that little boy who learned his prayers at
the knee of the gentle, kindly old priest in the Sisters' Convent
School.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderation, tolerance, trustful innocence? Don't wish for it
now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
