<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UPSTATE EMERGES AS BATTLEGROUND FOR CLINTON, GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Voters in upstate New York may be the deciding
factor in the ever-tightening U.S. Senate race between Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani, according to a new poll.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen percent of upstate voters surveyed by the Marist
Institute for Public Opinion remain undecided between the
Democratic first lady and the Republican mayor of New York.
Giuliani leads in the GOP-dominated region, 49 to 37 percent, but
undecided voters upstate could swing the race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the clear favorite in New York City at 60 to 34
percent, but the mayor is strong in the suburbs, 56 to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate hasn't seen this kind of battleground since the
Revolutionary War,'' Marist polling director Lee M. Miringoff said
Wednesday. ``If you're Rudy, you want to do well in the
traditionally Republican stronghold upstate. If you're Hillary, you
want to do well in an area where people don't know Rudy as well _
upstate. And most of the undecided voters are upstate _ in the city
and in the suburbs, it's harder to find switchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Giuliani's lead over Clinton narrowed in the Marist
poll, which last had the race tied in October. The poll gave the
mayor 46 percent of the vote to the first lady's 43 percent, with
11 percent undecided statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 561 registered New York voters was conducted Monday
and Tuesday, and has a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's downswing reflects voter dissatisfaction with his
response to the fatal shooting earlier this month of Patrick
Dorismond, a 26-year-old unarmed black man killed following a
scuffle with an undercover New York City police officer. In defense
of the police, Giuliani released Dorismond's juvenile arrest
records, which under law are sealed. The mayor also has refused to
offer condolences to Dorismond's family.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those surveyed by Marist disapproved of Giuliani's
handling of the incident. Still, 26 percent approved of his
actions, and 24 percent were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's and Giuliani's unfavorable ratings are growing, the
first lady's more so than the mayor's _ a fact his campaign seized
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to divide New Yorkers and play Arkansas-style politics
has hurt Mrs. Clinton with New Yorkers who view her more negatively
today than last month, while Mayor Giuliani continues to enjoy
strong support,'' Giuliani campaign spokesman Bruce Teitelbaum
said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, meanwhile, were quick to point out
Giuliani's national fund-raising in Ohio and Washington this week
and in Utah and Arizona Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rudy Giuliani hypocrisy tour rolls on,'' said Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee spokesman David DiMartino. ``Rudy
says he is too busy for upstate but not too busy to go out of
state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0117 </DOCNO>
