A2261 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-THESKULLS-TEX     03-30 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THESKULLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW WATTAGE SPOILS `THE SKULLS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually everything in ``The Skulls'' is bathed in natural
light, coming from behind the characters and creating a haze so
thick that it's a wonder the cast doesn't lapse into coughing fits.
The few electric-light sources in the movie don't provide much
illumination. Thus, the movie provides an apt metaphor for itself:
It's a dim bulb.
</P>
<P>
   This be-careful-what-you-ask-for drama had promise, but writer
John Pogue and director Rob Cohen turn it into a glorified Hardy
Boys drama with a little of ``The X-Files'' thrown in. Our intrepid
hero is Luke (Joshua Jackson of ``Dawson's Creek''), a townie
attending an Ivy League school with _ gasp! _ financial aid. Luke
has left behind what the screenplay continually refers to as his
``misspent youth'' to become a pre-law student and a top-notch
sculler. This is apparently enough to merit him consideration for
membership in the Skulls, a secret campus society.
</P>
<P>
   Luke's potential Skullership is frowned upon by his two best
campus buds, comely artist/love interest Chloe (''Popular's''
Leslie Bibb) and intrepid student reporter Will (Hill Harper of
CBS' ``City of Angels''). But loyalty to old friends apparently
isn't a criterion for Skulls membership, and in scenes that feature
the only things remotely resembling eeriness in the whole movie,
he's initiated into the group.
</P>
<P>
   The Skulls do expect loyalty to ``new'' friends, and Luke is
given a rule book and a ``soul mate'' in Caleb (''Varsity Blues'''
Paul Walker), which gives the movie a vague homoerotic subtext that
it never satisfactorily explores. Instead, it explores Caleb's
becoming a pawn in a power struggle between his father, an
ambitious judge (played with almost laughable oiliness by Craig T.
Nelson) and a grinning senator (William Petersen). Peterson's
performance is crammed with so many Clintonian mannerisms that it's
a mystery why the filmmakers just didn't use ``Saturday Night
Live's'' Darrell Hammond in the role.
</P>
<P>
   When the society's secrecy results in a death, Luke begins to
consider canceling his lifetime membership. Meanwhile, journalist
buddy Will investigates. Hard to see what he's investigating; the
death aside, the secret society's biggest sin appears to be that
it's secret. It does provide its young members with money, cars and
connections, but aside from supplying the phony menace of meetings
conducted in a subterranean war room (conveniently marked ``WAR''),
even the script can't figure out what The Skulls are all about.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Walker do decent enough jobs with this material, but
they're cast adrift by Cohen, who fails to provide any suspense. As
Luke edges closer to the truth, more people try to stop him, but
Cohen never gives the sense that the walls are closing in on him.
</P>
<P>
   With its forced melodrama and unintentional humor, ``The
Skulls'' could have been a guilty pleasure. But Cohen drags it on
about 20 minutes too long, getting more ridiculous, until the movie
finally burns itself out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Skulls''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rob Cohen
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Joshua Jackson, Paul Walker
</P>
<P>
   Length: 107 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ PG-13 for violence and brief sexuality
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
