<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ALMODOVAR-TEX     03-30 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ALMODOVAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK YOU, `GRACIAS' AND BYE-BYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Subtitles still scare some people, who might consider the
awarding of the Best Foreign Language Film a good time to raid the
refrigerator during the Oscars. They don't know what they're
missing, for two reasons. One is that as a rule, only the best
foreign films make it to these shores. And two is that, for the
past couple of years, the award has resulted in one of the most
effusive and entertaining acceptance speeches of the long Academy
Awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Roberto Benigni. This year, it was world-class
filmmaker Pedro Almodovar, winning his first Oscar for ``All About
My Mother,'' his elegiac tribute to motherhood and feminine spirit.
Here, to the best that we and the folks at Oscar.com could make
out, is his speech:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think they are one of the more beautiful couples?''
Almodovar began, referring to presenters Antonio Banderas and
Penelope Cruz. ``At least Spanish couple. You know, I come from out
in the country, it is very different than this. In that country,
now is six years in the morning. So let me dedicate this to the
Spanish people that are watching TV now, and they sacrificed their
Monday to look at you and me with this. I mean, this is for
Spain.'' (Prolonged applause.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very quick. So if you have to applaud, you'll
have to be very quick. I also want to thank my sister Maricruz
(spelling approximate) and Antonia for the amount of confidence
they've had in the last month.''
</P>
<P>
   Try as we might, we weren't able to get the exact wording of the
next segment, when Almodovar thanks Jesus and several saints,
including the Virgin of Guadalupe and St. Jude (the patron saint of
lost causes).
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the Sacred Heart of Mary,'' he continues. ``I told
that we are from a different country. Harvey Weinstein, listen,
Harvey one idea, consider my sister's Oscar. Recited by a paragraph
of my mother with Penelope and me. Next, it brings good luck. So I
think now I'm going to be leaving all this. Well, excuse me.
Thanks. Thanks to Sony because they believed a lot in our movie.
I'm very quick anyway. And, of course _ to my brother! And to all
the Spanish people. Bye-bye! I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A Pedro Almodovar primer
</P>
<P>
   If you're not familiar with Pedro Almodovar's work, here's a
crash course: It's filled with high emotion and splashy color,
often with ribald humor and strong but neurotic female characters.
Here's some of his best stuff, all available on video (and all
decidedly for adults). All are in Spanish with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown'': The must-see
Almodovar film, a 1988 movie that heaps crazy ideas (and gazpacho)
on the story of a film-dubbing actress who has just been dumped by
her longtime lover. Worth it alone for a scene involving an
unfortunate telephone-answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live Flesh'': This 1997 movie involves a paralyzed cop, a
prostitute's son, and the prostitute herself in a typically
Almodovarian cycle of coincidences, melodrama and dark humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matador'': Weirder than most of Almodovar's work (and that's
saying something), this 1986 film examines the sexual peccadilloes
of a troubled matador and his protege, played by Antonio Banderas
before he achieved fame in America. A bit disturbing, but better
than later overrated Almodovar films such as ``Tie Me Up! Tie Me
Down!''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
