<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-KOSOVO-POW-HNS &LR;      03-30 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A YEAR AFTER CAPTURE BY SERBS, EX-POW KEEPS HIS PEACE IN
TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Army Spc. Steven M. Gonzales fell from the
exposed turret of his Humvee into its protective cocoon, suddenly
realizing it was being hit by bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this is happening,'' Gonzales kept repeating
to himself. ``I can't believe this is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Friday, Gonzales and Staff Sgts. Christopher J. Stone
and Andrew A. Ramirez became the first and only American POWs of
the 78-day Kosovo air war.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not call them prisoners of war at first,
preferring the word ``detainees.'' But in a land where yellow
ribbons long have dotted trees and car antennas in remembrance of
POWs and hostages, they became instant heroes, soldier-celebrities,
the object of letters, e-mails and prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Beaten frequently by a sadistic guard, confined to a prison cell
and forced to mark the days off a crude calendar, Gonzales missed
his 22nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But this year he will celebrate in style with friends at Texas
A&AMP;M University, where he is a sophomore engineering major.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment, though, has just begun for Gonzales and the
other former POWs of the American campaign to drive Serbian army
and police forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales is engaged to Anne-Eva Schramm, 20, of Schweinfurt,
Germany, where he, Ramirez and Stone once served as scouts with the
1st Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, 25, of Los Angeles remains in the Army helping
recruiters in Southern California. Stone, 26, is on active duty as
a community relations specialist with the Michigan National Guard
in Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Their new lives began in the wake of a national celebration that
followed Slobodan Milosevic's abrupt decision in early May to
release the men from a Belgrade prison 32 days after their capture
along the border between the Yugslov province of Kosovo and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   After their release, the three received six medals before 3,500
people at the 1st Infantry Division's Victory Park in Wurzburg,
Germany, and met with President Clinton. During their first week of
freedom, the men were hounded by a frenzied media, which camped on
a grassy knoll overlooking their quarters at an Army hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shocking and overwhelming, but it was also funny,''
Stone said. ``I found it humorous that the press went to such great
lengths to get the story, sending letters to the hospital, and some
of them even sent their picture in these letters so we would
recognize their face.''
</P>
<P>
   Their return home was marked by parades, a Disney tribute and,
in Austin, a salute to Gonzales from Gov. George W. Bush and the
Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Stone and Gonzales returned to their unit in
Germany while Ramirez was reassigned to Los Angeles. Transformed by
their POW experience, Stone and Gonzales left the Army on Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gonzales returned to A&AMP;M, where he is studying and
working part time in the university's veterans services office. A
wedding may come before his graduation, now tentatively set for
2003.
</P>
<P>
   But a year ago, Gonzales and the two other Gis were outside a
Macedonian village when they heard the sound of rocks hitting the
Humvee.
</P>
<P>
   Rock-throwing had become a common occurrence since the Americans
joined a peacekeeping mission in Macedonia, a former republic of
Yugoslavia, but Gonzales knew something was different this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of yelled down to them, I said, `Those aren't rocks!
Let's get out of here!'''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion ensued. They thought Macedonian troops patrolling the
border might have mistaken the Americans for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The military vehicle sped up, then Ramirez took a turn to evade
the gunfire. As the wild ride ensued, the men saw soldiers with
AK-47s and red, double-eagle patches _ the emblem of the
Yugoslavian army.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez took another turn, and then yet another, bullets pinging
off the Humvee's shell. It was when they went down a trail that the
truck's engine began to smoke. Then it quit. And it wouldn't
restart.
</P>
<P>
   Riding shotgun, Stone radioed their position. Gonzales, in the
back of the Humvee, reached for his loaded M-16. But options were
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an unspoken agreement. It was over,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the United States and its European allies were
trying to end the campaign by Milosevic to drive ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo. Serbia, which dominates what remains of Yugoslavia,
snubbed peace entreaties by the U.S. and Europe, then endured more
than two months of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The United States resisted a military invasion, opting for
bombing raids. But the three Gis in the Humvee unwittingly became
tangled in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 Serbs fell upon the men as they exited the ruined
jeep. Gonzales expected to be killed. Instead, he was kicked in his
midsection and struck in the head by wooden rifle butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I was thinking. I was praying in my mind. I
was definitely thinking I would be shot,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the middle between Steve and Chris, and so I figured
I'm going to see one of them get it in the head before I do,''
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation began to improve when the Serbian troops used
a pair of twigs and cloth to craft a crude split for Gonzales'
injured right leg.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, each soldier was jailed in a 5-by-12-foot concrete
cell with crumbling white paint. Gonzales would break pieces of the
chalky paint and use them to write math problems on a wool blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Stone scraped the paint off to pass the time and lip-synched
rock songs, while Ramirez whispered rap tunes. Pacing back and
forth, Gonzales sang aloud Christian ``praise'' songs learned in
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers said they often were beaten at night.
</P>
<P>
   Freed on May 1, a day after meeting the Rev. Jesse Jackson in
Belgrade, Gonzales found the media's interest on the wane once back
in Texas. But he then began to have a recurring nightmare about an
escalating conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the dream, Gonzales would hear bullets and bombs blasting
buildings. Somehow he would escape his cell and walk through rubble
to a Bradley armored personnel carrier, where he identified himself
as an American. Then he awoke.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the nightmares are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in a sense that things don't happen randomly but at
the same time I'd still say I'm lucky, very lucky, for all the
things I didn't lose and things I came close to losing,'' Gonzales
said. ``I'm just very lucky that I didn't lose anything, that I can
still enjoy those things, that I am still living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
