<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FEMINIST-PARLEY-HNS &LR;      03-30 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-PARLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEMINISTS TO MEET IN BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest U.S. gathering of women in 23 years will bring the
warriors of the old millennium _ Smeal, Steinem, Friedan _ together
with the up-and-comers of the new one who strive to kick-start the
feminist movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rallying cry for women,'' said Alicia Daly of Girls
Inc. in Alameda, Calif., who will be among those attending the
Feminist Expo 2000 this weekend in Baltimore. ``It affords us the
opportunity to come together as one and learn from each other and
to be able to leave with some ideas of concrete things we can do to
move the feminist movement forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference is being sponsored primarily by the Los
Angeles-based Feminist Majority Foundation, at a cost of $1.2
million, with 575 other groups lending support.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 women have signed up, one-third of them college
students, according to Ellie Smeal, Feminist Majority leader and a
war horse of the movement since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it the biggest feminist gathering on U.S. soil since
the International Women's Year convention in 1977, which drew about
20,000 to Washington, D.C., Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to showcase the movement, for us to get a
status report on it ourselves, to inspire it, to ignite it more, to
really have a sharing of ideas,'' Smeal said. ``We are fervent
believers that what has made social change, especially for women,
isn't money. It's ideas and people.''
</P>
<P>
   Women from more than 65 countries are expected to attend the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues to be discussed is the failure of the United
States, lone among industrialized countries, to sign the Convention
to End All Forms of Discrimination Against Women. Born of an
international women's conference in Mexico in 1976, it was approved
by the United Nations three years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Friday-through-Sunday conference will reunite Smeal, Ms.
magazine founder Gloria Steinem, authors Betty Friedan and Bell
Hooks and others who are among the most active and visible
feminists of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Smeal says the feminist movement, far from fading out as some
have said, is bigger and stronger than ever. And the Internet has
strengthened its global reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so big and so active that no one can see it all. It's
become a part of the mainstream,'' Smeal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
