</P>
<P>
   EDUC-COMPARE (Undated) _ Gov. Bush likes to say that if elected
president, he has no intention of serving as the nation's education
superintendent, having the apparatchiks of the federal government
play the role of school board members. And Al Gore suggests that it
is teachers, and not bureaucrats and politicians, who would be
empowered and gain respect in his administration. But whether Bush
or Gore is elevated to the White House in November, the federal
government would parachute behind the closed doors of American
classrooms in ways that exceed the efforts of previous presidents.
By Jaques Steinberg. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-AUTOS (Washington) _ Vice President Gore promotes fuel
efficient cars. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Campaign news and notes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD-HAM (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ Smithfield Foods, operates hog
farms and slaughterhouses throughout the country, supplying pork to
the nation's biggest supermarkets and fast food outlets like
McDonald's. By aggressively acquiring its bigger rivals over the
last two years and turning itself into a vertically integrated
company that uses precision genetics, huge corporate hog farms and
giant meatpacking plants to control every aspect of production,
Smithfield Foods has ballooned into a $5 billion company that now
accounts for nearly a quarter of the nation's pork supply. But in
doing so, the company has come under intense scrutiny from state
and federal regulators who say that big agricultural companies may
wield too much control over the nation's food supply, and too much
pricing power in the meatpacking industry. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Analyzing the technical
issues behind the proposals Microsoft has put on the table in the
talks over the antitrust case. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PRIVATIZE (Hong Kong) _ On the problems in taking China's
state-owned enterprises public. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in mid-afternoon. At 2:10
p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 78 points, the S&AMP;P
500 down 6 points and the Nasdaq composite index down 142 points.
Treasury prices were higher. Crude oil was slightly higher at
$26.68. European stock markets closed lower: London was down 2.16
percent and Frankfurt ended down 2.80 percent. The Nikkei ended
down 1.28 percent and the Hang Seng fell 3.48 percent. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DIET-DRUG-SUIT (Undated) _ Thursday is the last day for people
to opt out of American Home Products' fen-phen settlement. Looking
at the legal cloud hanging over the company and what it means for
its prospects in any merger talks. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BREWERY (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil's antitrust regulatory
agency approves the $7 billion takeover by Cia. Cervejaria Brahma
of its main beer and soft drink rival Cia. Antarctica Paulista,
creating the world's No. 3 brewer. The approval of the combined
company, to be called Ambev, is a defeat for Coca-Cola and its
Brazilian bottler, which had sought to derail the merger as a
threat to competition. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPS-CZECH (Prague) _ Royal Philips Electronics, the Dutch
consumer electronics giant, will build one of the world's largest
television tube factories in the Czech Republic, reflecting growing
demand in Eastern Europe. The project, which could cost more than
$500 million, is the biggest single foreign investment in the Czech
Republic and will employ more than 3,000 people in one of its most
economically depressed regions. By Ladka Bauerrova.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI-LIBERTY (New York) _ CMGI Inc., an Internet venture-fund
company, and Liberty Media Group will buy 5 percent stakes in the
magazine publisher Primedia and will develop Internet-based joint
ventures. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins' ``Public Interests'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
