<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2326 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HIGHFIDELITY-TEX     03-30 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HIGHFIDELITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FOR A RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As John Cusack stares into the camera at the beginning of ``High
Fidelity,'' the usually wired actor looks momentarily haggard, his
boyish face slightly puffy as if it were tired of resisting growing
up. Of course, it could just be the way the stereo headphones he's
wearing are squeezing his face and disheveling his hair.
</P>
<P>
   They're practically part of a uniform for Cusack's character,
Rob, who runs a vinyl-only Chicago used-record store, an atmosphere
that director Stephen Frears and his crew have captured so
precisely that you can almost smell the dust on the old albums. Rob
is a collector, but not just of records _ he's a collector of women
as well. Or rather, he's a collector of breakups: He makes top five
lists of everything in his life, and his latest and most patient
flame, Laura (Danish actress Iben Hjejle), has just earned a place
on the Top Five Breakups list.
</P>
<P>
   This sets Rob off on a soul-searching tour of past breakups, and
that makes up the rather loose but amiably funny plot of ``High
Fidelity.'' Cusack's Rob tells us about his life, past and present,
the latter of which includes his two addled co-workers Dick (Todd
Louiso), who's so reserved and nervous that he always looks like
he's afraid someone's about to hit him, and Barry (Jack Black), an
aspiring musician who is prone to harsh criticism of customers'
pedestrian musical tastes. The present also includes Laura, who has
hooked up with the pretentious guy who used to live above Rob, and
her buddy Liz (Joan Cusack), who's torn by loyalty to Laura and
sympathy for Rob.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the movie, Cusack addresses the audience directly,
and his likability and energy keep this from becoming an annoying
device. The movie has an episodic structure, but it retains its
appeal because so many of us know (or have been) a guy like Rob,
who learned all his life lessons from rock music and discovers that
they don't necessarily apply outside the realm of three-minute
records. Iben _ who's also in the Danish film ``Mifune,'' opening
this week in Dallas _ makes an immediate impression as the only
person with the intelligence or patience (to a point) to figure Rob
out.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie goes on a little too long, heaping one ending
on top of another, it wraps up well and includes several amusing
cameos. It also, as is appropriate for a movie featuring three
rock-music snobs, has one of the best soundtracks to come along in
some time.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``High Fidelity''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Stephen Frears
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: John Cusack, Iben Hjejle
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
