A2333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     03-30 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVER WONDER ABOUT THAT JEEP IN THE POPEYE STRIP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: In the '40s I was a fan of the Popeye comic strip, and my
favorite character was a doglike creature called a ``Jeep.'' What
information is available on it and where can I track one down?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.L.D., Little Ferry, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Eugene the Jeep, an orchid-eating, truth-telling,
problem-solving creature who arrived at Popeye's house in a box,
was introduced in E.C. Segar's Thimble Theater comic strip in March
1936.
</P>
<P>
   The character was a combination of a fourth-dimensional creature
and an ``African Hooey Hound,'' according to a history compiled by
Northeast Dubois (Ind.) High School, whose mascot is the Fighting
Jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Stuff in Parker, Colo., sells a large variety of licensed
merchandise devoted to the character _ T-shirts, jackets, coffee
cups, tire covers and other items. The company is run by an
enthusiast of jeep automobiles, and some of the items feature the
Jeep driving a jeep.
</P>
<P>
   You can order items over the Web at www.eugenestuff.com. For
mail-order price and item information, write to Eugene Stuff, 5695
N. Thunderhill Road, Parker, CO 80134, or call (303) 805-8275 from
noon to 6 p.m. central time
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I buy bluebonnet seeds by the pound? I need to
plant a whole lot of seeds in a vacant lot.
</P>
<P>
   _ S.C., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Wild Seed Farms, which describes itself as the ``largest
working wildflower seed farm in the United States,'' sells
bluebonnet seeds for $13.50 per pound.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 848-0078; write to Wild Seed Farms, Box
3000, 425 Wildflower Hills, Fredericksburg, TX 78624-3000; or visit
the Web site www.wildseedfarms.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Seed Farms also sells for $83.50 per pound.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I send a fan letter to the author Ray Bradbury?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.M., Decatur, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: You can write to Bradbury in care of Author Mail, 7th Floor,
HarperCollins Publishers, 10 E. 53rd St., New York, NY 10022.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury, 79, had a stroke in November while traveling from Los
Angeles to his part-time home in Palm Springs. He lost some use of
his right side, but a full recovery was expected, according to
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   His upcoming novel ``From the Dust Returned,'' which was
originally scheduled for December 1999 release, takes its name from
a 1994 short story he wrote for Magazine of Fantasy &AMP; Science
Fiction.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
