<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      03-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEARST SAYS FOUR GOVERNMENT AGENCIES HAVE NOT OBJECTED TO
EXAMINER SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hearst Corp. has told a federal court that
four government agencies have not objected to its imminent plan to
sell the San Francisco Examiner and buy the San Francisco
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these agencies have indicated they have any intention
of challenging the closing of the transaction,'' lawyer Gary
Halling said Wednesday in a court declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst filed the papers to oppose former mayoral candidate Clint
Reilly's request for an emergency order temporarily blocking the
Chronicle purchase.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker is considering Reilly's
request.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle has been under review for
months by the U.S. Department of Justice, the state attorney
general's office and the San Francisco district attorney's and city
attorney's offices. The agencies have been told of Hearst's plans
to sell the Examiner to the Fang family, Halling said.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney Louise Renne said Wednesday her office had
finished its investigation of the deals and was satisfied Hearst
had made a ``good faith effort'' to ensure that San Francisco
remains a two-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale appears to meet the objectives we expressed to the
Hearst Corporation,'' Renne said. ``The new owners are newspaper
people with longstanding ties to San Francisco. Under the terms of
the agreement as they have been expressed to me, it appears the
buyers have a viable opportunity to continue the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the state attorney general's office
have told Renne they have no objections either, said Renne's
spokesman Marc Slavin.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for the Justice Department, District Attorney
Terence Hallinan, and the state attorney general's office declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly wants Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle blocked until
Walker holds a full hearing on his antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   The former political consultant claims Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle would result in Hearst's owning the only metropolitan
daily paper in San Francisco, creating an illegal monopoly that
would reduce the range of editorial voices and increase advertising
and subscription prices.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly filed suit as a newspaper subscriber and advertiser but
has since claimed in court papers that he is acting as a ``private
attorney general'' to protect the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Chronicle Publishing Co. have denied Reilly's claims.
Their court papers say Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle and its
plan to sell the Examiner to the Fangs with a $66 million subsidy
over three years to publish the Examiner as a morning paper would
restore economic competition between San Francisco newspapers for
the first time in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has argued that it would cost far more for the Fangs to
publish the Examiner as a viable competitor to Hearst's Chronicle _
as much as $250 million over five years. He has called the Fang
deal a ``sham'' designed to destroy The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But Halling's brief for Hearst said, ``In fact, the transaction
is structured to provide incentives to continue the Examiner's
business. Hearst is only reimbursing actual expenses incurred in
publishing the Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs' profits increase with revenue from the Examiner, and
the paper's ultimate success depends on market forces, Halling
said.
</P>
<P>
   F. Warren Hellman, chairman of the San Francisco investment firm
Hellman &AMP; Friedman, said he and his colleague, Joseph Niehaus, had
personally advised the Fangs on their bid for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that they have every intention of owning and
operating the paper for the long term, and that they have a
financially sound, achievable plan with reasonable prospects for
doing so,'' said Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst agreed to buy the Chronicle, which has a daily
circulation of 464,535 and is Northern California's largest paper,
for $660 million in cash. The Examiner's daily circulation is
108,968.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the afternoon Examiner and the morning Chronicle
have published under a joint operating agreement, an exemption from
antitrust laws allowing them to combine business operations while
keeping independent news staffs.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a temporary restraining order, plaintiffs typically
must show either that they have a good chance of winning their suit
and that without the order they may suffer irreparable harm.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding whether to issue a temporary restraining order,
courts balance those factors along with whether the requested order
will serve the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's attorney, contends his client need
not meet those standards because he is merely asking the court to
maintain the status quo pending a full hearing already set for
April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst counters that Reilly would suffer ``at most trivial''
harm if the sales go through as planned, and says his suit lacks
merit.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst contends it would suffer irreparable injury because a
temporary order ``would delay Hearst's efforts to expand the
Chronicle into a world-class newspaper and to begin speaking as
soon as possible with the editorial voice of the larger morning
Chronicle. Mr. Reilly has no right to delay Hearst's First
Amendment rights for even a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle claims it would lose as much as $102,000 each day
the deal is delayed and another $160 million that Hearst agreed to
pay above the next-highest bidder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
