<P>
   JAPANESE-ART-COLLECTOR (New York) _ Since 1954, Mary Griggs
Burke and her husband, Jackson Burke, built the greatest private
collection of Japanese art outside Japan, now exhibited at the
Metropolitan Museum. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-CHICAGO (Chicago) _ When friends from abroad come to the
United States, I always send them to Chicago, or try to. It is the
quintessential American city: muscular, inventive, wonderfully
diverse, worldly-wise (if a bit oafish at times) and as
unpretentious as its prairie-flat vowels. ``Chicago is American in
every chitling and sparerib,'' H.L. Mencken wrote wickedly during
the era when the city's stockyards, since demolished, were the
biggest anywhere. ``It is alive from snout to tail.'' Reviled in
the days of Al Capone and John Dillinger as a haven for hoodlums,
Chicago was maligned for years for its cheerful civic corruption
and dismissed in the effete East as a hick town. Nelson Algren, one
of the writers who knew it best, said that ``loving Chicago is like
loving a woman with a broken nose.'' But no more. Chicago enters
the 21st century as a prosperous, well-governed model for the rest
of the country. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (With a ``t'' category code.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5,6.
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-QUIZ-KIDS (New York) _ If you tune in Saturday afternoon
to the Texaco Opera Quiz, the popular intermission feature that is
part of the live radio broadcasts of the Metropolitan Opera, don't
be surprised if the three panelists sound rather young to be
experts. They are the Texaco Quiz Kids, as the producers of the
broadcasts are calling this first-ever panel of high school
students. Their knowledge and suitability have been tested through
a series of regional competitions in the New York, Houston, and
Washington areas. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   NY-JEWISH-MUSEUM (New York) _ The Jewish Museum has not flinched
from efforts to make the story of more than 3,000 years of Jewish
civilization viewer-friendly. And with an eye to enhancing and
streamlining the presentation, the museum has embarked on a
two-stage reinstallation. The first stage, dealing with the ancient
world and the early Diaspora is now open. The second stage, which
continues the story to the present, is to be completed by 2001. By
Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COMEDY-CLUBS (New York) _ Heard the one about the homeless
guy with the cell phone? I have. In fact, I've heard it over and
over and over again. I've also heard the one about how expensive
New York is and, of course, the one about the guy who can't get a
date. In fact, over the course of the last month, I have heard
hundreds of jokes, thousands of near misses and even a couple of
howlers, all perpetrated by the city's crack corp of comedians.
Considering the sheer number of comics and would-be jokesters, it
only stands to reason that New York is the wisecracking-est place
in the United States. There are nearly a dozen full-time comedy
clubs in the city, and scores of bars and restaurants across the
city regularly open their back rooms to those peculiar men and
women whose sole mission in life is to spread the joy of laughter _
and to book a spot on Letterman. By Jesse McKinley
</P>
