<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-30 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR PROVIDES BUSINESS INSIGHT THROUGH PRISM OF LITERATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the world's a stage, the Bard tells us, but perhaps
especially the business world.
</P>
<P>
   So why not turn to fiction for a bit of management advice?
</P>
<P>
   That is the premise behind Robert A. Brawer's ``Fictions of
Business: Insight on Management From Great Literature'' (John Wiley
&AMP; Sons, 248 pages, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   The book, now out in paperback, has received rave reviews as a
deft mix of business and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Brawer himself is an unusual mixture. Before a 20-year stint at
the Maidenform apparel firm, where he became chief executive and
president, Brawer earned a doctorate in English literature and
taught at the University of Wisconsin, specializing in medieval
studies. He returned to academia after his business career and now
teaches a cross-disciplinary course on fiction and business at New
York University.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt his book evolved from that course. Brawer's insight
from both his careers puts him in a unique position to address such
subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you enjoy reading fiction or not, this book definitely
outshines the woefully tedious management tomes flooding the
market.
</P>
<P>
   And as ``USA Today'' writes: ``Reading Brawer's book is like
taking a stimulating crash course in literature and management.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, you'll absorb enough literary snippets to
talk about ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' if you missed the movie, or
about ``Death of a Salesman'' if you missed the Broadway revival.
</P>
<P>
   But Brawer offers much more than a Cliffs Notes version of some
wonderful fiction. He seriously attempts to link business and
fiction _ along with anecdotes from his management career _ to
offer real solutions to real management problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immersion in the world of imaginative writing clearly has
nothing directly to do with maintaining a respectable bottom line,
controlling inventory levels, or drafting a marketing plan,''
Brawer says. ``I would insist, however, that the values and
insights we glean from serious literature sensitize us to ourselves
and, by extension, to the problems inherent in managing people in
an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Office politics, stress management and related issues are among
the topics Brawer addresses.
</P>
<P>
   On selling, he writes: ``If I were asked to identify a single
characteristic that the best business people have in common, I
would say that it is a sense of theater. Like theatrical
impresarios, they have mastered the art of illusion: creating the
perception in the minds of their customers that the product or
service they are selling has a unique value that transcends the
usual `features and benefits,' and does more than satisfy customer
`wants or needs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brawer uses David Mamet's play ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' to
illustrate the quintessential salesman making his pitch, then
offers examples from his career. Brawer suggests that firing up a
sales force should begin with ordering this play in bulk and
holding a seminar on it.
</P>
<P>
   In dealing with employees unable to flourish under a corporate
light, Brawer turns to Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman.''
Rather than seeing an oppressive corporation breaking a defenseless
employee, however, Brawer suggests that Miller meant for
protagonist Willy Loman to lack self-awareness, thus making himself
a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the more self-aware we become as managers,
the more alert we become to how we should handle failed employees
like Willy,'' he writes. By dragging an employee on for years,
despite declining sales performance, and cutting back on his income
until he's working on commissions, the company was treating Loman
worse than if it had fired him years earlier, Brawer contends.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is easy about human relations management, but Brawer
offers ideas and answers from a different angle.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mid-Career Tune-Up: 10 New Habits for Keeping Your Edge in
Today's Fast-Paced Workplace''
</P>
<P>
   By William and Rosemary Salmon
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $17.95
</P>
<P>
   Most of us will spend close to 100,000 hours on the job. William
and Rosemary Salmon offer ways for experienced workers to make
those hours more productive and fulfilling. In an increasingly
job-hopping world, fine-tuning your competence is increasingly
important. The Salmons cover such topics as sharpening
communication skills and developing product relationships with the
right people.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Value-Added Employee: 31 Skills to make Yourself
Irresistible to Any Company''
</P>
<P>
   By Edward J. Cripe and Richard S. Mansfield
</P>
<P>
   Cashman Dudley, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   ``Competency models'' is one of the new buzzword phrases these
days. They are like ``job blueprints'' in which skills, knowledge,
attitudes, motives and other characteristics are rated for
importance to getting and keeping a job. Edward Cripe is a
management consultant with experience in competency systems, and
Richard Mansfield is a competency-based job analyst with a Ph.D. in
education. Analytical thinking, determination and influencing
others are three of the skills described in their workbook.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Outfitting Your Home Business for Much Less''
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Zooi with Paul and Sarah Edwards
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $18.95
</P>
<P>
   The authors focus on the three things nearly every home business
needs: office and computer equipment, furniture and business
services. They help you to assess what you need out of the three
categories and steer you away from a common problem among small
businesses: overbuying. Walter Zooi is director of communications
and marketing at the University of Southern California's Thornton
School of Music, in addition to running his a communications and
marketing business from home. Their book is helpful whether you are
looking for a printer or negotiating phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
