<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIF. ECONOMY WILL BE GOOD THIS YEAR BUT MAY SLOW LATER,
REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's robust economy will continue to
grow apace in 2000, but tightening credit concerns and a crippling
housing crunch will help cool off the Golden State in coming years,
according to the latest quarterly predictions by UCLA's Anderson
School of Management.
</P>
<P>
   The state's economy, which is diversified both by region and
industry, will grow by 3.5 percent in terms of nonfarm payroll jobs
in 2000, says the report, which was released Wednesday. That will
continue the strong pace set in 1999 when the same kinds of jobs
increased by about 3 percent over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the pace of growth is expected to slow in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Lieser, the author of the report, ``California:
Continuing to Outpace the Nation,'' higher interest rates, rising
oil prices and an ever-increasing housing crunch will combine to
impede the state's white-hot economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Also looming large, according to Lieser, is the high-flying
stock market, which has fueled an unprecedented growth in personal
wealth throughout the state in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``A potential wild card would be a loss of investor confidence
in the highly valued stock market, particularly in the high-tech
issues, which are strongly represented in California's economy,''
wrote Lieser, executive director of the University of California at
Los Angeles' Anderson Forecast. ``However, the main impediments to
even stronger growth beyond 2000 may be in high home prices and in
increasingly widespread shortages of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the labor crunch more acute than in the San Francisco
Bay area. According to Lieser's report, the area's economy is fully
employed by any measure, with jobless rates ranging from 1.9
percent in San Francisco to 2.2 percent in San Jose and 2.7 percent
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting new workers to the area is difficult because of the
raging real estate market, which has priced most middle-class
workers out of home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, new residential building permits averaged just more
than 140,000 in 1999, the best since 1990. While that may sound
good, Lieser said, the numbers still fall short of what's needed to
accommodate the employment growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the obstacles to increasing housing supply in
California are more political than market-based, and the political
barriers are mainly at the local level,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``With limited new housing supply coming to market, home prices
have continued upward this year. For Los Angeles County, average
prices increased more than 6 percent, and the San Francisco Bay
area was in double digits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
