<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-FIDELITY-SPI &LR;      03-30 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FIDELITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSACK A WINNER IN `HIGH FIDELITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hero of the melancholy, funny and ultimately very winning
relationship comedy, ``High Fidelity,'' is Rob Gordon (John
Cusack), a twentysomething Chicago used-record store owner whose
live-in girlfriend Laura (Iben Hjejle) has just left him for
another man.
</P>
<P>
   The abandonment has created an emotional crisis and deluge of
soul searching in the harrowingly immature Rob that has him _ for
most of the rest of the movie _ facing the camera and leading the
audience on a guided tour of the numerous failed relationships of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   These include his junior-high first-crush (Shannon Stillo), his
high school sweetheart (Joelle Carter), a knockout he knew from the
beginning was way out of his league (Catherine-Zeta Jones, in a
cameo), and a fellow perpetual loser at love (Lili Taylor).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rob is also having an affair with a sultry recording
artist (Lisa Bonet), desperately trying to get Laura back from her
new guy (Tim Robbins, in a cameo), and endlessly kibitzing with the
two music-junkie clerks in his moribund store (Todd Louiso and Jack
Black).
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is not everyone's movie. It's aimed squarely at a
young dating audience, and is not likely to hugely captivate anyone
out of that demographic. And if you're not a big fan of Cusack, you
should run in the other direction _ because he's on camera for
virtually the entire movie.
</P>
<P>
   For its full appreciation, ``High Fidelity'' also requires a
considerable knowledge of pop music trivia, because so much of the
humor plays off references to obscure musical groups. (Would, for
instance, anyone who had never heard of the '70s band,
Bachman-Turner Overdrive, get a character's punning reference to
``Kathleen Turner-Overdrive''?).
</P>
<P>
   But English director Stephen Frears keeps the situations and
one-liners fast-paced, he balances Cusack with a likably goofy
ensemble of supporting players, and he gives the film the original
eye and succession of uniquely revealing moments that characterizes
his best work _ films like ``The Grifters,'' ``My Beautiful
Laundrette'' and ``Dangerous Liaisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack (who shares a screenplay credit) is also quite effective.
His delivery is crisp and deadly, and _ on top of his work ``Being
John Malkovich'' _ he seems to be establishing a new persona for
himself as a sexually frustrated, angst-ridden, ludicrously
self-centered everyman: maybe even his generation's version of
Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   High Fidelity. Directed by Stephen Frears. Written by D.V.
DeVincentis, Steve Pink, John Cusack and Scott Rosenberg, from the
novel by Nick Hornby. Cast: John Cusack, Iben Hjejle, Jack Black,
Joan Cusack, Catherine Zeta-Jones. Touchstone. 114 minutes. Rated R
for sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
