<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-PRODUCTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT SEEKS TO PROTECT ITS GOOD NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woe to the makers of salsa and chutney _ the ingredients of
which are harvested in California and bottled in New Jersey _ who
want to invoke the rural purity of the Green Mountain State. By
defining which foods deserve to use the state's name on their
labels, its attorney general is sending a message: If a product
bears the name ``Vermont,'' it had better be made in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   While the Federal Trade Commission regularly investigates
products labeled ``Made in USA,'' states rarely venture into the
same territory. But then, Vermont _ whose name has been estimated
to boost sales by between 5 and 10 percent _ is more than a state.
It's also a brand, and a good one. So, responding to complaints
from in-state food producers that ``people were trying to take
advantage of the Vermont name,'' the attorney general's office has
taken on labeling as a consumer protection issue, said Assistant
Attorney General Michael Duane.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's rules on food labeling, which probably
won't be finalized for months, will be used to flesh out the
state's consumer protection statute. In their final form, they
could require product labels to declare how much of their content
came from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are Heinz Food Corporation, the issue is not where
Heinz ketchup is made. You don't care. But when you get to a
Vermont company, you change context. Now the Vermont identity comes
into play,'' said Murray Burk, president of the Vermont Specialty
Foods Association. ``You've got to be someone without a heart or
soul to want to exploit something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's attorney general has already prosecuted two companies
for too-liberal use of the state's name _ first in 1989, when the
Stowe-based Mad River Traders were required to relinquish the name
``Vermont All-Natural Soda'' and state on their labels that the
product was bottled out of state. A maple syrup company was
prosecuted the next year for falsely claiming Vermont origin. And
as other states begin to capitalize on their state images,
Vermonters' sensitivity has never gone away.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion draft now being circulated for feedback from
specialty foods producers has some worried that the language could
be too purist for good business. Vermont's 300 specialty food
producers bring in $700 million in annual sales _ slightly more
than the ski industry, said Burk, who sells soup and pancake mix
from Post Mill, Vt. He says he's concerned that the rules will be
``micromanaging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my members would say that where the ingredients come
from is incidental to the identity of the food,'' Burk said. ``I
buy my flour from the King Arthur Flour Company, which is based in
Vermont, but do people really think that the wheat in the flour
comes from Vermont?''
</P>
<P>
   His fears are shared by Joanne and John Esau, owners of the
four-year-old Vermont Garlic Co. The Esaus like to think of
themselves as Vermont purists; when a salesman from Springfield,
Mass., called them, doggedly arguing that they could save 2 cents a
bottle by producing some ingredients out of state, the Esaus said
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that social conscience that is so strong, that people
would judge us,'' said Joanne Esau, who, like her husband, has a
day job, as a high school teacher. If she found a product from out
of state parading its Vermontness, she would consider it ``a little
bit deceitful.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Esaus have a confession: The garlic comes from
California, where there are efficient garlic-peeling facilities.
After making calls to reassure worried customers that ``it wasn't
being peeled by immigrants'' _ it was peeled in a wind tunnel _ the
Esaus have built up their business so that this year, for the first
time, they could afford to pay themselves. They worry new labeling
rules could change all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could totally put us out of business,'' said Joanne Esau.
``We are the epitome of startup, and our initial startup cost was
the cost of the label. If we had to take the word Vermont out of
the name of our product, it would really cut into name
recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Esau's anxiety notwithstanding, some of Vermont's
specialty food producers have a devotion to using in-state
ingredients which she refers to jokingly as ``political
correctness.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, David Lyon started his line of pasta and
grill sauce out of his home in South Londonderry, but when sales
had begun to pick up two years later, he contracted processing of
all his 21 Uncle Dave's products to plants in Long Island and
Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But he still gets incensed when entrepreneurs don't make the
effort to buy as many of their ingredients as possible from
Vermonters. That, to him, is a ``moral situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times in the past where people have taken post
office boxes in Vermont just to say they're part of Vermont,'' said
Lyon. ``What they're trying to do is not let the big guys
capitalize in Vermont. I think they're invading Vermont.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1525EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
