<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DORADO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EL DORADO'S' ANIMATION IS GOLDEN, BUT WE'VE BEEN DOWN THIS ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C+   
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When executive producer Jeffrey Katzenberg _ who inaugurated the
great cycle of Disney animated musicals of the '90s _ jumped ship
to become a founding partner at DreamWorks, the assumption was he
would soon make the new studio's animation department the industry
flag-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   But DreamWorks first major foray into the field, 1998's ``The
Prince of Egypt,'' was distinctly underwhelming. Its animation was
breathtaking and truly epic, but its storyline (a remake of the
first half of ``The Ten Commandments'') was disjointed and
uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost the same criticism can be leveled at the studio's
second big animated musical, ``The Road to El Dorado.'' Its
animation is simply glorious, but its story and characters are
trite. The film can't hold a candle to Disney's recent ``Toy Story
2,'' or even ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1519, it's the story of Tulio (voice of Kevin Kline) and
Miguel (Kenneth Branagh), two Spanish con artists, who accidentally
stow away on a conquistador ship and find themselves washed up on
the coast of Mexico with a map to the legendary lost city of gold,
El Dorado.
</P>
<P>
   When they find the city, its natives assume they're gods, and
enthrone them in their own temple surrounded by undreamed of
treasure. The rest of the movie has the rascals straining to
preserve the illusion of their divinity, while trying to figure
some way of getting the gold back to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the stew are a pair of cute animals that join the heroes
in progress, a triangular romance with a young Indian woman (Rosie
Perez), much intrigue and deadly supernatural manifestations
concocted by an evil high priest (Armand Assante) and regular
injections of songs by Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   As this familiar package comes together, the seamless mix of
computer and traditional animation cannot be faulted. The
show-stopping sequences include a tumultuous storm at sea, a trek
through the staggeringly beautiful rainforest, and a dazzling
recreation of a Mesoamerican civilization at its summit.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, the songs are forgettable and bear little
relationship to the action; the characters have no particular charm
(or chemistry with one another); the humor is awkward; and the
whole enterprise has a by-the-numbers feel to it: as it had been
put together by a committee with no guiding sensibility in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, its story is limp. A strange marriage of a
Hope-Crosby ``Road'' picture with ``The Man Who Would Be King,'' it
offers no emotional bite whatsoever. Unlike the best of the
animated musicals of the last dozen years, it doesn't even try to
work as a fable. It's just the story of a pair of 16th century
adolescents, yucking it up in Mayaland.
</P>
<P>
   The Road to El Dorado. Directed by Eric Bergeron and Don Paul.
Voices: Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Rosie Perez, Armand Assante,
Edward James Olmos. Animated. DreamWorks. 83 minutes. Rated PG for
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
