<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERILS OF LIFE IN THE FAST LANE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We lead accelerated, time-driven lives.
</P>
<P>
   In just 100 years, science and technology have transformed the
United States from an agrarian nation into a telecommunications and
high-tech center. New efficiencies abound, allowing us to save
time, improve production, and maximize energy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, James Gleick, author of ``Faster: The Acceleration
of Just About Everything'' (1999, Pantheon Books, New York), poses
a simple yet thought-provoking question: At what cost?
</P>
<P>
   Using humor and examples that range from the unusual to the
mundane, Gleick forces us to look at how the production of
innovative time-savers has had the opposite effect: The more time
we save, the more time we need.
</P>
<P>
   Gleick says we aren't working harder or even longer than our
predecessors, though many in law, high technology, and finance
would disagree. Even among lawyers, it seems, the average number of
billable hours per year is now 1,800. Compare that to the 2,500
average billable hours logged by attorneys at a prominent law firm
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   So, why do we feel so busy, so stressed, so time-pressed, so
harried, so overworked and worn out?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, says the author, it is because everything, from the way
we live to the way we think, is faster. And despite the complaints,
many of us are as addicted to the rush of life in the so-called
fast lane as drug users are to narcotics. Speed is a tonic, and
it's pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Helen Stein agrees with Gleick.
</P>
<P>
   The culture has changed, she says, and we run faster to keep up.
We probably have the same amount of time we've always had, Stein
says, but the way we use it, or spend it, has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, you could actually use the same number of hours in a
day as you did before, but you are now going at breakneck speed,''
she says. ``You may not even move, but something _ the beeper, the
mail, the telephone _ is always bombarding you. And one's work life
tends to intrude more into one's personal life. People are no
longer in the moment, or just quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gleick's book points out that sociologists in several countries
have found that increasing wealth and increasing education bring a
sense of tension about time. As a result, Gleick says, we believe
we have too little of it _ a myth many of us now live by.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is true is that we are awash in things, in information,
in news, in the old rubble and shiny new toys of our complex
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   We spend more time online, on the phone, on the freeway. For
example, market researchers have found that people 45 and over sit
at their computers for more than 70 minutes per day. A decade ago,
we spent 52 minutes a day talking on the telephone, up from 36.5
minutes in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the average time devoted to sex is four minutes and
a few seconds, or a half-hour per week.
</P>
<P>
   Not suprisingly, our accelerated society has its own lingo.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites allow us to converse from afar in ``real'' time. Other
terms include ``fast track, ``meth-paced,'' ``snail mail,'' ``rush
hour,'' ``sound bytes,'' ``cutting-edge,'' and ``quantum leap.''
</P>
<P>
   All have helped transform the American lexicon while reflecting
our new lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   We ``multitask,'' for example. And we would rather be
``quick-witted'' and working at ``lightning speed'' than slow,
methodical, or ponderous _ all terms once associated with sagacity,
thoughtfulness, and wisdom that comes with age.
</P>
<P>
   Gleick, referring to the voluminous amount of information we
ingest and decode daily, notes that our ancestors had little reason
to process tens of thousands of words, spoken or written, ``any
more than they challenged their visual cortex to process cinematic
montage. . . We absorb the stimuli of a fast, complex world; we
require specialized training to handle parts of it (automobiles,
VCRs, Gameboys); and often we enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard of unhurried qualities, but we think,
nonetheless, that the students who plod through laborious
calculations cannot be quite as smart as their comrades who snap
their fingers and know the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even companies have absorbed this mind-set, building their
recruitment efforts and employment policies around mind-speed tests
and games, according to Nicholas Lemann, author of ``The Big
Test.''
</P>
<P>
   At certain high-tech and finance companies, he notes, job
applicants are peppered with SAT-like questions, timed essays,
puzzles, and games, all designed to gauge speed and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster'' is entertaining, but I couldn't agree with Gleick's
pronouncement that Americans are far from overworked. Has he
forgotten the temps with two or three jobs?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Gleick's view of work differs markedly from those of
the work-addicted or work-abused. Even so, the author succeeds in
documenting our love-hate relationship with a frenzied race against
time, a state characterized by simultaneous feelings of freedom and
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   I asked several people about their perception of time. Do they
have more, but feel as if there is less? Since lunch is sometimes a
measure of how busy we are, I asked if it was eaten at a desk, at a
restaurant with clients or friends, or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Brier, a Newton marketing consultant and mother of two,
says she barely has time for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend two minutes eating it. I have to tell myself to sit
down. Usually I'm standing up when I scoop some cottage cheese into
a mug. There's just no time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brier wakes at 5:30 a.m. to exercise, make breakfast, make
lunches, start dinner, bid her husband goodbye, and see her
children off. She also carpools. She says she speeds through lunch
to make time for a full, sit-down meal with her family later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I eat lunch?'' Laura Russell, a program director at the
Women's Educational and Industrial Union in Boston, asked. ``Yes,
I'll eat _ while I'm doing something else.'' Russell also has
walking lunches. She eats while on her way to appointments around
town.
</P>
<P>
   Walking lunches, multitasking, rushing: They are all part of the
new paradigm. But what happens when we slow down? Can we?
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that when it's time to be alone, we might need
that cell phone or palm pilot or television?
</P>
<P>
   ``As nature abhors a vacuum, so we abhor the blankness, the lack
of stimulation, that comes with doing nothing,'' writes Gleick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, alone with our thoughts, we feel that there just isn't
enough to keep us entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
