<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CUSTOMS-FUNERAL-HNS &LR;      03-30 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A SEVEN-GUN SALUTE, AND WHIMPERS, FOR OFFICER'S LAST RITES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Photo available by calling the San Antonio Express-News
photo department at 210-250-3297.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE PASS, Texas _ At the first blast from the seven-gun honor
guard on Thursday, the barking and whimpering spectators fell
silent, as Labrador retrievers, German shepherds and dark-faced
Belgian Malanois looked anxiously at their handlers.
</P>
<P>
   By the third and final blast, they were petrified.
</P>
<P>
   As service funerals go, the one observed outside the Canine
Enforcement Section kennels near the Camino Real International
Bridge was short and to the point, but not without pathos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gathered here today to honor a fallen comrade, not an
officer, but Hamlet, a loyal canine,'' began the eulogy by John
Salazar, the U.S. Customs Service port director for Eagle Pass.
</P>
<P>
   At Salazar's right on a small table, was an urn containing
Hamlet's ashes, a bouquet of flowers, and the wooden badge, bearing
number 6C-66, that until recently had been attached to Hamlet's
kennel door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamlet had not been in the field very long, barely two years,
but he had already made his mark, intercepting over $7 million in
drugs, with excellent seizures of cocaine and marijuana,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year-old yellow Labrador retriever died of cancer on
March 15.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral was held at the suggestion of Hamlet's handler,
Customs agent Percy Lomax, who had trained with him at the
service's canine school in Virginia, and then worked with him in
Eagle Pass for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mellow, the mellowest dog here, but fun-loving. He
loved to play around,'' Lomax said before the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really loved that dog. It's just kind of hard to let it go.
It really hurt to find out he had cancer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his fellow canines, Hamlet's funeral was attended by his
veterinarian and other agents from Customs, the U.S. Border Patrol,
the Immigration and Naturalization Service, the Eagle Pass police,
and Mexican Customs. Eagle Pass is 150 miles west of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Most agents were dog handlers, and the Customs dog teams working
the two international bridges in Eagle Pass Thursday morning were
pulled off duty to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The common bond of the officers who attend was their four-footed
partners and their shared sense of grief, and the loss was as real
as the tears that appeared on Lomax's cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a parent-child relationship. In the Customs Service,
we take a new handler and put him with a new dog, and they work
together, so after a few years, they develop a strong bond,'' said
Robert Cagle, the team leader for the Customs' 14-dog canine squad
and partner of Crocket, a chocolate lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's your buddy, he's your pet, and he's your partner, and
you're taking care of him. The dog will defend the handler, take a
bullet for him,'' said Trinidad Sanchez, an INS dog handler, whose
partner is Eros, a German shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good dog makes the handler look good, and a good handler
makes the dog look good. And when you lose one, it's like a death
in the family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for the failure of a bugler to show up and play taps, the
funeral service went off without a hitch. After the crowd has
dispersed, calm returned, broken only by the sounds of eager
barking of the drug dogs waiting to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very long, but I think it was appropriate. And I
think it meant a lot to Mr. Lomax. We all would have felt the same
way if it had been our dog too,'' Cagle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
