<SLUG> BC-FILM-SKULLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUGHABLE PLOT PUSHES `SKULLS' TO BRINK OF ABSURDITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If it's secret and it's elite, it can't be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of The Skulls as the Freemasons for the Ivy League crowd,
an exclusive club of future movers and shakers with a taste for
dark Gothic theatrics. They're not so much secret as clouded in
mystery and myth _ everyone on campus knows all about them and even
where they meet _ but they are elite and very powerful.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ideal aphrodisiac for star athlete and street kid made
good Luke McNamara (Joshua Jackson from TV's ``Dawson's Creek'').
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of its running time, ``The Skulls'' is about
Luke's seduction. Lured by lavish gifts and cabal-like ceremonies
in torchlit stone chambers, he's an everyman toying with selling
his soul in exchange for entrance to the halls of American power.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much to jerk him back to reality, only the death
of his best friend Will (Hill Harper), an aspiring investigative
journalist who digs a little too deep into the secrets of the
Skulls. Luke discovers his own Skull ``soulmate'' Caleb Mandrake
(Paul Walker), son of ruthless society godfather Craig T. Nelson,
is the prime suspect. The moral compass in an amoral underworld, he
challenges the leaders and discovers that powerful friends make
vindictive enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is hopelessly dull as Luke, unconvincing as either a
reformed delinquent or a crusading rebel taking on the Skulls on
their own terms. Walker, with flashing eyes under furrowed brow and
an angular face pulled tight with tension, is far more interesting
as a haunted rich kid ``bad boy'' torn between pleasing an
overbearing father and a conscience pushed deep inside.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Cohen's direction is too solemn for this often laughable
twist in the Victorian ``secret society'' thriller. He fills every
image with haze and shadow, especially the secret ceremonies that
have the humorless gravity of a Satanic ritual, with elder members
standing in the shadows like demonic overlords.
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect between modern boys and ancient ritual is rife
with possibility, but the script is more interested in the plot
launched against Luke (who plays into their hands by ranting like a
paranoid) and the back-stabbing and blackmail of Skulls in
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen drives the film at a galloping pace, but it's not fast
enough to outrun its absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   The Skulls. Directed by Rob Cohen. Screenplay by John Pogue.
Cast: Joshua Jackson, Paul Walker, Hill Harper, Leslie Bibb,
William Petersen, Craig T. Nelson. Universal Pictures. 107 minutes.
Rated PG-13 for violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
