<HEADER>
A2377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-CLUTTER-BOS &LR;      03-30 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CLUTTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE CLUTTER-FREE ROAD TO HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelle Passoff is a yoga devotee who believes that cleaning
your life of clutter is ``the missing link'' to inner happiness.
</P>
<P>
   A line on the cover of Passoff's ``Lighten Up!: Free Yourself
From Clutter'' claims it's ``the first book of its kind to view
cleaning not as a burdensome chore but as a transformational
experience.'' By that, Passoff means spiritual as well as physical
transformation. In her view you can't have one without the other.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning your life of clutter will produce results, she
promises. It will lead to personal growth, even to ``magic'' and
``miracles.'' For some of us, merely making a dent in our clutter
would be miracle enough, but I suspect Passoff has something larger
in mind. In her book she writes that cleaning your clutter ``can
make a difference in your life, the lives around you, and
ultimately the world.''
</P>
<P>
   World peace through clutter cleaning? Well, it's safer and
cheaper than nuclear deterrents.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff is an amiable Manhattanite who seems pretty laid-back
for a woman who's made a career of organizing. It must be the yoga.
She was in Boston recently to teach a course to a small class, 12
people. Since opening her clutter-cleaning consulting business in
1991, she's traveled far and wide working with private clients and
holding classes for the clutter-confounded.
</P>
<P>
   She's never had a clutter problem herself, she said, thanks to
her mother, a superorganized woman who enlisted her husband and two
daughters in the job of keeping their home neat. It also helped,
she said, that the family lived in a glass house, an A-frame, where
every corner was open to view, so there was no place for clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Her business is thriving because the problem of clutter is
getting worse. ``Life is more complicated; there's more information
coming at us at a furious pace,'' she said during a break in class.
``More people are working from home; people are more mobile. This
is a point of great change in our society, and if we're not able to
anchor ourselves in our physical environment, all this stuff can
overwhelm us.''
</P>
<P>
   We were some of the overwhelmed, 10 women, two men, mostly
middle-aged, a few in their 20s, all of us _ well, all of us but
one, who claimed being organized was one of her chief interests in
life _ so burdened by clutter that we were willing to spend $34 and
sit indoors on a beautiful afternoon in hopes that Passoff would
inspire us to go home and finally deal with all the stuff we've
accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff had some bad news for us. Clutter never stops; it keeps
on coming. Just as there's no such thing as succcesful binge
dieting, there's no successful binge clutter-cleaning. The approach
has to be integrated into daily life. If any of us was hoping for a
quick fix that would last forever, she told us, we should forget
it.
</P>
<P>
   She started the class by instructing us to take 10 minutes to
think about why we want to clear our clutter: ``Ask yourself, What
am I making room for?''
</P>
<P>
   The sort of answer she was looking for wasn't ``New and better
clutter.'' We were supposed to dig deep and think big. What are our
goals? What do we want out of life? She suggested a few categories
for us to consider: Financial? Professional? Relationships?
</P>
<P>
   In 10 minutes I was supposed to come up with answers to
questions I haven't been able to resolve in 20-odd years of
therapy. Of course, it's possible I already know the answers. It's
even possible that I deliberately keep my life full of clutter,
physical and emotional, to avoid making decisions. Confirmed
clutterers don't like making decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about clutter is an intimate conversation,'' Passoff
said, encouraging us to delve into our psyches. ``It's talking
about the skeletons in your closet.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused for a second and chuckled. ``You know, I worked with
a client once who literally had skeletons in her closet,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't elaborate on the skeletons, but turned to a young
graphic designer who said he needed to clean his clutter to make
more room for his creative projects. ``I have a lot of nice
stuff,'' he said, ``but you know, if you have too much stuff, no
matter how nice it is, it's junk.''
</P>
<P>
   Passoff nodded, adding that some of her clients are people who
collect rare and beautiful things and turn to her when their
collections overwhelm their lives. ``When you start adding on rooms
to accommodate your stuff, that's a problem,'' she said. ``I don't
care how nice your stuff is.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman said needed to clean her clutter because she is now
working out of as well as living in a 900-square-foot apartment.
Another is expecting a baby and wants to clear up clutter at home
to make room for the new arrival.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman says she's completing her M.A. and running a
business from her parents' home. Her office needs to be better
organized, she said, so she can spend her time more productively.
</P>
<P>
   The urge to clutter-clean often comes at life-changing moments,
Passoff said. A marriage. A baby. Leaving school. A change of job.
Moving house. A death in the family. Yes, and aging, and changing
shape. Several women in the class, including me, had clothes
clutter. It's very hard to face up to the fact I'll never again fit
into all those clothes I wore 20 pounds ago. Passoff advises being
ruthless. After all, the clothes are useless and only remind me of
the weight I've gained. ``When you open your closet,'' Passoff
said, ``your goal is to get dressed, not get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Clothes should be clean and in good repair and fit your body and
your lifestyle. Anything that doesn't fit those criteria shouldn't
be in your closet. But how can I bring myself to get rid of all
that stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``One item at a time,'' Passoff said. This is the golden rule of
clutter cleaning, according to Passoff, and it's her own mantra.
``If you look at a whole project you may get discouraged,'' she
said. ``Focus on one paper, one piece of clothing, one object at a
time. Once you've cleaned your clutter, the one-item-at-a-time will
help you maintain a clutter-free lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last hour of class Passoff concentrated more on the
practical than the spiritual side of clutter cleaning. Pick a place
to start, she said. Desk, bedroom, closet, wherever. Then schedule
a block of time to clean, two to four hours, preferably four
because, she said, ``usually you can see a wonderful difference
after four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Gather up all your clutter. Get some boxes for presorting and
label them ``personal,'' ``professional,'' ``financial,'' and so
forth. Lay in a supply of file folders for organizing because, when
all is said and done, successful clutter cleaning involves a good
filing system.
</P>
<P>
   Presort your clutter into the boxes. Then go through each box,
one item at a time, and do what needs to be done. Answer that
letter. Pay that bill. Throw away that clipping you've been saving
for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   After class I told Passoff that I felt exhausted just thinking
about cleaning all my clutter at home and at work. She said it
would take time _ weeks, even months _ but that the effort would be
worth it because decluttering your life is energizing and brings
inner peace. She compared it to practicing yoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoga practice is about cleaning your mind of clutter,'' she
said, ``so you can go within yourself to a place of silence to
whatever is divine.''
</P>
<P>
   A place where, presumably, you don't need any file folders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lighten Up! Free Yourself From Clutter'' is a HarperPerennial
paperback, $13. Passoff's phone number is 212-222-2488; e-mail her
at lightenup(at)freefromclutter.com; her Web site is
http://www.freefromclutter.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
