<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING FAMILY IN A NEW LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My brother, my sister, and I have been estranged all our lives.
</P>
<P>
   We just didn't know it.
</P>
<P>
   Part it of has to do with the age differences between us. I'm
seven years older than my sister, 12 years older than my brother.
Until recently, we thought we'd grown up in ``different'' families
and been affected in different ways by our parents' changing
fortunes. Since my mother served as the spoke of a wheel, passing
messages between us and often creating conflict in the process, as
children all we knew about one another was what our parents told
us. We didn't really talk until we were adults.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't know how alienated we were because after we all got
married, we made the decision to get along. We got together at
holidays. We smoothed over occasional flare-ups and didn't look at
them too closely. We rose to the occasion of my father's death,
helping him die in hospice care at my sister's house. We probably
would have gone on being politely distant forever if my sister
hadn't gone into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Susan, however, didn't treat therapy as an act designed to fix
herself apart from her relationships with others. She wanted to
share the process, and so last fall she invited my husband and me
to spend a weekend on the Cape with her and her husband, discussing
the issues she was facing. I was reluctant. What fool wants to stir
things up? I was sure I'd made my peace with my parents who, in any
case, were no longer alive, and so I went with the sole intention
of being a good listener.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't plan to reveal a thing.
</P>
<P>
   After all, my parents had presented me to my younger siblings as
a great success story, someone whose accomplishments could not
easily be matched. Susan, in reaction, had rebelled against the
expectation that she follow in my footsteps, and I was sure that
she resented whatever success I had achieved. I didn't want Susan
to see the chinks in my armor. I was afraid that if I revealed the
childhood demons that had followed me into adulthood, she'd take
satisfaction from my pain. In my deepest soul, I really didn't
trust her. I was afraid of her anger.
</P>
<P>
   When we got together, Susan talked about her experience of
growing up in our home. I was shocked. Every word she said could
have come out of my mouth. We'd both felt the same terrible
loneliness as children, the same sense of disconnection from other
family members. She hadn't felt understood, or valued, or loved.
She hadn't felt supported, or safe, or lovable. And as she spoke
from her heart, mine tumbled open and revealed the same tangle of
painful emotions. I began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   To my immense surprise, Susan comforted me.
</P>
<P>
   It was an enormous relief to feel close to someone who'd shared
the same difficult and unique parents, to finally have someone who
could nod in agreement as I described the nature of my discomfort
in this world. There was such an indescribable feeling of mutual
compassion that we couldn't stop talking. We stayed away from the
disagreements and judgments that had distanced us as adults, and by
Sunday morning, discovered that they were no longer of any
importance, mere symptoms of our underlying distrust. We both felt
as if, through some quirk of fate, we were finally becoming true
friends to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Susan is close to my brother. At odds with him, I always felt
she was on his side. But in this new relationship, she was able to
help me understand that he was also trying to survive the childhood
forces operating in our lives. Eventually I called my brother and
confessed to all the negative feelings I'd been so carefully (and
unsuccessfully) hiding. I acknowledged how unfair I'd been, and how
ready I was to start again from a new place. Ken didn't say a word
of reproach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he asked if Susan and I would include him in our
process.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not recommending this to other families. I hardly believe
what is happening in my own, but I see that our decision to get
together regularly despite our inner reservations was an indication
of how much we each longed to be part of a loving, extended family.
I was wrong in thinking there was no need for me to deal with my
family of origin, which has left such a powerful mark on my psyche.
</P>
<P>
   We three have a shared history; it seems right that memory
should bond us to one another. Perhaps, in daring to examine the
puzzle of our childhoods together, we can add a new dimension of
healing to the meaning of the word family.
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
