<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE FOR OLDFANGLED MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the forgotten stepchildren of the modern media family.
In all the hoo-hah over the AOL-Time Warner deal, most mentions of
the company's famous magazines came in a few snide stories about
the sudden explosion of Time Inc. stock-option millionaires. When
Times-Mirror was sold to the Tribune Co., its stable of magazines _
from Popular Science to Field &AMP; Stream _ was treated as the
proverbial player to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, somehow, in this digital, high-speed, instantaneous news
cycle culture, the old-fashioned magazine business is alive and
kicking furiously. And some of the biggest names in the business
are about to unveil products, including Oprah Winfrey's magazine
for Hearst, an e-commerce publication from Time Inc., and a Conde
Nast entry about shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've been in better times,'' enthuses Samir
Husni, a University of Mississippi journalism professor and
magazine analyst. ``You don't read anywhere anymore about the death
of print.'' That may be something of an overstatement, but Husni
brandishes the vital stats to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   By his calculations, there were 866 magazine launches in 1999,
which translates to nearly 2 1/2 a day. (And that's a drop from the
1,067 launches in 1998.) Last year, the hottest categories among
startups were celebrity publications (108) and sports (95). But
specialty startups also flourished, which explains the debut of
Rubbertime for latex fetishists and Bark, described as a ``dog
lover's literary forum.'' The news is also bullish from the
Publishers Information Bureau, which reported that 1999 magazine ad
revenue was up almost 13 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Husni's estimate that only about 10 percent of startups
survive 15 years, publishers are constantly churning out new or
improved models. The already competitive celebrity magazine genre
heated up earlier this month when US went weekly and threw down the
gauntlet to the all-powerful People.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much, much younger,'' than People, insists USweekly
editor in chief Terry McDonell, carefully explaining his niche.
``We wouldn't do James Brolin. We would do Toby Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine shuffles off the newsstand for good, but here
comes Time Inc.'s 212-page Real Simple, with its attention focused
on ``life/home/body/soul.'' Details magazine is suspended and
retooled, but its place is filled by FHM, another British import
trying to crack the ``lad magazine'' category so named for its apt
attention to female flesh.
</P>
<P>
   This month marks the arrival of Offspring, the Dow Jones-Hearst
collaboration marketed as ``the magazine of smart parenting,''
featuring a cover photo of an elementary school-aged girl toting an
Apple iBook. To find out how she'll turn out in a few years, try
teenStyle, the new guide to youthful beauty tips published by H &AMP; S
media.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what is driving the magazine explosion is what the media
banking firm of Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates calls ``brand
extensions,'' the spinoffs created by major publishers looking to
match new products with ever tighter demographic niches.
</P>
<P>
   The products in the pipeline include O, The Oprah Magazine _
from Hearst and the Harpo Entertainment Group _ that is headed for
the newsstands April 19 as ``the women's personal growth guide for
the Twenty-First Century.'' This spring, Time Inc. introduces
eCompany Now to cover the burgeoning world of online commerce. And
in mid-May, Conde Nast publishes a trial issue of Lucky, a magazine
about shopping designed for young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one trend is that major magazine publishers are
launching, in force, new magazines,'' says Husni. ``More and more
of the companies are finding out that magazines are the missing
link in the electronic chain.'' Using Web sites that offer a taste
of the full magazine _ and taking advantage of the reliability
associated with print _ magazine publishers are wisely avoiding the
crucial mistake ``of trying to compete with the Internet instead of
complementing it,'' says Husni.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing wrinkle is the move by Nerve (www.nerve.com), a
sophisticated three-year-old online magazine about sex, to start
distributing a print version in April. The company's press release
sums up the undeniable appeal of Nerve's subject matter and the
resiliency of the magazine industry by promising readers
``something beautiful they can put their hands on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the theory that a fawning media aided and abetted the
presidential campaign of Sen. John McCain? Well a survey of almost
1,200 adults taken in mid-March by the Pew Research Center found
that 14 percent thought McCain's press coverage was too tough,
compared to only 10 percent who thought George W. Bush got a raw
deal and 8 percent who thought Vice President Al Gore was unfairly
treated. ``Complaints that the media have been too easy on John
McCain appear to have little resonance beyond the Beltway,'' the
survey concluded. Just one more example of that famous Beltway-Main
Street disconnect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1532EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EYES AT NIGHT,   WITH NEW SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   I am traveling at 60 miles per hour and it is a pitch-black
night. The 100 yards of highway ahead that are swept by my
headlights are clear.
</P>
<P>
   But there, seeming to dance on the leading edge of my car's
hood, I get an early, important look at potential danger _ 400-500
yards ahead. There is a car in the breakdown lane. Will someone
suddenly step from beside it into the road? It has stopped near the
glowing image of a highway overpass and I see an animal scurrying
up the grassy embankment from the highway to the overpass. Will the
creature _ it turns out to be a dog _ suddenly change direction and
dart back into my path?
</P>
<P>
   At 60 miles per hour, at that distance, I have between 12 and 17
1/2 seconds to weigh these potential dangers and adjust my driving
accordingly. Without the Night Vision system in the Cadillac
DeVille I am driving, I would have seen none of this until I was
100 yards or less from the car and the dog. If the dog darted or an
occupant of the car had been crouched, changing a tire, back
jutting into the travel lane, I would have had only about 3 1/2
seconds to recognize the danger, react, and, if necessary, bring my
car to a sudden stop.
</P>
<P>
   The DeVille is the first car offered in the United States with
Night Vision as an option. Right now, it's not cheap _ about $2,000
_ but its safety potential is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   This Night Vision system was developed by General Motors and
Raytheon Systems, with some work done in Massachusetts, but the
bulk of it done in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision was born, as are many civilian inventions, of
military design. Early systems designed to help fight in the dark,
such as the ``Starlight'' scope used in Vietnam or night vision
goggles, work by concentrating available ambient light _ what
Stuart Klapper, director of automotive programs for Raytheon, calls
image intensifier technology.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Gulf War came, America got a look at a different
sort of night vision enhancing technology. It was called far
infrared, or forward-looking infrared. It is these images, which
look like photographic negatives, that you may recall from news
photos and video from the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   What is different about forward-looking infrared is that it uses
heat, rather than light, to form an image for the operator of a
tank _ or a DeVille.
</P>
<P>
   Klapper says that even 15 years ago, a single, forward-looking
infrared system cost hundreds of thousands of dollars. That a
system can now be offered for $2,000 is remarkable. And Klapper
says that as Night Vision systems become more commonplace, their
costs could drop to what you pay today for a good television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens with prices will depend on public reaction,'' he
says, citing air bags and anti-lock brake systems, once expensive
options, as examples of safety features that drop in cost and make
their way into the mainstream automotive market.
</P>
<P>
   Cost, of course, is but one factor in selling the public on a
new technology. Another is persuading drivers that the technology
will help them and, further, that it will be easy to use and will
not distract them as they drive.
</P>
<P>
   Safety should be marketable based purely on common sense. Only a
quarter of the nation's drive time is spent on the road after dark,
yet that's when half of all fatalities occur. How many moose, deer,
dogs, cats, humans, broken down autos, get hit by vehicles whose
drivers don't spot the danger until too late?
</P>
<P>
   The ease of use and a lack of distraction factors require more
tangible proof _ like a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   So get behind the wheel of the 2000 DeVille (full review of the
car itself next week), fire it up at night, and let the Night
Vision system warm up for about 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   An image about the size of your interior rearview mirror appears
just above the top of your dashboard. With a couple of buttons you
can move it up or down an inch or so, or can alter its intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Though the image _ picked up by a forward-looking camera mounted
in the Cadillac's grille _ is projected through the dash ahead of
you and onto the windshield, you do not ``see'' it on the
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what Klapper calls a ``virtual image'' causes your eyes
to focus out at the very front of the car. If the image were
projected, say, on a flat or pop-up screen on your dash, your eyes
would have to refocus each time you glanced at the screen and again
when you looked back to the road.
</P>
<P>
   With Night Vision's virtual image system, your eyes are in
constant focus on the road ahead. After only about 10 minutes of
getting used to the system, you are looking right through the
virtual image _ aware of what appears on it _ but concentrating on
the road as you normally would.
</P>
<P>
   What you see is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all objects give off some heat. Humans and animals are
warmest and they give off the most heat. My own children, put well
out of headlight range and given a soccer ball to toss, appeared as
strong, milky images on the screen. Even the ball _ warm because
they were touching it, I assume _ was a glowing white orb.
</P>
<P>
   Children safely back in the car, we took a drive. Trees _
they're alive _ glowed in a roadside dance of their own, darker at
the trunks, radiant out near the tips of their branches.
</P>
<P>
   Autos appeared ahead of me even as their tail lights were only
first coming into view. Their bodies glowed, their exhausts were
pulsing emissions of light. Because this system uses heat, not
light, to capture its images, it ``sees through'' the headlights of
approaching cars, a scenario that would be a blinding problem for
systems that concentrate available light.
</P>
<P>
   Road signs are not as bright, but become quickly visible long
before headlights reach them. Bridges and their supports,
presumably giving off radiant heat stored during the daytime,
become visible way beyond the reach of headlights.
</P>
<P>
   It only takes 0.3 of a degree in temperature for the Night
Vision system to respond by offering gradients in the images it
produces. This is why the image _ though much like your old black
and white TV in negative _ is so detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision can tell that there is more activity at the tip of
a tree's branches; that sunlight has been stored as energy in a
concrete pillar and is now bleeding away as heat in the night; that
a crippled car is located dangerously on the edge of the shoulder
dead ahead; that a moose has wandered into the road; that a child
has run from her yard chasing a pet.
</P>
<P>
   It can show you all this, show you before your headlights reveal
the danger, show you while you still have time to react.
</P>
<P>
   Still rare and still expensive, Night Vision is not within reach
of everyone. But once upon a time, neither were air bags.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
