<HEADLINE>
IN `WEST WING'S' SHADOW, `D.C.' IS AN ALSO-RAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on ``The West Wing.'' If Aaron Sorkin's crackling-good
series about a chatty, natty, fratty White House staff hadn't come
along this season, maybe ``D.C.'' wouldn't seem like the Foggy
Bottom Follies.
</P>
<P>
   ``D.C.,'' a Fox-style soaper, isn't even of the same genre as an
ensemble drama like ``The West Wing,'' but Sorkin's take on
capital-ism has set the Beltway bar impossibly high. ``D.C.,'' a
creation of ``Law &AMP; Order'' producer Dick Wolf, will need special
enabling legislation and maybe a high-court ruling to reach it.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's premiere on The WB introduces us first to Mason
Scott, a low-level congressional staffer who tells us via voiceover
that Washington really runs on the spunk of its young people.
``We're the only ones with enough energy to write the laws, run the
committees, party till 3 and then do it all again the next day,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's best friend and roommate is Pete Komisky, a lobbyist for
an obscure nonprofit group that champions the rights of all the
``loser animals'' not claimed by the higher-profile organizations.
Pete (middle-class cynic from Arizona State) and Mason (wealthy
idealist from Harvard) are opposites who obviously need each other
to maintain balance in their symbiotic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Before too long, Mason's free-spirited sister, Finley, shows up
on their doorstep, an escapee from grad school. Though
job-o-phobic, she manages to score them a housesitting deal in a
Georgetown brownstone they'd never be able to afford without
federal aid. To make this a democratic party of five, they take on
a couple more housemates _ Sarah, a junior field producer for a
cable news network, and Sarah's boyfriend, Lewis, a clerk at the
Supreme Court _ and, during one scene in a subsequent episode, they
actually conduct a parliamentary procedure to govern food purchases
for the house.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. The five basic food groups in the
dog-eat-dog world of Washington, D.C.: legislative branch,
influence-peddling branch, do-nothing branch (a metaphor,
perhaps?), meddlesome-media branch and judicial branch.
</P>
<P>
   It's a potentially rich mix, but a coldly clinical aura pervades
``D.C.,'' maybe because being that close to the citadel of power
turns people into unemotional automatons. Or maybe doing ``Law &AMP;
Order'' for so many years has caused Dick Wolf to forget about
warm-and-fuzzy characters.
</P>
<P>
   The warmest is Mason, played with youthful earnestness by
Gabriel Olds, but even he could stand to take a space heater to
bed. Mark-Paul Gosselaar, as Pete, is the inscrutable pragmatist
who takes a different woman to bed each week. But there's plenty of
that inscrutability to go around. Sarah (Kristanna Loken) and Lewis
(Daniel Sunjata) are a pair of sphinxes, and for all her carefree
joie de vivre, Finley (Jacinda Barrett) is, at best, lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its WB stylishness, ``D.C.'' makes an hour seem like
two, as we watch a group of fabulously attractive people _ this is
The WB, after all _ come to terms with new responsibilities in a
politically charged atmosphere. If it were ``The West Wing,''
they'd be so interesting we'd want to move in with them. But, at
the end of Sunday's episode, when Mason says, ``Our entire lives
are ahead of us, and Washington is where we should be, whatever may
come,'' the overwhelming urge is to exercise one's veto power.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. One-hour drama series about five young adults living and
working in the nation's capital. Starring Gabriel Olds, Mark-Paul
Gosselaar, Jacinda Barrett, Kristanna Loken and Daniel Sunjata.
Series premiere Sunday at 8 p.m., The WB. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
