u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKING UP A FUSS ABOUT CUSSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Cuss Control,'' James V. O'Connor writes that at the rate
we're going, swearing will soon be so common that it will be about
as much fun as a nudist camp.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem an odd analogy, especially if you've never been to
a nudist camp, but speaking as one who has, it's appropriate. Like
institutionalized nudity, swearing is losing its mystery, its power
to shock. Cursing is so ubiquitous that it's boring. And that's a
shame, because cursing has its uses.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor is a self-appointed bad-language watchdog who founded
the Cuss Control Academy as a division of his public relations firm
in 1998. It was a strange time. Viagra had gripped the national
imagination, the male half of it at least. And most of us were avid
to know exactly what went on between Bill and Monica in the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor weighed these developments and issued a press release
predicting certain saucy words previously unspoken in public were
about to be heard everywhere. He was on top of a cultural wave that
would carry him all the way to ``Oprah!'' to talk about the
deterioration of language, the growing crassness of society, and
the notion that the world in general is going to heck because so
many of us can't stop talking like the cast of ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cuss Control,'' a Three Rivers Press paperback that will be
in bookstores next week, O'Connor explores the linguistic and
cultural history of swearing, but it's essentially a self-help
book, subtitled ``The Complete Book on How to Curb Your Cursing.''
Notice that O'Connor uses the word ``curb'' rather than
``eliminate'' or ``cut out.'' Although he thinks that an excess of
swearing has lowered the level of our national discourse, he
believes there's a place for the occasional curse. He quotes Mark
Twain: ``In certain trying circumstances, urgent circumstances,
desperate circumstances, profanity furnishes a relief denied even
in prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Sometimes nothing but a curse will do. Once, in a quiet
bookstore, I was stunned to hear a refined-looking elderly woman
utter a ringing ``Oh, (expletive)!'' I don't know what her problem
was, but I assume it was something trying or urgent or desperate,
perhaps all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor separates cursing into two types, casual and causal.
</P>
<P>
   Casual cursing is bad language we use for a variety of reasons,
for fun, because we're linguistically lazy, because we want to
exercise our First Amendment right to be rude, because we want to
be one of the boys (or one of the girls), because we want to annoy
our parents.
</P>
<P>
   Causal profanity is triggered by emotion and thus more difficult
to curb than the casual kind. Causal cursing springs from anger,
frustration, anxiety, rage. O'Connor warns it can be dangerous and
destructive, especially to the habitual curser. All may be true,
but there are times when it feels so good to vent. It's practically
impossible to drive a car around Boston and not curse. I'd like to
see O'Connor try.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cuss Control,'' he has numerous suggestions for curbing
cursing, among them think clean, think positively, practice
patience, drive like an angel, make up ``curse'' words (``That's a
bunch of Bolshevik!''), befriend clerics (``You are not going to
cuss when you spend time with the religious leaders of your church
or temple''). Basically, though, his advice boils down to two
elements: eternal vigilance and a total attitude adjustment. Can we
curb cursing in our time? With Oprah's help and a national book
tour, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1537EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
