<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSTABLE PEOPLE, RISKY TIME   SLOT, ARTFUL SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WONDERLAND &QL; 
Starring: Ted Levine, Martin Donovan, Michelle Forbes, Michael Jai
White, Billy Burke, Joelle Carter &QL; 
On: ABC, Thursday night &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those ready to call ``time of death'' for the hospital drama may
want to hold off for a week or two. While ``Chicago Hope'' and
``ER'' have slid into creative comas, and ``City of Angels'' has
failed to thrive, the MDTV genre is about to rally with a
</P>
<P>
   messy, compelling, and ambitious new series called
``Wonderland.'' Riskily slotted by ABC opposite ``ER,'' that
Nielsen-topping jewel in the crown of NBC's must-see lineup,
``Wonderland'' is actually interesting and memorable enough to pose
a ratings threat to that ever-expanding ensemble of
intubation-happy Chicagoans.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, ``Wonderland'' is produced, written, and
everything-elsed by Peter Berg, the actor who played Kronk on
``Chicago Hope'' for four years and then wrote and directed a bad
movie called ``Very Bad Things.'' Who knew he was capable of such
an intriguing TV concept, taking the frenzy of ``ER'' and dropping
it into the intense ambiguities of our mental-health system? The
chaotic action is set in the psychiatric department of a fictional
New York City institution called Rivervue Hospital. Instead of
groaning, bleeding patients on gurneys, ``Wonderland'' gives us
people with profound emotional injuries and chemical disorders _
raving street people, a warring elderly couple, a suicidal
executive. The complex nature of their problems, including
competency to stand trial, senility, and missed medication, gives
Berg an opportunity to avoid the black-and-white resolutions and
the sentimentality with which TV is most familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The unstable people in ``Wonderland'' tend to be extreme cases,
a fact that has already triggered criticism from advocates for the
mentally challenged. Such is the nature of TV drama, which distills
and heightens, and such is the nature of psychiatric emergency
rooms. If Berg can keep his patients from lapsing into
cartoonishness and cliche, they have the potential to fascinate,
like Wendall Rickle, played with intensity by Leland Orser. We hear
his internal voice reciting the ABCs of insanity, we know he is
receiving imagined messages about Zeus, and we then see him wander
into Times Square and shoot five people. Not a positive portrayal,
but certainly a dramatic one.
</P>
<P>
   The show's strongest element, though, is its regular ensemble of
doctors and residents. Amid the madness and mania of their jobs at
Rivervue, these characters are sane and confident; but in their
personal lives, they, too, live close to the edges of sanity. The
central figure is Ted Levine's Dr. Robert Banger, a caring advocate
for the mentally ill who has an unnervingly calm exterior. He's in
the middle of a tense divorce proceeding, and the opening show's
best scenes find his young sons testing his patience during a
custody review he knows he won't win. Levine, best remembered as
the eerie ``Silence of the Lambs'' killer, does incredibly subtle
work here. He delivers the show's powerful thesis, as he describes
treating ``the shadow people'' who ``remind us just how tenuous
mental health is. . . . They remind us how easy it can be to
slip.''
</P>
<P>
   Also along for this trip through the looking glass: ``Homicide''
alum Michelle Forbes plays Dr. Lyla Garrity, who finds herself at
the center of a controversy when she fails to admit a man who later
goes on a shooting spree. She's pregnant and married to Martin
Donovan's Dr. Neil Harrison, a gentle healer who finds himself
sitting on a keg of rage. Donovan has graced many independent
films, notably ``The Opposite of Sex,'' and he's a TV hero waiting
to happen. Billy Burke manages to make his Dr. Abe Matthews more
than a stereotypical commitment-phobic womanizer, and Michael Jai
White is promising _ if underdeveloped _ as a tough-minded
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' is helped by an intentionally disheveled visual
style that at times mimics disorientation. Like ``Homicide'' and
``NYPD Blue,'' it has an artful documentary flavor, and the opening
cleverly gives us a Rorschach test. The show also takes its titular
looking-glass reference seriously, as the shots are frequently
directed through glass, either in the maze of windowed offices in
the hospital or through restaurant and cafe fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Berg may be a little too eager to hook viewers from the start.
The premiere episode is overly dense with incident and exposition,
as everything short of Armageddon occurs in less than an hour. The
Forbes-Donovan plotline is the most overwrought. By next week,
though, ``Wonderland'' finds an engaging and evenly paced focus, as
it settles into the aftermath of Rickle's violence.
</P>
<P>
   Will ``Wonderland'' survive its time slot? ABC honchos seem to
think that with ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' as a lead-in, and
with ``ER'' in a mediocre season, it stands a chance. Let's hope
they're right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
