<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TILES ON STAIRWAY ARE NOT PRACTICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The vinyl tiles on my concrete basement floor are intact and
in good shape, but the tiles on the steps are breaking up. How can
I remove them and put new ones on?
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA SIDLEY, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, you must determine whether the tiles are vinyl or
vinyl-asbestos. If they are vinyl-asbestos and contain a certain
level of the carcinogen, they must be removed professionally, at
considerable cost. But since there are not a lot of tiles on the
steps, this chore may not be prohibitively expensive. If they are
100 percent vinyl, scrape them up and throw them away. To determine
if they contain any asbestos, break off a small piece, place it in
a plastic envelope, and take it to an asbestos abatement company.
Such companies are found in the Yellow Pages under, of all things,
Asbestos abatement.
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl-asbestos tiles on the floor can be left intact; they are
safe as long as they are not sawn, sanded, or abraded in any way.
They can be covered with indoor-outdoor carpeting or other tiles.
</P>
<P>
   You can retile the steps, but tiles on a stairway are not
practical, because their edges will be exposed at the sides and
nosing of the treads, and exposed edges tend to chip.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of new tiles on the treads, consider a stair carpet;
this will be easy to install on a straight run, but difficult if
the staircase turns a corner with wedge-shaped treads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My attic has a ridge vent and 3-inch-wide soffit vents going
the full length of all soffits. But for years, mold has been
creeping up the roof boards between rafters. It is mostly on the
north side, but some is on the south side, as well. I think I have
done everything right, and it stumps me. Could I put in a power
vent on one gable end?
</P>
<P>
   JIM SHERIDAN, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It stumps me, too, on the face of it. Make sure the clothes
dryer does not vent into the attic; if it does, it is expelling
moist air, which condenses on the roof boards, resulting in mold.
The cause could also be a furnace in the attic. (Yes, that happens,
and can make attics too warm, causing ice dams, leaks, and
consequent growth of mold.)
</P>
<P>
   A final thing to check: If you have folding stairs, or even a
large trapdoor, to the attic, poor insulation could be allowing
moist house air into the attic, causing mold. You can put an
insulated box on top of the stair opening or over the trapdoor.
</P>
<P>
   This might help: Those 3-inch soffit vents are louvered, and may
be blocking more airflow than they should. I suggest removing the
vents and installing insect screen over the openings, then nailing
an edging along each side of the openings that will cover the
screen edges and give a finished look. But even this increased
airflow is not going to do much good if any of the conditions
mentioned above exist.
</P>
<P>
   A last resort is to install a large power fan in one gable end
to pull out the moist air. I would avoid this if at all possible;
it is another power source, and expensive to operate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am buying a house with Formica counter tops. Can I put
ceramic tile over Formica?
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT MAHER, South Grafton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could but I wouldn't, because the plastic laminate is too
hard and too smooth, even when heavily sanded, to hold an adhesive
or thin-set mortar. Besides, if you put edge tiles along the
counter edges (maybe 1 1/4 to 2 inches wide), there is not enough
gluing surface to be effective, especially on plastic laminate.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest removing the laminate with heat, using a flat iron;
this will soften the contact cement and make it easy to pull up.
Then you can put down the tile with thin-set mortar or adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My deck looks really good, actually it looks like varnished
wood, and the ivory-painted railings match the house. Only one
thing is wrong. The pressure-treated latticework is not painted or
stained. I would like to make it ivory. Is that possible?
</P>
<P>
   URSULA DILLON, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, it is possible, and there are two ways to do it: 1.
Paint it with an exterior primer (latex or oil) and one or two
coats of a latex house paint. 2. Apply two coats of a latex solid
stain. The latter is better and will resist peeling, but both will
have to be repeated sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   But why not let the lattice weather? It will end up as a
relatively attractive gray color. The handyman has pressure-treated
lattice on one of his fences, and he would not dream of painting
it; another darned maintenance chore.
</P>
<P>
   One more possibility: Substitute the pressure-treated lattice
with vinyl lattice. That is one good use for vinyl. You can get
white, not ivory, but that might be OK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just bought a large cedar bird feeder. Should I finish it
or not?
</P>
<P>
   ERNIE DENTALI, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No, do not finish it for several reasons. Any color could be
a deterrent to some birds. A finish would require redoing
occasionally, making another maintenance chore. No finish is
necessary; let the cedar weather, and it will last indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail him at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
