<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS &LR;      03-30 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUBTLE SHADES OF ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PRAGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EQUAL LOVE &QL; 
By Peter Ho Davies &QL; 
Mariner Books, 178 pp, $12 (paperback) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rarely pure, rarely absent altogether, love is a many-splintered
thing. In ``Equal Love,'' author Peter Ho Davies explores its sharp
edges with a caring, seldom-erring sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   His is not the storybook sort of love happily ever after. The
characters in his 12 stories suffer and stumble, equivocate and
manipulate. And yet, they love.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this more acute than in the story of junkie love
called ``Everything You Can Remember in Thirty Seconds Is Yours to
Keep.'' The narrator left home at 16, when her mother forced her to
choose between drugs and family, and drugs was the runaway winner.
When she gets pregnant in Oregon almost a decade later, she kicks
the drugs but not the habit: ``I'd been high on Luke while I was
pregnant, but coming home all sore to our apartment . . . was a
downer.'' Almost immediately she's back in the haze, and soon her
son is a ward of the court. She's given six months to shape up, and
to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't spoken with her mother since the day she left, but
now she needs Moms again _ not as a mother but as a prop, to fool
the court into seeing a happy home. She drives to Phoenix to
collect her; Moms doesn't seem quite right, but that just makes the
con go easier. At the end of the six months, the scheme has worked,
and the social worker is willing to recommend that Luke be allowed
to come home.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch: The social worker says it's clear to her
that Moms has Alzheimer's, and would be a threat to Luke's
well-being. Just like that, Moms is taken back to Phoenix, needed
no longer. Those are Davies's facts: Luke is the new heroin, and
his mother will do whatever it takes to keep her supply line open.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as he crafts it, it's a sweet, sympathetic tale. Sure,
Moms started out as a prop, but they do reconnect. When Moms has an
episode of incontinence, her daughter's help comes with tenderness.
They look after each other. When they part, there's the hint of
happiness in Moms's return to familiar surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Davies adds to the appeal of his story with a subtle touch for
the language: When Luke poops, she gets out ``the baby works,'' a
mirror of her heroin days, when her ``works'' were needle, syringe,
and spoon. And there is the comparison of mother and daughter,
mother and son, with the narrator lovingly cleaning up the messes
of two generations.
</P>
<P>
   Davies employs that role reversal, of children becoming the
caretakers of their parents, in several of his stories. In another,
a crotchety dad reluctantly lets his son drive him to see his own
mother, who's 88 and addled, confined to a long-term-care hospital.
The grandson hasn't come in three years, but his father drives the
30 miles once or twice a week. The grandson doesn't like it there,
particularly when his father starts talking in baby talk: ``I wish
he wouldn't treat her like a child.'' When her mind went soft, the
grandmother had lived with them for a while, but her son feared she
might ``burn the house down, get hit by a car. (`All the things I
used to worry about happening to you when you were a youngster,' he
told me once.)''
</P>
<P>
   Marital infidelity also recurs as a theme. In one case, it's an
expectant father, 3,000 miles from home, consummating his first
love after years away. In another, it's only infidelity
spiritually, rather than in deed. And in a third, the facts are
even hazier: An encyclopedia salesman would rather be at work than
at home with his wife and son, for reasons never entirely clear.
Eventually, his wife takes the 6-year-old and leaves him. He
remains the good provider for the boy, but can never answer the
wife's question: What went wrong? Eventually, he even invents a
mistress, but only because it's easier than explaining.
</P>
<P>
   Davies revels in such ambiguities; they are simply part of his
landscapes. Thankfully, there's little ambiguity in how he
expresses them. His stories share a wonderful sense of place, and a
wonderful subtlety in how he imparts it: quickly, often in no more
than a phrase or two. In the salesman's story, for example, he has
established it by the third sentence: ``Mrs. Kidner, her name was.
Got on very well, we did, too.'' Clearly, we're in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Britain, Davies sets his stories principally in
Boston and on the West Coast, sometimes in combinations thereof.
One gets a palpable sense that these are the places Davies has
lived, and that some of his stories are rooted deeply in his own
experiences. That notion is reinforced by the short back-cover
biography, but it originates in the keen quality of authenticity he
delivers throughout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
