<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY OF LANDSCAPE ARCHITECTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Landscape architecture can be a lot of different things. It can
be a 23-acre plaza like the one George Hargreaves designed for this
summer's Olympics in Sydney, Australia. Or it can be old shoes
running up the columns of the Harvard Design School's Gund Hall,
like the installation Cambridge, Mass., schoolchildren are working
on with Detroit street artist Tyree Guyton to celebrate the
centennial of the nation's first department of landscape
architecture at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, landscape architecture started in the Boston
area. An evolving field that combines architecture, urban planning,
pollution control, ecology, sociology, and horticulture, it was
invented by the great park builder Frederick Law Olmsted, who
created a new scale (huge) and a new style (naturalistic) for
public urban spaces with the Emerald Necklace and Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 100 years ago, his son and business partner, Frederick
Law Olmsted Jr., designed and launched the first professional
course in landscape architecture at Harvard with Arthur A.
Shurcliff.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard celebration _ ``100 Years of Landscape Architecture
at Harvard'' _ includes two concurrent exhibits opening Monday in
Gund Hall and running through the end of the month: ``Our
Heritage,'' looking backward, and ``Imagining Futures,'' looking
forward. Two days of seminars open to the public will be similarly
divided: looking back at the last 100 years, April 7; and looking
ahead, April 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look into education and research, what's coming, where
the gaps are in what we should be doing on, for instance, in
sustainable landscapes, or how you design with a flood zone,'' says
George Hargreaves, a 1979 graduate of Harvard's landscape
architecture program and for the last four years its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The many notable conference participants are scheduled to
include Garrett Eckbo and Daniel Kiley, who were flunked in the
late 1930s for insisting on Walter Gropius-inspired modernism in
the face of a conservative landscape faculty dedicated to the Beaux
Arts style. ``Modernism was a revolution that began with the
students,'' says Hargreaves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, under the leadership of Hideo Sasaki, who will be
presented with the Centennial Medal next Thursday, Harvard
emphasized large-scale planning and offered classes taught by
leading practicing landscape architects who also trained students
in their firms as interns, especially at Sasaki Associates of
Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   The practice continues today with Sasaki Associates, and newer
Cambridge landscape architecture firms such as those of Carol R.
Johnson, Douglas P. Reed, Michael Van Valkenberg, Martha Schwartz,
and George Hargreaves, all reinforcing the area's position as an
international center for this kind of work. In recent years,
environmental scientists have been added to the faculty as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most significant landscape architecture school in
the country,'' says Hargreaves. ``The jobs in this field are
expanding, and the other schools produce landscape architects to
fill those jobs. We produce leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Though weary from a night flight from the San Francisco office
of his firm during a recent interview in his corner office of glass
walls perched over Cambridge Street, Hargreaves is imposing,
quietly intense, and handsome, in that fit California way, with
curly hair, chin stubble, and eyes of silver-blue echoed by the hue
of his crisp linen shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The summer he was 18, Hargreaves discovered his deep affinity
for natural landscapes while hiking in the Rockies with friends.
The Atlanta native enjoyed the mentorship of celebrated Berkeley,
Calif., minimalist Peter Walker (also a Harvard alum) and developed
from wunderkind into a force in the field with his original but
environmentally sensitive landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   In the forefront
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old chairman says that Harvard's landscape
architecture department, widely regarded as the best of about 50
such degree programs in the country, is in the forefront on
reclaiming abandoned industrial landscapes, including waterfronts;
countering sprawl; developing regional planning and sustainable
landscapes; and in green technologies such as toxic remediation and
water filtration, though he would like to see more research done in
this area.
</P>
<P>
   Hargreaves, who maintains homes in both Cambridge and San
Francisco (``the two ghettos of landscape architects''), admits to
being in a bit of ``post-project depression'' after completing work
on the Olympics in Sydney, which he considers one of his
masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of job that would traditionally have gone to an
architect rather than a landscape architect, but Hargreaves was
called in to produce a comprehensive plan after lack of
communication between architects of individual parcels produced an
unaccounted-for 5-foot change of grade in the middle of the Olympic
Village.
</P>
<P>
   Hargreaves's master plan unified the buildings by various
architects, including three stadiums, around a central plaza of
celebratory fountains that forms Australia's largest public space.
</P>
<P>
   Built on a defunct and contaminated slaughter yard, the project
illustrates two major themes that Hargreaves is promoting at
Harvard: reclamation of former industrial sites and employment of
ecological solutions for pollution. The Olympic fountains actually
purify water from a nearby polluted stream, as do buffer strips of
toxin-filtering plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a global rather than a regional view of landscape
architecture,'' says Hargreaves, and a quarter of the school's
students come from abroad. Harvard has students working on
landscape projects in Hong Kong, and starting next fall will have
some in China. Hargreaves is working on one class that is
redesigning access to the South Rim of the Grand Canyon at the
invitation of the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig landscaping
</P>
<P>
   But why, if this is such a landscape mecca, is nobody here
designing solutions to that other big hole in the ground, Boston's
Big Dig?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Dig is still looking for an idea of a landscape. It's
somewhat ingenuous to me that we've spent $12 billion so far trying
to get it underground, but no one's sure what it's going to be,
except that it's going to be green,'' says Hargreaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should be where you'd start, with an idea and funds for
what you're going to do when it's all done. . . . Sometimes they do
it right, like in Sydney, where they had $40 million for the
infrastructure but they had another $40 million for the landscaping
out of a total of $1 billion for the whole job _ less than 10
percent of the Big Dig.''
</P>
<P>
   What Hargreaves would like to see on the Central Artery surface
is ``a rich mosaic, some parts of it developed with buildings that
knit the city back together where it's appropriate, and in other
places, green spaces that are rich in color and texture, with
features you can enter into: gardens, people spaces. I don't want
to see them just roll out some grass and say, `There we go.' A lot
of thought has to be put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven or eight years ago Harvard's planning and design
department did a studio _ a brainstorming and design project with
students _ on the Big Dig. ``I'm beginning to ask myself why aren't
we returning to that problem, and we very well might. Funding is
not the problem. It would be more beneficial to have the city or
the state involved in it, so it won't just be 10 students saying
`Do this.' We need some political sponsorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargreaves is already involved with a small, partly pro bono
project to convert land along Chelsea Creek in East Boston into an
``urban wild.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
