<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PRICEOFGLORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRICE OF GLORY' THROWS NO KNOCKOUT PUNCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Price of Glory'' is the sort of movie that inspires backhanded
compliments like ``cliched but effective.'' It's practically asking
for trouble when it combines two genres, the boxing drama and the
father-son conflict drama, that have near-rigid sets of rules. It's
almost impossible to bring anything new to the party, and aside
from focusing on a Latino family, ``Price of Glory'' doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie gets by, thanks to an appealing family, solid
performances and a rousing climax. Jimmy Smits, making his first
feature appearance since his mournfully glorified exit from ``NYPD
Blue,'' brings his prideful bearing to the role of Arturo Ortega, a
once-promising boxer who was shafted out of a career by an
unscrupulous manager. Arturo now lives through his three sons, all
of them Golden Gloves fighters with professional-championship
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Each, of course, wants to do things his own way. Oldest boy
Sonny (''Homicide: Life on the Street's'' Jon Seda) is the steady
one but wants control over his own career. Middle son Jimmy
(Clifton Collins Jr.) is the maverick, whose careless fighting
style masks a desperate need to earn his father's respect. Youngest
son Johnny (newcomer Ernesto Hernandez) is the bruiser, and the one
who comes closest to pleasing his father. And mother Rita (Maria
del Mar) tries to hold the family together, playing peacemaker
between intractable father and willful sons, all the while wishing
they'd pick up some safer sort of career.
</P>
<P>
   The story is pretty much what you'd expect: Good things happen,
bad things happen, people triumph over adversity and Dad learns to
reconcile his feelings for his sons. Ron Perlman shows up as a
shady promoter, sporting a New Yawk accent even though this is set
in southern Arizona, and comedian Paul Rodriguez appears as his
even shadier lieutenant, who inadvertently causes a tragedy that
almost permanently divides the Ortega family.
</P>
<P>
   So many boxing movies have cropped up recently that sitting
through them all can make you feel a little punch-drunk. But the
cast rescues ``Price of Glory'' from total mediocrity, especially
Collins, whose performance echoes the punky rebellion of much of
Sean Penn's early work, and Smits, whose four seasons on ``Blue''
must have taught him a lot about portraying angry heartache.
</P>
<P>
   But director Carlos Avila rarely succeeds in making sportswriter
Phil Berger's screenplay into anything more than a glorified TV
movie. In fact, it would make a good double feature with some
future boxing match on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Price of Glory''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Carlos Avila
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jimmy Smits, Clifton Collins Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ for violence, strong language and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
