<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY FAITH, AND A LITTLE TINKERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hallelujah. It finally works.
</P>
<P>
   After much tinkering, I've set up the basics of a modern
computer network at my church. At the heart of it all is a gateway
to our high-speed DSL Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   We've had DSL for a couple of months now, and getting it was an
adventure in itself. Bell Atlantic is still a telephone company at
heart, and barely has a clue about delivering good DSL service.
It's not that they don't try; the folks I dealt with were
unfailingly polite.
</P>
<P>
   And I dealt with so many of them. There was one number to call
to order the DSL service, another number for actually setting up an
Internet account, and a third number to call when things went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Which they did. The original installation was scrubbed because
the DSL modem hadn't shown up. Bell Atlantic has the package sent
to the customer, and if it's not there when the installer arrives,
tough luck. We had to start the process all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we eventually got everything we needed. The installer _ a
clever lad who reads my column faithfully _ soon had everything up
and running. But only on one Windows computer.
</P>
<P>
   What about the others? We plan to hold Internet classes for the
members. Our pastor and his secretary want e-mail access. I'd love
to set up a machine in the lobby so visitors can visit our church
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The DSL connection provides Internet downloads at up to 640,000
bits per second. That's plenty for all our needs. The problem was
figuring out how to connect lots of computers to this one line.
It's a problem many of you will soon have. Computers are becoming
almost as popular as TV sets in American homes, and many of us are
starting to network them. Then you get home DSL or cable modem
service, and everybody wants a piece of the Internet. How do they
get it?
</P>
<P>
   I decided that our church needed a gateway _ a computer that
would be dedicated to linking our internal network to the Internet.
I had an old Pentium PC lying around that was well-suited to the
task. It already contained an Ethernet port for connecting to the
church network. I added a second Ethernet card for plugging in the
DSL line.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I'd have to get software that would route any Internet
requests from the networked computers to the gateway, then out to
the DSL line. I visited a local computer store to see what was
available.
</P>
<P>
   There are several products for connecting multiple Windows
computers to a single Internet access point _ Ositis Software
Inc.'s WinProxy, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But I was annoyed to discover that WinProxy's price varies
according to the number of computers you want to hook up. It was
$60 for a starter pack, and for that, I could connect just three
computers to the network. The unlimited version of the product
costs $700. Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. offers a cheap alternative. Their upgraded
version of Windows 98, called Second Edition, has a feature called
Internet Connection Sharing that's supposed to make for easy shared
access.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, I decided to dive off the deep end and use the
Linux operating system. Linux, after all, is free, powerful and
versatile. Simple, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic doesn't support DSL for Linux machines.
Fortunately, Roaring Penguin Software Inc.
(www.roaringpenguin.com), a Canadian Linux software firm, makes a
free DSL program. Unfortunately, they only provide the program's
raw ``source code.'' Before you can use it, you must use a program
called a compiler to transform it into machine language. I hadn't
installed the compiler on the computer when I'd installed Linux.
Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But I put it right. Soon I had the Linux box linked to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I took advantage of ``IP masquerading,'' another free
Linux feature that does the same thing as Internet Connection
Sharing. It took a lot of tinkering to make it all work properly.
But now the Linux box hums quietly away, shoveling data packets
back and forth across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And putting additional machines online is a simple matter of
plugging them into a network hub.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the pastor will have his e-mail, our kids and senior
citizens will have Internet training courses, and I'll be free to
spend less time in the computer room and more time in a pew.
Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   (You can reach Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
