<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RENO31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBAN-AMERICANS WILL 'FOLLOW THE LAW,' RENO PREDICTS
 &HT;    With ELIAN.
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno expressed confidence
Thursday that Cuban-Americans in Miami would not obstruct
government efforts to repatriate Elian Gonzalez if that became
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they came to this country to incite violence,''
Reno said. ``I think they came to this country to be able to speak
their mind, to follow the law, to respect others, and to see that
those processes were carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Miami officials said Wednesday that local law enforcement
officers would not support actions taken by the Justice Department
with regard to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, speaking at her weekly meeting with reporters, said she
hoped federal and local law enforcement agencies would work
together to resolve the issue in an orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in this great country, which is operated on
principles of federalism, the government in Miami will continue to
uphold the law and to work with other law enforcement to see that
the law is honored in the right way,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was a Florida prosecutor based in Miami for many years
before becoming U.S. attorney general in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the Justice Department is ready to enforce the law
regarding whether Elian must return to Cuba, but will proceed
cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   She said the federal government has had the right to take
custody of Elian Gonzalez since January, but has allowed his Miami
relatives to pursue legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relatives had their day in court and we gave them an
opportunity to file. A federal district judge in Miami heard the
case and affirmed our decision,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said it would be beneficial to allow Elian's father, Juan
Gonzalez, to come to the United States to speak for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always better when families work matters out between
themselves,'' Reno said. ``They do a much better job than
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
