<SLUG> BC-IVOR-ROD-STEIGER-LOOKS-BACK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROD STEIGER: A CINEMATIC LION IN WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Rod Steiger as
he appears today and with Marlon Brando in a scene from the classic
film ``On the Waterfront.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It comes near the end of ``The Hurricane'' (1999), as Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter (Denzel Washington) finally gets his last shot
at justice in an open courtroom.
 &HT;    The judge takes the bench ... but something is different.
Normally, in this sort of earnest drama, the role of the judge goes
to a B-actor of a certain age or even to a real-life judge. After
all, it demands nothing more than a seat-filler performance.
 &HT;    But this one is different. Unexpectedly, this judge is a force
of nature, a guy you don't mess with, a man you can't bend. Why?
Because this time out, the man in the black robes is Rod Steiger.
 &HT;    His contemporaries are long gone _ Montgomery Clift, James Dean,
Richard Burton _ or have all but written themselves off, as with
Steiger's old co-star and sparring partner, Marlon Brando,
vegetating atop his Los Angeles mountain.
 &HT;    But Rod Steiger is still here. Boy, is he here. As he settles
into a booth in his favorite Italian restaurant in Malibu, Steiger
seems to fill the room. He's still a huge presence, still equipped
with a voice that can zoom from a sibilant whisper to a volcanic
roar in a nanosecond.
 &HT;    He's reached that age and station in life at which tributes
start to arrive. On April 14 he'll turn 75, and to mark the
occasion the cable channel Turner Classic Movies will devote
several nights in its ``Private Screenings'' series to a Steiger
film festival, along with a no-punches-pulled interview with the
actor himself.
 &HT;    The best of Steiger will be front and center beginning on April
11, with classics such as ``Capone'' (1959), ``Dr. Zhivago'' (1965)
and ``In The Heat of The Night'' (1967). On April 14 there's ``The
Harder They Fall'' (1956), ``Jubal'' (1956) and ``No Way to Treat A
Lady'' (1968). Alas, there will be no screenings of ``On the
Waterfront'' (1954), ``The Big Knife'' (1955) or ``The Pawnbroker''
(1965).
 &HT;    His head billiard-ball smooth, his muscular arms protruding from
his short-sleeved shirt and his white napkin tucked under his chin,
the actor looks like a retired truck driver devouring the house
pizza. Steiger was never the pretty one _ Brando, Clift, Dean and
Paul Newman, Steiger's Actor's Studio colleagues, started maidens'
hearts pounding. They were the ones who got most of the glory.
 &HT;    But no one did menace better, as Steiger proved even in his only
musical to date, ``Oklahoma'' (1953), as the looming, obstinate Jud
Fry.
 &HT;    ``I was the only actor ever who sang the part, played the part
and then did the ballet,'' he says. ``Others may have danced and
sung, but ballet is very different.
 &HT;    ``Agnes De Mille was looking for someone to play me in the
ballet sequence,'' the actor recalls, ``but they couldn't find
anyone who looked heavy enough. After two weeks she called me and
said, `We found someone.' So I went down to the stage and said,
`Where is he?' and she said, `It's you.'
 &HT;    ``So I lifted 122 pounds of dancer 22 times,'' he says. ``We
figured it out _ it was over a ton. And I'm scared to death,
because she was a wonderful dancer and, if I'd dropped her, I would
have ruined her career.''
 &HT;    Almost a half-century after his film debut in ``Teresa'' (1951),
Steiger still knows what to do in a supporting role. In the past
year alone, he's played judges in ``The Hurricane'' and ``Crazy in
Alabama'' (1999), played a priest opposite Arnold Schwarzenegger in
``End of Days'' (l999) and co-starred with Burt Reynolds in ``The
Last Producer,'' a comedy about two would-be moviemakers that's due
out later this year.
 &HT;    ``Crazy in Alabama'' may have been his favorite, he says.
 &HT;    ```Crazy in Alabama' didn't stick around very long,'' he
recalls, ``When you hear anybody in this town say, `It's a sweet
film,' that means that's what's going to be on its tombstone. It's
finished in about a week.''
 &HT;    But he relished working for first-time director Antonio
Banderas.
 &HT;    ``He has a European attitude towards the people he works with,''
Steiger says. ``I always get spoiled when I work in Europe. They
say, `Mr. Steiger, would you do this or that?' In this place, some
12-year-old third assistant comes up and says, `Rod, baby, we're
ready to shoot.'''
 &HT;    Never one to suffer fools kindly, Steiger had no one to turn to
when a longstanding tendency to clinical depression hit him
full-strength in the 1980s. He was virtually unheard from for a
decade, making it through only with years of psychotherapy.
 &HT;    The lessons linger, he says.
 &HT;    ``If you're trying to obtain the respect that gives you a sense
of wholeness only through your profession, you'll never do it,'' he
says bluntly. ``You need medical or psychiatric help. Without it,
there's no such thing as success.''
 &HT;    After almost 90 movies, Steiger has battled back from depression
and surgery on both his heart and his hip. Even now, though, he
doesn't like to play it safe.
 &HT;    ``I've always loved playing around with the idea of failure,''
he admits between mouthfuls of pizza. ``So I looked for parts that
frightened me to death because of my crazy ego. But when I
succeeded like I did in `The Pawnbroker' and a few others, I had an
experience nobody in the world had. It was my high.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, he concedes, those kind of roles are harder to find.
 &HT;    ``Listen,'' he says, ``When you're my age, they're not exactly
rushing at you with great parts, not in this town. I certainly
don't expect to be a rival to Johnny Depp anytime soon.''
 &HT;    Still, he's out there looking for the kind of parts he wants,
unlike his ``On The Waterfront'' co-star Brando, with whom Steiger
has feuded off and on for decades.
 &HT;    ``Marlon doesn't like acting much,'' he says. ``At least so he's
said. But he's a very clever politician _ he'll say things so
you'll remember them that he may not believe at all.''
 &HT;    Unlike many older actors, however, Steiger doesn't insist that
the old days were the only really good days. He's enthusiastic in
his praise of several younger actors, including Al Pacino _
``because he takes chances'' _ and Meryl Streep.
 &HT;    ``Here's a woman who's such a good actress that I think people
subconsciously hate her guts,'' he says, ``because she makes it
look so easy.''
 &HT;    He envies English actors, he adds, because after long careers
they often are honored by their country in a way that Americans
rarely are.
 &HT;    ``Tony Hopkins is a friend,'' Steiger says, ``and I kid him,
`What is this ``Sir Anthony'' business? You're such a crude
fellow.' Now `Sir Rodney,' that has a ring to it: `Sir Rodney's car
is here.'''
 &HT;    Reluctantly, Steiger admits that there's some truth to his past
reputation as a ``difficult'' actor _ though, characteristically,
he isn't offering any apologies.
 &HT;    ``Clift was difficult,'' he says. ``So was Brando, and Dean. De
Niro and Hoffman, Pacino and Daniel Day-Lewis are all difficult.
And if that is difficult, then I intend to be difficult for the
rest of my life.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Private Screenings,'' consult
the Turner Classic Movies Web site at www.turnerclassicmovies.com.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
