<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE IN ILLINOIS RESTRICT PUBLIC ACCESS TO RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY SCHNEIDER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Edwardsville Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. _ Some law enforcement agencies in Illinois
are denying the public access to police records, citing a recent
state Supreme Court rule limiting what lawyers and prosecutors can
say to ensure that criminal defendants get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Media organizations attacked the response to the court's rule,
and Illinois Press Association officials have threatened to fight
it in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public will be less informed about things they otherwise
would be informed about, and it's going to get worse, probably,''
said David Bennett, the press association's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies in Edwardsville and several nearby
communities have denied reporters access to records deemed public
by state law. Officials said they were acting on the advice of
Madison County State's Attorney Bill Haine.
</P>
<P>
   The blackout of police news in Madison County is the most
extreme response to the ruling in the state. But Bennett called it
``the tip of the iceberg. We have some evidence it's spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   State's attorneys in Scott and DuPage counties have issued
strict guidelines about what prosecutors and the police can say,
and reporters in Tazwell County, near Peoria, are facing resistance
in getting routine police news, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the press group is working with prosecutors and has
received permission from the association's board of directors to
litigate against the rules, if necessary. ``The IPA will continue
to try and get these rules changed,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Dalglish of the Reporters' Committee for Freedom of the
Press in Arlington, Va., said police officers who now refuse to
release routine reports ``obviously have been frightened to death
by the state's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's profoundly ironic in all this stuff is the very reason
courts are by law public. The framers of our Constitution made it
that way to protect the defendants so you could not just lock them
away and no one would know. That's what makes this so stupid. How
do you know your mother's not in jail?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how you run a banana republic. You just lock up
anyone. It's un-American. It's absolutely ridiculous. I hope in the
next day or two, cooler heads are allowed to prevail here.''
</P>
<P>
   New Supreme Court rules of attorney conduct that went into
effect on March 16 regulate what lawyers and prosecutors can say in
criminal cases. The rules were designed to ensure the rights of the
accused to a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   The rules were so broad, however, that they prohibited the
normal flow of news from police departments to news media and had
the effect of a gag order on state's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts the state's attorneys in a box. They're personally
responsible and being gagged by the Supreme Court rules, but they
are also being held responsible for what others say,'' Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph R. Tybor, press secretary for the Supreme Court of
Illinois, said the new rules were well thought out. ``The court
gave very careful consideration to the rules changes and to the
objections to the rules changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tybor said that they imitate model rules put out by the American
Bar Association and used by many states. ``Illinois is not a
pioneer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dalglish called Haine's instructions to the police chiefs in
Madison County an extreme overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredibly hysterical response to what the Supreme
Court has done here,'' Dalglish said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Haine is overreacting to a portion of Amended Rule 3.8
which says, ``a public prosecutor ... shall exercise reasonable
care to prevent investigators, law enforcement personnel, employees
or other persons assisting or associating with the prosecutor in a
criminal case from making an extrajudicial statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in how you define `reasonable care.' He is obviously
taking it to the extreme. Reasonable care is telling a witness of
yours standing outside of the courtroom that there are press people
present, so don't say anything before you testify,'' Dalglish said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mulford, spokesman for the state Attorney General's
Office, said that the attorney general had done all he could do to
oppose the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court reviewed our objection and they denied our
appeal. And now, that's a fact of life. We made our objection
known, so at this point, it's something we have to live with,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While most Madison County police departments exercised a media
blackout, felony filings by the state's attorney's office were
still being released to the press Thursday by the circuit clerk's
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
