<SLUG> BC-GLF-AUTOGRAPHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS LEARNING TO SHUN TOUR'S AUTOGRAPH HOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Making his way to the locker room
after a practice round at The Players Championship, Ben Crenshaw
was doing what has been an important part of professional golf for
years _ signing autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Hats, programs, trading cards, golf balls. Crenshaw signed his
name to everything, all the while moving forward, smiling,
accepting thanks. Then he spotted something that turned him into
anything but ``Gentle Ben.'' He saw a young spectator hold out a
souvenir flag, a replica of those that sit atop flagsticks at golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't sign it?'' asked the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``No flags,'' said the two-time Masters winner. He was through
the gate now, safe to walk in peace, safe to put his Sharpie back
in his pocket, safe to vent his frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're killing us. The collectors are just killing us,'' said
Crenshaw. ``A damned nuisance is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw doesn't sign the souvenir flags, he said, because they
end up on e-Bay, the auction Web site, or get hustled in some other
fashion. Young children wouldn't have money to buy such pricey
souvenirs, he reasons. It pains him to turn them down, but it has
become a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely it has,'' said Bernhard Langer, another popular
target since he, too, has won two Masters. Items signed by major
championship winners traditionally fetch the most money, a reality
that is not lost upon these golfers.
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, Langer was signing autographs for youngsters,
putting his name on sweat-stained visors, crumpled programs, and
sheets with the starting times. When a youngster pulled out a
glossy, color photo of the German professional, Langer politely
handed it back, telling the boy he had signed one for him the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can recognize the same guys all the time. I'm not out here
to help them make a living,'' said Langer, and sure enough, the
youngster had a knapsack around the corner from where he had sought
out Langer. It was filled with similar photos of many Tour
regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't like the way the guy looks,'' said Davis Love, ``I
just don't sign it. That might not be right, but if a guy has got a
backpack or bag or football in one hand and he's got a baseball in
another, I just don't sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Love related a story about being approached by a young girl
holding a scorecard from Augusta National. ``Is your daddy a member
at Augusta National?'' asked Love, and the girl said no. When Love
asked her how she got hold of a legitimate Augusta National
scorecard, she pointed to a man standing nearby, at which point
Love respectfully declined to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she came back with a Winged Foot scorecard,'' said Love,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Funny? Not to Love and a growing number of PGA Tour players,
particularly at the Senior level since autographs draped in
nostalgia bring a higher price. ``But they are using kids to get
the autographs,'' said Love of these dealers who then turn around
and sell their items. ``I don't know what to do, but it is out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players don't hold such concerns. Love said that his
friend, Jeff Sluman, for instance, shrugs it off, figuring ``that
if a guy can make money off me, more power to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Andrade fears that trying to filter out the collectors
could leave an innocent kid holding a souvenir or photo he had just
bought with his own money. How do you know? he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, I guess, is in the money-making business,'' said
Andrade. ``But, for all those guys there are hundreds of thousands
of kids who keep them for themselves; that's what I look at. When I
was a kid, to get an autograph from someone, whether it was Ernie
DiGregorio or John Havlicek _ that was something I treasured.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade is pretty much the rule out on Tour, for he signs
autographs all the time. ``I like to do it,'' he said. ``It helps
you blow off some steam if you've had a bad day. Arnold Palmer
never seemed to have a problem signing autographs. He's the guy we
all look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   And most follow Palmer's lead, particularly during practice
rounds. Once the event starts, fans are asked to not to seek
autographs, at least until after a player has finished his round.
You would be hard-pressed to find Tour players who routinely refuse
to sign, but more and more of them are wary about what they are
signing and for whom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Combs is senior vice president of public relations and
communications for the PGA Tour. He said Tour officials are aware
of the situation that has some players concerned, that collectors
are after autographs on items that can be then sold for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the back of a ticket to a PGA Tour event, he said.
That's where you find this warning: ``Soliciting autographs from
the professionals with the intent to sell is prohibited and grounds
for removal from the property at the sole discretion of the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, is trying to distinguish between
legitimate, eager youngsters, and overbearing, profit-minded
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make our tournaments an enjoyable atmosphere
with players signing as they are used to. It is part of Tour
tradition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Tour is not actively seeking out the professional
collectors, ``the players and their caddies have become pretty
adept at picking them out,'' said Combs.
</P>
<P>
   And when they have been caught, they have been asked to leave.
``Some of the tournaments have been very good at throwing those
guys out,'' said Love.
</P>
<P>
   Players have also been very good at taking measures to combat
the problem. Tiger Woods, for instance, said he tries to autograph
items personally, asking youngsters for their names, a move that
reportedly cuts down on the value.
</P>
<P>
   It's a valiant effort, but when the youngsters come rushing _
and they do when Woods is the target _ it is very hard for him to
stop and put down a personal greeting for every enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman talked to reporters about a method he has found
successful to discourage would-be collectors. Having been told that
collectors prefer black or blue markers, Lehman carries green and
orange Sharpies, which is the marker of choice with PGA Tour
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, `Please, Mr. Lehman, can you use this black pen?'
'' while handing him a black pen. ``I'll say, `Sorry, but today is
green day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What it is, said many PGA Tour players, is a sad day when they
have to screen autograph-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the same three photos of me for a while now,'' said
Brad Faxon. ``On the one hand, I think it's cool to sign something
like that. But on the other, I hate to think I'm helping someone
make money with them. It's a tough call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1555EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
