<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-FINALFOUR-BOS &LR;      03-30 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINALFOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS HAVE TIES TO HOST CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There's no question fans represent the sixth
player. But the question this weekend is for whom will they cheer?
</P>
<P>
   The teams in the NCAA women's Final Four at the First Union
Center are filled with Philadelphia connections.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers will face Tennessee in the opening game Friday, followed
by the University of Connecticut against Penn State. Three of the
four coaches spent time in the area, and more than a handful of
players have local ties.?
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, located about 200 miles away, boasts forward Rashana
Barnes and center Amanda Garner, who grew up in Philadelphia. Coach
Rene Portland is a native of Broomall, a suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UConn coach Geno Auriemma, who grew up in nearby
Norristown, started his collegiate coaching career at St. Joseph's.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Pat Summitt can't boast of any local ties, but
her players can. Center Kristen Clement grew up in Broomall, and
teammate Tamika Catchings's father, Harvey, played for the
Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   And there are bound to be cheers for Rutgers, which is just two
hours up the New Jersey Turnpike and has senior guard Shawnetta
Stewart, a former star at Philadelphia's University High.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Rutgers' coach, C. Vivian Stringer, who first
coached college basketball at Cheyney State, and remains good
friends with John Cheney, the former men's coach at Cheyney and
current coach at Temple.
</P>
<P>
   So when the games tap off, the cheers might be confusing as fans
try to figure out whether to root for the team with the best stats
or best local ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
