<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SAUDI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI ABUSES UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amnesty International's latest report, ``Saudi Arabia: A Secret
State of Suffering,'' merits attention, particularly from
Americans. The report's descriptions of systematic human rights
abuses in Saudi Arabia are no more repugnant than the horrors
perpetrated in some other countries, but what makes the Saudi
monarchy a special case for Americans is its status as an ally of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi royal family has been able to veil from American eyes
the endemic injustices of its justice system. For a long time,
Americans have heard only occasional, isolated accounts of forced
confessions, torture, flogging, amputations, and the execution of
accused criminals and dissidents who are deprived of the right to a
fair trial that Americans often take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The Amnesty report draws on testimony from foreign nationals who
survived unimaginable cruelties at the hands of Saudi authorities
and were eventually able to leave the country. Saudis who suffer
human rights violations at the hands of the state rarely manage to
obtain a passport to travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the human rights organization has been able to
conduct interviews and documentary research over 20 years,
compiling a report that depicts unjust, discriminatory treatment of
defenseless foreign workers, members of the Shiite Muslim minority,
and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saudi Arabian government spares no effort to keep its
appalling human rights record a secret, and other governments have
shown themselves more than willing to help maintain the secrecy,''
the Amnesty report observes in what may be its most damning
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   If the concept of human rights is to have real meaning, there
can be no double standards for allies, clients, or crucial oil
producers. The public relations firms and lobbyists hired by the
Saudi government _ and named by Amnesty _ should not be able to
hide the truth about the kingdom. Precisely because the Saudi
rulers are allies of Washington, America has an obligation to
demand that discriminatory laws, arbitrary arrests, torture, and
executions without a fair trial are abolished in the kingdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1558EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
