<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DOG-TREATS-ART-BOS &LR;      03-30 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-TREATS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DOT-COM, NO; DOG-COM, YES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLYOKE, Mass. _ Ah, yes. Two fresh-faced 20-somethings launch a
dot-com start-up, grind away on a couple of PCs in the garage for a
while, latch onto a few million bucks of venture capital, do a
hotly anticipated IPO, get themselves listed on the Nasdaq, sift
through a batch of buyout offers, and blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   But wait.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie and Kara Healy are peddling real stuff that you can hold
in your hands. And they began with a pair of cookie ovens in their
grandparents' basement here. And they borrowed the better part of
their $40,000 start-up stash from their parents. And they talk
about owning their thriving little two-woman dog-biscuit company,
like, beyond the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   How refreshingly retro. Or as 27-year-old Debbie Healy puts it,
sounding surprised herself: ``We're in a business where you
actually make money when people buy the product, not when you go
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but doggie treats?
</P>
<P>
   Yes: silver-dollar-sized Hi5 Biscuits!, turned out in four
flavors and with no additives, originally concocted from stuff that
Healy and her younger sister, 25-year-old Kara, found around the
kitchen. ``These are something people can actually eat,'' Kara
Healy effuses, although it was the enthusiasm of the family's
chocolate Labrador retriever, Stel (short for Amstel, as in the
beer) that sparked the birth of the boutique biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Healy sisters are both former college English
majors _ Debbie at Dartmouth, Kara at Providence _ who never
cracked a business textbook, their projections tell them that
America's dogs will lap up some $500,000 worth of Hi5s this year.
That still makes them a minuscule pet supplier, but they impressed
Stop &AMP; Shop enough last year that the supermarket chain added their
canine niblets to the shelves of 168 of its 202 stores. Small
wonder that the sisters are smiling widely in the picture that
appears, Ben-and-Jerry-like, on the back of each 12-ounce, $2.99
package of Cheasy Pleasy, Nuddy Buddy, Papa Stel, and Original
Flavor.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Stel's photo that fittingly adorns the front of the
Hi5 Biscuits! bags. In 1996, the Healy sisters cooked up a batch of
snacks for the family dog because they and their mother, Gloria
Healy, didn't much care for the ingredients found in most dog
snacks. ``If you read a label in a typical bag of treats, you can't
figure out what's inside. You need a dictionary and a thesaurus,''
Debbie Healy contends, referring to the likes of ethylenediamine
dihydriodide or sodium metabisulfite. At the time, Debbie Healy was
a would-be professional tennis player who was recovering from
shoulder surgery here in her hometown. Her sister was still in
college. Stel, at 100 pounds, was simply hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the first batch of a dozen or so biscuits was
undercooked. ``Stel was so pumped he almost bit my hand,'' Debbie
recalls. ``We knew we were onto something.'' Soon, her plans to
attend law school were put on hold. So was Kara's notion of
becoming an elementary school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the sisters purchased two large stainless-steel
commercial cookie ovens and placed them atop cinder blocks in the
basement of the modest three-bedroom ranch home owned by their
grandparents, Therese and Ervin Holbrook. The neon-lit room had
served as their parents' living room for two winters during the
early 1970s. (Their father, Fran Healy, was a journeyman major
league catcher for nine seasons and is now a television broadcaster
for the New York Mets.) Making dog biscuits by hand, with rolling
pins and cookie cutters, turned out to be hard, hot work. Sore
shoulders and swollen hands were common. ``At least we got a good
upper-body workout,'' muses Gloria Healy, who pitched in. A
200-pound batch of biscuits required five hours of baking.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hi5 Biscuits! began turning up in small grocery
and pet stores from Massachusetts to New Jersey. Daniel Strum, the
owner of a meat market and deli located about a half-mile from the
two busy ovens, was an early buyer. ``Sales were slow at the
beginning,'' Strum says. ``I sold maybe 18 bags every six months.
Now I'm doing 30 or 40 a week. I've got people who come in for dog
biscuits and don't even want a steak or hamburger.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning out biscuits as fast as they could while making
deliveries to 200 stores, Debbie and Kara found by 1997 that they
couldn't expand any further. What's more, ``it wasn't fun,'' Debbie
recalls. ``We were completely held up, stuck in the basement,
trying to figure out how to increase capacity. That's why most
businesses fail: They can't keep up with demand.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of searching and researching, the sisters last
August contracted with a commercial baker on Boston's South Shore.
Now, they say, the company is turning out 30,000 to 40,000 pounds
of product per month. The business is expanding again. And the
Healys are no longer working the basement shift. Indeed, they're
completely free of their baking chores, able to market, sell, and
hand out samples to likely looking prospects. ``If I'm waiting in
line at the bank, I'm always asking people, `Do you have a dog?' ''
Kara Healy says.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters live together in a rented apartment in Boston,
although there's still an office in the basement here. ``But our
main offices are our cars,'' Debbie Healy points out, referring to
the two well-aged Saabs that are stuffed with papers, boxes, and
even clothes. ``We're working longer hours, seven days a week. But
it's more fun now.'' And Hi5 Biscuits! has reached the break-even
point, the sisters say.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly untrained in business, the duo is nevertheless
nothing if not businesslike. ``They're very determined people,''
says their mother, who still helps with paperwork. ``Even as young
children, they were independent and self-disciplined. So we had no
doubts about financing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie and Kara Healy dream of Hi5 Biscuits! eventually becoming
a household name, despite the fact that they're competing with such
corporate names as Ralston Purina, Heinz, and Nabisco. (Nabisco
produces roughly as many pounds of its Milk-Bone dog biscuits and
other snacks in a day as the Healys will during this entire year.)
``We want to be carried in every store in the country,'' Kara Healy
says. To that end, they are looking for an infusion of additional
capital _ more real stuff that you can hold in your hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
