<HEADER>
A2421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-30 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF POSSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You know what potential means? Potential means you haven't
done a damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, New York Jets &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells may know football. But with his hard-nosed
attitude he would be lost in today's stock market, especially the
technology end of the market.
</P>
<P>
   To tech fans, potential is everything. A company with potential
might become the next Cisco or Microsoft. The fact that a company
``hasn't done a damn thing'' is not a handicap. It is an advantage.
As Michael Lewis put it in his bestseller on Silicon Valley, ``The
New New Thing,`` ``The most appealing companies are those in a
state of pure possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are investors so willing to believe companies with no track
record are capable of such amazing things? And what would it take
for the market to take off its rose-colored glasses and adopt a
more ``Parcellian'' view of the world?
</P>
<P>
   We plan to answer both those questions. But first it's worth
taking a minute to show just how optimistic technology investors
actually are.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to do that is to look at some tech stocks and
calculate their price/sales ratio. You can't use earnings because
many of these companies aren't yet profitable. You arrive at the
ratio by taking a firm's market value and dividing it by annual
sales. In other words, if a company has a market value of $10
million and $10 million of sales, its price/sales ratio is 1.
</P>
<P>
   A high price/sales ratio indicates a business that is valued on
its potential. In effect, investors are saying: I know you haven't
done much yet, but I am confident you are going to do great things
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The price/sales ratio of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is about 2.
Gillette, a successful old-economy company, trades at a price/sales
ratio of 3. EMC, the data storage giant, has a price/sales ratio of
20.
</P>
<P>
   When you move to some of the newer companies, the ratios jump
off the chart. Before Wednesday's tech selloff _ the Nasdaq fell 4
percent _ Navisite, a start-up, had a price/sales ratio of 136;
Sycamore Networks, a telecom company, 300; Akamai Technologies, a
maker of Internet infrastructure, 1,740.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai had $2.7 million in sales in its most recent quarter.
When the market closed Tuesday, Akamai had a market value of $19
billion. Take that, Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the bullishness is clear: people are infatuated
with technology. ``Technology is making astronomical changes in the
way we live our lives,'' said Brian Grove, who manages a technology
mutual fund for Vaughan Nelson in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is allowing businesses to cut their costs
dramatically, even in old economy fields like steel and
automobiles. Consumers can buy stocks and books over the Internet
and they imagine the day when they will be able to do much more
with their computers and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Weiss, chief of equities at State Street Research, points
out another reason for the enthusiasm about technology: a growing
belief that businesses around the world will have to keep investing
in technology in any kind of economic climate. ``The use of
technology will grow as far as the eye can see,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have grasped that. They also have seen enough bona
fide success stories to know that great things are possible. A
dollar invested in EMC in 1990 was worth more than $800 at the
beginning of this year. All you have to do is find the next EMC and
bingo, you've got it made.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem: there aren't going to be that many
EMCs. The attrition rate in high technology has always been
enormous and there is no reason to think that has changed. In fact,
the failure rate could be higher this time around because Wall
Street has funded so many direct competitors in so many different
niches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outright failures by some of the high fliers could puncture
investors' confidence,'' said Maureen Allyn, chief economist at
Scudder Kemper Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Selectively, there is already some evidence of that happening.
Many e-retailing stocks that were so hot just last year have
already lost 50 percent to 60 percent of their value. The stock
price of MicroStrategy, a high-profile software company, fell 62
percent one day last week after the firm was forced to restate its
financial results for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Which group will get hit next? Will it be the auction companies,
the business-to-business providers, the Internet infrastructure
firms? Who knows? But logic suggests more disappointments are on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   As Parcells understands, it is great to have potential, but
eventually you have to get out on the field and show the world what
you've got. A few players with potential actually become
superstars; others turn out to be busts; still others wind up
somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same way with stocks. Over time potential will give
way to performance. When that happens, look for some of those
price/sales ratios to come back to earth.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1601EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TAMMYFAYE-FILM-REVIEW     03-30 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMYFAYE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EYES OF TAMMY FAYE': A TELEVANGELIST NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tammy Faye Bakker Messner, the former wife of Jim
Bakker, is that most American of stories, a figure of tragedy and a
joke. It doesn't help that her face suggests what would happen if
the masks of comedy and tragedy were tossed into a microwave oven
and nuked into a colorful blur. The documentary ``The Eyes of Tammy
Faye'' walks us through her life, a veritable catalog of bad
marriages, lost televangelist empires, squandered relationships
with children and, despite it all, Messner's indomitable optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The framing device _ each segment is introduced by hand puppets,
echoing the chapters of the children's movie ``Babe'' _ goes a mite
too far. (The puppets were probably used because Messner loves them
and started her television career turning the tops of bubble-bath
bottles into them.) Any movie with narration by RuPaul Charles
hardly needs an extra ladle of camp; it's already swimming in it.
As is so much of Messner's own story _ her life could have been
written by Danielle Steel and directed by Rainer Werner Fassbinder,
with makeup tips courtesy of Sears Best Latex. No wonder she's the
patron saint of drag queens everywhere. She spills her biography
with the same waves of determination, honesty and glitter that made
her such a compelling television personality.
</P>
<P>
   She falls in love with, and endures, a loveless marriage with
the boy wonder television religious personality Jim Bakker, perhaps
the one person who could burst into tears almost as quickly as she.
Between them, they create and are forced out of two television
ministries, the most notorious of which results in Bakker's 1989
conviction for defrauding his followers of millions of dollars.
Although she tearfully stands by her man during the trial, she
divorces him three years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' is taken with its protagonist, a
woman who made a career of living out every single moment of her
life _ she is the most compelling character to apply makeup with a
spatula who ever stepped in front of a camera.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary goes through her life a like a series of amiable
flash cards. Anyone who saw her on ``The PTL Club'' or ``The 700
Club'' _ deep-fried exhibitionism at its most extreme _ probably
was transfixed by her exhausting spectacle. It's why all of the
attempts to parody the Bakkers never quite worked, because no one
captured them accurately. They weren't bland and polyester like the
Osmonds, the other squeaky-clean icons of the era. The good
old-fashioned poor-folk anguish that poured from the television
screen _ Messner erased her past face with an airbrush _ was an
all-new breed of extemporaneous biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tammy Faye,'' which will be shown Friday night and Sunday at
the New Directors/New Films festival at the Museum of Modern Art in
Manhattan, cries out for a little more analysis of its subject.
Instead, it joyfully wallows in the backdraft of her excesses,
trailing her as she visits a network to pitch a talk show in which
she would chat with teen-agers, aided by puppets, and shows off her
collection of dolls, all of which feature round cheeks and frozen
smiles frighteningly similar to her own.
</P>
<P>
   The directors, Fenton Bailey and Randy Barbato, are awfully
quick to forgive Tammy Faye's lack of self-awareness, possibly
because she has a heart as big as her hair. She was one of the
first in the televangelist crowd to accept gay men with AIDS. The
movie makes a case for her because she's a survivor; it's more of a
mash note than a formal documentary, and there's nothing wrong with
that.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE EYES OF TAMMY FAYE'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Fenton Bailey and Randy Barbato;
director of photography, Sandra Chandler; edited by Paul Wiesepape;
music by Jim Harry; released by Lions Gate Films. Running time: 79
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Tammy Faye Bakker Messner, Roe Messner, Jim Bakker, the
Rev. Mel White, Pat Boone, Tammy Sue Bakker Chapman, Steven Chao,
Jim J. Bullock, Roseanne, Greg Gorman, Charles Sheperd, James
Albert and RuPaul Charles (narrator).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-CONTENT31-COX     03-30 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONTENT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEX, BAD LANGUAGE MORE PREVALENT IN PRIME TIME, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    With TV-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sexual content and offensive language are far more
common on prime-time television programs than they were a decade
ago, a media watchdog group reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings show that broadcasters have neglected their
responsibilities and violated the public trust by abandoning
minimum standards for content, said L. Brent Bozell, chairman of
Parents Television Council, the Virginia-based organization that
conducted the study.
</P>
<P>
   The group studied the first four weeks of prime-time programming
in the 1989-90 and 1999-00 television seasons and recorded
instances of sexual content, foul language and violence.
</P>
<P>
   It found that on average, sexual content appeared more than
three times as often in the 1999-00 season.
</P>
<P>
   Oral sex, never mentioned during the four weeks of study in
1989, was alluded to 20 times in 1999, the study found.
Homosexuality was mentioned 24 times more than in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Foul language was heard more than four times as often as in
1989-90, while violent content actually declined slightly, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that UPN dethroned ABC as the raunchiest
network.
</P>
<P>
   Several UPN programs were aimed at children, the group said. For
example, the World Wrestling Federation Federation's ``Smackdown!''
aired by UPN, has one of the highest rates of offensive material,
making up more than 11 percent of the combined sex, cursing and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The program is viewed by an estimated 3 million children under
the age of 18, half of whom are between the ages of two and 11,
Bozell said.
</P>
<P>
   UPN officials did not respond to a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress said such televised material was
contributing to the nation's moral decay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we are in a time when more than a million
teens are having children each year,'' said Sen. Joe Lieberman,
D-Conn. ``I'm not blaming television, but television (executives)
too often portray sex as just a joke or as any casual form of
recreational behavior without consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., said ``I think it is now time, with
studies like this, for the (Federal Communications Commission) and
Congress to step up and determine whether the public interest is
being met'' by television executives. He said an April 25
congressional hearing would address both the findings of the study
and the state of television.
</P>
<P>
   Television pioneer Steve Allen, who appeared at a news
conference releasing the report along with the senators, said,
``The time has come for these multibillion-dollar industries to
recognize that the values expressed in the programs they air and
sponsor are being perceived as their value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They must ask themselves, 'do they wish to be associated with
quality entertainment to be enjoyed by all, or do they wish to
increasingly be seen as marketers of vulgarity and violence?' `` he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said one solution for parents is to ``raise hell very
outspokenly.'' Bozell suggested that parents of the 48 percent of
American children who have television in their bedrooms remove
them.
</P>
<P>
   Bozell also suggested that parents boycott businesses that spent
$47.5 billion in 1998 to advertise on the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
