<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-CUSACK-TEX     03-30 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CUSACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TEEN STAR JOHN CUSACK FINDS HIS OWN GROOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the most indelible images of youth-oriented 1980s
movies: The summer after high school graduation, a forlorn-looking
young man stands in the humidity of a damp Seattle summer morn,
holding a boombox over his head as it blasts a melancholy serenade
of Peter Gabriel's ``In Your Eyes'' to the girl who had just broken
up with him.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1989's ``Say Anything ...,'' in which John Cusack
played Lloyd Dobler, an aspiring kickboxer whose pursuit of the
smartest girl in school resulted in one of the movies' most
realistic depictions of teen romance. Eleven years later, Cusack is
still plying women with music, this time in ``High Fidelity,''
opening this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the new movie, Cusack plays Rob Gordon, a list-obsessed
Chicago used-record store owner with women problems. The book is
based on a comic novel by Nick Hornby, and Cusack says that he can
relate ``100 percent'' to the lead character's fascinations and
frustrations. But then, he doesn't think he's alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people who read the book or see the movie can
say, `Oh, yeah, that's me. I'm Rob,' '' Cusack says during a phone
interview. ``Most of 'em can; they might not want to admit it, but
they all feel like they can relate to the character.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us can relate more than others. Rob's life is dominated
by pop music and record collecting (vinyl only, please), which he
encapsulates into lists such as Top Five Opening Tracks. Music is
so much a part of Rob's experience that at one point, he tries to
rearrange his album collection in autobiographical order _ by which
records apply to certain people in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack co-wrote the screenplay, faithfully adapting Hornby's
book and handling the first-person narration by having Rob
continually address the camera, as if in conversation with the
audience. The only major change the writers made was the setting,
which is switched from London to Cusack's hometown of Chicago.
Although the change of scenery removes a bit of the book's British
snottiness, Cusack says he doesn't think the location was
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that are most interesting about the book had
nothing to do with London,'' Cusack says. ``They had to do with
people's love affair with pop music, and how they use music
autobiographically, and they sort of live through the poetry of
other people to find themselves. And men's relationship to women,
and men's relationships to themselves _ all that sort of
male-confessional aspect to the book that made it a bestseller.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack is surprised to hear the movie described as offbeat,
although the loose plot and camera-addressing narration don't
exactly scream commerciality. But the movie does have a lot of
audience-friendly humor, and it's certainly less offbeat than some
of Cusack's recent work. The 33-year-old actor's major 1999
projects, the air-traffic-controller comedy-drama ``Pushing Tin''
and the surreal celebrity satire ``Being John Malkovich'' helped
boost the perception of Cusack as a risk-taker who avoids the
Hollywood mainstream. He enhances that image, perhaps
unintentionally, by staying rooted in Chicago, where he remains
active in theater as well as movies.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack wasn't always considered a maverick. He rose through
commercial movies such as 1983's ``Class,'' in which he made his
film debut, and John Hughes' ``Sixteen Candles.'' Yet even in the
'80s, Cusack was set off a bit from the Brat Pack, playing pining
but sensitive teen-agers in such comedies as ``The Sure Thing,''
``Better Off Dead'' and ``One Crazy Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Say Anything ...'' rolled around, he had attracted
the attention of such directors as ``Eight Men Out's'' John Sayles
and ``The Grifters''' Stephen Frears, who also directed ``High
Fidelity.'' Although he occasionally indulges in a highly
commercial project such as 1997's ``Con Air,'' he's more likely to
pop up in a Woody Allen movie or an ensemble project such as friend
Tim Robbins' ``Cradle Will Rock,'' movies that have kept him from
the TV destiny of most of his '80s peers.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's screen persona has a hyper side, but he sounded more
reserved in this interview. Perhaps because he prefers dark
clothing and a trademark trenchcoat, he has even been described as
brooding, which mystifies him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why people think I'm brooding,'' he says. ``Maybe
it's because when interviewers come to do me and they want to take
photographs, they're such silly photographs, I don't feel like I'm
in the mood. And maybe it's because I don't talk about certain
things in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``High Fidelity's'' open-book Rob, Cusack doesn't let on
much about his personal life. He's been linked with such actresses
as his ``Grosse Pointe Blank'' co-star Minnie Driver, who
coincidentally stars in an upcoming Chicago-filmed movie, ``Return
to Me.'' But he tends to be reticent about his personal life, which
has led writers to draw other conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I'm private, but that's just because I don't talk
about everybody I date,'' Cusack says. ``And they think that means
I'm intensely private _ that means you're sane. So I don't really
understand any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
