A2431 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ELDORADO-TEX     03-30 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ELDORADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `ROAD' IS PAVED WITH FOOL'S GOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one point during DreamWorks' new animated film ``The Road to
El Dorado,'' one of the heroes comments, ``This city is full of
suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the filmmakers had the same contempt for their
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Shoddy storytelling, questionable racial politics and one of the
worst sets of songs Elton John and Tim Rice have ever cooked up
come together in a film that proves that all that glitters is not
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``El Dorado'' has any shortage of glitz. It's a
visually impressive picture with rich, colorful backdrops and nice
animated effects work, and the cartoon leads are good-looking, if a
bit too reminiscent of the wannabe-Disney school of character
design.
</P>
<P>
   But a pretty picture isn't necessarily a good picture, and it
doesn't take much digging to dull the film's shine.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kline and Kenneth Branagh give voice to Tulio and Miguel,
a pair of Spanish con artists (with American and British accents,
no less) who find themselves unexpectedly ocean-bound for the New
World. With the help of an ill-gotten treasure map, the two set off
for the legendary city of gold, El Dorado.
</P>
<P>
   Following the map's various landmarks, they eventually arrive at
a dead end. But when a slinky native girl called Chel (Rosie Perez)
is captured in front of them by a group of hulking warriors, the
three are led to the magnificent golden city.
</P>
<P>
   Their odd dress, as well as their penchant for riding horseback,
inevitably leads to their being mistaken for gods, and when the
con-men duo gets a look at the kind of riches on hand, they're more
than happy to play the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Temple priest Tzekel-Kan (Armand Assante) is eager to goad the
two into demanding human sacrifice, while the town's chief (Edward
James Olmos) would rather ply them with gifts and festivities.
Chel, on the other hand, just wants a piece of the action and is
willing to do just about anything to get it.
</P>
<P>
   As Tulio falls for Chel and Miguel falls for El Dorado, they get
lax in their godly demeanor, drawing the suspicion of Tzekel-Kan.
But when the priest's evil plans are thwarted by our heroes, he
finds an unlikely ally in the wicked explorer Cortez _ who's been
tracking the pair since they stowed away on his ship _ and decides
to lead his armies right to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Peppered throughout are a series of forgettable Elton John/Tim
Rice ditties that succeed neither as catchy pop songs nor as
effective story devices _ a cardinal sin in the cartoon musical
genre.
</P>
<P>
   When executive producer Jeffrey Katzenberg was at Disney, he
built a reputation for being the mastermind behind the studio's
strong foundation of solid storytelling and the driving force
behind the success of ``The Little Mermaid,'' ``Beauty and the
Beast'' and ``The Lion King.'' With DreamWorks' first animated
feature, ``The Prince of Egypt,'' he went to great pains to ensure
that his fledgling studio's animated retelling of the story of
Exodus treated the subject matter with appropriate reverence.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened here? ``El Dorado's'' storyline pirates from
everything from ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' to ``Raiders
of the Lost Ark,'' and the film's slipshod approach to historical
accuracy and its rather queasy portrayal of native stereotypes has
already drawn an outcry from Mexican and Central American groups.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such criticism is written off as nitpicking or as an
attack on racism remains to be debated, but right now, ``The Road
to El Dorado's'' biggest crime is that it isn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Road to El Dorado''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Eric Bergeron, Don Paul
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Voices of Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh
</P>
<P>
   Length: 83 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ a brief skinny-dipping scene and sexual references
that might catch unsuspecting parents off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
