<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2432 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-SHANEWEST-TEX     03-30 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHANEWEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD TEEN SHANE WEST IS READY FOR GROWN-UP ROLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shane West is a 21-year-old who plays teen-agers, but he isn't
exactly what you'd call a teen star. His highest-profile role to
date is on an adult drama: He plays Eli, the popular but
academically troubled son of a single father on ABC's
divorce-romance series ``Once and Again.'' But unlike other actors
in his age group, such as WB stars Joshua Jackson, James Van Der
Beek and Sarah Michelle Gellar, West still lives a normal life.
Well, relatively normal, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird to watch the show and know that I got invited to
the Golden Globes and got to sit with the cast _ and to get
nominated, that's weird,'' West says during a Dallas stop. ``But
the show isn't exactly like a `Popular' or a `Roswell' or `Dawson's
Creek.' I don't think all the teen-agers watch this show, so I get
recognized more by adults.''
</P>
<P>
   West, sporting an incipient goatee that can't quite mask his
baby face, is in town to plug his new movie, ``Whatever It Takes,''
which is the highest-profile teen-oriented project he's done. But
again, ``high-profile'' is a relative term _ the movie, a comedy
very loosely inspired by ``Cyrano de Bergerac,'' opened last Friday
to mostly withering reviews and tepid box office. Some critics even
indicated that this movie could signal an end to the teen-movie
craze of the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Whatever It Takes,'' West plays Ryan, a nice guy with a shy
streak and a major crush on the most popular girl in school (played
by Jodi Lyn O'Keefe). One of the school jocks (James Franco), aware
of Ryan's plight, offers him a deal: He'll help Ryan win the
popular girl if Ryan helps him score with Ryan's best buddy, the
equally noncomformist Maggie (Marla Sokoloff). Who really belongs
with whom is pretty obvious from the start, but West still enjoyed
the similarities between himself and Ryan _ and says he also shares
some traits with ``Once and Again's'' Eli.
</P>
<P>
   ``From sixth to 10th grade ... I was very shy; I didn't have
that many friends, I used to dream about being able to go out with
the most popular girl in school,'' he says. ``What happened in the
10th to 12th, I don't know _ I let my hair go, I stopped slicking
it to the side, (and) a senior just said she thought I was cute to
certain people, and you know how high school is, it spread like
wildfire. So the end of 10th grade to 12th grade I had, like,
joined the popular crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-screen, West isn't as concerned with popularity as with
having a steady career, and his acting goals have a Fort Worth
link: Cowtown native Bill Paxton, whom West often lists as his
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Paxton's been working for a long time, and his first big
role was in (1985's) `Weird Science,''' West says. ``I loved him in
that movie, and it was just somebody that I thought was a truly
interesting guy. So what I did was, I just started watching all the
movies he was in. And I was so happy for him ... that he finally
succeeded. Because he did so many movies and nobody knew about him,
or people always forget these great characters that he makes up.
And when he finally hit, I guess with `Apollo 13' giving them that
shot and then `Twister' and everything, I was just very happy for
him. So he's always been an inspiration for me, because it took me
2 1/2 years to get one part.''
</P>
<P>
   That part was in a Tom Hulce-directed LA stage production of
``The Cider House Rules,'' years before the movie. According to
West, the play was even more faithful to John Irving's book than
the Academy-Award nominated movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play was huge,'' West says. ``It was a two-nighter during
the week. And on Saturday and Sunday, it was like, all day. It was
like, the first half, then you go to lunch, do whatever you wanna
do, and come back later that day to finish the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   West has another thing in common with ``Whatever It Takes'''
Ryan: He's a musician. But Ryan's instrument of choice, accordion,
wouldn't necessarily fit into West's music of choice: punk. He says
his band, Average Joe _ which doesn't have anything recorded _ is
like Green Day or Blink 182, but a little bit more hard-core. Makes
sense for a guy whose musical taste is so old-school, most of his
favorite bands made their debuts before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised on the Clash and the Kinks and Zombies and Elvis
Costello, the Pretenders,'' he says. ``It's really hard to have my
friends listen to the Kinks, because no one can really get into
them now. At least, (people) my age can't.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
