<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-PRIVACY (Falls Church, Va.) _ Census Director Kenneth
Prewitt, combating complaints that the Census Bureau's
questionnaire is so intrusive it ought to be ignored, urges
Americans to follow the law and answer the questionnaires sent to
120 million households. Prewitt stages his appeal at a fire station
in suburban Washington where the fire and rescue squad relies on
extensive information gathered by the Census to plan its spending
to respond to 80,000 calls a year. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-HAIL (Fort Worth, Texas) _ One of those killed by
Tuesday night's tornado in Fort Worth was a man who was hit in the
head by a softball-sized hailstone flying through the air at 100
mph. Such a death is highly unusual, meteorology experts say.
``There were only two deaths by direct hail strikes reported in the
20th century'' in the United States, says one Texas meteorology
professor and storm expert. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS-FUNERAL (Eagle Pass, Texas) _ As funerals go, the one
observed outside the U.S. Customs Service Canine Enforcement
Section kennels was short and to the point, but not without pathos.
Agents from the U.S. and Mexican customs agencies held a service,
complete with seven-gun honor guard, to bury Hamlet, a
four-year-old canine officer who died of cancer. By JOHN
MacCORMACK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ A U.S. lawyer plans to submit a visa
application so the father of Elian Gonzalez can come to the United
States to gain custody of the boy, who has been caught in a
four-month international custody battle. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno calls for
calm in Miami's Cuban-American community but refuses to back away
from her decision to return Elian Gonzalez to Cuba and his father.
In Miami, Immigration and Naturalization Service officials continue
their negotiations with Elian's relatives over the fate of the
6-year-old boy, whose mother and 10 others died when their boat
sank as they tried to flee to the United States last November. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-TAX (Washington) _ The Senate turns aside Majority Leader
Trent Lott's effort to repeal the 4.3-cent-a-gallon gas tax.
Republicans split on the issue. By GREG MCDONALD
</P>
<P>
   VENTURA-CHINA (Washington) _ Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura urges
Congress not only to approve China's entry into the World Trade
Organization but also to allow the United States to resume trade
with Cuba. His proposals come in testimony before the House Ways
and Means Committee. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (Washington) _ The Justice Department gives the
go-ahead for the Hearst Corporation to acquire the San Francisco
Chronicle and sell the Hearst-owned San Francisco Examiner. The
decision removes a major obstacle to the transaction that was
announced last August when the family that owned Chronicle agreed
to sell to Hearst. By the Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
