<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OATES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     03-30 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OATES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLONDE': DARKENING THE DREAM GIRL'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Marilyn. During her short, nervous life, she was abandoned
by her father, her mother and countless men. Her marriages all
ended in divorce; and after numerous abortions, her efforts to have
a child ended in a miscarriage. Though she wanted, more than
anything, to be taken seriously as an actress, she was relentlessly
promoted by Hollywood as a bubble-headed bimbo: the quintessential
dumb blonde.
</P>
<P>
   Since her death at 36 in 1962, the exploitation has continued.
She has been commodified by sleaze merchants and deconstructed by
academics. Her life has been pawed over by conspiracy theorists and
sifted by scandal mongers; her image, appropriated by Madonna and
dissected by everyone from Norman Mailer to Gloria Steinem.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes along Joyce Carol Oates to turn Marilyn's life into
the book equivalent of a tacky television miniseries. In
``Blonde,'' she does to Monroe what she did to Edward M. Kennedy in
``Black Water,'' her embarrassing 1992 fictionalization of
Chappaquiddick, playing to readers' voyeuristic interest in a
real-life story while using the liberties of a novel to tart up the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has concocted bad, sentimental poems and attributed them
to Monroe, even invented books the actress supposedly read. Worse,
lovers, foster parents, suicide attempts and abortions have been
conflated, and some of the central people in her life have been
given new identities: her first husband, James Dougherty, has been
transformed into someone named Bucky Glazer; her acting mentor Lee
Strasberg into a Max Pearlman.
</P>
<P>
   Other players in Monroe's life have been given generic,
fairy-tale names: Joe DiMaggio becomes ``the Ex-Athlete''; Arthur
Miller, ``the Playwright''; President John F. Kennedy, ``the
Prince''; and his brother-in-law Peter Lawford, ``the President's
Pimp.'' As for Monroe herself, she is variously referred to as
``the Blond Actress,'' ``the Girl Upstairs,'' the ``Fair Princess''
and ``Golden Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt these nicknames are meant as a hedge against possible
lawsuits or charges of defamation, but they're also meant to lend
the novel the mythic power of fable. In practice, however, they
simply point up Oates' tendency, in these pages, to turn her
characters into stereotypes: predictable morality-play figures,
smelling of cardboard and paste.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the novel's men are made to play the role of faceless
authority figures: Daddy substitutes who try to stage-manage the
actress' life. Such controlling men, of course, figure prominently
in the author's earlier fiction, and in this novel Monroe, too,
conforms to a familiar Oatesian pattern. Like Enid in ``You Must
Remember This'' and Ingrid in ``Man Crazy,'' she is another
strangely passive girl whose emotional neediness makes her a magnet
for destruction, a love-starved survivor of a dysfunctional
childhood in thrall to the specter of an unavailable man.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the earlier portions of ``Blonde,'' where Oates is
describing the young Norma Jeane's coming of age, are the most
persuasive part of this book: she depicts the fatherless girl _ who
would end up in an orphanage after her emotionally unstable mother
was hospitalized _ much the way she has depicted so many of her
more successfully realized heroines, filling in the melodramatic
arc of their stories with myriad psychological and domestic
details.
</P>
<P>
   When Norma Jeane Baker becomes the Marilyn Monroe we know from
movies and news accounts, however, a note of crude voyeurism creeps
into the book's narration, and we begin to wonder just how much
Oates has made up for the mercenary purpose of sensationalizing her
story.
</P>
<P>
   Was President Kennedy's cruel rejection of the actress after a
New York liaison really the catalyst for her accelerating slide
into despair, as Oates suggests? Did the Ex-Athlete really strike
Monroe, as Oates writes? Did Monroe really have a longstanding
menage a trois with Charlie Chaplin Jr. and Edward G. Robinson Jr.,
as Oates describes?
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the reader is even made to consider such questions
underscores the smarmy tone of the second half of this book. Oates
gives us pages and pages in which she imagines the graphic sexual
details of Monroe's relationship with lovers like President
Kennedy, and pages and pages of the sort of heavy-breathing,
romance-novel prose one would think beneath a writer of her
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has Monroe thinking that ``her womb was poisoned, &AMP; her
soul'': ``She knew she did not deserve life as others deserve life
&AMP; though she had tried, she had failed to justify her life; yet
must continue to try, for her heart was hopeful, she meant to be
good!'' She has President Kennedy tell the actress that she's
``alive to be touched'': ``To be breathed on like a flame. Alive to
be hurt, even!'' And she has the Playwright thinking that Monroe's
love ``could justify his existence as a playwright and as a man, or
it could destroy him.''
</P>
<P>
   These clumsy attempts to channel her characters' most intimate
thoughts, like her embroidering of already melodramatic events,
cannot help but remind the reader of how shamelessly Oates is using
the life of Marilyn Monroe as a substitute for inventing an
original story, how shamelessly she is trying to cash in on her
subject's status as a legend. Though ``Blonde'' purports to reveal
``the inner, poetic, and spiritual life'' of the actress, it turns
out to be just the latest effort to exploit the tragedy and fame of
Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BLONDE'
</P>
<P>
   By Joyce Carol Oates
</P>
<P>
   738 pages. HarperCollins. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1622EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PRICE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRICE OF GLORY': SPARRING WITH DAD, IN AN OUT OF THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If observed life could be translated literally into art, the
world's museums, libraries and film archives would overflow with
classics.
</P>
<P>
   But gifted transmutation is required, and that element is
missing from ``Price of Glory,'' a film about a father's frustrated
dream and the havoc it wreaks on its family, all set against a
background of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by a feature-film novice, Carlos Avila, and written by
Phil Berger, who formerly covered boxing for The New York Times,
``Price of Glory'' aspires to float like a butterfly, sting like a
bee.
</P>
<P>
   Though clearly rooted in observed behavior of the monomaniacal
parents to be found venting their fury under the cover of love not
only around boxing rings but also around tennis courts, ice skating
rinks and baseball diamonds, ``Price of Glory'' plods when it
should dance and throws roundhouse rights when a crisp jab would
snap the viewer to attention. Not particularly well acted, it
overstays its welcome and proves simultaneously predictable as a
sports film and unconvincing as family drama.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Smits, out of ``L.A. Law'' and ``N.Y.P.D. Blue,'' stands
in one corner of the conflict in ``Price of Glory,'' and his
family, three boys and a loving wife, Rita, in the other.
</P>
<P>
   As Arturo Ortega, father and husband, he holds down a galling
but unseen assembly-line job, lives in an Arizona town on the
Mexican border and still seethes with the memory of his promising
boxing career, destroyed when he was overmatched by a traitorous
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo is determined to live out his dream of a championship
through his little boys Jimmy and Sonny. His youngest, Johnny,
seems focused on a future in football, and his wife, Rita (Maria
Del Mar), would like to see the boys go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy (as an adult played by Clifton Collins Jr.) and Sonny (Jon
Seda) have talent, but the surprise turns out to be Johnny (Ernesto
Hernandez), pressed into the ring in a Silver Gloves competition as
a peewee to substitute for a child who has come down with hives.
</P>
<P>
   As the years pass, Johnny turns out to be the gym rat with hands
of stone and a will to win who shares his father's singleminded
vision. Jimmy, no matter how hard he tries or how often he wins,
can never seem to earn Arturo's praise; and Sonny, who plans on
marriage to Mariella Cruz (Danielle Camastra), a teacher, is led to
understand in no uncertain terms that Arturo views domesticity as
an impediment to a championship.
</P>
<P>
   In its blunt way, ``Price of Glory'' makes clear that the
psychological toll on these two boys is more punishing than any
blows they may suffer in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   But intent on popular entertainment, the film is determined that
a chastened Arturo, who is not evil though seriously misguided,
will have a reward after all his tantrums, trophy tossings and
other lavish displays of dissatisfaction with his children.
</P>
<P>
   On the outskirts of this tale are Ron Perlman as Nick Everson,
the polished big-time promoter who controls access to the boastful
undefeated champion Davey Lane (Louis Mandylor) and a few goons.
</P>
<P>
   When the proud, mistrustful Arturo crosses Everson, the stage is
set for bloody conflict both in and out of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   In films, as in the ring, heart and will without exceptional
talent don't produce winners.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `PRICE OF GLORY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Carlos Avila; written by Phil Berger; director of
photography, Affonso Beato; edited by Gary Karr; music by Joseph
Julian Gonzalez; production designer, Robb Wilson King; produced by
Moctesuma Esparza, Robert Katz and Arthur E. Friedman; released by
New Line Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jimmy Smits (Arturo Ortega), Jon Seda (Sonny Ortega),
Clifton Collins Jr. (Jimmy Ortega), Maria Del Mar (Rita Ortega),
Sal Lopez (Hector Salmon), Louis Mandylor (Davey Lane), Danielle
Camastra (Mariella Cruz), Ernesto Hernandez (Johnny Ortega), Paul
Rodriguez (Pepe) and Ron Perlman (Nick Everson).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 100 minutes. ``Price of Glory' is rated PG-13
(parental guidance suggested). The story includes bloody boxing
scenes, a violent crime, the use of drugs and occasional strong
language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
