<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-DETERRENCE-TEX     03-30 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DETERRENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH APOLOGIES TO HIGH-SCHOOL DRAMA CLUBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a topsy-turvy pop-culture world when Aaron Sorkin, a guy
responsible for some pretty good movies, produces a quality
political drama (''The West Wing'') for TV while Rod Lurie, a film
critic who no doubt has weighed in on Sorkin's work, brings to
theaters a lame political drama called ``Deterrence,'' which
resembles an episode of ``The West Wing'' as produced by a
high-school drama club.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, that's not fair. Apologies to high-school drama clubs
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deterrence'' takes place in 2007, immediately providing us
with the news that none of this year's presidential candidates made
it to a second term. Instead, the much-loved 2004 electee has died,
leaving Vice President Walter Emerson (Kevin Pollak) in charge.
During a blizzard, Emerson, who is running for election, and his
entourage take refuge in a snowbound Colorado diner just in time to
hear the news that Iraq has invaded Kuwait _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson quickly considers dropping the big one on Baghdad, an
idea that sparks immediate second thoughts from his two top
advisers (Timothy Hutton and Sheryl Lee Ralph), as well as
engendering opinions from the motley group inside the diner. The
most left-field (although not left-wing) of these comes from a
working guy named Ralph (Sean Astin), who teaches the president a
lesson in racial epithets even as stunned African-American advisers
stand by _ never mind the fact that Lurie has provided no
indication of Ralph's racist thinking.
</P>
<P>
   But that's within the nature of his pompous script and haphazard
directing. The first mistake was casting the smirking Pollak _ who
looks like the lost Belushi brother _ as someone who gets elected
to office. You'd think a guy like Lurie, who has TV experience,
could execute this better. Instead, he adds his name to a list of
American critics-cum-filmmakers who should've stuck to their day
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Deterrence''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
