A2438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AUDITS31-COX     03-30 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDITS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNCLE SAM'S BOOKKEEPING STILL UNRELIABLE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only 13 of the federal government's 24 major
agencies have won a clean bill of health from auditors for their
1999 financial statements, Congress will be told on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the total included one more success than last year, the
results fell short of the Clinton administration's goal to have at
least 18 agencies with ``clean'' audits for the annual consolidated
financial statement.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report, only the third ever, is an attempt to match
the annual reports corporations give their shareholders. The
government's statement is scheduled to be released Friday before a
House Government Reform subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Among the problem areas cited by agency auditors:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Defense Department, the single biggest offender, lacks
documentation to verify almost $120 billion in military equipment
and property. The Pentagon also pays out millions of dollars
without proper bookkeeping. In a test of 345 transactions, the
Defense Finance and Accounting Service, based in Columbus, Ohio,
could not provide backup information for $149 million payments.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) reported
paying $935 million in excessive rent subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare disbursed $13.5 billion in overpayments for
fee-for-service health care, an increase of $1 billion over the
previous annual report. The errors represented 8 percent of the
annual $170 billion fee-for-service program and ranged ``from
inadvertent mistakes to outright fraud and abuse,'' said the
inspector general's report for the Health and Human Services
Department.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internal Revenue Service reported sending a $15,000 refund
to a person who owed $350,000 in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are some bright spots in the 1999 financial reports as
well. For example, the departments of Justice, Transportation,
Veterans Affairs, as well as Health and Human Services, all won
statements from their auditors that their books were reliable.
</P>
<P>
   However, since many of the agencies are repeat offenders in
sloppy bookkeeping practices, the government seemed headed for yet
another bad report card from Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., chairman of
the House Government Reform's management subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Horn gave half of the agencies a grade of ``F'' and
most of the rest a ``D.'' This year he will add a category for the
entire federal government. Horn offered little hope that the
government would make the dean's list. He said Thursday that he saw
``early indications of the enormity of the government's accounting
problems'' in the 1999 reports.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Governmental Affairs Chairman Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.,
took aim at HUD, which last year succeeded in providing an approved
accounting but fell backwards this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think that financial management is an issue that
doesn't affect ordinary people,'' he said. ``But at HUD and other
agencies, poor financial management means that crooks are stealing
from the government, and people that need these funds are going
without.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
