<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-W     03-30 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE DEPARTMENT OKS SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: PRECEDE San Francisco; new throughout)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department gave the go-ahead Thursday
for the Hearst Corporation to acquire the San Francisco Chronicle
and sell the Hearst-owned San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The decision removed a major obstacle to the transaction that
was announced last August when the family that owned Chronicle
agreed to sell to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hearst said it would try to sell The Examiner,
published in the afternoon. If a buyer weren't found, Hearst said
it would merge the newspaper with the Chronicle and publish a
single newspaper, named the San Francisco Chronicle, in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Because both newspapers are partners in a 1965 joint operating
agreement administered by the Justice Department as an exception to
federal antitrust laws, the department had to give its approval to
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department approval came after Hearst agreed to sell The
Examiner to members of the Fang family, publishers of the
thrice-weekly free newspaper, The Independent. The department
announcement said the sale of the Examiner ``has resolved the
department's antitrust concerns relating'' to Hearst's plan to buy
the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Hearst has agreed to provide the
Fangs with a $66 million subsidy over three years to publish the
Examiner as a morning paper. The Fangs agreed to purchase The
Examiner's name, archives, subscriber list, examiner.com Web site,
computers, office furniture, delivery trucks and newsracks. The
staff, buildings and printing presses were not included.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, publisher of The Independent, has said The Examiner
would publish as a daily newspaper sold through home subscriptions
and newsracks. After a four-month transition period, Fang said he
plans to switch the Examiner into the morning field and compete
directly with the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Joel I. Klein, assistant attorney general in charge of the
antitrust division, said the sale of the Examiner means that ``For
the first time in 35 years, San Francisco will have two independent
daily papers. Consumers, such as advertisers and readers, will
obtain the benefits of full competition between the two daily
morning papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker in San Francisco
was weighing a request by Clint Reilly to block the deal on the
basis that the Fang-owned Examiner would not have sufficient
resources to survive in a battle against the Hearst-owned
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's suit contends that the purchase of the Chronicle would
result in higher advertising and subscription rates and thus harm
consumers. It also claims the purchase would violate federal
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied those contentions and argued that the
transaction would boost competition between newspapers in Bay Area
suburbs and between electronic media. Gary Halling, Hearst's
lawyer, has asked the court to dismiss the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has argued that it would cost far more for the Fangs to
publish The Examiner as a viable competitor to Hearst's Chronicle _
as much as $250 million over five years. He has called the Fang
deal a ``sham'' designed to destroy The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But Halling's brief for Hearst said, ``In fact, the transaction
is structured to provide incentives to continue The Examiner's
business. Hearst is only reimbursing actual expenses incurred in
publishing The Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs' profits increase with revenue from The Examiner, and
the newspaper's ultimate success depends on market forces, Halling
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle has a daily circulation of 464,535 and is Northern
California's largest paper. The Examiner's daily circulation is
108,968.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1965 joint operating agreement, both the Examiner and
the Chronicle were allowed to combine business operations while
keeping independent news staffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
