<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GLORY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GLORY' GETS TANGLED IN THE ROPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C+   
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second Hollywood boxing movie of the new century, ``Price of
Glory,'' is considerably better than the first: the abysmal, Ron
Shelton ring comedy, ``Play It to the Bone.'' But, granted, that's
not saying much.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite believable performances from a large cast, some
nail-biting fight scenes and a handful of touching moments, it
fails to be either a coherent sports drama or the kind of epic
family tragedy it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of Arturo Ortega (Jimmy Smits), a gifted
Hispanic-American boxer from an Arizona border town whose dreams of
glory are cut short when he's mismatched with a much better fighter
and pummeled into hamburger in the film's 1977 prologue.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 13 years later, and Arturo is now an assembly line worker
who has tried to transfer his dreams to his three very young sons,
and spends all of his spare time coaching them (often abusively) in
the state Silver Gloves competition _ the ultimate little league
father.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 10 more years later, and Arthur now has three budding
champions on his hands: Sonny (Jon Seda), the responsible oldest;
Jimmy (Clifton Collins Jr.), the weak-willed middle child; and
Johnny (Ernesto Hernandez), who Arturo at first wanted to keep out
of the family business but ends up being the most adept at it.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Isn't this the exact paradigm of ``The
Godfather'' _ right down to the name of the oldest son? Yes, it
sure is, and that classic echoes throughout this film, especially
in Smits' performance as an ethnic family patriarch who wants the
best of his boys, but brings them something else.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ``Price of Glory'' has some flavor and a core of
authenticity: its script was written by ex-journalist Phil Berger,
who covered boxing for the New York Times for seven years; and
director Carlos Avila brings the Hispanic-American milieu to life
without the usual stream of Hollywood cliches.
</P>
<P>
   But, somehow, the elements don't quite click; Smits' one-note
performance never generates the kind of interest or sympathy that
makes us want to stay with him through his long ordeal, and when
the film suddenly turns into ``Rocky'' _ as all boxing films of the
last two decades invariably do _ it totally invalidates its theme.
</P>
<P>
   Price of Glory. Directed by Carlos Avila. Written by Phil
Berger. Cast: Jimmy Smits, Jon Seda, Clifton Collins Jr., Maria Del
Mar, Ernesto Hernandez. New Line Cinema. 113 minutes. Rated PG-13
for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
