<SLUG> BC-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CUBS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 11th INNING GLAND SLAM BY MINORS-BOUND AGBAYANI GIVES METS A SPLIT(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ By the second night of Major League Baseball's excursion
to Japan, things were so normal that the game itself reverted to
the usual fare of Bobby Valentine's managerial etiquette and
incipient feuds, to say nothing of Benny Agbayani's announcing loud
and clear that he really ought to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   The brief experiment in exporting North American baseball like a
traveling rock show ended with Agbayani clobbering a grand-slam
homer in the 11th inning to give the Mets a 5-1 victory over the
Cubs, who had won the first game in the series Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani knows he is due to be demoted to the minor leagues as
soon as the Mets need to activate Glendon Rusch to be their fifth
starter, probably within a week. He has not been thrilled with the
prospect, since he showed considerable power as a part-time starter
last year.
</P>
<P>
   He showed more of it Thursday, drilling a homer over the
406-foot sign in deep center, to send all the hard-working Japanese
businessmen home for a few hours of sleep before they begin their
grueling jobs in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The split series will count in the standings. What will also
remain, aside from the good will generated by the Japanese hosts
and the players _ who generally got it _ was the itchy relationship
between managers Valentine and Don Baylor of the Cubs. That little
tempest in a pot of green tea will have legs when the Mets and Cubs
meet again in the States later this season.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor had been pretty much hacked off Wednesday night by
Valentine's protest of an irregularity on the lineup card. Baylor
had written Jeff Reed's name twice as a reserve and omitted Jeff
Huson's name, and Valentine decided that could mean the Cubs were
using an ineligible player. It was merely a slip of the hand, and
Valentine soon admitted ``there is no protest,'' but in the
meantime, he had introduced an American-style litigious note in
front of a bemused Japanese audience, which was not used to such
arcane maneuverings.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor cogitated on it overnight, and decided he was still
hacked off nearly 24 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have done it, just out of respect for the guy on
the mound,'' Baylor said Thursday night, defending his pitcher,
Rick Aguilera. ``Aguilera has over 200 saves in the major leagues.
You keep him standing out there trying to distract him. For me, it
was pretty much nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, it was mostly straight baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored first off Kyle Farnsworth in the fifth on walks
to Todd Zeile and Rey Ordonez, a sacrifice bunt by Rick Reed and a
solid sacrifice fly to center by Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs tied the game in the fifth after a walk to Joe Girardi.
Farnsworth put down a bunt to the right of Zeile, who has been
converted to first base this season, an experiment still very much
in progress. Zeile turned to his right and heaved the ball wide of
second base, sending Girardi to third on the error. Girardi scored
on an infield double play.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed pitched eight innings for the Mets, giving up four
hits and the one unearned run. Both teams went deep into their
bullpens, which they could afford to do because they did not have
another game until their stateside openers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A bemused laugh went around the ball park at the end of nine
innings when the announcement was made in Japanese that the game
would be played to its conclusion. In the Central League here, all
games must stop after 15 innings if tied, and in the Pacific League
the limit is 12 innings, presumably so the fans can catch public
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs worked up a rally in the 10th against Turk Wendell on a
walk, a sacrifice and an out. Most of the 55,000 fans were still
around, and began clapping in anticipation of a Sosa home run.
Instead, Valentine had Wendell walked Sosa intentionally, touching
off a chorus of boos louder than the ones the night before for two
Sosa walks, a more raucous sound than usual for the the normal
Japanese baseball crowds. Dennis Cook came in and walked the
left-handed Mark Grace but caught Henry Rodriguez, also
left-handed, on a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th, Zeile hit a single with two outs, Ordonez and
Melvin Mora walked, and Agbayani whacked the grand-slam shot. He
will be flying back to New York with the Mets anyway, but he might
force them to cancel any flight reservations they might be making
for him to the minor leagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
