<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MIFUNE-TEX     03-30 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MIFUNE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARKLY FUNNY, WILD RIDE THROUGH A TANGLE OF DYSFUNCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iben Hjejle, who plays John Cusack's long-suffering, bemused,
off-and-on girlfriend in the new ``High Fidelity,'' also shows up
this week in a vastly different film from Denmark, her native
country. In ``Mifune,'' Hjejle gives an eye-opening, four-barrelled
performance as a hooker with a heart of pyrite, who finds herself
cast into the roles of housekeeper, sister, mother figure and
mother.
</P>
<P>
   The variety is apropos to a movie that's largely about
role-playing. ``Mifune'' gets its title from the late Japanese
actor Toshiro Mifune, star of such Akira Kurosawa films as ``The
Seven Samurai.'' ``Mifune's'' protagonist, Kresten (Anders W.
Berthelsen), often pretends to be Mifune when he needs to calm his
mentally challenged brother Rud (Jesper Asholt).
</P>
<P>
   Kresten hasn't had to do this for about 10 years, though,
because he's made a life for himself as a successful businessman in
Copenhagen and just married his boss's daughter, without revealing
to anyone his impoverished rural roots. But when Kresten, after a
night of honeymoon bliss, receives word that his father has died,
he returns to the family farm to wrap up matters and take care of
his brother. He also hires Hjejle's Liva, a prostitute on the run
from an angry client and a persistent obscene phone caller, as his
housekeeper, in all innocence of her real career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mifune's'' primary plot is predictable, but it hangs a lot of
surprises on its formula story line, and director Soren
Kragh-Jacobsen steers it from ribald comedy (this isn't for prudes)
to sudden violence to slapstick without losing his grip. The movie
is from the Danish collective Dogma 95, a group of iconoclastic
filmmakers who follow 10 strict rules, the most familiar of which
is that no artificial lighting must be used in filming. Considering
the strength of Mifune's story and characters, the rules come off
as more of a gimmick, although the natural lighting does make for
some astounding shots. But the stunt filmmaking isn't necessary; in
any light, Mifune is a darkly funny, wild ride through a tangle of
dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Mifune''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 99 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1638EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CHINA-HUMAN-RIGHTS-$A     03-30 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HUMAN-RIGHTS-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HUMAN RIGHTS ACTIVIST LOBBIES ON CHINA TRADE BILL)  
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 2)  &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As armies of lobbyists for businesses, agriculture
and Silicon Valley press Congress to approve permanent trading
rights for China, a lone human rights activist is urging lawmakers
to grant the trading rights only if China improves its human rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jendrzejczyk, the Washington lobbyist for Human Rights
Watch, a private New York City-based research group, says China
must be encouraged to ``go beyond opening its markets, to opening
its jails, easing restrictions on the press and the Internet, and
protecting the rights of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to this year's State Department survey of human rights
around the world, China has tightened controls on basic freedoms
since 1998, jailing pro-Democracy activists, arresting labor
organizers and tax protesters. The Chinese government also has
banned the Falun Gong, a spiritual meditation movement with
thousands of followers, arresting more than 35,000 of its members
and burning its books and videotapes. China also has required all
corporate Internet users in Shanghai to register with police.
</P>
<P>
   Jendrezejczyk, in an interview, said Congress should require
China to ratify two United Nations human rights treaties
guaranteeing freedom of speech, freedom of religion and the right
to organize trade unions, among other rights, before approving
permanent normal trading relations, referred to in Congress as
``PNTR.'' The president would be required to certify that China is
honoring those rights before Congress would grant PNTR, according
to this proposal.
</P>
<P>
   He wants China to dismantle its ``reeducation through labor''
camps, which force thousands of citizens into camps for up to three
years without judicial review. He wants Tibet and Xinjiang, where
large ethnic minority populations are routinely persecuted, to be
open to the foreign press and human rights monitors. And he wants
Congress to pass a code of conduct that would spell out human
rights principles for U.S. companies in China, such as urging them
to stop using prison labor and halt political indoctrination
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Jendrzejczyk, 50, an intense, high-energy, 10-year veteran of
Human Rights Watch who was formerly with Amnesty International,
acknowledges there is no quick fix to any of these problems.
</P>
<P>
   But he says the United States, which carries considerable clout
as the biggest market for Chinese goods, ``needs to develop a
careful strategy that combines carrots and sticks'' to pressure
China to stop squashing human rights. He is critical of the Clinton
administration, saying President Clinton has ``no real strategy''
on improving human rights in China and ``tends to be driven by
crises.''
</P>
<P>
   Jendrzejczyk says if Congress acts in the next few months, China
would have time to make the human rights improvements before China
is accepted into the World Trade Organization, which is expected at
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a good chance of making human rights prominent
in the China-WTO debate,'' Jendrzejczyk said. ``But whether China
makes any real progress on human rights will largely depend on how
much pressure the White House and Congress exert on Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and President Clinton are pushing Congress to
grant PNTR to China, which would give the United States greater
access to China's markets as part of China's entry into the World
Trade Organization, the 135-member group that regulates
international trade.
</P>
<P>
   China is subject to the Jackson-Vanik amendment, a 1974 law that
limits the trading privileges the United States can grant countries
that Congress judges to be suppressing their own people. The law
allows an annual waiver if Congress and the administration agree
that it would substantially promote the law's goals for encouraging
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   China has been granted a waiver each year since 1980, though
some lawmakers have used the yearly vote to voice their disapproval
of China's human rights record, its posture toward Taiwan, or its
trade surplus with the United States. While U.S. labor leaders
oppose PNTR with China, Jendrzejczyk merely wants to make it
conditional on improvements in China's human rights record. PNTR is
accorded to all U.S. trading partners except for a few countries
that don't have trade agreements with the United States, such as
Cuba, Vietnam, Afghanistan, Laos, North Korea, Serbia and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Jendrzejczyk said the United States should not isolate China or
cut them off from trade. ``I don't think that would help,'' he
said. ``We intend to pressure China to become a government that
fundamentally respects rights.'' He says better trade relations
with China can help advance human rights ``only if it is combined
with effective sustained pressure on China to respect civil and
political rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The House, which is expected to vote before the end of May, is
sharply divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. David Dreier, R-Calif., chairman of the House Rules
Committee, and Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., are urging their
colleagues to vote for the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the most important thing we can do is expand
trade,'' Dreier said. ``For the first time we will be prying open a
market with 1.3 billion consumers. That's a winner for U.S. workers
and businesses.'' Dreier said economic reforms would help bring
about change and be ``a winner for a repressive society.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui, a longtime free-trader who is rounding up Democratic
votes for the China trade bill, warns that loading the legislation
down with too many human rights demands could sink it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have so many things in there that it blows the whole
thing up,'' Matsui said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., takes a tougher stance than does
Jendrzejczyk.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi praises him as ``a very informed and politically astute
advocate for human rights'' but criticizes his position for failing
to include an annual review of China's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Without that, she says, the United States would lose its
leverage on human rights or violations of the trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no credibility when it comes to honoring their
agreements,'' Pelosi said. ``I don't believe we should give PNTR on
the basis of broken promises. They have broken promises on market
access, use of prison labor and intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which will follow the House in considering the China
trade bill, is likely to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., says a trade bill defeat
``simply kicks American businesses in the derriere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe human rights is improved by isolating a
country tradewise,'' Feinstein said. ``We're in a global trading
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul David Wellstone, D-Minn., is in the minority with his
view that Congress must retain its annual review of China to
protect human rights. Without that, ``we won't have any leverage
and we'll continue to see the same brutal picture'' on human rights
issues, Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
