<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, March 31. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ After two days of often rancorous
debate, the House on Thursday approved a $12.6 billion spending
bill that commits the United States to help train and equip
Colombia's security forces, which are battling drug traffickers and
leftist guerrillas. Lawmakers, by a vote of 263-146, approved the
emergency aid package, which also includes money for the Pentagon
to pay for the peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, and for disaster
relief in the Carolinas. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ In most countries, an election can
mark the end of political struggle. In Russia this year, the
victory of Vladimir Putin in last Sunday's presidential election
has only intensified the infighting between various groups vying
for seats in the new government and influence in the new court.
Much of the attention is focused on an opulent Moscow building
known as Aleksandr House, the home of a privately financed think
tank set up last December by Putin when he was still prime minister
to devise a program of legal and economic reforms. Many of those on
the Aleksandr House team are refugees from President Boris
Yeltsin's first reform government of 1991, and they are ready to do
battle with tycoons like Boris A. Berezovsky, the financier who
exerted great sway in the latter years of Yeltsin's rule, for the
country's future. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ Without winning or conceding
anything of substance on his tour of South Asia last week,
President Clinton may still have helped to modestly reduce the risk
of war between nuclear-armed India and Pakistan by talking sweet to
India and talking tough to Pakistan. A news analysis by Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Rushojwa, Uganda) _ The carnage in Uganda deepened
again Thursday as investigators unearthed another 81 bodies at the
home here of a member of a doomsday cult. Of the dead, packed tight
in a mass grave dug deeply into red soil, 44 were children. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE (Washington) _ The Army's highest-ranking
woman, Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy, whose career is often cited as
an example of the expanding opportunities for women in uniform,
filed a sexual harassment complaint against another Army general,
accusing him of groping her in her office in 1996, Pentagon
officials said Thursday. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developing. INS officials are meeting again
with the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez after extending by 24
hours the deadline for revoking his temporary residency status and
beginning proceedings to send him back to Cuba. Fernando Remirez de
Estenoz, chief of the Cuban interests section in Washington, meets
with the State Department to discuss the proposal of Elian's father
to come to Miami, but says so far they haven't asked for visas.
Attorney General Janet Reno appeals for calm and reiterates that
the boy belongs with his father. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-COMPARE (Undated) _ George W. Bush likes to say that if
elected president he has no intention of serving as the nation's
education superintendent, dispatching the apparatchiks of the
federal government to play a role that is better left to school
board members. Al Gore suggests that it is teachers, and not
bureaucrats and politicians, who would be empowered and gain
respect in his administration. But whether Bush or Gore is elevated
to the White House in November, the federal government would
parachute behind the closed doors of American classrooms in ways
different from and beyond that of previous presidents. By Jacques
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-FUNDRAISING (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani raised
nearly twice as much money as Hillary Rodham Clinton during the
first three months of this year, bringing his total fund-raising
figure so far to close to $20 million. The latest figures suggest
that Giuliani will significantly outraise and outspend the first
lady in the contest ahead for the U.S. Senate. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-SENATE-CORZINE (Trenton, N.J.) _ In his race for U.S. Senate,
Jon Corzine has spent millions of dollars to introduce himself to
voters, but on Thursday it suddenly seemed that many in New Jersey
would base their first impression of him not on his record as an
investment banker but on his joking slurs against Italian
Americans, the state's largest ethnic group. As Corzine sought to
put those derogatory references and even his apology for them
behind him on Thursday, Italian American leaders expressed outrage
and asked whether he had the sensitivity to serve in public office.
By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Over and over again for the
last three years, Microsoft Corp. has claimed that separating its
Web browser, Internet Explorer, from Windows was utterly
impossible. Now, in settlement talks with the government, the
company has offered to do just that. But one possible reason for
the change of heart, some experts say, is that it doesn't really
matter anymore. Trial evidence showed that Microsoft built its
browser into Windows as a tactic to disadvantage its chief
competitor, Netscape. But the browser war is over; Microsoft won.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
