<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-PRIVATIZE-(TRIM     03-30 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PRIVATIZE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET FINDS PITFALLS IN PRIVATIZING CHINESE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Wall Street's top-drawer investment firms are
falling all over each other to take China's state-owned companies
public. After the furor unleashed by the latest deal, they may
wonder whether it is worth the grief.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. set the price Thursday for its initial
public offering of PetroChina Co., China's dominant oil and gas
producer. At 1.28 Hong Kong dollars a share, or about 16.45 cents,
it is at the low end of the company's predicted range. That will
hardly soothe the architects of the deal, who spent months putting
it together only to see it ripped apart by critics ranging from
Republican lawmakers to Tibetan monks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PetroChina offering has been a very complex and grueling
process,'' said Paul Shapira, a managing director at Goldman Sachs,
at a news conference here last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When PetroChina's bosses traveled to the United States on March
20 to sell the offering, they faced repeated charges of
human-rights and labor abuses. Critics said the listing would lead
to 1 million layoffs at PetroChina's parent company, China National
Petroleum. They also said the company was exploiting people in
Tibet and abetting an outlaw regime in Sudan through a joint
venture there.
</P>
<P>
   Not content just to criticize, the AFL-CIO organized a shadow
road show in New York and other cities to persuade investors to
steer clear of PetroChina. Fund managers in Hong Kong said Thursday
that the campaign had an impact _ scaring off some American funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political concerns have been a major overhang,'' said a
fund manager, who like most people interviewed for this article
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Not that many Asia-Pacific funds
invest in oil and gas companies, so you need demand in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   PetroChina's bumpy ride has far-reaching implications for
China's campaign to overhaul its sclerotic corporate sector. As
part of that effort, Beijing hopes to sell shares in dozens of huge
state-owned companies, including Sinopec, the second-largest oil
company; China National Overseas Oil, the No. 1 offshore oil
company; and China Unicom, the No. 2 telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   With PetroChina limping into the market, however, the prospects
for these other deals are now cloudier. The AFL-CIO, emboldened by
its success, said it planned to go after future Chinese stock
offerings that it feels are bad investments or represent companies
that violate human rights and labor practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that there is going to be 120 of these
IPOs coming out of China,'' said Richard Trumka, the
secretary-general of the AFL-CIO. ``On ethical issues and
shareholder governance issues, most of these are going to be just
as bad as PetroChina.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such criticism, PetroChina may feel vindicated
that it was still able to raise about $3 billion from the offering,
which values the company at roughly $30 billion. China National
Petroleum will retain a 90 percent stake and will appoint the
entire board, including the two independent directors.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of PetroChina begin trading on April 6 in New York and on
April 7 in Hong Kong. In New York, they will trade as American
depository receipts that represent 100 shares, or $16.45 at the
price set in Hong Kong Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   China National Petroleum had initially hoped to raise $5 billion
or even $7 billion. To meet even the more modest goal, Goldman was
forced to round up strategic investors to soak up the shares. BP
Amoco agreed to buy 20 percent of the offering, or as much as $1
billion, while three politically friendly property developers in
Hong Kong agreed to chip in another $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's performance was also tainted by an unauthorized e-mail
that four of the firm's salespeople sent to 83 clients. Because the
note contained claims that the firm feared may have violated
securities laws, Goldman tried desperately to recall it. Later, on
the advice of lawyers, it took the extraordinary step of reprinting
the e-mail _ and correcting portions of it _ in the prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly was a mistake,'' Shapira said tersely at the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The disputes surrounding PetroChina obscure the fact that it is,
in many respects, a trail-blazing deal for China. The company has
instituted an incentive plan for its top 300 managers, tying as
much as 75 percent of their compensation to profit targets. That is
unheard of among state-owned companies in China, which only
recently began paying attention to profits, let alone the role of
managers in producing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a world-scale oil and gas company, and the flagship of
China's reform,'' said Ma Fucai, the chairman of PetroChina, in the
news conference in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Because China National Petroleum is a classic state-owned
enterprise _ with a vast network of hospitals and schools in
addition to oil and gas operations _ the company decided to carve
out its most valuable assets and place them in a separate venture,
PetroChina.
</P>
<P>
   By doing that, the company also removed the burden of its
bloated payroll from PetroChina. The new public company will retain
480,000 employees, while the remaining 1 million workers will stay
at China National Petroleum, where most are likely to be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   These layoffs were a main reason that the AFL-CIO decided to
oppose the deal. But the labor federation also warned that the
proceeds from the stock offering could be siphoned off by the
parent, where they could contribute indirectly to its activities in
Tibet or the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire wall they created between PetroChina and CNPC is
illusory at best,'' Trumka said, ``so money will find its way back
into the parent company.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's prospectus, 90 percent of the
proceeds will be used by PetroChina to pay off debt and finance
capital expenditures. The remaining 10 percent will go to China
National Petroleum to reduce debt and pay for employee severance
and retraining. Ma said the company had hired outside auditors to
guarantee that the money would not be used for any other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ma tried to distance PetroChina from its parent's activities in
Sudan. China National Petroleum is an investor, along with
Malaysian and Canadian companies, in a pipeline there. ``PetroChina
does not have any overseas assets and operations,'' he said. ``We
do not have any plans to expand overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Even aside from questions about Sudan, PetroChina has been hurt
because it is indisputably an old-fashioned company. At a time when
investors are bewitched by technology stocks, PetroChina's
discussion of benchmark crude prices does not send hearts
fluttering _ even though the company has proven oil reserves of
10.3 billion barrels, making it the world's fourth-largest publicly
listed oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Given the low price of its shares, analysts said PetroChina may
prove a shrewd investment. For its labors, Goldman Sachs also gets
a high fee. The firm can expect to split a payment of 3 percent to
4 percent of the offering, or about $90 million, with the other
underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   2 Chinese Oil Companies to Merge
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's second- and fourth-largest oil
companies will merge by order of the government, the companies said
Thursday. The move will make China New Star Petroleum, the
country's fourth-largest producer, a subsidiary of China
Petrochemical, or Sinopec, the country's second-largest oil
company. The combination is expected to reinforce Sinopec's
strength in oil and gas exploration as the company prepares for a
global public offering of its shares. Sinopec plans to list on the
Hong Kong, New York and London stock exchanges by the end of June.
China National Petroleum Corp. remains the country's largest
producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
