<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLOOD-AID31-COX     03-30 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-AID31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLOOD AID STILL IN DOUBT DESPITE HOUSE PASSAGE
 &HT;    520&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than $300 million in flood aid for victims of
Hurricane Floyd is stuck in Congress, despite a House vote Thursday
to approve the money.
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies in a $12.6 billion emergency spending package
for the current fiscal year that includes the disaster relief.
Senate Republicans say the bill is bloated and that Congress should
deal with much of the spending _ including flood relief _ as part
of the normal appropriations process for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina lawmakers, however, said they remain optimistic
the emergency aid package will pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just arriving here in the Senate. ... Give us time,''
said Michael Briggs, a spokesman for Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.
``There is always more than one way to skin a cat around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Briggs said that Edwards and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., are
``working hand in glove on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate concerns about the bill have nothing to do with the
disaster relief, but with other spending items, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency package includes $2.1 billion for peacekeeping
operations in Kosovo and $1.7 billion for drug intervention in
Colombia. The Colombia issue dominated the two-day House debate,
where critics warned against U.S. involvement in Colombia's bloody
civil war and expressed concerns about human rights violations and
drug trafficking by military and paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Walter Jones, D-N.C., said he is ``very pleased'' that the
House approved the hurricane aid. He said he hoped that North
Carolina's senators ``will protect what we have gotten in this
bill'' to help flood victims, ``and I believe they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., criticized GOP
leaders, including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., on
Thursday for not focusing on passage of the supplemental spending
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important,'' he said. ``Instead of dealing with flags,
Elian Gonzalez, and (the) gas tax, we ought to be dealing with the
real problems affecting real people. It's drug abuse. It's our
morale in our armed forces and it's currently a disastrous
situation in North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-day House debate rarely focused on flood-ravaged areas,
where scores of victims remain in temporary housing.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of a temporary trailer park in Greenville, N.C., who
identified herself as only as Nebraska said Congress should pass
the bill, regardless of the their concerns about the foreign
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody needs some money, I need some money. I ain't got
nowhere to go when I leave here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of her neighbors, Diane Moore, said that the senators and
representatives, ``with all those degrees behind 'em,'' should be
able to figure out a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Hines, also living in a temporary trailer park in
Greenville, said Congress should look homeward, and Colombia should
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should take care of people in their own
country,'' Hines said. ``There's a lot of people suffering right
now who need help that can't get help.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   During the House debate, North Carolina lawmakers asked their
colleagues to remember flood victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about the widow or the widower who lost a life partner
in the flood waters. ... Think about the farmers ... who are
struggling to repair their fields, their barns, their equipment.
... Think about the thousands of families who are in cramped travel
trailers,'' said Rep. Bob Etheridge, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency package includes $43 million to repair
flood-damaged highways and bridges, $12 million for a new Armed
Forces Reserve Center in Greenville, and $1.5 million for a U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers study on raising the dike on the Tar River
in the historic town of Princeville, in Edgecombe County.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ $81 million to forgive loans from the federal Commodity Credit
Corp. on flood-damaged tobacco, cotton and peanut crops.
</P>
<P>
   _ $77 million for the Federal Emergency Management Agency to buy
out homes in the 100-year flood plain. The majority _ $68 million _
would be used to buy homes in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ $6 million for North Carolina fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   _ $500, 000 for rural firefighters in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   T. Scott Batchelor, a reporter for the Greenville Daily
Reflector, contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
