u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-30 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECALOGUE SERIES IS OUT, FINALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next month a large and fine item indeed lands among assorted
good little foreign films to be released on tape and disc. In 1988
the Polish director Krzysztof Kieslowski produced a series of 10
one-hour films, called ``The Decalogue,'' for television.
</P>
<P>
   A year later they were shown at the Venice Film Festival, and
then in 1996 at Lincoln Center in New York, the year Kieslowski
died at 54. Other than that, what many critics consider a
masterpiece has been screened infrequently and has never appeared
on video.
</P>
<P>
   On April 11, the series will be released on five cassettes from
Facets Multimedia, the Chicago distributor. (Information:
800-331-6197).
</P>
<P>
   The delay can be described simply: ``Frozen in Canada,'' said
Milos Stehlik, director of Facets. He added that the rights were
not in the tangle they often are in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``North American rights were owned by a Canadian company that
sat on it for a very long time,'' Stehlik said. ``Now, after nine
years, they decided to let go, license it and do a video release.''
</P>
<P>
   Best known in this country for ``The Double Life of Veronique''
(1992) and the ``Three Colors'' trilogy, ``Blue'' (1993), ``White''
and ``Red'' (both 1994), Kieslowski made documentaries and feature
films for television earlier in his career.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 installments of ``The Decalogue'' are set in a huge
Warsaw apartment complex. Each story is rooted in one of the Ten
Commandments, but as in his films Kieslowski can't be pinned down
to literal meanings and traditional concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Moral and ethical issues are under consideration, but the
commandments take unexpected turns. For example, in Decalogue 4
(``Honor Thy Father and Mother''), an actress adores the parent she
lives with, but the relationship goes in another direction when she
discovers that he is not really her father. ``I simply wanted to
show that life is complicated,'' Kieslowski said of ``The
Decalogue,'' ``nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the foreign niche will get three worthwhile if more
modest additions from Steeplechase Entertainment, a new California
distributor named for an old Brooklyn racetrack. In ``Love Is the
Devil,'' Derek Jacobi stars as the troubled and often very nasty
British painter Francis Bacon, who died in 1992 but has been in the
news this month when lawyers for his estate sued his gallery,
Marlborough International, charging fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi gives a convincing performance, but the most intriguing
aspect of the film is its look. Denied the use of Bacon's work, the
director, John Maybury, used light, shadow, reflection and other
optical tools to make the entire film resemble a Bacon painting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another Steeplechase release, ``Voyage to the Beginning of
the World,'' Marcello Mastroianni, in his last film, stars as an
88-year-old Portuguese-French director touring the countryside with
three younger colleagues. The third title, ``Dry Cleaning,'' about
a staid French couple who enter new sexual territory, is by Anne
Fontaine, one of France's emerging female directors.
</P>
<P>
   All three films are also on DVD, a format whose low production
costs sometimes encourage small films as much as large ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Releases &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The time is a generation before the original ``Star Wars'' (in
case anyone has forgotten) and the bucolic little planet of Naboo
and its teen-age queen, Amidala (Natalie Portman), have been
overrun by the giant Trade Federation, ruled by the electrostatic
presence called Darth Sidious. Later, on the planet of Tatooine,
two Jedi knights (Liam Neeson and Ewan McGregor) turn up the more
familiar Darth (Vader) as a child space-chariot driver (Jake
Lloyd), in a film that, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and offers a
swashbuckling extragalactic getaway.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $24.98. 133 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: April 4. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Love of the Game &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing sentimental hardball, the stiffly noble pitcher Billy
Chapel (Kevin Costner) ends his glorious 19-year career in front of
56,000 fans in Yankee Stadium. Darned if he doesn't have a
no-hitter going, too, even if that tired arm of his causes a
grimace or two. Seeming as suited for Mount Rushmore as the Hall of
Fame, Billy reveres the game, going back to the days when he first
threw in the back yard with his tall, noble dad. But don't tell it
to Jane (Kelly Preston), whose frustration with Billy has her
headed for London in a film that, despite a talented lineup,
``produces unexceptional results'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $26.98. 137 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: April 4. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe zey are zending a woman,'' comments a
bystander in Luc Besson's skull-clanger of a film about the Maid of
Orleans. Well, get used to it because here she is: blond and rangy
and trading on all her good rapport with the French who believe
that she is sent by God to help them drive the English back across
the Channel. As Joan, Milla Jovavich is bristling, grimy and a
trifle too maniacal for refined spiritual tasks in a film of
``jarring, hand-held carnage interspersed with religious visions
straight out of music video'' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $108.97; DVD, $27.95, 148 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: April 4. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Body Shots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Michael Cristofer's film, four women and four men in their
20s convene in Los Angeles to bare their views on sex. Saying that
she has been raped by a professional football player (Jerry
O'Connell), an actress (Tara Reid) shows up at the apartment of her
friend (Amanda Peet), a clerk in the district attorney's office.
One of the men plays pornography on his office computer and another
urinates on a closed toilet. Cristofer won the 1997 Pulitzer Prize
for his play ``The Shadow Box.'' Here he seems ``more focused on
surface than true revelation'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Line. $107.37. 115 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bone Collector,'' ``Double Jeopardy'' and ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' are on top of the best-renter list. Beneath them, though, a
subcategory of smaller films with limited theatrical release (475
screens or fewer) form their own list. Here are some examples, as
tabulated by Video Business magazine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST LAID PLANS. Mike Barker's thriller mixes two friends
(Alessandro Nivola and Josh Brolin) and a young woman (Reese
Witherspoon) who has a sexual encounter with one but was the
girlfriend of the other. 1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. 90
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS. Based on Kurt Vonnegut's 1973 novel,
Alan Rudolph's film stars Bruce Willis as the '50s suburban car
dealer Dwayne Hoover, Barbara Hershey as his neurotic wife and Nick
Nolte as his partner, a closet transvestite. 1999. Hollywood.
$104.16. 110 minutes Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   TEA WITH MUSSOLINI. A tight-knit group of Englishwomen (Dame
Maggie Smith, Dame Judi Dench, Joan Plowright) try to perpetuate
their set ways in Florence before World War II. 1999. MGM. $104.16.
117 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   THE WINSLOW BOY. Arthur Winslow (Nigel Hawthorne) defends his
son (Guy Edwards), expelled from school for stealing a
five-shilling note. 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $27.95.
110 minutes. Closed captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   THE RED VIOLIN. In a kitschy series of adventures, a legendary
instrument travels from 17th-century Italy to contemporary
Montreal. 1999 Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.98. 131 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   RUN LOLA RUN. Repeating her sprint over and over, Lola (Franka
Potente) with the cranberry hair has 20 minutes to come up with the
money to save her boyfriend (Moritz Bleibtreu). 1999. Columbia
Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $27.95. 81 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
</TEXT>
