<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDINAVIAN DEALER SELLS HIS TREASURES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Denmark)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's sale of the Arne Schlesch collection next
week marks the passing of an era. Schlesch, 77, has sold his
five-story Scandinavian antiques gallery on East 64th Street,
consigned its contents to Sotheby's and retired to Copenhagen.
``There's a limit to how long you can go on buying chandeliers and
chairs,'' he said. ``I made my hobby into a lucrative business. I
was thrilled to buy things, especially from families I knew. It was
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He was fun too. A native of Denmark, Schlesch said he was
descended ``on both sides'' from Charlemagne (742-814). ``I am not
a snob,'' he insisted. ``I simply belong to an old family.''
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the Schlesch gallery was like walking into a grand
townhouse in Copenhagen in the 18th century. Beneath the Russian
chandeliers (never electrified), a grand Danish rococo elm settee
with gilded decorations would be paired with a pair of George
II-style carved consoles whose bases were muscular golden eagles.
Huge mirrors reflected the fire roaring in the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Schlesch would offer guests sherry. He always sat in the same
chair, a Danish neoclassical giltwood wing chair, upholstered in
buttery leather with a reclining backrest. This chair, lot 414 in
Sotheby's sale on Wednesday, is an 18th-century precursor to the
La-Z-Boy. In theory everything in Schlesch's gallery was always for
sale, but he would sometimes refuse to part with things, like that
chair. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   He opened his New York gallery in 1965 with a Mexican partner,
Jose Juarez Garza. Early on the shop attracted tastemakers like
Babe Paley and Anne Getty. The decorators soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hail, a San Francisco interior designer who is also Danish,
was an early client. ``Arne Schlesch was the one who started the
whole fascination with Scandinavian style,'' he said. Craig Wright,
a Los Angeles designer and a client for 25 years, called it ``this
special Baltic taste,'' adding: ``He bought Scandinavian furniture
that was very sculptural, so it blended well with French and
Italian pieces. It was always very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The 434 lots include 18th and 19th-century porcelain from
Denmark, Vienna and China; 18th-century cobalt-blue Russian glass,
Scandinavian mirrors, Dutch rococo silver wall sconces, Danish
silver and a great deal of Baltic wood furniture.
</P>
<P>
   To American eyes, the most unusual piece will probably be lot
311, a rare German rococo blue tilt-top tripod table. Its top is
entirely covered in beadwork. Carefully sewn glass beads depict a
formal garden outside a country manor. There are walled sections
with a fountain, a pair of topiary trees in the form of pyramids
and checkerboard flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   Mary F. Cunningham, a Sotheby's specialist in European
furniture, is trying to identify the site. ``We don't know if it's
a real house or a fictional one,'' she said, ``but a nearly
identical tabletop is in the Stadtischen Museum in Brunswick,
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham describes beadwork from Brunswick as one of the 18th
century's great arts. The beadwork for this table is attributed to
Johann Michael van Selow, who worked under royal patronage at a
Brunswick factory that existed from 1755 to 1772.
</P>
<P>
   Glass beads do not fade, so the palette is faithful to the time:
chartreuse green, acid yellow, bright blue and red. Such beadwork
is fragile but protects the table from watermarks. The estimate is
$25,000 to $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   The top of another mid-18th-century rococo table in the sale is
inlaid with ceramic tiles from the Kellinghusen factory in
Schleswig-Holstein, a part of modern Germany that was then held by
the king of Denmark. The dark lavender and white tiles are
decorated with star and geometric motifs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purple was not a common color at that time,'' Cunningham
pointed out. ``Such tiles are usually blue.'' The table has
cabriole legs painted purple and white to complement the tiles. It
is a typical Schlesch piece: charming, elegant, yet relaxed enough
for a country house or city apartment. Its estimate is $12,000 to
$18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Schlesch was known for his magnificent chandeliers. ``He had the
greatest selection of chandeliers and mirrors in the United
States,'' Wright said. Lot 432 is a Russian neo-classical six-light
chandelier that was never electrified. Its stem has three ormolu
mounted, baluster-shaped cobalt blue glass balls that reflect
candlelight, as do the faceted crystal drops hanging from a
hexagonal crown at the top and from a larger hexagonal tier on the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The candle nozzles are joined by delicate swags of pierced
bronze in a cross-hatched pattern. ``It probably has its original
bronzing,'' Schlesch said. ``We can tell by the quality of the
bronzes it was probably made in the St. Petersburg workshop of
Johann Zech, a German who was called there by Catherine the Great.
There's a similar one in Pavlosk Palace outside St. Petersburg.''
The estimate is $30,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 433 is an equally fine Russian chandelier with 12 lights and
three cobalt glass balls. Beneath its pinecone finial is a crown of
arching golden wires that each end in a crystal pendant. The candle
holders on the base are interspersed with faceted glass obelisks
and the drip pans are pierced. It has not been electrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York decorator Rose Cummings once owned it,''
Cunningham said. ``Arne coveted it for years, until she finally
sold it to him.'' Estimate: $30,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 361 is a German rococo console in white and gold whose apron
is a piece of gold-and-white Frankenthaler porcelain. Its gilt
monogram, C.T., is for Carl Theodore, Elector of Palatinate
(1742-1799), in Bavaria. It is simply dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 283 is a pair of German rococo silver and gilded metal
mirrors from the mid-18th-century. The silvered metal mounts in the
frame are in the shape of shells, waves and foliage. ``They are
very rare,'' Schlesch said. ``I've only seen one other pair for
sale, at the Biennale fair in Paris.'' Estimate: $40,000 to
$60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although some characterize Schlesch's taste as aristocratic, he
disagrees. ``I don't have rich taste,'' he said. ``I don't know
what taste is. I despise decoration. I like things that look as
though they were inherited. I had things from every era and country
_ Danish, French, English, Irish, Swedish, Norwegian, even Turkish.
I had the things you'd expect to find in a manor house in Denmark
or Sweden. They were chosen because they were rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Harrison, a partner in the Manhattan antiques shop H.M.
Luther, put it this way: ``Arne Schlesch has got the quality that
makes dealers interesting: a real individual point of view. It's
like a collector's sensibility. One thing the auction houses will
never have is a point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to learn more about one of his specialties, a
daylong seminar, ``The Decorative Arts From Denmark and Sweden,
1720-1820,'' is to be held on Monday at Sotheby's Institute of Art.
Information: (212) 894-1112.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
