<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATKINS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atkins' age-defying diet less a weight-loss guide, more a
lifestyle change
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dr. Robert Atkins is back with a new
revolt. His previous ``Diet Revolution,'' first published in 1973,
was a bestseller and shot him to fame. But his unconventional
premise of a diet where you could eat steak and eggs, but no bread,
was soundly rejected by the medical community.
</P>
<P>
   His new book, ``Dr. Atkins' Age-Defying Diet Revolution,'' has
doctors talking again, but this time, some of them are nodding in
agreement, Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say he's moving to mainstream, nor embracing
popular nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is that the doctors can't ignore what they're
seeing, and that's their patients, who went on my diet, and lost
weight and had no adverse reactions. In fact, they were healthier
in most cases than when they began,'' he said in a recent interview
while visiting for a speech at Lynn University in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The new book focuses on using diet to promote longer lives
without the damaging effects of aging, Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Foods containing antioxidants, such as green, leafy vegetables
and bright fruits, are a major part of the diet. But it also gives
followers free rein with fat and protein. That's where mainstream
medicine and Atkins part ways.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Atkins, a licensed physician who practices at the
Atkins Center for Complementary Medicine in New York, is listed as
a quack by Dr. Stephen Barrett. Barrett publishes a newsletter and
maintains a Web site (www.quackwatch.com) to expose unsupported
medical claims. Dr. Robert Eckel, chairman of the American Heart
Association's Nutrition Committee, said, ``There are many concerns
with Atkins' diet. But the main one is that his diet is high in
saturated fats and cholesterol. Dieters can eat as much cheese,
butter and meats as they wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturated fats are connected to heart disease, Eckel said,
citing several medical studies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a point Atkins disputes, and he cites other recent
published studies that show no correlation between dietary
cholesterol and high blood cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   Eckel acknowledged that many dieters have shown success with the
Atkins diet, but long-term health problems with a low-carbohydrate,
high-saturated-fat diet haven't been studied. There's no evidence,
he said, to show that it's healthful over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   But Atkins points to what he calls the failure of current
medical theory on weight loss and disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Centers for Disease Control released the study last year
that showed Americans are at an all-time high for obesity,'' he
said. ``Yet they're all supposedly eating less fat than ever before
_ it doesn't take a scientist or a doctor to figure out you don't
lose weight by restricting fat.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says things are slowly changing, and even the medical
community is beginning to look again at what he calls the myths of
nutrition. ``No country in the world has been so criminally misled
about nutrition as the United States.'' Greedy health care
providers and politically connected food manufacturers are to
blame, he said. ``Who would it benefit least if Americans got
healthy? Doctors. And who do you think some of the biggest
lobbyists are in Washington? Cereal manufacturers, the sugar
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites studies and journal articles by respected physicians
who back up his theory, but says there is no formal research on his
diet because he can't afford it. ``I'm a practicing physician.
We're hoping to establish a research fund,'' he said, but ``it's
not in the best interest of all those food manufacturers who have
made a killing selling the low-fat plan to Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes on other old and new opponents in the new book. The
American Heart Association, a frequent target of the past, comes
under attack for endorsing such nutritionally empty foods as Count
Chocula and Froot Loop cereals and low-fat Pop Tarts. He said the
USDA should be particularly embarrassed by its Food Pyramid, and
the way it's translated to the nutrition labels on foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a listing on the label for percentage of recommended
allowances for carbohydrates. There is no such thing as a
recommended allowance of carbohydrates! We do not need these in the
diet. Essential amino and essential fatty acids _ that's it. That's
all we need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a big shift from all his other writings, Atkins includes
complex carbs as part of the age-defying diet. He's quick to point
out, however, the difference between complex carbs and the much
more prevalent simple ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complex carbohydrates are nuts, whole good grains, fruits and
certain vegetables. Quality carbohydrates that are nutrient dense
and beneficial in other ways as well _ fiber and other nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to think of bread, pasta and white rice as complex
carbohydrates, when instead, they are so processed, the body thinks
of them as simple carbohydrates and treats them just like sugar,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to provide a line of foods that help the low-carb
dieter pick foods that are on the diet.
</P>
<P>
   The new book is more of a lifetime diet than a weight-loss
guide. He recommends exercise, using organic foods and eliminating
as many toxins from our food, air and water as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can reverse diseases, and certainly prevent them,'' he
said. ``And most of it can be done by diet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``in order to practice the age-defying diet,
you have first defy conventional wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, he said, he dedicated himself to opposing the
American Medical Association by practicing what he calls
``complementary medicine _ I use medicine and natural and
alternative medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``But diet is key.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
