<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-JEWISH-MUSEUM-2TAK     03-30 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JEWISH-MUSEUM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH HISTORY FROM HOES TO A LADY LIBERTY MENORAH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The saga of Jewish civilization over some 4,000 years
is no small matter to tackle in a visual presentation. But the
Jewish Museum at Fifth Avenue and 92d Street has not flinched from
efforts to make the story viewer-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   When the museum reopened in 1993 after extensive renovations,
one of its chief presentations was an ambitious permanent
exhibition, ``Culture and Continuity: The Jewish Journey.''
Occupying two floors, it traces Judaism from 1200 BCE to the
present with graphics, photographs, maps, texts and objects taken
largely from the museum's collection, bolstered by loans.
</P>
<P>
   Over time some parts began to look a little dated. So, to
enhance and streamline the exhibition, the museum has embarked on a
two-stage reinstallation. The first stage, dealing with the ancient
world and the early Diaspora, has opened on the fourth floor. The
second stage, which continues the story to the present, is to be
completed by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Compressing thousands of years of a civilization into a magazine
layout with sound, so to speak, is not the ideal educational
approach. But despite cramped quarters, the exhibition effectively
displays a sampling of the collection's 28,000 objects while
providing a capsule introduction to Judaism. What is now on view,
in the first and in part of the second of the exhibition's four
major divisions, is a more sophisticated presentation with a less
cluttered format and it is easier to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in objects, including additional works from the
collection and the use of video monitors to show a spectrum of
material not exhibited, provide a more varied arrangement. The
galleries and showcases have been redesigned with new lighting and
better-placed texts to emphasize the highlights of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Simplified maps, timelines and documentary photomurals
strengthen the viewer's sense of where and when. And there is more
emphasis on the global nature of the Jewish experience. However, a
few objects are replicas or _ as with a case of Torah scrolls from
the 18th to 20th centuries _ later examples of unobtainable earlier
objects. Help in exploring the show is provided by random-access
audio guides that allow listeners to hear explanations in any order
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, as the briefest of briefings on Jewish history and
culture, this presentation is an improvement. It was organized by
two members of the museum staff, Fred Wasserman, director of
curatorial administration, and Dr. Susan L. Braunstein, curator of
archaeology and Judaica.
</P>
<P>
   To begin, visitors walk through two rooms of introductory
material that focus on what has kept Jews together for so long.
Four simple stone plinths, each engraved with a biblical quotation,
suggest basic explanations: a unifying tradition founded on a
covenant with God, the shared ordeal of exile in Egypt, acceptance
of a code of laws based on divine revelation, and the promise of
the land of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes ``Forging an Identity: 1200 BCE-640 CE,'' the first
of the exhibition's four divisions. It covers the transition of
Israelites into Jews. The Israelites lived on their own land, were
led by kings and priests and worshiped through animal sacrifice.
Because of the Diaspora they became Jews, stateless people under
foreign rule throughout the ancient world, who turned to worship
through prayer and Bible study with the guidance of rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Farming _ the cultivation of olives, wheat, dates, barley, sheep
and goats _ occupied most early Israelites. One exhibit, set
against a photomural of the green Judean hills, shows primitive
implements like hoes, pickaxes, plow points and storage jugs, some
dating to 2,000 BCE.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby display devoted to sacrifices and offerings includes
one of the show's highlights: a small but assertive terra cotta
female figurine with hands on hips and ample breasts (600-700 BCE).
Some scholars consider her a representation of Asherah, the
possible mate of God.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting artifacts in the exhibition are from the
Diaspora, after the Babylonian sack of Jerusalem in 586 BCE and the
destruction of the Temple built by Solomon some 400 years earlier.
These events brought about the exile of the ruling class of Judah,
one of the two Israelite nations, and forced many of its citizens
into slavery. Scattered to other lands, the Israelites became
culturally integrated into their new communities while trying to
keep their traditional ways. (Later, liberated by Cyrus, the
Persian king who conquered Babylonia in 538 BCE, many returned to
Israel and rebuilt the Temple.)
</P>
<P>
   A rare object from the Jewish community of Rome, established in
the second century BCE, is glass from the fourth century, the
circular bottom of a bottle, with a Jewish burial inscription in
Greek and Hebrew commemorating a mother and a daughter. Also
depicting ceremonial objects _ a shofar and a menorah _ the glass
was probably set into the wall of a catacomb, the customary form of
Jewish burial at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That Israelites lived with the gods of their new rulers is seen
in several artifacts from Beit Shean, a city in central Israel that
accepted Greek rule in the second century BCE and was renamed
Scythopolis. One is a huge carved marble toe from a colossal cult
statue taken from a temple honoring Dionysius or Astarte, the
Phoenician goddesses of fertility. It is displayed with a stone
helmet of Castor or Pollux, the sons of Zeus, from the Isis Temple
in Samaria (third century BCE).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Forced to worship in exile without the Temple and its tradition
of animal sacrifices performed by an elite priesthood, the Diaspora
exiles turned to personal prayer and study of the Torah, the first
five books of the Bible. Despite the rebuilding of the Temple in
516 BCE, they eventually established synagogues as less lofty
communal centers for this new form of worship, which became the
primary distinction between the Israelite religion and Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   A one-third-scale replica (with several original ceiling tiles)
of the third-century Dura-Europos Synagogue, from a Euphrates River
frontier fort in what is now Syria, shows wall frescoes depicting
biblical scenes. When first discovered in 1932 the frescoes caused
a shock because they contradicted the widespread belief that the
ancient Jewish religion forbade figurative art. Pagan imagery is
even evident in the ceiling tiles, one depicting Demeter, Greek
goddess of fertility. But rabbinic discussions at the time
indicated that pagan symbols could be used as decoration if they
were not objects of worship.
</P>
<P>
   The periodic uprisings of Jews against their conquerors is
illustrated by the disastrous rebellion of 66-70 against the
Romans, which again brought about Jerusalem's destruction, along
with that of the Second Temple. The event illustrated by a massive
foundation stone of the fortification wall that the Romans
breached. A photomural of a detail from the Arch of Titus, built in
Rome as a further commemoration of the victory, depicts soldiers
carrying off a menorah and other Temple property to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The show segues at about this point into ``Interpreting a
Tradition,'' the second section of the four-part exhibition, still
only partly completed. It's a lot more vivacious. Meant to convey
the vitality and diversity of Jewish life in the Diaspora, it draws
on objects and photographs from all over the world, including
enlarged photographs of a cross section of Jews, among them an
Arizona pioneer, Charles Strauss, and his young son, dressed as
rifle-packing cowboys (circa 1880).
</P>
<P>
   A quote (1781) from the Irish political philosopher Edmund
Burke, ``From the east to the west, from one end of the world to
the other, (Jews) are scattered and connected,'' introduces a
wonderful display of objects, from the silver sugar bowl of an 1861
breakfast set given to a Baltimore rabbi by his congregation, to an
18th-century Chinese figurine of a ``semitic merchant'' in glazed
terra cotta from the Tang dynasty. Monitors show photographs of
many other items.
</P>
<P>
   But the piece de resistance is a huge display of Hanukkah lamps
from various places and centuries. Most are silver, but they range
from serious endeavors, like the intricately worked 18th-century
sculptural form from Galicia that depicts a Torah ark, to the
lighthearted wood structure made in 1974 by Mae Shafter Rockland of
Princeton, N.J. On a platform covered with the American flag stand
eight plastic figures of the Statue of Liberty, torches raised to
receive the Hanukkah candles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
