<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAINS31-COX     03-30 2146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Come aboard America's private rail cars, the magic carpets made
of steel
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding on the City of New Orleans, Illinois Central Monday
morning rail...
</P>
<P>
   You're trundling north through Louisiana bayous, pulled by
Amtrak Train 58, The City of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours out of the Big Easy, and you're still in the
Mississippi delta, dogwoods blooming in old cedar swamps, shotgun
shacks with last night's rain steaming off tin roofs.
</P>
<P>
   This is not America from 30,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   And the domed observation car you're riding isn't economy class.
It's not even Amtrak. A railroad baron could get used to this car _
opulent, private and built well in the U.S. Henry Flagler would
approve.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Northern Sky, called the most exquisite train car in
America by ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Romance.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 private railroad cars are afield in the land _
sleepers, coaches, lounge cars, even a couple of old mail cars. A
few are corporate-owned, many can be chartered, some are simply the
weekend obsession of their owners _ 90 tons or more of steel and
aluminum graced with carved woods, silk brocade, crystal stemware
and fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be rich to buy one _ $10,000 can get you an
old Pullman, with rusted wheels that still might turn. No, you
don't have to be rich to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing one up is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let's say you're looking at $200,000 as a start, just to
put a car back on the tracks,'' says Dave Hoffman, owner of the
Northern Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you could spend virtually forever on decoration,
maintenance. A million wouldn't be out of line,'' says Hoffman.
``It's like redoing an old house, top to bottom, plumbing,
electrical. Paint. Carpets. An old house on steel wheels that has
to meet Amtrak standards before it moves an inch.''
</P>
<P>
   And then what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   ``America,'' says Hoffman. ``You get America like you can never
get it from 30,000 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed you do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can see America just as well from the worn seat
of an Amtrak coach.
</P>
<P>
   But when you ride a private rail car, your fellow riders will
most likely be history and train buffs, with a great deal to say.
And if you transcend the luscious meals and focus instead on the
views that streak past, you'll see America as it is. As it was.
</P>
<P>
   A train ride is a door on America, maybe the back door or the
servants' entrance.
</P>
<P>
   It's the America Steve Goodman wrote of and Arlo Guthrie sang of
in ``The City of New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   The conductor sings his song again ... this train's got the
disappearing railroad blues.
</P>
<P>
   It was written in 1970, the year Amtrak took over passenger
routes from once-great carriers such as Illinois Central, Sante Fe,
New York Central.
</P>
<P>
   Trains were romantic. Trains were historical. And about to be
history.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger trains were rolling toward a sidetrack to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Into the vacuum stepped people like Dave Hoffman. They want
their railroading to live. For them, railroad museums are a sad
sight. Henry Flagler's green-and-gold car sits on the lawn behind
his Palm Beach house. Built in 1886. Fascinating. Beautiful. But it
will never roll again.
</P>
<P>
   But America is not found inside museums, says Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   He owns not one, but two cars. The other's a sleeper, 11
bedrooms. Both are tagging along on Train 58, north to Chicago.
Nineteen hours. Nine hundred and eighty-two miles. Amtrak charges
Hoffman $1.80 a mile for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen cars and fifteen restless riders, three conductors and
twenty-five sacks of mail.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip to Chicago, the Amtrak part of the City of New
Orleans still pulls 15 cars, but 189 paying passengers are aboard
at $154 a pop, and just one conductor, Ernie Lozano, 30 years on
Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   And the sons of engineers ride their father's magic carpets made
of steel.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano's father was a steam locomotive mechanic in Guatemala
City. Loves the rails, he says. Grew up on them. There's no mail on
board today, hasn't been mail for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Card players?
</P>
<P>
   ``Always card players,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He waves the all aboard at 2:08 on a misty afternoon, two
minutes late, and Train 58 lurches to life on Track 6 in New
Orleans' Union Station. The name evokes the grandeur of another
age, but it's a squat concrete box strewn with yesterday's
newspapers and plastic coffee cups that dance on the wind into dark
corners.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's cars are at the rear of the train, their red and gray
livery fresh and clean. Inside, white snapdragons grace tables.
Nice sound system throughout. Air conditioning, too. The wood is
polished, the wine vintage, the shrimp jumbo and ice-cold.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is hosting about 20 guests. One of them is reading a
history of the transcontinental railroad. The rest are talking
trains. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Sky was built in 1955 for the Union Pacific. Amtrak
picked it up in 1970. It ran on the Auto-Train until 1978. Hoffman
found it in 1990. New, it cost Union Pacific about $500,000.
Hoffman paid less than 10 cents on the dollar, one cent on the
dollar adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like trains,'' says Hoffman. ``Love them, really. Since I
was a kid. So I heard about this car and thought, OK. And my wife,
Marilyn, said, `You're going to what?'''
</P>
<P>
   He's a road contractor, lives in Wisconsin, mid-50s, three kids.
About the same demographics as the other rail-car owners on board _
guys who make private money in small private companies. Some guys
retreat to lakeside cottages, or polish their old Corvettes, or
dabble in fishing or 19th-century landscape art.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and his pals bought railroad cars. They call them iron
mistresses.
</P>
<P>
   The car owners had met in New Orleans for the weekend, members
and associates of the American Association of Private Railroad Car
Owners.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Heard from Fernandina Beach was there, with his 1930
dark-blue Georgia 300, the car Bill Clinton used in a 1992
whistle-stop tour. When he was a kid in Moultrie, Ga., Heard waited
at crossings just to watch that car roll by. He told his pals he'd
own it someday. He does.
</P>
<P>
   Association President Dean McCormick, from Santa Ana, Calif.,
was there, but his car, The Scottish Thistle, was in the shop on
the West Coast. Wheel bearings or brakes or something. There's
always something, he says. And Jim Larson was there, 46 years on
the railroads. He pretty much lives on the rails. Jim Larson knows
everything about trains. Everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grew up near the Boston and Maine?'' he says. ``I knew the
B&AMP;M president, John Berriger, back in the '60s. Good man.''
</P>
<P>
   How many people in the country can name the president of the
B&AMP;M?
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode that passenger train down in Florida,'' says Larson.
``What's it called? Tri-Rail? Strange thing is the stations aren't
where they should be, near stadiums or airports. Good track,
though. And concrete ties. Had dinner at Hoot, Toot and Whistle in
Delray Beach. Had to eat there. The FEC freights run right by.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the paper bag that holds the bottle ...
</P>
<P>
   Not on this train. Northern Sky steward, Louis Nowicki, pours
top-shelf tequila, California cabernet, 12-year-old Scotch. Heavy
crystal goblets. Buckets of cold shrimp. Napkins embossed in gold
with the Northern Sky logo. Nowicki is more innkeeper than steward.
He prepares the 11 bedrooms, handles reservations, gets things
straight with Amtrak. He's been on the train eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best job in the world,'' he says. ``If you don't love
trains when you start, you will soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   While he works the upper level, chef David Klugler is down below
in his kitchen, about the size of a big refrigerator. Klugler has
been on the Northern Sky four years. Tonight, he's cooking up 10
roast chickens, gravy, mashed potatoes, salad, corn, fresh baked
rolls and croissants. And a chocolate cake to murder for. If you
need a snack, he'll slice some cold filet mignon, add a dash of
horseradish and slide it under a hot deli roll, couple of shrimp on
the side.
</P>
<P>
   If it all sounds appealing, their services, along with the car,
cost about $500 per day, per person, says Hoffman. You pick your
trip _ Chicago to L.A., New York to Miami, anywhere there's Amtrak
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a luxury land cruise, a grand hotel on
wheels,'' he says. ``And if it's a business trip, and you're on
this car for three days, well, you have a captive audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealin' card games with the old men in the club car, penny a
point, ain't no one keeping score.
</P>
<P>
   The men talk trains while their wives play a dice game at a big
table in the front of the car. They've heard all the stories.
They're playing for nickels.
</P>
<P>
   They roll dice, and the men talk trains and more trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that trip to Churchill, Ontario, for the polar-bear
migration ...'' ``So I was going across Kenya on the old British
track when ...''
</P>
<P>
   They know all the routes, all the train names, all the train
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Panama Limited made this run from Chicago to New Orleans
in under 15 hours. Fifteen hours, on old track, under steam ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Railroad Post Office was the most efficient in the
country. Killed by JFK and that crony of his, Kenny O'Donnell in,
what, 1962? A real shame. You could walk right up to a mail car and
post a letter through a slot ...''
</P>
<P>
   One fellow starts to tell about fishing in Costa Rica. His table
mates stop and stare, as if to say, fishing?
</P>
<P>
   The conversation rolls on into the gray afternoon. And so does
The City of New Orleans, past farms and fields and red sand roads
that shine with the spring rain. Past junkyards full of old oil
derricks and twisted pipe. Past the backside of the Crescent City,
where wet laundry hangs behind tenaments, and bums sleep under
bridges, and rubber tires smolder in big piles. The back door of
America.
</P>
<P>
   It arrives early in Hammond, La. A prim little station, old
brick stores, neat wood houses framed by azalea. A couple jumps out
of their automobile at the crossing, armed with a camera. They
wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, what a beautiful rail car,'' yells the man. ``I took a
car like that once on the Southern Crescent ... Hey, send me a
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   His name is Eddie Litolff. Everybody loves a train.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Dave Hoffman love them just a little more.
</P>
<P>
   They name their cars. The Palm Beach, built in 1949, is owned by
a fellow in Wisconsin. It ran from New York to Miami until 1978.
The Survivor, built in 1926 for Woolworth heiress Jesse Woolworth,
was a frequent Palm Beach visitor. The new owner lives in Atlanta.
Lives in the car. He named it The Survivor because it did.
</P>
<P>
   And so did the railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Train 58 snakes up the old Natchez Trace, into Jackson, Miss., a
city bypassed by the latest economic boom. The old station is gone,
most of the sidings and platforms, too. The abandoned Noble Hotel
stands near the derelict Hotel King, which looms over an empty
warehouse on a broken street.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Sky looks like a tourist lost in the wrong
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers with their babes asleep, are rockin' to the gentle beat.
And the rhythm of the rails is all they feel.
</P>
<P>
   For 500 miles, a baby has been asleep on Northern Sky. Not a
peep. She wakes just before Memphis, Tenn. A squawk, then she's
rocked back to sleep by the constant roll of the train.
</P>
<P>
   Evening. Passengers repair to their staterooms. Jim Larson is
still telling stories. The time he had to use liquid detergent and
bars of soap to free up an overheated wheel bearing. Got the car
rolling again. The years when 200 trains a day came and went from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime on the City of New Orleans, changing cars in Memphis,
Tennessee. Halfway home, we'll be there by morning ...
</P>
<P>
   The digital speedometer in the Northern Sky observation deck
clicks down from 82 to 50, to 30, to zero. The map on Hoffman's
laptop computer says the train is in Memphis. So does a sign on the
station. The station is a small metal trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Klugler jumps down to stretch his legs. He whistles the
``Battle Hymn of the Republic.'' Good whistler.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hoffman jumps down to check his car, take a walk around and
look under here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Lozano, the conductor, snaps his Amtrak jacket against the
chill. He checks the length of his 15 silver cars, checks
couplings, electrical connections.
</P>
<P>
   A lone taxi waits for fares in the empty parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some railroad car,'' says the cabbie, with a nod to
Northern Sky. ``Beautiful colors. Took one like that back in, what,
1966? On my way to the Army. Lemme tell you about that ride. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's got a train story. Everybody old enough to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Good night, America, how are you ... I'm a train they call the
City of New Orleans ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
