<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BENCHLEY-PROFILE-ART-     03-30 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENCHLEY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR GREAT WHITES: I DIDN'T REALLY MEAN IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT34, has been sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After making a career, not to mention millions, from
swimming with the fishes and living to tell about it, Peter
Benchley, the writer who created and murdered a shark in the
ubiquitous fish story ``Jaws,'' resurfaced in Manhattan the other
day with amnesty on his mind. For himself and for sharks. Don't
blame him for the bad rap sharks have gotten since forever. Please
lend an ear as he tries to undo it. Partly.
</P>
<P>
   Benchley has not forgotten two sharks _ an oceanic whitetip that
ambushed him as he swam in a school of tuna for a Bahamian photo
shoot, then a great white that got the rope from his diving cage
stuck between its teeth like dental floss _ that tried to make a
meal of him since ``Jaws'' made him that rarest of literary
delicacies, an overnight success.
</P>
<P>
   Are sharks capable of plotting revenge? Don't they know Benchley
has claimed he would not write ``Jaws'' today, could not, in good
conscience, demonize them now as he did then? (The eight species of
known killers out of 400 shark varieties have killed an average of
slightly less than one human per year over the last century. Four
of the five people attacked each year survive, as did Benchley.
Twice.)
</P>
<P>
   He beat off the whitetip with the broken broomstick he always
carries for protection, like a set of aquatic brass knuckles,
during dicey dives. His wife, Wendy, spared him from the great
white by coolly reaching out a hand and, as the cameras rolled,
yanking the rope out of the shark's mouth. ``I like to think she
saved my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies indicate sharks have a more sophisticated palate
than previously assumed and far prefer seals to humans. But they
bite first, discriminate later. ``If you happen to be a human,
after one bite, it may be too late for you,'' said Benchley, who
turns 60 this year but still dives at the drop of a hat. ``White
sharks are, for any diver, the apex _ the Tom Cruise of the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, for Benchley, that and then some. ``If I'm elected
pope and win the Nobel Prize, at my funeral they'll still play the
John Williams music from `Jaws.''' Though Benchley has been other
things (reporter, editor, speechwriter for Lyndon B. Johnson), he's
had a boomerang relationship with sharks since childhood summers on
Nantucket. They've been a major meal ticket since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Benchley calls it coincidence that, just in time for the 25th
anniversary of the film version of ``Jaws,'' he and the National
Geographic photographer David Doubilet teamed for a television
special, ``Great White, Deep Trouble'' (April 9, 8 p.m., CNBC),
that makes a case for the conservation of his old nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to slide into the cliche that, 25 years later, I'm
trying to atone for some damage done to them by my book, but that's
nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Benchley owes to sharks, starting with the
malicious, fictitious one he conjured while working for a $7,500
book advance inside a $50 per month office in the bowels of a New
Jersey furnace factory: homes in Princeton, N.J., and Stonington,
Conn.; college educations for his three children; a reputation as
an underwater specialist that has brought him steady employment on
television and radio, in films and the print media.
</P>
<P>
   He was ``a struggling freelance with two kids to feed'' when he
came up with his idea for a shark story after reading a Daily News
account of the harpooning of a 4,550-pound great white by an
eccentric Montauk fisherman, Frank Mundus. (Though Mundus accused
him of stealing his life story, Benchley insists the captain in his
tale, Quint, was a composite of Old Salts from Nantucket, Martha's
Vineyard and Long Island.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I read that newspaper story and thought, `What would happen if
one of those things came around and wouldn't go away?''' said
Benchley, wearing a vaguely nautical navy blazer and khakis, as he
sipped coffee in a hotel before heading to a bookstore for a
magazine-signing (``Never done one of those before'') for National
Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   When he wrote ``Jaws,'' Benchley was not signing much except
ious. ``I was 27 and just out of a White House speechwriting job
I'd been utterly unqualified for,'' he recalled of his job with
LBJ, a fluke that opened his eyes to the fact that presidents lie,
left him cynical about top-level politics and a little ashamed of
his puffball stuff for LBJ. So he went back to freelancing. ``I was
stone broke. It was an atmosphere of survival. There was certainly
no ambition to create a phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also, Benchley said, no truth to the tale that
Doubleday plucked him from obscurity and determined to create him
in the image of his grandfather, the humorist Robert Benchley. A
grandfather he hadn't known and whose humor appears to have been
lost on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 5 when he died, didn't know him except by legend; my
grandfather was a terrible profligate, he made a fortune during the
Depression and spent it on fast women, stuff, and booze in
Hollywood,'' Benchley said. ``His legacy was a $1,500 bar bill at
`21.'''
</P>
<P>
   Benchley, whose father, Nathaniel, a novelist, groomed him to
sink or swim as a writer by charging him to shut himself in a room
each summer vacation day for four hours or 1,000 words, whichever
came first, already knows his own legacy: sharks and more sharks.
``I'm deeply grateful, if one can be deeply grateful to an animal.
Thanks, fellas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
