<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSSIA-BALLET-REVIEW-     03-30 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUSSIAN HAMLET': IT'S NOT EXACTLY HAMLET, BUT MORE A STATE OF
MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ History is treated better in tomes than in tights and
despite appearances, a historical drama is exactly what ``Russian
Hamlet,'' Boris Eifman's new ballet, is not. It is, rather, a work
of extravagant artistic license about Czar Paul I, the unhappy son
of Catherine the Great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian Hamlet'' was, in fact, helpfully subtitled ``Son of
Catherine the Great'' at its U.S. premiere on Wednesday night at
City Center, where the superb dancers of the Eifman Ballet of St.
Petersburg will perform it through Sunday night as part of a
three-week season.
</P>
<P>
   Those who missed this exceptional company on its previous visits
to City Center in 1998 and last year will find that a narrow view
of ballet no longer obtains. If the dancers perform with such
power, it is because Eifman has molded them into perfect creative
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Love him or hate him, Eifman stimulates and provokes. Like
others before him, including Moussorgsky and Pushkin, he is a
Russian artist who sees the intrigues and passions of the Russian
czars as a springboard for his own creativity. ``Russian Hamlet''
is not so much about the historical Paul, who is depicted as a
Hamlet-like prince before he reigned briefly as czar (1796-1801),
as it is about a state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to read the program's printed synopsis to
understand the emotional outpouring and passions on stage. Eifman
has a way with electrifying images and theatrical fantasies (helped
enormously by Slava Okunev's stunning sets) that other
choreographers do not.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the tale, he telegraphs the drama of the moment through
an emblematic image. For Eifman, Paul is a victim, crushed by his
mother and his court. We do not see him murdered by his own guards,
as he was in fact. But we see him in ultimate defeat at the end. As
the empress sweeps across the stage in a huge gold train, the
prince sits on her cape and is pulled along, reduced symbolically
and literally to following in his mother's wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian Hamlet,'' which was commissioned by the Bolshoi Ballet
and was also danced by that company in Moscow last month, is not a
perfect work. As a meditation on relationships, the brilliant first
act yields to a diffuse second half. This is not because it opens
up into a fantasy world full of hallucinations (the ghost of Paul's
murdered father makes regular appearances). But the angst is spread
out. The center shifts from Paul to Catherine and even her lover
has a soliloquy to meditate upon his sins.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Eifman image is always provocative, frequently
outlandish and always daring. It is relevant, never dull. You can
gasp or groan when Catherine and her lover dive onto the throne and
a crowd surrounds them for their lovemaking: only their feet stick
up above the group.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, seen briefly as a child (Alexsander Eifman, the
choreographer's 5-year-old son), suddenly becomes a man-sized child
in a crib, surrounded by dancing nursemaids. His wedding night is a
lyrical arching duet in silhouette behind a pale blue cloth
stretched across the stage. When his bride's lust for power is
symbolized in tangled acrobatics with Paul on the throne, Catherine
has her killed.
</P>
<P>
   Like the men in a Georgian war dance, the palace guards stand in
a three-tiered circle. Each tier consists of men on the shoulders
of those below. In a throat-catching toss upward, the bride leaps
up to the top tier and dangles over the men's arms. The spring
upward is a shock, more than her drop to the ground below.
Catherine, for her part, steps up on the men's backs to the top
tier with measured dignity to look down triumphantly on her prey
below.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, there is a certain cartoon simplicity to some of
Eifman's characters, but this distillation of personality does not
come across as caricature.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the characters are generalized without the names
of the real figures who inspired them. Just as Jose Limon called
Othello ``The Moor'' and Iago ``The Moor's Friend'' in his ``Moor's
Pavane,'' so Catherine here is ``The Empress'' and Paul is ``Son of
the Empress, Heir to the Throne.'' Catherine had so many lovers
that the one on stage is generic, called ``Favorite of the
Empress.'' Paul's bride and first wife, Natalya, becomes ``The Wife
of the Heir'' and Czar Peter III, Paul's murdered father, appears
as ``Ghost of the Heir's Father.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions are primary and, as usual, Eifman's choreography is at
its most thrilling in the duets. There are those who find his
vocabulary limited. One would like to see a Western ballet troupe
attempt the swift, acrobatic and always innovative partnering in
these duets. Even the Bolshoi reportedly had trouble adjusting to
the intricacies of Eifman's style.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, it is a highly expressive style put to dramatic
purpose rather than used as form for its own sake. Eifman draws his
strength from an extension of the ballet idiom and his dancers are
exceptional ballet dancers. He has the power in his narrative
ballets that Kenneth MacMillan and John Cranko did not always
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Where he stumbles is in his attempts to find a new vocabulary.
Growing up in the Soviet Union, a country bereft of modern dance,
he emerged as an un-Soviet choreographer (no uplifting hero in his
ballets) who was not confined to gesture. But the solos he has
choreographed here to expose an interior emotional state often
become one-dimensional. And while the male-female ensembles are
effective in moving the action along, there is a robotic simpleness
to the male groups in the second act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1724EST &QL; 
