<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CORRRECT-CUSACK-LADN &LR;      03-30 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRRECT-CUSACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK OF ALL TRADES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Corrects name of earlier movie to `Gross Pointe Blank.') 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Cusack loves music. Sinatra, Mozart, the Cramps _ you name
it, he'll have an opinion about it. He prefers LPs to CDs, knows
the locations of the best record stores around the world and has
already picked out what song he wants to be played at his funeral
(Jimmy Cliff's ``Many Rivers to Cross,'' unless he changes his mind
again).
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's appreciation for music was evident in ``Gross Pointe
Blank,'' the charmingly offbeat 1997 film that he co-wrote and
co-produced under his New Crime Productions banner. Clash frontman
Joe Strummer scored the movie, and the soundtrack, a nice sampler
of Reagan-era pop music, continues to be a big seller to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's latest film, ``High Fidelity,'' continues along the
same path. Cusack and his Evanston, Ill., pals Steve Pink and D.V.
DeVincentis have again written the screenplay, adapting Nick
Hornby's novel about a music junkie trying to figure out women. The
film, which is often set in a barely functioning record store,
features 65 different songs, ranging from classic rock to cult
bands like the Thirteenth Floor Elevators and the Beta Band.
</P>
<P>
   Here we talk to the 33-year-old Cusack about his feelings for
rock, ``Crocodile'' and otherwise, his proclivity for wearing Clash
T-shirts in his films and why music always seems to sound better in
a record store.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did you discover music?
</P>
<P>
   A: As soon as my sister (actress Joan Cusack) allowed me into
her room to play 45s on her turntable. There was no turning back
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of stuff did your parents listen to?
</P>
<P>
   A: They would listen to classical and stuff like Gladys Knight
and the Pips and Sinatra. But nothing modern. We'd introduce stuff
to my dad and he'd say, ``Where was I?'' I remember when I got out
of high school, I told him, ``You've got to listen to Bob Dylan.''
He had never heard one of his records.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do your tastes run?
</P>
<P>
   A: All over the map. There's something satisfying about
listening to classical music and then there's something equally
satisfying about listening to music that sounds like it was made in
a concrete bunker underwater with some tape rolling. It makes no
difference, as long as it's got soul creeping through it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``High Fidelity'' features some pretty heated debates among
the three guys working in the record store. Did you and your
co-writers get into the same kind of arguments?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, the battles were huge. It was a war. It was just like in
the book. We'd talk about music and each one of us was absolutely
right beyond a question of a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the biggest fights about?
</P>
<P>
   A: What 65 songs we'd have in the movie. If it were up to those
guys, we would have limited it more to these specialized bands that
nobody knows. Don't get me wrong. I love those groups, but there
comes a point where you have to broaden the range and include songs
for people who don't know as much about music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Like Elton John's ``Crocodile Rock''?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Grimacing) That was (director) Stephen Frears' choice. I
hate that song with a passion to this day, but he liked the faux
innocence of it to match the scene it's in. And that's OK. It's not
that big of a deal. But at the time for us, including ``Crocodile
Rock,'' was a travesty and we made a great big stink about it:
``You can't! You can't!'' That's how obsessive we were about the
music in this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any song you wanted in that didn't make the cut?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was this one Warren Zevon song that I thought was
perfect, but nobody else felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you remember your first concert?
</P>
<P>
   A: I went to a simulcast of the Who just after Kenny Jones
joined them. The first concert that blew off the back of my head
was Fishbone. Back in the day, those guys were great. They were so
ahead of their time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've worn Clash T-shirts in a few of your films. That had
to be another favorite band.
</P>
<P>
   A: Definitely. But I started out listening to ELO, KISS and
Cheap Trick. I guess you'd consider them guilty pleasures, but
those were the bands that I cut my teeth on. You know, when you're
13, 14 years old and you want to figure out what's radical and you
realize you can be an individual and buy stuff that your parents
don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what was your parents' reaction?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think, like all parents, they didn't understand what the
hell we were listening to. There was this store in Chicago, Rick's
Record Exchange, that's just like Championship Vinyl (the record
store in the movie). I used to go there every day after school and
listen to music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You must have a pretty fair collection.
</P>
<P>
   A: You'd think. But I don't collect. I have things and then they
go away. I don't have a place where things stay. It's probably
because I'm so disorganized. I'll grab a CD to go somewhere and
I'll leave it in somebody's car. I'll go out and buy stuff ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you just won't hold onto it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Right. I mean, I'll be in a record store and hear something
great, buy it, listen to it for a while and then it's gone. But in
my head, I'll have it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does music always sound better when you're listening to
it in a record store?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a good question. It's true. I've bought albums I've
heard in stores and then when I listen to them again, I wonder what
the hell I was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because everybody goes to a record store hoping to
find that piece of treasure and you have all that energy around
you. It's almost a sacred observance. Everybody's kind of serious
when they're in a record store. You know what I mean? There's this
undercurrent of focus where people are looking, looking, searching
for something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the last treasure you've found?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's this band called Ozomatli. The music is like a
cross-cultural block party.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you say you agree with your ``High Fidelity'' character
that Jimmy Cliff's ``Many Rivers to Cross'' would be your funeral
song?
</P>
<P>
   A: That would do just fine. (Pause) But then again ... actually
... nah, I'd probably want Bob Marley. He'd turn it into a party.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It doesn't usually turn out that way despite the best of
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't, does it? Maybe we could start with Cliff and
segue into Marley. You've got to give it a try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS-REFUSE31-COX     03-30 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-REFUSE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN UNASKED CENSUS QUESTION: HOW MANY DISTRUST THE GOVERNMENT?
 &HT;    770&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many Americans, Census Day, April 1, is a day
of protest. Don't mail in your form, they urge, or if you do, don't
answer every one of those nosy questions.
</P>
<P>
   They are the census refuseniks _ a small but growing number of
Americans who refuse to fill out the questionnaire because they
feel it represents undue government intrusion in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that this is a modern society and that the
government needs information, but I just don't like it,'' said
Howard McCarthy, 62, a commercial real estate developer in
Lakeport, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his life, McCarthy intends to break the
law in an act of civil disobedience. Fed up with the federal
bureaucracy, he says he left some answers blank and answered others
incorrectly on his copy of the 53-question long form.
</P>
<P>
   The founding fathers designed the census to count people.
Questions such as his race, age and how much he earns go too far,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last census in 1990, the level of mistrust Americans
have about the federal government has grown, a phenomenon that the
Census Bureau acknowledges as one of its chief challenges as it
tries to coax 120 million households to respond to the form, or a
less detailed short form.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent Capitol Hill Republicans, including Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, have told their
constituents not to answer questions they deem objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people to throw it in the trash,'' said Lott
spokesman John Czwartacki. ``We encourage them to fill out all the
questions. But we'd rather them leave blank the ones they find
objectionable than not to reply to the census at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Census Director Kenneth Prewitt has received plenty of calls and
e-mail in the past few weeks from irate Americans telling him just
what he can do with the form. The census has been a hot topic in
recent weeks on talk-radio stations and Internet chat sites.
Commentator Andy Rooney of CBS's ``60 Minutes'' fueled the debate
on Sunday's program when he ranted about the long form.
</P>
<P>
   Most American households received the short form. It has only
eight basic questions, including name, age, race and number of
people living in your house. The in-depth long form probes deeper
into topics such as income, housing and lifestyle; it was sent to 1
of every 6 households.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution mandates a national head count every 10 years
to apportion seats in Congress. Prewitt defended the long form
Thursday as ``an essential tool'' in determining the needs of
communities across the country. The census also determines the
distribution of spending for education, health care, emergency
services and other public services.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt points out that every question is on the long form for a
reason, primarily dealing with the distribution of federal money to
the states and tied to specific laws passed by Congress. Only one
new question was added to the 2000 census long form, concerning
grandparents who are the prime caregivers to their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a question on the form that hasn't been put there
by Congress. So Congress is having an argument with itself and not
with the Census Bureau,'' said Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary survey by the Census Bureau shows that its
extensive promotional campaign is having little effect on the
people wary of the federal government and the census. ``The ad
campaign is reaching them, but it's having a hard time convincing
them,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Edwards, 43, a community activist in Chicago, says he threw
his long form into the trash the day it arrived. Using his Internet
nickname ``the Viscount,'' he's expressed his views on a Yahoo.com
message board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of any rational reason as to why they would
want this information. It's just none of their damn business,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much I paid for utilities? I don't get that. Why do they
need to know that?'' said Mike McBride, 31, a computer network
engineer in Columbus, Ohio. He received the long form but plans to
fill out only the eight questions asked on the short form and leave
the rest blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the scandals that have come along and more. Things
like the FBI files showing up at the White House. It makes me
think, yeah, legally they weren't supposed to be there. But they
were. Well, what if that happens to my census form? It's supposed
to be confidential. But what if Congress passes a new law six
months from now saying it isn't?'' said McBride.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, the Census Bureau had received 46 percent of
the forms it sent out, an encouraging response toward its goal of a
70 percent response rate before census workers go into the field on
April 11 and begin knocking on doors of those who have not returned
their questionnaires. In 1990, only 65 percent of Americans
returned their forms.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are legally required to fill out their forms. There is
a $100 fine for failing to return the questionnaire and a $500 fine
for providing false information.
</P>
<P>
   But the law has rarely been enforced because of a Catch-22: its
policy never to share the forms it receives with other federal
agencies means the Census Bureau cannot use its information to ask
the Justice Department to seek prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Public confidence in government eroded following the Watergate
scandal in the 1970s and has taken a further dip in the 1990s
following President Clinton's woes with Whitewater and Monica
Lewinsky and the scandals surrounding former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and other members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll in late February found that 50 percent of all
Americans do not believe the Census Bureau when it says the
information and identity on census forms will not be shared with
other government agencies and 60 percent believe the government
cannot protect the information from computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the skepticism, eight of 10 Americans said that
their answers matter and that the census is a useful process, the
Gallup poll found.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., has urged people to answer just the
first six questions on the long form and to send it back to the
Census Bureau with a letter of protest. In a statement issued
earlier this week, Coburn said he was ``appalled and outraged by
the intrusiveness'' of the census questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt said Thursday that
Republicans were conducting a campaign to keep response to the
census low. ``The Republicans have been trying to frustrate this
census from the beginning. They don't want more people counted
because they think it serves their political purposes. That's a
pretty shoddy reason to do what they're doing,'' he told reporters
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
