<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON WEEKEND TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commercial television is rarely hospitable to new concepts, so
the trick is to fuse familiar ingredients in an innovative, or at
least pleasing, manner. So here's ``D.C.,'' the earnest drama
series that the WB network is unveiling on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of five improbably attractive young adults
sharing a house (and their innermost thoughts) in Washington while
they try to grab hold of the bottommost rung of the power ladder.
</P>
<P>
   An echo of ``The Real World''? A whiff of ``The West Wing''? A
digit of ``90210''? Yes. But, curiously, there is scant evidence of
the wearily wise grown-up sensibility you expect from the new
show's executive producer, Dick Wolf, who presides so successfully
over the ``Law and Order'' franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of ``D.C.'' is the oft-tested friendship between two
recent college graduates. You can tell that Mason Scott comes from
money: he has two last names. His pal Pete Komisky has just one,
and it's vaguely ethnic, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, an idealistic Capitol Hill gofer and Harvard grad, is
played by Gabriel Olds, a real-life Yale grad who appeared on
Broadway in ``A View From the Bridge.'' Pete, a would-be
pragmatist, womanizer and lobbyist (state college, naturally), is
Mark-Paul Gosselaar, who grew up in full view during the endless
run of the children's series ``Saved by the Bell.'' These actors
make an easy-to-take pair of buddies, guys who can still taste
adolescence as they stuff their frames and dreams uncomfortably
into suits.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, do they have a lot to learn. As Pete says to Mason in next
Sunday's installment, ``Until I got to D.C., I thought Brooks
Brothers was a country band.''
</P>
<P>
   In this Sunday's scene-setting episode, Pete and Mason are
living in a dingy apartment when Mason's twin sister, Finley (she
has two last names, too), shows up, announcing that she is quitting
graduate school to find her destiny in Washington. She is played by
Jacinda Barrett, who joins this fake ``Real World'' after spending
a season living under glass on the real ``Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason can't miss the vibes flying between his sister and his
pal. He declares: ``I have enough stress at work. I don't need two
little pheromone factories running in my apartment.'' (Judging from
the first two episodes, when Finley and Pete do get together
they'll do so discreetly.)
</P>
<P>
   Finley uses her wiles and family connections to get the trio an
open-ended house-sitting assignment minding a gorgeous town house,
which has room for at least two more. That would be Sarah Logan
(Kristanna Loken), a junior producer for a CNN-type news operation,
and her boyfriend, Lewis Freeman (Daniel Sunjata), a Supreme Court
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour also squeezes in a subplot about Mason's effort
to serve the senator for whom he works (played with appropriate
smarminess by Len Cariou in a guest role). Trying to deal with the
vexing issue of the red ring-tailed squirrel, whose forest sits
smack in the path of progress, Mason finds a compromise. His good
deed goes punished, of course, as he suffers what promises to be a
weekly character-building rude awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Pete is philosophical. ``Who'd have thought Washington would be
so political?'' he asks with a smirk. But Mason's optimism is not
diminished. ``Think about it,'' he says, ``our entire lives are
ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people think they'll live forever. Young television shows
can't afford such naivete. So now that the characters have been
established, Wolf and his co-conspirators had better dream up some
stronger lines for them. Borrowed though the elements of the show
may be, the premise has promise. With luck, ``D.C.'' will last
longer than the presidential campaign. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `D.C.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on WB (Channel 11 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Wolf Films in association with Studios USA
Television. Created by Dick Wolf and John August. Wolf, executive
producer; Peter Jankowski, James Andrew Miller and Arthur Forney,
co-executive producers; John L. Roman, producer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Jacinda Barrett (Finley Scott), Mark-Paul Gosselaar (Pete
Komisky), Kristanna Loken (Sarah Logan), Gabriel Olds (Mason
Scott), Daniel Sunjata (Lewis Freeman) and Len Cariou (Senator
Abbott).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
