<HEADER>
A2503 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES30-COX     03-30 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrity seduces writers, `Plainsong' author fears
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe Kent Haruf should have called his National Book
Award-nominated novel ``Eyes Wide Shut'' instead of ``Plainsong.''
To set the mood for his story of a pregnant teenager, two bachelor
brothers and other inhabitants of a small Colorado town, Haruf
hunkered down in his unheated basement, pulled a stocking cap down
over his eyes and blindly wrote the first draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty crazy,'' says Haruf, 57, a soft-spoken professor
at Southern Illinois University, ``but it seemed to work for me. It
was a way of not paying attention to the extraneous things, and not
being analytical. You can't go back and rewrite a sentence; it's
storytelling, not polishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique did indeed work. Critics raved about the simply
told story of complex relationships. As New York Times reviewer
Michiko Kakutani wrote: ``He has conjured up an entire community
and ineluctably immersed the reader in its dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   Haruf is used to such praise. He won a Whiting Writers' Award
and a PEN/Hemingway Foundation citation for his first book, ``The
Tie That Binds.'' It's the author-as-celebrity syndrome that comes
with the acclaim that bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it's healthy for writers to be anything but
ordinary,'' Haruf says. ``I think most writers have not written
nearly as well after they have gotten some fame. It's seductive and
troublesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says, when a publisher pours a lot of money into
marketing a novel, the author has an obligation to dutifully go on
book tours. That's why Haruf is on the road again, talking about
not only ``Plainsong'' but also the new paperback editions of ``The
Tie That Binds'' and ``Where You Once Belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   Haruf will read and sign copies of his books at 7 p.m. April 6
at Chapter 11 bookstore at Ansley Mall. 1544 Piedmont Ave. N.E.,
404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Award winners: Two books and a work in progress have won the
J. Anthony Lukas Prize for superb nonfiction writing. One of two
$10,000 prizes from Columbia University went to Witold Rybczynski
for his book about one of the world's great landscape designers,
titled ``Clearing in the Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and
America in the Nineteenth Century.'' The second $10,000 prize is
for a book chronicling the American post-World War II occupation of
Japan, John W. Dower's ``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of
World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Named for the late Pulitzer Prize-winning author J. Anthony
Lukas, the awards are co-administered by the Columbia University
Graduate School of Journalism and the Nieman Foundation at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mystery nominees: Atlanta writer Ruth Birmingham (the pen name
of Walter Sorrells) is one of five finalists for best paperback
original in the Edgar Allan Poe Awards competition.
Birmingham/Sorrells was nominated for ``Fulton County Blues''
(Prime Crime, $5.99), the story of sleuth Sunny Childs'
investigation of the death of a Vietnam veteran who was her late
father's friend. The investigation uncovers secrets that suggest
Childs' father may not have been a war hero after all.
</P>
<P>
   Other paperback finalists are Laura Lippman (``In Big
Trouble''), Tony Dunbar (``Lucky Man''), Mark Graham (``The
Resurrectionist''), and Jose Latour (``The Outcast'').
</P>
<P>
   In the hardback category, finalists are Rennie Airth (``River of
Darkness''), Jan Burke (``Bones''), Robert Crais (``L.A.
Requiem''), Stephen Greenleaf (``Strawberry Sunday'') and Peter
Robinson (``In a Dry Season'').
</P>
<P>
   The awards by the Mystery Writers of America will be presented
May 4 in New York at the Grand Hyatt Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Joining the club: With a few exceptions, most of Oprah
Winfrey's book club selections are downright depressing. The
characters are abused, misused and barely hanging onto a tiny shred
of hope. Oprah's latest choice, Tawni O'Dell's ``Back Roads''
(Viking, $24.95), is no different. Set in a lower-class,
crime-ridden section of western Pennsylvania, the novel chronicles
the life of Harley Altmyer, a teenager trying to raise his three
younger sisters after his mother murders his father and was sent to
jail. This book is not recommended for readers prone to depression.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
