<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-TAXES31-COX     03-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET TAX PANEL FAILS IN LAST ATTEMPT AT CONSENSUS
 &HT;    350&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal commission's last-ditch effort to reach a
consensus on Internet sales taxes failed Thursday when a
contentious telephone conference ended with no new agreements.
</P>
<P>
   That means Congress, which created the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce to sort out thorny tax issues, will not get the
clear advice it had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impasse, a majority of the commissioners agreed they
could send a ``report'' to Congress saying that a majority backed a
tax proposal supported by business interests. It will not include a
minority viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the commission in 1998 to get advice on whether
to force online merchants to collect sales taxes from all
customers. It required the 19-member panel to reach a
``supermajority'' of 13 votes to make a recommendation. The
deadline was April 21.
</P>
<P>
   At its final meeting in Dallas last week, the panel broke into
bitterly divided factions, and finally voting 11-8 for a
business-backed plan.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's phone conference, which could be heard over the
Internet, was thought to offer some hope for last-minute
compromises, but it quickly became clear no one was going to budge.
A simple majority finally voted to issue a report and block
inclusion of a minority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to take this to Congress and the people of the
United States,'' said Gov. James Gilmore, R-Va., chairman of the
commission and leader of the majority bloc. ``We'll let the
American people decide whether they like the report.''
</P>
<P>
   The report will call for extending the current moratorium on new
Internet taxes until 2006 while urging state and local governments
to simplify their sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommends ending sales taxes on any product that can be
distributed digitally, rescinding the current 3 percent federal
excise tax on telecommunications, and permanently extending the
World Trade Organization's moratorium on tariffs and duties on
international electronic transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan commission included representatives from the
Clinton administration, state and local governments, anti-tax
activists and six businesses with major Internet-based operations.
The tax opponents and business representatives, joined by Gilmore,
made up the majority voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   They were charged with examining the issue of sales taxes, and
how they might apply to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, states can require retail stores to collect
sales taxes from customers. But companies that sell by phone, by
mail or on line need do so only in states where they have a
physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   As more business shifts to the Internet, the reduction in tax
collections could cause states to begin losing $10.8 billion
annually within three years, a recent University of Tennessee study
showed.
</P>
<P>
   The eight commissioners who represented federal, state and local
governments say they need that tax revenue to pay for schools,
roads, police and other basic services. They wanted to recommend
that Congress move the nation toward a tax system in which all
merchants will have to collect and remit sales taxes, regardless of
how or where they operate.
</P>
<P>
   The six business representatives on the commission agreed that
states should be able to require tax collections, but they wanted
several major concessions. For example, they want to exempt from
taxes all items that could be ``digitized,'' such as books, music
and movies, even when they are sold the old-fashioned way in
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that would create a gigantic tax loophole for many
merchants. Because the government representatives on the panel
would not go along, the business representatives refused to support
their plan for a new national system for collecting sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The business bloc instead sided with the a group of five members
more opposed to taxes. Together, they made up the 11 votes to
support the moratorium and other tax-limiting measures.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was able to reach broad agreement on some smaller
issues. Its report to Congress will formally recommend that
lawmakers clarify federal welfare guidelines to allow states to
spend certain surplus welfare funds to ``provide needy families
access to computers and the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Another formal recommendation urges Congress ``to explore the
privacy issues involved in the collection and administration of
taxes on electronic commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
