<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPANESE-ART-COLLECTO     03-30 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-ART-COLLECTOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOW OF JAPANESE ART WITH A LAVISH LINEAGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan)  By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary Griggs Burke is a third-generation Japanophile
and a second-generation collector, with these characteristics
descending on the matrilineal side. In the catalog for the large
and lavish exhibition of her collection of Japanese art at the
Metropolitan Museum, which runs through June 25, she writes of a
grandmother whose trips to Asia usually included stops in Japan.
She alludes to her childhood fascination with a black silk kimono
that her mother, Mary Livingston Griggs, brought back from her own
visit to Japan and wore when she posed for a portrait by Whistler.
</P>
<P>
   She describes other fruits of her mother's trip, particularly a
Japanese garden commissioned for the family's large Victorian house
in St. Paul and the influence of the Japanese belief in the
aesthetic potential of all objects. The mother lived by this belief
with a flamboyant ecumenicism: the Victorian house was retrofitted
with 18th-century French rooms and filled with art, artifacts and
furniture from around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   As indicated by the sweep and quality of this show, a partial,
revealingly biased survey of several millennia of Japanese art,
Burke's eclectic childhood environment did not sway her from her
special destiny.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, she saw Japan for herself, on the advice of Walter
Gropius. (She was thinking of building a house; he encouraged
familiarity with Japanese architecture before selecting an
architect.) From the vantage point of the present, this first
encounter with the Japanese way of life and art resembles a pebble
tossed into calm waters, creating ripples that have become larger
and more widely felt with each passing decade.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1954, Burke, with her husband, Jackson Burke, and, after
his death in 1975, on her own, has built the greatest private
collection of Japanese art outside Japan. The Burkes became
benefactors of Japanese scholarship, setting up a foundation that
dispenses study and travel grants and establishing the collection
in its own Manhattan apartment so that, for more than three
decades, it has been accessible to scholars, students, curators and
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Containing nearly 200 objects, this is the largest exhibition of
Japanese art in New York since the last show of works from the
Burke collection, at the Metropolitan in 1975. They range from
Neolithic ceramics from the third millennium B.C., to examples of
nanga painting (inspired by Chinese ink monochrome painting) dating
from the mid-15th to late-18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding in the first category is a large black vase from the
Kofun period (A.D. 300-538) with striking horizontal drips of glaze
that give it a sense of forward, torpedolike propulsion.
Outstanding in the second category is the ``Landscape After Xia
Gui,'' attributed to Tensho Shubun (active from 1414-1463), the
first master of Japanese monochrome painting, and ``Landscape of
the Four Seasons,'' by Kano Tan'yu (1602-1674), both characterized
by daring expanses of blank surface and misty washes. In contrast,
the surface of ``The Gathering of the Orchid Pavilion and Autumn
Festival,'' by Ike Taiga (1723-1776), is lush with deft brushwork.
</P>
<P>
   In between are large-scale Buddhist sculptures and exquisite
mandalas inspired by the sixth-century arrival of Buddhism from
China, handscrolls and hanging scrolls, extravagant Momoyama and
Edo period screens and lacquerware, both distinguished by rich
colors and gold leaf, and exquisitely rustic Edo tea bowls. There
are odd showstoppers, like Kato Nobukiyo's 1792 ink painting of
``Ten Rakan Examining a Painting of White-Robed Kannon,'' an image
of Buddhist disciples gathered around a painting-within-a-painting
of a bodhisattva in which every last pictorial element is
delineated in Chinese characters spelling out a section of the
``Lotus Sutra.''
</P>
<P>
   This show illuminates the cycles of research and development, of
borrowing and transformation, that characterize Japan's cultural
history. It brings the viewer into close contact with indelibly
Japanese qualities: the veneration of natural beauty that has its
origin in the Shinto religion; an appreciation, encouraged by
Shinto, of the rituals and objects of everyday life; and finally, a
vitality and expressiveness, and above all a feeling for materials,
that distinguish Japanese art from its Chinese models.
</P>
<P>
   These various qualities seem to meet in a Late Heian religious
sculpture, carved simply in wood, that personifies a Shinto deity
in human form. Such personification did not occur until after
Buddhism reached Japan and its hierarchy of depicted deities began
to influence Shinto. But while the god is shown in a Buddha-like
pose and has a squarish ascetic face, he is not entirely from
another world: his headdress and his scepter reflect secular
authority and possibly even the style of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting thing about the Burke collection, or at least
the selection displayed here, is that it seems to reflect a
typically Western bias about painting's superiority. Astoundingly,
more than three-quarters of the show's inclusions are
one-of-a-kind, two-dimensional works. At the same time, this
emphasis goes against the Western tendency to appreciate Japanese
culture primarily for its elevation of more lowly forms _ like
ceramics, lacquer and textiles _ to the level of high art while
limiting its two-dimensional achievement to well-known
accomplishments like woodblock prints and screens.
</P>
<P>
   Although the few ceramics and lacquers included here are
outstanding, they serve primarily as illuminating detours or points
of cross-reference along what is by and large an amazing
centuries-long progression of surfaces. Measurable in inches or in
yards, these surfaces have been variously drawn, painted or written
on, sometimes all three. By the time one reaches those magnificent
Momoyama and Edo screens, they have been placed in a context of
pictorial and calligraphic developments in a way rarely seen in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   The viewer will also have been exposed to an extraordinary
give-and-take: between Japanese and Chinese influences, between
religious and secular impulses and purposes, between the innovative
and the conservative, and the natural and the decorative.
</P>
<P>
   After the disconcerting variety of the first gallery, where five
periods, 40 centuries and several media are encompassed by two
dozen objects, the show begins to hit its stride. In the next
gallery, a few ultrarefined 10th- and 11th-century Late Heian works
are mixed in with the more plentiful, rambunctious works of the
13th- and 14th-century Kamakura period. Different as these two
periods were _ one dominated by a highly cultured aristocratic
elite, the other by pragmatic military provincials _ they were
marked by a turning away from China and the blossoming of cultural
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Among the displays, different Japanese motifs and conventions
seem to hatch before the eyes. Portraiture is evident in a small
Kamakura ink rendering of a poetry contest, where the battling
poets are portrayed as individuals, one clearly dismayed by
something the other has just recited. Early signs of caricature and
the grotesque, so central to later Japanese art, are visible in an
excerpt from a scroll that recounts the temptations of the young
Prince Siddhartha (who became the Buddha), showing him meditating
while set upon by hordes of fiendish, smoke-trailing devils.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   One sees the promise of the specifically Japanese landscape
basic to the Momoyama and Edo screens in a distinctive Kamakura
mandala that depicts two shrine complexes in a verdant park.
Buddhist-Shinto gods float in halolike mandorlas in the sky, but
the dramatically tilted aerial view, boxy architecture and natural
details like rolling hills, hovering clouds, deer and blooming
cherry trees all look to the future. So, in their way, do the two
pages from Late Heian poetry albums, scattered with the elegant
kano script that the Japanese distilled from the more difficult
Chinese writing in the ninth century.
</P>
<P>
   Kano script made possible the development of a secular Japanese
literature, beginning with such Late Heian classics as Lady
Murasaki's ``Tales of Genji.'' Genji's adventures, in turn,
inspired some of the earliest narrative scrolls, helping to set in
motion a pictorial style that would culminate in the Momoyama and
Edo screens.
</P>
<P>
   One also sees the germ of the screens in the album leaves
themselves: the calligraphy dances across unusually decorative
paper printed with patterns in mica and stamped with silver leaves.
This practice has its own apotheosis in the breathtaking early
17th-century handscrolls that mingle poetry inscribed by the
influential calligrapher Hon'ami Koetsu with the atmospheric gold
and silver landscape patterns of Tawaraya Sotatsu, who became one
of Edo's greatest screen painters.
</P>
<P>
   Not all roads lead to the great screens. After one
knee-weakening Edo-screen moment, dominated by monumental images of
curving bridges and spacious scenes from ``Genji'' (the latter
attributed to Sotatsu), come pleasantly minuscule echoes: a white
Mino ware bowl with the tiniest intimation of a figure on a bridge,
and Tosa Mitsunori's little album of white-on-white scenes from
Genji. Both are as affecting as anything else in this ravishing
show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2511 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FUNDY-STJOHN02-COX     03-30 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDY-STJOHN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A world of influences in surprising Saint John
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT JOHN, New Brunswick _ The first thing a visitor notices,
undeniably, are the smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   Towering exhaust shafts atop area pulp mills and refineries loom
over this working-class city on the Bay of Fundy _ population,
125,000 _ like noxious shrines to the gods of commerce. Around
these parts, those gods are called Irving, the name of a local
family that made it big in shipping, timber, paper production and
oil. Visitors flying or driving into Saint John for the first time
may feel like they're entering the Newark of New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   But, to borrow the movie poster come-on from ``American
Beauty,'' look closer: Behind the mask of industry is a charming,
history-rich town that reflects a world of influences.
</P>
<P>
   Stroll along the Loyalist Trail, which visits historic sites in
the heart of downtown, and you may think you're in jolly old
London. Canada's oldest incorporated city, Saint John (spelled out
so the post office won't confuse it with St. John's in
Newfoundland) was founded in 1783 by British loyalists who
abandoned the states during the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The trail reflects the settlers' Anglo bent. Amble down the
paths in King's Square, an idyllic park laid out in the shape of
the Union Jack. Wander around the Loyalist Burial Grounds, where
settlers are stacked nine deep. And check out the street names in
the picturesque Trinity Royal district _ they include King, Queen,
Princess and Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, pop into O'Leary's on Princess Street and you'll be
transported to downtown Dublin. In this raucous pub, and in other
neighborhood establishments such as the knickknack shop House of
Tara, you'll see the influence of the next culture to dominate
Saint John.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1800s, thousands of Irish immigrants fleeing the
potato famine landed on Partridge Island, Canada's version of Ellis
Island, about two-thirds of a mile out in Saint John Harbour. Many
died under quarantine there _ you can still find the foundation of
a hospital and a cemetery on the deserted island. Today, their
descendants and subsequent Irish immigrants make up 60 percent of
Saint John's population.
</P>
<P>
   This is a town that celebrates St. Patrick's Week. Each year in
the days leading up to March 17, there are charity breakfasts for
the children of Belfast, rousing sets of Celtic music at O'Leary's,
Irish plays at the Imperial Theatre and traditional religious
observances at local churches.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Saint Johners with green in their veins and they'll tell you
the celebration doesn't end when the week's up. ``Every day is St.
Patrick's Day when you're Irish,'' says House of Tara owner
Anne-Marie Mullin, whose ancestors hail from County Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Stand on the corner of Germain and Princess streets in the
Trinity Royal district and you'll get the feeling you're in
Boston's Back Bay, or on a quiet side street on Manhattan's Upper
East Side. The elegant brownstones lining Germain were, in fact,
designed by architects from Boston and New York. They were brought
in to help rebuild the city after it was nearly destroyed by fire
in 1877, which started in a hay shed down on the wharf.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilt structures were done in the high Victorian style of
the time, with rounded windows and intricate ornamentation. On an
overcast day the street can look like a scene straight out of ``The
Alienist.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the more fresh-faced, touristy side of Saint John,
represented by Market Square and Brunswick Square, conjoined
shopping and entertainment complexes. The malls are connected by an
elevated, indoor pedestrian crossing that offers winterproof access
to stores, restaurants, an aquatic center and a hockey arena, home
to a farm team for the Calgary Flames. You'll also find two
must-see attractions.
</P>
<P>
   In Market Square, there's the New Brunswick Museum, a
three-story industry, natural history and art museum that rivals
institutions in cities many times the size of Saint John. One
exhibit, a series of huge globes, details the geographical
evolution of New Brunswick; another features the skeleton of
Delilah, a right whale who washed up on nearby Grand Manan Island
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick Square connects to the Old City Market, a sprawling
farmers' market, the oldest in Canada, that offers fresh seafood,
produce and meats, and souvenir trinkets and quick-stop cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this inviting mix of historical sites and easy-access
shopping, Saint John is a burgeoning tourist destination. This
summer, 85 cruise ships will visit, almost three times as many as
in 1999. Paula Harris, a spokeswoman for the Saint John port
authority, attributes the rise in part to a team effort by all the
Atlantic provinces to market themselves as alternatives to the
mundane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of people who are interested in going someplace
other than the standard cruise destinations like the Caribbean,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Local hospitality can't hurt either. The natives are invariably
good-natured and lack pretense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain speaking is highly valued, as is the politeness of being
succinct,'' says Richard Vaughan, a Toronto playwright originally
from Saint John.
</P>
<P>
   Succinctly put, the people of this off-the-beaten path port
would like you to look their way. Smokestacks be darned.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
