<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2514 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GARDENTOUR02-COX     03-30 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENTOUR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paint town green in Toronto's gardens
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toronto _ If you're visiting here for only a couple of days,
there are plenty of gardens worth checking out within walking
distance of downtown hotels.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're lucky enough to manage an extended stay, the list
of must-stops can take you across Lake Ontario or into suburban
mainland towns, all within an hour's drive.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you garden or just lust over beautiful gardens, don't
miss these sites, beginning downtown and then venturing out. And
don't forget your best sneakers, some sunscreen and plenty of film.
</P>
<P>
   CASA LOMA
</P>
<P>
   AND SPADINA
</P>
<P>
   There's a lovely tale of civic support behind the beauty of the
gardens of Casa Loma, the majestic castle in the heart of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Financial ruin tints the history of the biggest private home
ever built in Canada, and the city's most famous landmark after the
CN Tower _ the world's tallest building. The 5-acre estate is the
legacy of Sir Henry Mill Pellatt, a prominent Canadian financier,
who lost his fortune in 1914 just as he was completing the castle.
The city seized the property for back taxes, and the gardens
succumbed to the forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the gardens are a prime attraction, thanks to a
restoration by the Garden Club of Toronto. A vaulted marble
conservatory overlooks a formal terraced garden accessed by a pair
of stone stairways at the east and west ends re-created from their
original stone. The property was redesigned as a series of eight
specialty gardens, including upper and lower terraces, an 80-foot
rose arbor that leads to a secret garden, perennial gardens and a
woodlands walk. The gardens feature a century-old ginkgo tree, rare
Japanese tree peonies, 100 varieties of roses and more than 200
types of perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Casa Loma, at 1 Austin Terrace, is open 9:30 a.m.-4 p.m. daily
from May through October. Guided garden tours are available.
Information: 416-923-1171.
</P>
<P>
   While here, wander next door to historic Spadina, an 1866
mansion that was once home to financier James Austin. Its Victorian
gardens, also restored by the Garden Club of Toronto, offer a
magnificent view of the city and include an interesting mix of
fruit orchards, grape arbors and cutting gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the house and gardens, at 285 Spadina Road, is $5.
Hours vary so call 416-392-6910 for information.
</P>
<P>
   ART AND MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   GARDENS
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's waterfront is a hub of activity because its
restaurants, parks and docks make it so pedestrian friendly. Amid
the noise of streetcars and other traffic are 13 oases of
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, the Ontario Arts Council and Sheridan
Nurseries developed this string of unique gardens near Harborfront
Centre. Artists and landscape designers were selected to create
spaces with concepts from the lofty to the whimsical. Six of the
gardens are seasonal installations, while the rest are permanent
and feature metal sculptures as focal points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came by to see the gardens, but it's almost like you're in
an art gallery, too,'' said Carolyn Stokes, visiting the city from
Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest gardens is the six-block Music Garden created
by landscape designer Julie Moir Messery in collaboration with
renowned cellist Yo-Yo Ma. The design was inspired by Bach's
``Suites for Unaccompanied Cello,'' and each section corresponds to
a movement in the piece. Winding pathways within some sections of
the public park mimic the shape of musical clefs.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO ISLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Ward's and Algonquin islands _ two of the 15 lying east of the
city _ are as rich in history as they are in plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 19th century, Toronto residents seeking an escape
from city life built cottages here to fish, skate and sail their
iceboats. But much of that lifestyle changed in 1953 as the Metro
Toronto Council made a radical shift in policy toward the islands
in efforts to modernize a retreat frozen in time. The city
transferred its land leases to the council, and businesses were
sold and houses demolished. As the leases came up, the city
reclaimed the land for parks. Residents protested the dissolution
of their community and in 1993 established a trust that procured
99-year leases on the remaining property.
</P>
<P>
   Today, competition for the land, with its panoramic view of the
city, is so stiff some buyers wait 10 years for a lot in the
community spanning the contiguous Ward's and Algonquin islands.
Sandy bike paths and dirt alleys form a grid on the vehicle-less
islands, accessed by ferry and boats. Many of the nearly 300
residents are artists who years ago found the seclusion a haven for
painting or sculpting, and their pieces make quite the statement in
some of the cottage gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Here, gardeners emphasize plants that thrive in the moist, sandy
soil warmed by the lake. Wildflowers, milkweed and goldenrod are
staples, as are foxgloves, forget-me-nots, wild roses and water
hyacinths. And the gardeners don't hesitate to share a bloom or two
with admiring passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of their gardens can be enjoyed from the street,
residents leave their gates ajar every other year for public tours.
This year's Toronto Islands Garden Tours is in August. Call
416-203-2500.
</P>
<P>
   PICOV'S WATER
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN CENTRE
</P>
<P>
   AND FISHERIES
</P>
<P>
   Any gardener away from home for long periods experiences soil
withdrawal. For many, the antidote is to shop for the garden when
they can't work in it. Picov's Water Garden Centre and Fisheries in
suburban Ajax is one of those must-stops.
</P>
<P>
   At 10,000 square feet, the family-owned operation is the largest
water garden retailer in North America, offering everything from
state-of-the-art pumps and equipment to plants and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Brightly colored Japanese koi have become popular ingredients
for home water gardens, employee Tina Carpenter said. One frequent
question is how the fish survive Toronto's winters. Holding tanks
are 3 to 6 feet deep so that the fish have room to hibernate at the
bottom, where the water is warmer. (Homeowners learn quickly to
avoid shallow ponds.)
</P>
<P>
   Picov's, at 380 Kingston Road E., is open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. daily.
Call 905-686-2151.
</P>
<P>
   CULLEN GARDENS AND
</P>
<P>
   MINIATURE VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Floral Peacock, with a 55-foot-wide tail made of 3,400
plants, seems more like a Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade float than
a horticultural attraction. But it's the most photographed exhibit
at Cullen Gardens and Miniature Village, a quirky family attraction
in nearby Whitby that's part display garden and part amusement
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come mostly to see the flowers,'' said owner Len
Cullen, who opened the site 20 years ago. The 1,600-square-foot
miniature village is a model of Main Street in the typical southern
Ontario small town. The outdoor display, similar to a gigantic
railroad garden, contains more than 160 models crafted at one-inch
scale. The ``town'' is populated by 600 little people staged in
various aspects of everyday life. Boats zip across a pond, while a
train chugs through a tunnel beneath your feet.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Cullen added gardens, and today the park is
known as much for its kaleidoscope of colorful annuals as for its
miniature village. Beds and baskets overflow with red, green and
purple coleus, chartreuse sweet potato vines, red impatiens and
orange marigolds.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that Floral Peacock. The 65-foot-long form,
made of half-inch rebar, is stuffed with 9,000 plants that extend
to the ground, where its spread of ``feathers'' stretches along a
hillside. Two dozen plants form the feathers, including ageratum,
impatiens, dusty miller, marigolds, begonias and cleome.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen's wacky world of plants doesn't end with the first frost.
``A big time for us is Halloween, when we dress the place up with
lots of spooks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fall, thousands of chrysanthemums take center stage. In April
and May, daffodils, irises and 80,000 tulips scream ``spring'' to
winter-weary Canadians, while in June, the park is ablaze with a
rainbow of 10,000 fragrant roses.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens, at 300 Taunton Road W., are open 10 a.m. to 8 p.m.
daily, April through December. Admission, $12. Call 905-686-1600.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL BOTANICAL
</P>
<P>
   GARDENS
</P>
<P>
   If you have time to visit only a couple of gardens outside
Toronto, this should top your list.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Botanical Gardens, established in 1929, has blossomed
into Canada's largest botanical garden. The site, along the western
tip of Lake Ontario near Hamilton, boasts the largest collection of
fragrant lilacs, 100,000 spring-flowering bulbs, a children's
Discovery Garden, a natural habitat and international center for
plant research.
</P>
<P>
   The property spans 2,700 acres, yet only about 300 are
cultivated. The rest is a natural sanctuary sheltering many plants,
birds and mammals associated with those of the southeastern United
States, thanks to the lake-warmed climate.
</P>
<P>
   The developed areas include the Laking Garden, which features an
English border with 600 cultivars of waist-high bearded irises, new
perennials and ecological, or low-maintenance, plantings.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Rock Garden, a landscaped amphitheater on the
site of an old abandoned granite pit that erupts each spring with
thousands of tulips. ``But one thing we're doing is putting in more
and more perennials,'' said Chris Graham, the gardens' horticulture
director. ``It doesn't make sense to bring in so many annuals each
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other major areas are the Rose Garden and the Arboretum,
home to more than 800 varieties of lilacs.
</P>
<P>
   And for those gardeners seeking practical ideas, there's the
World of Botany Garden, containing four beds representing the four
corners of the world, each filled with flowering perennials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created demonstration borders here with the hope that
homeowners can replicate them in their own gardens,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Botanical Gardens are open 9 a.m. to dusk daily.
Admission: $7. Information: 905-527-1158.
</P>
<P>
   NIAGARA PARKS BOTANICAL GARDENS
</P>
<P>
   Niagara's not just for honeymooners; it's for folks with plant
passions, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara Parks Botanical Gardens, a good day trip while in
Toronto, straddles 100 acres along the Niagara River. Don't miss
its Victorian rose garden, display vegetable garden and ``Annual
Showcase,'' designed as an idea forum for home gardeners. Save
enough time for taking in the Butterfly Conservatory, too, which
houses 2,000 native and exotic species.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens are open from dawn to dusk daily. Admission is free,
except for the Butterfly Conservatory ($8 adults, $4 children).
Information: 877-642-7275.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Toronto tourism information: Contact Tourism Toronto,
1-800-363-1990; www.toronto-tourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
