<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' R (strong sexuality, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   violence and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey
</P>
<P>
   and Annette Bening.
</P>
<P>
   5 Oscars: picture, actor (Kevin Spacey), director, original
screenplay, cinematography. The ever-more-remarkable Spacey plays a
man caught in a midlife limbo in this scarily disturbing, daringly
hilarious, well-written and well-acted comedy-drama. It's a
hauntingly optimistic elegy for America the Beautifully Screwed Up.
(ERG)1 hour, 58 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack
</P>
<P>
   and Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   It's a loopy original. John Cusack plays a quirky file clerk who
discovers a door that leads into the noggin of actor John
Malkovich. Toying with big concepts _ the nature of identity, the
lust for celebrity, sexual desire, the illusion of free will, it's
playfully profound one moment, gonzo the next. (SM) 1 hour, 52
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiler Room'' R (profanity and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Giovanni Ribisi,
</P>
<P>
   Vin Diesel and Ron Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   A high-powered descendant of ``Wall Street'' and ``Glengarry
Glen Ross,'' this study of muscle-mouthed stockbrokers aiming to
make their first million before getting their first wrinkle pays
onscreen tribute to those two movies. It's a bracing reminder that
greed is still good _ so long as you don't get caught when you
pretzel the rules. (SM) 1 hour, 59 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' R (sex, profanity, nudity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hilary Swank
</P>
<P>
   and Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar: actress (Hilary Swank). This intense true story of Teena
Brandon, a 21-year-old woman who believed she was a man. After
cutting her hair and reversing her name, she hung out with some
hard-drinking rednecks in rural Nebraska, which didn't work out.
The movie is a bit low-budget, but it's still a remarkable film.
(ERG)1 hour, 54 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' PG-13 (nudity,
</P>
<P>
   substance abuse, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Caine
</P>
<P>
   and Tobey Maguire.
</P>
<P>
   2 Oscars: adapted screenplay, supporting actor (Michael Caine).
John Irving adapted his own novel. In the first half, Dr. Larch
(Caine) delivers babies and performs illegal abortions in his Maine
orphanage. In the second, less-engaging half, Larch's protege,
Homer Wells (Tobey Maguire), runs off to learn about the world.
(ERG) 2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Drowning Mona'' R (profanity and brief sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Danny DeVito,
</P>
<P>
   Bette Midler, Neve Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   As we get to know Mona (Bette Midler) through flashbacks, we
quickly understand why nobody is disturbed by her demise. It turns
out that the Yugo in which she took a header into the Hudson River
had its brakes sabotaged. Police Chief Wyatt Rash (Danny DeVito)
begins investigating her murder and finds that everyone in town had
something against Mona. (Hap Ernstein, Palm Beach (Fla.) Post) At
metro theaters. 1 hour, 30 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor and the Assassin'' R (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gong Li
</P>
<P>
   and Li Xuejian.
</P>
<P>
   The birth of a nation, Chinese-style. Set in 221 B.C., Chen
Kaige's film tells the true story of how the would-be emperor of
all China sets about unifying the then-existing six kingdoms into
one. Though long and occasionally confusing, the movie has the
panoramic impact of a Kurosawa epic, the bloody violence of a Greek
tragedy and the human intrigue of a Shakespearean drama. (ERG) 2
hours, 40 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Roberts
</P>
<P>
   and Albert Finney.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts delivers in a funny, down-to-earth film about an
everyday mom with business spunk who, without a law degree but with
a lot of pluck, helps crash a big-time company responsible for
devastating health problems in a small, dirt-poor town. Call it
``Working-Class Girl.'' (Bob Longino)2 hours, 11 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Final Destination'' R (bloody violence and raw language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Devon Sawa,
</P>
<P>
   Ali Larter and Kerr Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Final Destination'' aims for young audiences with an
``X-Files: The Wonder Years'' science/suspense plot about a kid who
escaped death from a plane crash and learns more than mortals
should about death. Our hero (Devon Sawa) and six others find
they're still targeted for death. The Grim Reaper, feeling cheated,
has plans for them. (Chris Hewitt, Knight Ridder Newspapers) 1
hour, 33 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghost Dog:
</P>
<P>
   The Way of the Samurai'' R (strong violence and language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Forest Whitaker
</P>
<P>
   and John Tormey.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jim Jarmusch takes the overused gangster genre and
makes it compellingly unfamiliar. Ghost Dog (Forest Whitaker), who
makes a fascinating lone wolf, is a gun-for-hire who follows the
philosophy of the samurai, especially their utter devotion to their
masters. His is Louie (John Tormey), a tubby, graying soldier
working for a gang boss. Louie saved him from thugs as a teenager.
(SM)1 hour, 54 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' R (profanity and drugs
</P>
<P>
   content, sexuality and suicide)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Winona Ryder
</P>
<P>
   and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar: supporting acrtress (Angeline Jolie). Based on Susanna
Kaysen's memoir about the two years she spent in the late '60s at
an upscale mental hospital, the movie goes for a rip-roaring tone
reminiscent of ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.'' Angelina Jolie
provides the fireworks in a fiercely showy turn as a charismatic
sociopath. (ERG) 2 hours, 5 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'' R (profanity, violence, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks
</P>
<P>
   and Michael Clarke Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   A manipulative but meticulously crafted, absorbing and
beautifully acted adaptation of Stephen King's prison novel. Tom
Hanks plays a 1930s death row guard whose latest prisoner, a
mysterious hulk played by Duncan, has mystical powers of healing.
(SM)
</P>
<P>
   3 hours, 2 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on Earth'' PG-13 (sensuality
</P>
<P>
   and thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chris Klein,
</P>
<P>
   Leelee Sobieski and Josh Hartnett.
</P>
<P>
   A limp and clueless variation on ``Love Story.'' Leelee
Sobieski, Chris Klein and Josh Hartnett star as kids in a love
triangle. Trapped in this hermetically sealed setting, with a
script that would run 10 minutes if the cliches were yanked out of
it, they can't win. (SM) 1 hour, 37 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack,
</P>
<P>
   Iben Hjejle
</P>
<P>
   and Jack Black.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly dumped by his longtime girlfriend, record-store owner
Rob (John Cusack) rhetorically asks himself, ``What came first _
music, or the misery?'' In other words, does he listen to songs
about heartbreak because he's miserable, or is he miserable. ``High
Fidelity'' is as smart as it is enjoyable. It's a great date-movie
about dating. (SM) 1 hour, 54 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' PG ( sci-fi violence and mild language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gary Sinise,
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins, Don Cheadle.
</P>
<P>
   Brian De Palma's Red Planet opus is too much like other films
(``Contact,'' ``The Abyss'' and, especially, ``2001: A Space
Odyssey''), but it's still a decent popcorn movie packed with
thrills and sharp special effects. Gary Sinise, Tim Robbins, Connie
Nielsen and Jerry O'Connell are part of an astronaut team trying to
rescue others lost on Mars. (SM) 1 hour, 53 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip'' PG (violent content and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Frankie Muniz,
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lane and Kevin Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the late Willie Morris' memoir about growing up in
small-town 1940s Mississippi, this family film is a remembrance of
how things can pass from our lives but never really leave us.
Nine-year-old Willie (``Malcolm in the Middle's'' Frankie Muniz) is
a shy only child whose life changes when his mom (Diane Lane) gives
him a Jack Russell terrier puppy, despite dad's (Kevin Bacon)
objection. (ERG) 1 hour, 35 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Next Best Thing'' PG-13 (profanity, partial nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Madonna
</P>
<P>
   and Rupert Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue, the melodramatic situations, the performances all
scream ``Phony!'' Madonna and Rupert Everett play best pals (she's
straight, he's gay), who end up raising a child together. Some bad
movies, of course, are perversely enjoyable. This isn't one of
them. (Robert W. Butler, Kansas City (Mo.) Star)1 hour, 40 minutes.
D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ninth Gate'' R ( violence and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Johnny Depp
</P>
<P>
   and Lena Olin.
</P>
<P>
   A major disappointment from Roman Polanski, the film stars
Johnny Depp in a tale of old books, the devil and the gateway to
satanic powers. Imagine one of those seasonal Halloween horror
houses, but designed by librarians. And what do you get at the end
of the trek? The spectacle of a bunch of rich twits in black robes,
play-acting a satanic mass. (SM) 2 hours, 13 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Not One Less'' Unrated (designed for
</P>
<P>
   mature audiences, subtitles)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Wei Minzhi.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned director Zhang Yimou, who's better known for such
sumptuous efforts as ``Raise the Red Lantern,'' presents this
simple film. In a poor rural Chinese village, a 13-year-old girl is
hired to be the substitute teacher. She'll receive a bonus if all
the students are still there when the regular teacher returns. A
small, pared-down film with deep emotional and political
undercurrents. (ERG)1 hour, 46 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Man and the Sea'' Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   A live-action animated short.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar: best animated short. This 'toon, based on Ernest
Hemingway's novel, is, like the author's word choice, deceptively
simple and strikingly beautiful. It's everything a moviegoer would
expect, but didn't get, from ``Fantasia 2000.'' (Bob Longino) 40
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' R (profanity and sci-fi violence and gore)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vin Diesel
</P>
<P>
   and Radha Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry aliens, stupid humans: the usual. ``Pitch Black'' is just
the latest sci-fi rip-off of ``Aliens,'' packed with caricatures.
In the movie's last hour, writer-director David Twohy pretends to
explore his stick figures' moral choices, and he forgets to deliver
the thrills. (SM)1 hour, 47 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Price of Glory'' PG-13 ( violence, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and brief drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jimmy Smits
</P>
<P>
   and Jon Seda.
</P>
<P>
   A boxing movie that goes down for the count. Jimmy Smits stars
in another retelling of the age-old story of sons struggling to
please a demanding father. It's about as dramatically subtle as a
head-butt. (SM) 1 hour, 57 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games'' R (sex, violence, nudity, and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Affleck,
</P>
<P>
   Charlize Theron and Gary Sinise.
</P>
<P>
   When it's good, it's very good, but when it's bad. ... Ben
Affleck plays an ex-con who poses as his former cell mate in order
to bed babelicious Charlize Theron and gets caught in a nasty mess
with her psycho brother (Gary Sinise), who wants him to help rob a
casino. With John Frankenheimer as the director, the movie is
always watchable, but sometimes it's just plain ludicrous. (ERG)1
hour, 45 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' PG (mild thematic material and
profanity.)
</P>
<P>
   Animated film featuring
</P>
<P>
   the voices of Kevin Kline
</P>
<P>
   and Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Not cute enough for kids, not clever enough for adults,
DreamWorks' latest animated feature is gorgeous but curiously dull.
Kenneth Branagh and Kevin Kline voice a couple of 16th century scam
artists looking for the Lost City of Gold in the New World. The
movie fuses visual splendor with unsteady storytelling and tone.
The waterfalls are beautiful. But the movie is a washout. (SM)1
hour, 23 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo Must Die'' R (violence, some profanity
</P>
<P>
   and brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jet Li and Aaliyah.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the martial arts genre, the violence is strong. This
is Jet Li's first English-language film and it has a great look and
an edgy feel, along with some broad swaths of humor. (Kevin Thomas,
Los Angeles Times)1 hour, 55 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' R (profanity and strong horror violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Arquette, Courteney Cox Arquette and Neve
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a scream anymore, but it's a decent wrap-up of the
series. Neve Campbell, Courteney Cox Arquette and David Arquette
are all back and on the Hollywood set of ``Stab 3,'' ducking the
knife-swings of a killer clad in the familiar Halloween get-up. The
new movie isn't as clever with its clues as the others, but it
manages to wheeze its way across the finish line, wrapping up the
trilogy in satisfying fashion. (SM)1 hour, 56 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skulls'' PG-13 (violence and brief sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joshua Jackson
</P>
<P>
   and Paul Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In this conspiracy thriller for the Clearasil set, WB's Joshua
Jackson plays an average Joe sucked into an elite, monied club. It
comes with a price, though. Like he can't ever get out. (SM) At
metro theaters. 1 hour, 47 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Day'' PG (mild peril and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chevy Chase.
</P>
<P>
   A lame kids movie about Syracuse, N.Y., schoolkids trying to
extend one out-of-school snow day into two. Chevy Chase plays a TV
weatherman suffering all kinds of humiliation and Chris Elliott
appears as the ominous Snow Plow Man with bad teeth. (Robert
Denerstein, Denver Rocky Mountain News) At metro theaters. 1 hour,
30 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' R (violence, profanity, brief
nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matt Damon,
</P>
<P>
   Jude Law
</P>
<P>
   and Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome but flawed adaption of novelist Patricia Highsmith's
twisty thriller. Matt Damon plays the title character, who travels
to Italy to bring back a rich man's son but ends up adopting his
lifestyle and committing murder. (SM) At discount theaters.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 18 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tigger Movie'' G
</P>
<P>
   Animated feature with
</P>
<P>
   Tigger, Pooh, Baby Roo, Piglet, etc.
</P>
<P>
   This charming animated feature clearly knows its intended tot
audience and takes care of them. The irrepressible, ever-bouncing
Tigger goes searching for his family and discovers his real family
isn't necessarily other Tiggers. Pooh, Piglet, Baby Roo and the
whole A.A. Milne gang are back, as are the Sherman brothers (``Mary
Poppins''), who wrote the sprightly songs. As Tigger himself would
say, it's tiggerific. (ERG) 1 hour, 16 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking the Dead'' R (sexuality and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Billy Crudup
</P>
<P>
   and Jennifer Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   A haunting romance in which an aspiring politician (Billy
Crudup) in the early '80s thinks his radical beloved (Jennifer
Connelly), killed in a car bombing in the '70s, may be back from
the dead. Crudup is superb and Connelly is effective in a more
limited role. The movie is a little too earnest, a little slow, but
it's more than recommended to those who love fine acting. (ERG)1
hour, 43 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever It Takes'' PG-13(sexual situations and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Shane West
</P>
<P>
   and Jodi Lyn O'Keefe
</P>
<P>
   Very loosely based on ``Cyrano de Bergerac,'' this generic
teen-hormone comedy has two seniors who help each other woo the
girl of their dreams and/or lust. The cast is pleasant enough, but
if you saw a single John Hughes movie in the '80s, you've seen this
territory covered with more style and insight. If your kid is
begging to go, do whatever it takes to palm him or her off on a
clueless grandparent. (ERG)1 hour, 32 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whole Nine Yards'' R (sexuality, nudity, and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Perry
</P>
<P>
   and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   A comedy with a body count and familiar mafioso premise, but
with enough twists to eventually overcome its familiarity. Bruce
Willis stars as a hit man. As in ``The Sixth Sense,'' he doesn't
seem to mind playing genial straight man to his funnier cast mates:
Matthew Perry, Patricia Arquette and Kevin Pollak. (SM)1 hour, 43
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonder Boys'' R (profanity and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Douglas,
</P>
<P>
   Tobey Maguire
</P>
<P>
   and Frances McDormand.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas plays scruffy, scattered English lit professor
Grady Tripp in director Curtis Hanson's (``L.A. Confidential'')
well-written version of Michael Chabon's novel. Part satire and
part coming-of-age tale of a man in his 50s, the film is full of
episodes and digressions that are as interesting as the final
destination. It's also a feast for actors, who make the most of
tiny, telling moments. (SM)1 hour, 57 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
