<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-GARDENS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As the weather warms, Toronto touts a somethig-for-all blaze of
blooms
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The narrow, sandy streets wander past funky little
gardens ablaze with towering sunflowers, rampant petunias and perky
dahlias, all with heads held so high you'd swear you could see them
nod hello.
</P>
<P>
   Behind these postage-stamp-size Edens are vine-shrouded
clapboard cottages with front porches sporting everything from
ratty old recliners to broken-down washing machines. It's a
neighborhood so eclectic, so earthy, you'd expect to find it in the
villages of the English countryside or the rural hamlets of the
Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   But a sudden breeze off the water jolts your attention to
another locale _ the gleaming modern skyline of Toronto, just 15
minutes by ferry across Lake Ontario. There, along the banks of
Canada's largest city, are small public parks that double as
pristine gardens celebrating music and the arts with giant
contemporary metal sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Among Torontonians, interpretations of what constitutes a garden
are as varied as the city's quilt of ethnic neighborhoods. To some,
gardens are those quaint cottage retreats across the lake on Ward's
and Algonquin islands. To others, they're the historic grounds of
the city's landmark castle, Casa Loma, restored in 1987 by the
Garden Club of Toronto for $1.5 million. Many point to the Royal
Botanical Gardens, which boast the world's largest lilac
collection, while some insist you can't beat the gardens at Niagara
Falls, which shower visitors with a showcase of thousands of
annuals each summer.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's green thumbs pride themselves not only on the variety
of their gardens but on the city's growing sense of ecological
awareness, emphasizing natural habitat restoration, native plants
and community spirit, said Janet Davis, garden columnist for the
Toronto Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The area enjoys a growing season much like that of Chicago.
Brown barren yards turn into artists' palettes in April as hardy
perennials return with their spattering of color, bidding a long
winter farewell. But the true gardening season doesn't unfurl until
late May _ when all risk of a late freeze has passed _ and lasts
until the first frost of October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the start to be the Victoria Day (May 24) holiday
weekend, when you're generally safe to put out annuals. That's when
the nurseries here get incredibly busy,'' Davis said. ``After that,
June, July and August in the city are just beautiful in
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the thaw begin.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
