<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warm to these Great White North events
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a list of events across Canada this spring and summer:
</P>
<P>
   ALBERTA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 7-16: Calgary Exhibition and Stampede. Calgary. Wild West
exhibition features a rodeo, a giant midway, street dancing and
pancake breakfasts. 1-800-661-1767, www.calgary-stampede.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 20-29: Edmonton Klondike Days. Edmonton. Step into the
gold-rush era and enjoy gold panning, pancake breakfasts, saloon
nights and more. 780-423-2822, www.klondikedays.com.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH COLUMBIA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 23-July 2: DuMaurier International Jazz Festival.
Vancouver. Wynton Marsalis, Holly Cole and Jonny Lang are among the
1,500 performers at this annual event. In addition, a two-day New
Orleans-style street festival is held in historic Gastown.
1-888-438-5200, www.jazzfest.bc.sympatico.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 29-Oct. 8: Okanagan Fall Wine Festival. Visitors relish
tours, tastings, grape stomps, dinners, lunches and brunches
throughout the wine-growing Okanagan Valley region. 250-861-6654,
www.owfs.com.
</P>
<P>
   MANITOBA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 6-9: Winnipeg Folk Festival. Winnipeg. Folk music
hootenanny spotlights more than 200 performers. Concertgoers can
also enjoy a craft village and an international food area.
1-888-655-5354, www.wpgfolkfest.mb.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 20-30: Winnipeg Fringe Theatre Festival. Winnipeg. An
alternative-theater extravaganza with performances by troupes from
around the globe on outdoor and indoor stages in the historic
Exchange District. 1-877-446-4500, www.mtc.mb.ca.
</P>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 3-11: Shediac Lobster Festival. Shediac. 50th anniversary
celebration includes lobster-eating contests, concerts and a
children's parade. 506-532-1122, www.lobsterfestival.nb.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 11-19: Festival by the Sea. Saint John. Arts festival
features more than 300 musicians, dancers and artists from across
Canada. 506-632-0086.
</P>
<P>
   NEWFOUNDLAND AND LABRADOR
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 2- Aug. 6: Full Circle: Viking _ Skraeling First Contact.
St. John's. Exhibit at Newfoundland Museum details the Vikings'
arrival at L'Anse aux Meadows through multimedia presentations,
artifacts, and living displays. 709-729-1999,
www.gov.nf.ca/tourism.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 17-Sept. 8: The Grand Encampment. L'Anse aux Meadows. A
re-creation of a Viking village, showcasing crafts, skills and
foods of the Viking era. 709-454-8888, www.gov.nf.ca/tourism.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 23-28: Viking Sail 2000. The Wonderstrand, L'Anse aux
Meadows. Viking boats from around the world will leave the southern
coast of Labrador and undertake a six-day voyage to L'Anse aux
Meadows, arriving at the peak of the Grand Encampment on July 28.
709-454-8888, www.gov.nf.ca/tourism.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST TERRITORIES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 8-14: Festival of the Midnight Sun. Yellowknife.
Celebration of northern culture spotlights artists, galleries and
businesses. 867-873-4262.
</P>
<P>
   NOVA SCOTIA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 29-July 7: Nova Scotia International Tattoo. Halifax.
Indoor pageant features military bands, pipes and drums, choirs,
gymnasts, dancers, military displays and competitions.
902-451-1221, www.nstattoo.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 19-24: Tall Ships 2000. Halifax. Tall ships from around
the world converge on Halifax Harbour and are heralded by
fireworks, parades and a concert on Citadel Hill.
www.tallships2000.ns.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 9-13: Hector Festival. Pictou. Musical series featuring
Celtic and Scottish concerts. 902-485-8848,
www.pictou.nsis.com/pages/ent.html.
</P>
<P>
   ONTARIO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 3-Nov. 5: Stratford Festival. Stratford. Acclaimed theater
festival's 2000 season includes plays by Shakespeare, Moliere,
Oscar Wilde and Euripides. 1-800-567-1600,
www.stratford-festival.on.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 21-Aug. 7: Caribana. Toronto. Carnival-like celebration
of Caribbean culture peaks on Aug. 5 with the Costume Parade, a
huge downtown street party. 416-465-4884, www.toronto.com/caribana.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 7-16: Toronto International Film Festival. Toronto.
Prestigious annual film festival draws actors, filmmakers and film
fans from around the world. 416-968-3456, www.bell.ca/filmfest.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-14: Oktoberfest. Kitchener-Waterloo. Billed as the
largest Bavarian festival in North America, featuring concerts,
horse racing and a midway. 519-570-4267, www.oktoberfest.ca.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE EDWARD ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 29-July 2: Festival of Lights. Charlottetown. The
birthplace of Canadian Confederation celebrates summer with
buskers, fireworks, a midway and a birthday party on July 1, Canada
Day. 1-800-955-1864, www.capitalcommission.pe.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 21-23: Lucy Maud Montgomery Festival. Cavendish. Tribute
to the author of ``Anne of Green Gables,'' featuring dramatic
readings, music, period games, an ice cream social and a film
festival. 902-963-2149, www.town.cavendish.pe.ca
</P>
<P>
   /lucymaudfestival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 31-Sept. 3: The Festival of the Fathers. Charlottetown.
Event commemorates the 1864 Canadian Confederation conference with
concerts, historic walking tours, a fair and re-enactments.
1-800-955-1864, www.capitalcommission.pe.ca.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 8-17: Le Mondial de la biere. Montreal. Billed as the
largest international beer event in North America, this festival in
Montreal's Old Port offers samples of more than 200 brews from
around the world. 514-722-9640, www.festivalmondialbiere.qc.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 29-July 9: Montreal International Jazz Festival.
Montreal. Multivenue, largely free music festival showcases top
names in blues, gospel, rock and jazz, including Rickie Lee Jones
and Shirley Horn. 1-888-515-0515, www.montrealjazzfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 6-16: 2000 DuMaurier Quebec City Summer Festival. Quebec
City. Annual event in Old Quebec hosts a diverse lineup of pop,
rock, alternative, techno, world beat, classical music and street
performers. 418-523-4540, www.infofestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   SASKATCHEWAN
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 23-July 2: SaskTel Saskatchewan Jazz Festival. Saskatoon.
Jazz, Dixieland, blues and other musical styles transform
Saskatchewan's largest city into a great big party. 306-934-3378,
www.saskjazz.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1, 4, 11, 18, 25 and Aug. 1, 8, 15: RCMP Sunset Retreat
Ceremonies. Regina. Dressed in their traditional scarlet tunics,
Royal Canadian Mounted Police Training Academy cadets perform drill
displays, as well as the lowering of the flag and other ceremonies.
1-800-661-5099, www.tourismregina.com.
</P>
<P>
   YUKON
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1: Yukon Gold Panning Championship. Dawson City. Annual
competition attracts novices and professionals for timed panning
trials. Participants receive a certificate; the top three finishers
get medals. 867-993-5575, www.dawsoncity.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
