<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FUNDY-COVE02-COX     03-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDY-COVE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Inn on the Cove, you're part of the family
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT JOHN, New Brunswick _ Rigid with anticipation, the dog
eyes the stone in Willa Mavis' hand. With a casual flick she tosses
it toward the surf, where it lands among thousands of rocks of
similar size and color.
</P>
<P>
   Bosun, a 60-pound Nova Scotia duck tolling retriever, scampers
after it and soon returns to deposit the very same (though
saliva-soaked) rock at our feet. Again and again, Willa throws it
and Bosun brings it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such a nose!'' Willa exclaims. ``Our vet says he
would make a good narc dog.''
</P>
<P>
   I have joined Willa and Bosun on their evening walk around the
grounds of Inn on the Cove, the bed-and-breakfast she runs with her
husband, Ross Mavis. An appealingly quirky melange of Victorian and
1950s-style architecture, the inn sits on a 3-acre climb above Sand
Cove, a tranquil inlet on the Bay of Fundy west of downtown Saint
John.
</P>
<P>
   It is, the Mavises feel, home. Stay here a few nights and you'll
no doubt feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we're on McLaren's Beach, a gravelly strand of shoreline
about 100 yards below the inn. A hillock to the north obscures
Saint John's industrialized skyline. Far out in the bay, you can
see the outline of Partridge Island, where thousands of Irish
immigrants landed during the potato famine of the 1840s. Seals loll
on the rocks on and around the island _ if you look through the
telescope in the inn's kitchen you can spot them. They look like
little wiggly sausages.
</P>
<P>
   From the beach, the land behind the inn rises in terraces. The
first holds a sheep pen _ Ross and Willa sheep-sit for friends who
travel during the summer. On the second tier is a filled-in
swimming pool, built and subsequently abandoned by the inn's
previous owners, who found the upkeep too costly. Also here is the
patio where the Mavises film summer installments of their
cable-access cooking show, ``Tide's Table.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the inn itself, which is similarly tiered, rising
four multicolored stories from sub-basement to eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Willa looks up at her dream house in awe. ``From the front, it
looks so modest. But when I look at it from this side, I sometimes
get overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple bought the place in 1991, shortly after they married.
``We found it in the classifieds, can you believe it?'' Willa, 54,
says. ``It's like it was sitting here waiting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The central part of the house was built at the turn of the
century. A local construction magnate bought it in the '50s and
added a front bedroom, a back den and a kitchen (along with that
pool).
</P>
<P>
   Willa handled decorating duties, playing to the inn's eclectic
look. Each of the five guest rooms has its own personality _ Room 3
upstairs has the feel of a Cape Cod beach house, with white wicker
furniture, an ocean view and a bay-blue color scheme. Room 1 is
darker, more masculine, with a stout brass bed and oak fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   The homiest place in the house is the den, or Ocean Room, which
overlooks the water. It's here that guests sit down for sumptuous
breakfasts, stealing glimpses of the bay as they tuck into Ross'
rich egg-and-cheese breakfast pudding or his tart-sweet cranberry
orange muffins. Ross is head chef, though both Mavises are handy
with a skillet. Besides hosting the TV cooking show, the couple
have authored a cookbook, also titled ``Tide's Table,'' and are set
to release a second on outdoor cooking this month. In between
breaking eggs, Ross will let Bosun out to fetch the morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of innkeepers strive to make their accommodations homey,
but any traveler who's ever been met at the door by a plastic smile
knows that a lot of times the exertion shows. The Mavises make it
look effortless. Their interactions with guests are chummy without
being intrusive or fake. ``There's a fine balance between warmth
and overdoing it,'' Ross, 58, says. ``We like to do things with a
little bit of class.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, they focus on little extras. There's a dish of bridge
tokens on the table next to the door _ guests, or even curious
visitors, are invited to take one to pay the toll on their way into
Saint John. There are no phones in the rooms, but guests are
invited to use the one in the Ocean Room to call anywhere for free.
A tin of homemade cookies rests on the kitchen counter, and this
summer, Willa plans to offer jars of her homemade straw-
</P>
<P>
   berry-rhubarb jam.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hanley loves the inn's laid-back atmosphere. This is the
third visit in five years for the fisheries enforcement clerk, up
for the weekend from St. Andrews, 70 miles southwest, with her
friend Rita O'Rourke. Both are recovering from recent maladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get away,'' says Hanley, 50, warming herself by
the Ocean Room fireplace. ``It's like an escape from reality. It's
so relaxing to just sit by the fire and forget about the
hustle-bustle of the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Chimes in O'Rourke, 63: ``The owners certainly have the gift of
hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so, in fact, that I'm sure I'm not the first guest to
try to adopt the family pet. On the final day of my stay, the
Mavises let me take Bosun out for a walk on my own. After a
leisurely hike down the path that leads into neighboring Irving
Nature Park, we head to McLaren's Beach.
</P>
<P>
   I want to see if Bosun will fetch for me as he does for Willa.
So I heave a small lump of rust-colored sandstone as far as I can,
into a heap of countless shore rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Bosun bolts after it but overshoots the landing point by about
10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He wanders around, sniffing the wind for the scent. When he
starts to trot the opposite way I think about calling him back, but
suddenly he stops, reverses and goes right to the target. He scoops
the rock up in his jaws and deposits it, slobber-soaked, at my
feet.
</P>
<P>
   At the Inn on the Cove, hospitality runs in the family.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Five rooms with private baths (two with
Jacuzzis). $65-$100, including full breakfast. 1-877-257-8080,
www.innonthecove.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
