<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS02-COX     03-30 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The 70's' explores the hedonistic decade that brought us to
today
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In five years, from 1971 to 1975, I directly experienced EST,
Gestalt therapy, bioenergetics, rolfing, massage, jogging, health
foods, tai chi, Esalen, hypnotism, modern dance, meditation, Silva
Mind Control, Arica, acupuncture, sex therapy, Reichian therapy and
More House. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The man who ran this gantlet and wrote those words was none
other than Jerry Rubin, baton twirler in the revolutionary marching
band a decade earlier. Revolution, it turned out, was less urgent
than self-actualization. The gassy rhetoric that fueled the
protests and politics of the '60s long ago fizzled, and even the
music of those years is beginning to sound quaint. The civil rights
acts of 1964 and 1965 survive as testaments, but to the very system
that was under siege. By decade's end, it had become ugly carnival,
tatterdemalion white kids running about like scamps. Nothing
mattered more at the time than the perpetuity of the moment. The
moment, alas, came and went.
</P>
<P>
   What followed could hardly be more ironic. The hedonism and
self-spelunking of the '70s _ so easy to satirize at the time _
would leave a deeper imprint on American life than all those campus
sit-ins, ``The Port Huron Statement,'' ``The Strawberry
Statement,'' ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'' or any
number of forgotten shibboleths of the '60s. (Wouldn't most people
have to be told that the author of ``The Strawberry Statement'' was
not Darryl but a Columbia University student named James Kunen?)
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, as David Frum's subtitle qualifies it, the
lives we live today are rooted in social changes that took place in
the decade that saw us eating granola, listening to James Taylor
and Jimmy Buffett, sitting in gas lines, witnessing the resignation
of a disgraced president, abandoning the idea of marriage until
death do us part, jogging not just for healthy recreation but on
the moral principle of fitness and low resting pulse rates.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the '70s, never the '60s, could magazines like People
and Self have been created. If the '60s saw the flowering of free
love, the '70s gave us _ briefly _ the legitimation of open
marriage. ``If it comes down to your marriage or your identity,''
the authors of ``Open Marriage'' wrote, ``we think your identity is
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   The brave new world of connubiality that George and Nena O'Neill
espoused in 1972 (they later had second thoughts) was a little
further than most of their readers wanted to venture. But the genie
of self-realization was out of the bottle. And so the divorce rate
_ one marriage in 20 through the first 65 years of this century _
was knocking on the door of 50 percent by the end of the decade. As
Frum writes, ``A society in which people are encouraged to put
themselves first is not likely to be a society in which many people
celebrate their golden wedding anniversaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Frum, a frequent contributor to The Weekly Standard magazine,
The Wall Street Journal and National Public Radio's ``Morning
Edition,'' might be the most acute social commentator writing
today. He sees how the new is transformed into the now _ and why
social change and technological change do not travel on parallel
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is often said that we live in a time of unusually rapid
change,'' he writes. ``If we are referring to economic and
technological change, this isn't true.'' When long-distance phone
calls are part of everyday life and even laymen have a fair
understanding of DNA, most people can ``take the Internet and Dolly
the Cloned Sheep in stride.'' Indeed, little that's happened since
1970 has been so astonishing as what Americans witnessed earlier in
the century: the advent of air travel, motion pictures and
television, the control of infectious diseases through antibiotics,
interstate highways and the automobile, the birth control pill and
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   It's other changes that are more bewildering. A Rip van Winkle
who nodded off in 1970 and awoke this morning would wonder where he
was: women sleeping in military barracks, the percentage of babies
born out of wedlock rising from 11 percent in 1970 to 32 percent in
1996, magazines flaunting homoerotic advertising, smoking
proscribed, the mainline Protestant churches losing their
franchise, children going off to day care and ``middle-aged men
going to work in khaki pants and baseball caps.''
</P>
<P>
   He would see, in short, a world turned upside down, but socially
more than technologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live,'' Frum writes, ``in a world made new, and made new
not by new machines, but by new feelings, new thoughts, new
manners, new ways.'' And in all that newness, nothing has been more
transforming _ for better or worse _ than the priority of the self.
It was in the '70s that Phil Donahue appointed himself therapist at
large. It was in the '70s that the self-help market for books took
off. Whatever else you did with your life, you first looked out for
No. 1. The effects extended beyond the personal: ``People bear
fewer children in economically troubled times. But the Americans of
the 1970s did not merely postpone children, as the Americans of the
1930s did. They actually changed their minds about wanting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pendulums shift sooner or later. The self-seeking of the '70s
has brought us Dr. Laura as knuckle-rapping national scold. Women
are forsaking the careers they thought they wanted in order to have
children, and skeptics ask whether ``self-esteem'' is really the
answer to all of life's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hardly conceivable that it will swing all the way back.
The barricades that were stormed in the '60s are museum pieces, and
the gaudy figures of that time a gallery of cartoon characters. Not
so the new way of looking at life that emerged a few years later.
It is, for better or worse, the way we live now, and anyone reading
David Frum's witty retrospective knows there is enough reason for
discontent to move on to something newer.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOOK
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from ``How We Got Here: The 70's''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there was a time when Americans thought of
themselves _ and were thought of by others _ as a taciturn people.
The Puritan heritage and the rigors of frontier life had instilled
in Americans a mistrust of garrulity, of the blatherskite, of the
flibbertigibbet. ``Speak not but what may benefit yourself or
others; avoid trifling conversation,'' urged Benjamin Franklin in
his autobiography, and even into the mid-twentieth century,
Americans wanted to think of their heroes as men of few words, like
Gary Cooper or John Wayne. But the public display of one's
suffering, one's wrongs, one's pitiableness, one's misfortunes,
which would have seemed shameful, ignoble, even disgusting before
World War II, became in the 1970s the distinctive American national
style. Don't bottle it up; you have a right to tell others how you
feel. It was, said the author Tom Wolfe, the undeclared motto of
the 1970s: ``Let's talk about me!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   How We Got Here: The 70's _ The Decade that Brought You Modern
Life _ For Better or Worse. By David Frum. Basic Books. $25. 224
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
