<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2523 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-FUNDY02     03-30 2686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-FUNDY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wealth of wildlife and grand vistas await in Bay of Bundy
welcome
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVER FUNDY NATIONAL PARK, New Brunswick _ ``Keep an eye out for
moose tracks,'' shouts Heinz Limpert over the thup-thup of the
helicopter blades.
</P>
<P>
   He lowers the chopper to within a hundred feet of the treetops,
then tilts it passenger side down to give me an unimpeded look.
Gripping the seat beneath me, I lean over and peer into a dense
stretch of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   It is a frigid morning in March, and snow still lies in patches
on the ground between the towering blue spruce. We're near the edge
of the Bay of Fundy, its famously fluctuating tide now at its
lowest level, laying bare a mile or more of bay floor. Behind us
are Hopewell Rocks _ impossibly stacked sandstone pillars created
by the sluicing bay. Ahead, over a few rolls in this undulating
landscape, looms Saint John, New Brunswick's oldest, largest and
most industrialized city, its skyline a dissonant panorama of
stately church spires and belching smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   Just now, though, I only have eyes for moose.
</P>
<P>
   And Limpert knows where to look. The 59-year-old German pilot
tracks the movements of moose and deer through this rugged terrain
for New Brunswick's Department of Natural Resources, when he's not
squiring the occasional tourist around in his chopper. Out of the
corner of my eye I see him pointing, and I follow his finger. It
leads to a long, crooked column of deep hoof prints in the snow.
Another set of tracks crosses it; yet another crosses the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll be able to pick one out,'' Limpert bellows. ``The
snow makes it easier to see them, but if they're lying down they
may blend in with the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it must be nap time for the moose population. We make
several circles over the area, paying special attention to large
groves of spruce seedlings planted by local timber companies.
(``They like to feed on the young trees because they're more
tender,'' Limpert explains.)
</P>
<P>
   But I'll see no moose today. It's just as well. I have already
witnessed so many eye-popping sights on this buzz over a sliver of
New Brunswick's Fundy coast, which spans 220 miles between the
borders of Maine and Nova Scotia, that I'm starting to get sore
sockets.
</P>
<P>
   Every turn of the head brings another astonishing vista. The
craggy, plunging cliffs of Black Point and Cape Enrage. The wild
splash of the Big Salmon river, swollen with winter runoff. The
picture-puzzle-perfect fishing village of St. Martins, with its
white clapboard churches, covered bridges and little red
lighthouse. And the gorgeous, sun-infused emerald of the bay
itself, the banks of Nova Scotia hazy on its horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Later, back on terra firma, I'll tramp through a couple of
coastal nature parks and discover that the view is just as dizzying
with my feet on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   New Brunswick is a place of vast, untouched beauty _ a little
too untouched for many in the tourism industry here. Slightly
smaller than Maine, with a population roughly that of Fulton County
(about 725,000), the laid-back province isn't exactly the first
place that springs to the minds of travelers planning a Canada
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Nova Scotia, with its ruggedly handsome Cape Breton
Island and popular Cabot Trail, is sexier. Newfoundland, with its
edge-of-North America mystique, is more extreme. And there are
always the big-city, big-ticket destinations: Toronto, Montreal and
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, visitors have trickled in, whether to whale-watch off the
islands that guard the mouth of the bay, to moose-watch in
51,000-acre Fundy National Park or to bird- and seal-watch at
Irving Nature Park in Saint John. In 1998, about 1.5 million people
visited New Brunswick _ peanuts compared with Georgia's tourist
numbers for the same year (47 million).
</P>
<P>
   That's changing. Provincial and city governments have recently
focused on tourism with a new vigor, and New Brunswick now leads
the Atlantic provinces in tourism growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Fundy coast is getting the biggest push. The Fundy Trail
Parkway, a 15-mile series of roadways and hiking and biking trails
in a 7.5-mile corridor between St. Martins and the Big Salmon
River, opened in May of last year and drew 79,000 visitors in its
debut season. Saint John is becoming a popular cruise ship port _
85 ships will visit this summer, up from 30 last year. And two golf
resorts are opening in September, one in St. Andrews near the Maine
border and the other in the inland city of Moncton.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we didn't have much to offer,'' concedes Mitchell
Franklin, the Fundy Trail's most fervent and enduring champion. The
86-year-old hotel and newspaper magnate, who lives on an 8,000-acre
estate west of St. Martins, has been trying for half a century to
get the trail established.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a failure for 50 years!'' he jokes. ``I knew the
beauty of the coastline and knew it had tremendous tourism
potential. But nobody would listen.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Franklin says, the provincial government focused on
industry, granting rights to large swaths of crown land to the
locally based Irving conglomer-
</P>
<P>
   ate. (Those are Irving pulp mills and oil refineries smoking up
the sky over Saint John.)
</P>
<P>
   The focus shifted somewhat in the late 1990s with the increasing
popularity of outdoor adventuring. ``When Mitchell first started
his crusade in the '50s, there wasn't any such thing as
eco-tourism,'' says Fundy Trail marketing manager Brian Clark.
``But I think people see the possibilities in that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the dream is to expand the Fundy Trail along the entire
coast. There are already plans afoot to connect it to Fundy
National Park, 25 miles east. Franklin, who serves on the board of
the Fundy Trail Development Authority, hopes to complete the
coastal expansion within a decade. ``I think we're finally on the
right road,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the Fundy Trail's Fox Rock Lookout, gazing across a
bay inlet to the lighthouse on Quaco Head, it's easy to understand
Franklin's passion for this land.
</P>
<P>
   The trail doesn't officially open for the year until May 1, but
I'm being offered a sneak peek (perks of the trade) by maintenance
manager Jim Clayton, who waits patiently as I gingerly teeter on
the icy paths that lead down to the park's nine lookout points.
</P>
<P>
   All the slipping and sliding is worth it. Though Clayton admits
that a few hardy locals venture here to walk their dogs this time
of year, the park is quiet on this chilly morning. The pervasive
silence and the cold, calm air create the perfect atmosphere for
the heavenly lookout views.
</P>
<P>
   On the suspension footbridge that spans the Big Salmon River, I
contemplate the rush of water as it courses past remnants of
logging wharfs from the early 1900s. Elsewhere, heavy cascades at
Fuller Falls catch the late-morning light as they gush through
copses of birch, maple and spruce. Below the falls, the lonesome,
rocky expanse of Pangburn Beach waits to be covered by the bay,
which rises as much as 48 feet between low and high tides, the
biggest tidal shift in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, the beaches and bay lookouts here will be teeming
with eco-minded visitors hoping to catch sight of the right,
humpback, minke and finback whales that come to feed on krill, a
tiny, shrimplike crustacean. But not even the whales are here yet _
I'm told they're off the coast of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to see them, but it's nice to have the park to myself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   If the Fundy Trail is a testament to Franklin's persistence (OK,
and his multimillionaire clout), Irving Nature Park shows us what
can happen when big business grows a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Does the Irving name ring a bell? That's right, it's the same
company that runs the paper mills, shipyards and refineries in the
area. In fact, the Irving Paper and Tissue plant is just down the
road, the sign out front emblazoned with the brazen motto:
``Committed to a clean environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1992, the park, which sits on a peninsula of volcanic
rock that juts into the Bay of Fundy west of downtown Saint John,
was a gift from James Irving, who runs the Irving industries with
his brothers, John and Arthur. (The siblings' combined wealth is
estimated to be more than $6.5 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   The motivation behind such largesse is open to interpretation.
``This is the Irvings' way of giving back to the community,'' says
the park's naturalist, Kelly Honeyman. Others consider it
reparation to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the results are lovely. The 600-acre park
encompasses several diverse man-made and natural ecosystems. The
salt marsh on the west side draws more than 250 species of birds,
including great blue herons, which should be arriving from Central
and South America this month.
</P>
<P>
   Porcupines, foxes and white-tail deer forage among the spruce,
fir and birch of the Acadian Forest. The mud flats lure sandpipers
and the occasional moose. And the eastern shore is the place to see
Seal Rock, where harbor seals jockey for position at low tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hierarchy for who gets the best place on the rock,''
Honeyman says. ``You'll see a lot of the big guys jostling the
little guys.'' At high tide the rock is under water, but if you're
lucky you can still see a seal or two splashing in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Honeyman, who gives tours of the park to school, civic and
seniors groups, proudly shows off a new section called the
Children's Forest. Created on land that was once a gravel pit, the
forest gives youngsters the opportunity to plant a tree and monitor
its growth. ``We have a grid, and we record who planted what and
where,'' Honeyman says. ``In 50 years, you'll be able to come back
and find your tree.''
</P>
<P>
   It is windy and sleeting on the morning of our visit. We stand
looking out over clusters of birch, maple, ash and spruce saplings.
They look so vulnerable, huddled together against the elements.
Their survival truly would be a gift.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   If a visit to the Fundy coast is this rewarding in March, you
can imagine what it's like during the summer, when the temperature
can climb into the 90s and the migratory animals return to feed and
frolic.
</P>
<P>
   The humpbacks should start showing up around mid-June, while the
dawdling right whales, with their big gnarly skin calluses, should
make it in by mid-July. Die-hard birdwatchers may have to make two
trips _ Atlantic puffins, Arctic terns and pied-billed grebes are
in by early June and out by the end of July, while August brings
great flocks of semipalmated sandpipers.
</P>
<P>
   Sailboats begin to dot the bay in May, growing to a grand
flotilla by high summer. And the whale-watch tours off Deer Island,
Campobello Island and Grand Manan gear up at the first sign of a
whale tail. But unless you have a wet suit, you probably won't want
to swim with the big beasts _ the bay's dramatic tides draw a daily
transfusion of bone-chilling water from the Atlantic Ocean, keeping
temperatures at about 50 degrees year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Let the crowds have their regular tourist haunts. Myself, I'll
be coming back to this pretty province for one more hike down the
Fundy Trail (hopefully, no frozen paths next time), to catch one
more soul-nourishing sunset from Sheldon's Point in Irving Nature
Park and maybe for one more spin over the coast in Limpert's
helicopter. And to Fundy National Park's coy moose populace, I'll
just say this _ you can't hide forever.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   (All prices listed have been converted to American dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFARES
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada offers $466 round-trip flights Mondays through
Thursdays from Atlanta to Saint John, with a connection in Toronto
(add $25 each way for weekend travel). Fourteen-day advance
purchase, Saturday stay required. Travel must be completed by June
9.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AROUND
</P>
<P>
   You'll want to rent a car if you plan to explore much of the
Fundy coast _ the Saint John airport has kiosks for Hertz
(1-800-654-3001), Avis (1-800-331-1212) and National
(1-800-227-3876). OUTDOOR ADVENTURES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canadian Helicopters Limited. Heinz Limpert, base manager.
Tours are about $475 an hour, limit four people per flight.
506-446-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fundy National Park. Open daily year-round. Visitors center
hours during peak season, May-October, are 8 a.m.-10 p.m. $2.40
park entrance fee; campground rates start at about $7.
506-887-6000, www.parkscanada.pch.gc.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fundy Trail Parkway. Open 6 a.m.-8 p.m. daily May-October.
Wednesdays, June 7-Sept. 7: Historic walks through Fownes burial
grounds. Aug. 4-7: Salmon River Days, featuring slide presentations
at park interpretive center and fly fishing demonstrations. Bat
walk and astrology walks held weekday evenings in July. $3.40
entrance fee. 506-833-2019; www.fundytrailparkway.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Irving Nature Park. Open daily year-round; naturalists lead
seasonal tours from May to November. Guided outings to see stars or
to snowshoe by moonlight may be arranged throughout the year. Free
admission. To book a tour, call 506-632-7777. General information,
506-653-7367; www.ifdn.com.
</P>
<P>
   BAY OF FUNDY ADVENTURES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Island Coast Boat Tours Inc. Four five-hour, narrated
whale-watching tours. July 1-Sept. 15. $30 adults, $27 seniors, $15
children under 12. North Head Fishermen's Pier, Grand Manan.
506-662-8181, www.angelfire.com/biz/icbt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fundy Tide Runners Whale Watching and Nature Tours. View
whales, seals, porpoises and eagles on two-hour tour aboard 24-foot
Zodiac Hurricane raft. May 12-Oct. 31. $30.60 adults, $15.30
children ages 5-13. St. Andrews. 506-529-4481,
www.townsearch.com/ftr.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reversing Falls Jet Boat Tours. Twenty-minute jet boat ride
over Reversing Falls, where St. John River and Bay of Fundy meet.
Raincoat included. June 3-Oct. 15. $17 adults, $15.65 children 12
and under. Saint John. 1-888-634-8987.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Baymount Outdoor Adventures Inc. Two-hour guided kayak tours
of Hopewell Rocks. Includes kayak equipment and basic instruction.
June-August. $27 adults, $24 children under 18, $82 per family.
Hillsborough. 506-734-2660.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inn on the Cove. See article, Page K12.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Delta Brunswick Hotel. Large, reasonably priced hotel in
downtown Saint John. Connected to shops, restaurants and sports
facilities through elevated, indoor pedway. 255 rooms. $65-$115.
1-800-268-1133, www.deltahotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Quaco Inn. Restored inn on the Bay of Fundy, in historic
fishing village of St. Martins. Near beaches, lighthouse, trails
and covered bridges. Six rooms. $65-$100. 1-888-833-4772,
www.intellis.net/quacoinn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Algonquin. Upscale resort overlooking Passamaquoddy Bay in
St. Andrews, near Maine border. Golf course, tennis courts, spa.
250 rooms including 13 suites. $58-$170. 1-800-441-1414,
www.cphotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mexicali Rosa's. Credible Mexican food in the heart of Saint
John's historic Trinity Royal district. Try the Clyde Burrito,
named after co-founder Clyde Ross, a Los Angeles entrepreneur who
has opened eateries across Canada. 506-652-5252.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grannan's. Seafood restaurant in Saint John's Market Square
shopping complex. Known for its seafood chowder, Prince Edward
Island blue mussels and fish croquettes. Chicken, pasta and steak
also available. 506-634-1555.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chizzler's. Casual, Bennigan's-style eatery in Saint John's
Trinity Royal district. Pizza, pasta, ribs and fried seafood.
Shakers Nightclub, a late-night lounge, is upstairs. 506-652-1331.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ossies. Drive-up seafood takeout place that is legendary with
locals. Fresh Bay of Fundy clams, scallops, fries, coleslaw. On NB
1 about 30 miles east of St. Andrews. Open March-November.
506-755-2758.
</P>
<P>
   TOURISM INFORMATION
