<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-CHICAGO-ART-3R     03-30 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-CHICAGO-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: tall buildings.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Da Bulls an' Da Bears
</P>
<P>
   Chicago loves its sports. It loves the Cubs and their cozy
little park, Wrigley Field, with ivy-covered outfield walls and
seldom-used floodlights. (God made baseball to be played under his
own light, the Cubs and their fans believe.) Forget the fact that
the Cubs haven't played in a World Series since 1945 or won one
since 1908. Chicago loved Da Bears in the heyday of Mike Ditka and
Walter Payton. It swooned over Da Bulls and their balletic,
clutch-loving, gravity-defying star of stars, Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Air Jordan and the Bulls carried the city's name around the
globe; so did Sir Georg Solti and the mighty Chicago Symphony
Orchestra, which he made one of the finest on earth. But both are
gone now, Air retired, Solti dead. The Bulls are rebuilding, and
the orchestra has not quite managed to maintain its old luster,
despite the manifold gifts of its current music director, Daniel
Barenboim.
</P>
<P>
   Barenboim's goals are different from those of Solti, a
taskmaster if not a martinet, who drilled his players until they
achieved a rare precision. At its peak the Chicago was best noted
for the sonority of its brass choirs, especially in the late
romantic repertory. Sometimes its Bruckner rang out with the
awesome power of the horns of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over in 1991, Barenboim has encouraged subtlety.
Today quiet passages are often as impressive as climaxes, though
some critics, including James R. Oestreich of The New York Times,
have detected occasional raggedness. Many listeners wonder how
things will change when the virtuoso trumpeter Adolph Herseth, who
is now 78, finally yields his chair.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barenboim is a musician of substance as well as a figure
of glamour. At Orchestra Hall and on tour in the United States and
abroad, he not only conducts but doubles as a piano soloist, and he
has kept the orchestra ensconced among the nation's elite musical
ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   The big stir in Chicago music this past season came from the
Lyric Opera's heralded premiere of a work it commissioned, William
Bolcolm's ``View From the Bridge,'' based on the Arthur Miller
play. The critics were kind, and the company liked it so much that
it has asked Bolcom, a genial University of Michigan professor who
likes Gershwin and Youmans as much as Puccini, to produce two more
new scores for production in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   It was a general director named Ardis Krainik, one of the rare
women in her line of work, who propelled the Lyric into the first
rank of American opera houses, along with the Metropolitan and San
Francisco. (Some would add Houston to the list.) She died in 1997,
to be succeeded by William Mason, and the company has gone from
strength to strength. It sells more than 100 percent of its seats
every year, an unparalleled accomplishment, because subscribers
religiously turn in unwanted tickets for resale.
</P>
<P>
   Dance and Drama
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has also taken the Joffrey Ballet to its heart. Directed
by Gerald Arpino, the company moved its base here in 1995 from New
York after running into financial trouble. It seems to have
restored its bank balance and renewed its classical style. Daley
regularly attends performances.
</P>
<P>
   Big-league drama abounds in the Windy City. Two of the most
widely applauded Broadway productions of the past couple of years
originated at the Goodman Theater here: Arthur Miller's ``Death of
a Salesman,'' starring Brian Dennehy, and Eugene O'Neill's ``Moon
for the Misbegotten,'' starring Cherry Jones and Gabriel Byrne.
Another O'Neill play, ``Desire Under the Elms,'' directed by Walter
Dallas, scored a hit this winter at the Court. And the Steppenwolf
helped propel David Mamet and John Malkovich to fame.
</P>
<P>
   No better evidence could be found that Chicago has long since
shed the ``Second City'' complex A.J. Liebling diagnosed 50 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune, still ensconced in its lacy neo-Gothic
tower on Michigan Avenue, is in almost every respect a different
animal from the wacky, pugnaciously conservative, isolationist
sheet full of local puffery and idiosyncratic spelling that Col.
Robert R. McCormick oversaw in the 1940s and '50s. It is in the
process of buying The Los Angeles Times, The Baltimore Sun and
Newsday, plus several television stations, which will make it one
of the nation's handful of dominant media conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons of the Arts
</P>
<P>
   Swift and Armour and the other barons of beef are no more;
Chicago is no longer ``hog butcher to the world.'' Only a gate
adorned with a bas-relief of a Hereford steer remains of the Union
Stockyards, where in 1892 alone 2.5 million cattle and 5 million
hogs were slaughtered. Many of the big corporations hereabouts,
like Walgreen's, United Air Lines, Motorola and Sears, which
abandoned its eponymous skyscraper in the Loop, are out in the
suburbs. Amoco and Ameritech and a couple of big banks succumbed to
takeovers. But many biggies remain, including Bank One, Sara Lee
and Quaker Oats, to which the city gave $9.75 million in tax breaks
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them support the arts with enthusiasm. C. Steven
McMillan, who takes over as chief executive of Sara Lee on July 1,
told me not long ago, ``The arts, politics and the business
community are more heavily comingled in Chicago than in any other
American city I know of, to everyone's benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Down at the foot of La Salle Street, in a fine Art Deco building
with a statue of Ceres on top, is the headquarters of the Chicago
Board of Trade, where the big commodity traders do their (to me)
incomprehensible thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few economic institutions,'' the social historian Thomas
Cronon tells us sternly in ``Nature's Metropolis'' (Norton, 1991),
``more powerfully affect human communities and natural ecosystems
in the modern capitalist world. Even those of us who will never
trade wheat or pork bellies on the Chicago futures markets depend
upon those markets for our very survival.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll have to take his word for it. Meanwhile, allow me to focus
for a moment on Chicago's writers: the early reformers Frank Norris
and Upton Sinclair; the overearnest but underrated Theodore
Dreiser, whose ``Sister Carrie'' still moves me; James T. Farrell,
whose ``Studs Lonigan'' is set in one part of the South Side, and
Richard Wright, whose ``Native Son'' is set in another; Ben Hecht
and Charles MacArthur, who gave us the greatest of all newspaper
plays, ``The Front Page,'' and Carl Sandburg, who for better or
worse gave Chicago its overfamiliar nickname, ``City of the Big
Shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the city and its ways have been depicted by Mike
Royko, the irascible newspaper columnist; Studs Turkel, the oral
historian; and Ward Just, the novelist.
</P>
<P>
   A moment, too, for the popular arts: the blues that Muddy Waters
and others brought up the Illinois Central from Mississippi; the
jazz that King Oliver and Louis Armstrong brought to the South
Side, echoed by white kids from the suburbs like Benny Goodman and
Eddie Condon; and the wacky, wonderful plaster cows (including
Ferragamoo, sponsored by the Italian fashion house) that appeared
all over the city in the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sinatra's kind of town, and it is mine, too.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
