<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-CHICAGO-ART-4T     03-30 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-CHICAGO-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: mine, too.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU GO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By R.W. APPLE Jr. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of Chicago's attractions, along with travel
information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   BURNHAM, 1 W. Washington St., (312) 782-1111. In a minor miracle
of adaptive restoration, D.H. Burnham's Reliance Building (1891),
one of the world's first skyscrapers, has been raised from
near-dead and turned into a boutique hotel, managed by the Kimpton
Group of San Francisco. In the heart of the Loop, it has 103 rooms
and 19 suites, average in size, below average in price. A lot of
fine original detail has been retained, including the terra cotta
facade, terrazzo floors and Carrara wainscoting. Double room: $135
to $230.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRMONT, 200 N. Columbus Drive, (312) 565-8000. A businessman's
favorite a few blocks north of the Loop, the Fairmont occupies a
42-story post-modern tower sheathed in pink granite. Its 692
exceptionally large rooms offer drop-dead views over the city or
the lake, plus marble-topped desks and tables. Give the Primavera
restaurant a pass; the waiters sing. Double room: $159 to $259.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SEASONS, 120 E. Delaware Place, (312) 280-8800. In city
after American city, the Four Seasons is the top-rated hotel. The
Windy City is no exception. The English-country-house-fantasy lobby
occupies the 7th floor of a 66-story skyscraper, above a mall full
of chic shops (Bloomie's, Bendel's). Whatever you want, it's right
at hand: barber and beauty shop, sauna, indoor pool and a stellar
restaurant, Seasons, with Mark Baker as chef. Double room: $465 to
$900.
</P>
<P>
   RITZ-CARLTON, 160 E. Pearson St., (312) 266-1000. Operated by
the Four Seasons chain, despite the misleading name, this luxurious
lair forms part of the Water Tower Place complex, smack in the
middle of the Magnificent Mile. Its bright, expansive lobby,
complete with octagonal fountain, is on the 12th floor. Guest rooms
are all that anyone could ask, as is Sarah Stegner's cuisine; her
Sunday brunch, Chicago's most sumptuous, ranges from gravlax to
mini-souffles. Double room: $400 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEHALL, 105 E. Delaware Place, (312) 944-6300. European in
style and ambiance, this little hideaway is tucked into a side
street, well away from Michigan Avenue's noise and bustle. In-room
faxes, phones with data ports and wall safes were installed in a
recent renovation. On weekends and during special promotions,
prices are low by Magnificent Mile standards. Double room: $199 to
$379.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   ARUN, 4156 N. Kedzie Ave., (773) 539-1909. This is America's
best Thai restaurant, a kitsch-free zone where the food on the
plates is just as delicate as the ceremonial headdresses adorning
the room. Miang kum, the first of 12 stellar dishes at a recent
meal, consisted of batons of lime peel, ginger and coconut, heaped
with tiny red peppers and peanuts on betel-nut leaves with tamarind
sauce. It would awaken the most jaded palate. Superb Austrian and
American wines; tasting menu only, $75 and worth it.
</P>
<P>
   BERGHOFF, 17 W. Adams St., (312) 427-3170. Old Chicago, alive
and kicking. Owned by the same clan since 1898, the Berghoff holds
the first liquor license issued by the city after Repeal. It brews
its own beers and root beer and serves all the old favorites from
Mittel Europa, like herring, bratwurst and knackwurst with
sauerkraut and real wiener schnitzel.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLIE TROTTER'S, 816 W. Armitage Ave., (773) 248-6228. One of
the nation's two or three premier chefs, Trotter makes gastronomic
Faberge eggs. He bathes foie gras, salmon and Japanese mushrooms in
a warm broth to create a dish that is both rich and refreshing: a
rarity. The service is fluent and the wine list (check the big
bottles) mind-blowing.
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST, 440 S. LaSalle St., (312) 663-8920. The next time
someone tells you he never eats on top of skyscrapers, send him to
Jean Joho's place, 40 floors up. Alsatian-born, J. blends the
cuisine of kings with the cooking of commoners in dishes like
creamy sauerkraut soup with caviar. The attention to detail is
constant, the tapestry of lights below stirring, the service urbane
and the Alsatian wines the best in the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   FRONTERA GRILL AND TOPOLOBAMPO, 445 N. Clark St., (312)
661-1434. You could spend half a lifetime in Oaxaca and know less
about Mexican food than you will learn at Rick and Deann Bayless'
two restaurants, one casual, the other less so. Both, saturated
with vibrant color, serve food prepared with immense care from the
best ingredients. Every sip or bite is a revelation, from
margaritas to marlin ceviche to tacos al pastor.
</P>
<P>
   GIBSONS, 1028 N. Rush St., (312) 266-8999. Chicago is a steak
town from way back. It has plenty of places to satisfy your
carnivorous impulses, but this one, packed with politicians,
visiting show-biz types, bulky guys in warm-up jackets and
head-turning dolls, epitomizes the city's exuberance. Order a
martini, chopped chicken livers (try them on the house raisin
bread) and either a W.R. Cut (a bone-in rib-eye named for the
Tribune's food columnist, William Rice), or tender London broil
(made with top sirloin). Desserts, like strawberry shortcake, are
the size of a steamboat.
</P>
<P>
   M K, 868 N. Franklin St., (312) 482-9179. The letters stand for
Michael Kornick, the chef, and he stands for modern American
cooking with bright, true flavors. Sweetbreads with caramelized
endive, for example, and definitive calves' liver with grilled
Vidalia onions, Nueske bacon strips and a sauce of mustard and pan
juices. The decor is terminally chic.
</P>
<P>
   SPIAGGIA, 980 N. Michigan Ave., (312) 280-2750. The name means
``beach,'' and you can glimpse the lake from this snazzy aerie
perched above the Magnificent Mile. But bag the view. Paul
Bartolotta's thoroughbred Italian cooking, the best between New
York and Santa Monica, is the thing to focus on here:
full-flavored, grown-up, fantasy-free dishes like asparagus with
unctuous fonduta, gnocchi with duck ragu and wood-roasted rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   TRU, 676 N. St. Clair St., (312) 202-0001. In from the suburbs,
Rick Tramonto and Gale Gand are challenging Charlie Trotter and
Jean Joho for local supremacy in an airy glacier-white room.
Tramonto sends out a lobster risotto in a miniature copper saucepan
and serves dazzling savory sorbets (beet, orange pepper, etc.) in
parmesan cones. Gand, his wife, whips up whimsies like pineapple
``carpaccio.'' Well-chosen wines.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
