<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2532 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-30 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROBERT BYRD: A PROFILE IN COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They don't call Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., the
conscience of the Senate for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   At 82, Byrd is one of the institution's last great orators, an
old-fashioned patriot who reveres the Constitution and is
determined to defend its integrity. And Byrd was at his best this
week as he reversed himself to help block a constitutional
amendment aimed at banning the desecration of the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment has been around since 1989, when the
Supreme Court ruled that flag-burning was constitutionally
protected by our free speech rights under the First Amendment.
Congress, incensed by demonstrations disrespectful of the flag
during the radical 1960s, rushed to make political points by
undoing the high bench ruling, and Byrd initially joined in.
</P>
<P>
   But now he has come to his senses, observing wryly that changing
one's mind is a perfectly acceptable political practice, given a
sufficiently important reason. Not that he favors burning the flag,
mind you.
</P>
<P>
   He just believes the Founding Fathers did not mean the
Constitution to be trivialized by an issue that neither affects the
structure of government nor protects personal rights by narrowing
the powers of government, the two suitable amendment categories.
``This is neither fish nor fowl,'' he intoned majestically. ``It
does not belong in the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure fell four votes short of the 67 needed to change the
Constitution. But to their shame, 63 senators did support it,
cringing before the prospect that political opponents might accuse
them of lacking proper patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Such a good commercial sound bite: Senator thinks its OK to
trash American flag! Senator doesn't love American flag! Shocking,
shocking. Terribly UnAmerican.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, former Gov. George Allen of Virginia, a Republican,
didn't even wait for his rival, Democratic Sen. Charles Robb, to
cast his opposing vote before attacking Robb as ``out of touch''
with ``the values and beliefs of Virginians.''
</P>
<P>
   Robb, a Vietnam veteran who literally had men die in his arms,
countered that American soldiers do not sacrifice ``for a piece of
cloth'' but for ``all that our flag represents _ including the
freedom to express views we don't share.'' The amendment sailed
through the House of Representatives last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sensible men and women know that flag-burning is not a major
threat to the republic. It is stupid and in bad taste. But it does
not rise to this level of congressional intensity. Such events
happen only rarely, are universally greeted with disgust and do no
substantive damage to our culture, our values or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Protection of the Constitution, however, needs constant
vigilance. It is under assault from many directions. Majorities
always want to bend it to favor their views and ignore the rights
of racial, religious and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is right. We cannot allow this to happen. The Constitution
protects the fundamental liberties of all of us.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, Byrd reminds us, is designed to be ``an oasis'' for
reasoned debate, resistant to the political passions of the moment.
Tinkering with the great document that is the foundation of our
democracy ``can have far-reaching and unexpected consequences'' not
immediately clear, he warns.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd also worried that a flag-burning ban would be mocked,
providing a tiny minority of rabble-rousers an opportunity to defy
the Constitution itself. ``Some verbiage can't be enforced, won't
be enforced,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the prohibition of liquor in 1919 as a misguided but
temporarily popular attempt to dictate human nature that distorted
the grand principles of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one provision is unenforceable, what about the other
provisions?'' he asked rhetorically. Prohibition, a law enforcement
disaster, was finally repealed in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd also stood against the popular mood six years ago when he
led the Senate fight to reject a constitutional amendment to
mandate a balanced federal budget. He dismissed it as an accounting
device that had no business being in the Constitution. And indeed,
Congress managed to balance the budget all on its own afterward
without a constitutional straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is an extraordinary political figure. After more than four
decades in the Senate, he is second in congressional seniority only
to that invincible geezer Strom Thurmond, R-S.C. His influence is
not what it was when he was Senate majority leader, but he is
greatly respected for his sense of institutional history, his deep
commitment to civility and protocol, and his protective instincts
about the power of the legislative branch.
</P>
<P>
   He has produced two volumes of Senate history that are already
regarded as the legislative bible. He began in politics as a member
of the Ku Klux Klan, but he learned along the way he had been
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He stands, in fact, as testimony to the wisdom of old age and
long service. He is running for re-election and likely to win.
</P>
<P>
   We need him. Phooey to term limits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
