   FILM-ALMODOVAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ One of the more entertaining moments on Oscar night
the past two years has been the presentation of the Academy Award
for Best Foreign Language film. Hyperactive Roberto Benigni stole
the show last year with his rambling stream-of-consciousness
acceptance speech; this year, Pedro Almodovar of Spain was almost
as entertaining with his over-the-top, if not coherent, acceptance
speech. We look at who he is and some of his previous work. By
ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SHANE WEST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Shane West isn't a teen-ager, but he plays one on TV,
as one of the cast members of the divorce-romance drama ``Once and
Again.'' He's also in a teen movie, ``Whatever It Takes,'' but he's
ready to break into more mature roles _ and maybe rock out a little
with his punk band. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HIGH FIDELITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Although ``High Fidelity'' goes on a little too long,
heaping one ending on top of another, it wraps up well and includes
several amusing cameos. It also, as is appropriate for a movie
featuring three rock-music snobs, has one of the best soundtracks
to come along in some time. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PRICE OF GLORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Price of Glory'' is the sort of movie that inspires
backhanded compliments like ``cliched but effective.'' It's
practically asking for trouble when it combines two genres, the
boxing drama and the father-son conflict drama, that have
near-rigid sets of rules. It's almost impossible to bring anything
new to the party, and aside from focusing on a Latino family,
``Price of Glory'' doesn't. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EL DORADO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ At one point during DreamWorks' new animated film
``The Road to El Dorado,'' one of the heroes comments, ``This city
is full of suckers.'' Apparently, the filmmakers had the same
contempt for their audience. Shoddy storytelling, questionable
racial politics and one of the worst sets of songs Elton John and
Tim Rice have ever cooked up come together in a film that proves
that all that glitters is not gold. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THE SKULLS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Virtually everything in ``The Skulls'' is bathed in
natural light, coming from behind the characters and creating a
haze so thick that it's a wonder the cast doesn't lapse into
coughing fits. The few electric-light sources in the movie don't
provide much illumination. Thus, the movie provides an apt metaphor
for itself: It's a dim bulb. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Gov. George W. Bush doesn't need the help of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People to win
Texas. Therefore, it is well that NAACP President/CEO Kweisi Mfume
has exhibited the industrial-strength good sense to decline to
dilute the national organization's resources by taking an active
role in the effort by the state chapter to persuade Bush to take a
stand against the Confederate battle flag. By CECIL JOHNSON. Story
has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ All the world's a stage, the Bard tells us, but
perhaps especially the business world. So why not turn to fiction
for a bit of management advice? That is the premise behind Robert
A. Brawer's ``Fictions of Business: Insight on Management From
Great Literature'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 248 pages, $16.95). The
book, now out in paperback, received rave reviews when it was first
published, as Brawer melded two of his favorite topics _ business
and literature. By TERESA MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f''
financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
