<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-SILICON-ALLEY-NY     03-30 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-SILICON-ALLEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST, AND FOUND, AS THE VALLEY HUNTS FOR A HIDDEN ALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MATT RICHTEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TO: My friends in the San Francisco Bay Area, center of the
universe
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Matt
</P>
<P>
   SUBJECT: Search for Silicon Alley
</P>
<P>
   Friends, I write from the Big Apple, home to Broadway shows,
museums and unmatched cuisine. What a backwater!
</P>
<P>
   Unlike our enlightened and searingly focused Silicon Valley,
this place is distracted from the most important pursuit of our
era, the Internet revolution. Here, innovation is not a cause
celebre, tech entrepreneurs are scarce and, sadly, many people are
in their late 20s before they get their first stock option.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is said to be a place called Silicon Alley, New
York's answer to Northern California, a Manhattan enclave of
high-technology entrepreneurs. I decided to check it out, which
wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, many people I spoke with on the street cared
little about the digital revolution, and inexplicably have no plans
to quit their jobs, drop out of school or leave a spouse to start
an Internet company. More to the immediate point, they have no idea
where Silicon Alley is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it what?'' said Bashir Saleh, who sells coffee and
bagels just off Times Square, and who suggested I walk south.
``Maybe it's near Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't he just say he doesn't even want to be an Internet
billionaire?
</P>
<P>
   So I began my descent, walking through the garment district and
past Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Saleh wasn't the only person incapable of giving directions to
the Alley. I stopped, but got no satisfaction from, a police
officer, security guards, food vendors and numerous passers-by,
including a woman named Alison Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in Washington State,'' Bradford said. ``That's
where Bill Gates is from.''
</P>
<P>
   Have these people no shame?! I engaged her in word association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Bezos,'' I said reverently of the founder of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't heard of him,'' she admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPO,'' I said next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's when you get stock shares before someone
else,'' she muttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandwidth,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No idea,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   I gave up. This woman wasn't tech-savvy in the least. She
probably thinks Unix refers to people who have been neutered.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford was in a hurry, she said, because she had to get to a
taping of ``The Ricki Lake Show,'' a program whose appeal is
utterly beyond me, given that they rarely talk about day trading.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked farther south, and east, I met Maryann Finnegan.
``You've come to the wrong place if you want to talk computer
jargon,'' Finnegan said. I was, however, in the right place to talk
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   She owns Foliage Garden, a shop in the flower district.
Surrounded by beautiful azaleas in front of her shop, she said she
suspected Silicon Alley was just another commercial district in New
York, like the diamond or toy district, or a neighborhood, like
Chelsea or Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has everything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aha! It's just as I suspected. Silicon Alley is an afterthought
here. After all, Northern California has great activities, too, but
we don't let them subvert the Internet revolution. I would have
told Finnegan that, but I got directions to Little Italy instead. I
also asked for a restaurant recommendation, directions to the East
Village, tips on getting tickets to ``Cats'' and what it would be
like to get into the flower business.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case this e-commerce stuff doesn't pan out.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Finnegan has an interesting business model in
that she appears to be making a profit. This is something we may
want to experiment in the e-commerce space.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I was becoming discouraged, fearful that this backwater
might pull me in, a vision appeared across the horizon. As I
wandered south on Broadway, around 25th Street, munching on a giant
falafel from a street vendor, I saw a giant sign hanging from a
building two blocks away on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   It read ``DoubleClick welcomes you to Silicon Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Success!
</P>
<P>
   Drawn like a Crusader to the Grail, but with much less chain
mail, I headed for the sign. I had arrived. There, beneath the
sign, was a familiar sight, a man strolling down the street working
on a Palm Pilot (albeit an outdated version). I called out to him,
high-tech brother to high-tech brother, ``Sir, can you tell me
where to find the heart of Silicon Alley?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of what?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Alley,'' I said, bewildered. ``Aren't we in Silicon
Alley?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never heard of it,'' he said, standing beneath the sign, which
he apparently had not seen or bothered to read. ``Maybe it's near
SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, Ben Bocardo, said we might or might not have been
standing in Silicon Alley, but he didn't know and didn't care. He
said he did know the music district, which is uptown. He said he
was a bass player. I asked him if he performed music for streaming
over the Internet or for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live,'' he explained. Sounds interesting, I thought. Maybe I
can check out his performance after I see ``Cats'' and visit the
Empire State Building and the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But I still wondered: Had I found Silicon Alley or not?
</P>
<P>
   I finally found out. I took a subway to Wall Street (fascinating
area; you should check it out sometime) and asked the participants
in a conference titled ``Silicon Alley Executive'' where I could
find the Alley.
</P>
<P>
   They confessed the truth: They were not sure either. The area
where I had been standing beneath the DoubleClick sign turned out
to be the original center of it all. But, they explained, it is now
a broader term for the community of Internet companies in the New
York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a general place,'' said Len Duckman, the sales manager
for Interactive Futures, a Web consulting firm. ``It's like
Brigadoon.''
</P>
<P>
   So it turns out Silicon Alley is both everywhere and nowhere,
and, in either case, merely a piece of New York, along with Wall
Street, Broadway, the flower district, nooks and neighborhoods,
fashion, falafel vendors, street-side food, artists and musicians
and even, in what they call the ``boroughs,'' places where people
actually make tangible things. In short, can you believe how myopic
this place is? It doesn't hold a candle to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   To find out how myopic, I plan to stay awhile to check out the
attractions. Anybody know the way to SoHo?
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Matt Richtel is a staff writer for The New York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ECOM-SHOPPING-TRIAL-N     03-30 1882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-SHOPPING-TRIAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTERNET DUMMY LOGS ON FOR A SHOPPING ADVENTURE
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BRIAN ALEXANDER  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Sen. John McCain thinks that online shopping is so vital to
America's prosperity that it should be tax free. Until now, I had
shirked my patriotic duty. I had never shopped online. When I
confessed this, people reacted the way women at Vogue magazine
would react if someone mispronounced ``Manolo Blahnik.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid being labeled a misfit and to help keep our national
economic engine humming, I jumped at the chance to shop on the Web
for things I really needed and wanted. I then compared online and
real-world shopping experiences by buying the same items the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   I kept score by price, time and frustration level (a 0 is no
frustration; 3 is highest), and included driving time when judging
real store shopping.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, I should admit a few things. First, I am biased
toward interacting with real people rather than sitting at home
with my computer and credit card. So if the scores for the real
stores and the online stores were close, I favored the real stores.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is a learning curve to shopping online. My early
purchases proved more frustrating than later ones. For example, it
took hours for me to realize that typing a fairly common word into
a search engine was hopeless. A search for ``modems'' generated a
list of more than a million Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Third, regardless of where I shopped on the Internet, I was
continually assaulted by DoubleClick advertisements; requests for
``cookies''; warnings about my Netscape security certificate
lapsing (whatever that means); windows upon windows alerting me to
a ``Java Script Error'' (whatever that means); and my favorite:
``This program has performed an illegal operation and will be shut
down.'' I half- expected Eliot Ness to burst through my door. (I
also learned to click ``OK'' or ``Continue'' and keep my fingers
crossed.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, my perception was also influenced by the fact that my
computer is almost five years old. It has a 75-megahertz processor
and 16 megabytes of memory. The modem is a 14.4K. I have made
coffee while waiting for sites to download. In Silicon Valley's
view, this means I should buy a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   MODEM
</P>
<P>
   Instead of replacing my computer, however, I hijacked my wife's
laptop and beefed it up with a new 56K modem. After two hours of
ineffective searching, I found the 3Com Web site and selected a 56K
V.90 Wintel modem card. The purchase took 20 minutes, only because
I read the 14-paragraph legal document headed ``Contract'' and the
privacy statement that said, essentially, there was no such thing
as privacy. I paid $133.81, including tax and shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The modem arrived three days early. Installing it was tricky, so
I added 25 penalty minutes for consulting a technician by phone,
plus 10 minutes for the moment he said, ``Man, I give this a 2-to-1
shot of ever working.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked, finally, but did not increase the laptop's speed
because of its limited memory. I returned to my own digital jalopy.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping at a real store for the same type of modem was even
more frustrating. I drove to Radio Shack, Circuit City and Staples.
None stocked the modem. Circuit City had an Actiontec for $99.99;
with tax, $107.75.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: Online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: Two and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $133.81, including tax and shipping.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: 2.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: 3Com accepted the return without a hitch and
promised to credit my charge card, but I had to pay to ship the
modem back.
</P>
<P>
   PROSCIUTTO
</P>
<P>
   Two hours into my search for prosciutto, I knew more about
Parma, Italy, home of arguably the best prosciutto in the world,
but had failed to order any of the ham. I did find Muscovy duck
prosciutto. At last I settled for Serrano ham, a Spanish
prosciutto, from Dean &AMP; Deluca, in New York. That site was easy to
use, and the ham arrived in two days, on time, packed in an ice
chest. But I paid $47.21 (yikes!), including shipping, for one
pound.
</P>
<P>
   Prosciutto was simple to find at the Italian deli a couple of
miles from my house. The guy behind the counter had suggested San
Daniele, for only $19.95 a pound. No shipping.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: The store.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: None.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: Dean &AMP; Deluca would accept the return of the meat if
it was unopened, but I would have to pay shipping. The deli would
not accept the return of perishable food.
</P>
<P>
   TERMITE STAKES
</P>
<P>
   I have been fighting a chemical war with termites for two years.
So I clicked onto an America Online shopping link for
HomeTownStores.com, an online hardware store. The site required
that I register and select a password, which I immediately forgot.
</P>
<P>
   When I searched for ``termite'' I found termite paper and
termite shields. I had no idea what they did, and the site did not
tell me. I scrolled down and found termite stakes, which are placed
in the ground around the house to kill termite colonies. I ordered
and paid $67.37, including shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the stakes arrived almost a week later than
promised, but they weren't stakes. The box, in fact, contained four
washing-machine hoses. Somewhere there is a guy in dirty clothes
holding 20 termite stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot stocked the Terminate brand stakes, charging only $49
for 20.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: The store.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $52.60, with tax.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: 2 (I forgot where I had parked my car).
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: Easy at Home Depot, except for the long line at the
return counter. I paid to ship the hoses back to
HomeTownStores.com, and it promised to credit my account.
</P>
<P>
   TOASTER OVEN
</P>
<P>
   Several months after my wife and I moved into our house, we
realized, thanks to the oven door's exploding open, that the gas
ignition was not working properly. Last month, the handle on our
toaster fell off. So we decided to buy a countertop toaster oven,
solving two problems at once.
</P>
<P>
   First we tried the Yahoo Kitchen and Home site. We chose a
DeLonghi convection toaster oven for $179.95, which was at least
$100 more than I had expected to pay, but it was Italian and
sounded sexy, so we got it.
</P>
<P>
   The next day I received an e-mail message saying that the
company was out of the ovens. That same morning, however, I had
seen an advertisement in a newspaper for a site called Tavolo.com.
I typed in the Web address, the site popped up, I searched for
DeLonghi ovens, and there they were.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other sites, Tavolo offered the option of not registering
an account with passwords and other information. I liked that. The
oven was also $179.95, so I bought it. With tax, I paid $193.04.
Tavolo did not charge for shipping. The oven showed up three days
later, as promised. A week later, Tavolo.com sent me free jam and
chocolate candy.
</P>
<P>
   I drove to a local Williams-Sonoma store and quickly found the
same oven. It was also $179.95. With tax, it would be $193.90.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: A tie. Tavolo was easy and took less time, but I liked
the saleswoman at Williams-Sonoma, who showed me how to use the
oven.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: One hour for Williams-Sonoma; 15 minutes for
Tavolo.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $193.90.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: 1.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: Both items were simple to return. Williams-Sonoma's
policy is unconditional, as is Tavolo's. Tavolo will have the
appliance picked up under most circumstances. No charge for
shipping, though I was unable to make my computer print out the
no-postage coupon Tavolo sent by e-mail. On second try, Tavolo
faxed the coupon to me.
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I buy our coffee at a warehouse store. It is not
great coffee, but it is about $8 for two pounds of whole beans, a
deal. I figured that the Web might offer better coffee at a good
price and that I might be able to subscribe to a service that would
ship coffee to my door every month.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites sell coffee, but few offer regular home delivery.
Then I found E-Java.com. It offered a choice of three coffees, each
in 12-ounce bags to be delivered monthly. I ordered Vienna Roast,
Guatemala Antigua and French Roast. Including shipping, I paid
$24.49 for the three bags, or 36 ounces. I also got a friendly
e-mail message confirming the order, and when the coffee arrived on
time two days later, the box included two samples as well as coffee
candy.
</P>
<P>
   Because the site did not sell the cut-rate beans I was after, I
compared the E-Java.com deal with what was available at a local
gourmet roaster. The shop sold beans by the pound. Vienna Roast,
French Roast and Guatemala beans were $10 a pound each; 48 ounces
cost $30, no tax.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: A close call, but the store was cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $30.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: 2. (I got caught in traffic and realized I could
not afford good coffee from either source.)
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: E-Java would accept the return and credit my
account, but I would have to pay the shipping costs. The roaster
did not accept returns.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK
</P>
<P>
   When I told people I had never bought anything online, they
responded, ``Not even a book?'' So I clicked onto Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   I considered buying ``Technopoly: The Surrender of Culture to
Technology,'' by Neil Postman, a techno-skeptic and cultural
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to click the buy button, I recalled all the people who had
considered me a rube. I also thought of John McCain and my nation's
economy. So I raised a white flag and ordered ``The Complete
Idiot's Guide to Internet Shopping'' for $18.43, including
shipping. It arrived two days later, on time.
</P>
<P>
   I then drove to a large bookstore, but the book was out of
stock. The store could order it in four or five days for $18.26,
including tax, but I would have to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   WINNER: Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL TIME: 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: $18.43.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATION: 1. (I took a point off for the brief identity
crisis I suffered upon re-entering the site: ``Hello, Brian
Alexander! If you are not Brian Alexander, click here.'')
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN: I paid the shipping costs to return the book to
Amazon.com. The store would accept returns if the book was in its
original condition.
</P>
<P>
   POSTSCRIPT
</P>
<P>
   One week after my shopping excursion, I bowed to the inevitable
and ordered a 700 megahertz computer at the Hewlett-Packard Web
site. I am also signing up for a digital subscriber line. Now let
them smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Alexander contributes to Wired and other
publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
