<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ECOM-PRICE-DISCOUNTS-     03-30 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-PRICE-DISCOUNTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBODY PAYS RETAIL, BUT THE REAL BARGAINS MAY FADE AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By STACY KRAVETZ  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Come on, admit it. Who does not love getting a deal, no matter
how much it costs?
</P>
<P>
   Marketers depend on consumers' desires to go after deals, even
for things we would never buy without a dollar-off coupon. Online
retailers are equally savvy, offering all types of discounts for
shopping on their sites. The fact is that online discounts are much
like their real-store counterparts: they lure us in, get us to
spend more than we planned and send us home reassured that we got a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   But keep this in mind: Online retailers are not charities. Even
Web sites will need to make money some day.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been bona fide deals, especially around
the recent holidays. In December, for instance, many sites offered
free shipping and deep discounts that undercut prices at their very
own brick-and-mortar stores.
</P>
<P>
   But as post-holiday reality set in, discounts reverted to more
typical forms: most were 9 percent to 16 percent off the regular
price, but many retailers compensated with costly shipping and
handling, or by charging fees for returns. Retailers make higher
profits on shipping charges than on merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites make comparison shopping arduous by forcing you to
click through multiple screens to find out what a sweater really
costs, all told, with tax, shipping and handling. Retailers hope
you will invest so much time that you will go ahead and make the
purchase, discounted or not.
</P>
<P>
   In case that makes you want to head for the malls, here are some
of the newest players in the online retail contest: sites that help
you get a good deal at other sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reverse auctions. Sites like priceline.com, buyersedge.com and
liquidprice.com have popularized the concept of searching for a
retailer to match the price you are willing to pay. Often such
sites automatically charge the item to your credit card if a
retailer agrees to your price (so you had better want it). Others
allow retailers to bid against each other until one prevails with
the lowest price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Group purchasing. Buytogether.com, mercata.com and
accompany.com gather buyers who are interested in the same product
and offer a group discount. The price goes down as more buyers
enter the group until a specified deadline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online coupons. Hotcoupons.com and clickrewards.com, among
other sites, give you incentives ranging from frequent-flier miles
to online coupons for local stores.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are sites that help you navigate through the discount
jungle. Most people do not even know they exist. A study of 5,831
online shoppers revealed that only 34 percent were aware of sites
that compare prices, according to Forrester Research, a consulting
firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Price-comparison sites will sift through discounters when you
specify the item you want. Automated shopping robots, or bots, like
mysimon.com and hotbot.com, scan the Web for the lowest price on
the item. Pricing engines like dealtime.com, bottomdollar.com,
deals.com and pricegrabber.com list online retailers who carry the
item and offer merchant ratings and delivery information.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, like bizrate.com, offer rating systems that
evaluate an online retailer's prices, promptness of delivery and
shipping charges.
</P>
<P>
   All this assistance, however, does not necessarily mean that
there are great deals to be had. Experts say, for example, that the
bargains carry costs of their own.
</P>
<P>
   David Cooperstein, the director of online retail research at
Forrester, says that by and large, Web discounters are worth
looking at when you are buying an item that costs a few hundred
dollars or more. If you can save 5 percent by shopping
comparatively for 15 minutes, it is usually worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the trade-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Time, for instance. How long does it take to find a good price,
and how long until delivery? Do you really want a weeklong delay
for a Zip disk drive to travel via ground transport just because
the out-of-state purchase allows you to skirt sales tax?
</P>
<P>
   Some online retailers offer a good deal if you are willing to
give information about yourself and do not mind having your name
circulating among marketers. You can get anything from rebates to a
free mouse pad for filling out customer surveys and product
registration information.
</P>
<P>
   If you like your privacy, you should save your money another
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers make consumers choose,'' Cooperstein said. ``To get
discounts you have to give some data or spend your time
researching.''
</P>
<P>
   Web shopping is no place for suckers. The discounting sites
shout at you with bold colors and spinning logos, prodding you to
jump at the low, low prices. Some retailers pay to advertise on
price comparison sites, fooling you into thinking that their price
is the best. Sometimes deep discounts are real, albeit temporary _
meant to build loyalty and subliminally lure you to buy full-price
items later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sites in the health- and beauty-aids business may offer
incredible discounts on over-the-counter items to hook you so
you'll come back to buy more expensive items,'' said Alan Alper, an
analyst with Gomez Advisors in Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Brand-name items like the Sony Walkman or the Apple iMac are
less likely to have wide swings in prices, whether online or in a
retail store.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not care about buying a brand name, your chances of
finding a deep discount are greater. Your chances of being
enormously confused are, unfortunately, also greater, because your
searches will turn up hundreds of choices.
</P>
<P>
   Online shopping, of course, is in its infancy. It has the
potential to offer one-stop shopping through sites that can build
profiles for shoppers to be used to troll the Web for sales, deals
and new online retailers that will match shoppers' exact
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   That is still a leap into the future. But one thing is certain.
For people who seek a deal, Internet shopping provides one more way
to persuade themselves that they have found one.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Stacy Kravetz covers business from Los Angeles. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
