<HEADLINE>
NEW SPECIES FACE AN OLD STRUGGLE, AS COMPETITION HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A century from now, Internet archaeologists may look back at the
last several years and liken them to an electronic Precambrian era:
a time when new life exploded in spectacular abundance. But as in
that prehistoric era, not all the creatures emerging from the
fecund swamps are equally adapted for survival.
</P>
<P>
   When the Net was still new and all potential (about six months
ago), it seemed that practically everyone who had a half-baked idea
or worse was starting a dot-com enterprise, raising a truckload of
cash, going public and becoming a millionaire. So many prospered so
easily because investors, both public and private, were willing to
buy into companies with enormous losses on promises of great future
returns.
</P>
<P>
   This could not go on forever, and, in fact, since the new year
it has been clear that the venture capitalists and the public
markets alike are becoming skeptical of promises of fabulous future
earnings and are starting to tighten the capital flow to
e-retailers. There is still money flowing, but it is often going to
ventures that facilitate commerce among businesses, a rather more
stable proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The pull of real-world gravity has been widely felt. From
service providers like Juno to community sites like iVillage,
e-businesses have seen their stock prices sink from celestial
levels. But the punishment has been particularly brutal to
retailers that do business solely on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do those merchants have to contend with an increasingly
crowded field, but they also have to battle clicks-and-mortar
retailers like Wal-mart.com and Macys.com, which were slow to enter
the Internet game but are now wielding their well-established brand
names like clubbed tails.
</P>
<P>
   In this tougher environment, the evolutionary winnowing should
begin pretty quickly. Companies that cannot show a plausible way to
stanch the outflow of cash are going to be very vulnerable very
soon. ``Come April, we are going to be watching first-quarter
results very closely,'' said Steve Westly, a vice president for
business development at the profitable online auction site eBay,
his voice purring with the contentment of a predator about to be
well fed. ``We think after the news of the disappointing results
gets out, there will be a lot of bargains out there'' for bigger
companies looking to expand by acquiring smaller ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the gold-rush mentality has started to fade, and it is
apparent that not every company with a dot-com in its name will
strike the mother lode, serious players _ venture capitalists,
stock analysts, company executives _ are beginning to evaluate
survivability in a more systematic manner. Of the organisms that
have crawled out of the primordial electronic muck, a rough
consensus has emerged as to which types are eventually going to be
profitable. Of course, evolution on the World Wide Web is happening
so fast that generalizations get out of date quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Today, people who shop on the Web are used to getting bargains.
Drugstore sites will sell, say, a large package of disposable
diapers, a tube of toothpaste, vitamins and athlete's-foot powder,
all for $3.50 (only a small exaggeration). Electronics sites will
sell DVD players for $169.95 each, less than their cost, and then
ship them free overnight. ``It's too good to be true,'' you say to
yourself. And you're right!
</P>
<P>
   The first victims of tighter investment capital will be Web
sites that have been selling goods at a loss or giving them away
while they were, in effect, buying customers. Not long ago,
building market share at any cost was the mantra of the Web, but
the gratuitous cash-bleeding model is increasingly being viewed, to
quote that famous, now out-of-business, New York retail innovator,
Crazy Eddie, as ``Insane!''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of most sites that lose money on products _ the most
prominent example of which is Buy.com _ is to draw a huge customer
base and sell those eyeballs (and data on their buying habits) to
advertisers. Here is the problem with that model: most shoppers do
care about price, but they have other concerns, like credit-card
security, familiarity and reliability _ priorities that retailers
overlook in their chase for advertising dollars rather than sales
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it turns out that the number of people willing to give
away their souls for bargain-priced goods is smaller than was
anticipated _ and certainly smaller than the threshold for enticing
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of last year, Free-PC _ whose plan was to give
away computers to customers willing to accept two permanent strips
of company-controlled advertising space on either side of the
computer screen _ was bragging that it would be bigger than
Microsoft. But in November, Free-PC agreed to be acquired by
another computer manufacturer in a tacit admission that its
business plan had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that to get the business model to work we needed
at least one million users,'' the founder, Bill Gross, said at the
time. ``At 10,000 a quarter, we couldn't get to one million fast
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another drawback to the below-cost model. It turns out
that consumers who care only about price are gone the moment they
smell a better deal. ``Price-loyalty people are the most fickle,''
said Ken Orton, the chief strategist at Cognitiative, an e-business
consulting firm in San Francisco. ``They are antibrand loyal. They
can't tell you where they bought their last toy or CD.''
</P>
<P>
   BRED FOR THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   The best business to have on the Web, logically, is a business
that cannot exist in the real world because such a venture faces
none of the very real, very fierce competition being perpetuated by
the clicks-and-mortar retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concepts that have the best chance of surviving,'' said
Henry Blodgett, an Internet analyst with Merrill Lynch, ``are those
whose content and services are not portered from traditional media
and retailing, but are purely Internet or interactive services.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that fit best into this slot are those that let
consumers negotiate their own price, and the best of these are
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   EBay, of course, has popularized the online auction model and is
still the biggest operator of such a site. It used the Web's
technology to bring together an audience that had previously been
hopelessly fragmented by geography. Suddenly, a collector of 1940s
soda bottles did not need to peruse every flea market on the
Eastern Seaboard to find the perfect World War II Coke bottle; he
just needed to search online.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of being a middleman, from the site operator's point
of view, is low overhead: no inventory, no shipping and primarily
word-of-mouth advertising, in return for a cut of each transaction.
Compare that with Amazon.com, which lost $720 million in 1999,
largely by investing in marketing and very expensive
infrastructure, like automated warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Most online retailers, if they want to service their customers
well, will have to do the same thing. But not eBay, which made $11
million in 1999. That is why its model is being duplicated widely.
Now Yahoo does auctions. Amazon does auctions. Ubid does auctions.
And so will anyone else with half a brain. Allowing customers to
sell to one another is a path to easy money.
</P>
<P>
   The real question now is whether there is another
alternative-pricing model that makes as much sense.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft, has put money into
finding out. He is an investor in the two leading examples of such
models: Priceline.com and Mercata.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline is the best-known actor in the reverse-auction
business, where the consumer names a price and sellers bid to meet
it. To keep customers happy, the company used to make up the
difference (within reason) between what buyers bid and sellers will
accept. That translated into a $1 billion loss last year (ouch!)
and a stock price that has gyrated between $160 and the $50s.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata's plan is to allow consumers who want to buy the same
item to group together and negotiate a price from a seller: the
idea is that the bigger the sale, the lower the price. Despite
television ads comparing this power-buying concept to having sex,
Mercata has not aroused enough naturally existing passions to
bargain as much as eBay and other auctions do. But sometimes it
takes a while for kinkier practices to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   DANGER IN THE NICHES
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, entrepreneurs rushed to set up stores that
they inevitably promised would be the Amazon.com of
fill-in-the-blank: pet stuff, watches, beauty products, baby gear,
furniture, pig entrails (OK, that's made up), wine, ad infinitum.
Some of these stores are focusing on a startlingly narrow array of
merchandise. FogDog.com sells sportswear, but Chipshot.com just
sells golf clothes and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the street is that the next big set of goners is a
majority of the niche retailers. That is because there are too many
in each category and many are in businesses where profit margins
are too thin to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we approach the third or fourth inning,'' said James W.
Breyer, a managing partner of Accel Partners, the Palo Alto,
Calif., venture capital firm, e-businesses without high
gross-profit margins will not succeed. ``One has to be highly
suspect of the pets portals that are about to go public,'' he said.
``I would run for the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   AGE MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just the niche retailers who look vulnerable. It
is all the new Internet retailers that have no connection to or
history in the physical world. The big lesson from the most recent
Christmas shopping season is that a long-established brand name is
an unmatchable asset.
</P>
<P>
   To make their names known, dozens of dot-coms spent millions of
dollars each to advertise on programs like ``Ally McBeal'' and
``Monday Night Football.'' The outcome? The start-ups' cost per
customer was stratospheric, while Old World retailers new to the
medium walked away with the majority of customers.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 most-visited Web sites during Christmas read like a who's
who of land retailing. JCPenney.com, Barnesandnoble.com, Gap.com,
Wal-Mart.com and VictoriasSecret.com were among the
clicks-and-mortar merchants who made the grade. With few
exceptions, the dot-coms that thrived were already fixtures _
including eBay, Amazon and CDnow.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that in Silicon Valley, the hottest Web sites for
investing are hybrids of the new and old. Bluelight.com, for
example, is a joint venture of Kmart, Yahoo and venture
capitalists. The independent company, which will sell Kmart
merchandise and more, will make use of the chain's vast buying
power and giant customer base to lower its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Passing along those savings to shoppers may be critical to sales
volume. Steve Jurvetson, a managing partner of Draper, Fisher
Jurvetson, a venture capital firm, envisions a future where
consumers will shop through an electronic wallet service _ a place
where you keep credit-card information that follows you as you
browse the shelves at Amazon.com and Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Such a service would allow one-click shopping anywhere on the
Web, eliminating the time-consuming step of filling out forms on
the first visit to each e-store. But such a service could also be
used to do comparison shopping by offering the same product from a
competing merchant at a lower price.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, retailers would not want to cooperate with
such a service. But if consumer demand forced them to comply, only
merchants selling brands they completely control would be safe from
price-cutting wars. If, for example, a customer wants Nike
sneakers, and Nike sneakers can only be purchased at FogDog.com, no
amount of competitive comparison would have an effect.
</P>
<P>
   Such an e-tailing plan is at least five years off, Jurvetson
said. And one never knows what fierce creature might spring from
the fertile Web-based loam and change the rules all over again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
