<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CUSTOMER-SERVICE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMER SERVICE: SOLVING PROBLEMS OR PREVENTING THEM? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PAUL GRIMES 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Expedia, the giant online travel agency that is owned primarily
by Microsoft, prides itself on customer service. In a gesture to
uneasy visitors to its Web site (www.expedia.msn.com), it recently
stopped insisting that they register and provide personal
information before browsing for flights, car rentals and hotel
rooms. The site now requires registration only when a browser turns
into a purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   The site promises replies to e-mail messages within 24 hours,
offers immediate assistance by telephone at any time and
meticulously follows up sales with offers of further service.
</P>
<P>
   For example, after Expedia sold me two airline tickets to San
Juan, Puerto Rico, it followed up a week before departure with an
e-mail message suggesting that the itinerary be reviewed, and
offered to book a hotel room, arrange a car rental and even buy
luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when I tried to look at the itinerary, I was
stymied. I had forgotten my ID and password, which were issued when
I bought the tickets. No wonder: I am registered with at least 50
Web sites and have many IDs and passwords.
</P>
<P>
   As the Web site advised, I dialed (800) Expedia (397-3342) for
help. After five minutes on hold, I was told that six calls were
ahead of mine. Four minutes later, ``Chuck'' responded, but the
connection was soon cut off. Six minutes later, I got through to
``Lawanda,'' who quickly e-mailed my user name and password.
</P>
<P>
   As online customer service goes, this experience was good. Web
businesses may be proliferating, but customer service varies
remarkably from site to site.
</P>
<P>
   As e-commerce is maturing, however, there is a new emphasis on
customer service, and virtually every online trade conference
addresses the issue. On the customer end, a recent report by
Forrester Research, the market research firm, found that 90 percent
of online shoppers consider good customer service to be critical
when choosing a Web merchant.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester calculated that 4.8 million people, or 37 percent of
those who have made purchases on the Web, had used customer
services while shopping on the Internet. The report cited
unhappiness with service as a main reason shoppers stopped using
Internet merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The growing importance of online shopping is most apparent in
travel. According to a November report issued by PhoCus-Wright
Inc., a travel research company, 45 percent of online buyers said
they had bought travel on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the number of Americans who had booked trips
online had soared more than 80 percent in 1999, to 11 million. It
estimated the value of the online travel market at $7 billion in
1999 and projected a rise to $20 billion in 2001. Improvements in
customer service and security were cited as reasons for the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted that many people who browse online are
reluctant to buy because they object to the lack of human contact
and are uneasy about privacy and credit-card security.
</P>
<P>
   The more one reads about e-commerce customer service, the more
apparent it is that this can mean many things. It can mean the way
a business promotes its product (whether it gives a full, clear
description, answering the predictable questions without being
asked); the billing and checkout procedure (how simple is it, and
how secure?); the way a company responds to consumer problems and
questions. Is the purchase delivered as promised, with the customer
able to track it electronically before delivery? How easily can it
be returned for a replacement or credit?
</P>
<P>
   Some e-commerce sites go beyond satisfying a customer by
striving to build loyalty for future sales. Incentives include
frequent-flier miles and bonus miles to those who book an airline
on its own site. Some sites that sell beauty products send samples
to customers; others may send chocolates or flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some sites go to great lengths to promote loyalty. Two
years ago, I had Amazon.com send a book about Middle Eastern
history to Shlomo Sokol, my brother-in-law in Israel. The book was
charged to my Visa card. When I recently returned to Amazon to
order a book for myself, Amazon asked, ``Would you also like to
send this book to Shlomo Sokol?'' (My answer was no.)
</P>
<P>
   Customer service is handled in several ways: referring queries
to a telephone number (preferably toll-free); accepting or
soliciting e-mail messages and replying by e-mail; accepting e-mail
but replying by telephone; posting answers to predictable questions
on the Web site; and live online communication, or chats, between
the dealer and the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Live chats, or in Internet terms the exchange of written
messages, are among the most intriguing. The technique is used by
several large companies, like Lands' End, which sells clothing and
household goods through catalogs and online. Live chats work like
most chat rooms on the Web: One person types a question and clicks
``send,'' and the other replies. The aim is to have experts ready
to answer customers' questions.
</P>
<P>
   I recently tested this chat service on the Lands' End site
(www.landsend.com). Typing in my question, I received a message on
my computer screen that seemed remarkably like what I often hear on
the telephone: ``Your call is very important to us. Please continue
to hold and an agent will be with you momentarily. Thank you.''
Actually, the wait was not long, but the ensuing exchange took
longer than a discussion would have by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Asking questions by e-mail presents other problems. Some sites
promise quick replies and actually deliver them. Other sites take
much time, and some never respond. Among some sites that do
respond, it is clear from their generic or irrelevant replies that
little attention is paid to the questions.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively recent development is the subcontracting of
customer-service business. Companies like IBM
(www.ibm.com/solutions), LivePerson (www.liveperson.com),
PeopleSupport (www.peoplesupport.com) and Kana Communications
(www.kana.com) provide services for companies that prefer not to
manage their own. This means that when you have a live chat with
Lands' End, you will probably speak with a representative provided
by LivePerson.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a real person actually intrudes. A shopper may be
clicking on a retail site when suddenly word is received from a
sales clerk offering help. The clerk has been watching without the
shopper's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in customer-service communication online is by voice,
and that is important, because it is as close as you can get to
face-to-face communication. In an example, an online jewelry store,
Miadora (www.miadora.com), offers voice chats, instant messaging,
e-mail queries or toll-free telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   At almost every e-commerce site, customer service means, at
least partly, posting responses to ``frequently asked questions,''
or FAQs. Sometimes that is sufficient, but there are almost always
questions that cannot be answered this way. Forrester Research
found that only 19 percent of online shoppers with questions
searched for answers on the site, and only 11 percent went to the
FAQ's.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because a FAQ is not personal contact, researchers say.
They recognize that to answer all questions by e-mail or by
telephone would be costly. But they say that if e-retailers would
provide full product description, prompt shipment, delivery
tracking services and, for repeat customers, perks like free
express shipping, there would probably be fewer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paul Grimes is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
