<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-PENTAGON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOVERNMENT SHOPS THE NET, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR.  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been two years since the Pentagon decided to
build a virtual shopping mall on the Internet, and although its
corridors are stocked with goods from rations and uniforms to paper
and floppy disks, the military's main venture into e-commerce has
been going a little more slowly than planned.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the ``electronic mall,'' as the Pentagon calls the
project, had sales of more than $50 million in 1999, and expects
them to grow substantially this year. Its catalog lists more than 2
million different items, which military buyers worldwide can
theoretically obtain either from the military's depots or directly
from commercial vendors, whose own Web pages are linked to the
Pentagon's ordering system.
</P>
<P>
   But just like dot-coms in the civilian world, the Pentagon's
e-commerce venture is not exactly breaking even. Even though
start-up costs are modest and the e-mall allows buyers to shop
around for the lowest prices, a recent study found that it would
not start saving the Pentagon money until 2003 and that the savings
by 2005 would amount to just $48.5 million _ compared with the
Pentagon's current procurement budget of $54.28 billion a year. And
even as the project grows, the Pentagon has discovered some vexing
barriers to wider acceptance of its e-mall.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recently released report by the Pentagon's
inspector general, the military, under orders ``to aggressively
adopt best business practices'' including e-commerce, rushed the
e-mall into being even though it knew that it was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Two consultants and the federal Office of Management and Budget
had warned against moving too fast, the inspector general said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes 30 years to get a customer and 30 seconds to lose
one,'' said one of the consultants, the Scranton Electronic
Resource Center. ``The e-mall must be as near perfect as possible.
Anything less will result in large-scale customer disinterest,
alienation and, finally, nonparticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what happened in the early days, as the military
services found that the operation did not live up to its billing.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem cited by the inspector general was that many
procurement offices still rely on older computer systems that are
not fully compatible with the e-mall's ordering systems. In some
cases that meant that customers would have to enter their orders
twice _ once on the e-mall system and then on their local computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Don O'Brien, one of the e-mall's managers at the Defense
Logistics Agency, said the program was working to accommodate
buyers' needs and that for many types of purchases, like the
thousands of transactions of less than $2,500 for office supplies,
maintenance hardware and other items that the Pentagon buys each
year, the system was already working well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out ahead of the power curve, and being a pioneer is
not always the best position to be in on something like this,''
O'Brien acknowledged. So far, he said, the vast majority _ perhaps
90 percent _ of all e-mall purchases are for uniforms. But he said
this limitation was comparable to Amazon.com's strategy of starting
with online book sales and expanding later into other markets.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the military, the federal government is moving across
the board toward a day when electronic commerce is a common way of
doing its business.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Government Services Administration, which
manages all kinds of government purchases, has a program called GSA
Advantage that allows government employees to order products and
services directly over the Internet at the preferred government
price. The number of items available grew 30 percent in 1999, and
sales grew 50 percent, to more than a million dollars a day in late
September.
</P>
<P>
   For companies that want to do business with the government,
there is the Electronic Posting System, where more than 29,000
vendors are registered to receive automatic notices of
opportunities to sell to the government, an increase of 24 percent
in a year. Last year, the Department of Veterans Affairs and the
Commerce Department joined the Government Services Administration,
NASA, the Department of Transportation and the Department of the
Air Force as participants, and more are expected to join this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department has set up the Phoenix Opportunity
System, which notifies minority-owned companies of potential
partnerships and other business opportunities. The department also
offers a one-day e-commerce course for minority-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Another course in e-commerce is being developed by the Small
Business Administration for its online classroom at
http://classroom.sba.gov. It also maintains a ``gateway'' for
procurement information, linking small businesses to purchasing
offices at http://pronet.sba.gov.
</P>
<P>
   And the Treasury's Financial Management Service is testing an
electronic check-payment system to pay vendors; the first e-check
was delivered in 1998 and 50 vendors receiving federal payments of
at least $1 million a day are now participating in the pilot
program.
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge for the government is to tie all these systems
together into a single, electronic Sears, Roebuck catalog, complete
with its own billing system. There are already steps in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, for instance, there is the Central Contractor
Registry _ a Web site where contractors provide basic information
to the government before doing business with the military. It
replaces paper forms and includes 140,000 contractors, which is
expected to grow to 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the aerospace and other big industries are
moving toward online selling in civilian markets, don't expect the
Pentagon's e-mall to grow any time soon into an online system for
buying aircraft engines or radar electronics, O'Brien cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an internal debate about how far to take this,
and we are not talking that big,'' he said, citing considerations
like the security of information on the Internet. ``A lot of people
in the military have concerns about that, and their concerns are
well founded.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (John H. Cushman Jr. is a staff editor for The New York
Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
