<SLUG> BC-ECOM-INCUBATORS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE NOISE IN THE HUDDLE ROOM: A DAY IN AN INCUBATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By COREY KILGANNON  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As you step off the elevator onto the sixth floor of 55 Broad
Street in downtown Manhattan, you see a sign that says ``Ernst &AMP;
Young.'' But the scene just says young.
</P>
<P>
   A smiling 20-something receptionist wears a name tag identifying
him as Elvis Presley, and a blast of Bob Marley music accompanies
an employee leaving a conference room. Actually, they are called
``huddle rooms'' and have plush easy chairs and white walls on
which employees can write. The ``college rooms'' nearby have
dormitory-style couches where workers on marathon shifts can take
naps.
</P>
<P>
   The office sound system can rival a dance club's, and there are
assortments of bagels, croissants and sandwiches at the numerous
sleek, black food counters.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young is the world's third-largest consulting and
auditing firm, but it was clear one recent weekday that workers
casually talking over pizza at communal workplaces were not
analyzing financial statements. They were putting the finishing
touches on PlusFunds.com, the Web site for a company that is
scheduled to start and then go public in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The pizza and the personnel are all part of Ernst &AMP; Young's
incubator, begun last June to help entrepreneurs develop Internet
companies. By this June, the incubator is expected to become part
of Cap Gemini, the French company that agreed last month to buy
Ernst's consulting business in a deal worth $11.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Online businesses have grown more complex than the basement
start-ups of the Web's early days. Now, starting a company often
means multimillion-dollar stock deals, and the rush to market is
on. This is where incubators come in, helping online entrepreneurs
build Web companies, often within several months.
</P>
<P>
   Incubators began appearing in Silicon Valley several years ago
but are now cropping up nationwide and are even being started at
some universities, including Yale University and New York
University. With Internet initial-offering fever running high on
Wall Street, New York City has been particularly fertile ground.
Dot-com entrepreneurs are racing to sell investors on what could be
the next big start-up company, and many New York businesses that
were engaged in e-commerce have turned instead to hatching new
Web-based companies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 100 full-service incubators in the United States,
at least five are operating in New York and 20 others are forming,
said Seth Goldstein, a principal at Flatiron Partners, the New York
venture capital firm. With Internet companies spawning rapidly,
taking start-up ideas from the business plan into a fully formed
company is considered crucial to online success.
</P>
<P>
   The incubators provide entrepreneurs with financial, strategic
and technical support in exchange for a percentage of stock, hoping
the stock soars when the businesses are acquired or go public. The
incubators also offer business wisdom, connections to business
partners, access to venture capital and the all-important ``speed
to market'' _ the time needed to turn a business plan into a
working company.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young screens about 15 entrepreneurs a week over the
phone, said Alvi Abuaf, a partner at the firm and the founder and
director of the incubator, which employs 140 people. Some
entrepreneurs are invited before the ``idea-lator,'' a panel of
five experts. If the idea is approved, project managers from both
companies go through intense brainstorming sessions to develop
business and project strategies at Ernst's Accelerated Solutions
Environment on the second floor of 55 Broad Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young clients come with substantial financial backing,
and incubator services are not cheap: A typical initial fee is
$500,000, half of which must be paid in advance. Then there is the
cost of creating the online company _ $5 million to $20 million,
part of which is in the form of equity.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerated Solutions looks like a day-care center, and
participants use toys, video cameras and schoolroom desks. Artists
draw the concepts being discussed on wall-size blackboards, and
entrepreneurs role-play, pretending to solicit financing from
venture capitalists played by actors. Keeping the projects under
wraps during early stages is crucial in the office, which is shared
by several clients at once. There are large private phone booths
and machines throughout the offices that make white noise.
</P>
<P>
   After the workshops, the scramble to get online begins. Over a
six-month phase of intense project development, both the site and
the business are built by people working around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, entrepreneurs entering the incubator _ usually
financial-service companies with some financial backing _ pay 50
percent of the estimated fee early on and pay the rest when the
company is up and running or issues its first shares, which is an
incentive to make the business successful. In return for deferring
the fee, Ernst usually receives an extra 25 percent of its fee in
stock. Similar deals are struck with various service vendors for
the project, such as law firms and branding services, which accept
stock in exchange for deferring part of their fees.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world that Gregory Pappajohn, 35, a hedge-fund
manager, stepped into in 1998. Although Pappajohn had no experience
running an Internet business, two of his biggest investors
persuaded him to start a Web site that would analyze hedge funds
online, giving constant updated evaluations of investments.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1998, with $2 million devoted to the project, the three
partners hired Ernst &AMP; Young for a flat fee to plan and consult on
strategy for PlusFunds.com and to help develop its Web site from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But as the project progressed, PlusFunds, one of the clients
that showed Ernst &AMP; Young the value of developing an incubator,
began having the firm do more, including hiring service vendors and
recruiting technical teams to work on the site. Ernst &AMP; Young used
company contacts to obtain insurance policies, lease hardware and
software, arrange for legal and accounting services, and line up
venture capitalists for future financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff takes a lot of time, and Ernst &AMP; Young already had
those relationships,'' Pappajohn said, ``so it became like one-stop
shopping for us, and we get a nice stable of financial-services
firms.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few months, like most start-ups, PlusFunds offered Ernst
&AMP; Young some stock in return for deferring some of its fee until
the project was able to go public. Now Ernst &AMP; Young was more than
just a consultant; it had a stake in the success of the start-up.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership expedited the project and cut costs, Pappajohn
said, and Ernst &AMP; Young's expertise in the hedge-fund industry has
helped. Also, he said, the firm's well-known name, displayed
prominently on the site, lends credibility to a new
financial-services site.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hedge-fund site isn't one of those you can build out of your
garage,'' he said. ``If it had that image, people would giggle.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the same token, wouldn't Ernst &AMP; Young's name lend a
stodgy Old World feel to a site that calls itself revolutionary?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think it's like driving your father's
Oldsmobile,'' Abuaf of Ernst &AMP; Young said. ``It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing number of incubators, there are critics of
entrepreneurs who team with them.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, of Flatiron Partners, compared the
assembly-line-style minting of start-up companies to ``bringing a
high school athlete into the big leagues too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You rush ideas to launch to take advantage of the bullish
stock market, and the incubator just jumps to the next project,''
he said. ``In the long run, the entrepreneurs suffer from being
protected so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incubators are the safe route,'' he added. ``I call it
`entrepreneurship lite.' Real entrepreneurs take risks. In giving
you less chance to fail, incubators also give you less chance to
succeed. You tell an entrepreneur, `We'll take care of everything,
including the coffee cups,' and he misses out on the very culture
of his own company.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters argue that the initial stock offering _ not
company coziness _ is the name of the game. For that, it doesn't
hurt to connect with a firm that deals extensively with the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the investment-banking
community and has relationships with many Fortune 500 companies,
Pappajohn said.
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, groups of 20-something staff members of
Ernst &AMP; Young and PlusFunds worked out kinks in the data-delivery
systems, made sure Web pages were loading correctly and made
cosmetic adjustments to the site, which is scheduled to open for
business next month. An initial public offering is expected in
September.
</P>
<P>
   As work on the project winds down, Ernst employees are teaching
their jobs to PlusFunds employees. And then they will move on to
the next hot idea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Corey Kilgannon is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-WOMEN-NYTSF &LR;      03-30 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-WOMEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINCE WOMEN ASK FOR DIRECTIONS, THE WEB IS BEING REVAMPED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By STEVEN E. BRIER  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The demographics of the Internet have changed. Where men once
ruled, women are taking over. They account for about half the Web's
audience, various studies find, and are signing on in greater
numbers than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, there were not that many women on the
Internet,'' said Carol Kovac, a vice president at the Watson
Research Center at IBM. ``Today, we're on there and using it for
everyday things.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are looking for different information and in different
ways from the traditional male audience, forcing Web site designers
to rethink their products, from the colors used to the tools
provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women report learning their way around the Internet with
the help of someone,'' said Juliet Habjan Boisselle, a research
librarian at Mount Holyoke College in South Hadley, Mass., speaking
at a recent seminar discussing women on the Web. ``Men report
learning solo. In other words, women will ask directions, men
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are more pressed in their personal and professional lives,
which also affects their use of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at women in the United States,'' Kovac said,
``most women work outside the home but still do most of the
housework. They have a second shift. The women on the Web are using
it to enrich their lives and get their work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Habjan Boisselle said many women were further hampered by
limited access to a computer connected to the Internet, logging on
through public libraries and other systems open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Steltmann, an IBM executive whose job is marketing
equipment to women over the Web, said, ``Research shows that women
put a higher value on service, reputation and quality. They also
value different kinds of information; they're not as interested in
raw horsepower.''
</P>
<P>
   Men, Steltmann explained, typically want to know the ``speeds
and feeds'' of the technology that IBM is offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``For women, our message is not only the technology but what it
can do for their businesses,'' she said. ``Women want to know how
it will make them more profitable and allow more work to be done in
less time.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM provides that sort of information in a special section of
its small-business Web site ``where we can communicate directly to
women business owners,'' Steltmann said.
</P>
<P>
   There are also advice columns from other women who own
businesses along with time-management tips and technology tools.
Although these could help any business owners, they are aimed at
women and geared to their reliance on peers and experts.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar fashion, Hifi.com has introduced Herhifi.com, which
sells the same stereos and televisions as the original Web site but
in a different way. Links to a plain-spoken expert are displayed
prominently. And, instead of listing products in traditional
categories such as home theater or video, with emphasis on the
gadget, Herhifi.com emphasizes context, selling products by room,
such as kitchen and home office.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that cater to women generally have more prominent search
tools, links to chat rooms and forums or other places where the
users can ask questions _ features that female Web users in surveys
say more sites should adopt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers should consider moving from a broadcasting model of
communication to an interactive and dynamic palette where users are
collaborators,'' Habjan Boisselle said. ``E-mail and forums are
information-seeking and gathering behaviors themselves, not just
socialization.''
</P>
<P>
   But as in the real world, not all women in cyberspace want the
same thing, which marketers ignore at their peril. Indeed, Heather
Wagner, a multimedia artist and former designer for HBO, said it is
often wrong to think of female Web users primarily as women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go to a site as a woman,'' Wagner said. ``I go to find
out financial information or something about the Knicks game. So,
I'm going as a financial person or a sports fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Newer sites that cater to women tend not to replicate the look
or the content of a supermarket tabloid, something many
female-oriented sites did at first.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Geller Ettenheim, the librarian for Femina.com, a
collection of women-oriented Web sites, said newer sites also
tightly integrate design and technology to speed performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``New sites geared to women are designed to load quickly and
help women navigate clearly to the information they are seeking,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites for women, such as Womenconnect.com and Silicon
Salley, take these lessons to heart, providing quick links on their
home pages to financial advice, for example. They include tips on
how to craft a resume, as well as chat rooms, e-mail and other
community-building features that were not available before the
Internet created site niches.
</P>
<P>
   But just as there is not a single type of site to serve all men
on the Web, neither is there a single quick fix to attract women
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any site, it is important to have strong design,'' Wagner
said. ``If you are presenting serious information, it is important
to be serious. You can't just go with pinks and purples.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Steven E. Brier is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
