u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-30 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Met Pledged Japan Art &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As soon as the last statues and scrolls, urns and
laquerware pieces were in place for the opening of ``Masterpieces
of Japanese Art From the Mary Griggs Burke Collection,'' a spring
exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum, Burke announced that she had
promised her entire collection to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, a trustee who has been involved with the Met since 1962,
has spent the last 37 years putting together what is now considered
the finest collection of Japanese art in private hands outside
Japan. ``This is one of the few private collections that is not
concentrated in one area,'' Philippe de Montebello, director of the
Met, said. ``It is truly encyclopedic.''
</P>
<P>
   Her collection includes about 300 works, everything from early
ceramic vessels from the middle Jomon period (circa 2500-1500 B.C.)
to ink paintings from the 14th century to 17th-century screens.
Fewer than 200 are in the current show.
</P>
<P>
   Burke and her late husband, Jackson Burke, a printer and
designer of typefaces who died in 1975, first became involved in
the Met in 1962. More than 100 works from their collection were
shown at the museum in 1975. In 1985 Burke lent her holdings to the
Tokyo National Museum, the first American collection to be shown in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Burke has consistently lent art to the Metropolitan. Because so
many works in the Japanese galleries are light sensitive, the
curators rotate the collection several times a year and there are
always several of her objects on view.
</P>
<P>
   But the gift of her entire collection, de Montebello said,
``will transform the museum's collection in one stroke into one of
the greatest collections of Japanese art outside Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be able to present not just a good representative
cross-section of Japanese art,'' he said, ``but a sweeping panorama
of that great culture, and in many areas with great depth.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High Director &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a five-month search, the High Museum of Art in Atlanta has
announced that Michael E. Shapiro, its deputy director and chief
curator, will become the director. He replaces Ned Rifkin, who
became director of the Menil in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who was director of the Los Angeles County Museum for
10 months in 1994, joined the High the following year as director
of museum programs and its chief curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to maintain high-profile exhibitions,'' Shapiro said,
noting the six blockbuster shows, including ones on Matisse,
Picasso and Norman Rockwell, that have followed the exhibition the
museum put on during the Olympics. That 1996 show, ``Rings: Five
Passions in World Art,'' was organized by the High and J. Carter
Brown, director emeritus of the National Gallery of Art in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One coming show Shapiro expects will cause a stir is devoted to
Elton John's photography collection. John, a part-time resident of
Atlanta, has amassed one of the world's largest photography
collections. It includes about 2,000 vintage modern and
contemporary works, by artists like Berenice Abbott, Diane Arbus,
Henri Cartier-Bresson, Man Ray, Edward Steichen, Alfred Stieglitz,
Edward Weston and Tina Modotti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chorus of Light: Photographs From the Sir Elton John
Collection'' will be at the High Museum from Nov. 4 through Jan. 8,
2001. The exhibition, which will not travel elsewhere, will fill
the museum's fourth floor and will also spill over to the High's
downtown branch in the Georgia-Pacific Center. About 150 celebrity
photographs will be on view there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton John feels an attachment to the city,'' Shapiro said.
``He has been a member of the museum's Director's Circle, which is
the highest level of membership.'' He is also recording the show's
audio tour. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asian Focus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Asia Society's plans for its newly renovated home at 725
Park Ave., at 70th Street in Manhattan, include commissioning
site-specific works by Asian and Asian-American artists.
</P>
<P>
   Five arts professionals, working as a committee, will each
nominate two artists, who will be invited to submit two proposals
for installation pieces. Three to five of these proposed works will
be commissioned. The committee will submit their nominations by
June and the artists will be asked to submit proposals by August.
</P>
<P>
   The selections will be made by the fall. The goal is for the
works to be ready for installation next summer, in time for the
museum's re-opening next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pieces will be more or less permanent,'' said Vishakha N.
Desai, director of the Asia Society galleries and cultural
programs. ``Like the Calder at the National Gallery, we want pieces
that can be identified with the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Desi added that the invitational competition underscored the
institution's commitment to contemporary Asian art. The society has
also established a new curatorial post: associate curator of
contemporary Asian and Asian-American art. It will be a rotating
three-year position and the first curator will begin in early
2001. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harlem Moves &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as director of the Studio Museum in Harlem,
Lowery Stokes Sims has come up with new ways to entice visitors _
especially while the museum's century-old building undergoes a
facelift.
</P>
<P>
   During the work, the 125th Street entrance will move from the
west door to the east door of 144 W. 125th St. The museum's store
will move, too. From Wednesday through Sept. 17, it will be in the
main galleries instead of in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we are inconveniencing the public, we will change our
admission from $5 to pay-what-you-wish,'' Sims said. The new policy
begins Friday and will continue through Sept. 17. The museum is
also permanently extending its hours. Starting Saturday, it will be
open Wednesdays and Thursdays, noon to 6 p.m.; Fridays, noon to 8
p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. It remains closed on
Mondays and Tuesdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
