<HEADLINE>
MYMS, PINGS AND VORTALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By DAVID KIRBY and HENRY FOUNTAIN 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Travelers in the land of the up-and-dot-comers require neither
passports nor magic portals, but a dictionary of e-speak isn't a
bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   As with any industry, this one is generating buzzwords, idioms
and acronyms that are spicing up business exchanges and casual
chat, while confounding the ill-e-terate with their meanings.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are some choice candidates in the categories of
office talk, a field ripe for phrase-picking, and professional
parlance, the terminology tossed around by marketing mavens who are
in the know. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; INSIDERSPEAK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Ill-defined units of free time _ see ``How's Your Bandwidth?''
Example: ``Hey, Roberta, you have some cycles. Give me a hand.''
</P>
<P>
   + Double-click on that.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: That is really quite good. Example: ``Our IPO
tripled in value today. Double-click on that!''
</P>
<P>
   + Go bosh.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Go Big Or Stay Home.'' An acronym, meaning
something along the lines of ``Go for broke or withdraw from the
playing field.'' Example: ``When you're not sure what to do, it's
best to just go bosh.''
</P>
<P>
   + How's your bandwidth?
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Are you busy? Example: ``Hey, how's your bandwidth?
Can you stay late? Until Tuesday?''
</P>
<P>
   + It's just one iteration.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It's only the first draft. It will go through more
edits.
</P>
<P>
   + I've got to log off now.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: I have to hang up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   + Mym.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Meet Your Milestones. Example: ``When you launch,
you better go mym _ out there it's sink or mym.''
</P>
<P>
   + Ping.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: To contact, to call. Example: ``Where is Bob?'' ``I
don't know. Why don't you ping him?''
</P>
<P>
   + RLH.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: An e-mail sign-off, short for ``Run Like Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   + Take that offline.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Discuss in private. Example: ``Let's take your
insinuations offline, after this conference call.''
</P>
<P>
   + WIFH.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Warm, inviting, friendly and a little bit hip.''
This is how Internet companies want to be perceived by their
clients. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; INDUSTRY STANDARDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Airplane Rule, Banana Problem.
</P>
<P>
   These terms apparently evolved independently, but are variations
of the same idea.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane rule is another version of the old ``Keep it
simple, stupid.'' The idea is that with hardware, software or Web
design, complexity can increase the possibilities of failure. A
two-engine plane is likely to have twice as many problems as one
with a single engine.
</P>
<P>
   The banana problem evolved from the old joke about spelling the
word ``banana'': You don't know when to stop. It refers to sites
where the designers, perhaps under orders to maximize the time
users stay, can't stop adding bells and whistles, until everything
is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   + Brochureware.
</P>
<P>
   Not the kindest of terms. It refers to a Web site that lacks
interactivity, that contains only basic information about a company
_ in short, a site that is little more than a brochure.
</P>
<P>
   + Disintermediation.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting out the middleman. A stodgy term, but it applies well to
selling on the Internet, which allows a manufacturer to have a
direct relationship with customers. And yes, the people who talk
about the next new thing are talking about re-intermediation.
</P>
<P>
   + Scalability.
</P>
<P>
   A good thing to have _ it means that your hardware and software
will keep working even as site visits or transactions soar.
Metaphorically, it applies to whether your whole concept will fly.
</P>
<P>
   + Viral Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Word-of-mouth marketing, Internet style. The customer does the
dirty work of spreading the news about a product or a service, as
with the notes that free services append to every e-mail message
telling recipients how to get the service.
</P>
<P>
   + Vortal.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new term that only sounds like something the cat
dragged in. It's short for ``vertical portal,'' an Internet portal
for a narrow audience, such as Britney Spears fans.
</P>
<P>
   What's a portal? Such an old term hardly needs defining.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kirby is a Brooklyn-based free-lance writer. Henry
Fountain is deputy editor of the Circuits section of The New York
Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-DOMAIN-NAMES-NYT     03-30 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-DOMAIN-NAMES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-FOR-ALL ON THE NAME EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By SUE CUMMINGS 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Joan Kron, an editor at Allure magazine, did not think of
herself as a speculator when she registered some domain names in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   But her Net-savvy son, Daniel, who is the founder and creative
director of SportsForWomen.com, convinced his mother that the time
was right to reserve a few addresses that she could use later to
promote a book that she was writing about plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Kron registered before-and-after.com and beforeandafter.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get `lift,' and it was owned by Otis Elevator,''
she says, laughing. Facelift.com was taken, too, so she claimed
face-lift.com for the Web site where she eventually posted reviews
of her book ``Lift: Wanting, Fearing and Having a Facelift''
(Viking, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later, she actually bought the nonhyphenated
name _ which is easier to type _ for $2,500, and the traffic to her
site rose instantly. Meanwhile, the calls she got from strangers
who wanted to buy beforeandafter.com only reinforced her feeling
that she was on to something. So began her participation in
domain-name acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The recent surge in advertising by dot-com companies has
heightened the demand for names that are simple, memorable and
immediately connote a marketable product or service. Many of those
coveted names are still available when followed by ``net'' and
``org,'' but most companies would rather have a dot-com name, the
equivalent of a storefront on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Web's beginning, there has been a rush to grab virtual
real estate. That rush has now turned into a free-for-all, with
many people and companies registering, buying and selling names,
sometimes for astronomical sums.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of business.com to Ecompanies, an incubator of Internet
businesses, for a record $7.5 million last November signified the
value of the right domain name. That is because an Internet domain
is an internationally unique address, a potential brand, positioner
and tag line all in one. In the best situation, it is also not
registered as a trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Start-up businesses are as likely to buy a dot-com domain name
as to create one. In the thriving aftermarket for such names, many
are on their third or fourth owners. Domains change hands both at
general-auction sites such as eBay and at new sites, such as
Afternic.com and GreatDomains.com, which are dedicated to such
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Some one- or two-word dot-com names are trading in the low six
figures. Afternic, started in November, listed more than 78,000
domains for sale in February _ at least 80 percent of them
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   How much is a dot-com name worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to find its true market value is to float it,
like any other commodity,'' says John Whalen, a chief operating
officer at Afternic. ``The New York Stock Exchange is an exchange
for securities _ well, we're an exchange for domain names.''
</P>
<P>
   If the market value is high, the seller will reap a windfall,
because it costs only $70 every two years to register rights to a
domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Muenyong, a 23-year-old entrepreneur from Diamond Bar,
Calif., recently put mad.com for sale on Afternic, and is looking
forward to reaping a substantial profit. The bidding had reached
$225,000 as this article went to press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an addiction,'' Muenyong says. ``You find a name. It
costs you $70. You sell it for 10 times more than that. You're
like, `That's unbelievable.'''
</P>
<P>
   It has become difficult at times to distinguish among
domain-name speculation, cybersquatting and outright theft.
Speculators reserve names with the potential for future brand
development.
</P>
<P>
   So-called cybersquatters register names they know are
trademarked, hoping to coerce payment from the trademark owners.
Such was the case in January, when the Federal District Court in
Manhattan ordered Sau Wong of Hillsborough, Calif., to relinquish
msdw.com to the securities firm Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Another tactic is to exploit public confusion by registering a
domain name closely resembling a high-profile name, to try to
increase traffic on the similar-sounding site. Web surfers who go
to WhiteHouse.com instead of WhiteHouse.gov, for example, wind up
at a pornographic site.
</P>
<P>
   But most speculators say they register their domain names in
good faith, often while brainstorming business ideas. The practice
becomes more controversial if they grab a couple of names
simultaneously. Such speculators spend hours searching Network
Solutions, a database of registered domains, to devise new ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1998, while he was researching the name of his
new site, iranks.com, Muenyong discovered that a series of domain
names with the prefix ``i'' had not been taken. Within weeks, he
had registered several hundred _ he is now selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Muenyong began operating mad.com as a site for the Massive Adult
Directory, a guide to the development of pornography sites, when he
was barely old enough to view those sites' content legally. A
future buyer of mad.com, however, may use the name for an entirely
different kind of site.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Lackert, a lawyer who handles domain-name dispute
resolution for the World Intellectual Property Organization, says
buyers are taking a risk if they purchase a domain name that
resembles someone else's registered trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Registering such a name on the Internet is easy, he says, but it
is ``not the same thing as clearing a trademark for availability
and use.''
</P>
<P>
   For those others, who, like Kron, are sitting on domain names
that do not infringe on a trademark, foresight may prove lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, I'm going to keep the name,'' she says of
facelift.com. ``I think it's an annuity for my children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a long-term investment,'' she adds, ``but I
didn't buy it for a long-term investment. I bought it for vanity,
for power, for the fun of ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sue Cummings is editor-in-chief of MJI Broadcasting's
new-media division.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
