<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-BOL.COM-NYTSF &LR;      03-30 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-BOL.COM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOL.COM SERVES LOCAL FLAVORS ALL OVER EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Europe may be an Internet laggard, but the e-commerce sites that
seem to be succeeding are growing on European turf, not imported
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One German company, Bertelsmann Online (www.bol.com), is trying
to replicate the success of Amazon.com in Europe, with sites in
Britain, France, Germany, Spain, Switzerland and the Netherlands.
Bertelsmann, the parent and media conglomerate, owns a stake of
barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Wermelinger, the chief executive of bol.com, discusses the
challenges of creating such an e-commerce site. Here are excerpts
from the conversation. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Bol.com is trying to appeal to customers in six countries. If
the Internet is global, why do you need separate sites?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: One really important issue for an e-commerce
company to successfully enter Europe is to be localized.
</P>
<P>
   You have this multicultural situation, not only with many
languages, but even with customers' payment behavior. In parts of
Europe, if you're only going to accept credit cards, you're lost.
In some places you'll lose 60 percent of your customers, simply
because they won't give you their credit-card number.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If each bol.com site is local, what is the benefit of
creating a Pan-European brand?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: Take, for instance, Holland and Belgium, which have
the same language. Sites in Europe can do cross-border business
using the same site.
</P>
<P>
   Take Germany and Switzerland. They have the same newspapers,
which talk about the same things, so we can do cross-border
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can a European brand crack the American self-centeredness on
the Web?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: Amazon is in Europe, but they haven't been able to
break into more than two countries. You can't find a French or
Spanish Amazon yet.
</P>
<P>
   Every country is so different that it's the local businesses
with local partners that I suspect will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Isn't it harder to reach many fragmented audiences?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: It doesn't make it harder. When you look into the
individual sites, the framework is the same.
</P>
<P>
   The content is local, and we have local people working for each
site, but the development costs are spread across all the sites.
You have three or four products on one site, and that's what you
have in every country, but the products are not the same.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the United States, analysts predict that many Web
businesses will either merge or go bankrupt. With so many
micromarkets in Europe, are sites equally vulnerable?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: In every country we have many competitors. In the
end, there will be one or two big ones who will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The price of goods in Europe tends to be higher than in the
United States. Is it more expensive to operate in Europe than it is
across the pond?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: I don't think the costs are that different.
</P>
<P>
   On the labor issue, yes, you might have to pay higher wages. But
that is offset by the revenue generated from the products, which in
Europe are sold at a higher pricing level than in the States.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many e-commerce sites in the United States are financed
partly from sky-high valuations that were spawned by the frenzy for
initial public offerings. Is the European market ready for dot-com
mania?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: Doing an IPO in Europe is certainly newer than in
the States. But right now, with so much talk about the Internet,
I'm sure the markets will be receptive to IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Asia seems to be fertile ground for e-commerce expansion.
Indeed, bol.com is preparing a site in Japan. Will Americans
prevail there, will Europeans give them a fight or will local
companies dominate?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: Asia is an important market. When you look at
Japan, China, Korea, no big site is there yet.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the single biggest market for our business outside of
America. But, again, what's important in Japan is to not be
European or American. It's a very service-driven country, so being
localized will be the key.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Technology is changing, at different rates in different parts
of the world. How do you respond to the continuous changes?
</P>
<P>
   A : Some countries are going to skip the PC generation and move
directly into the mobile generation. For instance, there will be
more hand-held devices in China in two years than there will be in
all of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That is something that an e-commerce company has to be aware of,
and we will have to adjust our model and our technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will you adapt your business to accommodate hand-held
devices?
</P>
<P>
   WERMELINGER: The concept of doing e-commerce on a mobile is
different doing it on a computer. You can't put everything into
that small window on the mobile.
</P>
<P>
   The business model will change. It will become more promotional,
more search-engine-driven and more lists-driven. Mobile customers
will act faster _ they will need information faster. Therefore, you
will need to change the interface.
</P>
<P>
   However, the offerings will probably be more limited on mobile
devices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ross Sorkin is a writer based in The New York Times'
London bureau.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
