<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-SILICON-ALLEY-NY     03-30 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-SILICON-ALLEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST, AND FOUND, AS THE VALLEY HUNTS FOR A HIDDEN ALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MATT RICHTEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TO: My friends in the San Francisco Bay Area, center of the
universe
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Matt
</P>
<P>
   SUBJECT: Search for Silicon Alley
</P>
<P>
   Friends, I write from the Big Apple, home to Broadway shows,
museums and unmatched cuisine. What a backwater!
</P>
<P>
   Unlike our enlightened and searingly focused Silicon Valley,
this place is distracted from the most important pursuit of our
era, the Internet revolution. Here, innovation is not a cause
celebre, tech entrepreneurs are scarce and, sadly, many people are
in their late 20s before they get their first stock option.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is said to be a place called Silicon Alley, New
York's answer to Northern California, a Manhattan enclave of
high-technology entrepreneurs. I decided to check it out, which
wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, many people I spoke with on the street cared
little about the digital revolution, and inexplicably have no plans
to quit their jobs, drop out of school or leave a spouse to start
an Internet company. More to the immediate point, they have no idea
where Silicon Alley is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it what?'' said Bashir Saleh, who sells coffee and
bagels just off Times Square, and who suggested I walk south.
``Maybe it's near Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't he just say he doesn't even want to be an Internet
billionaire?
</P>
<P>
   So I began my descent, walking through the garment district and
past Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Saleh wasn't the only person incapable of giving directions to
the Alley. I stopped, but got no satisfaction from, a police
officer, security guards, food vendors and numerous passers-by,
including a woman named Alison Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in Washington State,'' Bradford said. ``That's
where Bill Gates is from.''
</P>
<P>
   Have these people no shame?! I engaged her in word association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Bezos,'' I said reverently of the founder of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't heard of him,'' she admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPO,'' I said next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's when you get stock shares before someone
else,'' she muttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandwidth,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No idea,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   I gave up. This woman wasn't tech-savvy in the least. She
probably thinks Unix refers to people who have been neutered.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford was in a hurry, she said, because she had to get to a
taping of ``The Ricki Lake Show,'' a program whose appeal is
utterly beyond me, given that they rarely talk about day trading.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked farther south, and east, I met Maryann Finnegan.
``You've come to the wrong place if you want to talk computer
jargon,'' Finnegan said. I was, however, in the right place to talk
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   She owns Foliage Garden, a shop in the flower district.
Surrounded by beautiful azaleas in front of her shop, she said she
suspected Silicon Alley was just another commercial district in New
York, like the diamond or toy district, or a neighborhood, like
Chelsea or Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has everything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aha! It's just as I suspected. Silicon Alley is an afterthought
here. After all, Northern California has great activities, too, but
we don't let them subvert the Internet revolution. I would have
told Finnegan that, but I got directions to Little Italy instead. I
also asked for a restaurant recommendation, directions to the East
Village, tips on getting tickets to ``Cats'' and what it would be
like to get into the flower business.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case this e-commerce stuff doesn't pan out.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Finnegan has an interesting business model in
that she appears to be making a profit. This is something we may
want to experiment in the e-commerce space.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I was becoming discouraged, fearful that this backwater
might pull me in, a vision appeared across the horizon. As I
wandered south on Broadway, around 25th Street, munching on a giant
falafel from a street vendor, I saw a giant sign hanging from a
building two blocks away on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   It read ``DoubleClick welcomes you to Silicon Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Success!
</P>
<P>
   Drawn like a Crusader to the Grail, but with much less chain
mail, I headed for the sign. I had arrived. There, beneath the
sign, was a familiar sight, a man strolling down the street working
on a Palm Pilot (albeit an outdated version). I called out to him,
high-tech brother to high-tech brother, ``Sir, can you tell me
where to find the heart of Silicon Alley?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of what?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Alley,'' I said, bewildered. ``Aren't we in Silicon
Alley?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never heard of it,'' he said, standing beneath the sign, which
he apparently had not seen or bothered to read. ``Maybe it's near
SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, Ben Bocardo, said we might or might not have been
standing in Silicon Alley, but he didn't know and didn't care. He
said he did know the music district, which is uptown. He said he
was a bass player. I asked him if he performed music for streaming
over the Internet or for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live,'' he explained. Sounds interesting, I thought. Maybe I
can check out his performance after I see ``Cats'' and visit the
Empire State Building and the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But I still wondered: Had I found Silicon Alley or not?
</P>
<P>
   I finally found out. I took a subway to Wall Street (fascinating
area; you should check it out sometime) and asked the participants
in a conference titled ``Silicon Alley Executive'' where I could
find the Alley.
</P>
<P>
   They confessed the truth: They were not sure either. The area
where I had been standing beneath the DoubleClick sign turned out
to be the original center of it all. But, they explained, it is now
a broader term for the community of Internet companies in the New
York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a general place,'' said Len Duckman, the sales manager
for Interactive Futures, a Web consulting firm. ``It's like
Brigadoon.''
</P>
<P>
   So it turns out Silicon Alley is both everywhere and nowhere,
and, in either case, merely a piece of New York, along with Wall
Street, Broadway, the flower district, nooks and neighborhoods,
fashion, falafel vendors, street-side food, artists and musicians
and even, in what they call the ``boroughs,'' places where people
actually make tangible things. In short, can you believe how myopic
this place is? It doesn't hold a candle to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   To find out how myopic, I plan to stay awhile to check out the
attractions. Anybody know the way to SoHo?
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Matt Richtel is a staff writer for The New York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
