   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN _ MIAMI _ A mood of public resistance was rising here as
the Thursday deadline approached for U.S. immigration officials to
begin the process of repatriating 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to Cuba
unless his relatives here agree to give the boy up if their legal
case to keep him fails. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ The Elian Gonzalez case could be a
political setback for Al Gore. Though Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
has the advantage in a state where his brother is governor, the
Clinton-Gore ticket won the state in 1996. That victory was partly
due to strong support from Miami's Cuban-American community,
however, and the Elian case threatens to sap that support.
(Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RENO _ WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno expressed
confidence Thursday that Cuban-Americans in Miami would not
obstruct government efforts to repatriate Elian Gonzalez if that
became necessary. ``I don't think they came to this country to
incite violence,'' Reno said. ``I think they came to this country
to be able to speak their mind, to follow the law, to respect
others, and to see that those processes were carried out. (Schultz,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Florida's two senators said
Thursday they were ready to immediately move forward with a bill
granting permanent U.S. residency
</P>
<P>
   to Elian Gonzalez and several of his close relatives if the
Justice Departments revokes the boy's permission to stay in the
United States. (S.Schultz, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-REFUSE _ WASHINGTON _ Census Director Kenneth Prewitt,
facing widespread privacy concerns among many Americans and even
some members of Congress, has scheduled a news conference Thursday
to highlight the value of the information collected on the census
long form. A look at what's behind the census resistance. (Holmes,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-AID _ WASHINGTON _ North Carolina victims of last year's
Hurricane Floyd flooding face the prospects of more months without
disaster relief funds because of a congressional dispute. The House
on Thursday approved a supplemental funding bill containing more
than $2 billion in aid, but the Senate is refusing to act of the
bill, provoking outrage among some members. (Moscoso, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXES _ WASHINGTON _ The Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce, split on the question of taxing Internet
sales, holds a 3 p.m. ET conference call Thursday in a final
attempt to reach consensus before sending a report to Congress.
(Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDATION _ WASHINGTON _ Despite yesterday's report that
foundations are giving away more money than ever, community groups
say that it is misleading to think that there's a bigger pot of
money to divide. Most of the increase comes from large corporations
with specialized interests, said Rick McKelvey, vice president for
development at the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra. ``There is not this
plethora of new money out there,'' he said. ``Most communities are
working harder than ever for a smaller piece of the pie.'' (Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CONTENT _ WASHINGTON _ The Parents Television Council
releases a report comparing four weeks of prime-time TV programming
from the falls of 1989 and 1999. (Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   AUDITS _ WASHINGTON _ Only 13 of the federal government's 24
major agencies won a clean bill of health from auditors for their
1999 financial statements. Although that was one more success than
last year, the results fell well short of the Clinton
administration's goal. The Pentagon remains the biggest offender,
with auditors saying that it had insufficient records for $119
billion in property, plant and equipment. (Malone, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ALAMIN _ ATLANTA _ Evidence specialists will begin combing
through Jamil Al-Amin's Mercedes , looking for something that might
suggest a motive for the shooting of two Fulton deputies. They will
vacuum up every speck of dirt and fiber in the car and examine it
all. Most of what they find will be meaningless. But evidence of
contraband, such as guns, would be a big score. The car, the tag
found nearby, might also provide clues about others who might have
helped him in Alabama. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DABRAT _ The shooting outside rapper Da Brat's Buckhead
apartment complex two weeks ago had nothing to do with the singer,
according to authorities. ``This is just a terrible coincidence,''
said Sgt. Rick Chambers of the Atlanta police department's guns
unit. APD says the shooting was a drug-related hit that went awry
and they are trying to get the intended target to talk. Police
however are still looking for the two shooters, masked men in a
mid-90s silver Thunderbird. Meanwhile, in Miami DaBrat said she was
busy with her new music video and had never really thought much
about whether or worried that the shooter was targeting her. She
also said that her family moved her out of the area for safety
reasons. (Longa, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUS-TRAIN _ TENNGA, Ga. _ Investigators began the tedious task
Thursday of recreating the train-school bus crash that killed three
children. Using a 1998 school bus matching the one hit Tuesday and
the same CSX locomotive involved in the accident, safety officals
spent the day making measurements to determine when driver Rhonda
Cloer should have been able to see and hear the oncoming train.
(Bennett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONVICT-COMMENCEMENT _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Outraged law enforcement
organizations from across the region and nation are mobilizing to
persuade Antioch College to cancel a planned audiotape commencement
address by a Pennsylvania death-row inmate convicted of killing a
Philadelphia police officer. (Fisher, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUNS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ At sunup in an open field near
Houston, in a photo op, Bush learned how guns can banfire. Aiming
for publicity for a staged dove hunt, Bush knocked a protected
species from the sky. But overall, guns have served Bush's
political career well, inc luding his high-profile support for
concealed weapons bill, which helped propel him into state office.
Now the gun industry could help propel him to national office.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ The Elian Gonzalez case could be a
political setback for Al Gore. Though Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
has the advantage in a state where his brother is governor, the
Clinton-Gore ticket won the state in 1996. That victory was partly
due to strong support from Miami's Cuban-American community,
however, and the Elian case threatens to sap that support.
(Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-UNITER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He is, he tells us constantly, a
``uniter, not a divider.'' But George W. Bush's self-proclaimed
big-tent credentials are under fire from the Log Cabin Republicans,
a gay group that says Bush's unwillingness to meet with them is
``no way to win converts, which Bush needs to do for the sake of
the GOP's chances of winning elections.'' (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED WEDNESDAY
