<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CENSUS CHIEF DEFENDS AGAINST PRIVACY CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Stands for CENSUS-REPUBLICANS)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLS CHURCH, Va. _ Census Director Kenneth Prewitt, rejecting
complaints that census questionnaires are so intrusive they ought
to be ignored, urged Americans Thursday to answer every question on
census surveys sent to nearly 118 million households.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt warned that if residents leave questions unanswered on
Census forms, field workers would follow up with a knock on the
door in the weeks ahead to urge cooperation or to take the
information in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel a constitutional obligation to count everyone
in this country and if we think that any set of activities is going
to keep us from doing that, then we will do whatever we can do by
way of correcting that,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt was responding to a firestorm of citizen complaints over
privacy that has prompted some members of Congress and radio talk
show hosts to urge Americans to ignore Census questions they deem
too intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Five out of six of the nation's roughly 118 million households
have received a short form questionnaire with seven questions _ the
shortest survey in 180 years.
</P>
<P>
   But one-sixth of the recipients _ or approximately 20 million
households _ have received a 53-question survey that asks
everything from marital status and ethnic origin to home telephone
number, personal income, monthly household expenses and the
disability status of residents.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt urged Americans to complete every question to enable the
federal government to properly finance existing federal programs
and address unmet social and economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said Congress had reviewed each question. The requested
information is either required by federal law or required to carry
out federal law, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the Census every 10 years are used not only to shift
the location of congressional districts for the 435-seat House of
Representatives to keep apace of population shifts but also to
target about $185 billion in federal funds awarded each year to
states and localities based on population statistics. The first
census was in 1790.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more that the Census is described as an inappropriate
activity, the more the American people are going to come to believe
that it is something which is either not needed or is inappropriate
or is intrusive or could somehow be turned against you,'' Prewitt
warned. ``I'm only hopeful that our leadership will stand up and
urge the American people to complete this Census form.''
</P>
<P>
   Citizen complaints about the scope of the questionnaire have
skyrocketed as residents fill out the forms before the April 1
mail-in deadline. Reps. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and Nick Smith,
R-Mich., as well as Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., have suggested that
people should be free to skip questions they consider too invasive.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., raised such concerns
with Prewitt during a private meeting earlier this week. Prewitt
said that he told Lott that ``we very much needed this information
in order to carry out the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, said Thursday that citizens
ought to fill out the questionnaires but added: ``If there's a
question that invades their privacy, they should leave it blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's home state of Mississippi trails the nation in responding
to the Census questionnaires, with only 32 percent of the surveyed
households having returned the questionnaires to the Census Bureau
by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has the highest rate of return _ 55 percent.
Nationwide, 46 percent of households have replied so far _ en route
to a Census Bureau goal of a 70 percent response by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said mixed signals from Congress about answering the
questionnaire imperil the Census goal of getting the complete
picture of America that is needed to target everything from
spending on fire and rescue operations to the location of veterans'
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that the message is not completely understood
and that it might get translated to, `Oh, well, this information
isn't very important after all,''' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize his point, Prewitt issued his appeal in front of a
red, white and blue ambulance at a fire station in a Washington
suburb where emergency personnel routinely rely on house-by-house
details gathered by the Census to help map their responses to
80,000 emergency calls a year.
</P>
<P>
   Confidential personal information gleaned from the Census
questionnaires will remain secure, Prewitt said, noting that
violators, including Census workers, would face 5 years in prison
and a $5,000 fine if convicted of breaching the confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said Americans'
concerns over privacy stem in part from worries about keeping
personal information private in the age of the Internet. Americans
want to ``be careful about all matters regarding privacy these
days, especially because there are so many more invasive
opportunities that there have been in the past,'' Daschle
explained.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
