<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-ABUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO GIANT PROMOTING WAR AGAINST SPOUSAL ABUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Philip Morris, long under fire as a purveyor of
disease and death among smokers, donned its white hat Thursday to
promote a national war against another kind of suffering _ domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Operators of the National Domestic Violence Hotline, which is
located in Austin, honored the cigarette maker for the millions of
dollars it has spent assisting victims of spousal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Philip Morris sponsored a national television ad
that highlighted the problem, and women seeking help flooded the
hot line with calls. The company also gave the hot line $400,000 to
help expand its staff and call center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education efforts like this save lives. Thousands of people,
for the first time, were exposed to our phone number, called and
got help,'' said Sheryl Cates, executive director of the Texas
Council on Family Violence, which operates the hot line
</P>
<P>
   But some anti-smoking activists counter that no amount of good
deeds can make up for the human suffering that has helped enrich
the tobacco giant. Philip Morris manufacturers 10 well-known brands
of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still the same company that addicts kids every day to
nicotine, and a large number of those kids end up dying early,''
said Carter Headrick, a spokesman for the Campaign for Tobacco-Free
Kids. ``It's a smoke-and-mirrors campaign to make the public think
they're a good company.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Collamore, Philip Morris' vice president of public affairs,
said his company has been contributing to community efforts and
charitable causes for 40 years. But, he admitted, Philip Morris has
been making a greater effort to publicize its involvement in those
efforts since the tobacco industry came under strong attacks over
its products and marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the industry has spent billions of dollars
settling lawsuits brought by Texas and other states over marketing
practices and smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Collamore said the company has a $100 million TV ad campaign
that includes the anti-domestic violence ad and a spot encouraging
teen-agers not to smoke. Two other ads in the package promote a
drive by Miller Brewing Co., a Philip Morris subsidiary, to provide
water to disaster victims, and a hunger relief effort by Kraft
Foods, another company subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is really about us trying to show the people who
the people of Philip Morris are,'' Collamore said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's domestic violence ad about ``Laura,'' based on the
true story of an abused woman, began airing last October and is
still running. It carries the hot line number and increased calls
to the center by almost 70 percent during the last three months of
last year, Cates said.
</P>
<P>
   The hot line now receives more than 11,000 calls a month.
Staffers, many of whom are survivors of domestic violence, help
victims and people calling on their behalf deal with crisises and
provide referrals to local service providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upsurge in call volume generated by the ad shows that
domestic violence is an epidemic in this country,'' Cates said,
challenging other businesses and groups to follow Philip Morris'
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cates said the Texas Council on Family Violence initially had
reservations about accepting Philip Morris' money, when the company
first proposed the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like that in order to be responsible to battered women
we obviously needed to come forward and do the right thing in terms
of this ad. We knew it was a call to action, and our primary
concern, of course, was battered women,'' she said. ``We also
looked at the leadership that Philip Morris was willing to take on
a controversial issue and become a partner with us, to allow us to
help save lives.''
</P>
<P>
