<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A potent low pressure zone will swirl over the Southwest
accompanied by scattered valley showers and mountain snow. The
heaviest snow will occur above 5,000 feet in southeastern Colorado
where amounts over a foot will be common by Friday night.
Intermittent snow will also occur in the high elevations of
northern New Mexico and Arizona. Meanwhile, strong winds from the
east along the northern flank of the storm system will course
through many mountain passes from Utah to California.
</P>
<P>
   A few strong thunderstorms, some with hail, will erupt Friday
afternoon from eastern New Mexico to the hills of western Texas.
Scattered thundershowers will also dampen western parts of Kansas
and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, high pressure will bring tranquil conditions, ample
sunshine and near seasonal temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DAMAGE SURVEY
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary damage survey by the National Weather Service in
Fort Worth, Texas, on Wednesday indicated that the tornado that
struck late Tuesday rated F2 on the Fujita scale, while the twister
that hit nearby Arlington ranked F3. By inspecting damage,
meteorologists can estimate the winds in the tornado by applying
principles of engineering and computing the force needed to knock
down walls or lift roofs off houses, for example. Based on such
forensic principles, a F2 twister packs winds between 113 and 157
mph, while an F3 tornado has winds between 158 and 206 mph.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
