<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-HIGH31-COX     03-30 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HIGH31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Cusack slaps together a hands-down funny `Fidelity'
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Top Five Reasons Why I Love ``High Fidelity'':
</P>
<P>
   1. It's based on the beloved cult novel by Nick Hornby.
</P>
<P>
   2. John Cusack is perfect as the music-obsessed protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   3. The story is honest, touching and funny.
</P>
<P>
   4. The 59-song soundtrack is incredible.
</P>
<P>
   5. I've lived much of this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Frears' endearing film is a quirky and original
romantic comedy about rock music and relationships. Its central
character, Rob Gordon (Cusack), is a self-professed music junkie
who runs a semi-failing vinyl record store in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Rob and his two employees, Dick (Todd Louiso) and Barry (Jack
Black), have an encyclopedic knowledge of music and are perpetually
creating top-5 lists of their all-time favorite songs for specific
situations, from Monday mornings to funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Rob, still single in his late 30s, also compiles a list of his
top-5 breakups _ inspired by his latest girlfriend, Laura (Iben
Hjejle), who walks out on him as the story opens.
</P>
<P>
   Laura met Rob when he was working as a club DJ, but she has
traded her punk look for a successful law career. Rob hasn't
changed so much as a pair of socks, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Confiding to the camera, Rob recounts his romantic travails _
which unfold in flashback vignettes _ to get to the root of his
lifetime of rejection. Meanwhile, he pursues sultry local singer
Marie De Salle (Lisa Bonet) while also trying to put things right
with Laura.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' is a hip and witty look at love, adapted by
Cusack and his ``Grosse Pointe Blank'' writing partners, D.V.
DeVincentis and Steve Pink, along with ``Con Air'' screenwriter
Scott Rosenberg. The tale has been transplanted from London to
Cusack's native Chicago, outraging some fans of Hornby's novel, but
otherwise it plays exactly like the book.
</P>
<P>
   Rob's constant asides to the audience are initially off-putting,
but his direct narration allows us to bond with the sad-sack
character so that we end up rooting for him.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the film is steadily amusing; the second half
is full-blown hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   When not agonizing over his love life or lack thereof, Rob
comically bickers with meek Dick and caustic Barry _ whom he dubs
the ``musical moron twins'' _ over pop-music minutiae. Rob also
dispenses the rules for making a great compilation tape, which he
uses as romantic overtures. The film's musical sources range from
The Kinks to The Beta Band.
</P>
<P>
   In one screamingly funny sequence, Rob considers a variety of
responses during a confrontation with Laura's pretentious new
boyfriend, Ian (Tim Robbins). Each escalates in cartoonish
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Rob's ex-girlfriends are played by such top actresses as
Catherine Zeta-Jones and Lili Taylor. Cusack's comedically gifted
sister, Joan, appears as Laura's best friend, Liz.
</P>
<P>
   A major rock star makes his movie debut in a surprise cameo.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, who co-produced the film with DeVincentis and Pink,
plays broke and grumpy Rob with self-deprecating charm.
</P>
<P>
   Black, the lead singer of Tenacious D and a longtime supporting
actor whose credits include ``Cradle Will Rock,'' steals every
scene he's in with the manic energy of John Belushi.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati native Louiso played a similarly music-driven
baby-sitter in ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I listen to pop music because I'm miserable or am I
miserable because I listen to pop music,'' Rob asks. Anyone who has
ever eased the pain of a broken heart with a stack of albums will
find it easy to relate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
