<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ROAD31-COX     03-30 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROAD31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Road' paved with too much Hope (&AMP; Crosby)
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tulio and Miguel are a cartoon Hope and Crosby,
in search of fortune, adventure and romance on ``The Road to El
Dorado.''
</P>
<P>
   The title of DreamWorks' animated musical pays tribute to the
seven highly successful ``Road'' pictures Bob Hope and Bing Crosby
made with Dorothy Lamour over three decades, from 1940's ``Road to
Singapore'' to 1962's ``The Road to Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   Like their live-action counterparts, Tulio (the voice of Kevin
Kline) and Miguel (Kenneth Branagh) are comical con men who become
involved in overseas shenanigans. As was often the case in the Hope
and Crosby movies, both men also go after same woman.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the cartoon buddy comedy isn't nearly as funny as
the films from which it draws inspiration. The tropical adventure's
colorful look is contrasted by a drab story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' boasts stronger character design than
DreamWorks' previous animated feature, ``The Prince of Egypt.'' The
film also features six terrific new songs from Elton John and Tim
Rice, who won an Academy Award for their collaboration on Disney's
``The Lion King.'' Composer Hans Zimmer won an Oscar for ``The Lion
King's'' score.
</P>
<P>
   Kline and Branagh are well-matched as the verbally sparring
protagonists _ never mind the Spanish characters' American and
British accents.
</P>
<P>
   But the characters' search for the legendary City of Gold is
tarnished by a rudimentary plot, in which Tulio and Miguel stumble
onto El Dorado and are proclaimed to be gods by nefarious High
Priest Tzekel-Kan (Armand Assante).
</P>
<P>
   Tzekel-Kan has a taste for power and a thirst for human
sacrifice. He plots to use Tulio and Miguel's fortuitous arrival to
take power from the Chief (Edward James Olmos).
</P>
<P>
   The con men are only concerned with sustaining their ruse long
enough to escape with the gold, until a curvaceous native named
Chel (Rosie Perez) comes between them.
</P>
<P>
   The PG-rated story is too sophisticated and intense for young
viewers and too dull and simplistic for adults. Although it held
children's interest during the screening, the film could have used
more punch. It's mildly amusing, but there are few big laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a clever war horse named Altivo and a cute little
armadillo _ neither of which speak _ there are no comedic animal
sidekicks.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the songs are performed by John to move along the
story, a la Disney's ``Tarzan.'' Kline and Branagh, who share a
winning chemistry, sing ``It's Tough to Be a God.''
</P>
<P>
   John and Rice are likely to be in the running come next year's
Oscar race. Animated musicals are a favorite in the best song
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado's'' high points have the supposedly
infallible Tulio and Miguel facing off against a team of large
warriors in an Aztec version of basketball, and later running for
their lives from a giant stone jaguar brought to life by
Tzekel-Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Though the latter sequence features a beautiful shot of the
monster amid molten volcano lava, the film doesn't blaze any new
trails in animation. First-time directors Eric ``Bibo'' Bergeron
and Don Paul fail to integrate computer and traditional cel
animation as seamlessly as Disney did in ``Tarzan.'' It's fairly
obvious when the two are combined.
</P>
<P>
   The Peter Maxx-inspired title sequence recalls The Beatles'
``Yellow Submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers are sensitive to the Latin community, using
Hispanic voice actors such as Perez, Assante and Olmos and giving
Chel hips like Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   However, the movie skirts the limits of family entertainment
with much talk about human sacrifice, scenes of the stomping
jaguar's carnage and a brief ``Jaws'' homage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy ship!'' exclaims Tulio, when he, Miguel and Altivo go
overboard directly into the path of Cortes' galleon, en route to
the New World.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Dorado's'' path will likely be the road to home video.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
