<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER31-COX     03-30 2336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore changes stance on Cuban boy
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Cuban-American vote critical in Florida and angry
Miami-area voters saying they will unite behind George W. Bush, Al
Gore came out Thursday in favor of permanent residence status for
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez. Most of the area's 780,000
Cuban-Americans are furious at the Clinton administration for
ordering the boy's return to Cuba. Gore's stated position has been
that ``a custody matter for the courts to decide based on due
process, with a full hearing in which all parties are heard.'' Gore
said Thursday: ``It now appears that our immigration laws may not
be broad enough to allow for such an approach in Elian's case. That
is why I am urging ... permanent resident status to Elian, his
father, stepmother, half-brother, grandmothers, and grandfather, so
that this case can be adjudicated properly.''
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHERS HAD GOOD IDEAS, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from both John McCain and the Clinton administration,
George W. Bush proposed Thursday a big increase in the ``troops to
teachers'' program for turning retired military personnel into math
and science teachers. ``This is a signal that says there are a lot
of good people who should be welcomed into the ranks of teachers,''
Bush said. ``Senator McCain talked a lot about this in the course
of the primaries, and I appreciate him bringing this issue to our
collective attention.'' After a morning of finger-painting and
storytelling, Bush promoted his new package for teacher training,
recruitment and retention in a discussion with a dozen education
policymakers at a middle school in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE PAYOFF COME VEEP-PICKING TIME
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Gov. John Engler has a new political action committee
and has given thousands of dollars to candidates for federal
office, an indication that the Republican is trying to boost his
national profile and influence. Without fanfare, the Governor
Engler Leadership Fund was established in July. It collected
$77,450 from 61 donors in its first six months, with 46
contributions coming from people living outside Michigan. The PAC
allows Engler to give up to $5,000 to a candidate _ rather than the
$1,000 per election he is limited to as an individual _ and pay for
his travel for appearances for various candidates.
</P>
<P>
   `BEING JOHN MCCAIN,' STARRING PAT BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's Pat Buchanan wants to follow John McCain's
lead in attracting voters to a maverick candidate. He said he
thought he would have wide appeal in Connecticut and other states
where McCain won seven Republican presidential primaries by running
as a non-establishment candidate. But Buchanan acknowledged a
problem: ``If you're a liberal Republican and you're doing very
well, you're probably not going to vote for Pat Buchanan.''
Buchanan was on a four-day swing through New England, including a
$100-a-person fund-raiser in Stratford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN READY TO HIT THE ROAD AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will make his initial campaign foray on behalf of
House Republican candidates early next month. His first campaign
swing is expected to be in the Northeast _ campaigning for Mark
Nielsen, challenging Rep. Jim Maloney in Connecticut, and Greg
Becker, running against Rep. Carolyn McCarthy in New York. The
disclosure came shortly after McCain held an unannounced meeting in
his Senate office with Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, head of the
House GOP campaign committee. Last week, McCain offered to campaign
on behalf of Republican candidates. The meeting with Davis came one
day after McCain and George W. Bush talked by phone.
</P>
<P>
   SORRY, GRANNY, KEEP ON WALKING
</P>
<P>
   In talking about his being a born-again campaign finance
reformer, Al Gore has referred to 90-year-old ``Granny D.'' The
woman recently completed a yearlong coast-to-coast walk to draw
attention to the campaign reform issue. Gore called Granny D _
actually Doris Haddock _ the embodiment of a grass-roots effort.
National Public Radio, however, reported that Granny D. had sought
to talk to Gore during her trek, only to be told it would cost her
$500. NPR said the incident occurred in Arkansas when Granny D
presented herself at a Gore event that turned out to be a
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU CAN'T SAY SOMETHING NICE ABOUT SOMEONE . . .
</P>
<P>
   Al Sharpton turned up on the steps of the Republican National
Committee headquarters in Washington and announced he's suing the
RNC and its chairman, Jim Nicholson, over a letter Nicholson sent
to the Washington Post. Sharpton, charging that his reputation had
been besmirched, said he was suing for $30 million. In the letter,
published March 11, Nicholson objected to the newspaper describing
Sharpton as a ``civil rights leader.'' Nicholson called Sharpton a
hatemonger, an anti-Semite and a racist, and the Washington Times
said Nicholson stands by his statements.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES YOUR GARDEN (STATE) LEAD GROW?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's bruising Republican primary contest against
John McCain has helped give Al Gore a commanding lead among New
Jersey voters, according to a poll released today. A day after Bush
visited the state where independent voters outnumber both
registered Republicans and Democrats, the survey by Quinnipiac
College in Hamden, Conn., showed Gore surging to a 50 to 37 point
lead. The same poll (2.9 percentage point margin of error) in
February had Gore with a 6-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOW DRESSING FOR THE FEC REPORTS
</P>
<P>
   Top Democrats are urging the rank and file to reach for their
checkbooks in the next few days so key candidates can have as much
money in the bank as possible when they file campaign fund-raising
reports March 31. ``Maximize your early support. Please remember to
help them as much as you can,'' Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode
Island wrote fellow Democrats. A fat bank balance provides more
than psychological comfort for a candidate. It also can scare off
potential challengers or discourage contributors from making
donations to a rival whose candidacy looks like it will be
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   TORT REFORM AND TART CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Attorneys General Association, holding its annual
meeting in Austin, Texas, opposes industry-wide lawsuits, such as
those against tobacco companies and gun manufacturers, that have
cost some companies billions. Acting under the umbrella of the
Republican National Committee, the group seeks contributions to
help fund state attorneys general races around the country. But the
nonpartisan Texans for Public Justice, is criticizing RAGA's
fund-raising practices, saying it sells big donors immunity from
state lawsuits. ``The entire RAGA operation raises serious
questions of conflicts of interest and selling government access
and policy to the highest bidder,'' said Craig McDonald, head of
the watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RILEY TIT FOR TAT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Education Secretary Richard Riley traded
charges over education, with Bush accusing the department of
spending taxpayer dollars to campaign against him and Riley saying
Bush had manipulated his words for political gain. Bush started it
by releasing a statement saying Riley had praised Bush's statewide
reading reforms as a model for the nation. In a statement of his
own, Riley accused Bush of claiming undue credit for administration
reading programs and manipulating the remarks from a 1996 Riley
speech to support those claims.
</P>
<P>
   UNDECIDED NOW, SO WHAT ARE YOU GOING TO DO?
</P>
<P>
   Voters in upstate New York may be the deciding factor in the
ever-tightening Senate race between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudy
Giuliani. Fourteen percent of upstate voters surveyed by the Marist
Institute for Public Opinion remain undecided between the
Democratic first lady and the Republican mayor of New York City.
Giuliani leads in the GOP-dominated upstate region, 49 percent to
37 percent, but the now-undecided voters there could swing the
race. Clinton is the clear favorite in New York City at 60 percent
to 34 percent; Giuliani is strong in the suburbs, 56 percent to 32
percent. The poll has a 4 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   BROKER'S MONEY PAYING OFF
</P>
<P>
   A new poll shows ex-Wall Street brokerage Chairman Jon Corzine
closing the gap on ex-Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic race to
succeed retiring Sen. Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.), probably because
of heavy television spending. A Quinnipiac College Poll said 50
percent of registered Democrats support Florio, 26 percent favor
Corzine. The poll was conducted March 21-27, right after Corzine
began a TV ad blitz aimed at boosting his name recognition. A
Quinnipiac poll the month before showed Florio leading 57-22
percent. Poll's margin of error: 4.9 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   WATCHING HIS MOUTH IN NEW JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Senate candidate Jon Corzine, running in a state
where one-quarter of Democrats are Italian-American, reportedly
made a disparaging remark about Italians two weeks ago. According
to the New York Times, Corzine said to an Italian-American
contractor: ``Oh, you make cement shoes!'' Corzine's rival for the
Democratic nomination is ex-governor Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING THE NAME GAME
</P>
<P>
   It's Gebhardt vs. Gephardt in a Missouri congressional primary
that has the House minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt, accusing
Republicans of dirty tricks. The 12-term St. Louis congressman drew
a Democratic primary challenge on the last day of filing from
Richard A. Gebhardt, a 65-year-old political newcomer from St.
Peters near Gephardt's home base of St. Louis. That prompted
Gephardt, who hopes to become speaker of the House if the Democrats
regain control, to submit paperwork changing his ballot name to
``Richard A. (Dick) Gephardt.'' Gebhardt entered the race for the
Democratic nomination in the 2nd District on Monday, but switched
the next day to the 3rd District. Residency in a congressional
district is not a requirement to run.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS AND TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton may be running in New York, but she
showed her support for women entrepreneurs at the Women's
Technology Cluster in San Francisco, an incubator for
Internet-related companies. Political candidates from across the
spectrum are frequent visitors to Northern California, hoping to
tap support from an industry flush with new wealth brought on by
the rise of the Internet in communication and commerce. Clinton's
roundtable discussion with leaders of several female-owned Internet
companies was not billed as a fund-raiser, but she also was
scheduled to attend a fund-raiser at the home of Apple Computer
founder Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   IN NEW YORK, IT'S NOT JUST DEMOCRATS AND REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudy Giuliani find themselves
confronting a series of decisions over the next two months that
might be as important as any they make between now and Election
Day: how to pick their way through a maze of six independent
parties listed on the New York state ballot, each clamoring for a
role in a contest in which third-party endorsements could make a
crucial difference. For years, the small-party dynamic in New York
amounted to the Liberal Party backing the Democratic candidate and
the Conservative Party cross-endorsing the Republican. But as of
now, both Clinton and Giuliani seem inclined to seek the support of
the Liberal Party and, perhaps, the more problematic Independence
Party, which is the New York incarnation of Ross Perot's
division-wracked Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH NUT TO CRACK IN KEYSTONE STATE
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins Pennsylvania's six-way Democratic primary for
Senate next month will face two obstacles in November: Republican
Sen. Rick Santorum and nearly 40 years of history. No Pennsylvania
Democrat has been elected to a full term in the Senate since Joseph
Clark in 1962. The primary has emerged as a too-close-to-call
three-way race among Rep. Ron Klink, former state Labor Secretary
Thomas Foley and state Sen. Allyson Schwartz. Philadelphia-area
lawyers Phil Berg, Murray Levin and Robert Rovner have failed to
register beyond single digits in any poll.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN YOU HAVE A CHANCE, YOU GET BIGGER HELP
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton helped the Senate bid of Rep. Debbie Stabenow
(D-Mich.) by attending a cocktail party in Washington that raised
$250,000. Stabenow held a slight lead over Sen. Spencer Abraham, a
freshman Republican, in a Epic/MRA Inc. poll earlier this month.
Abraham's standing suffered partly because he had backed George W.
Bush when Michigan Republicans went for John McCain in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREMISM IN THE DEFENSE OF PRESS RELEASES IS NO `VICE'
</P>
<P>
   Just how closely are the Bush and Gore campaigns watching each
other? When a wire service dropped the word ``vice'' from Al Gore's
title in a press release, George W. Bush's aides likened the
mistake to other verbal slips or grand claims by Gore. ``Since he
invented the Internet, inspired ``Love Story'' and discovered Love
Canal, it's fitting that the vice president promote himself to
president,'' said Ari Fleischer, a Bush campaign spokesman. But it
was the Bush campaign that was overreaching: U.S. Newswire said it
made the error.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE FOR ME OR DIE
</P>
<P>
   A hacker cracked into Marquette University's Web site and
replaced the main page with a fake that falsely accused Al Gore of
making outrageous comments during his address to the school. The
sham Web page, according to the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, had
counterfeit quotes about Gore's speech at Marquette on Monday,
claiming among other things that Gore said he plans to ``rid this
country of anyone who might question my motives, starting with
deporting all Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
