<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TOONS31-COX     03-30 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TOONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hollywood's new ventures draw upon success of 1999's cartoon
hits
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hollywood is enjoying a 'toon boom.
</P>
<P>
   Not the sort of explosion that occurs when one of Wile E.
Coyote's ACME products goes awry, but an animation renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   On his year-end Top-10 list for 1999, Los Angeles Times film
critic Kenneth Turan named four animated films _ The Iron Giant,
Princess Mononoke, Tarzan and Toy Story 2 _ as the collective
first-place winner. ``It was the best year for animation in the
history of the movie industry,'' Turan told Premiere magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The major studios are releasing 10 animated features in 2000, up
from seven in 1999. That's a huge jump from the three cartoon
features released in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This year's first animated feature, ``The Tigger Movie,'' has
made an impressive $43 million since its release in February _
outperforming such big-budget live-action films as ``Reindeer
Games'' and ``The Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' _ an animated musical adventure
featuring the voices of Kevin Kline and Kenneth Branagh and songs
by Elton John and Tim Rice _ opens today.
</P>
<P>
   Top stars such as Mel Gibson, Matt Damon, Chris Rock, Drew
Barrymore, Alfre Woodard, Susan Sarandon and Bill Murray are also
lending their voices to forthcoming animated features.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the year's most anticipated live-action films _
``X-Men,'' ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' and ``How the
Grinch Stole Christmas'' _ are based on comics and cartoons. So,
too, are ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' and ``102
Dalmatians.''
</P>
<P>
   Feature animation drew almost $600 million at the box office in
1999, tripling the take for animated films from 1997, according to
industry figures. Disney's ``Tarzan'' and ``Toy Story 2'' combined
for almost $400 million and made millions more in merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' is the second highest-grossing animated film in
history, with $241 million and counting. The computer-animated
adventure will probably end up as the 16th highest-grossing film of
all-time, ahead of ``Twister'' and ``Raiders of the Lost Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. acquired the Japanese ``Pokemon'' movie for $5
million, re-dubbed it into English, added a pop music soundtrack
and made $84 million domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' grossed $52 million,
more than double its $21 million budget, last year in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   All should substantially increase their profit margins on home
video.
</P>
<P>
   Disney spent about $100 million to make ``The Lion King,''
according to ``Variety,'' but made $1.2 billion in profit.
</P>
<P>
   Feature animation can pay off big, but the risks are equally
great. Studios must commit to projects years before they see the
results. Failures can be costly in terms of money, time and labor.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Animation Studios reportedly laid-off two thirds of its 320
animators in Phoenix, Ariz., where it produced ``Anastasia.'' The
1997 film cost $53 million to make and grossed a disappointing $58
million domestically, according to Internet Movie Database figures.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Animation will release ``Titan A.E.,'' a sci-fi adventure
featuring the voices of Damon, Barrymore and Bill Pullman, this
summer. It will compete with a crowded slate of 'toons that also
includes ``Dinosaur,'' ``Chicken Run'' and the 35mm release of
``Fantasia/2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at this year's animated features. Like Wile E.
Coyote's best-laid plans, release dates are subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE ROAD TO EL DORADO''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Eric ``Bibo'' Bergeron, Don Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Rosie Perez, Armand
Assante, Edward James Olmos.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Kline and Branagh give voice to a pair of two-bit con
men who win a map to El Dorado, the legendary City of Gold. There
they are proclaimed to be gods by the High Priest Tzekel-Kan
(Assante), who plots to use their arrival to take power from the
Chief (Olmos). The adventure reunites the Oscar-winning musical
team from ``The Lion King'': songwriters Elton John and Tim Rice
and composer Hans Zimmer. (Opens today)
</P>
<P>
   ``DINOSAUR''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Ralph Zondag, Eric Leighton.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Alfre Woodard, Ossie Davis, D.B. Sweeney, Julianna
Margulies, Joan Plowright, Della Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Combining computer character animation with digitally
enhanced live-action backgrounds, this action-filled drama focuses
on the journey of a three-ton Iguanodon named Aladar, who is raised
from an egg by a clan of lemurs and reunited with his own kind.
With flaming meteors devastating the landscape and water in
diminishing supply, Aladar must lead a group of misfit dinosaurs to
the safety of their nesting grounds. (May 19)
</P>
<P>
   ``FANTASIA/2000''
</P>
<P>
   Supervising director: Hendel Butoy.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts: Steve Martin, Itzhak Perlman, Quincy Jones, Bette Midler,
James Earl Jones, Penn &AMP; Teller, James Levine, Angela Lansbury.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Walt Disney originally conceived of his 1940 animation
masterpiece, ``Fantasia,'' as ``repertoire program'' with changing
musical selections. Sixty years later, the classic experiment in
sight and sound is updated with seven new selections and one
returning favorite from the original film that visually interpret
classical compositions by Beethoven, Shostakovich, Respighi,
Gershwin, Dukas, Saint-Saens, Elgar and Stravinsky. The 35mm
release follows ``Fantasia/2000's'' Jan. 1 debut on select IMAX
screens. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``TITAN A.E.''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Don Bluth, Gary Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Matt Damon, Bill Pullman, Drew Barrymore, Nathan
Lane, John Leguizamo, Janeane Garofalo.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: In a journey that begins after Earth ends, a rebellious
teen-ager named Cale (Damon) embarks on an adventure through space
to find a legendary spacecraft, the Titan, that holds the secret of
salvation for the human race. Facing deadly Drej aliens and
betrayal within his own ranks, Cale becomes a heroic renegade
warrior as he fights to find a whole new world. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``CHICKEN RUN''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Peter Lord, Nick Park.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Mel Gibson, Julia Sawalha, Miranda Richardson, Jane
Horrocks, Timothy Spall.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: This clay-animated comedy is the first full-length
feature from England-based Aardman Animations, the Academy
Award-winning team behind the popular ``Wallace and Gromit''
shorts. The story is set at Tweedy's Chicken Farm, where any
chicken that doesn't make her egg quota can meet a ``fowl'' fate.
Fearing for their lives, the chickens hatch a desperate plan to fly
the coop before they can be fried, filleted or fricasseed. (June
23)
</P>
<P>
   ``POKEMON THE MOVIE 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Not available.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Not available.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: The sequel to last fall's lucrative hit is an adventure
about a terrible force that arrives on Earth and throws the Pokemon
universe horribly out of balance. The only one who can stop it
before all Pokemon are annihilated is young trainer Ash Ketchum.
The Japanese import introduces six new Pokemon. Four new Pokemon
Trading Card Game cards will be handed out to moviegoers with the
price of admission, as long as supplies last. (July 21)
</P>
<P>
   ``MONKEYBONE''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Henry Selick.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Brendan Fraser, Bridget Fonda, Chris Kattan, Giancarlo
Esposito, Rose McGowan, Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Fraser is a cartoonist who becomes trapped in an
incredible fantasy world that takes place in his mind after he
slips into a coma. He must somehow find the means to escape this
outrageous land, called Down Town, and return to reality. Directed
by ``The Nightmare Before Christmas''' Selick, the comedy is touted
as the first feature film to combine stop-motion animation in a
live-action format in the same scene. (Fall)
</P>
<P>
   ``OSMOSIS JONES''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Piet Kroon, Tom Sito.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Chris Rock, David Hyde Pierce, Bill Murray, Brandy
Norwood, William Shatner.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Osmosis Jones (Rock) is a maverick white blood cell cop
who is paired with a no-nonsense partner, a cold tablet named
Drixorial (Pierce). When their human host, Frank Detomello
(Murray), catches a cold, the two team up to fight off invading
viruses intent on taking over his body, known as the ``City of
Frank.'' (Nov. 22)
</P>
<P>
   ``RUGRATS IN PARIS _ THE MOVIE''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Stig Bergqvist, Paul Demeyer.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: Christine Cavanaugh, Cheryl Chase, E.G. Daily, John
Lithgow, Debbie Reynolds, Susan Sarandon, Kath Soucie.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: When Stu Pickles is summoned to Reptarland, an amazing
new amusement park in Paris, to work on his Reptar invention,
Tommy, Chuckie, Angelica, Lil, Phil, Baby Dil, Didi and the whole
gang tag along to the City of Romance. But the Rugrats' big
adventure turns out to be more than glamour, fashion and stinky
cheese. The world's favorite babies learn new lessons about
loyalty, trust and above all, true love. (Thanksgiving)
</P>
<P>
   ``THE EMPEROR'S NEW GROOVE''
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Roger Allers, Mark Dindal.
</P>
<P>
   Voice cast: David Spade, Carla Gugino, John Goodman, Harvey
Fierstein, Eartha Kitt, Trudy Styler, Patrick Warburton.
</P>
<P>
   Premise: Originally titled ``Kingdom in the Sun,'' this ``Prince
and the Pauper'' update concerns Incan Prince Manco, who agrees to
trade places with a llama herder named Pancha. The two are
identical except for the royal mark of the sun on Manco's arm. When
an evil sorceress discovers the switch, she turns Manco into a
llama. She then plots to take over the kingdom, knowing that the
imposter Pancha is powerless to stop her. (Dec. 15)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
