to Tultex straight out of high school and had a year and a half
till she could retire. They told her that she had 20 minutes to
gather up her things and get out of the building,'' Minter
recalled. ``It was like a slap in the face to people who had worked
so hard for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's squeezing a living from an unemployment check of
about $200 a week, the grandchildren ``want to know why Nanny can't
buy'' any more Matchbox cars or Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, John, is disabled. He had a heart attack one
Christmas Eve in the parking lot of K-Mart and has since had
open-heart surgery and several operations on his back. They're
worried about how to pay for the pills that regulate John's
heartbeat. Their health insurance had been provided by Tultex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting more desperate as the weeks go by,'' said Mary.
She has put in applications at businesses all over the area, but so
have hundreds of other job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   She's looking forward to the NASCAR season opening at the
Martinsville Race Track, where she can earn some money working in
the concession stand on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The signs marking Martinsville's city limits now feature a
checkered flag motif rather than sweatshirt production. The city
council has offered to give away land to companies that will invest
in the community and create new jobs. So far, there are few takers.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Bassinger is worried.
</P>
<P>
   She worked in the cutting room at Tultex for nearly 13 years
until, at the age of 36, she lost her job ``with no warning or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bassinger tells it, for decades the town was run by a few
families who owned and operated textile mills or furniture
factories. They resisted other industries coming in because they
wanted to keep wages low. Eventually, the local textile owners sold
out to national corporations. Beset by foreign competition, the
corporations pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   But Bassinger doesn't want to pull out. She grew up in
Martinsville. Her parents still live here. Her three teenage
children are immersed in their high school. Her husband has a job
at a tire dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have roots,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's putting in job applications at furniture factories in
North Carolina. Sitting in the sunny back yard of her small brick
house, Bassinger said she's willing to drive an hour each way if
she can find a job. She doesn't want to move away from
Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   This is her home town.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
