<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-GORE31-COX     03-30 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-GORE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, IN BREAK WITH CLINTON, SAHIFT STANCE ON ELIAN
 &HT;    490&AMP;add. Moving in (i) international and (p) politics
categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, in a politically strategic
break with the Clinton administration, endorsed legislation
Thursday that would grant Elian Gonzalez and his Cuban relatives
permanent resident status.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said Elian's case ``is a matter that should be decided
by courts that have the experience and expertise to resolve custody
cases.'' That position apparently aligns him with those who want
Florida family courts to decide the case rather than the Justice
Department or even the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's action _ and the immediate reaction it drew from Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee _ reflected the explosive political nature of the case and
the importance of Florida, the country's fourth largest state, in
this fall's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic Party's choice for president this year,
blamed ``the oppressive regime'' of Cuban leader Fidel Castro for
the controversy surrounding the case. It was a message apparently
aimed at Florida's politically active Cuban American community,
which has criticized the administration's handling of the case and
could tilt the state's political balance against Gore this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore urged Congress to pass a law that would grant permanent
resident status to the 6-year-old, his father, stepmother,
half-brother, grandmothers and grandfather, ``so that the case can
be adjudicated properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation has supported by Bush, who reacted to the
vice president's action Thursday by challenging him to persuade
President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno to join him in
supporting a court remedy of the case rather than one ordered by
the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he ought to do is convince the attorney general and the
president to accept the same position,'' Bush said. ``We'll see
what kind of influence he has in this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert said, ``The president and the
vice president have a different view'' on Elian's case. At his news
conference Wednesday, Clinton said the legal process should be
followed.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said Thursday that the Gonzalez case indicated U.S.
immigration laws ``may not be broad enough'' to allow the boy's
fate to be decided by courts ``that have the experience and
expertise to resolve custody cases _ with due process, and based on
Elian's best interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was left stranded on an inner tube after his mother and 10
others drowned while trying to flee Cuba for the United States over
Thanksgiving weekend. His Miami relatives took custody of him even
though his father, still in Cuba, and Castro demanded his immediate
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian should never have been forced to choose between freedom
and his own father,'' Gore said Thursday. ``Now we must take
action, here on our own shores, to make sure that Elian's best
interests are served.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's already slim chance of carrying Florida in the November
presidential election has grown slimmer with the controversy over
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't help Al Gore,'' former senior White House
political adviser Paul Begala said Thursday before Gore's latest
position was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's electoral calculations in his anticipated fall contest
against Bush include the possibility of adding Florida's 25
electoral votes to Tennessee's 11, helping him break the GOP's grip
on the South, a region that is solidly Republican in presidential
voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore ticket carried Florida in 1996, 48 percent to
43 percent, against the GOP's Bob Dole and Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   That surprise victory came largely as a result of Clinton's long
cultivation of Cuban-Americans, who number some 800,000, about 12
percent of the state's voting population, and are one the
Republican Party's most reliable voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried 40 percent of Florida's Cuban-American vote in
1996, enough to become the first Democratic nominee to carry
Miami-Dade County since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the equivalent of a Republican carrying 40 percent of
the African American vote,'' said Begala.
</P>
<P>
   Very few polls have been conducted on the American public's
opinion of the case. The Gallup Organization found in January that
60 percent of Americans thought it was in the best interest of
Elian to return to Cuba to live with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an emotional issue that it's very hard to gauge in
terms of presidential politics,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of
the Pew Research Center, one of the nation's leading polling
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Gore may view Florida as a possible crack in the
GOP's Southern base, ``he can kiss that goodbye if (the Gonzalez
case) turns out really bad,'' said Charles Jones, a noted
presidential scholar with the Brookings Institution, a Washington
research center.
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts question how seriously Gore intends to
challenge Bush in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I looked there was a governor in Florida named
Bush,'' said Stephen Hess, a former Nixon White House adviser who
also is a Brookings political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brother, Jeb, was elected governor in 1998, giving the
Texan an even greater advantage in Florida than a Republican
presidential nominee would otherwise have in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush has lost some of his popularity among black voters
because of his plan to end affirmative action in state
universities. But Gore has ``nothing to match'' the political
organization in Florida that Jeb Bush has put to work for his
brother, said University of Florida political science professor
Richard Scher.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Gore plans a campaign trip to West Palm Beach, Fla.,
and Miami next Thursday and Friday, an indication that he has not
written off the state.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
