A2585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PEOPLE31-COX     03-30 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PEOPLE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life is beautiful for Dizdar's `People'
 &HT;    By Steve Uhler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Film pioneer D.W. Griffith believed moving
pictures to be the universal language, capable of transcending
cultural and class barriers to unify humanity. I think he would
have been delighted with ``Beautiful People,'' the enchanting and
stunning debut by writer-director Jasmin Dizdar.
</P>
<P>
   On a crowded cross-town bus in 1993 London, a Croat man
recognizes an old enemy, a Serb who came from the same village in
his homeland, and attacks him. Their fight sets off a chain of
events and encounters that make up this beguiling, labyrinthine
fable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful People,'' which opens today, combines multiple
storylines and characters, coalescing into a nearly perfect movie
mosaic: A compassionate obstetrician, whose wife has just deserted
him, tries to persuade a young Bosnian couple not to kill their
unborn baby; a doctor from an upper-class family falls in love with
her patient, an illegal immigrant; a somnambulistic working-class
junkie finds himself literally dropped into ground zero in Bosnia;
a BBC correspondent's compassion for war's victims unhinges his
grip on sanity.
</P>
<P>
   These and other stories intersect and overlap like an elaborate
cross-stitch, combining into a whole cloth greater than its parts.
It's like a great Robert Altman movie, with a hopeful agenda. It's
packed with small, perfect moments; its considerable humor and
depth come from the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful People'' boasts a large ensemble cast (there are
more than 50 major speaking roles). Each performance resonates with
the perfect pitch of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Dizdar, a Bosnian who has lived in London since 1989, has put
together a captivating and enriching movie. You will feel uplifted.
Maybe that's why Griffith called them ``moving pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
