<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-MOPEDS-NYT &LR;      03-30 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-MOPEDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY'S MOPED DRIVERS MAY BE SAFER, BUT THEY'RE NOT HAPPIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The grumbling began at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   That was when a new, and by Italian standards, draconian law
requiring moped drivers to wear helmets went into effect. By
Thursday morning, the streets of Rome, always jammed with
motorbikes, displayed the novel, slightly surreal sight of riders
actually wearing helmets, most of them muttering bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worn one before and I think it is totally
unnecessary,'' Luca Raetano, 27, complained as he pulled off the
helmet he bought on Wednesday and held it out with distaste. ``It's
uncomfortable and hot. Now, summer is coming and it will be
completely unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic safety is a sore subject in Italy, a country where
studies show that only 10 percent of drivers fasten their
seatbelts, despite a 1988 law making seatbelt use mandatory. (In
law-abiding Germany, 92 percent of drivers buckle up.) Until now,
only a third of Italian moped drivers wore helmets, which were
obligatory for minors and drivers of mopeds with engines of 125
cubic centimeters or more. Italy _ where it is estimated that one
in five people drive a motorcycle or a moped, a smaller version of
a motorcycle _ is the last country in the European Union to pass a
helmet law for mopeds.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where mothers defy the law to ferry children to
school on mopeds and businessmen make business calls on cellphones
while steering their ``motorinos'' through chaotic traffic jams,
the new regulations requiring helmets have unleashed angst and
media agitation. The front page of every Italian newspaper Thursday
carried dire warnings about the consequences of going without a
helmet _ fines that range from $30 for an unbuckled helmet to $70
for no helmet at all. Minors caught without helmets are to be fined
$120 and risk a three-month confiscation of their mopeds.
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetic costs of the new law are taken even more
seriously. On Monday, the hosts of a morning television show
interviewed a hairstylist who demonstrated with flowing wigs how
women drivers could maintain a locks-blowing-in-the-wind look even
while wearing a helmet. Paolo di Pofi, a Roman hairdresser, advised
female readers of the daily newspaper La Stampa to maintain their
coiffures by twisting brightly colored sponge rollers into their
hair underneath their helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put them on and take them off in a minute and they look
adorable,'' di Pofi promised.
</P>
<P>
   La Stampa excitedly but incorrectly reported that top designers
like Armani and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana are unveiling chic helmets in their
next collections. But Gattinoni, a Rome-based designer, did receive
50 orders for his $300 ``Claire de Lune'' model, covered in a white
iridescent fabric and embossed with a giant G on the front.
</P>
<P>
   The physical risks of riding without a helmet have received less
attention, but the statistics are daunting. Every sixth automotive
death in Europe happens in Italy, where the road fatality rate is
twice as high as in Britain or Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the research shows that when you do not wear a helmet, you
double your risk of a fatal or serious injury,'' Jeanne Breen,
executive director of the European Transport Safety Council,
explained. ``We are delighted that Italy has made this move. But it
requires enforcement and a serious information campaign to get
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic police did hand out tickets to riders without helmets
Thursday morning. But enforcement was dampened Thursday in Rome by
2,000 traffic police officers who suspended work for three hours to
protest what they described as low pay, poor career advancement and
inadequate resources. (They had a point: Rome's vigili urbani have
70 motorini to help patrol traffic, but could not use them Thursday
because, due to bureaucratic delays, they did not have helmets.)
</P>
<P>
   In Naples, where helmet use is so rare the police often stop
helmeted riders, suspecting they are about to commit a crime, the
police handed out 890 tickets by mid afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   All over Italy, citizens complied with the new law, but there
were some rather melodramatic examples of civil disobedience. The
news agency Ansa reported that a helmet-free couple in a suburb of
Naples were arrested after they tried to crash through a police
blockade and nearly mowed down one law enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   It would be almost impossible to live in Italy and not know
about the new law _ television programs and newspapers have been
holding tense countdowns to Thursday's deadline, which many moped
drivers have been bracing for with the kind of bitter anxiety
usually reserved for taxes or occupying armies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sell a single helmet until yesterday, then suddenly,
at the last minute, my store was jammed,'' said Maurizio Polidori,
59, owner of a motorcycle parts store in central Rome, whose
shelves and floors were piled with helmet boxes. ``But Italians do
everything at the last minute. Five customers came in this morning
with traffic tickets in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Polidori, who said he approved of the new law, said it would be
difficult to enforce it for long. ``In Germany, they pass a law and
people obey it,'' he said. ``But Italy is different than anyplace
else _ people make a point of honor to flout the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
