<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GORE-EDITORIAL31-COX     03-30 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDITORIAL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore's a long way from being taken seriously on campaign finance
issue
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to marching the path of righteousness,
few do it with the determination of the reformed sinner. In that
context, a chastened Al Gore may eventually become the man to lead
the charge for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   But based on the reform plan he's now proposing, he's not quite
ready yet.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore did not violate the law in his zeal to collect money for
the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign, he surely pushed it to the limit
with his White House phone solicitations and his Buddhist temple
caper. He still has some explaining to do about e-mail messages
concerning 1996 fund-raising activities, messages that were
subpoenaed but somehow disappeared _ owing to a computer glitch,
his office says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in an obvious political gambit meant to blunt the jabs of
his GOP rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Gore has promised to make
campaign finance reform his first priority if he is elected
president. That commitment _ practically a ``read my lips'' vow _
indicates that Gore at least recognizes the importance of the issue
to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the plan that Gore proposes to cure the problem
falls well short of what's necessary. To be blunt, it's unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of his reform effort is a proposal to establish a
privately funded $7 billion endowment, from which U.S. Senate and
House election campaigns would be financed starting in 2008. The
admirable goal of the fund is to create contests where a
candidate's qualifications and ideas are more important than how
much money he or she can raise from special interests seeking
influence in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   However, the plan doesn't offer a dime to finance primary
campaigns, where incumbents usually have the greatest financial
advantage over political newcomers. It's also unlikely that
political contributors can be coaxed to donate to an endowment that
gives equal financing to candidates from across the political
spectrum. Under the current system, people give money to acquire
influence with politicians. If there's no influence to be gained,
there won't be any money either. Even Gore's plan to offer a tax
write-off won't attract contributors who are used to donating to
champions of their causes, rather than shelling out for some
generalized public good.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has at least moved beyond the issue of whether the system
should be reformed; his plan should move the process to the next
stage, debating how that reform can be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that's more than can be said for Gov. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
