<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES-$A     03-30 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT COULD HAPPEN NEXT TO MICROSOFT?
 &HT;    With COX-MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are seven possible outcomes that could eventually result
from a ruling that Microsoft violated antitrust laws or emerge from
a negotiated settlement:
</P>
<P>
   1. Microsoft is split into two or more separate companies. One
of them would market Windows, the firm's flagship product, while
another would sell its suite of applications, such as Word. Yet a
third company might be formed to offer Internet-based content and
services.
</P>
<P>
   2. Microsoft is split into several equal-sized entities,
popularly known as ``Baby Bills'' after chairman Bill Gates.
Initially, at least, each of the newly formed rivals would sell the
same software and products while competing against each other on
price and quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   3. Microsoft is broken up into several firms that target
different market segments. Under this plan, one such successor
company could tailor its products to consumers while another might
focus on large business customers. To ensure uniformity, a separate
company also could be formed to guarantee that divergent flavors of
Windows can still run the same basic applications.
</P>
<P>
   4. Microsoft is required to license Windows to its rivals. These
companies would then be free to market enhanced Windows clones that
would compete against Microsoft's ``classic'' version.
</P>
<P>
   5. Microsoft is required to provide detailed programming
``hooks'' into Windows to help its rivals compete. By opening up
the ``source code,'' they would become free to extend the Windows
operating system into such new areas as ``smart'' browsers, voice
or touch-screen commands, and next-generation audio and video
services.
</P>
<P>
   6. Microsoft is forced to ship a version of Windows that strips
away its built-in Internet browser. It could also be obliged to
offer other Windows versions that feature competing browsers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Microsoft is made to change its business practices. One
possibility: It would be barred from striking exclusive licensing
deals or required to publish a price list for its software and
services that would offer all comers the same deal, calling a halt
to current preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV02-COX     03-30 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT ANTITRUST CASE REACHEST A CROSSROADS
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT-REMEDIES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Midway through the Reagan administration, the
Justice Department settled a long-standing case against the
nation's telephone monopoly by creating the framework for its
eventual breakup into seven regional Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   Now that a federal judge threatens to break up Microsoft Corp.
as a predatory monopolist, the combatants in this high-stakes legal
struggle wonder whether the beleaguered software giant could some
day recover _ as AT&AMP;T has _ from having been ground down in the
antitrust mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go by the historical precedent, investors would probably
benefit,'' said Wall Street analyst Donald Selkin, who has watched
Microsoft's shares more than double in value since the government
filed its landmark suit nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the combined value of the four surviving Baby
Bells and other major spin-offs is now roughly double that of
parent AT&AMP;T, whose shares in recent years have also soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a consumers' standpoint, I don't really think anybody
knows whether or not it's better if Microsoft is broken up or
not,'' Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, however, fear that dividing up Windows,
Microsoft's flagship product, which serves as the operating system
on 90 percent of the world's personal computers, will spawn chaos
on the intellectual property front rather than bring about a fresh
surge of technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of consumers would still like to dial zero and get
somebody on the other end of the phone,'' says Jonathan Zuck, head
of the Association for Competitive Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Zuck, whose group was founded in 1998 to combat the government
in the Microsoft suit, argues that ``the notion that somehow
breaking up Microsoft and splitting up product development teams,
creating multiple version of Windows without increasing the size of
the market is, I think, crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a good way to break them up, Microsoft could do
that themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is an argument to which the clutch of multi-billionaires
calling the shots at Microsoft strongly subscribe, even as they
strive to cut a deal with the government to forestall a final
ruling by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson. The judge
has postponed issuing a verdict, but probably only until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in an e-mail message, composed at the company's
sprawling Redmond, Wash., campus and aimed at more than 30,000
Microsoft employees around the world, Steve Ballmer, the company's
recently named chief executive officer, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're very sure of our legal position and we're prepared
to take it all the way on appeal, we've learned that discretion is
the better part of valor, so we are working very hard to resolve
the case through settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, however, put down several markers of his own that, he
said, Microsoft will not cross _ at the risk of ultimately being
found guilty and exposed to potential triple damages in civil suits
that would inevitably follow an adverse verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we've put more on the table than the judicial
process would ultimately provide, even if we lost the case,'' he
wrote, adding: ``Any settlement must preserve our ability to
innovate and improve our products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine a scenario where you can work out details of a
very complex set of conduct remedies on Microsoft terms using a
Microsoft draft,'' said Ken Wasch, president of the Software and
Information Industry Association, which in February filed an
extensive brief with Jackson supporting the government and
suggesting the company be broken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You (have) got to be suspect when the defendant in a law
enforcement action proposes his own punishment,'' Wasch added.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanley Liebowitz, an economics professor at the University
of Texas and a critic of the government, believes Jackson has
pressed so hard for a last-minute settlement because he recognizes
the danger of imposing the kind of structural remedy once accepted
by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he wants to do anything that's too strong,
because it runs the risk of backfiring and getting him a reputation
in history as a judge who really messed up the economy,'' said
Liebowitz.
</P>
<P>
   For its own part, the government has also sent some ambivalent
signals in trying to settle the case. After a spate of reports the
Justice Department had given up on the notion of behavioral
remedies, new accounts surfaced that it was willing to stop short
of seeking an outright breakup.
</P>
<P>
   This apparently gentler and kinder strategy did not sit well
with some of 19 state attorneys general who are, in theory, full
partners in the historic litigation. The state officials were also
upset that Richard Posner, the tenacious judicial mediator in the
case, had failed to deal with them as equal players.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to placate state officials, Assistant U.S. Attorney
General Joel Klein reverted to a harsher tone in congressional
testimony last week.
</P>
<P>
   Said Klein: ``The findings of fact reveal a serious pattern of
anticompetitive conduct,'' referring to the 150-page ruling handed
down by Jackson last November. ``I think that a remedy ought to be
commensurate with those practices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiffs have always been willing to talk about a
(conduct-based) remedy with Microsoft, said Stephen Houck, the
former trial counsel for the states involved in the lawsuit and a
onetime antitrust prosecutor for the state of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Houck, now a private lawyer, believes the toughest problem in
crafting a settlement is making sure that Microsoft is forever
barred from doing to other companies what it once did to the former
Netscape Communications Corp., in using its huge Windows leverage
to tear down the market share of the competing browser offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the browser is a prime example of a tactic that
Microsoft has used, and I'm confident the government would not
settle a case unless there were some way to resolve issues like
this in the future,'' Houck said.
</P>
<P>
   If his view prevails, it means any settlement would have to set
firm restrictions on Microsoft's ability to integrate applications
with its dominant Windows operating system. But that may also mean
that a settlement, at this point, remains beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
