</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT COULD HAPPEN NEXT TO MICROSOFT?
 &HT;    With COX-MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are seven possible outcomes that could eventually result
from a ruling that Microsoft violated antitrust laws or emerge from
a negotiated settlement:
</P>
<P>
   1. Microsoft is split into two or more separate companies. One
of them would market Windows, the firm's flagship product, while
another would sell its suite of applications, such as Word. Yet a
third company might be formed to offer Internet-based content and
services.
</P>
<P>
   2. Microsoft is split into several equal-sized entities,
popularly known as ``Baby Bills'' after chairman Bill Gates.
Initially, at least, each of the newly formed rivals would sell the
same software and products while competing against each other on
price and quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   3. Microsoft is broken up into several firms that target
different market segments. Under this plan, one such successor
company could tailor its products to consumers while another might
focus on large business customers. To ensure uniformity, a separate
company also could be formed to guarantee that divergent flavors of
Windows can still run the same basic applications.
</P>
<P>
   4. Microsoft is required to license Windows to its rivals. These
companies would then be free to market enhanced Windows clones that
would compete against Microsoft's ``classic'' version.
</P>
<P>
   5. Microsoft is required to provide detailed programming
``hooks'' into Windows to help its rivals compete. By opening up
the ``source code,'' they would become free to extend the Windows
operating system into such new areas as ``smart'' browsers, voice
or touch-screen commands, and next-generation audio and video
services.
</P>
<P>
   6. Microsoft is forced to ship a version of Windows that strips
away its built-in Internet browser. It could also be obliged to
offer other Windows versions that feature competing browsers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Microsoft is made to change its business practices. One
possibility: It would be barred from striking exclusive licensing
deals or required to publish a price list for its software and
services that would offer all comers the same deal, calling a halt
to current preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
