u w BC-SOC-SEC-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      03-30 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SEC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SAYS ECONOMY HAS EXTENDED LIFE OF MEDICARE FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A vibrant economy has significantly improved the
financial condition of Medicare and Social Security, extending the
life of Medicare's hospital trust fund by eight years, to 2023, the
Clinton administration said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable accomplishment,'' said Donna Shalala, the
secretary of health and human services. ``When this administration
took office, the Medicare trust fund was projected to be depleted
in 1999. We have extended the life of the trust fund a full 24
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore can use the new numbers to his advantage,
as evidence of the administration's record of helping the elderly,
an important and pivotal group of voters, whose traditional
allegiance to the Democratic Party has frayed in the last few
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures will make it easier to add a prescription drug
benefit to medicare, as President Clinton and lawmakers from both
parties want to do. The new estimates will also reduce the
political pressure for cutbacks or radical changes in the structure
of Medicare or Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report says the Social Security trust fund will not
be depleted until 2037, three years later than estimated last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Summers, secretary of the Treasury, said the improved
condition of Social Security and Medicare resulted from ``the
robust expansion of the economy and the continued brightening of
the long-term outlook as a consequence of technological progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final three months of 1999, the American economy grew at
an annual rate of 7.3 percent, the fastest growth rate in nearly 16
years, the government reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine million people get Medicare. More than 152 million
workers are covered under Social Security, and the program pays
benefits to 45 million people each month.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare trust fund has gained 22 years of life just since
1996, when the administration predicted that it would run out of
money in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the change include the Balanced Budget Act of 1997,
which curbed all types of Medicare spending, and a federal
crackdown on Medicare fraud, which has made doctors and hospitals
much more conservative in filing claims. Also, health care prices
have grown at a relatively modest pace, compared with past trends.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said she feared that the good news would invite
complacency, discouraging efforts to ``modernize Medicare.''
Hospitals, doctors, nursing homes and HMO's are already lobbying
Congress to restore money cut from their Medicare payments in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said, ``Today's report should take
the wind out of the sails'' of people who seek to raise the
eligibility age for Social Security or cut benefits in order to
finance risky individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Ball, who worked at the Social Security Administration
for more than three decades and was commissioner from 1962 to 1973,
said, ``Arguments for radical changes in our approach to Social
Security are weakened by today's report.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Bixby, executive director of the Concord Coalition, a
bipartisan fiscal watchdog group, said: ``People will use this
report as an excuse to say we don't really need to move too quickly
on these issues because there's less of an immediate crisis. But
people shouldn't be lulled into thinking that the problem has gone
away. The big problem is still out there. Social Security will
still run cash deficits in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
