<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-CONGRESS31-COX     03-30 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CONGRESS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS READY TO MOVE ON RESIDENCY BILL FOR ELIAN
 &HT;    With ELIAN.
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida's two senators, Connie Mack and Bob Graham,
said Thursday that if the federal government revokes Elian
Gonzalez's permission to remain in the United States, they were
prepared to press legislation that would grant the boy and his
family permanent U.S. residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Elian's parole is lifted, then we will have to move forward
quickly with the legislation,'' said Mack, a Republican. He was
joined at a Capitol Hill news conference by Graham, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, also sponsored by Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., is
backed by the expected presidential nominees of both major parties.
It was first endorsed by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, a
Republican, and on Thursday also won the support of Vice President
Al Gore, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said the legislation faces a possible filibuster in the
Senate, but he was hopeful that the backing of Gore and other
officials will help get the 60 votes needed to bring the bill to a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation has been introduced in the House by Rep. Bob
Menendez, D-N.J. That bill, introduced Jan. 24, would grant
permanent resident status only to Elian. It has been referred to
the House Judiciary Committee along with a number of other bills
concerning the case, including one that would grant citizenship to
the 6-year-old Cuban boy.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to President Clinton, Mack urged the
administration to extend Elian's immigration status until all legal
proceedings regarding the child in federal and state courts,
including appeals, were complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department's daily threat to revoke Elian's legal
permission to remain in this country is an outrageous tactic,''
Mack said in the letter to Clinton. ``I am calling on you to stop
the Justice Department's harassment of this family.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Mack argued that Elian's case has turned into a legal
battle over immigration laws, and has lost sight of the issues of
child custody and what is in Elian's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he hoped the case made it to state court and was
examined on the basis of Elian's custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is a decision that needs to be made by someone
experienced in the matter of child custody judgments,'' Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Mack said they did not believe the federal government
should give custody of Elian to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
if he came to the United States on a temporary visa. Graham added
that giving the father custody while awaiting the appeals process
would take the custody decision away from the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Mack expressed his concerns about sending Elian back to Cuba,
saying, ``the boy would disappear from the public eye if allowed to
stay in the United States,'' but would be used as a symbol of
Castro's regime in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while he doesn't doubt love of a father for his
son, he believes that Juan Gonzalez and other Cuban family members
are not acting on their own, but are being influenced by Cuban
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
