<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      03-30 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY'S DEBATE OVER PRESIDENT SEEN AS THREAT TO STABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ When Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit boarded a
plane Thursday to begin a state visit to India, he left behind a
country that suddenly seemed on the edge of political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I am in India, I shall reflect on many things, including
the continuation of the government,'' Ecevit said before departing.
``Let everyone think about that for the next four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit's warning followed a turbulent session of Turkey's
Parliament that lasted into the pre-dawn hours Thursday. The
session was called to consider a constitutional amendment that
would allow President Suleyman Demirel to serve another five years
in office, but it dissolved into a partisan battle that may bode
ill for the country's stability.
</P>
<P>
   It also opened up new possibilities for change in a country
where the political elite is widely viewed as highly conservative.
Ecevit had argued that Demirel, 75, should be re-elected because he
is ``a factor for stability,'' but Turks appear more eager for
change than stability. There was no public pressure on members of
Parliament, who choose Turkey's president, to support Demirel, and
Thursday, with his prospects suddenly in doubt, there were no signs
of regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Demirel will withdraw,'' predicted one of his oldest
political allies, Husamettin Cindoruk, a former speaker of
parliament, in an interview. ``He is an experienced statesman.
Parliament has shown its will, and he will not resist it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a crisis of stability in Turkey, but there is a
crisis of democracy,'' Cindoruk said. ``The system is in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Ecevit took power as prime minister last May at the head
of a delicately balanced left-right coalition, Turkey has had its
first stable government in years. The government has presided over
a virtual end to the long war with Kurdish rebels, won enactment of
economic reforms, and persuaded the European Union to name Turkey
an official candidate for membership.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks Ecevit has been warning that the end of Demirel's term
threatened to upset all that his government has achieved. He fears
that if a way is not found to keep Demirel in office, the scramble
to succeed him will release political passions that he has so far
managed to control.
</P>
<P>
   Because the constitution requires Demirel to step down when his
single seven-year term expires in May, a constitutional amendment
must be passed if he is to stay in office. Ecevit proposed such an
amendment in Parliament on Wednesday, hoping that it would win the
367 votes necessary for a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment failed by a wide margin, winning only 253
votes. If it fails in a second vote next week, it will be dead and
Demirel will have to give up the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Various power blocs in Parliament evidently have their own
reasons for opposing the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic-oriented politicians say they will support it only if it
is accompanied by legal changes that would make it harder to close
political parties and ban people from public office. Their own
party is facing closure, and several of its leaders have been given
jail terms and political bans for making speeches that were
considered subversive.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the far-right party that is Ecevit's coalition
partner do not seem worried by the prospect that a bitter race to
succeed Demirel could bring down the government. They believe they
would emerge stronger from new elections, perhaps strong enough to
take over the government themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Parliament of Kurdish origin have vowed never
to support Demirel because of what they say is his hostility to
Kurdish aspirations. And groups backing ambitious politicians
apparently hope that in a deadlock, their favored figures might
have a chance to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been trying for a long time to protect political and
economic stability, but I am concerned about this now,'' Ecevit
said before leaving for India. ``I hope those who voted against the
amendment will think about what they are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
