<P>
   MI-DATE-RAPE-TRIAL (Detroit) _ Four men were sentenced to up to
15 years in prison in one of the nation's first trials involving a
death linked to a ``date rape'' drug. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-OUTLOOK (Washington) _ A look at the political,
diplomatic and legal aspects of the Elian Gonzalez case as U.S. and
Cuban officials seek to engineer a conclusion to the story.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAI-RADIO (Hemingway, S.C.) _ Williamsburg County, a rural
slice of the Bible Belt an hour's drive from the Atlantic coast, is
just the place one expects to find religious radio. Roadside signs
testify that Jesus saves, and the steeples of Baptist and
Pentecostal churches can seem as ubiquitous as the tall pines and
Spanish moss. Yet it is this setting that makes WLGI, a 50,000-watt
FM station outside this small town, such a surprise. To listeners,
WLGI is known as ``Radio Baha'i,'' a 15-year-old project of one of
the world's newer religions, a monotheistic faith that emerged in
19th century Persia (now Iran). By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT11,12 on March 27; map.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WORKPLACE-PROTEST (New York) _ In immigration detention cells
and on college campuses, in the pulpits of churches great and
small, and across political beliefs of all variations, people are
fasting. They do it to make a statement, to prove a point, to draw
attention, to make a personal kind of peace. And in New York State
this week, more than a thousand people, from the bishop of Albany
to janitors in Buffalo, have joined in one of the country's largest
collective fasts, this one to protest abuses in the work place. By
Steven Greenhouse.
