<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-GUNS-COX     03-30 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guns have paid off nicely for Bush
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At sun-up in an open field near Houston in 1994, in a photo op
aimed at becoming governor of Texas, George W. Bush learned how
guns can backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, ostensibly after dove but really hunting for publicity,
fired seven times and connected once. He downed a killdeer, a
protected species.
</P>
<P>
   The gunplay cost him a $130 fine and a heap of campaign trail
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the long run, guns have paid off nicely for Bush. He
rode a gun-industry issue into his first term in office that year
and now, gun-industry money may help him ride into higher office.
Bundled in with the massive amounts of money that will boost his
candidacy, Bush will get help from from what is, so far, almost
$500,000 in soft money poured into Republican candidates and causes
by the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is in the hip holster of the NRA,'' Chris
Lehane, spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, Bush's November foe,
said Wednesday. ``He's in lockstep with the gun lobby, but he's out
of step with America.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Bush is in step with Texas, a state
where gun ownership is sacred to many, including some who see a
never-ending, international conspiracy to disarm them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly support the proposition that no governmental
agency or the UN shall require citizens to register their
firearms,'' says the state GOP platform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's political career got a high-caliber boost from that kind
of Texas thinking. In June 1993, then-Gov. Ann Richards, still
popular by most measures, vetoed a measure calling for a nonbinding
statewide vote on whether Texans should be allowed to carry
concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   She dismissed the concealed weapon referendum as ``nothing more
than game playing by a few legislators who appear intent on
embarrassing the great state as a place where gun-toting vigilantes
roam the street.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year later, Texans dismissed Richards and
replaced her with Bush, who said he saw no harm in allowing
law-abiding Texans to pack pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Richards now believes she was the victim of gun politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the race really over guns,'' she said on ``Larry King
Live'' several months ago. ``That was the number one issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed the concealed weapons bill into law during his first
legislative session in 1995. Since then, the state has issued
208,185 permits. Another 2,923 applications were denied, including
about 700 from convicted felons ineligible to carry concealed
weapons. Gun control advocates have blasted the state's record of
not investigating felons who, through their concealed weapon permit
applications, hinted they might be packing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are they convicted felons, now they're well-trained
convicted felons in possession of a firearm,'' Handgun Control Inc.
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ongoing opposition from gun-control advocates,
law-enforcement officials _ many of whom opposed the measure _
decline to say the concealed weapons law has produced the kind of
dire outcome some feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen open chaos in the streets,'' said Texas
Department of Public Safety spokesman Mike Cox, adding that it is
difficult to measure the crime-fighting success of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, is convinced the concealed weapons bill has
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the law we passed in Texas has made Texas a safer
place,'' he said last September near the scene of a Fort Worth
church shooting that left eight dead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush treats guns as products that are legal, useful and enjoyed
by many law-abiding citizens. His mindset tells him to find ways to
make sure law-abiding citizens can keep guns, rather than looking
for ways to restrict them.
</P>
<P>
   That mindset has been seen in his approval of a law banning
municipalities from suing gunmakers, his less-than-enthusiastic
support of pre-purchase background checks, his doubts about the
effectiveness of mandatory trigger locks and his support for
increased penalties for juveniles who use weapons in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
