<SLUG> BC-GORE-CARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CALLS FOR EXPANDING TAX SUBSIDIES TO PROMOTE FUEL-EFFICIENT
CARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With sleek models of fuel-efficient cars on display
behind him, Vice President Al Gore called for expanding federal
government tax subsidies to make such vehicles affordable for
average motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with executives from the Big Three U.S. automakers
Thursday, the vice president said that encouraging the production
of fewer gas-guzzling cars was key to dealing with rising oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do more to ensure our independence from a source of
fuel that makes us vulnerable'' to rising high oil prices, Gore
said at the presentation by the Partnership for a New Generation of
Vehicles, which he helped launch in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The event also provided a forum for the presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee to address the pressing political problem of
high gas prices as well as stroke the automobile industry, which
dominates a key election battleground state of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   With financial aid from the federal government,
Daimler-Chrysler, Ford and General Motors have strived to develop
cars that get 80 miles per gallon using hybrid technology that
combines gasoline or diesel powered engines with an electric
motors.
</P>
<P>
   While the auto companies have been successful in designing such
vehicles, they acknowledge that they still cannot make them cheaply
enough for mass production. Daimler Chrysler executive Jim Holden
said that his prototype would cost motorists an extra $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   To make such vehicles more enticing, Gore has proposed giving
auto buyers tax credits ranging between $2,000 and $4,000 if they
purchase vehicles, including SUVs, minivans and pickups, that use
fuel-efficient technology. The tax credit would cost the federal
treasury about $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the federal government gives a 10 percent credit, up
to $4,000, for the cost of qualified electric vehicles. However,
that credit begins to phase down in 2002 and does not include
hybrid vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   By using tax credits to voluntarily promote fuel-efficient cars,
Gore hopes to steer a pragmatic middle course between
environmentalists, who want to mandate higher fuel-efficiency
standards and the auto industry, which has opposed such controls.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists were unhappy with the voluntary
approach, arguing the automakers will not be motivated to put
fuel-efficient cars on the market until the government raises
standards, particularly for SUVs and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In a written release, the Sierra Club noted that since 1994, the
Republican-controlled Congress has barred the Clinton
administration from raising fuel-economy standards for light trucks
and SUVs to the same level as other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Corporate Average Fuel economy, called CAFE
standards, requires that cars average 27.5 miles per gallon while
light trucks and SUVs have to average 20.5 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club also pointed out that the American carmakers
have already been beaten by their Japanese counterparts who have
put vehicles, averaging 50 miles per gallon, on the market.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has long aligned himself with environmental causes,
he has not dwelled on some of his more controversial stands as he
tries to court voters in key Midwestern auto-producing states,
particularly Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican presidential opponent, George W. Bush, has
attacked Gore for at one time proposing that the combustion engine
be phased out to curb air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   While the automobile executives praised Gore at the
show-and-tell event, the traditionally Republican industry still
has been putting its money with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, the automobile
industry executives and political action committees gave $934,199
to Bush's campaign in 1999. By contrast, they contributed $65,274
to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
