<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot fills key post
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Depot named Mark Baker to the new post of executive vice
president and chief operating officer of U.S. stores.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 41, will run nine divisions with more than 880 U.S.
stores initially. The retailer also operates stores in Canada and
Latin America. By 2003, it expects to have1,900 stores, mostly in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He also will oversee marketing and communications, proprietary
brands and Apex Supply Co., a recently acquired distributor of
plumbing products.
</P>
<P>
   Baker joined Home Depot, based in Cobb County on Paces Ferry
Road at I-285, four years ago, when he left California home
improvement retailer HomeBase, where he was executive vice
president. He joined Home Depot as vice president of merchandising
for the company's Midwest division. Other posts included Midwest
division president and, most recently, group president of the
Mid-South and Southern divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Martineau, currently president-Western division, will
replace Baker as group president, Mid-South and Southern divisions.
Martineau joined Home Depot in 1979 as an assistant store manager.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
