<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-BC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING IN B.C.
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by LANG) 
(Eds: fact box follows story.) 
By MARY RAMOS 
c.2000 Dallas Morning News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Shopping in this city is, like the
city itself, laid-back, yet sophisticated _ a multicultural,
international experience. With Vancouver's mild climate year-round,
it's no wonder visitors to this largest city on the west coast of
Canada enjoy indulging in some adventurous shopping, going beyond
department stores and malls into the neighborhoods of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Vancouver shopping neighborhoods mentioned here has
its own distinctive flavor. All are easily walkable and fun to
explore. And with the exchange rate highly favorable to Americans,
they're full of potential bargains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gastown &QL; 
This neighborhood is interesting for its architecture and also for
its place in Vancouver's history as the oldest commercial area in
town.
</P>
<P>
   The Victorian-era buildings were saved from demolition in the
1960s and `70s and restored for retail use. Gastown's location near
Vancouver's cruise-ship terminal makes it a magnet for visitors.
The graceful old buildings are filled with galleries offering
beautifully handcrafted native arts and crafts. There are also
boutiques, restaurants and bars interspersed with shops selling
cheaper, mass-produced crafts, trinkets and T-shirts. The
tree-shaded brick streets complete a charming picture.
</P>
<P>
   At the corner of Water and Cambie streets, the Gastown Steam
Clock is a bit of fun. It whistles _ with a puff of steam _ every
15 minutes and chimes, with even more steam, every hour. Although
it looks as old as the rest of Gastown,  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Punjabi Market
</P>
<P>
   Also called ``Little India,'' this three-block strip of shops
along Main Street between 48th and 51st streets is identified by
distinctive street signs.
</P>
<P>
   Spice shops, sweets shops and restaurants tantalize with the
aromas of Indian foods. Indian music spills out onto the sidewalks
from stores.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing shops predominate, however, with many offering women's
traditional saris and tunic/pant suits and little girls' frilly
dresses. One specialty shop displays elaborately elegant finery for
an entire wedding party, created in silks and velvets and enriched
with gold embroidery. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yaletown &QL; 
One of the hottest new shopping areas in Vancouver is this
neighborhood of red brick warehouses on the north bank of False
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The area was developed in the 1880s around the Canadian Pacific
Railway's maintenance yards. Later it was the site of Expo '86,
after which it was neglected for many years. Today the loading
docks are peppered with umbrella-shaded, fresh-air restaurants and
bistros.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are being transformed into home-designer
showrooms, architects' and attorneys' offices, galleries,
boutiques, and pubs that attract a trendy clientele. Residential
high-rises edge False Creek, and an amazing, upscale grocery store,
Urban Fare, recently opened around the corner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robson
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best-known shopping street in Vancouver, Robson
concentrates on fashions, accessories and more fashion, with food,
gifts and jewelry thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Covering about six square blocks in the middle of downtown
Vancouver, the Robson shopping area boasts a midprice to upscale
mix of American and Canadian chain stores, with a sprinkling of
shops with European panache: Banana Republic, Levi's, The Gap,
Armani, Club Monaco and Laura Ashley, as well as the very British
Marks and Spencer, and many others.
</P>
<P>
   And where else can you see one intersection (Robson and Thurlow
streets) with two _ count 'em, two _ Starbucks shops?
</P>
<P>
   But for truly elegant boutiques, check out the area around the
Hotel Vancouver, the Grand Dame of West Georgia Street. There you
find Fendi, Chanel, Valentino, Louis Vuitton, Aquascutum and other
equally chic shops. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Granville Island
</P>
<P>
   A wildly successful example of urban rehab, today's Granville
Island was created out of a district of decaying corrugated-metal
warehouses. The former industrial area is now a spot popular with
both locals and visitors; its quirky mix of businesses guarantees
something of interest to just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The focal center of the neighborhood is the Granville Island
Public Market, housed in a 50,000-square-foot complex that features
fresh produce, fish, poultry, meats, baked goods, gourmet coffees,
wines and a food court with a mouth-watering assortment of ethnic
fast foods. And there's nary a golden arch to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Tables at one end of the food court overlook False Creek harbor.
In good weather, diners spill onto the dock area outside. Shops and
galleries nearby feature art, crafts and gift items, and one
building is filled with shops offering merchandise for children.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant offerings on Granville Island range from seafood to
vegetarian. The island's other businesses include an art school, a
cement company, a hotel and several marine-maintenance specialists.
Access to the island (actually a peninsula) is by car, bus, private
pleasure boat, or the little passenger mini-ferries that depart
every few minutes from a dock behind the Aquatic Center at Thurlow
and Pacific streets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chinatown
</P>
<P>
   Chinese laborers came to British Columbia in the 1880s to help
build the Canadian Pacific Railway. After the railroad was
completed, many stayed in Vancouver. Others who had come to work in
lumber camps and mines joined them. From that nucleus grew
Vancouver's present-day Chinatown, home to about 35,000 people of
Chinese descent.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being just a tourist attraction, Chinatown is a working
business and market center for the city's Chinese population. A
walk down the crowded, bustling sidewalks of this vibrant district
is like being transported to Hong Kong. Signs are mostly in
Chinese, and English is rarely spoken. Shops offering the daily
necessities _ pots and pans, shoes, plastic baskets _ alternate
with bakeries displaying Chinese cakes and poultry shops where
barbecued ducks hang in the windows. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   IN THE NEIGHBORHOOD:
</P>
<P>
   Gastown stretches east of Canada Place, which is recognizable by
its trademark white ``sails'' on the north side of downtown
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Punjabi Market, take a bus or a taxi from downtown
Vancouver. The district extends along both sides of Main Street
from 48th to 51st streets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Yaletown is on the east side of downtown Vancouver, roughly bounded
by Homer Street on the west, Pacific Boulevard on the south, Beatty
on the east and  &QL; 
Robson Street on the north.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Robson Street is the center of this shopping hot spot, generally
from Jervis Street to Burrard Street, and the district also
stretches a block in each direction from Robson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Granville Island is on a peninsula across False Creek from downtown
Vancouver. It can be reached by bus, taxi, car or passenger ferry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chinatown takes in the area roughly from Hastings Street south to
Keefer Street and from Carrall Street east to Gore Street. A staff
member at the Vancouver Tourist Info Centre warned us that though
the distance from there to Chinatown was not great, we should not
walk. A taxi or city bus is the safest way to the neighborhood
shopping areas of the district. Ask at the Info Centre for specific
information.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Vancouver Tourist Info Centre, on the Plaza
Level at 200 Burrard St., is a good first stop in Vancouver. The
friendly staffers can help with accommodations, sightseeing and
transportation reservations, free of charge. They have route maps
for Vancouver's transit, as well as a handy guide called ``Discover
Vancouver on Transit'' that tells you what buses, rail or ferries
will take you to the places you want to go. They also sell
comprehensive Vancouver transit route maps. Phone (604) 683-2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
