<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-ECOMMERCE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern buys stake in online seller of power
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co., jumping into e-commerce, announced an
investment Thursday in a California Internet company that plans to
market electricity online across the country.
</P>
<P>
   With its second major Internet-related announcement in as many
days, Southern becomes the preferred electricity supplier to a
2-year-old company that plans to market electricity to homes and
businesses in 23 states and the District of Columbia by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Company Energy Marketing, Southern's wholesale energy
trading arm, is taking a minority stake in Utility.com with rights
to expand the investment in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Southern was among 15 major utilities that announced plans
Wednesday for a buying consortium that will purchase supplies
ranging from gas turbines to paper clips over the Internet. This
week's announcements were Southern's first two major Internet
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The $350-billion-a-year U.S. utility industry has been slow to
embrace the Internet, in part because it was until recently
dominated by regulated monopolies with little incentive to
innovate.
</P>
<P>
   But as the industry is deregulated and opened to competition,
the pace will surely quicken, said Edward Tirello, an analyst at
Deutsche Bank. ``This is the tip of the iceberg,'' he said of the
two Southern announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Utility.com is currently selling electricity to ``tens of
thousands'' of retail customers in Pennsylvania and California,
said its chief executive, Chris King. The company is licensed to
sell power in Arizona, Massachusetts and Nevada and plans to expand
as other states are deregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers going to the Utility.com Web site at www.utility.com
can sign up for service in areas served by the company by typing in
name, address and utility account number. Payment is by checking
account deduction or credit card. Monthly statements come by
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The service is not available in Georgia, where Southern's
Georgia Power Co. subsidiary maintains a monopoly over most of the
state and deregulation is not expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   Utility.com is a privately held company with almost 100
employees based in Albany, Calif., north of San Francisco. The
company has been relying on volatile wholesale markets for its
electricity supplies.
</P>
<P>
   King said the Southern deal will lower costs for his company and
allow it to be more competitive. ``It will enable us to focus on
customers and allow Southern to manage risks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern decided against entering retail power sales in
California when that state became the first to deregulate
electricity several years ago. The company has instead been buying
power plants in deregulating states and concentrating on sales to
other utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Morsches, president of Southern Company Energy
Marketing, said Thursday's deal ``helps us reach into the retail
energy markets.'' Southern Co. owns 60 percent of Southern Company
Energy Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates by Morgan Stanley investment bankers, 50
percent of American consumers will purchase electricity online by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
