<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-565(2T     03-30 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-565(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON MAY HAVE SLIGHTLY EASED INDIA-PAKISTAN TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Without winning or conceding anything of
substance on his tour of South Asia last week, President Clinton
may still have helped modestly reduce the risk of war between
nuclear-armed India and Pakistan by talking sweet to India and
tough to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   He spent five days courting India, the region's democratic
colossus and rising economic power, with the ardor of a smitten
suitor _ and half a day treating Pakistan, America's Cold War ally
and a nation yet again ruled by generals, like an old girlfriend
who is part of the past.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of estrangement, Clinton gambled that the best way
to build a closer relationship with India _ a nation of 1 billion
people that is hungry for respect, and to encourage it to act
soberly with regard to its smaller, but detested, rival, Pakistan _
was to give it a dose of unconditional affection.
</P>
<P>
   He demanded no quid pro quo for his visit here _ for example,
requiring India's signing of the nuclear test ban treaty. And he
seconded India's demand that Pakistan reduce the level of violence
by militants it supports in Kashmir, the Himalayan territory both
countries claim, as a step toward coaxing India back to peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats and experts on the region have become
increasingly worried that India, angered by intensified attacks by
Pakistani-backed guerrillas in Kashmir, will strike across the
so-called Line of Control that divides the Indian- and
Pakistan-held parts of Kashmir to hit at militant training camps in
Pakistani territory.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview , Brajesh Mishra, the national security
adviser to India's prime minister, said India had assured the
Americans that as long as there were no new large-scale Pakistani
incursions into Indian territory, ``we will not take any
provocative action on the other side of the Line of Control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we have to do to curb the militants will be on our
side of the Line of Control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. approach to Pakistan was motivated by a different
assumption: that Pakistani generals were operating under the
illusion that if they stirred up enough trouble in Kashmir, the
United States, fearing a conflict that could turn nuclear, would
step in and insist that India make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Pakistan-backed militants have become
increasingly bold. At the same time, the Indians have added to an
already immense military presence that has been criticized for
well-documented human rights violations against the civilian
population. Pakistan, weaker than India, has long pleaded for
international intervention _ and sought to provoke it by stoking
the militancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for many years they thought that might get us involved
and it won't,'' Clinton told Peter Jennings of ABC News days before
his trip to Pakistan. ``I'm not going to be dragged into something
that, first of all, that India doesn't want us to be part of and
secondly, that I got dragged into from deliberate acts of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sternly worded warnings, issued privately to Gen.
Pervez Musharraf, the army chief who has ruled Pakistan since an
Oct. 12 coup, and in a televised address to the nation, were meant
to leave the generals with no doubt that further violence in
Kashmir wwould deepen Pakistan's international isolation while
failing to bring America to the rescue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the significance of the trip was not limited to issues of
war and peace. In a traveling exhibition of political performance
art, Clinton also began rebuilding America's long-estranged
relationship with India, the world's most populous democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In New Delhi, he wowed one of the world's most hard-boiled
groups of politicians, the Indian Parliament. ``As Clinton walked
to the exit, suddenly, as if the dam of hostility had been
breached, almost everyone wanted to shake his hand,'' the news
weekly India Today reported breathlessly.
</P>
<P>
   In Rajasthan, the president danced spontaneously with village
women. In Hyderabad, he sang the praises of India's fast-growing
software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook, a national magazine, said Clinton would be remembered
as ``a warmhearted, fun-loving man'' and described the president
expertly scooping up dal makhani _ a rich, creamy lentil dish _
with roti, a flat bread, then approvingly quoted him saying, ``I
wish I had two stomachs.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans in the embassy in New Delhi and those visiting from
Washington were almost giddy with relief and amazement that India
seemed to have fallen head over heels for Clinton. After all, the
president was in the final year of a second term tainted by
scandal, coming to a country that has had notoriously prickly
relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the good feelings of this moment could quickly fade. That
has happened in the past. The Clinton administration had been
warming up to India in 1997 and 1998 _ planning the first visit to
India by a U.S. president in more than two decades _ when India
shocked the world by conducting nuclear tests in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in the gulag for a couple of years and this was
their chance to rehabilitate themselves,'' said a U.S. diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the ground lost at the time of the tests was recovered
last week as the Americans simply agreed to disagree with India on
its development of a nuclear deterrent. But economic sanctions
imposed by the United States after the tests are still in place.
And the sensitivities of India, once a restive colony in the
British empire, to what it has often perceived as U.S.
highhandedness are still just below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   And it is far from certain that Clinton's trip will produce the
concrete long-term results he seeks: that both nations accede to
the test ban treaty, get back to the negotiating table, calm their
hostilities and slow down spending on nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not fundamentally change the U.S. position on
Kashmir, the length and warmth of his visit to India and the
brevity and coolness of his time in Pakistan left the impression in
both places that the United States has tilted toward India.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it became clear that Clinton would be tough with the
Pakistanis when he went to Islamabad _ as indeed he was _ India
smiled,'' said Dennis Kux, author of the definitive history of
Indian-U.S. relations, ``Estranged Democracies'' (Sage
Publications, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the end of the Cold War _ during which India drew
close to the Soviets and Pakistan to the Americans _ there is a
more solid foundation for cooperation between India and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Both are great, multicultural democracies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' thriving high technology industry has spawned
a crop of successful Indian-born entrepreneurs who are becoming a
force in U.S. politics. India itself has a growing software
industry that has rapidly rising sales to U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, India's more open, market-driven economy is
producing opportunities for American investors, though the dollar
amounts remain relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was in India, U.S. companies _ among them Enron,
Motorola, and Hewlett-Packard _ signed deals worth about $4 billion
with Indian companies and state governments in the high technology
and power sectors, among others. U.S. officials said they helped
move some of these deals through the still ornate Indian
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of India has accepted an
invitation to visit the White House before Clinton leaves office
and both governments have committed themselves to high-level
consultations on nuclear nonproliferation, trade, the environment
and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kux, the historian, cautioned that one good visit
is no guarantee of better relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only time will tell,'' he said, ``if Clinton and his
successor, whether Gore or Bush, and the Indians stay the course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
