<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-NORTHCAROLINA-COX     03-30 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHCAROLINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heels' Forte can handle it
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Forte follows a long line of illustrious baggage
handlers. Kids named Worthy and Jordan and Carter, freshmen of such
influence and precocity they were told to give their team a lift.
</P>
<P>
   When ordered to embrace a rich North Carolina tradition and
carry the green bag, how could Forte refuse?
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought I needed humbling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Every upper-class teammate raised his hand one day in the fall,
and Forte became the bag man. All season long, he has carried the
green bag on road trips, lugging the trainer's duffel full of tape,
scissors and ointments to the bus, to the arena and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times,'' Forte said, ``I may have my Walkman on, walking to
the locker room, and the managers will tap me on the shoulder and
say, 'Come get the bag.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the afterglow of North Carolina's 59-55 victory over Tulsa in
the NCAA South Regional final, Bill Guthridge was asked if Forte's
bag days might be over. ``Oh, no,'' the Carolina coach said. ``We
might just put some bricks in there for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Forte doesn't hoist bricks, of any sort. It was
abundantly clear long before Sunday, when the 6-foot-4 shooting
guard got a temporary reprieve. When Carolina left the arena, a
student manager carried the green bag to the team bus. ``The guy
just dropped 28 on Tulsa,'' the manager explained. ``He's taking us
to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   To Indianapolis, where North Carolina (22-13) meets Florida
(28-7) in Saturday's second semifinal. For Carolina, an NCAA-record
15th Final Four is also its most improbable Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And Forte is the tourney's leading scorer with 80 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no fool. I'm no Michael Jordan,'' he said. ``I haven't
even met Mr. Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Mr. Jordan, who capped his freshman season with the
jump shot that beat Georgetown 63-62 in the 1982 NCAA final,
crashed the NCAA Tournament party quite like Forte.
</P>
<P>
   After a ``nervous'' 13 points against Missouri, Forte's 17 led
UNC to an upset of top-seeded Stanford. He hit two 3-pointers in
the last five minutes after Guthridge had scolded, ``Stop shooting
it like you're scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's dramatic rally against Tennessee began with a late
3-pointer by Forte, who finished with 22 points. He scored a
career-high 28 against Tulsa, one point better than Jordan's best
tournament game. The silken shooter scored 10 of UNC's 14 points in
the decisive run and grabbed eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scores so easy,'' Tulsa coach Bill Self said. ``He's
probably the best freshman in the land, or at least had the best
year. Even though he made tough shots, he made them look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte, averaging 16.7 points, is the first freshman to lead
North Carolina in scoring. He also is the ACC rookie of the year.
Now, he's in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And all he wanted was to start as a freshman. ``That was really
big for me,'' he said. ``Not many freshmen got a chance to start at
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was a kid in Smyrna, Forte played rec ball in a
10-and-under league. By the eighth grade, he stood 6-foot-2 and
stood out in almost every way.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he was the focus of an intense recruiting battle
involving which high school he'd attend. Campbell, the school in
Forte's district, vowed to petition the board of education if he
chose another high school in the area. Some 95 coaches applied for
the coaching vacancy at Campbell. Wanda Hightower saw the furor
over her oldest son and, much like his North Carolina teammates
last fall, decided a little humility was in order.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower took a job transfer with Hewlett-Packard, moved to
Greenbelt, Md., and enrolled Forte at famed DeMatha High. She
already had persuaded Morgan Wooten, DeMatha's legendary coach, to
take Joseph. Wooten's idea of humility was having Forte spend the
ninth grade playing on the JV. By the time he graduated, Forte was
a USA Today All-American.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1999, he was a cocky, gifted freshman who looked
like a kid and was eager to start and impress. ``The baby-faced
bandit,'' center Brendan Haywood has called Forte. ``He looks like
he's 12.''
</P>
<P>
   During the informal pickup games before Carolina officially
started practice, he talked as if he already belonged. ``When we
were playing pickup games, I was like, 'I'm going to average
this,''' Forte said. ``Then everybody's like, 'Shut up, you're just
a freshman.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard to figure out,'' Haywood said. ``We were
just trying to figure out where he was coming from. But he's a good
person, just a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's confident,'' senior point guard Ed Cota said. ``He might
boast a little bit about the things he does well, but we just kick
him in the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   They patted him on the back after Forte debuted with 24 points
in the opener against Southern Cal, then was the MVP of the Maui
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when I started off, I was taking advantage of no one
knowing me and not giving me any respect because I was a
freshman,'' he said. ``Then I struggled a bit. But I think I did
well late in the season because of how I struggled earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte adapted to the college game. When Maryland held him to
seven points, Forte responded by averaging 24.2 points over the
next 10 games. Since he scored seven in a first-round ACC
Tournament loss to Wake Forest, Forte has averaged 20 in the NCAAs
and was named the top player in the South Regional.
</P>
<P>
   And this weekend in Indianapolis, Joseph Forte still will be
carrying on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
