<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      03-30 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ If ever there was a movie that seemed too hip for
the room, it was ``The Matrix'' going into the 72nd annual Academy
Awards on Sunday at the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly what we thought,'' said Joel Silver, the
producer of the genre-bending science-fiction thriller that became
one of last spring's biggest hits and the first in a string of
unlikely, word-of-mouth successes that defined the year, including
``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``The Sixth Sense'' and ``American
Beauty.'' But the room turned out hipper than expected.
</P>
<P>
   First, ``The Matrix'' won the Oscar for best sound. Then it won
for best sound-effects editing. Fine, both were technical
categories in a movie celebrated for its technical achievements.
But then ``The Matrix'' beat out George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode
I _ The Phantom Menace'' and its groundbreaking special effects for
the evening's best visual effects prize. And finally it beat out
``American Beauty,'' the eventual winner of the best picture prize
and four other Oscars, for the film editing award. At one point,
``The Matrix'' had won four Oscars _ every one it had been
nominated for _ and ``American Beauty'' had yet to win one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great news is that the academy recognized a totally unique
picture and validated it in a way that surprised some people,''
said Lorenzo di Bonaventura, president of production at Warner
Brothers, which released the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt the picture was a groundbreaking picture and
that it was something special and warranted to be separated from
the pack and get some special accolades, but you never know what
will happen at the Academy Awards,'' Silver said. ``I just wanted
to get one award, because I felt that if you get one, then the
movie is always an Academy Award-winning movie and that would
follow it around forever. The sequel would become, sequel to the
Oscar-winning `Matrix,' and so on. One award would have been more
than I would have dreamed. But four? I was really surprised we got
the editing award.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sequels to ``The Matrix'' are in pre-production _ and will
reunite the co-directors Andy and Larry Wachowski with the star
Keanu Reeves. The plan is to shoot both simultaneously, about a
year from now. ``We'll be shooting two movies literally at the same
time,'' Silver said. ``Actually, what we're doing is we're shooting
one giant movie and then splitting it in half, releasing it in two
parts.'' The plan is for the first one, ``Matrix 2,'' to come out
around Christmas 2002, with ``Matrix 3'' following the next summer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly sweet night for Silver because 12 years
ago he produced another movie, ``Die Hard,'' that got many of the
same Oscar bids but came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that `The Matrix' was just a very smart action movie,
if that's not an oxymoron,'' Silver said. ``It was about more than
explosions and fistfights; it really raises the bar on these kind
of movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Here Today, Gone ...
</P>
<P>
   You may remember Keith Gordon from playing the owner of a
haunted car in John Carpenter's ``Christine'' or as Angie
Dickinson's techno-detective son in Brian De Palma's ``Dressed to
Kill,'' or even as Rodney Dangerfield's somewhat embarrassed son in
``Back to School.'' But Gordon has spent the last decade putting
together an increasingly accomplished career as a director of
independent films, not that he has anything against studio films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at the point where I have a development deal,'' said
Gordon, 39. ``My office is in my house. But I guess if a studio or
someone were to offer to pay for an office and for somebody to
answer my phone, well, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   His first film, ``The Chocolate War'' (1988), a decidedly creepy
drama set in a Catholic boys' school, was followed in 1991 with an
adaptation of William Wharton's antiwar novel set in 1944 France,
``A Midnight Clear.'' That film's cast of then largely unknowns has
a more familiar ring a decade later: Ethan Hawke, Gary Sinise,
Peter Berg, Frank Whaley, John C. McGinley. In 1996, Gordon
finished an adaptation of Kurt Vonnegut's ``Mother Night,''
starring Nick Nolte.
</P>
<P>
   And now he's back with yet another adaptation, of Scott
Spencer's politically tinged romance ``Waking the Dead,'' starring
Billy Crudup as a liberal congressional candidate who begins to
have visions of a former lover (Jennifer Connelly) more radical
than he was in the early 1970s who supposedly died in an explosion.
The movie had its premiere at the Sundance Film Festival in January
and opened in limited release on March 24 to mixed but generally
positive reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been doing a lot of traveling for this, to about
eight or nine cities,'' Gordon said. ``Which is great, except you
visit all these places but never really get a chance to get out of
the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he'd been getting more worried about the future of
adult-oriented independent films, wondering whether the audience of
those who came of age during the great burst of American filmmaking
in the early 1970s are getting too old and settled to go to movies
as often as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie is doing very well in New York and Los Angeles, but
in some other places it's more difficult,'' he said. ``I even have
some good friends who tell me, oh, great, the new movie is out, and
that they'll go see it in the next couple of weeks. And I have to
say, `No, you must go see it now, right now, or in two weeks it
will be gone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Canvass and Canvas
</P>
<P>
   When the director Carlos Avila went looking for a young man to
play one of Jimmy Smits' sons, an aspiring prizefighter, in his new
movie, ``The Price of Glory'', he put out the word through Los
Angeles' boxing clubs that he was more interested in a fresh face
with boxing talent than a young actor who could learn to box.
</P>
<P>
   He also put out the word on Spanish-language radio and
television stations in Los Angeles. The result was that more than
1,000 men showed up at the Conga Room, Smits' Los Angeles
nightclub, and each was given a chance to read. Some were young
actors who tried to pass as boxers, others were boxers who tried to
pass as actors, but one of them was Ernesto Hernandez, ``who was
incredibly charismatic and very distinctive looking,'' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez got the job.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a bonus. One 8-year-old boy, Gilbert Leal, came
with his father. The boy had been training to box since he was 5.
Avila decided to hire him to play Hernandez's character as a youth.
``One of the things I wanted to do,'' Avila said, ``was to expand
the pool of young Latino acting talent that is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
