<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CMGI-LIBERTY-NYT &LR;      03-30 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-LIBERTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MULTIMEDIA COMPANIES WILL DEVELOP INTERNET VENTURES FOR
PRIMEDIA'S MAGAZINES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teddy Bear magazine, make way for Teddy Bear Interactive, Teddy
Bear streaming video, Teddy Bear e-commerce and Teddy Bear, the
broadband version.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that marks a significant expansion for Primedia, a
magazine company once known for its highly specialized magazine
publications such as Teddy Bear, Drag Racing USA and National Hog
Farmer, the company's chairman and chief executive, Tom Rogers,
announced an agreement Thursday with two multimedia companies, who
will buy stakes in the company.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., an internet venture-fund company, and Liberty Media,
the cable-television programming company owned by AT&AMP;T, will each
purchase 5 percent stakes in Primedia _ for a total of about $400
million. The three companies will develop internet-based joint
ventures with Primedia's 250 magazine titles and develop Primedia's
newly formed broadband video division. Primedia is controlled by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., the leveraged-buyout firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primedia has a reputation as a sleepy media company that
hasn't done much,'' Rogers said Thursday, after making the
announcement in a conference call with analysts. ``We are going to
create a lot of activity. The company's asset base is perfectly
suited to translation to the new-media world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers told analysts that, ``in the future, you will no longer
refer to us as, Primedia, comma, a magazine publishing company.''
He stressed that the highly targeted niche titles of Primedia and
their enthusiast audiences are the key to the transformation of
Primedia to the new-media realm.
</P>
<P>
   Some analyst remain skeptical. Mark Mooradian, an internet
analyst at Jupiter Communications, said, ``The big question is
whether these categories are big enough to build stand-alone
ventures that really work, which is tough given the size of the
audience of most of the Primedia publications.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deal with Primedia, CMGI will receive 8 million Primedia
shares in exchange for 1.53 million of its own shares. CMGI
introduced a venture capital fund in January of $1 billion to focus
on companies that offer Internet technologies and infrastructure.
CMGI and Primedia will fund new internet entities focused on
categories including construction and digital entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media will invest $200 million in cash in exchange for
the 5 percent stake and 1.5 million warrants, which will allow
Liberty to purchase 1.5 million shares of Primedia stock at $25 a
share over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Digital, the interactive television and internet company
owned by Liberty Media, also received an option to buy a 12.5
percent stake in Primedia Broadband Video, a new unit of the
company; Primedia, in exchange, will purchase $25 million of
Liberty Digital stock. Liberty and Primedia will work specifically
on developing interactive video. Primedia already owns video
properties like Channel One, the television news channel provided
on video to high schools around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took over as chairman in September, Rogers, the former
president of NBC cable, has implemented plans to generate
e-commerce off the magazines' Web sites and to put the company's
video properties to use on the Internet. He has exchanged
advertising in the magazines for equity in new-media ventures like
Digital Media Online, PrintCafe.com and BabyPressConference.com.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Rainbow Media Holdings, the division of
Cablevision that produces MetroChannels, announced an agreement
with New York magazine, owned by Primedia, to create an Internet
site. The agreement will allow content from New York magazine to
appear on MetroChannels.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have responded with enthusiasm Thursday to Rogers'
plans. The stock jumped $6.375 a share, or 24 percent, to $33.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
