<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN31-COX     03-30 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALKS ON ELIAN GONZALEZ EXTENDED AGAIN
 &HT;    With ELIAN-GORE, ELIAN-CONGRESS and ELIAN-RENO.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A tense Miami edged away from the brink of explosive
protests Thursday as federal officials again extended a deadline on
Elian Gonzalez's immigration status and discussed a possible visit
by the boy's Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can anyone really doubt that the time has come for this boy to
be reunited with his father?'' said Gregory Craig, a Washington
attorney who represents the father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Craig consulted with State Department officials Thursday and
said he intends to apply for a visa that would allow Gonzalez to
come to the United States. It was unclear how soon the visit might
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives and federal
immigration officials held eight hours of negotiations over the
6-year-old boy's fate, but reached no agreement. They will resume
their talks Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration officials, who had already extended a deadline
for revoking Elian's permission to remain in the country until
Friday, set a new deadline of 9 a.m. ET Tuesday and said Elian
would be allowed to stay with his Miami relatives until at least
then.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials want the Miami family to pledge that they will
turn the boy over if they lose their federal court fight to keep
him in this country. The family has so far refused, saying they
want to keep open the possibility of taking the legal battle to a
Florida family court once their federal appeals have been
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   But the possible visit of Juan Gonzalez overshadowed other
developments Thursday. A spokesman for the Miami relatives said
they would welcome Elian's father to their home, but did not say
whether they would turn the boy over to him.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unclear how Miami's volatile Cuban exiles would
react to such a visit. Elian has become a symbol of their deep
hatred for Cuban leader Fidel Castro, and exile groups Thursday
practiced forming a human chain to block the boy from being removed
from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   One exile activist said protesters would allow Elian's father to
visit the boy in the Little Havana home of his Miami relatives, but
didn't say whether they would allow the boy to leave with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will tell everybody to stand aside and let that visit
happen,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez, leader of the Democracy Action
group. ``This is a family issue, and we want them to have the
chance to sit down and talk it out as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was still unclear Thursday whether the visit of Elian's
father would actually take place. In announcing the proposal late
Wednesday, Castro said he wanted to send a 31-person entourage with
Gonzalez, including Elian's teacher, classmates and a team of
psychologists who would help the boy readapt to life with his Cuban
family.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said the group would live at the home of a top Cuban
diplomat near Washington, remaining there until the federal court
case over the issue was resolved. A hearing in the case has been
set for May 8 at the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro insisted the visit would only take place if U.S.
officials promised they would put Elian in his father's custody for
the duration of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible stumbling block was the size of the entourage.
State Department officials said Thursday that while they could
process Gonzalez's visa application quickly, visas for the rest of
the entourage would have to go through normal channels, which could
take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's saga has now lasted more than four months. He was found
floating in an inner tube at sea on Thanksgiving Day, after his
mother and 10 other people drowned as they attempted to flee Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials decided in January that he should be returned
to his family in Cuba, but the Miami relatives who have cared for
Elian since he was rescued filed a federal lawsuit to block that
decision. Last week a Miami federal judge ruled against them, but
the family immediately filed an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case continued to make waves outside South Florida, as Vice
President Al Gore broke with the administration's position
Thursday. Florida is the nation's fourth most populous state, and
Cuban-Americans make up a significant block of voters.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration supports sending Elian back to
Cuba, Gore said he supports legislation that would grant permanent
resident status to the boy and his Cuban family _ a position
similar to that of his likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us be clear that the real fault in this case lies with the
oppressive regime of Fidel Castro,'' the vice president said in a
statement. Elian should never have been forced to choose between
freedom and his own father. Now we must take action, here on our
own shores, to make sure that Elian's best interests are served.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams's e-mail address is mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
