A2667 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACKS-NI     03-30 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACKS-NIX-GOP-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GULF BETWEEN BLACKS AND GOP NOT BEING CROSSED ANYTIME SOON  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VERNON JARRETT  
 &HT;    Nobody wants to publicly admit it, but the Republican Party can
forget about reaping the benefits of the black vote in the first
presidential election of this new millennium.
 &HT;    Come November 2000, African-Americans _ regardless of social
class or region _ will probably vote for Vice President Al Gore in
overwhelming percentages.
 &HT;    Although blacks have appeared as incorrigible Democrats since
the second term of President Franklin D. Roosevelt, the current
crystallization of black attitudes has been decades in the making.
In the minds of a large majority of black voters, the image of
present-day Republican leadership has become near permanently
etched as ``the enemy.''
 &HT;    In the old days, the black man's true enemies were Southern
Democrats, and their Northern allies, who were willing to maintain
or tolerate Jim Crow at any cost. The Southern-based enemy was
adamantly opposed to any governmental interference that might
assure equal voting rights, equal access to education, fair
employment, fair housing or even protection from lynch mobs.
 &HT;    Back then, blacks considered the word ``enemy'' as synonymous
with ``Southern Democrat.''
 &HT;    Even when Northern politicians of good will occupied the White
House, the Senate, the House of Representatives or the U.S. Supreme
Court, their private sentiments were consistently nullified by a
deference to Southern Democrats. Consequently, the horrendous lynch
mob activity of the 1920s never resulted in the passage of an
anti-lynching bill.
 &HT;    Yet, since Roosevelt's New Deal of the 1930s and 1940s blacks
have made great strides under the administrations of Presidents
Harry S. Truman, Lyndon B. Johnson, Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton _
all Southern Democrats.
 &HT;    Step by step, the GOP's counter southern strategy has wrought
success. It broke up the ``Solid South'' by giving conservative
Democrats a new identity. Meet the New Southern Republican, who can
now work shamelessly in open concert in right-wing crusades that
cross all regional boundaries.
 &HT;    The heart of this political dynamic is not confined to the
right-to-life crusades against abortion, or the end of big
government and the cessation of big taxes. Slap dab in the middle
is the right to contain _ if not stop _ any further concessions or
``giveaways'' to blacks.
 &HT;    Stopping affirmative action is central to the Republican appeal.
Even when it tries to soften that goal by displaying a few blacks
in upfront positions, the strategy is in motion.
 &HT;    Time after time, at crucial moments, the Republican strategy has
been to send a clear, not-so-subtle message to the white South,
which declares: ``We sympathize with you on the race issue.'' Here
is a chronology for that message, which could not be missed by any
knowledgeable black.
 &HT;    When Gov. Ronald Reagan, patron saint of Republicanism, launched
his southern crusade for the presidency, he chose little
Philadelphia, Miss., to kickoff his drive.
 &HT;    Philadelphia's only previous claim to fame was providing a site
for the 1964 murder of three youthful civil workers: James E.
Chaney, a black, Michael H. Schwerner and Andrew Goodman, both
white.
 &HT;    When Richard Nixon announced his presidential bid in the
Midwest, he chose Pontiac, Mich., which had gained recent notoriety
by the highly publicized burning of integration-bound schoolbuses.
 &HT;    Who tried to scare the daylights out of white folks with the
likes of imprisoned killer Willie Horton turned loose to roam your
streets? None other than strategists for Vice President George
Bush, a group that used race to catapult Bush into the White House.
 &HT;    When in this new millennium Gov. George W. Bush chose Bob Jone's
University to launch his South Carolina campaign for the
presidency, he was not breaking ground. He merely was following
suit. His willing presence at the university was a proclamation.
 &HT;    After the Bob Jones scenario, it was patently evident that Bush
would chose ``neutrality'' on the Confederate flag flying over
South Carolina's capitol dome, thereby offering fresh solace to
this homage to slavery and racism.
 &HT;    Bush and all GOP presidential candidates simply acted out the
New Republican Tradition on Race.
 &HT;    It is racially offensive to suggest that African-Americans do
not see or understand what is going on. Don't be misled by the few
cheerful black faces occasionally seen on the evening news nodding
agreement with Republican speakers.
 &HT;    I have never seen any candidate for the presidency, however
repugnant his advocacy, who could not find a black supporter. But
last week I welcomed one hint of resistance from within the GOP as
I watched CNN's television coverage of California's black
anti-affirmative action campaigner Ward Connerly in Dallas.
 &HT;    Answering a question from his near all-white audience, Connerly
conceded that Congress' lone black Republican, Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, disagreed with Connerly's campaign, calling it ill-timed.
 &HT;    So, let us give thanks for even microscopic concessions to
reality. However, the die is cast because the GOP has too many
promises to keep with former Democrats.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (VERNON JARRETT is an active member of the National Advisory
Board of the Rosa and Raymond Parks Pathways to Freedom Program for
Youths. In 1991 he received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the
National Association of Black Journalists.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Vernon Jarrett 
