<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-HISPANIC-VEEP?-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKET TO RIDE?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By PATRICIA GUADALUPE  
 &HT;    Energy Secretary Bill Richardson is the highest-ranking Hispanic
in the Clinton Administration.
 &HT;    A former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations and New Mexico
congressman, he helped secure congressional approval of the North
American Free Trade Agreement.
 &HT;    Lately, he's been using his international contacts to press for
lower oil prices worldwide.
 &HT;    Richardson also is helping with Hispanic outreach for the Gore
for President campaign, and his name has been bandied about as a
possible vice-presidential candidate on the Gore ticket.
 &HT;    Here, he talks about politics and other matters.
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;     Q:  Is the country ready for a Hispanic vice president?
 &HT;     A:  Yes, absolutely. The American public is ready to accept a
Hispanic candidate. I think it would not only be a pleasant
surprise, it would be right on target and make sense.
 &HT;    If it doesn't happen in this election, it'll happen in the next.
But I won't speculate that I will be the one. It's a presidential
candidate's call. I'm not campaigning for the job. I don't think I
would be the only one to be considered.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  What are some of the things you are doing as part of the
Gore campaign's outreach efforts within the Hispanic community?
 &HT;     A:  We have a group of Hispanic leaders and legislators,
Ganamos con Gore, and we have been meeting to get a strong
organization going in support of the vice president. He has good
support in the Hispanic community, but Bush and McCain have a
greater impact on the Hispanic community than other Republican
candidates.
 &HT;    I think we are going to win, but what we don't want is for the
Republicans to get more than 30 percent of the vote. If that
happens, it could negatively affect our numbers in several states.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Are you worried about the Republican candidates' appeal in
the Hispanic community?
 &HT;     A:  Yes, because Bush and McCain have run in states with large
Hispanic populations. They've been successful in appealing to
Hispanics and they haven't acted like other Republican candidates
who have been totally negative toward the Latino community. It's a
challenge.
 &HT;    The main challenge is making sure that their percentage of the
Latino vote doesn't rise. (The GOP's all-time high of 40 percent of
the Hispanic vote occurred with President Reagan in 1984.)
 &HT;    If the Republican candidate gets 40 percent of the vote, for
instance, that would be a serious problem for the Democratic Party,
because it would be in key states for us, like California, Florida,
Texas, Illinois, New York.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  The meetings that you are involved in with Ganamos con Gore
_ how are you developing a strategy targeted to the Hispanic
community?
 &HT;     A:  We've been traveling all over the place _ New Hampshire,
Iowa, California, New York. There are many members of the group who
are working as volunteers in those and other states.
 &HT;    Part of our plan is to organize every state and to also do some
fund raising for the campaign. And I'm not just talking about
getting elected officials involved. We want to have a real
grassroots campaign, and we're working to appeal to the younger
generation in our community, with issues like the global economy
and technology.
 &HT;    We also are talking to the community about a whole range of
issues, not just about ``Latino issues'' like civil rights and
bilingual education. Those are important issues, but we also talk
about mainstream issues, like the federal budget, defense, Social
Security, the economy. It's very important to talk about mainstream
issues as well as the issues we always talk about.
 &HT;    The Hispanic community is not homogeneous and not concentrated
on the same issues. The community is interested in a whole range of
issues.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  The Clinton administration has an almost eight-year-old
record in the Hispanic community. So why do you think that some
polls show Bush with greater support over Gore in the Hispanic
community?
 &HT;     A:  The polls I've seen show Gore ahead of Bush. The important
thing is the margin of victory. Bush is going to be a challenge, as
would McCain. What is key is to not take the Hispanic vote for
granted. We have to be really aggressive as far as getting the
Hispanic vote is concerned.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  How do you even find the time to do this, with all the work
as energy secretary at the same time?
 &HT;     A:  Of course I don't have all the time I would like. But I'm
not the only person involved in reaching out to the Latino
community for the vice president. I'm probably the main one, but of
course not the only one.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Speaking of your day job, you recently unveiled a
departmental initiative to increase the number of Hispanics working
in the science field.
 &HT;     A:  We have a program to try to increase the number of Hispanic
scientists. We are working with several universities that have a
significant Latino population, and with groups that work with
Hispanic students, such as the Hispanic Association of Colleges and
Universities, establishing internships and scholarship programs.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Patricia Guadalupe is a contributing editor to Hispanic
Business magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business magazine 
