<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNDATIONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Community groups face competition from nonprofits for foundation
funds
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a record level of foundation giving,
community groups say they are scrambling for their share of the
funding pie.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound contradictory, given that the nation's
foundations shelled out 17 percent more last year than they did in
1998 _ nearly $23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But community organizations say they are competing against a
growing number of nonprofit groups for the same dollars. And they
are facing an environment where foundations are targeting their
donations for specific causes.
</P>
<P>
   Where foundations once gave to social service organizations,
they are increasingly giving to groups that address narrow issues
such as building homes for the homeless or providing computer
training in inner city schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not this plethora of new money out there,'' said Rick
McKelvey, vice president for development of the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra. ``Most community organizations are working harder than
ever to get a smaller share of funding.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason foundations are targeting their funding is to achieve
greater impact, said Sara Engelhardt, president of the Foundation
Center, a New York-based nonprofit organization that tracks
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many big social issues out there that any one
foundation is a relatively small piece of the answer,'' Engelhardt
said. ``So foundations try to bite off the piece that they think
will have the most impact.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation is giving
$750 million over five years to vaccinate children in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But a reduction in government funding is another reason why
community groups are finding such a competitive environment,
Engelhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Jackson-Randolph, artistic director of Atlanta-based
Jomandi Productions, felt that hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based theater production company saw its funding
from the National Endowment of the Arts sliced in half over the
last four years. That, coupled with a loss in revenue, has left the
theater group with a $250,000 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that there is more money available than ever
before, yet so little spent on arts, Jackson-Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more money out there, but we are fighting to keep art
and culture in our lives,'' she said. ``There is a mentality out
there that arts and culture should be marginalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Causes such as improving education and revitalizing communities
should be funded, she said, but not at the expense of supporting
art and culture.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of nonprofits increasing by some 30,000 each
year, organizations must constantly search for new funding sources,
said Mark O'Connell, president of the United Way of Metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell understands why foundations are targeting their funds
for specific causes. He sees that they can have a greater impact.
But he worries that some foundations are limiting their donations
to groups that bring them greater name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to be a public relations grant, rather than a
community betterment grant,'' O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell is concerned that a number of foundations no longer
follow the creed of Robert W. Woodruff: ``There's no limit to what
a man can accomplish, or the good he can do, if he doesn't care who
gets the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture is changing,'' O'Connell said. ``It used to be
that you didn't give to look good, you gave to do good. Now they
want to do good and look good.''
</P>
<P>
   If nonprofits are going to be successful, they are going to have
to diversify their funding sources, said Alicia Philipp, president
of the Community Foundation for Greater Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that community groups appeal to individuals rather
than relying on foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the worry over funding, Philipp said, the good news is
that there is more money out there. ``A rising tide lifts more
boats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
