<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DABRAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DaBrat not the target of gunmen
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _A barrage of bullets fired at a limousine in the
parking lot of a Buckhead apartment complex this month was not
intended for Atlanta-based rapper Da Brat, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all just a terrible coincidence,'' said Sgt. Rick
Chambers of the Atlanta Police Department's guns unit. ``The
bullets were intended for someone else. It just so happened it was
in the apartment complex where she lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Several residents at the Post Chastain Apartments were shaken
from their beds in the wee hours of March 12 when a succession of
bullets was fired at a black Toyota stretch limousine trying to
make its way out of the apartment complex on Roswell Road.
</P>
<P>
   The complex is where Shawntae Harris, known as Da Brat, lived
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   At first, police speculated the assault was retaliation aimed at
Harris. But on Wednesday, Chambers said the attack was drug-related
and meant for someone else. The targeted person may not have been
in the limo, Chambers said. Detectives would not identify that
person.
</P>
<P>
   Occupants of the vehicle that morning said they went to the
complex to drop off one of the passengers whose boyfriend lives at
the 10-building property.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants _ two masked men in a silver late-model Ford
Thunderbird _ shot at the limousine 13 times, police said. Five of
the nine passengers were hit, including the driver, who bolted from
the limousine and jumped in a patch of woods adjacent to the
property. The shooters have not been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Carmille Plummer, one of those injured, said she and her friends
had gone to a birthday party at a private house nearby. They were
calling it a night and driving one of the women in their group to
Post Chastain. Plummer said neither she nor any of the other
passengers knew Harris lived in the building adjacent to the one
where they had left the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the incident, police at the scene said the
shooting was most likely payback for Harris. The 25-year-old rapper
had gotten into a brawl with another woman March 7 at the Buckhead
nightspot Chili Pepper. A police lieutenant taking statements from
the passengers said one of the victims told him they knew Harris
and that the shooters probably thought she was in the car. The next
day, investigators said the passengers claimed they did not know
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper, who moved from the complex three days after the
shooting, was in Cancun, Mexico, when the gunfire erupted. In Miami
this week after filming a new video in Mexico, Harris told The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution she was somewhat puzzled by the
incident, but had not thought about it much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what happened?'' Harris mused. ``You would have to
ask the people who did it _ if they ever catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why she had left Post Chastain, where she had lived
in a comfortable townhouse, the singer replied: ``My family moved
me. They did it for my safety. And I love them for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Charged with aggravated battery in the Chili Pepper fight,
Harris is scheduled to appear in Atlanta Municipal Court on April
13, the day before her 26th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
