<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-JUANCARLOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO VICTIM SOUGHT BETTER LIFE IN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHELLE MELENDEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Juan Carlos Oseguera bought his first truck
two weeks ago, and already he had vacuumed and washed it twice. He
liked nice things.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Oseguera was at work at Cici's Pizza in Lake Worth
when a deadly tornado roared through the area. As he ran outside to
move his shiny black Mazda LX to safety, a softball-size hailstone
struck his head. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He died Wednesday without regaining consciousness. He was 19.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, his nieces and nephews were using the truck as a
jungle gym, climbing in and out of the cab and bed while their
mourning parents talked about their little brother, Carlitos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of those people who, everything had to look nice.
He'd vacuum his car out twice a week, and he wouldn't let his shirt
get dirty at work. His favorite thing to wear was his black,
steel-toe boots, black pants and yellow shirt,'' said his
girlfriend, Jennifer Mallett.
</P>
<P>
   In his small, immaculate apartment behind his stepsister and
brother's house in north Fort Worth, Oseguera kept an ironing
board, black shoe polish, a brand new pair of soccer cleats still
in the box and a backpack full of schoolwork. In a note to himself,
he said he wanted to help his peers, and he underlined the acronym
``TAAS'' four times, indicating his goal of passing the state test
to obtain his high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very studious and responsible,'' said his sister, Maria
Fidelina, 26, with whom he lived for two years in Arlington after
immigrating from Honduras. Fidelina, as her family calls her, moved
to Colorado Springs with her husband three weeks ago and asked
Oseguera to go with her.
</P>
<P>
   But he decided to stay in Fort Worth with a stepsister, Lilian
Ayala, and his oldest brother, Antonio Marcos Oseguera.
</P>
<P>
   All the siblings were born in the mountainous, banana
tree-shaded town of Omonita San Manuel Cortes near El Progreso in
northwestern Honduras. Oseguera has five brothers and sisters
remaining at home with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wanted something better in life, and we always said,
all of us together could help our parents more,'' said his brother
Jose, 21, who lives in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the family must return his body to his birthplace.
Paramedics said Oseguera's skull was shattered. His stepsister and
girlfriend stayed with him through the night and day until he died
about 3 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is inconsolable,'' Fidelina said. ``He was her
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett, 16, said her relationship with Oseguera was secret at
first. But over the past three months, they had begun spending time
together at her house. She said they had also begun talking about
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lilian said he stayed here because of me,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An account has been established at Texas Bank to help with the
cost of returning Oseguera's body to Honduras. Donations may be
made to the Juan Carlos Fund, Account No. 2620003448, and will
accepted at any branch or by mail at Texas Bank, 300 W. Seventh
St., Fort Worth 76102.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
