<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ELIAN-GORE-HNS &LR;      03-30 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE SUPPORTS KEEPING CUBAN BOY IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Breaking with President Clinton and Attorney
General Janet Reno, Vice President Al Gore urged Congress Thursday
to pass a law that would allow the fate of Elian Gonzalez to be
decided by a family court and not by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning move, Gore, the presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee, took a position similar to that of his
Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the case of the
6-year-old Cuban boy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said Elian's case ``is a matter that should be decided
</P>
<P>
   by courts that have the experience and expertise to resolve
custody cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In a quick response, Bush said, ``I'm glad the vice president
has seen the wisdom'' of going to a state family court rather than
a federal immigration proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he ought to do is convince the attorney general and the
president to accept the same position. ... We'll see what kind of
influence he has in this administration.''The White House and
Justice Department had no comment on Gore's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's action and Bush's reaction reflected the explosive
political nature of the case and the importance of Florida, the
country's fourth largest state, in this fall's presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore blamed ``the oppressive regime'' of Cuban leader Fidel
Castro for the controversy surrounding the case, but many in the
Cuban-American community in south Florida have accused the Clinton
administration of mishandling the case.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was one of three survivors of a shipwreck in which his
mother, her boyfriend and nine others drowned when their boat sank
as they were trying to flee Cuba for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gore urged Congress to pass a law that would grant permanent
resident status to Elian and his father, stepmother, half-brother,
grandmothers and grandfather from Cuba, ``so that the case can be
adjudicated properly.''Such legislation has been introduced by Sen.
Bob Graham, D-Fla. A similar bill has been filed by Rep. Robert
Menendez, D-N.J. Moving toward his current position, Gore has said
previously he felt the case would be best resolved in a Florida
family court. Bush supports similar legislation introduced by
Graham's colleague, Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who also said
Thursday that the vice president should persuade Clinton and Reno
to change their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, on Thursday
applied for a visa to allow him to travel from Cuba to the United
States to take custody of his son. His move came as Immigration and
Naturalization Service officials failed to reach an agreement with
the boy's Miami relatives over how to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, lawyer for the Juan Gonzalez, said in Washington
that Elian's father was ``ready at a moment's notice'' to fly to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he will only come if he has assurances that he will have
custody of his son when he leaves,'' Craig said. ``The time is long
overdue for Elian to be with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, speaking at her weekly news conference at the
Justice Department, Reno declined to discuss what officials would
do if the boy's father travels to the United States.``I don't deal
in what-ifs,'' she told reporters. Since being rescued as he was
floating on an inner tube in the ocean on Nov. 25, Elian has been
living in Miami with his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, who has said
he would be willing to release Elian to his father if Juan Gonzalez
came to Florida from Cuba. Lazaro Gonzalez has repeatedly said he
would not deliver the boy to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently calling the great-uncle's bluff, Cuban President
Fidel Castro said Wednesday that not only would the father go to
the United States but would stay during the entire court process as
the Miami relatives appeal federal orders to surrender custody of
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Cuban government released a list of 31 people
who would accompany Juan Gonzalez, including his wife and their
6-month-old son _ Elian's half brother. The list included Ricardo
Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly and Castro's point
man on American affairs, who was listed as an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Reno called for calm in Miami's Cuban-American community _ where
many demonstrations have taken place since Elian's arrival _ but
she refused to back away from her decision to return Elian Gonzalez
to Cuba and his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a community I was born in, and raised in,'' she said at
the news conference. ``It's a community I love, and when it's
hurting, it hurts me.''Reno said she would continue to negotiate
with the Elian's Miami relatives for a ``cooperative'' agreement
that would decide the fate of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But she reiterated that the family and Miami's Cuban-American
community must respect the ``rule of law'' and abide by the ruling
of a federal district court that last week upheld the INS' decision
to return the boy to Cuba and his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been heartbreaking for everybody involved, but
we believe the law is clear,'' she said. ``The father must speak
for the little boy because there is a sacred bond that must be
honored and the boy must be reunited with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   INS officials had set a deadline of 9 a.m. Friday for an
agreement to be reached that would provide the government with
assurances that the Miami family members would give up the boy
should they lose their next court battle. The INS had threatened to
revoke Elian's temporary parole, or permission to stay in the
United States, and begin steps to deport the boy to Cuba if an
agreement wasn't reached by that time.
</P>
<P>
   But after daylong negotiations, the two sides agreed to postpone
that deadline until 9 a.m. next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the federal government is prepared ultimately to
enforce law, Reno replied, ``You bet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During her news conference, Reno also took offense at comments
by Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas and other South Florida mayors
that they would hold President Clinton and Reno responsible if
violence broke out over the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I know in the Cuban community came to this country
and have contributed so much to it because they believe in the rule
of law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the INS announcement that it may revoke Elian's parole, a
growing crowd has gathered in front of the boy's home in Little
Havana to protest the government's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government is provoking the community,'' Pensalas
said at rally in Miami. ``We do not condone inappropriate behavior.
But I have a responsibility to tell the federal government when
they've gone too far and they've gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Penelas and other mayors also have said that local law
enforcement officers would not assist federal authorities in
``repatriating the boy.'' However, the Miami mayor did give
assurances that local police would make sure that the protesters
``did not get out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
