<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-TRENDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINTER RESORTS SEARCHING FOR NEXT NEW THING
</HEADLINE>
  (mg)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when skiers have gotten used to a six-pack _ the six-seater
chairlift that scoops six people up at once _ along comes plans for
an eight-pack. And just when they learned to ski around big, noisy
snowmaking guns, along comes interest in making thousands of little
guns that would spread out like a sprinkling system.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of efforts by winter resorts to keep skiers and
snowboarders coming to the slopes. Fickle weather and swings in the
stock market make that job all the harder. Even with a brisk
economy, skier and snowboarder visits _ a universal quantifier
based on daily lift ticket usage _ have hovered at the 50 million
mark for nearly a decade. Who among the industry managers has an
idea for breaking up the ice?
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives are focusing on the personal likes and
dislikes of their guests, on and off the slopes. Others are banking
on the next generation, the children of the post-war baby boomers _
the so-called echo boomers. Many are preteen-agers and teen-agers
who thrive on skiing and snowboarding, skateboarding, inline
skating and motocross racing, all in the extreme sports genre.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few views of trends in the skiing industry as
expressed in telephone interviews with the management at four of
the largest resort companies in North America:
</P>
<P>
   Les Otten, American Skiing Co., Bethel, Maine.: Lack of snow
during the December holidays cut into the busiest time of the
season for American Skiing Co. So did Year 2000 computer worries,
which Otten, chairman of the company that owns nine ski resorts
nationwide, believes kept skiers at home. In the future, he sees
such short-term vagaries having less impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes through for the future is an extraordinarily strong
trend in young people entering the sport of skiing and
snowboarding,'' Otten said. ``I think we'll see the trend continue
on over the horizon, and that's going to have a very positive
effect. It's the clearest bright spot that we can easily
identify.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gillet Jr., Booth Creek Holdings, Vail, Colo.: Gillet is
counting on the increasing importance of what he calls the boutique
ski areas _ those small-town, mostly out-of-the-way places that
develop a personality. Gillet's group owns eight resorts, including
Grand Targhee, Wyo., which it bought just recently, partly because
it is one of those destination resorts.
</P>
<P>
   He said that capital expenditures at ski areas _ such as adding
chairlifts, gondolas, restaurants and lodges _ is less important
than improving amenities. ``Capital expenditure was king, but now
the guest is back in,'' Gillet said. ``It's a total integration of
golfing, skiing, great food and hotels. I call it retro _ it may be
a little harder to get to such places, but people will probably
stay a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Pitoniak, Intrawest, Vancouver, British Columbia: Pitoniak
believes that the new generation will bring a change in style. The
industry estimates that half of all 16-year-olds who go to mountain
resorts are on snowboards rather than skis; that compares to
snowboarders of all ages making up about 23 percent of all skier
visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the choices in the last 10 years, especially for
girls, have been team sports,'' said Pitoniak, whose company owns
10 ski resorts. ``Now it's action sports. The kids live these
intense lives at school Monday through Friday, and on the weekends,
they just want to tear the lid off and let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Tebo, Boyne USA, Boyne Falls, Mich.: People want
alternatives in their holiday, said Tebo, whose company owns five
ski resorts. Access to the Internet in particular makes it more
difficult for resorts to attract skiers; with one or two clicks of
a mouse, a person can instantly find another place if they do not
like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the trend is going to be that people will look at us
on a daily basis to see what we're offering on any one day,'' he
said. ``We are a society who changes its minds constantly. We are
in the entertainment business now, not fitness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
