<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-HAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE HAIL DEATH OCCURRED DURING TEXAS TWISTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Defying odds, the storm that struck this
city Tuesday night caused one death and one injury from hail.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Oseguera, 19, died Wednesday from the head injury he
got from baseball-size hail produced by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   One of four people confirmed dead, Oseguera &UR;  &LR; was attempting to
move his truck outside the fast-food restaurant where he worked
when he was struck. Two of the people killed in the storm died from
falling debris and a third drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Studies cited by the National Weather Service show that while
hail causes more property damage yearly than any other natural
disaster, it results in fewer than five deaths nationally each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost surprising that it doesn't'' kill more people,
said Bill Proenza, southern regional director for the National
Weather Service in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider that a hailstone the size of a baseball is
harder than that baseball and is traveling at 100 mph plus, it's
not surprising that it could kill someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Proenza cited a study at the University of Oklahoma that shows
tornadoes cause 125 deaths annually; lightning, 110; flash floods,
165; and hail, ``fewer than 5.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, people can make it to shelter,'' said Proenza.
</P>
<P>
   David Johnson, 70, couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   When the storm struck, Johnson was working in the yard of his
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always heard the bathtub was the safest place to get in a
tornado and that's where I was headed when the hail struck,'' he
said. ``It was about golf-ball size, and it knocked me around.
Then, the west wall of my house fell over on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson received head injuries and bruises as a combination of
the hail and the collapsed wall. He was in good condition Thursday
at Harris Hospital and expected to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And, as search and rescue operations ended Thursday, city
officials said no further victims of the storms had been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We searched 10 of the major buildings without finding
anyone,'' said Fire &UR;  &LR; Chief &UR;  &LR; Larry McMillen. ``The search team
members have been sent home.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials estimate that up to $450 million in
damage was caused by two tornadoes that swept through this
metropolitan area of 1.3 million people, hitting hardest in
downtown Fort Worth and nearby neighborhoods in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   McMillen said the assessment of damage remained unchanged
Thursday, with eight commercial structures destroyed, 27 with major
damage and 15 with minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cash America Building, the most extensively damaged office
building in the city, appeared to be a loss, said the chief. ``I'm
not an engineer, but I'd guess it will have to be demolished.''
</P>
<P>
   The building housed an FBI office, which lost many of its
documents when they were blown out the sixth-floor window. About 20
FBI agents wearing disposable gloves sifted through scraps of
debris, searching for sensitive files.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we don't know if we lost sensitive files,'' FBI
spokeswoman Lori Bailey told The Associated Press. ``It's hard to
say if this will jeopardize cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McMillen said a countywide assessment of
residential damage in Fort Worth, Arlington and other communities
showed 101 homes destroyed, 206 with major damage and 808 with
minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   No estimate had been made of the monetary damage to residences.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr said he believed the downtown
area, part of which remained closed Thursday, will be
``functional'' by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that, I don't mean all the offices will be operating,''
said Barr. ``I mean people should be able to get into those
buildings and begin repairing the damage inside.''
</P>
<P>
