<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OPERA-QUIZ-KIDS-ART-2     03-30 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-QUIZ-KIDS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO ARE THE OPERA WHIZ KIDS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Texas, Conn., N.Y.)  ART ADV: A photo, NYT7, has been sent to New York Times photo
clients. Subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you tune in Saturday afternoon to the Texaco Opera
Quiz, the popular intermission feature that is part of the live
radio broadcasts of the Metropolitan Opera, don't be surprised if
the three panelists sound rather young to be experts.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Speight, 15, is a sophomore in the vocal music department
of the High School for the Performing and Visual Arts in Houston.
Mahan Esfahani, 16, a classical pianist and theater enthusiast, is
a junior at Richard Montgomery High School in Rockville, Md. Evan
Diamond, 17, a senior from East Meadow High School in New York who
plays saxophone in his school jazz band, has become an opera
enthusiast through taking college-level Italian courses.
</P>
<P>
   If these students are not yet experts, they are at least
experts-in-training. They are the Texaco Quiz Kids, as the
producers of the broadcasts are calling this first-ever panel of
high school students. Their knowledge and suitability have been
tested through a series of regional competitions in the New York,
Houston and Washington areas. A total of 57 students from 18
schools competed. Three semifinalists were selected in each region.
Final rounds in the three cities produced the three panelists who
will be on the air tomorrow during the second intermission of
Wagner's ``Walkure.'' (The quiz should start about 3:35 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   These panelists will hold the same seats once occupied by such
renowned authorities and raconteurs as the conductor Boris
Goldovsky, the critic and translator Andrew Porter and the
mezzo-soprano Marilyn Horne.
</P>
<P>
   For making it to the panel, each student has won a crystal
trophy; gift certificates to Texaco's online store; a parcel of
CDs; a free trip to New York for themselves, a parent and a
teacher; seats in the Texaco box for Saturday's performance; a
private backstage tour of the Met; tickets to ``Kiss Me Kate'' on
Broadway; and, of course, the experience of being a panelist on the
quiz program, heard by millions of opera buffs on more than 325
stations in North America, Australia, New Zealand, Brazil and 27
European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The producer of the intermissions features, Michael Bronson,
thinks presenting what he expects to become an annual Texaco Quiz
Kids panel is a logical step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original mission statement from Texaco when the company
started sponsoring the broadcasts in 1940 was that the intermission
features should be entertaining and informative,'' Bronson said.
``One area I felt we could do better with was in making listeners
aware of the importance of music education: that young people can
and do enjoy opera. This is critical if we are going to have people
sitting in the seats 20 or 30 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronson said that his office often receives letters and quiz
questions from listeners seeking advice on how to introduce opera
to children. The idea of a student panel grew out of talks among
Bronson; Diane Herzman, who is the manager of the
Texaco-Metropolitan Opera sponsorship; and David Dick, the director
of education for the Metropolitan Opera Guild, which was founded in
1935 and is the oldest outreach department of any American opera
company.
</P>
<P>
   Bronson proudly reported that for the final round in Washington
in February, held at the auditorium of the American Film Institute
in the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, a teacher from a
participating school brought her whole class to see the final
face-off. Esfahani, the winner, was presented his award by Supreme
Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, a big opera fan.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is the first year of the Texaco Quiz Kids project,
the organizers limited the search for panelists. ``The idea was to
reward schools that already included the study of opera, and the
attendance of operas, as part of their curriculums,'' Bronson said.
The Met's Opera Guild has long run such outreach programs, as has
the Houston Grand Opera and the Washington Opera, which is why
those cities were the first selected.
</P>
<P>
   A chance to see how the competition worked came in mid-February,
when the three semifinalists from the New York region assembled for
the showdown at the studios of WQXR in Manhattan, which carries the
opera broadcasts. The oldest regional semifinalist was Ali Kagan,
18, a soft-spoken and articulate woman who attends the Gunnery, a
private school in Washington, Conn. Her musical background is
limited to a few years of flute lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do listen to the opera broadcasts on occasion,'' she said
before the final round started. ``At least when I am not with
friends on Saturday who don't really appreciate opera as much as I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a young opera fan can still brand you among your peers,
she said. This is something the Texaco Quiz Kids project is working
to change.
</P>
<P>
   Kagan was introduced to opera by the teacher who runs the
humanities program at her school, Tom Adolphson, whose dogs are
named Fasolt and Fafner after the giants in Wagner's ``Ring.'' He
organizes regular school trips to dress rehearsals at the Met.
``These kids are closer to this art form than they realize,''
Adolphson said. ``I always tell them that everything they see on
the opera stage in the evening is played out in terms of drama at
the student center every day.''
</P>
<P>
   William Zaientz, 17, is, like Diamond, a student at East Meadow
High. Though he has never studied music formally, he is a budding
opera fan who became interested while doing a research project on
Galileo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that Galileo's father, the composer Vincenzo
Galilei, was a member of the Camerata Florentina, where opera
started,'' he said. Zaientz had never attended an opera until he
went on class trips to Met rehearsals of ``Cavalleria Rusticana''
and ``Pagliacci,'' and ``Rigoletto.'' He was amazed, he said.
``Going there live, not just hearing the music, but seeing the
staging, everything at once, the intense emotions which inspired
the audience, including me _ it was all incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond was introduced to opera through his teacher Frank
McLarney, who runs the foreign languages department at East Meadow
High and has used opera as a teaching tool for his Italian classes
since 1975. ``I was selected to compete for the Opera Quiz panel on
the basis of my Italian studies,'' Diamond said. ``I had come in
second in the United States and Canada in the American Association
of Teachers of Italian exam.'' The students in McLarney's Italian
classes study two librettos each year, coordinated to the Met's
schedule, so that they can attend the operas as well.
nn
</P>
<P>
   The final round for the New York region was essentially a tryout
opera quiz. The three students were seated before microphones in
the radio studio and asked questions by Dick of the Opera Guild.
Seated discreetly behind them were the judges: Thomas Bartunek, the
president of WQXR; Susan Braddock, the president of the
Metropolitan Opera Guild; and Mary Jo Lassen, who teaches
kindergarteners through fifth graders at Public School 314 in
Brooklyn, about opera, the only teacher in the New York City public
school system to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The judges were interested not just in what the students knew,
but also in whether they could share their knowledge with relaxed
enthusiasm. To reduce the tension, the students had been instructed
to focus their preparation on three operas: Mozart's ``Don
Giovanni,'' Donizetti's ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' and Verdi's
``Rigoletto.'' They were also given the first question in advance,
a standard inquiry about how they got into opera and what they
liked about it.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond seemed eager to answer this question. ``Opera is a
classic multimedia art form,'' he said. ``Look at the quartet from
`Rigoletto,' which Victor Hugo greatly admired. Opera is the only
art form that can express what four people are thinking at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaientz, whose subdued manner does not mask his strong opinions,
compared opera favorably to rock videos, which are so popular among
students at his school. ``Music videos are really quite routine,
remedial and emotionally vapid,'' he said. ``Opera is so rich with
excitement and tension. That's the draw for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the prepared question had been dealt with, Kagan was asked
about the types of love relationships in the three operas. She made
some telling points about the superficiality of Don Giovanni's
out-of-control passions, and also discussed the hurtful way Lucia
and her secret beloved are kept apart because of the hatred between
their families, comparing it to the outside pressure on their lives
that students feel today. Diamond was asked how anger and betrayal
play a role in the operas. His answer, in which he described family
betrayals in ``Rigoletto,'' class conflicts in ``Don Giovanni'' and
sectarian rivalries in ``Lucia,'' may have won him the day.
</P>
<P>
   When the questioning ended, the judges retired to another room
to deliberate, and then, with congratulations to all the
contestants, announced that Diamond would be going to the
broadcast. Applause and whoops filled the small room, and everyone
headed to a table of cookies, cheese and soda to celebrate. ``It
was a wonderful experience,'' Kagan confided, ``but I think I'm
relieved that it's Evan and not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's quiz may well be high-pressured. As always, the
questions have been sent in by listeners, but this time they have
been selected with a sensitivity to the abilities of the young
panelists, Bronson said. The questioner Saturday will be the critic
Martin Bernheimer, an avuncular and frequent quiz host, who is good
at getting stumped panelists to relax.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's Texaco Opera Quiz can be heard Saturday afternoon
on the Texaco-Metropolitan Opera International Radio Broadcast of
``Die Walkure,'' by Wagner, at the Metropolitan Opera House. The
opera, starring Jane Eaglen, Deborah Voigt, Hanna Schwarz, Placido
Domingo, James Morris and Eric Halfvarson, begins at 12:30 p.m. The
quiz takes place during the opera's second intermission, starting
around 3:35 p.m. . Information on broadcasts around the United
States and in more than 30 other countries is available at
www.texaco.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
