<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-3TAKE     03-30 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SERIOUS PURSUIT OF TOP COMEDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Heard the one about the homeless guy with the cell
phone? I have. In fact, I've heard it over and over and over again.
(He's homeless _ and he's got a cell phone. Rimshot!) I've also
heard the one about how expensive New York is (it is apparently
quite expensive) and, of course, the one about the guy who can't
get a date (he can't get a date!). In fact, over the course of the
last month, I have heard hundreds of jokes, thousands of near
misses and even a couple of howlers, all perpetrated by the city's
crack corps of comedians.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the sheer number of comics and would-be jokesters,
it only stands to reason that New York is the wisecracking-est
place in the United States. There are nearly a dozen full-time
comedy clubs in the city, and scores of bars and restaurants across
the city regularly open their back rooms to those peculiar men and
women whose sole mission in life is to spread the joy of laughter _
and to book a spot on Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in many ways the city's comedy circuit is in something
of a renaissance after years of losing its talent to sitcoms and
its audience to television. Older clubs like Caroline's have been
joined by newcomers like the Upright Citizens Brigade Theater and
P.S. NBC, which give performance time to downtown acts that
challenge the traditional idea of what comedy should be. And where
it should be, for that matter. There are, no kidding, a weekly
comedy show set in a laundry (``Spin Cycle Comedy'' on Wednesdays)
and one in the back of a Times Square hamburger place (Gladys
Comedy Room in Hamburger Harry's). Even Soho, so serious, so chic,
has a regular comedy night, played out in Circa Tabac, a handsome
smoky lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who enjoyed the show,'' John Mooney, a Tabac regular,
told the audience, ``throw their Prada bags.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Kinds of Clubs
</P>
<P>
   The clubs in Manhattan fall into two categories: mainstream and
alternative. The differences are in price, approach and geography.
Most mainstream clubs, with the exception of the Comedy Cellar and
the Boston Comedy Club, are above 14th Street; most alternative
ones are below. And while uptown clubs generally mean work _ and
some pay _ for comics, downtown clubs generally just mean play.
</P>
<P>
   For cautious people, mainstream clubs like Caroline's, the
Comedy Cellar or the Comic Strip Live are probably the best places
to start. They are almost always a sure thing on the weekends,
stocked with professionals who can make pretty much anybody laugh,
and they have the added advantage of well-lubricated,
ready-to-giggle audiences. Not surprisingly, those clubs are also
the most expensive; you can expect to spend $25 to $50 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown acts are much cheaper, with nominal cover charges and
no drink minimums. The talent downtown is also more hit or miss.
(See the ``Sloopy'' incident below.) At the same time, downtown
jokesters are often far more experimental and intellectual than the
``take my wife'' comics, who still exist in older clubs. And the
crowds are younger, prettier and often tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody here like impressions?'' asks the slacker comic Sean
Conroy at a Monday night show at Luna Lounge on the Lower East
Side. ``OK, how about Impressionism?''
</P>
<P>
   In between the alternative and the mainstream are newer clubs
like Gotham Comedy Club in Chelsea, a sleek joint that has recently
been the home base of the quintessential New York comic, Robert
Klein. It has a young clientele (a lounge and smoking area are
downstairs) and special nights tailored to female, Latino and gay
comedians, a trend mirrored in larger clubs as well. A recent visit
found an appreciative audience for an evening of young female
comics like Laurie Kilmartin and Tina Georgio.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of adventure, I made it my mission to visit each
major club in the city and many of the smaller ones, a journey that
ranged from the hysterical to the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   I saw dozens of comics crack up audiences with observations on
everything from strip clubs (``It's like Thanksgiving; there's a
plate of nice yummy turkey and all you can do is yell at it'') to
the mounted police. (``You're under arrest. Now hop on.'')
</P>
<P>
   Other times I saw comics just crack up. One night in the East
Village I watched as a middle-aged woman wiggled her way through an
interpretive dance to the strains of ``Hang On, Sloopy,'' just
moments after she had described a recent gynecological visit. It
was, unfortunately, an unforgettable experience.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, both uptown and down, the jokes were needlessly
cruel, coming at the expense of gays or ethnic groups or wallowing
in bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious pitfalls of open mikes and closed minds, the
comedy circuit shows plenty of vitality. And like a hobo with a
cell phone, you can find them pretty much anywhere, any night of
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of the Game
</P>
<P>
   There are a few rules that most stand-ups will recognize, if not
obey. Cursing is usually good for a laugh, but cursing alone is not
enough. Never let a heckler get the last word. And always end on a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the look of most mainstream clubs adheres pretty
closely to a brick-wall, ceiling-fan, tiny-stage aesthetic. Oh,
yeah, and lots of comedians' head shots on the wall; it gives a
place character.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are some radical differences in the feel of the
establishments. Caroline's, with classy digs near Times Square and
a swarming staff, has more of a family entertainment feel, with
lots of couples, tourists and well-known comics, like Craig
Shoemaker who waxed comedic on topics from minivans to war movies.
New York Comedy Club, on the other hand, on East 24th Street, is
like the club that time forgot. Pictures behind the bar feature
Johnny Carson, Bob Hope and Robert De Niro in the film ``King of
Comedy.'' Even the dust has dust.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the comics who make their living at it call at all the
clubs, traveling from one to another, sometimes hitting three or
more a night. On a recent Friday night, my brother Gabe and I set
out to emulate this experience as audience members.
</P>
<P>
   First Stop, the Village
</P>
<P>
   The first stop was Boston Comedy Club, a college favorite near
New York University in Greenwich Village. It is the home of the
comic Lewis Schaffer, a bespectacled MC who looks like Jerry Lewis'
long-lost nephew. His business card, which has a quarter taped to
it and the words ``Call Me,'' pretty much sums up his approach,
which also involves constantly denying that he is gay. This
evening's banter was typical.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
