<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-2NDTA     03-30 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: was typical.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Do I seem gay to you?'' Schaffer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhat,'' answered an audience member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' Schaffer responds, seeming concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the audience member says.
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, we entered a crowd of about 25 people seated in
rows around a tiny stage adorned by Schaffer's head shot. It looked
like a self-help meeting of some sort, or perhaps a memorial
service.
</P>
<P>
   But there were more jokes than your usual wake; when we entered,
in fact, there was a guy telling a joke about a babushka.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either a head scarf or a grandmother,'' he says. ``I
don't which. Do you?'' There is no answer.
</P>
<P>
   The next comic, Sherrod Small, seems a little more comfortable
with the crowd. Looking at the decor _ ceiling fans, brick walls,
empty seats _ he commented: ``Look at this place. You can do
anything in here. You can smoke crack in this place and they
wouldn't raise a finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Another comic follows. He tells a joke about a homeless man with
a . . . enough said.
</P>
<P>
   The show's final act is Judah Friedlander, a large man whose
outfit never differs: red baseball cap, heavy dark glasses, blue
jeans. He looks like a redneck intellectual, and he knows it. His
routine goes fairly well but never catches fire. Finally near the
end of the set, he catches a break. A cell phone starts ringing and
the audience member, alarmed, answers it. Friedlander follows
another of comedy's golden rules: Use what you've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' he says, ``Excuse me. What are you doing? Do I
come to your workplace and make phone calls?'' The audience,
semi-somnolent till now, wakes up and laughs heartily.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been so embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   A Real Pro
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was the Comedy Cellar, another Village club with a
good reputation for booking strong acts. Indeed, on this night, the
lineup was strong, led by the MC, Cynthia Koury, a pleasant
patterer who looks a little like Bridget Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's penultimate act was Greer Barnes, a charismatic
black comic with the type of stage ease that separates pros from
the pack. His material is smart, and aims to play off stereotypes,
not with them. His first words are something along the lines of:
``So I'm in the park last night mugging this white guy . . .'' And
the laughter explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' joke highlighted one of the curious _ and convincing _
arguments for seeing comedy live: it is one of the few
entertainments popular with many racial groups. It is also often
one of the few places where races can openly laugh at themselves
and each other without fear of recrimination. It has enormous power
to put people at ease.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' set continued rolling, hitting topics from a stoned
President Clinton debating policy _ ``I like it, I really like it''
_ to gays in the military. It was only a 20-minute set, but by the
end the audience was exhausted by laughs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we made it to Dangerfield's on the Upper East Side,
a different type of exhaustion had set in. Dangerfield's, named for
the comedian Rodney Dangerfield, is something of an anachronism.
Waiters wear red tuxedo jackets, and each table has a small red
lamp. I felt as if I had died and gone to the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   The MC that night was a hefty woman in a tuxedo with a purple
bow tie. She was talking to the audience as we entered, trying to
tell them that although people think she's a lesbian, she's really
looking for the right man.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Schaffer, do I have a woman for you.
</P>
<P>
   The next night I set out alone to hit two clubs across town from
each other. The first was Stand Up New York, the Upper West Side's
only major club, on West 78th Street. The space is clean if
slightly industrial, and the atmosphere this Saturday was low-key.
While the club was nearly full, the staff wasn't picky about my
showing up late and waived the drink minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The comics, too, seemed at ease. One, a bald Texan named Steven
Kent, who calls himself Spanky, pretty much laughed his way through
his own set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a ticket on the way over, going 53 in a 35,'' Spanky
said. ``I told the cop I was dyslexic.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, until Spanky pulled a maneuver nobody saw coming:
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started here 11 years ago,'' he said, pulling on his black
jacket, ``and I just want to say: find the comedy in life. If you
do, you will live a long happy time.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience waited a second _ I don't think they were sure he
was serious _ and then broke into loud applause.
</P>
<P>
   I then moved to the Comic Strip Live, a venerable Upper East
Side institution that claims a whole roster of famous comics (Jerry
Seinfeld, Eddie Murphy, Chris Rock, Adam Sandler) as its own. This
could not be independently confirmed, but when has a comic ever
lied?
</P>
<P>
   The club is a good example of how an efficient operation can
bring in big dollars. The Comic Strip runs three shows a night on
the weekends; most sell out. With more than 200 people at a show
spending $25 to $35 each, the potential profits are (warning: pun
ahead) no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   But an audience wants laughs for its money, meaning the Strip
keeps a steady roster of talent on call. This night the comics were
all good, but the MC was the real showman.
</P>
<P>
   His name is William Stephenson, and while he is a comic himself,
he is often hired to oversee the entertainment. Easy as that
sounds, it is something of an art form, requiring an ability to
unite a crowd _ all different ages, different backgrounds and
different tastes _ around each comic who appears. Perhaps more
important, he also feels out the audience, to provide fodder for
the comics' routines later in the night.
</P>
<P>
   How is this done? The first step is the ancient comedic
demographic test, i.e. ``So where are you from?'' or ``Anybody here
from New Jersey?'' Stephenson used both, made a few cracks, and
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the ``why are you here?'' question. In less time
than it takes to plead the Fifth, Stephenson had one table pegged
as a bachelor party and another as a 40th birthday fete. Rich
material indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the old ritual of teaching the audience how to
clap. Sounds easy, but Stephenson made it complex _ ``put your
hands together like this,'' he said slowly _ so complex the
audience found itself laughing at itself before it had heard a
single joke.
</P>
<P>
   His work done, Stephenson retreated to the sidelines to let the
show _ already well under way _ begin.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
