<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-3RDTA     03-30 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMEDY-CLUBS-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: way _ begin.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laughs on Week Nights
</P>
<P>
   While Sundays and Mondays at the city's mainstream clubs are
generally open-mike nights, where wannabes are sometimes expected
to bring three paying guests for the privilege of performing,
downtown clubs thrive during the week. This is particularly true at
Surf Reality, a small, ramshackle second-floor theater on the Lower
East Side, where on Sundays you can see up to eight hours of comedy
for $3.
</P>
<P>
   To perform all you need do is throw your name into a coffee can
and follow three simple rules laid out by Faceboy, the bald
20-something MC: ``No. 1, respect other performers. No. 2, no
heckling. And No. 3 and most important, don't set fire to the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Surf Reality was one of the neighborhood's trailblazers in
alternative comedy, along with the Luna Lounge, which blossomed in
the mid-1990s. Nowadays the neighborhood is bustling with bars
offering free yuks, including Tonic, Baby Jupiter, the Sidewalk
Cafe and the Parkside Lounge, where one night I watched an odd
young man calling himself Craig B. wrap himself in a Mexican
blanket and chug down seven increasingly hot bottles of pepper
sauce. His set ended moments later when he found it impossible to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown theater spaces like Todo Con Nada, Collective
Unconscious and PS 122 also periodically have comedy. The casual
movie house, Cinema Classics on East 11th Street, also offers
comedy of sorts with its 10 O'Clock Mock, when three local comics
crack wise about a bad movie as it is screened. (Devotees of
Mystery Science Theater 3000 will love it.)
</P>
<P>
   It's Comedy Every Night
</P>
<P>
   Surf Reality is also one of the few downtown clubs to program
comedy _ or some derivation thereof _ every night of the week. The
Upright Citizens Brigade Theater, opened in 1999 in an old
burlesque theater on West 22nd Street, is another, especially
popular with comics who know that producers from Comedy Central
often drop by. A similar idea is at work at PS NBC, a
four-night-a-week cabaret that recently opened at Here in the South
Village to develop talent for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Surf Reality may not draw as many talent scouts, but dozens of
downtown comics show up for Faceboyz Open Mike Night on Sundays,
signing up for eight-minute sets clocked on a kitchen timer. The
show begins around 8 p.m. and sometimes runs until 4 a.m. A sign on
the wall reads: ``Pray for Laughs.'' Few performers use their real
names.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is more party than performance. The audience _
many of whom will perform _ bring beer from the local delis.
Typical hallway conversation runs like this: ``I'll go on for three
minutes, then you break in with this poem . . .'' All performers
get a care package, which this night included a condom, a lollipop
and a mint.
</P>
<P>
   The first act was a large blond fellow who went by the name Big
Mike's Erectile Dysfunction. He was dressed all in black and, in an
odd sartorial flourish, wore a belt of small black flashlights. Big
Mike got to the microphone, unfurled several handwritten pages, and
started screaming about a conversation that he had overheard on the
subway.
</P>
<P>
   Ting. Eight minutes later another performer: Ivan Youngblood,
who read a poem and took questions from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ting. Next was a comedian whose nerves caused her to bolt from
the room (ting). Then one whose Jackie Gleason imitation sounded
suspiciously like Christopher Walken (ting). And finally, that
infamous ``Hang On Sloopy'' woman (ting, ting, ting, ting!!!!)
</P>
<P>
   My companion leaned over and said, ``This is when you need a big
gong.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the evening moved along, more laughs came. (There were
several trips to the deli, mind you.)
</P>
<P>
   Hank Flynn, a Surf Reality regular, recited a poem, accompanied
by a Gordon Lightfoot song, celebrating his trip to the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, cab driver, for your incense and most direct
route,'' he intoned. He was interrupted several times by laughs and
by a fellow comedian, known as Johnny Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut it out, man,'' said Senor Spanish. ``That music is giving
me the creeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Faceboy himself did a dramatic reading of personal ads taken
from a pornographic magazine. It was, like much of that evening's
six hours, unprintable. And very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Brand New Jokes
</P>
<P>
   A slightly more sophisticated ethos is at work at the Luna
Lounge, where the Monday night comedy series, ``Eating It,'' is in
permanent residence. (The show's title is comedian slang for
bombing.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating It'' began in 1995 and has since become a downtown
institution, regularly drawing a standing-room-only crowd to Luna's
orange-walled back room. The rules for the comics are the same now
as they were then: nothing but brand new material is allowed. Many
acts, including bigger names like Janeane Garofalo and Colin Quinn,
take notebooks to the stage; sometimes, they eat it just like
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the scene was typical: a long line down the block,
with a large young crowd already piled in the back. A French lounge
singer _ accordion, accent, attitude _ entertained the crowd before
the show.
</P>
<P>
   The draw was a stunt act: the comedian Todd Barry had put a
personal ad in Time Out New York, and his blind date was coming to
the gig. The date, in fact, was the gig. A booth had been set up
with two candles, a menu for a Thai restaurant and two microphones.
Before the date arrived, Barry and his cohost, Jonathan Groff, had
a short predate discussion onstage. It was not a typical
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Groff quizzed Barry on his habit of growing hydroponic lettuce
in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No offense, Todd,'' Groff said, ``but your apartment is not
very big.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lettuce,'' replied Barry, mock offended, ``is not very big,
Jon.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry swore that if he met the right woman, he would ``throw all
the lettuce stuff right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, the date, Karen Rabinovitz, a freelance journalist,
arrived. As she reached the stage, she made a remark to Groff.
``What,'' said Barry, ``are we fighting already?''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd loved it. It was unclear how Rabinovitz felt. Still,
for the next two hours, she sat with Barry, ate and watched the
show. Near the end of the show, which included Garofalo's funny
account of a punk rocker giving himself a concussion, Groff quizzed
the couple on how it all went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you embarrassed?'' Groff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Rabinovitz responded. ``I'll never see most of these
people again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny,'' Groff said. ``That's how I got through my entire
stand-up career.''
</P>
<P>
   And he ended, as he should, on a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
