<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-VENTURA-CHINA-1STLD-W     03-30 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURA-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VENTURA URGES END TO CHINA, CUBA TRADE BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: REPLACES headline)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura urged Congress
Thursday not only to approve a bill that would permanently
normalize trade with China but also remove all trade embargoes on
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closed doors don't work,'' he testified before the House Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura made a strong plea for the lawmakers to back President
Clinton's request that the United States grant China the same low
tariffs it gives most other nations on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   In a loud, deliberate voice he said granting such status ``is
the biggest economic decision of the 21st century. Please don't
blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   For each of the last 20 years, Congress has reviewed trade
status with China and, after many bitter disputes over Beijing's
poor human rights record, granted the status but only on an annual
basis. Permanent normal status would end Congress' yearly reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, especially Democrats, are under strong pressure to
oppose the China deal from many labor leaders who charge that
American jobs would be lost if trade with Beijing is expanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Ventura argued that boosting trade would not cost Americans
their jobs, citing 44,000 job o &Cx1f; penings in parts of Minnesota that
are now unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see one bit how union jobs are going to leave America
based on a trade relationship with China,'' the governor said.
``It's simply not going to happen and the statistics bear it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura told the committee that the United States does not need
to approve of China's human rights stance in order to continue
trading with its people. The opening of more Chinese markets to
U.S. goods would, over time, instill in the communist nation
American business practices, culture and democratic ideas, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreeing with some Clinton administration officials, Ventura
said China has enough support among World Trade Organization
nations to join the group regardless of whether the United States
backs its admission.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura also insisted that the United States should open trade
with Cuba. He contended that Cuban dictator Fidel Castro's regime
has lasted for four decades because closed trade has shut off U.S.
ideas about democracy from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   He also said America should end embargoes against Cuban
products. ``I'm very tired of feeling like a criminal every time I
want a Cuban cigar,'' Ventura quipped.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
