<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFER-HIGHWAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: ROADSIDE USE OF NATIVE PLANTS; HIGH-RISK PASSENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Making highways safe and environmentally sound
usually means planning for guardrails, oil runoff and the like. But
the Federal Highway Administration has a surprise success on its
hands with a book about a completely different aspect of the road:
the plantings along the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In January the agency, part of the U.S. Department of
Transportation, published a 665-page handbook, ``Roadside Use of
Native Plants,'' and all 5,000 copies flew out of the warehouse.
Most went to state and local highway departments, environmental
groups, universities, elementary schools and military bases.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for highway departments is to plant something that
will prevent erosion _ which can undermine roads or can let dirt
and rocks wash onto them _ but that will not grow into obstacles
that could kill someone in a car or truck that strays off the
pavement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem is to avoid plantings that will turn into roadside
hazards, like trees, or that will spread like kudzu, an East Asian
vine that has run wild in much of the South since it was brought in
for erosion control about 125 years ago. The Transportation
Department is quick to note that that particular error was made by
the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Still, highway departments make similar mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie L. Harper-Lore, who put the guidebook together, said, for
example, that many states now list crownvetch (Coronilla varia) as
a ``noxious weed,'' and some are trying to eradicate it. But, she
said, in their efforts to prevent erosion, ``it's hard to find a
state that hasn't tried crownvetch.''
</P>
<P>
   Other roadside pests include grasses, vines, shrubs and trees.
Still others are tall fescue grass, English ivy, English holly,
privet, Alianthus trees and Norway maples. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The guidebook divides each state into vegetation zones and lists
what is native to each. Connecticut has two such zones, but New
Jersey has five and New York has eight. Texas has 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A boiled-down version of the guide, handy for gardeners, appears
on the Web at www.fhwa.dot.gov/environment, under roadside
vegetation management. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plants that are not native, variously called ``invasive'' and
``alien,'' squeeze out native species, and experts complain that
they contribute to the sameness of the landscape, with the same
lack of regional variation as the endless vistas of gasoline
stations, chain stores and fast-food restaurants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Highway roadsides, the handbook notes, are some of the most
viewed natural environments in the country. And in some places
where everything else has been given over to malls, parking lots
and roads, roadway edges are the only remaining area for
vegetation; the U.S. Transportation Department said they should be
maintained in as natural a form as possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to protecting the environment along the
nation's highways,'' said Kenneth R. Wykle, the federal highway
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Use of native plants also can minimize the need for fertilizer
and water, experts said. That presumably leaves more resources
available to maintain the paved portion of the road. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Limiting Teen-age Passengers  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age drivers are more dangerous than older drivers,
statistics have long shown, but a recent study says that teen-agers
increase the risk of a crash in another way: by being passengers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing federal data on fatal crashes, researchers at Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore found that for 16-year-old drivers,
the risk of dying behind the wheel rose 39 percent with one young
passenger, 86 percent with two passengers and 182 percent with
three or more passengers.
</P>
<P>
   For 17-year-old drivers, the risk increase was even larger; with
three or more passengers it was triple the risk of driving alone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, noted that a survey of high school seniors found
strong correlations between carrying passengers and various risky
behaviors, including speeding, swerving, purposely skidding or
running a red light, and driving after drinking or using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four states have set limits on younger drivers, called
graduated licensing, but only 10 regulate the number or age of the
passengers a teen-age driver may carry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, a bill introduced in Maryland would have limited
drivers age 16 and 17 to carrying no more than two passengers under
21. But the sponsor, state Delegate William Bronrott, acknowledging
that it would not pass a committee vote, agreed to water it down to
require simply that back-seat passengers, who in Maryland need not
wear a seat belt, must do so if the driver is under 18.
</P>
<P>
   That will at least limit the number of passengers to the number
of seat belts, he said, since front-seat passengers already must
wear belts under an older state law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the old days, when people would try to cram as many
people in a phone booth as you could?'' Bronrott said. ``Put it on
wheels, and that's what we see all to often on our roads.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other states also have been lukewarm. In Virginia two years ago,
one lawmaker proposed that if a 16-year-old or 17-year-old was
convicted of a moving violation, the driver should not be allowed
to carry other teen-agers. The Virginia Legislature, however,
settled on no more than three; before a violation, they can
transport as many as will fit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
