<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STARCHY IN RHODE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great thing about politics in the United States of America,
people, is that there's always something. If you find the
presidential campaign dreary, you look around and there's the state
of Rhode Island, embarking on a plan to decorate its landscape with
dozens of 6-foot-tall statues of Potato Head.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, you're already asking yourself why your state
didn't think of this first.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island Tourism Division is rolling out a new marketing
program that stars Potato Head as the symbol of ``Rhode Island _
the Birthplace of Fun.'' Thanks to corporate sponsors, there are
already 43 giant depictions of or Potato Head scattered around the
state, most of which actually look more like 6-foot eggs with feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhode Island will peel ahead of the crop when it comes to
attracting visitors from around the world,'' said Gov. Lincoln
Almond, as he swore in Potato Head as the state's official travel
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   About the motto. The Tourism Division says Rhode Island is the
official Birthplace of Fun because it's the birthplace of Potato
Head, a fun guy conceived and manufactured in Pawtucket. Until this
very moment, most people probably thought of the state as the
birthplace of the TV series ``Providence'' and the Claus von Bulow
trial, but there you are. According to the governor's office, Rhode
Island is also the birthplace of the Industrial Revolution, an
important but not really feel-good concept.
</P>
<P>
   All sorts of meaningless yet strangely intriguing stuff is going
on at the state level these days. New York, I am proud to report,
is about to celebrate its failure to pass a budget on time for the
16th straight year. The Empire State, in fact, regards itself as
the Birthplace of the Perpetually Overdue Spending Package. We just
haven't quite figured out how to turn it into a tourism campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee state legislature recently passed a bill making
the Tennessee walking horse its official horse. The measure is now
on the governor's desk, giving him something to think about when he
isn't engaged in overhauling the entire state tax structure.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is one of a number of states that's very much into
symbol clutter. It has six different official state songs, only one
of which is ``The Tennessee Waltz.'' (Try asking Al Gore to hum a
few bars of ``When It's Iris Time in Tennessee.'') The legislature
ought to take the bit in its teeth and give that walking horse full
State Animal bragging rights. The current occupant, the raccoon,
could be downgraded to Official State Varmint.
</P>
<P>
   What this country needs is a mandatory sunset law for state
Things. We could wipe the slate clean every five or 10 years and
start over. Refilling the symbol supply might give citizens a new
interest in state government; the state of Washington experienced
an unprecedented degree of attention a few years back when a disc
jockey started a movement to make ``Louie, Louie'' the official
state rock 'n' roll song.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, a lot of the current honorees don't seem to have
been given much thought. We have way too many cardinals and robins
out there in State Bird Land, and a lot of the mottos need work. I
am thinking of you, Maryland (``Manly deeds, womanly words''), and
Michigan, whose motto sounds as if it had been written by a real
estate developer. (``If you seek a pleasant peninsula, look around
you.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right, each generation should have the opportunity,''
agreed Sen Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. He is something of an
expert on this issue, having served in the state Senate back when
Connecticut was trying to come up with an official song, so bands
would stop playing ``Boola Boola'' whenever the governor entered
the room. After a lengthy songwriting competition that demonstrated
how difficult it was to fit repeated references to Connecticut into
a tune, the legislature wound up adopting ``Yankee Doodle.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Rhode Island's legislature went through an
intense fight between coffee milk and lemon ice for the title of
official state drink. The winner was the coffee milk, a beverage
made with a coffee extract that, like six-foot-statues of Potato
Head, can be found only in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
