<P>
   CENSUS-PRIVACY (Falls Church, Va.) _ Census Director Kenneth
Prewitt, rejecting complaints that census questionnaires are so
intrusive they ought to be ignored, urges Americans to answer every
question on census surveys sent to nearly 118 million households.
Prewitt says that if residents leave questions unanswered on Census
forms, field workers will follow up with a knock on the door in the
weeks ahead to urge cooperation or to take the information in an
interview. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-HAIL (Fort Worth, Texas) _ One of those killed by
Tuesday night's tornado in Fort Worth was a man who was hit in the
head by a softball-sized hailstone flying through the air at 100
mph. Such a death is highly unusual, meteorology experts say.
``There were only two deaths by direct hail strikes reported in the
20th century'' in the United States, says one Texas meteorology
professor and storm expert. By EVAN MOORE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-ABUSE (Austin, Texas) _ Philip Morris, long under fire
as a purveyor of disease and death among smokers, dons its white
hat to promote a national war against domestic violence. The
reaction is mixed. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
