<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS AGAIN SEEK SAFETY OF BONDS
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By ROBERT HURTADO  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Largely ignoring news that the economy grew at a pace
of 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of last year, faster than
previously reported, bonds reacted instead to a decline in stocks
as investors sought the safety of Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds continue to be influenced by stocks, so when global stock
markets dropped before the opening of the markets in the United
States, Treasury yields fell to their lowest level in more than a
week. When the U.S. stock market opened on a relatively firm note,
Treasuries trimmed some of those earlier gains. But bonds advanced
later as the Nasdaq slumped on a selloff in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 1 21/32, to 105
9/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction of the
price, fell to 5.87 percent from 5.97 percent on Wednesday, its
biggest one-day drop in almost two months. The yield is at its
lowest level since Aug. 24, when the Federal Reserve Board raised
its rate on overnight loans between banks by one-quarter point, the
second of five increases since last June designed to slow the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department's final estimate of gross domestic
product for the last quarter of 1999 reported a growth rate of 7.3
percent, revised from the previous estimate of 6.9 percent and
higher than economists' expectations of 7.1 percent. Even though it
was a strong number, some market participants felt it was not
necessarily new information.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said, ``The U.S. economy is in uncharted waters, roaring ahead at a
prodigious pace in the midst of the longest expansion on record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, GDP growth has accelerated over the past nine months
despite five pre-emptive tightening moves by the Federal Reserve,''
he said. ``And while the nation's economic momentum during the
first quarter of the year 2000 will not be quite as torrid as the
blistering 7.3 percent pace registered during the fourth quarter of
1999, it will still be in excess of the Fed's perceived maximum
non-inflationary 3.5 percent trend rate of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Fine said he believes the Fed will continue to
raise rates until it sees signs that the economy is moderating.
Most market participants expect the Fed policy-makers to raise
rates by another quarter point at the next meeting on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Another recurring theme in the bond market is the effect of the
government budget surplus and buyback program, which have caused an
inverted yield curve, in which investors who take on more risk by
owning long-term debt are paid less than those holding short-term
instruments. The yield on a two-year note is now at 6.48 percent,
and yields on the longer maturities are lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition,'' Fine said, ``growing concerns about risks in
other sectors have, at times, produced a flight-to-quality movement
into Treasuries, and with asset allocations jumping around between
cash, bonds, traditional stocks and particularly tech-sector
equities, the markets appear to be searching for some kind of
anchor in what has recently become a rather volatile financial
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, corporate bonds got off to a bad start, with market
participants concerned that the government will not be responsible
for agencies like Fannie Mae if they default on their debt, which
has caused some unwinding of those positions. Those agencies have
only an implied backing from the government. Yield spreads between
corporate issues and comparable Treasuries with similar maturities
widened three to four basis points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
