u s BC-BKC-NCAA-WOMEN31-COX     03-30 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WOMEN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Vols nor UConn cocky
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They both missed the Final Four a year ago.
Tennessee and Connecticut watched while the Purdue-Duke NCAA
championship game generated record television ratings and got
people thinking that perhaps women's college basketball was bigger
than two teams with a national profile.
</P>
<P>
   That theory has pretty much been discarded this season.
Tennessee and UConn split two nailbiting regular-season games and
occupied the top two spots in the national rankings most of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Their losses last year, however, taught them not to look too far
ahead. It is an approach they will share in their national
semifinal games tonight at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (32-3), whose ambitions for four consecutive NCAA
titles were derailed in the Elite Eight a year ago, meets Rutgers
(26-7) in the 7 p.m. opener. The Lady Vols are on a 19-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   UConn (34-1), which has been ranked No. 1 all season and whose
only loss was to Tennessee by a single point, plays Penn State
(30-4) in the nightcap about 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basketball team is not assuming that,'' Tennessee coach
Pat Summitt said about a UConn rematch for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are certainly focused on playing Rutgers and
understanding the challenge that lies in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights, in their first NCAA Final Four after
knocking off Georgia on Monday, play a tenacious matchup zone that
befuddled the Lady Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Volunteers, who haven't lost since Georgia won a
decisive 78-51 contest in Athens on Jan. 17, have improved,
although they had to pull out a late win over Texas Tech on Monday
to get here.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State is making its first Final Four journey a relatively
close one. The Lady Lions, who lost to UConn by 13 points in
December, have plenty of senior experience and easily routed a more
athletic Louisiana Tech team to reach this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that teams aren't looking past us,'' Penn State
point guard Helen Darling said. ``We came here to win it, just like
everyone else is here to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For UConn, getting to the Final Four after a four-year absence
has eased a tremendous burden. None of the current Huskies has
Final Four experience, but no team has more depth and scoring
balance or better pressure defense that routinely piles up baskets
in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking to that Tennessee matchup yet, but I've
heard a lot about it, and there's been a lot written about it,''
UConn guard Shea Ralph said. ``And you can really only expect a lot
of people to say that, because for so many years now it's been a
tradition. UConn-Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the rivalry dates back only to 1995, when the Huskies
went 35-0, beat Tennessee for the NCAA title and brought the
mainstream East Coast media into the picture. The Lady Vols
responded by winning the next three championships with the
now-departed Chamique Holdsclaw.
</P>
<P>
   Three coaches with Philadelphia roots will be returning to their
hometown: UConn's Geno Auriemma, C. Vivian Stringer of Rutgers and
Rene Portland of Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two weeks ago I told somebody that I'm not looking
forward to the hysteria that's going to be down here,'' said
Auriemma, whose family emigrated from Italy to nearby Norristown
when he was seven. ``But at the same time, I don't want to miss it.
I don't want to be sitting at home watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
