<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PROMOTION31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke getting in on the 'millionaire' craze
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. is giving away more than 10,000 cash
prizes _ including five $1 million prizes _ in a promotion this
summer to boost sales of its flagship Classic brand.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing effort, which will include partnerships with
Universal Studios and Universal Music, comes as the industry's
colas face intense competition from other carbonated and
noncarbonated beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Both Coca-Cola Classic, the nation's top-selling brand, and No.
2 Pepsi Cola lost market share last year, according to Beverage
Digest. Part of the decline was caused by price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola hopes its Summer 2000 promotion, which begins May 15
and runs through July 31, will reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of innovative program that Coke needs to do to
create some news and excitement both around Coke Classic and the
cola segment of the beverage industry,'' said John Sicher, editor
and publisher of Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   The ``You Win'' prizes will be under the lid of a new
``pop-top'' can, which is indistinguishable from an ordinary can of
Coke. The can was developed in Germany. Coke has the rights to its
use in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The winning cans will be randomly inserted in 12-, 18-, 20- and
24-can multipacks of Coke Classic and caffeine-free Coke Classic.
Prizes also will be behind labels on Classic bottles, but they will
not be in vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has already created a lot of excitement and enthusiasm
among our bottling partners and customers, and we believe this
promotion represents a tremendous opportunity for all of our
businesses,'' said Ralph Cooper, president of Coca-Cola North
America.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $1 million, $10,000 and $100 cash prizes, the
Atlanta-based company has teamed up with Universal Studios and
Universal Music to give away ``experiential'' prizes. These include
the chance to win walk-on roles in movies and music videos, and the
opportunity to cover a movie premiere as an on-camera
correspondent. There are also trips to Universal Studios theme
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Scott Williamson said the promotion is the
result of conversations with consumers who indicated they want
contests that are simple and straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like the idea of winning cash as well as prizes that are
unique and easy to understand,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time in a decade that Coke has tinkered
with the top of its can to offer prizes. Last year's summer
promotion involved the Coke Card, which gave consumers discounts at
participating retailers. ``It was successful in its own right,''
Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say how much this summer's promotion will cost
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
