<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-2TAKE     03-30 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BACKS SPENDING BILL THAT INCLUDES ANTI-DRUG SUPPORT FOR
COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: also moving in `i' category) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two days of debate, the House on Thursday
approved a $12.7 billion emergency spending bill whose centerpiece
commits the United States to train and equip Colombia's security
forces to combat drug traffickers in a country where the narcotics
trade and guerrilla insurgency have blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Central American civil wars of the 1980s has the
United States thrown such political, diplomatic and military
backing behind a crucial Latin American ally threatened by
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan House vote Thursday, 263-146, approved an
emergency aid package that also includes money for the Pentagon to
pay for the peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, and for flood disaster
relief in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But most significantly, the House has cast judgment on a plan
backed by the Clinton administration to spend $1.7 billion during
two years to help Colombia and other Andean countries, despite
critics' complaints that the anti-drug plan is ill-conceived and
could drag the United States into an open-ended conflict that has
already cost tens of thousands of lives during the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program will strengthen democratic government, the rule
of law, economic stability and human rights in that beleaguered
country,'' said Barry R. McCaffrey, the White House's drug czar.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy those who warned of a Vietnam-like quagmire, the
House approved by voice vote an amendment to limit U.S. military
personnel sent to Colombia to 300 at any one time, unless more are
needed for a rescue mission. In promoting his amendment, Rep. Gene
Taylor, a conservative Mississippi Democrat, said, ``I expect they
want American kids to fight in the war they won't fight and
American taxpayers to pay for a war they won't pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid to Colombia, which is the source of 90 percent of the
cocaine and 65 percent of the heroin seized in the United States,
was the main lightning rod in the debate. But the overall spending
measure that includes the anti-drug program is imperiled in the
Senate because of opposition from the Senate's top two Republican
leaders, Trent Lott of Mississippi and Don Nickles of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators do not oppose the Kosovo or Colombia aid. But
Lott has vowed to block the bill, saying it has become ``bloated''
with pork and other non-urgent spending.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to roll the most pressing aid proposals _ including
those for Kosovo, Colombia, as well as millions of dollars in flood
relief for North Carolina farmers _ into Congress' annual
appropriations process.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's proponents say that approach would postpone badly
needed aid for months, leaving disaster-stricken Americans in the
lurch and jeopardizing Washington's commitment to the fragile
democracy in Colombia, the hemispheric hub for narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert made the anti-drug program one of
his top legislative priorities, and on Wednesday he took to the
House floor to give a rare speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must act now,'' Hastert said. ``We cannot wait. We have a
responsibility to stop drugs in Colombia, to stop them in transit,
to stop them at our border, and to stop them on our streets and in
our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, which has been borrowing from other accounts to
pay for the Kosovo operation, says that if it does not get $2
billion by late April, the Army, in particular, will have to cancel
training and postpone maintenance, all steps that could hurt
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's lopsided vote in the House and a brewing revolt by
influential Senate Republicans who favor the immediate dispatch of
the Kosovo and Colombia aid may force Lott to relent. Sen. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, who heads the Appropriations Committee, said his
panel would take up a $9 billion spending bill, which includes the
Kosovo aid, in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The administration originally proposed a $5.2 billion emergency
spending bill, but the House Appropriations Committee added about
$3.8 billion more earlier this month. Lawmakers on Wednesday night
then loaded on $4 billion more in additional military spending to
cover unanticipated costs of spare parts, military healthcare and
safety maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the projects in the House bill that the White House did
not request _ and Lott is grumbling about _ include $600 million to
repair highways and bridges and $75 million to spruce up NASA's
fleet of Shuttles and $20 million to build a new Food and Drug
Administration building in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   All but $421 million of the bill would be paid for from this
year's projected $26 billion non-Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the House floor Tuesday and Wednesday, lawmakers passionately
debated the plan to send $1.7 billion during two years to help
Colombia, as well as other Andean nations like Ecuador and Peru,
step up its fight against drug traffickers by reducing cocaine and
heroin production.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's final vote reflected divisions across party lines,
both over Colombia and the bill's ballooning cost: 143 Republicans
and 119 Democrats voted in favor, while 61 Republicans and 84
Democrats voted against. Each side drew the vote of an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the aid package framed their debate not only in
terms of supporting an embattled Latin American ally, but also as a
bold move in the war on drugs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more hundreds or thousands of our kids will get
hooked on drugs or die from overdoses?'' said Rep. C.W. Bill Young,
R-Fla., who heads the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But critics warned that the United States was being drawn more
deeply into a convoluted civil conflict in Colombia, a country with
two leftist guerrilla armies fighting the government, right-wing
paramilitary forces fighting the guerrillas, and civilians trapped
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the aid package is 30 Blackhawk and 33 Huey
helicopters for the Colombian army and police forces, as well as
$470 million for the Colombian army and $115.5 million for the
police, that would be used to train and equip three Army battalions
for anti-drug operations, two of which would be new.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The measure also offer farmers incentives to grow other crops,
and finance programs to promote human rights and judicial reform,
but that did not assuage critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting involved in a civil war for which we're going to
pay a price,'' said Rep. Jose E. Serrano, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also balked at giving the bulk of the aid to the
Colombia military, which has ties to paramilitaries implicated in
human-rights abuses. Given these objections, many critics said the
aid would be better served treating patients for drug abuse in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't really get to the heart of the matter: the drug
problem in our country,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif. ``Some
5.5 million Americans need substance-abuse treatment, and only 2
million are getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall spending bill also includes $143 million in
emergency economic aid to Balkan countries and other nations in
southeast Europe. House members, by a vote of 219-200, defeated an
attempt to force President Clinton to start withdrawing U.S. troops
from Kosovo unless he certified that European NATO allies shoulder
their share of costs for international police, humanitarian aid and
economic reconstruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-30 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CALL it Phi Slama Scrama.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no excited throng filling every nook and
cranny of the O'Quinn Great Hall for the announcement. Just Clyde
the Glide skating out the back door.
</P>
<P>
   Dynasties are like blenders, refrigerators and presidents these
days. They don't make them like they used to, and the Clyde Drexler
Coaching Era at the University of Houston came to a close just 28
years, 572 wins and five Final Four appearances short of Guy V.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Family commitment, Drexler said, and no one dares question that
most heartfelt obligation. Only the notion that it never dawned on
Drexler until after he took the job that this coaching stuff is one
other thing in addition to drawing up X's and O's: hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Successful coaching requires long hours and dedication to the
details. It means breaking down game tape and devising strategies
on into the night. At the college level, it means getting off the
airplane following the season-ending loss in the conference
tournament and getting on another plane to visit an 18-year-old
recruit who wants you to tell him he'll become the next great
thing.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, Drexler was a real sharp dresser. But he never had
the qualifications for the job, and the fact his run was shorter
than the lifespan of a firefly is by no means his fault alone.
</P>
<P>
   For athletic director Chet Gladchuk, Drexler was the popular,
easy choice two years ago, like asking the kids if they would like
to eat candy for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Such a grandstanding move prods the alums and the student body
to conjure up images of young colts named Clyde and Akeem who could
jump through the roof and Guy V. who had the know-how to pull it
all together.
</P>
<P>
   For Gladchuk, it was also the wrong, lazy choice, a box-office
gimmick that was more smoke and mirrors than Siegfried &AMP; Roy with
none of the tiger's bite.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind up-and-coming names such as Larry Eustachy and Bill
Self or others. Let them go to Iowa State and Tulsa or wherever and
make good by working to build a program. We'll just give them a
famous name, and they'll buy tickets and pack the house. And they
did. For one year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the homage to the legendary Lewis as it was billed,
it was an insult, an implicit statement that learning the craft is
not required, only a Hall of Fame resume from the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   One does not become a coach simply by trading in your uniform
and high-tops for a designer suit and a whistle. It is a profession
that has to be in your blood. Even Larry Bird, who made a
successful transition at the pro level, is getting out after just
three years and says that if he had to do it all over, he would
prepare for several seasons as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   When asked recently if he had any inclination to become a coach,
Drexler's former teammate Hakeem Olajuwon shook his head quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you get to walk away when the game is over, win
or lose,'' he said. ``Do you see those coaches? They never stop.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his appointment, there were questions about how
Clyde would make the transition from ultra-rich superstar player to
coach of a college program that is not exactly flush with money. He
talked early of a desire to fly charter planes _ a la the NBA _ to
road games. But that is an extravagance that is not in the UH
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his first season on the job, word came out that
Clyde was phoning old NBA friends in San Antonio and Miami, seeking
to hitch on for a playoff ride. Would it have given him an
advantage over Bob Huggins and Denny Crum on the Conference USA
recruiting trail if he soared in for a slam dunk in the NBA Finals
with ``Come to UH'' on the soles of his sneakers? Not if he was
unwilling to put in the long hours away from the family.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did Drexler take the job? Naivete and perhaps a touch
of ego.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the matter of convenient timing. For in the
spring of 1998, when the NBA contracts of Drexler and his feuding
teammate Charles Barkley were set to expire, the Rockets were going
to re-sign only one. And it was Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Without saying a word in public, the Rockets' coaching staff
would speak volumes about which of the two they thought was better
to keep around and who was a more divisive influence in the locker
room. Thus, a chance to help save the old alma mater was a golden
parachute for Drexler's image.
</P>
<P>
   Until he hit the ground hard with 10-17 and 9-22 seasons and the
realization this was far more work than he had bargained for. So
Clyde glides.
</P>
<P>
   And Gladchuk is back where he was two years ago on the day he
gave the job to Drexler _ still in need of a real coach.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
