<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION NEED FINISHING TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Kicking a soccer ball into an 8-yard-by-8-foot net
is the most basic of sporting skills. A 2-year-old can accomplish
it with ease.
</P>
<P>
   But converting goals in a soccer game, against bunched defenses
and hot goalkeepers, is a different proposition. Then it becomes
one of sport's most difficult tasks, even for the most finely tuned
athletes, which is one reason goal scorers capture imaginations and
generate so much passion.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have been a good example of the vagaries of goal
scoring this season. They have had many excellent chances but have
scored only once and have 1 point after two games. And their
prospects are not great Saturday night since they visit the Los
Angeles Galaxy, among MLS's strongest teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always waiting for somebody else who is in better
position to score a goal,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said.
``We have to pull the trigger, become more selfish in the (penalty
area) instead of looking for a beautiful goal. You have to hit it
when nobody expects it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, scoring has never been the Revolution's greatest
problem. Three of the top five goal scorers in MLS history have
played for the Revolution. And the current strike force, Wolde
Harris and Eduardo Hurtado, should be among the most dangerous
combinations in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goal scoring takes a lot of confidence and a little luck,''
Harris said. ``I don't think anybody has higher expectations than
we have in ourselves. I put more pressure on myself than the
coaches do, and we all have that attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have high expectations. That is a challenge that
comes with the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution players are continuing to adjust to each other.
Of the starting midfielders, only Imad Baba was with the team two
years ago. But Baba, who converted off a Ted Chronopoulos free kick
in a season-opening 1-1 tie March 18 at Miami, has played only four
games since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And the Revolution are counting on the Harris-Hurtado
combination to provide finishing. Both are speedy, strong, and
comfortable with the ball at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Harris scored 26 goals in 83 games with Colorado before joining
the Revolution last month. Hurtado, who is in Quito, Ecuador, for
the Ecuador-Venezuela World Cup qualifier Thursday night, had 47
goals in 114 games with the Galaxy and MetroStars. Hurtado is also
the leading scorer in Ecuador national team history with 25 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hurtado) is mobile and he can hold possession, which gives me
time to find open spaces,'' Harris said. ``And I can do the same
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need to find out where we work best together. We like
to play one- and two-touch and give-and-go, especially at the top
of the (penalty area). We need to combine better there.''
</P>
<P>
   The best Revolution goal scorers of the past _ Raul Diaz Arce,
Joe-Max Moore, and Giovanni Savarese _ were opportunists who often
converted out of chaotic situations. Now the Revolution are
attempting to play a more fluid style, and it paid off in several
excellent chances last Saturday at Tampa Bay. But those
opportunities were either parried by goalkeeper Scott Garlick or
squandered by inaccuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Miami, we were concentrating on defending and played
with one forward up front,'' Harris said. ``Against Tampa Bay,
everyone was working for everyone else. If you noticed, when we
lost the ball, everyone got back behind the ball. And that gave us
confidence to create. All we have to do now is finish our
chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
