<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     03-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S SETTLEMENT OFFERS: AS ANTITRUST REMEDIES, TOO LITTLE,
TOO LATE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (News Analysis) 
(bl) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over and over again for the last several years,
Microsoft Corp. has asserted that separating its Web browser from
Windows was impossible. And yet, in settlement talks with the
government, the company has reportedly offered to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   One possible reason for this change of heart, some experts say,
is that it doesn't matter anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's closing the barn door after the horses are already out,''
said Stephen Houck, who was the chief lawyer for the 19 states that
filed suit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Trial evidence showed that Microsoft built its browser, Internet
Explorer, into Windows as a tactic to put its chief competitor,
Netscape Communications Corp., at a disadvantage. But the browser
war is over. Microsoft won. Industry studies show that Netscape's
share of the market _ about 50 percent when the antitrust trial
opened two years ago _ has precipitously declined since then,
though the precise estimates vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great remedy in 1995, but now Netscape Navigator
has been defeated; the battle's lost,'' said Steven Salop, a
professor of law and economics at Georgetown University who has at
times served as a consultant for some of Microsoft's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The manner by which Microsoft has offered to do this has not
been disclosed. The company has several options. But the most
likely method is the one Microsoft employed once before, in January
1998, in response to an earlier federal lawsuit. Then, the company
said it would hide or partly disable the browser, though the code
would remain in Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Felten, a Princeton University computer scientist, hid
and disabled the browser with a removal program he wrote while
serving as a government witness during the antitrust trial in 1998.
But in court, Microsoft adroitly demonstrated that, the way its
software is written, Internet Explorer shows up unexpectedly now
and then _ no matter how well the program is hidden _ backing its
contention that the browser is integral to the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Several other proposals that Microsoft is said to have offered
in the settlement talks also have significant potential problems.
Experts also say that none of the remedies that have been discussed
as a solution to this case come without liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   One official close to the talks said the problems and
liabilities are the very issues under discussion now as the parties
exchange drafts of their settlement proposals in an effort to come
to an agreement by next Wednesday, the deadline set by a
court-appointed mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every single provision,'' the official said, ``there are a
lot of questions about how you define the terms, how you enforce
it, how they might try to evade it and how it addresses tomorrow's
issues, not just today's.''
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said the Justice Department has been a strong,
longtime advocate of one of Microsoft's ideas, to publish price
lists for the Windows operating system, so Microsoft could not use
prices to penalize companies that defy its will.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea is accepted, Microsoft would most likely formulate
standard, tiered prices for Windows. The more copies a computer
manufacturer bought, the lower the price. But that variation aside,
every manufacturer would pay the same price.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Economides, an economist at New York University, said
he likes the idea ``of having a uniform price list for all
customers'' to prevent price discrimination. But others see
significant pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Hovenkamp, a professor of law at the University of Iowa
who serves as an occasional consultant for the state and federal
governments in this case, notes that there are myriad ways that
Microsoft could continue rewarding friends and punishing others,
even with a uniform price list.
</P>
<P>
   The company could make special joint marketing arrangements with
preferred customers, or give them special terms in
technical-support contracts. ``One of the things we know about
pricing is that firms are extremely creative about evading price
restrictions,'' Hovenkamp said.
</P>
<P>
   Salop added that ``if Microsoft can't punish them with the price
of Windows any more, they can punish them with the price of
Office,'' Microsoft's suite of application programs that also holds
more than a 90 percent share of its market. It is not a part of the
current legal case.
</P>
<P>
   Houck, who is now in private practice, raised an additional
concern. Maybe Microsoft would no longer be able use prices as
punishment. Conversely, however, companies would no longer be able
to negotiate the best price, ``and I think that will lead to higher
Windows prices overall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under another major Microsoft proposal, the company would make
available all of the interface codes that allow software developers
to write programs for Windows. Microsoft has argued for years that
it already does that because making the codes widely available is
in the company's interest. That way more software companies will
write programs for Windows, Microsoft says.
</P>
<P>
   But trial evidence showed that Microsoft's enthusiasm for making
the codes public varied by circumstance. Salop notes that Microsoft
seems less willing to publish the codes for use by software
programs that are serious competitors to Microsoft products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new development, something they haven't offered
before,'' Houck said. ``But it's extremely complex. They can bury
the codes deeper and deeper. It's very hard to figure out what they
are doing, and you will have to have a detailed regulatory regimen
to keep up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that is the chief complaint all of the experts offered
about the whole package _ those that have been discussed in the
media and others that are still not publicly known.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of this,'' Salop said, ``you're going to need ongoing
cooperation from Microsoft, and you'll be unlikely to get it
voluntarily.'' He and others said they feared that, trying to
enforce the settlement agreement, the government would continually
find itself back in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
