<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-TAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TO TAKE UP PROPOSAL TO SUSPEND 4.3-CENT-A-GALLON GAS TAX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate agreed Thursday to take up a proposal by
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that would temporarily suspend
the 4.3-cent-a-gallon federal gasoline tax enacted in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the procedural motion, passed by a vote of 86-11, was no
guarantee that the bill will ever be seriously debated or moved to
a final vote since many Republicans have split ranks to join with
most Democrats in opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the vote suggested that lawmakers do not want to be
seen as opposing a tax rollback in an election year. By keeping the
measure alive members will also have more time to consider how to
respond, if at all, to the high gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lott insisted on moving ahead with his bill despite a decision
this week by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
boost oil production. The OPEC move is expected by this summer to
lower and stabilize prices at the pump, which now average about
$1.50 per gallon nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's proposal, dubbed the ``fuel tax holiday'' bill, would
suspend the 4.3-cent tax until Jan. 1. It also contains a provision
that would trigger the suspension of the remaining 14.1-cent a
gallon federal tax if gasoline prices reach $2.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said his measure would ``do something immediately'' to
ensure that ``people aren't hammered'' by high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said the measure would provide little, if any,
relief for car-dependent Americans and accused Lott of using the
issue in an attempt to focus blame for the high prices on the
Clinton administration and Vice President Al Gore. Lott has often
referred to the federal gasoline tax as the ``Gore tax'' because
the vice president, the presumed Democratic presidential nominee,
cast the tie-breaking vote in the Senate to make it law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear that repeal of the gas tax is really an
effort to make a political statement,'' said Sen. Harry Reid,
D-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP House members also shrugged off the Lott proposal as
``political theatrics,'' noting that it has little chance of
passing in that chamber even if approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, made that clear
earlier this week when he told reporters that Lott's proposal would
provide ``scant relief'' to motorists. Armey said the plan also
presents ``a real dilemma'' for Republicans who only last year
signed off on a measure guaranteeing that the federal gas tax would
be put into the National Highway Trust Fund and dedicated to
helping states maintain and improve their road systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot repeal the trust fund after we've just restored the
trust find. We cannot turn around from the commitment we've made on
it,'' Armey said, echoing a view held by many GOP House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumed Republican presidential
nominee, has apparently adopted a similar position. However, he has
suggested that a ``temporary repeal'' of the gas tax might be one
option he would explore as president to deal with rising prices.
Bush speaks cautiously about the idea because Texas and other
states could be forced to make up lost revenues if federal gas tax
funds are cut off, if only temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is now one of largest recipients of federal highway money.
It recoups nearly 95 cents of every dollar it pays into the trust
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Up until last year, most of the trust fund money _ $7 billion to
$8 billion a year _ was being siphoned off by Congress for use in
other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan measure sponsored by Sens. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., outlawed that practice as part of the
national transportation program that was reauthorized last year by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said he would not vote to ``undue the Byrd-Gramm bill,''
but he would support ``a temporary set-aside'' if it can be made up
from other funding sources.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said his proposal would make up the loss of the gas tax
money by shifting other federal funds around in the 2001 budget and
using anticipated surpluses to replenish the trust fund on Dec. 31
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark., labeled that approach a
``hocus pocus'' way to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even have a budget (for the 2001 fiscal year), let
alone a budget surplus,'' she said in a floor speech.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
