<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HEDGE-FUND-ART-2TAKES     03-30 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUND-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD-ECONOMY GIANT PLACES THE ULTIMATE HEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT20, has been sent to New York Times photo
clients and a graphic has been sent to New York Times graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The financial markets humble ordinary investors all
the time. In Julian H. Robertson Jr., head of Tiger Management,
they have humbled an investing giant.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of generating superlative investment returns by
buying stocks that were undervalued and selling short those that
carried excessive valuations, Robertson confirmed Thursday that he
is shutting Tiger's operations. He has essentially decided to stop
driving the wrong way down the one-way tech thoroughfare that Wall
Street has become.
</P>
<P>
   In the conference room of his sumptuous Manhattan offices
Thursday just after he had written his farewell letter to the
roughly 700 investors in his six funds, Robertson mused cheerfully
about his career in the stock market, the joys and perils of
managing other peoples' money and the end of the era in which his
investment calls regularly moved markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not capitulating,'' he said. ``I'm not going to quit
investing. But it will be nice to get out of the public eye. I
don't mind people calling me an old economy investor, but it
doesn't go over well with the clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does losing money, of course, which is what forced
Robertson to fold Tiger's tent. The difficulties began in the early
fall of 1998 when Russia defaulted on its debt. Tiger lost $1.6
billion in bad currency bets that year, producing a decline of
almost 4 percent for 1998. Things got worse the next year when
technology stocks roared and value shares tumbled. Tiger's returns
plunged 19 percent. So far this year, the funds are down 13.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a frustrated value investor, Robertson finds himself in good
company, like Warren Buffett, whose returns last year, measured by
Berkshire Hathaway's book value, rose a woeful 0.5 percent. Then
there's Robert Sanborn, a once-hot mutual fund manager, who
resigned last week from his stewardship of the Oakmark Fund after a
dismal 1999 in which the fund lost 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Robertson's long-term record is a stand-out. An initial
investor in his fund would have seen his capital grow 85 times as
of earlier this year. Robertson's 25 percent annualized return
since his fund's inception in 1980 handily beats the 17.5 percent
average annual gains in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, with
dividends reinvested, for the period. Tiger's returns also exceed
the 14.7 percent average annual gains in the Morgan Stanley total
return world index, a proxy for international equities.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, as Tiger's woes became pronounced in recent years,
investors grew nervous and quickened their withdrawals from his
hedge funds, which cater to institutional investors and wealthy
individuals. At its peak in 1998, Tiger managed more than $21
billion. Since August 1998, however, investors have withdrawn $7.65
billion, including $950 million in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is a testament to Robertson's management that even as word
spread of Tiger's closing, the financial markets remained calm.
That is because Robertson has been slowly liquidating his holdings
over the last 18 months and reducing the fund's use of borrowed
funds. As a result, Tiger's unwinding created none of the upheaval
that surrounded the near failure of Long Term Capital Management in
September 1998. Then, the prospect of the huge hedge fund dumping
its holdings into already damaged markets pushed the Federal
Reserve of New York to broker a deal to unwind the fund gradually
with the help of several big Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long process,'' Robertson said. ``Since 1998,
we've been trying to take the leverage out of the funds. Because of
partner withdrawals, we've probably sold or bought between $60 and
$70 billion of securities.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he will have paid his clients 80 percent of what
they are owed by the end of April. Because he has been unwinding
his funds' positions over time, he said that 75 percent of the
refund will be in cash and an additional 5 percent in 11 stocks
that Tiger still owns. These are Bear Stearns Companies, Bowater
Inc., Federal-Mogul, Navistar, Niagara Mohawk Power, Pittston
Brinks Group, Royal Bank of Scotland, Sealed Air, Starwood Hotels,
Tosco Corp and Unum Provident. Because the holdings represent
relatively small slivers of the total shares of these companies,
the prospect of some Tiger investors selling should not hang over
them too darkly.
</P>
<P>
   Another five stocks in which Tiger has a large stake represent
the remaining 20 percent owed to investors. These will be kept by
Tiger to be disposed of later, in blocks perhaps, at better prices
than the fund would get if it dumped them on the market at once.
The five are GTech Holdings, US Airways, United Asset Management,
Xtra Corp. and Normandy Mining Limited. Robertson said he had
fielded many calls over the last few days from investors or
corporate executives looking to buy his positions.
</P>
<P>
   It is not lost on Robertson that many of the same stocks he had
been betting against in recent months _ Internet shares, technology
stocks and other beloved new economy stocks _ have been in freefall
since Tiger's shutdown became public. In the last four trading
sessions, the Nasdaq composite has lost 10.2 percent. ``If we had
been in business this week, it would have been one of our best
weeks ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's exit from the hedge fund business makes some market
observers wonder if the bear market in value stocks may finally be
ending. ``I have great faith that this too will pass,'' he wrote in
letter Thursday to investors. ``The difficulty is predicting when
this change will occur and in this regard I have no advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson may have been bloodied by the mania for technology
stocks and shares of untested and unprofitable Internet companies.
But he remains unbowed in his belief that value stocks will make a
comeback. ``The key to Tiger's success over the years has been a
steady commitment to buying the best stocks and shorting the
worst,'' Robertson wrote to his clients. ``In a rational
environment, this strategy functions well. But in an irrational
market, where earnings and price considerations take a back seat to
mouse clicks and momentum, such logic, as we have learned, does not
count for much.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson fears for investors in stocks with little in the way
of history, earnings or even revenues when the current mania ends.
``Investors are rightly fascinated by the Internet.'' he said,
``but wrongly they do not include price in these equations. It's
going to end in a real bloodbath.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson was one of the last holdouts in value investing; many
others have gone against their beliefs and jumped onto the
technology bandwagon. ``Life and investing are long ballgames,''
Robertson said. ``The people who were cynical and jumped in and
played this boom are going to win this game. But to take the
cynical risk against your fundamental belief, I wonder if in the
long run that will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he will have more time on his hands, Robertson said he
may try to write a novel. ``I've got a great wife that I'm looking
forward to spending more time with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he supports the Strang Clinic for cancer research
and Lincoln Center, and in his hometown of Salisbury, N.C.,
population 25,000, he and his wife have created a charitable
foundation named for his father, who had a textile operation, and
his mother, known for her volunteer work. In just two years, the
Robertson Foundation has given more than $3.5 million to education,
community development and health programs. About half the
foundation's assets are in the Jaguar fund, run by Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Robertson's time will probably be spent with a
handful of Tiger employees hunting for undervalued stocks. ``I'm
looking forward to investing on my own,'' he said. ``I've not
believed in playing the markets. I've always believed fundamentals
will win out.''
</P>
<P>
   Against all the odds, he still does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GENIUS AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ They did not waste his time, nor did they
engage him. They were just there, a collection of nuisances
standing before him in Minnesota uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   They bored him Thursday afternoon at City of Palms Park. It's a
wonder he didn't doze in the middle of his windup. It was the kind
of boredom you sometimes find on a date. You know the punchline
long before the first icebreaker joke has been told, but you sit
there politely and force a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez has heard the jokes before. He's a genius. Not a
comedic genius. He is the know-it-all with the ball. If these
spring ``games'' weren't so mundane, he would have told you how
mundane they are. But that would have been a waste of his time.
</P>
<P>
   His best sunny-day alternative Thursday was to pitch against the
Twins. It was his last warmup before Opening Day, Tuesday in
Seattle. He went five innings, threw 83 pitches, the Red Sox won,
6-5, and . . .
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second. You want numbers? You don't understand him if you
want numbers. They don't matter. The box score will show the Twins
roughed him up in the fifth. A homer. A triple. A run-scoring
single.
</P>
<P>
   A joke.
</P>
<P>
   He knew exactly what they were doing. Todd Walker hit a home run
_ the pitch was a cut fastball _ and the genius explained that the
ball ``stayed low and matched (Walker's) bat speed.'' There were
six strikeouts. There were six other hits, only one of which he
anointed as legitimate. A catcher named Marcus Jensen took a low
changeup and turned it into a single up the middle. Martinez
respected that hit. ``The rest were mediocre pitches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was calm as he spoke. You felt like you were interviewing a
computer programmer rather than a pitcher. You got the sense he
knew exactly where everything was supposed to be. He spoke, again,
of how boring spring training is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I didn't have to come to the field,'' he said. And that
statement roused an idea: This guy could literally mail in his
work. I'll bet that Martinez could sit at a computer, write out a
pitching plan _ including the mental and physical aspects of the
game _ and e-mail it to an aspiring Pedro clone. I say that clone
could stay competitive for six innings by following Martinez's
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if boredom overwhelms, Martinez will try that next spring.
Imagine: ``You've Got Mail . . . from Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pitchers, those not blessed with Martinez's gifts, shrug
when you ask them what went wrong in a game. They tell you it was a
bad day, they don't know what happened, and they'll have to move
on. Martinez knows what happened. If you ever meet him, watch the
way he looks at you. He studies you. He picks up your quirks,
patterns in your speech, everything. He then files them away. He's
always ahead.
</P>
<P>
   He was ahead before he left his native Dominican Republic for
the United States in 1990. He didn't speak English, but he studied
his older brother's English books. When he arrived in the US, he
made a habit of learning a new vocabulary word every day. Now he
knows English well enough to correct yours. He probably wouldn't do
that, but he could.
</P>
<P>
   Back to these games. Can't you give him a bigger challenge than
this? He says, yes, the Sox could win the World Series. He says the
Yankees won't intimidate him unless they ``bring in somebody from
Venus.'' He knows the routine.
</P>
<P>
   The genius dresses as carefully as he pitches: Dark blue
two-piece suit. Perfect material. Collarless antique-white shirt.
Meticulous black shoes. On the mound he wears No. 45, the same
number the dominating Bob Gibson wore. He says he doesn't know much
about Gibson. Finally, he's wrong. If he watches a tape of himself
at his best, he will have a better understanding of who Gibson was.
The only people who can truly understand his genius are other
living members of the Genius Tribunal, men such as Gibson, Sandy
Koufax, and Juan Marichal.
</P>
<P>
   His big brother understands, too. Ramon Martinez talked on a
cell phone as his 28-year-old brother tried to do the impossible:
explain what he does to those who don't do what he does. At times,
it sounded as if he were cocky. He's not. He is confident enough to
make insecure people believe that he is cocky.
</P>
<P>
   There is a question coming in from his right. The questioner
says something about Martinez historically beginning seasons well.
Whoa. The cool pitcher takes his hands out of his pockets, walks to
a wooden locker stall, and knocks on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you from Boston?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You trying to jinx me?''
</P>
<P>
   He continues.
</P>
<P>
   Really, what did people think he would do against the Twins? He
was hurt during last season's playoffs, but he is not hurting
anymore. He says he feels good. It will take three or four starts
before he gets his rhythm. He knows rhythm like Beethoven knew
sonatas. He will win a lot games this year, not walk many batters
(37 last season in 213 innings), and have a low ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be more consistent with my release point,'' he says.
``Do you know what a release point is? It's the point where you
release the ball. Very important.''
</P>
<P>
   He walks away, thinking of correcting these technical flaws in
his profession. Some of his contemporaries don't see what he sees.
That makes sense. He's a genius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
