<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-SENATE-CORZINE-ART     03-30 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-CORZINE-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY SENATORIAL HOPEFUL IN SPOTLIGHT OVER RACIAL SLUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. _ After promising to spend a million dollars a
week on television commercials to introduce himself to New Jersey
voters, Jon Corzine, a Democratic Senate candidate, on Thursday
found himself trying to distance himself from the kind of exposure
no candidate could buy or would want _ publicity about ethnic slurs
against Italian-Americans, the state's largest ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, whose appearances on the campaign trail have typically
been attended by a few print reporters, found himself looking into
11 television cameras Thursday morning as he apologized for making
derogatory references to Italians as recently as two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intended to cause embarrassment, and I never intended
to offend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's offhand remarks _ most recently, suggesting that a
contractor he had just met made ``cement shoes'' for a living _
drew loud protests Thursday from a number of Italian civic leaders
and even from the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were doubly damning for Corzine, a political
neophyte who became a multimillionaire as chairman of the
investment firm of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and is running against Jim
Florio, the former governor, in the June 6 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   First, the furor was the first time many voters paid attention
to him and to a race that is just taking shape. Second, they played
into questions even some of his own supporters have raised about
whether Corzine has the political skills and experience to
translate his millions into a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's done that on Wall Street,'' said Thomas P. Giblin,
the state Democratic chairman, who is supporting Corzine. ``But
this is the big leagues as far as politics are concerned. You can't
make another mistake like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine expressed hope that he would be given credit for owning
up to his mistakes immediately and candidly. ``I would hope that
people will find that Jon Corzine handles these things in a
straightforward way, consistent with integrity,'' he said. His
staff released a letter of support Thursday night signed by 24
Italian-American Democrats, saying: ``We accept Jon's apology as
sincere and heartfelt. Jon made the apology immediately last night
and repeated it twice today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli issued his own statement, saying: ``There
is a difference between an offhand comment and prejudice. Jon
Corzine is my friend and I bear some responsibility for his
candidacy. Neither would be the case if there was not genuine
mutual affection and an absence of any prejudice against
Italian-Americans or anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics were not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have an individual who is a decided underdog in the
campaign, and he's not thinking of the things that he says, where
you should be extra careful, trying to make friends,'' said A.
Joseph Fortunato, a former Democratic state legislator who is
publisher of The Italian Tribune, a weekly newspaper based in
Newark. ``Sometimes flippant remarks like that are indicative of
what his actual feelings are.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Corzine's apology _ delivered at a news conference where he
received the endorsement of Unite, a union representing about
15,000 garment-industry workers statewide _ drew mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by reporters to clarify his offensive statements,
Corzine declined, and became increasingly tongue-tied as he
deviated from a prepared statement. ``I shouldn't have said what I
am reported to have said,'' he said. ``And if I did, I apologized
for them, and I apologize for them again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Florio, who is Italian-American and who remains well ahead of
Corzine in the polls, seized on Corzine's missteps again Thursday.
``I know enough people who have been subject to bitter treatment
over their lives to not regard this as humorous,'' he said. ``I
don't think it is befitting anyone who would like to be a lawmaker
in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, supporters of Corzine on Thursday impugned the
motives of those who had come forward with the allegations about
his slurs against Italians.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Fumosa, a former president of the New Jersey Sons of Italy
who was one of several people who quoted Corzine making a
derogatory remark at a dinner with several Italian-Americans last
July, acknowledged Thursday that he had since been rebuffed in an
attempt to have the Corzine campaign hire a friend of his.
</P>
<P>
   But he said one had nothing to do with the other. ``It did
happen, though, really,'' he said of Corzine's slur.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Giblin, the state Democratic chairman, said that Fumosa had
asked him to put the same friend on the state Democratic
committee's payroll as recently as 10 days ago. ``Their hands
aren't clean either,'' Giblin said of Fumosa and other accusers of
Corzine. ``When you have this much indignation, how come you keep
it shelved for six months, and when you don't get a job, you use
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph V. Doria Jr., the assembly minority leader and mayor of
Bayonne, accused the Florio campaign of engineering the
disclosures, but offered no proof. ``I have Italian-American
credentials you don't have and no one else has,'' Doria said,
before listing his parentage of immigrants, his affiliations with
fraternal organizations, and his Legion of Merit award from the
Italian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``A politician having dinner, having a discussion, and making a
misstatement, that doesn't offend me,'' he said. ``It offends me
when people use it as an issue politically.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the strangest sideline to Thursday's drama of traded
accusations and reciprocal indignation, Corzine (pronounced
CORE-zyne), who grew up on a farm in Illinois, provided a little
more information about his own roots. the question, however,
remained, how he could have survived 25 years making small talk in
a state as ethnically diverse as New Jersey without finding out for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said that his mother's lineage was English, and that his
grandmother was a member of the Daughters of the American
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   As for his surname: ``My father used to argue that we were
French,'' he said. ``Everyone else says we're Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   What does he think he is, Corzine was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``For certain,'' he said with a sheepish grin, ``I am Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
