<SLUG> BC-CRANBERRY-LIMITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRANBERRY GROWERS SEEK LIMIT ON MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cranberry industry has asked the US Agriculture Department
to impose limits that could reduce this year's projected crop by
about 15 percent, or 500,000 barrels, Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc.
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed market limit is a bid to ease a crisis caused by a
huge cranberry glut. In only a few years, the price growers receive
could drop by nearly 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The restriction was agreed to in a meeting of industry leaders
in Minnesota Thursday. The proposal needs the approval of
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ocean Spray, a Lakeville-based cooperative of
growers, Glickman has promised to respond to the industry's
request, though no timetable has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Under the market-limit proposal, a complex formula would allow
cranberry growers to bring to market this year only about 85
percent of their average production from previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Glickman were to approve the industry's recommendation,
Robert Hawthorne, Ocean Spray's president and chief executive,
cautioned that such market limits would ease the situation but not
resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   To boost demand, the industry agreed to invest an unspecified
amount of money into a joint marketing campaign to promote
cranberry consumption, Ocean Spray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cranberry industry has come together for the good of
growers,'' Hawthorne said in a statement. ``We have set aside our
competitive differences to meet this crisis head-on together.''
</P>
<P>
   Local growers were reluctant to comment Thursday on the
industry's proposal until they had time to scrutinize it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, at an earlier meeting, industry leaders failed to
reach a consensus on market limits. At that time, some local
growers expressed concern that some proposals on the table would
have benefitted Wisconsin at the expense of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Many cranberry operations in Massachusetts are much smaller than
those in Canada and Wisconsin, now the nation's largest
cranberry-growing state. According to some local growers, a market
limit could favor big growers.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Decas, a grower who also owns a cranberry processing
plant in Wareham, Mass., noted that cranberry production in
Massachusetts has held steady at just under 2 million barrels in
recent years. The surplus, he contended, has resulted from growers
in Wisconsin and Canada expanding operations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Decas, the market limit could force small, local
growers to subsidize the out-of-state growers who are largely
responsible for the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, many growers got more than $60 for a 100-pound barrel
of berries. This year, barrel prices could dip below $20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LUMINEX31-COX     03-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUMINEX31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas biotech company braves market drop, raises $76.5 million
in IPO
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin-based Luminex Corp. braved an unfavorable
stock market Thursday with its initial public stock offering, but
the company's shares still managed a 34.5 percent rise from the
opening price of $17.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old company raised $76.5 million in its offering of
4.5 million shares, the first IPO by a local biotech company. The
stock price rose as high as $26 before closing at $22.88, up $5.88
in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   But Luminex was one bright spot a cloudy day, as investors sent
many technology stocks tumbling. The Nasdaq Composite Index fell
186.78 to 4,457.89 and the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down
38.47 at 10,980.25. Local stocks also fell, led by NetSolve Inc.
and Crossroads Systems Inc., which dropped 13.3 and 8.5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the market's weakness Thursday, investors have been
bullish recently on biotech companies, which are developing
promising drugs and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Luminex makes tools that simplify biological testing and that
can help in detecting genetic variations and diagnosing diseases.
The market for those tools, valued by some analysts at $7.8 billion
in 1998, is expected to grow annually by 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech is coming into its own because it's resulting in real
products, not just research like it was in the 1980s,'' said Gail
Bronson, senior analyst at investment research company IPO Monitor
in California. ``We're starting to see things move from a trickle
to a torrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every company wanted to tough it out in this week's soft
market for tech stocks, in which the Nasdaq index is down almost
400 points. Drugabuse Sciences Inc. postponed its IPO until next
week, a move some analysts attributed to the market drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always too uncertain as to when things are going to
improve again,'' Bronson said. ``But Luminex had to go out
sometime, and I think they just figured, 'What the heck.'''
</P>
<P>
   After the offering, led by Warburg Dillon Read, Luminex had 26.7
million outstanding shares worth roughly $611 million, based on the
day's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Mark Chandler owns 14.6 percent of the company.
Other major shareholders of record include investment banker G.
Walter Loewenbaum, who represents a partnership that owns a
14.3-percent stake, and Van Chandler, vice-president of
instruments, who owns 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company posted a net loss of $9.2 million in 1999 on revenue
of $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's first ever biotech IPO offers evidence that the area's
long-awaited development of biotech companies may be taking root.
</P>
<P>
   For years, pundits pegged the Austin-San Marcos corridor as an
up-and-coming biotechnology center, but an Austin biotech boom
never took hold, in part because the area lacks a major medical
school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Luminex debut and a related IPO _ Introgen
Therapeutics Inc. _ in the pipeline, the local biotech community
seems to be picking up steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to describe this as a major defining
moment,'' said Matt Winkler, chief executive of Austin's Ambion
Inc. ``We're past the stage of just founding biotech companies here
_ now they're starting to IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
