<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS PEACEFULLY HOLD FINAL BIO2000 MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Bio2000 wound down Thursday, protesters dressed in
biohazard suits and carrying a black coffin labeled
``biodiversity'' made a final 20-minute march downtown.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 demonstrators opposed to wide use of genetically
altered foods peacefully met with a line of 20 police officers next
to the convention center where the five-day conference was held.
``We are just trying to save you,'' said one protester as she tried
to hand out pamphlets to street onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last day for us to make a statement,'' said Markus
Nechay, who was dressed in a blue lab coat with ``Doctor Gene''
written on the back. He got the lab coat from his mother, who was a
biochemist.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology Industry
Organization, which sponsored the conference, said those who
marched outside were actually the ``kind of people you can speak
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention center, demonstrators managed to get into
the last scheduled luncheon and disrupted actor David Lander _
Squiggy on the 1970s hit TV show ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley'' _during his
speech about a new biotech drug he is using to treat multiple
sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the protesters apparently had forged conference badges
and ran up on the speaker's stage to denounce corporations making
biotech drugs. They were immediately escorted away.
</P>
<P>
   Feldbaum said he applauded the Boston police for its
``sensitive'' job this week of keeping the peace while allowing
demonstrators the chance to voice their objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for one lone incident at lunch, it was utterly
peaceful. It was the industry's best meeting,'' said Feldbaum.
</P>
</TEXT>
