<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-COMPARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER BUSH OR GORE, U.S. TO GET NEW ROLE IN EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush likes to say that if elected president he has no
intention of serving as the nation's schools superintendent,
dispatching the apparatchiks of the federal government to play a
role that is better left to school board members.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore suggests that it is teachers, and not bureaucrats and
politicians, who would be empowered and gain respect in his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But their protestations to the contrary, with Bush or Gore as
president, the federal government would have a more forceful
presence in U.S. classrooms than in previous administrations.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to suggest that Gore and Bush are in complete
accord on education. Bush's vision is much less expensive and
relies more heavily than Gore's on holding schools responsible for
student performance. Gore, who is more interested in testing
teachers than students, proposes a wider array of federal programs
than Bush does.
</P>
<P>
   But each is taking his party in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, taking a more hands-on approach than his conservative
Republican allies, this week proposed a national reading initiative
with the kind of sweep and urgency more likely to roll off the lips
of a Democrat. He would spend more than $1 billion a year for five
years to train teachers to diagnose illiteracy in young children
and to remedy such problems in individual classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he proposed nearly $600 million a year in
additional aid to education, most of it for teacher training, but
also to give teachers tax deductions for out-of-pocket expenses on
school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Photocopying and enlarging a page from the winning playbook he
wrote as governor of Texas, Bush had already announced that he
would encourage states to give standardized tests in reading and
math to all students in grades three through eight _ any state that
refused would lose five percent of its federal education money _
and would compel the districts to publish the results.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also the first leading Republican to call for increasing
the budget and responsibilities of the federal Department of
Education, which became a discrete Cabinet agency in the Carter
administration; for years, the Republican party has called for the
department's abolition.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a Democrat whose party has a long
history of supporting the Department of Education and of shaping
policy at the classroom level, would immerse his administration
even deeper into the day-to-day operations of districts and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Taking, in effect, a seat at dozens of collective bargaining
tables around the country, he would award ``signing bonuses'' of
$10,000 each to 75,000 new teachers who agreed to work in
inner-city and rural schools, and he would increase salaries for
thousands of other veteran teachers whose districts mounted
aggressive improvement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would also lean on school districts to break their largest
high schools into smaller academies, giving financial incentives to
those that developed such blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems,'' said Michael Beschloss, a historian of
the presidency, ``that there is a general consensus between the two
sides that education is so important that even if, in general, you
feel it is a good thing for power to go away from Washington and to
states and localities, that here is a case in which ideology may
bend to necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   But each only bends so far.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush refrains from using the politically laden term
``vouchers,'' he has proposed making taxpayer spending on students
at failing public schools a ``portable'' expense. Bush would
provide students from low-ranking public schools that post no
improvement for three years with $1,500 annually to attend a
private school.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, supported heavily by teachers' unions, adamantly opposes
vouchers, which, the unions argue, would siphon money and jobs from
public education and would violate the Constitution by using the
state to subsidize the church.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would make available $25 billion in bonds to pay for new
school construction and modernization in urban and rural districts
where classrooms are falling apart from age. Bush, in keeping with
a Republican Congress that has steadfastly refused to take on such
a role, has made no such provision.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has spoken of raising federal education spending by $115
billion, about 50 percent, over 10 years. Bush has said his
investment would be significant but more modest, increasing
spending by $13 billion over five years, with money for his
``portability'' program shifted from existing education programs
for poor students.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Bush, and not Gore, who would attempt to hold schools
more accountable. Not only would Bush set financial penalties for
schools that did not demonstrate improvement on standardized tests,
but he would also insist that they separate the performance of
minority children so that diverse schools could not coast on the
high scores of some white children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in evaluating teachers, would rely more heavily on the
reviews they received from peers than on the test scores of their
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush beats Gore hands down on accountability,'' said Amy
Wilkins, a principal partner of the Education Trust, a nonpartisan
organization that closely monitors policies affecting poor
children. ``Gore beats Bush on money. If you mash them both
together, maybe you have something that will benefit kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither,'' she added, ``are sufficient answers in
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his party's resistance to federal interference at the
local level, it is Bush's position that is a more pronounced
departure from conventional thinking.
</P>
<P>
   To Beschloss, the historian, Bush's attempts to remake the
federal role hark back somewhat to Dwight Eisenhower. It was
Eisenhower who, concerned about the Soviet challenge represented by
the unmanned Sputnik spacecraft, defied the Republican Party by
concentrating far more on federal help for math and science
instruction than the party would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's involvement at the local level would have clear
limits. While arm-twisting states to give tests to students, for
example, he would leave it to the states themselves to write the
tests and define what constitutes improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Gore face stiff challenges in Congress, as each
would rely on the federal budget surplus to finance most school
initiatives, at a time when Congress has no shortage of designs on
that money.
</P>
<P>
   But each also faces the challenge of changing the perception of
the federal role: as it stands now, the $23.5 billion that the
federal government spends yearly on elementary and secondary
education represents just 8 cents of every dollar spent in schools.
That, many state and local superintendents believe, entitles the
president to a degree of influence that is directly proportional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
