<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY'S HIGHEST-RANKING WOMAN ACCUSES FELLOW GENERAL OF SEXUAL
HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Texas, Ariz.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army's highest-ranking woman, Lt. Gen. Claudia
Kennedy, whose career is often cited as an example of the expanding
opportunities for women in uniform, has filed a sexual harassment
complaint against another Army general, accusing him of groping her
in her office in 1996, Pentagon and government officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy complained informally to her superiors when the incident
allegedly occurred in 1996 and then filed a formal harassment
complaint late last year, when the other officer received a
prominent new assignment, according two officials familiar with the
case. In 1996, both officers held the lesser rank of major general,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's accusation threatens to become a huge new
embarrassment for the Army, which, like the other armed services,
has been roiled in recent years by sexual scandals, charges of
harassment and accusations of double standards when the accused is
a senior officer.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have in recent years sought to portray the
overwhelmingly male-dominated military as more open than ever to
women, even at the highest ranks. For a woman as senior as Kennedy
to have filed a complaint of harassment against another senior
officer seriously undercuts the impression they hoped to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a zero tolerance for harassment,'' the Pentagon's
spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said Thursday during a news conference in
which he refused to identify the accused general and repeatedly
sidestepped questions about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After Kennedy filed her complaint, the Army's inspector
general's office began an investigation and has since interviewed
several people who were involved or were familiar with the
circumstances, officials said. Because of the ranks of those
involved, the Department of Defense's inspector general is
overseeing the Army's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are continuing their work and have not yet reached
a conclusion on the merits of the accusation, according to the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Army and Pentagon officials cited the privacy rights of the
accused general in declining to identify him. The Army declined to
discuss the case publicly at all, refusing to either confirm or
General Kennedy's complaint, which was first reported Thursday in
The Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't comment on the existence of investigations,'' said
Col. Edwin Veiga, an Army spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is one of only three women in the military who now serve
as three-star officers. The others are Vice Adm. Patricia Tracey of
the Navy, who serves as deputy assistant secretary of defense for
personnel, and Lt. Gen. Leslie Kenne, commander of the Air Force's
Electronic System Center at Hanscom Air Force Base in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 52, has served as the Army's deputy chief of staff for
intelligence since her promotion to lieutenant general in May 1997.
She was the first woman to reach that rank in the Army. She
recently announced that she intends to retire later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Kennedy served at the Pentagon as the Army's assistant
deputy chief of staff for intelligence. After the incident now in
question, she chose to handle the matter internally, reporting it
to her superiors in the Army staff, according to one official
familiar with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, Kennedy was satisfied with the results at the time.
It was only when the officer's name came up for a prominent
assignment last year, the official said, that she filed a complaint
with the Army's inspector general's office, which is supposed to
operate independently of the Army's chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by The New York Times for comment, Kennedy declined to
discuss her accusation.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews after her promotion to lieutenant general,
however, she said that she had experienced sexual harassment in her
career. In an interview with ABC in June 1997, she said she had
dealt with an incident earlier in her career ``individually'' and
then alluded to what appeared to be this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important thing about it was that early in my
career, what I did was I dealt with it individually,'' she said.
``And later in my career, in fact in the last _ just in the last _
within the last 10 years, my approach was to turn it over to my
boss. And I was very impressed with the way it was handled. In
other words, it was investigated carefully, and there was a very
positive response on the part of the Army. ``Anytime someone is
sexually harassed, it is a very serious matter,'' she continued.
``When we think about sexual harassment, sometimes we're distracted
by the word `sexual,' and we think that this is a matter of very
aggressive courting or dating or flirting. It has nothing to do
with the interactions between men and women that are of mutual
interest. This has everything to do with nonmutual activity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy joined the Army in 1969 after receiving a bachelor's
degree in philosophy from what is now known as Rhodes College in
Tennessee. At the time of her induction, the Army had a separate
Women's Corps and opportunities for women were relatively limited.
</P>
<P>
   She rose through the ranks as a military intelligence officer,
one of the few elite career paths then open to women. She
eventually became commander of two military intelligence
battalions, in Germany and Hawaii, as well as commander of the San
Antonio Recruiting Battalion at Fort Sam Houston in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After being promoted to brigadier general in 1993, she held
staff positions in the intelligence field, serving for a time as
assistant commandant of the Army's Intelligence School at Fort
Huachuca, Az.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has been buffeted by controversies over sexual
behavior, including highly publicized rape and assault cases at the
Army's Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland beginning in 1996 and
the sexual assault trial in 1997 of its senior enlisted man, Sgt.
Maj. Gene McKinney, who was acquitted at a court martial of all
charges except one of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the Army has twice demoted generals for having
adulterous affairs. Maj. Gen. John Maher 3rd was stripped of two
ranks and forced to retire last November after having affairs with
two subordinate officers' wives and ``an improper personnel
relationship'' with an enlisted soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. David R.E. Hale, was demoted one rank and fined after
pleading guilty to eight counts of misconduct stemming from affairs
he had with the wives of four subordinate officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Army had allowed Hale to retire quietly even though a
complaint about his behavior had been filed with the inspector
general's office. Once the accusations became public, the Army
called him out of retirement to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for expanding the role of women in the military said
Kennedy's complaint suggested the military still had far to go to
root out harassment and bias.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy ``broke the glass ceiling but still was not immune from
sexual harassment,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y. ``It took
courage to come forward and file a complaint knowing her own
reputation would be the first on the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
