<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-SELENA-ANNIVERSARY-TE     03-30 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-ANNIVERSARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNIVERSARY PROMPTS A LOOK AT THE LEGACY OF SELENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ADRIANA TORREZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ The little girl stood under the arches
of the memorial overlooking Corpus Christi Bay, letting the strong
breeze hit her face and play with her hair.
</P>
<P>
   She turned and clambered atop the statue of Tejano singer
Selena, hugged it for a brief moment, and then outlined the face
with her fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Amris Chacon, 6, is an avid Selena fan. She listens to her CDs
and frequently watches the movie about the singer's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the part where she dies, so that's where I turn
it off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Selena Quintanilla Perez was fatally shot in a Corpus Christi
motel March 31, 1995, when Amris was 1 year old. Yolanda Saldivar,
the former manager of Selena's clothing boutiques and president of
her fan club, is serving a life sentence in a Texas prison.
</P>
<P>
   Amris is among the loyal fans who keep Selena's memory alive.
</P>
<P>
   Selena was a perennial winner at the Tejano Music Awards from
1986 to 1995. Her album ``Selena Live'' won a 1994 Grammy as
orchestra album of the year. One month before her death, she
performed before a record crowd of more than 61,000 people at the
Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   But many Americans learned of her only after her death at age
23, and the tremendous outpouring of mourning it spawned.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 people viewed the casket at the Bayfront Plaza
Convention Center in Corpus Christi. ``People'' magazine published
its first-ever regional cover, with Selena on the front in the
Southwest edition. The edition sold out in one day. A subsequent
Selena tribute issue sold 1 million copies nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Rincon, research psychologist with the market research
firm Rincon &AMP; Associates in Dallas, said that Selena's popularity
greatly affected the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She demonstrated to the world that there are dollars
associated with Latinos, a population that many were used to
relating to negative things like poverty and voter apathy,'' Rincon
said. ``She made the connection between Latin entertainers and
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena's father and manager, Abraham Quintanilla, agreed that
much of America was unaware of his daughter before her death, and
inattentive to the Hispanic market in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think corporate America had yet caught on to such a
large, untapped market,'' Quintanilla said. ``After Selena's tragic
death and the commotion in the media, they were freaking out. I
think that was the beginning of the `Latino explosion.' After all
this happened, everyone started paying attention to Latinos.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintanilla should know. He owns Q-Productions, a recording and
production studio that also represents eight bands, including the
Kumbia Kings, a band that mixes Latin rhythms with hip-hop, funk
and rhythm and blues. His son A.B. is a member of the band, created
after the death of Selena and the disintegration of her band Los
Dinos, in which he played bass and wrote many of the songs.
</P>
<P>
   The Kumbia Kings' album, ``Amor, Familia y Respeto,'' is eighth
on Billboard's Latin 50.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perez, Selena's widower, is also part of a new bilingual
rock band, the Chris Perez Band, which won a Grammy this year for
best Latin/alternative performance for its debut album,
``Resurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perez, who has worked hard to re-establish himself as a
musician, believes that his success _ and that of other Latin
artists such as Ricky Martin, Marc Anthony and Jennifer Lopez _ has
more to do with talent than with an increased interest in Latin
music.
</P>
<P>
   For Selena's fans, talent is what made her a star.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Cotto, a longtime fan from Waco who was in Corpus Christi
to visit Selena's memorial, museum, gravesite and boutique, said
she admired the singer's versatility and musical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a way with people,'' Cotto said. ``She had that
charisma about the audience, and she brought in the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think of where she could have been today. I think
she would have gone really far.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Miranda, public relations manager for ``People en
Espanol,'' said the reaction to Selena's solidified the decision to
launch the Spanish-language magazine. It had been in the research
phase at the time of Selena's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proved what some people in the company had been feeling all
along, that there was a dynamic market that did not have a national
magazine to call its own,'' she said. ``It told a great story that
Latinos were ready, that when you printed information that was
relevant, they would go out and buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rincon has noted that in the years since Selena's death, more
companies have become interested in the Hispanic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past five years we are seeing more internet companies
targeting Hispanics, more telecommunications companies,'' he said.
Companies such as SBC Communications, GE Directories and US West
have hired his firm to study the Hispanic market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery stores such as Fiesta and Carnival have been pioneers in
targeting Hispanics, Rincon said. In the Fort Worth/Dallas area,
Hispanics spent an estimated $1 billion on groceries last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, stores such as Albertson's are trying to access
the booming market, setting up stores in mostly ethnic
neighborhoods and advertising in Spanish-language media.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon also mentioned that, in the past five years, audience
shares for Spanish-language media have increased dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Navarrete , president of the Fort Worth Hispanic Chamber
of Commerce, said the huge media blitz focusing on Selena's death
prompted many companies to review information about the Hispanic
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely motivated people and made them aware of how
profitable the market can be,'' he said, adding that he recently
met with an architect interested in building affordable housing in
Fort Worth for Hispanic families, which he said tend to be younger
in age and larger than most Anglo families.
</P>
<P>
   For Rincon, Selena was representative of this growing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hispanics are excited about something, they buy in record
numbers,'' he said. ``When we're passionate about something, we can
really make a lot of noise.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
