<HEADER>
A2760 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-LAWNCARE-ASBESTOS-SPI     03-30 1989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWNCARE-ASBESTOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIALLY LETHAL ASBESTOS FOUND IN SOME LAWN AND GARDEN
PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER and CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Federal investigators have found potentially lethal
asbestos in several lawn and garden products that contain
vermiculite, a mineral used in hundreds of such products
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency stressed that its
findings are preliminary and that weeks of additional testing need
to be performed to determine how widespread and serious the problem
is.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial results raised alarms with public-health
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is cause for concern,'' said Dr. Christine
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, assistant clinical professor of medicine at Harvard
Medical School, who has about 600 patients with asbestos-caused
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no safe level of asbestos exposure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA findings could explain some of the so-called
``spontaneous'' tumors that arise in people who have no known
exposure to asbestos, Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contention is they are not arising spontaneously and these
data support that,'' she said. ``Who would have known asbestos was
in these products?''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA declined to name the brands tested, or to release the
levels of asbestos found. ``I can only say that some of the samples
showed asbestos at varying levels,'' says Phil Wong, who heads the
investigation and engineering unit in Seattle that did the tests.
Wong said the results are ``being turned over to the risk
assessment analysts, so we don't really know what the dangers
are.''
</P>
<P>
   No asbestos warnings
</P>
<P>
   None of the products tested carried labels warning consumers
that it contained asbestos, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   After the first results came in, the investigators repeated the
tests and confirmed the findings. The types of asbestos found were
fibrous actinolite and tremolite, both classified as carcinogens by
several government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've completed multiple tests of multiple products ... by two
different methods of microscopic examination, and asbestos was
found in several of the products,'' says Keven McDemott, who is
heading the team of EPA investigators examining the products.
</P>
<P>
   In its followup testing, the EPA will work with other agencies
to evaluate the level of health hazards from the commonly sold soil
additives.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the three vermiculite mines currently operating in the
United States will receive additional scrutiny from the EPA and the
Mine Safety and Health Administration, officials said. MSHA
recently initiated a new round of testing at the mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our role is to protect human health. If there's something out
there that may be a risk to the public _ and asbestos is a major
concern right now _ our job is to address it,'' says Chuck Findley,
EPA deputy regional administrator in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committing whatever resources we have to get it right
the first time, and that's why we're doing this additional testing.
Obviously we'll continue to do what it takes at the regional and
national levels to address the public's concern about asbestos in
consumer products.''
</P>
<P>
   If asbestos is present in consumer products, even as a
contaminant, the bags should be labeled so people are aware of the
hazards, said Dr. Mike Harbut, chair of the
Occupational/Environmental Section of the American College of Chest
Physicians, and a clinical assistant professor of medicine at Wayne
State University in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fundamental,'' he said. ``It's an issue of ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern from mine stories
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the safety of vermiculite was sparked by
Post-Intelligencer stories in November about a now-closed W.R.
Grace &AMP; Co. mine in Libby, Mont., where more than 300 miners and
their family members contracted fatal diseases including
asbestosis, cancer and mesothelioma because of their exposure to
tremolite asbestos fibers in the vermiculite ore.
</P>
<P>
   EPA's results confirm similar tests of several brands of potting
soil, soil enhancers and vermiculite conducted by the
Post-Intelligencer from December through March as part of the
newspaper's ongoing investigation of asbestos dangers in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got numerous calls from citizens who had read about the
deaths in Libby and asked if there was asbestos in garden products,
will they be exposed to it and will they become sick from it,''
McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We answered two of the three questions. Yes, there is asbestos
in some of the products. And, yes, in using the product the way
many people do, asbestos can be released. The last question, will
they be harmed if exposed to the asbestos, will have to be answered
by the health experts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those health authorities will be faced with assessing the
hazards of such activities as handling the products, picking or
eating plants grown with the products, and tilling previously
treated soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, if you used it even one time you could be at
risk. But the more times people are exposed, and the longer they
are around the product, the greater their risk of developing an
asbestos-related disease, including lung cancer,'' said Harvard's
Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Drew Brodkin, associate professor of internal medicine and
environmental health at the University of Washington, said there
shouldn't be asbestos in those products, but more study is needed
before public health officials can make any recommendations about
what consumers should do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that everyone should run out and get a chest
x-ray,'' said Brodkin. ``It does take substantial exposure over
time (to cause disease.) That's not to say people are not at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For weekend gardeners, the risk may not be that significant,''
he said. ``However, the risk would be greater for people who did
extensive work with these products, such as nursery workers.''
</P>
<P>
   At New York's Mount Sinai Selikoff Center for Occupational and
Environmental Medicine, which did most of the major early studies
on the health hazards of asbestos, medical director Dr. Stephen
Levin says the dry, dusty composition of the vermiculite increases
the chance of inhalation of asbestos fibers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more of that stuff you inhale, over the course of a spring
and a summer, the greater your risk. The higher the fiber counts,
the worse the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite with gardeners
</P>
<P>
   Horticultural industry analysts estimate that at least 65 local,
regional and national companies produce more then 375 different
lawn and garden products containing vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners have been using vermiculite for decades. The puffy
material is popular because of its ability to hold water and
fertilizer, pesticides and as an aid in aeration and drainage. No
fertilizers or pesticides have been tested yet, but are expected to
be included in subsequent tests.
</P>
<P>
   Vermiculite, which is mica-like in appearance, is a natural
material which has the unique characteristic of expanding 15 times
in size when exposed to heat.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that any of the manufacturers added
asbestos to their products. The lethal fibers are a contaminant of
the vermiculite used in the products.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest vermiculite mine is located in the
northeastern corner of South Africa. It produces ore that is highly
concentrated, and therefore more expensive. Some U.S. companies buy
it, but many say they purchase ore from the Grace mine in Enoree,
S.C., or from Virginia Vermiculite's mines in Louisa, Va., and near
Enoree, owned by Robert Sansom.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies insist that their ore is free of asbestos. Both
cite analysis that they paid for in laboratories in Canada, Denmark
and Scotland, which, they say, show no asbestos in their
vermiculite. Both companies point to tests by EPA and MSHA as
evidence to support their views.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 16 letter to the Post-Intelligencer, Sansom, a former
associate EPA administrator, pointed to ``MSHA test results from
1984 to 1998.'' Grace sent the Post-Intelligencer the results of
MSHA sampling done on workers at its South Carolina mine on March
7.
</P>
<P>
   No asbestos was detected in the air-collection cartridges used
to sample the air where the miners work.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean there is no asbestos in the ore? MSHA says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone is saying that our air sampling is giving them a
clean bill of health, of saying there is no asbestos in their ore,
it's totally inaccurate. It's ludicrous to think that clean results
on air sampling means that there is not asbestos or some other
contaminant in the ore,'' says Earnest Teaster, MSHA Administrator
for metal and non-metal mine safety and health.
</P>
<P>
   MSHA inspectors did gather samples of ore from stockpiles on the
Grace mine property, which showed no asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is not to issue a seal of approval for the quality or
lack of contamination of the ore they're selling,'' says Davitt
McAteer, MSHA's boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this testing means is that at that time and at that
location, no asbestos was detected. No one, not for a moment,
should interpret that to mean that this agency is certifying their
mine as asbestos-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the EPA regions responsible for Virginia and South
Carolina said there was no indication the agency had inspected any
of the vermiculite mines in recent years. EPA studies on
vermiculite mines were done in 1981, 1982 and 1991. The studies
showed the presence of asbestos at Grace's Enoree mine, but at
levels far lower than those at Libby.
</P>
<P>
   `We have an obligation'
</P>
<P>
   McAteer said his agency is eager to work with EPA to determine
whether there is asbestos contamination at the three mines, and
apparently, EPA is willing to check the mines out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asbestos is a toxic substance and if it's in commercial
products, we have an obligation to look as far back as it takes, to
get to the bottom of where it's coming from,'' said John Melone,
EPA director of National Programs, Chemical Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that product leaves the mine, someone is putting it into
commerce,'' Melone said. ``Whoever that someone is, whether they
own the mine or not, that person is responsible for knowing what is
in the product. And we have a right to ask for that information.''
</P>
<P>
   The vermiculite testing is part of a coast-to-coast EPA
examination of common household items. Additional testing of
non-horticultural products for asbestos is being conducted in
Dallas, Boston and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA ``has on-going concerns about asbestos in consumer
products'' and ``is undertaking a nationwide effort to sample and
evaluate a wide range of products to determine if they contain
levels of asbestos that pose significant risks to public health,''
says Jim Aidala, an acting assistant EPA administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the findings of the studies presently under way, EPA
stands ready to address the risks that may be identified,'' Aidala
added. ``Actions could range from the dissemination of consumer
information regarding these products to potential regulatory
controls.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA has a long, turbulent history of trying to regulate asbestos
and in the past has had a ban against asbestos overturned on a
technicality and other efforts stifled by the White House or
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   There is much hand-wringing in headquarters over the asbestos
testing being done in the field. Some agency officials fear that if
the Seattle results hold up, EPA will have to assume the costly
role of protecting the public from asbestos, a responsibility
abandoned years ago by the Consumer Product Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   When CPSC was asked in January whether it had checked garden
products containing vermiculite for asbestos, spokesman Ken Giles
said, ``We couldn't find anything in the files, but one scientist
remembered someone looking at garden products about 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they found anything,'' Giles said.
</P>
</TEXT>
