<HEADLINE>
READY OR NOT, BUCKY GOES TO THE FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Bucky doesn't ordinarily do Final Fours.
</P>
<P>
   Bucky does Frozen Fours. Although, as all good Eagles know,
Boston College has shattered this year's dream.
</P>
<P>
   Bucky does Rose Bowls, too. What would New Year's Day be without
some nice camera shots of all those Cheeseheads?
</P>
<P>
   Bucky's grandfather won an NCAA basketball championship in 1941,
but our Bucky does not know from Final Fours. Not at a school that
has only had four 20-win seasons in its history, not at a school
whose team exited last year's NCAA tournament having scored a
gruesome 32 points, not at a school whose team was 11-10 at one
point this season, and not at a school where the coach's methods
have been met with near-universal skepticism from the day he was
hired.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, ``Bucky.'' This is the symbolic nickname of the
Wisconsin Badgers. You know, ``Bucky Badger.'' The school's
athletic teams are generally referred to this way, as in ``Bucky's
got to start doing better on third down,'' or ``Bucky let in some
soft goals against BC,'' or ``Did you see the way Bucky shut down
LSU?''
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, Bucky is going to the Final Four, and people
hereabouts don't need written instructions to learn the best way to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like a football game in here last Saturday
night,'' said Eric Suemmicht, who tends bar at the Nitty Gritty, an
eating and drinking establishment one block from Kohl Center, the
school's 17,000-seat showplace athletic arena. ``People were
calling from Milwaukee. They just wanted to be here, so they could
celebrate on State Street. That's the way it works here. Six days a
year, Madison is their town. They come in early. They start
drinking at 11 a.m., and they're still going strong at 6. That's
the way it was last Saturday. The (Purdue) game was late afternoon
here and we were full at 2 or 2:30. The game ended, and everybody
piled out to go celebrate on State Street. Then a half-hour later
everybody came back here and continued to celebrate. We don't
ordinarily have that going on for basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never been a big basketball state, and Wisconsin has
never been a big basketball school,'' said Marsh Shapiro, a Madison
native and longtime local sportscaster who owns the Nitty Gritty.
``It's always been difficult to find not just good players, but to
find some who could cut it academically.''
</P>
<P>
   But this group is demonstrating that Bucky can play basketball,
too, and when Bucky growls, the entire state of Wisconsin snaps to
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is having a terrific impact,'' said Clark Chesley, who
runs Badger Sporting Goods, a leading supplier of equipment for
Wisconsin high schools and colleges. ``I travel all over the state.
I just came back from Tomahawk, a small town about three hours
north of here. The first thing I would hear was `How about those
Badgers?' And not just the basketball team. It was also, `What
happened to the hockey team?' People care very deeply about
Wisconsin sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everything,'' said Shapiro. ``This is the state capitol,
but there isn't a lot of industry. There's Oscar Mayer, Rayovac,
and some insurance companies. There are several major research
parks. But this is very much a university town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought about it,'' said junior guard Mike Kelley,
the acclaimed defensive pest. ``Wisconsin matters here. What we're
doing is real important. But it's been 59 years since we've won
anything. So you wonder, `Could we become a basketball state?' It's
a great thrill to see the smiles on everyone's faces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given people reason to be proud of the basketball
team,'' said junior forward Mark Vershaw. ``Now people can go out
and buy basketball shirts, instead of football jerseys. Kids can go
out in their back yards and pretend to be Mike Kelley or Andy
Kowske. People can get on the phone and tell their brother in LA
all about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley reveals that even if no one else believed a Wisconsin
basketball team could get this far, Dick Bennett and his coaching
staff certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we juniors were being recruited, they took us into the
locker room,'' said Kelley. ``They had jerseys with our names over
each locker. They played a mock play-by-play from a Final Four
scenario in which we were all involved. Kelley to Kowske to Linton
to Vershaw. He shoots. It's good! Wisconsin wins the national
championship!
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at each other and said, `Man!' Our heads were
spinning. Then we started playing as freshmen, and we realized just
how hard a thing like getting to the Final Four really was. But the
hope never really died, and here we are _ in the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Kelley and his friends know all too well, nobody in
Madison was fantasizing about the Final Four when the team was
11-10, following a loss to Ohio State Feb. 2. The National
Invitation Tournament was starting to sound pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers seemed to be confirming the belief that Bennett was
the wrong man in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just hated the team's playing style,'' said Paul Zach,
co-owner of the popular Avenue Bar, a definite Bucky kind of place.
``People were coming in here and saying you could never win with
that style and he could never get the athletes to compete in the
Big Ten. They said the system was outdated.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the doubters was Bob Mueller, whose opinion counts for a
lot. Mueller was a freshman when Wisconsin won the NCAA
championship in 1941. He wasn't eligible to play, but he practiced
against Fred Rehm, John Kotz, Gene Englund, and all the rest, and
he has remained a loyal Badger follower, holding season tickets the
past 49 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think we'd ever win with Dick Bennett?'' he said. ``You
want an honest opinion?''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Bob, what do you think?
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is no. I was skeptical. I thought they played
defense so hard they couldn't relax and play offense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from the doubters and the rumblings as to whether
Dick Bennett has a future here to total ecstasy,'' said Shapiro,
who swears that he personally never lost faith. ``It's a total love
affair.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, people really wanted to like Bennett, who counts as
one of them even if he had the misfortune of being born in
Pittsburgh. He went to school here (Ripon), coached high school
basketball in Green Bay, coached nine years at the University of
Wisconsin-Stevens Point and 10 years at the University of
Wisconsin-Green Bay before getting the job of his dreams in 1995.
In ways that matter a great deal in this state, he is perfect for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Wisconsin-Platteville, a member of Bennett's
old Division 3 state college conference, lies about an hour and 15
minutes southwest of Madison. On a recent blustery day,
Wisconsin-Platteville's baseball team was practicing in the wind
and rain on Kendall Murray Field, but the players were more than
eager to talk about the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone on the campus is excited,'' said Aaron Mack, a junior
from Madison who played high school basketball with Badgers guard
Roy Boone. ``We all feel a connection to Coach Bennett. After all,
he used to coach in this league. We feel his kids aren't really any
different than us. You really want to pull for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most Badger followers, the Platteville kids have become
disciples of the Dick Bennett defensive philosophy. ``Defense is
getting them through,'' said catcher Tony Mitchell, a senior from
Walworth, Wis. ``I think high school coaches all over the state are
looking at this and realizing that defense is the way you win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Roy (Boone),'' said Mack. ``He was always a tough
offensive player, but he wasn't going to play for Coach Bennett
until he started playing the defense. Now he's really helping
out.''
</P>
<P>
   People in Wisconsin weren't excessively demanding. Football has
always come first. Hockey has dominated the winter for years. They
just wanted the basketball team to stop being an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be competitive,'' said Paul Zach of the Avenue
Bar, ``finish in the top half of the Big Ten. Just give us a nice
competitive team. Nobody was looking to go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's where they are, and people in Wisconsin are trying to
put it in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' said Suemmicht, the Nitty Gritty
bartender. ``All year long the hockey team was on Page 1 and the
basketball team was on Page 3. Now you've got to feel sorry for the
hockey players. I would say the football team going to the Rose
Bowl in '93 was the biggest thing around here, but this is very
close. Even with Ron Dayne winning the Heisman and the team going
back to the Rose Bowl, there was a feeling of `We've done that.'
And you could see the Rose Bowl building up. No one saw this
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This overshadows the second Rose Bowl,'' said Zach.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl and Final Four make for a pretty good parlay.
Let's hope Bucky isn't neglecting his studies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
