<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-FUNDRAISING-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI FAR AHEAD OF CLINTON IN FUND   RAISING FOR SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani raised nearly twice as much
money as Hillary Rodham Clinton during the first three months of
this year and has now collected a total of $19 million for his
Senate campaign, according to figures provided by both candidates
Thursday. The latest numbers leave little doubt that Giuliani will
significantly outraise and outspend the first lady in the race in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a lot of people out there who don't like her,'' said
Bruce J. Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager, grinning as he
released the Republican mayor's side of what turned out by day's
end to be a fairly lopsided fund-raising picture.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum said that more than half of Giuliani's total
contributions came from out of state, though he contended that the
strong showing _ news of which clearly unsettled some of Clinton's
supporters _ was as much a tribute to Giuliani as a testament to
Clinton's unpopularity.
</P>
<P>
   He said Giuliani had raised $7 million in the reporting period
required under federal law, from Jan. 1 to March 31, for a total of
$19 million for his campaign. Clinton's campaign aides said she had
raised about $4 million in the period, bringing her total to about
$12 million. The figures do not count millions in additional
so-called soft money contributions, which are largely unregulated,
that the two candidates have been energetically soliciting.
</P>
<P>
   The report by Giuliani was startling, not only because of its
size _ the mayor has already raised more money than Charles Schumer
collected for his entire Senate contest in 1998 _ but also because
the figures appeared to undercut what had once been a widespread
assumption of the contest: that Clinton would raise more money than
Giuliani. Earlier this year, Clinton's advisers had said they were
confident that she would raise $25 million for her campaign; she
has yet to reach the halfway point toward that.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Clinton's campaign manager, Bill de Blasio, said
he was now certain that Giuliani would raise ``at least several
million more dollars'' than Clinton. ``We think they will have a
significant amount more than we have,'' de Blasio said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum called a formal news conference to announce the
figures, which he presented in a series of brightly colored charts,
filled with graphic illustrations that demonstrated the scope of
Giuliani's accomplishment for the sake of the television cameras at
the back of the room. By contrast, Clinton disclosed her figure in
a short statement e-mailed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani now seems certain to break the fund-raising record of
$21 million set in Virginia by a nonincumbent candidate for Senate,
Oliver North, in 1994. He has already surpassed Schumer, who raised
$17 million in his run for Senate in 1998, and his advisers say
they now think that he might end up raising close to $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The splurge of fund raising was condemned Thursday by Theodore
W. Kheel, the former labor negotiator who has taken the lead in
trying to work out an agreement between Clinton and Giuliani to
renounce voluntarily the use of unregulated soft money in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely terrible,'' Kheel said. ``It tells the public
that the electoral process depends on how much money you can raise.
The assumption is that more money will buy the election. It's
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The actual filing period does not end until midnight Friday.
Giuliani's aides said he was putting out the numbers a day early
because he would be in Arizona attending fund-raisers Friday. The
release of what the aides saw as a bit of good news also came as
the mayor has tried to tamp down criticism of his response to the
fatal police shooting of Patrick M. Dorismond earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Because the figures were preliminary, neither campaign was able
to provide what is a critical way to measure the financial health
of a campaign: the amount of cash on hand. But Giuliani seems
likely to enjoy an advantage in this area. Unlike Clinton, Giuliani
has yet to hire much of a campaign staff, a reflection of the fact
that he has not done much campaign traveling and has a network of
City Hall aides. Teitelbaum said the campaign was about to begin
hiring more staff members within the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani appears to be in a strong financial position, for
reasons going beyond the numbers in the latest report. Teitelbaum
said that more than half of the contributions came in response to
direct-mail solicitations, which meant that Giuliani, who has kept
a modest campaign schedule, did not have to leave City Hall much to
raise the cash. And Teitelbaum said the campaign now has gotten
contributions from 135,000 donors, most of whom have given below
the $1,000 legal contribution limit and whom the campaign can hit
again for more money.
</P>
<P>
   That said, political analysts cautioned Thursday that it would
be a mistake to read too much into the political position of either
candidate based on fund-raising figures. For one thing, no matter
how Clinton stands in comparison to Giuliani, she still has raised
what in any other Senate race would be a huge amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   And there is, Clinton's aides said, no corollary between a
candidate's fund-raising ability and victory, ``Senator D'Amato,
Senator North and Senator Huffington can all attest to the fact
that more money doesn't necessarily get you elected to the
Senate,'' said Howard Wolfson, Clinton's press secretary, referring
to unsuccessful Senate campaigns by Alfonse D'Amato in New York,
North in Virginia, and Michael Huffington in California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
