<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLETRON-CUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. NETWORKING-EQUIPMENT COMPANY TO LAY OFF 800 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in Cabletron Systems Inc. sank 40 percent Thursday after
the company said it plans to lay off as many as 800 workers and
report restructuring costs of about $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron posted financial results in line with expectations for
the three months ended Feb 29. But its other disclosures, including
a projected operating loss of up to $45 million in the current
quarter, prompted a Goldman Sachs analyst to downgrade his rating
on the Rochester, N.H., networking-equipment company.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparently enough to send shares tumbling $19.875 to
$30 in New York Stock Exchange trading, wiping out $3.8 billion of
Cabletron's market value.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decline was even more remarkable as other securities
analysts maintained or reiterated their ratings on the company,
which, with 2,000 employees in New Hampshire, is one of the state's
largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron has about 4,500 employees altogether. It said it will
lay off 600 to 800 of them as it becomes a holding company that may
spin off up to four separate public units.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Mike Quinn said the company hasn't yet determined
where it will pare jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron's difficulties come as its chief executive, Piyush
Patel, struggles to turn around the company he was named to head
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron's components once were in high demand. But more
recently, the company has trailed Cisco Systems Inc. in the race to
produce gear that can transmit data at ever-faster speeds.
</P>
<P>
   With his plan to split up Cabletron, Patel hoped to improve its
focus and stimulate growth. Until Thursday, the market seemed to
buy the strategy. Shares reached $52 on Tuesday, up from around $27
in late January.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts emerged after the close of trading Wednesday when
Cabletron reported quarterly earnings of $28.1 million, up from
$3.8 million a year earlier. Sales rose 11 percent to $381.7
million from $345.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Patel said he was ``very pleased'' with the results. But Goldman
analyst Ajay Diwan wrote a research note citing concerns that
Patel's steps have reduced revenue expectations and that the stock
had already reached his $50 price target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disruption to business was the biggest risk in Cabletron's
restructuring, and this risk appears to have materialized,'' Diwan
wrote. Patel and other Cabletron executives were not available for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts remain optimistic. Robertson Stephens analyst Paul
Johnson reiterated his ``buy'' rating, citing Cabletron's new
product line and loyal customer base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
