<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-METEOROLOGY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METEOROLOGISTS TRACK TWISTER'S PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANITA BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After a half-day of searching from ground
and air Thursday, National Weather Service meteorologists said they
believe that the same tornado that cut a swath of destruction
through south Arlington danced its way into Grand Prairie to damage
56 additional homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to find where things began and ended, and what
I determined was this was not a separate tornado in Grand Prairie,
but a continuous track from Arlington,'' said Jim Stefkovich, a
warning coordination meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst in Grand Prairie, the tornado reached an F2
designation as it hit a housing subdivision between Pioneer Parkway
and Arkansas Lane. An F2 on the Fujita scale, which gauges damage,
has winds from 113 mph to 157 mph and can cause significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   At its birth in Arlington, the twister was at its strongest, an
F3, just southwest of the Cooper Street-Interstate 20 intersection.
In between, it rose and fell in intensity from F3 to F0, the latter
the weakest of tornadoes, as it spiraled across the southern end of
the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, an F5 _ the strongest tornado, with winds as high
as 318 mph _ left a trail of death and destruction across Oklahoma
on May 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington/Grand Prairie tornado was the second to touch down
Tuesday evening. Fort Worth got the first punch when an F2 tornado
formed near Castleberry High School just north of White Settlement
Road and cut through the city for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A weather damage team investigated Fort Worth and Arlington
damage Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stefkovich said the damage path of the Arlington/Grand Prairie
tornado was easy to follow as it cut across Arlington Municipal
Airport and destroyed homes and the Texas Department of Human
Services building on Bardin Road.
</P>
<P>
   When it crossed I-20, the path became more difficult to follow
across open fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stefkovich said that pictures of damage and the tornado's path
are posted on the Fort Worth's offices Internet Web page at
www.srh.noaa.gov/fwd.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are really thankful for is the low loss of life and
low injuries as well,'' he said. ``That tells us a couple of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who did not hear warnings recognized the signs and
took the right action, Stefkovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, some have the mistaken idea that it is safe to
hide underneath bridges. Bridges funnel wind and debris underneath,
and there is nothing to hang onto, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth twister was the first to cut through the heart of
the city and the first to take lives in Tarrant County since 1927.
</P>
<P>
   In that year, a 16-month-old girl was killed when a tornado cut
through the rural Watson community, now part of south Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
