<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 Sides of Banking Online &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Customers of traditional banks are not quite comfortable buying
stocks, bonds or mutual funds from them online. It is a somewhat
different story with customers of Internet-only banks, according to
a recent online survey of 207 consumers by the Stern Marketing
Group of Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of Internet-only bank customers thought that
their bank was a good place to make investments, the survey found.
Only 19 percent of traditional bank customers who visited both
their bank's branches and Web site said they felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the respondents said they would buy their next
financial product on the Internet. And 75 percent said they wanted
to get all their financial information and services in one place.
(The survey, which was conducted in February, had a margin of error
of plus or minus five percentage points.)
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Stern, president of Stern Marketing, said the results
indicated that virtual banks were solving a brand image problem _
namely, that banks in general are no place to buy investment
products. The survey also illustrated how consumers have changed
the way they shop for and buy financial services, Stern added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net has opened up the customer's perception of what a bank
can be, and customers feel that the virtual bank is more in tune
with the way they need to shop and buy financial services today,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional banks all have a Web site. But they have a long
way to go in changing their image as being more than a place to
open a checking account.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Vivian Marino
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
