<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TECHNOLOGY SELLOFF SENDS NASDAQ INTO CORRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sharp selloff in technology stocks continued for
a third consecutive session Thursday, driving the Nasdaq composite
index into a correction, and analysts said the slide could very
well continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may really have crossed an important threshold here,'' said
Douglas R. Cliggott, domestic equity strategist at J.P. Morgan
Securities. ``We could be talking about months rather than days or
weeks'' before reaching a floor.
</P>
<P>
   A late rebound lifted the Nasdaq off its lowest level of the day
_ a stunning decline of 289 points, or 6.2 percent _ and the index
finished down 186.78 points, or 4 percent, to 4,457.89, the
fifth-largest point decline ever for the Nasdaq. But the late rally
was not enough to keep the cumulative slide from reaching 10
percent, the benchmark Wall Street uses to define a correction. The
Nasdaq is now down 11.7 percent from the peak of 5,048.62 it set
less than three weeks ago, when nothing, not even the likelihood of
further interest rate increases by the Federal Reserve, seemed able
to dampen investor enthusiasm for stocks, especially those of
companies not yet generating significant profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which has declined every day this week, was led
lower by Qualcomm, which fell 12 17/64, to 145 15/64; Cisco
Systems, which dropped 2 7/16, to 73 5/8; Network Appliance, which
fell 12 11/16, to 79 1/8; and Citrix Systems, which slumped 13 3/4,
to 72 1/8, after an analyst warned it might miss revenue and profit
estimates for the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's session was the 10th this year in which the Nasdaq
fell at least 3 percent, already breaking the full-year record of
nine, set in 1998. It has fallen 500.56 points over the last three
days.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike many other recent sessions, when investors rotated
heavily into traditional growth and cyclical stocks, the Dow Jones
industrial average slumped, closing with a modest loss of 38.47
points, or 0.35 percent, to 10,980.25, after being up as much as
125 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, with a hefty weighting of
technology companies, sank 20.60 points, or 1.4 percent, to
1,487.92.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said that while some of the selling was from customers
unwilling or unable to put up more cash in support of eroded
portfolios, it was not a significant factor in the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Some depressed onetime favorites did perk up Thursday, with
Gillette gaining 2 1/16, to 37 1/16; Coca-Cola rising 1 11/16, to
48 9/16; PepsiCo climbing 2 11/16, to 35 15/16; and IBM rising 3
3/4, to 122 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley Jr., a strategist at State Street Global Advisors,
said he thought this might mean that long-term investors who
stepped nervously to the sidelines while momentum buyers pushed
prices to ``truly idyllic'' levels, might have begun to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is still a growth orientation, it's with older,
established names,'' Riley said. ``Clearly, some of the excesses
are being corrected'' and the huge gap between Nasdaq highfliers
and the rest of the stock market is closing, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Already, nearly two-thirds of the stocks in Nasdaq have fallen
30 percent from their 52-week highs, said Jeffrey Warantz, a
Salomon Smith Barney strategist.
</P>
<P>
   This could lead Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, to worry less
that newly created stock-market wealth will lead to revived
inflation. If so, that could relieve the upward pressure on
short-term interest rates, which eased substantially Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The markets paid little attention to the fact that the
government revised the pace of economic growth in the fourth
quarter to 7.3 percent, up from 6.9 percent, regarding it as
ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   But stock trading was still being affected, traders said, by
end-of-quarter maneuvering by portfolio managers and the prospect
of cascading offerings of stock by employees of fledgling companies
who will be free to sell at the expiration of lockup periods. Riley
said there were 126 such companies whose shares are expected to hit
the market over the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo was one of the numerous high-technology losers, dropping 7
9/16, to 169 1/2, after it disclosed that the Federal Trade
Commission was investigating its compliance with regulations for
protecting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, Intel, Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard were the
biggest drags on the Dow, 16 of whose components rose while 14
fell.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, advances led declines by 1,551
to 1,487 as 86 issues made new 52-week highs and 60 made new lows.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover on the Big Board climbed to 1.17 billion shares from
1.06 billion on Wednesday while volume on Nasdaq moved up to 1.89
billion from 1.74 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks dropped between 2 percent and 3 percent across
Europe and in Brazil and by 3.5 percent in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
