<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Icahn Seeks to Take Control of Nabisco Group Holdings
</P>
<P>
   Just 15 days after being rebuffed by the board of Nabisco Group
Holdings, the investor Carl Icahn appealed to shareholders in a
campaign to take over the troubled maker of Oreo cookies and Ritz
crackers. In a letter to the board that was widely distributed to
others, Icahn offered shareholders a premium of 40 percent for 100
million shares that would give him control of the company. Once in
control, Icahn said, he would try to sell the company at what he
expects would be a ``very attractive price.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Responds to Congress
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, told members of
Congress in a letter that the central bank's goal in raising
interest rates was not to bring down the stock market, and he
reiterated his opposition to growing calls for the Fed to make it
more difficult for investors to buy stock with borrowed money. The
letter was in response to written questions from the committee to
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Dime Sues Salomon Smith Barney
</P>
<P>
   Dime Bancorp is suing its former investment banker, Salomon
Smith Barney, for going to work for North Fork Bancorp, which is
pressing Dime to accept a $1.9 billion buyout offer. Dime, which
owns the Dime Savings Bank of New York, contends that Salomon Smith
Barney agreed in May 1997, while advising Dime on an acquisition,
not to represent any company on a bid for Dime without its consent.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo to Cooperate With Inquiry
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo notified the Securities and Exchange Commission that it
was cooperating with an inquiry by the Federal Trade Commission
into how Internet sites gather personal data. Analysts said the
disclosure underscored how important the mining of demographic data
and concerns about consumer privacy can be to an Internet company's
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers Object to Fen-Phen Plan
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers opposed to the proposed settlement for the millions of
people who took the diet drug combination fen-phen filed objections
in federal court contending that the plan is illegal and unfair.
The lawyers' objections were filed on the last day that diet drug
users had to opt out of the national settlement and instead pursue
separate lawsuits against American Home Products, the drug company
that sold half of the diet pill combination. Thousands of the six
million people who took fen-phen have decided to opt out of the
proposed settlement, under which American Home has agreed to pay
$3.75 billion. Shares of American Home fell $1.8125, to $52.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Panel Approves Internet-Tax Plan
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. commission studying whether electronic commerce should be
taxed approved a report that asks Congress to extend an existing
ban on Internet taxes for five years; simplify state and local
sales taxes; and exempt from sales taxes products delivered
digitally and their physical equivalents, like books and compact
discs.
</P>
<P>
   Primedia Sells Two 5 Percent Stakes
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, an Internet venture fund company, and Liberty Media, the
company controlled by John Malone, will each buy 5 percent stakes
in Primedia, a company once known for specialized magazines like
Teddy Bear and Drag Racing USA, for a total of $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Economy Grew 7.3 Percent in 4th Quarter
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a 7.3 percent annual rate in the fourth
quarter, the government said. The pace was stronger than the 6.9
percent previously reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
