<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-ONLINE-TICKETS-AR     03-30 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ONLINE-TICKETS-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING SEATS WITH ONLINE DISCOUNTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Pa., N.J., Ga., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ticket discounts for online customers, already favored by the
airlines for filling empty seats, are rapidly spreading to sports _
and entertainment might be next. But the same technology that
allows discounts is also likely to allow higher prices for some of
the sports and entertainment seats that everyone wants.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets of the National Basketball Association offer
discounts to anyone who signs up for ``Nets News'' online
bulletins. Last week, the team offered $50 seats to Sunday's
Detroit Pistons game for $20, and $20 seats for $17.
</P>
<P>
   Since last season, Texas Rangers followers who signed up on the
Web for the baseball team's fan club, Inside Pitch, have received
e-mail offers of steep discounts. Hockey fans get similar breaks
from the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly successful,'' said Jeff Cogan, executive vice
president of the Southwest Sports Group, a company led by the
Dallas investor Thomas O. Hicks that owns the Stars and Rangers.
Aided by data from online sales, Cogan is also considering higher
ticket prices for games on weekends or against popular rivals for
the Stars this fall and for the Rangers next year.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of online ticket sales makes it much easier for
sports teams or entertainment companies to gather data and set
prices according to demand. The newest technology will let online
buyers print their own tickets rather than having to wait for them
to arrive by mail or pick them up at box offices.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, fans attending sports events at the Staples
Center in Los Angeles, the First Union Center in Philadelphia and
22 other sites will be among the first in the nation to use tickets
they printed on their own computers. Within a year, that capability
is likely to spread to wired patrons of most major theater chains,
stadiums, arenas and performing arts centers.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting convenience is expected to help raise online
ticket sales from $300 million last year to $4 billion by 2004,
according to Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Sports and entertainment executives are already debating whether
they are entering a new era of pricing seats according to demand.
W. Thomas Gimble, chief executive of Tickets.com, based in Costa
Mesa, Calif., which has formed partnerships with the Stars and the
Rangers, has no doubts. ``When you can print your own tickets, it
busts apart the old rules of selling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But sports teams, promoters and entertainers, fearful of
alienating their fans, are proceeding cautiously, especially in
raising prices. In November, Tickets.com began auctioning some
prime seats for Elton John and Backstreet Boys concerts at an
average of 45 percent over face value, but the extra proceeds go to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   Operators of movie theaters and some concert halls are openly
skeptical. Mark Pascucci, a senior vice president of Loews Cineplex
Entertainment, which has 2,900 screens, says that discounted movie
tickets for some shows would only steal audiences from others.
``There's no practical reason for this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loews is joining the Regal and Edwards theater chains to begin
an online ticketing service this summer. Movietickets.com, based in
Boca Raton, Fla., and owned by the National Amusements theater
chain, AMC Theaters and CBS, plans to begin selling movie tickets
online over Memorial Day weekend. Both groups plan to let filmgoers
to print their tickets at home, beginning in December. To attract
customers, both sites plan to forgo service charges for at least
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets printed at home on standard paper and printers will
include bar codes that can be scanned by readers at theaters and
stadiums. The printouts might also include driving directions,
seating charts, parking coupons or restaurant advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Stars, however, have already gone a step
further, using software from Talus Solutions of Atlanta that helps
airlines and hotels gauge demand and set their rates. Marriott
International uses Talus software to set as many as 10 different
rates for identical hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium and team owners are especially eager to fill empty
seats, because so much of their revenue comes from food, drink and
souvenirs. ``To those owners, it's a big deal, regardless of what
patrons pay for the tickets,'' said Tom R. Madison, president of
Talus Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, wanting to fill some of the 15,000 seats that, on
average, remain empty in their stadium, are also offering breaks
like free extra tickets or coupons for discounted food and
beverages to frequent ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is the perfect opportunity to introduce dynamic
pricing because so many seats go unsold,'' said Gimble of
Tickets.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gimble's company also expects to allow ticket buyers to print
their own tickets beginning this summer for some of its 4,100 other
sites, which include those at Lincoln Center. But sports teams are
more likely to adopt variable pricing than the entertainment
industry, Gimble said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
