<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: TALIBAN FOE FLEES
</P>
<P>
   Iran's official news agency said Ismail Khan, former governor of
Herat Province in Afghanistan and a major figure in the opposition
to the ruling Taliban, had crossed into Iran and reached the city
of Meshed after escaping from a Taliban prison. Khan, a hero to
many Afghans for his fight against Soviet forces in the 1980s, was
said to have reached Iran with another anti-Taliban leader who
escaped from prison with him, Hafiz Qadir. Iran strongly opposes
the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: QUEEN HONORS CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark of the United States, NATO's supreme allied
commander Europe, is to be given an honorary knighthood by Queen
Elizabeth for his leadership in the bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia. A Buckingham Palace spokesman said because the general
is not a Briton he will be entitled to put ``K.B.E.'' _ for Knight
of the British Empire _ after his name, but not put ``Sir'' before
it.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: LIBEL AWARD
</P>
<P>
   Sean McPhilemy, a Northern Ireland filmmaker, won a $230,000
libel judgment against The Sunday Times when a High Court jury
ruled that the newspaper failed to prove its claim that his 1993
program ``The Committee'' was a ``hoax.'' The program said there
was collusion between Royal Ulster Constabulary officials and
Protestant politicians in the killing of prominent Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: KOSOVO OFFICER REASSIGNED
</P>
<P>
   A paramilitary police officer freed from jail after being held
for 48 hours on suspicion of leaking secret military papers on
Kosovo to the news media will be reassigned. Lt. Col. Jean-Michel
Mechain, 46, has denied giving journalists documents describing
tensions between French commanders and the United Nations
administrator in Kosovo. He remains under judicial investigation,
however, and cannot leave France.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: HOLOCAUST ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Banks have agreed to publish the names of owners of 26,000
dormant accounts to see if they belong to Holocaust survivors, a
move recommended in December by the Volcker Commission. The delay
has held up payment from the $1.25 billion setttlement reached with
Swiss banks by Jewish groups in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND: NAZI-ERA PAYMENTS UNTAXED
</P>
<P>
   Payments by German companies to 400,000 Poles for forced labor
during World War II will be exempt from income tax, Prime Minister
Jerzy Buzek announced. Poles will be eligible for payments of
between $2,500 and $7,500 each from a $5 billion fund.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: NEO-NAZI BEGINS JAIL TERM
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Terre'Blanche, the leader of South Africa's neo-Nazi
Afrikaner Resistance Movement, began a 12-month jail sentence on an
assault charge. Terre'Blanche, whose followers set off bombs that
killed 21 people on the eve of the first nonracial elections, in
1994, was imprisoned for setting his dogs on a gas station
attendent in 1996. He is appealing another conviction, for the
attempted murder of another black man.
</P>
<P>
   ALGERIA: RIGHTS INVITATION
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups welcomed a decision to invite them to make
separate visits to Algeria in May and June. The invitation to
Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, Reporters Without
Borders and the International Federation of Human Rights was made
through Algeria's diplomatic mission in Geneva. Since fighting
between guerrillas and the army began in Algeria in 1992, the
country has been closed to rights groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
