<SLUG> BC-FISHY-THREAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS FALL FOR FAKE THREAT AGAINST FISHING CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To bass anglers in East Texas, it sounded like an April Fools'
joke _ and it was.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials took the bait.
</P>
<P>
   PETA _ People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals _ threatened
Tuesday to sabotage Friday's Red Man Cowboy Division Fishing
Tournament at Lake Palestine by dumping sedatives into the lake,
which has an area of 25,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, the fish will be napping, not nibbling,'' the faxed
news releases stated, asserting that ``impaling'' bass on hooks is
painful and hardly sporting.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it would take millions of soluble tranquilizers
to sabotage the tourney, which takes place April 1, and that PETA's
spokeswoman was identified as ``April Phule.'' Officials at the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department and the Upper Neches River
Municipal Water Authority took it all seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The officials went so far as to mobilize park rangers to catch
any drug-dumping activists this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the real PETA spokeswoman conceded that the
threat was a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very impressed that somebody got it,'' said Dawn Carr of
Norfolk, Va., after initially declining to own up to the prank.
``But the important thing to remember is the fish have nothing to
laugh about.''
</P>
<P>
   A careful reading of the statements provided clues that PETA's
tongue was firmly in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``April Phule'' was one clue. Another hint that the ``joke is on
you'' was ``Jo Kizonu,'' listed as a PETA official in a statement
sent to the Upper Neches River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that?'' said Tom Mallory, general manager of the
river authority, a state agency, when the hoax was pointed out to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of relieves me a little bit,'' Mallory said before
using a more colorful expression not usually printed in family
newspapers. ``I guess my reaction is, `Aren't they cute?' But a lot
of resources have been dedicated to this silly thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The premature April Fools' joke netted the activists bucketloads
of free publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Articles taking the sedative dumping seriously appeared in the
Tyler Morning Telegraph, the Palestine Herald-Press and The Dallas
Morning News as well as USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   While the threat was bogus, angler Gary Bostic said the bass
hadn't received the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not biting,'' said Bostic, 48, of Tyler, speaking by
cellular phone as he fished along the north end of the lake.
``They're acting like they've already been sedated.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Villages resort on Lake Palestine, where 200 boats are
expected for the fishing tournament, employees said they suspected
all along that PETA was pulling an April Fools' stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the resort is not letting down its guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know with this group,'' assistant manager Chris Site
said. ``Them saying it's an April Fools' Day joke could just be
another prank.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
