<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT STEALS THE HEADLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUNDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Final Four is here again and Thursday the man
who is not here was in the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Bob Knight has been under siege the past few weeks
amid reports of verbal and, at times, physical confrontations with
his players.
</P>
<P>
   That those reports came out years after the alleged incidents is
somewhat disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Knight having ``tough love'' encounters with his players is not
news. But the story in Thursday's Indianapolis Star kicked it up
another notch. The Star reported that following a loss to Ohio
State last month, Knight had words with Indiana athletic director
Clarence Doninger and it became so heated that a longtime friend of
Knight's had to step between the men.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, who played for Knight at
Army, tiptoed through a question about his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Krzyzewski tried to joke about it. ``I got a lot of
stuff for my scholarship,'' he said. ``And I got paid and when I
graduated, he said, `I'm going to give you a tank.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Coach K chose the path most Knight supporters have followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Knight has been good for the game and done many positive
things for people who have played for him,'' said Krzyzewski.
``He's been very supportive for me and helped me immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question Knight can coach as well as anyone. He has
won three national championships, his players graduate, and he
plays by the rules. But he also coaches in a fishbowl, where his
temper has been well documented. Now we are hearing more about his
private displays of emotion . Indiana officials say they are
looking into these latest allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Less publicized are Knight's acts of kindness and generosity to
many of his former players and others.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are this will all be chalked up to ``Knight moves'' and
life will go on with ``The General,'' as Dick Vitale has labeled
him, still in charge.
</P>
<P>
   But in this day and age, when discipline is a four-letter word
to many, Knight's ways may seem out of date and boorish.
</P>
<P>
   It may indeed be past his time, but it would be unfortunate if
these allegations lead to the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coaching carousel
</P>
<P>
   Hartford is close to making a decision on its coaching opening
and UConn assistant Karl Hobbs is very much in the mix . . .
Nebraska is making a hard push at Tulsa coach Bill Self. Nebraska
officials flew to Tulsa earlier this week, reportedly ready to
offer Self a package between $800,000 and $1 million per year . . .
Michigan officials followed the UMass route when they came out
publicly and said coach Brian Ellerbe would be back next year. Even
though Ellerbe has four years remaining on his contract, rumors
about his future were so distracting that the school felt compelled
to issue a statement of support . . . Georgia Tech athletic
director Dave Braine continues his search for a coach to replace
Bobby Cremins. His original list of candidates included Self, Seton
Hall coach Tommy Amaker, and Miami coach Leonard Hamilton, but
those apparently are not going to pan out, so Dayton coach Oliver
Purnell became the unofficial leader in the clubhouse. That is
until Thursday, when Delaware's Mike Brey moved into the picture.
Brey would be a perfect fit. He has a Duke pedigree, an outgoing
personality, and a Washington D.C. background, which would help in
recruiting . . . NABC officials have talked about their hopes for
the continuation of summer recruiting, as opposed to the NCAA,
which wants it banned. The NABC wants to cut it from 24 to 20 days
. . . In a similar area, Krzyzewski said he would like to see the
NCAA open the scholarship umbrella for basketball players to get
something short of a cash stipend but more than the bare bones an
athletic scholarship provides. Coach K's point was that in 25 years
there have been a lot of changes in college basketball but what is
offered in a scholarship has not changed . . . North Carolina and
Wisconsin are unranked, the first time two such teams have made the
Final Four since 1980 (UCLA and Iowa) . . . When Wisconsin plays
Michigan State Saturday it will mark the second straight year the
Final Four has had two Big Ten teams, a first for the conference .
. . The last time two Big Ten teams met in the semifinals was in
1989, when Michigan and Illinois played in Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
