<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA CONSIDERS ELIMINATING COACHES' SUMMER EVALUATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ If NCAA officials have their way, college
basketball coaches will have to spend their summers involved in
activities other than evaluating prospects.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA president Cedric Dempsey said Thursday the governing body
is considering eliminating the summer evaluation period for coaches
as part of several initiatives designed to ``change the culture in
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches use summer basketball camps and tournaments to home in
on potential recruits, usually high school underclassmen or junior
high schoolers. But the NCAA, which Dempsey said is bothered by the
negative influences kids encounter during summer recruiting, would
like to do away with the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said the proposal, one of several matters to be
presented at the April meeting of management council in Division 1
and the governing body's board of directors, would call for
implementation of the legislation to be delayed for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would spend the year trying to rebuild a culture that is
more beneficial to prospective student-athletes, and we have the
right people influencing student-athletes in our future
direction,'' Dempsey said. He said the move would not affect
basketball camps run by the coaches, which are geared toward
younger children.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey admitted the proposal will be controversial, but
declined to predict how it would be received.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a little premature,'' he said. ``We want to see
whether or not we can work with all the organizations, including
high school programs, and adopt a different culture of how we run
our summer programs. We'll encourage participation by all parties
and then we'll know better how much of an impact it is going to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer evaluation measure and other matters discussed
Thursday would lead one to believe that the NCAA has concerns about
the integrity of the sport _ as well as the proliferation of the
notion that it has become a unofficial minor league system for the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said the NCAA also is proposing providing financial aid
for incoming men's and women's non-qualifiers for a five-year
period and revisiting the non-qualifier rule to see whether it has
affected graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey also said the NCAA has been proactive in trying to get
anti-gambling legislation through Congress that would outlaw
betting on college sports, high school sports, and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very encouraged by the response we are getting from the
House and the Senate on the issue,'' he said. ``We recognize we
have strong opposition in the gaming association, but we are
somewhat confident if we can get it to the floor for a vote, we
will win the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey was asked to comment on a University of Michigan report
that polled Division 1 officials of men's and women's basketball
and football, and found that 84 percent say they have gambled
(mostly on lotteries and at casinos) and one fifth have bet on the
NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already started last year a background check on
officials,'' Dempsey said. ``Last year we had one official who was
not approved because of the background check process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
