<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIAMI, THE ISSUE IS NOT A BOY, BUT A MAN: CASTRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for complete writethru; adds developments, quotes; note new
bylines) 
(See also CUBAN-BOY-GORE and CUBAN-BOY OUTLOOK) 
(jt) 
 By RICK BRAGG and LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even miles away from sign-waving demonstrators who keep
vigil outside the tiny house in Little Havana where Elian Gonzalez
lives with his great-uncle, talk about the standoff between Elian's
Miami relatives and Immigration and Naturalization Service
officials pours hot and quick from coffee stands on Calle Ocho and
any other place Cuban Americans gather.
</P>
<P>
   In rapid-fire Spanish, so fast that even people who learned the
language in other Hispanic cultures can have trouble keeping up,
they villify Attorney General Janet Reno, President Clinton and
others who want to send the child back to his father in Cuba. And
they question _ or ridicule _ news that the boy's father is
planning to come here to retrieve his son.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Communist plot hatched by the hated dictator, Fidel
Castro, they say. If you are not Cuban, they said, you just would
not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't Cuba, the child should go to be with his
father,'' said Delfina Miranda, 49, who works at a beauty salon in
Little Havana. ``But it is Cuba. That kid will get nothing in Cuba.
Well, maybe electro-shock treatment, so they can brain-wash him.''
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, Cuban Americans said that outsiders who did not
suffer under the Castro regime simply could not understand their
passions in the Elian standoff.
</P>
<P>
   As talk on the streets swirled, talks between lawyers for
Elian's Miami relatives and government officials crept to an
uneventful close.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Immigration officials postponed until Tuesday morning any
action on revoking the boy's temporary permission to stay in the
United States, which would allow federal officials to, ultimately,
take the boy from his relatives' house and eventually return him to
Cuba. ``Like the family, we are monitoring developments concerning
the possible arrival of (Elian's father) Juan Miguel Gonzalez in
the United States,'' said Robert Wallis, INS director for the Miami
district.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials had threatened to revoke the boy's parole
if his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, did not sign a document
agreeing to hand Elian over to federal officials once the family's
appeal in the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals was decided.
</P>
<P>
   But that standoff became less important in the eyes of Cuban
Americans here after Castro announced Wednesday that the boy's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is ready to travel to the United
States to take his son home.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's lawyer, Greg Craig, asked for a visa Thursday for his
client for the expected visit, but was told by U.S. State
Department officials that Gonzalez himself had to apply for the
visa at the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Miguel Gonzalez is ready at a moment's notice to come to
the United States,'' said Craig.
</P>
<P>
   But in Miami, many Cuban Americans said Castro is orchestrating
the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said Gonzalez would travel with his current wife and
their son, a top government official, doctors, nurses,
psychiatrists, Elian's Cuban kindergarten teacher, classmates and
his old school desk.A list of 31 people issued by the Cuban
government Thursday included Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's
National Assembly. Castro has suggested that Elian and his
relatives stay at the residence of Cuba's chief diplomat in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden in the entourage, cautioned Cuban Americans here, will be
Cuban security agents who will make sure that Gonzalez _ and
everyone else, for that matter _ does not defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are coming with everyone, including psychologists,'' said
Armando Sanjurjo, 73. ``You know why? To give Elian an injection
and take him back to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanjurjo, sipping a cafecito in front of Versailles restaurant,
the nerve center for Cuban political discussions here in Little
Havana, is convinced, like many others here, the entourage is
designed to prevent any defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming with an entire court of people? What's that
about?'' said Angela Esparragera, 71.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda said Elian's father will be ``a virtual prisoner here if
he comes with all those people. He'll be surrounded by people if he
goes to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Estefan, the wildly popular singer of Cuban descent who
has become an entertainment and cultural icon, was also suspicious
of this visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in fact, Elian's father is permitted by the dictatorship of
Fidel Castro to come to the United States, then, as a Cuban
American, I welcome him and urge him to make all his decisions
based on the well being and best interest of his son, and not that
of the Cuban government,'' Estefan said.
</P>
<P>
   All week, elected officials in Washington, D.C., and at the
state capital in Tallahassee have issued statement of support for
Elian's Miami relatives, even Vice President Al Gore, breaking from
his own administration's stand. In Miami-Dade County, elected
officials went as far as to say they their police departments would
have no role in taking the boy from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Among non-Cuban Americans, there was a drastic shift in their
feelings on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send him back,'' said Marsha Raeber, 47, an airline employee.
``There are rules and regulations in this country. Some people are
born rich, some people are born poor. That's the luck of the draw.
Who's to say that he's better off at Disney World and eating fast
food here instead if breathing the fresh air of Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Pichardo, 44, is from Nicaragua, and said the
Cuban-Americans ``need to follow the law. What about all the other
poor kids in South and Central America?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Cuban-Americans insist that Elian be allowed to stay.
Diana de Cardenas, 33, was born in Cuba in 1984. ``I think he
deserves to be with his father,'' she said. ``It would be ideal if
his father came,'' and then stayed, in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MARKET-TECHNOLOGY-BOS     03-30 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TECHNOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH JITTERS STILL PULLING DOWN NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technology-laden Nasdaq exchange continued its weeklong
descent Thursday, as uneasy investors sold off shares in new
economy stocks that have climbed sharply for months.
</P>
<P>
   For a time Thursday, the Nasdaq appeared headed for the worst
day in its history. With less than 30 minutes remaining in the
session, the exchange was down 289 points. But it rallied in late
trading and by day's end had fallen 186.78 points, or 4 percent, to
close at 4457.89.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the steep drop brings the weekly loss to 10 percent and
marks an official correction for the highly volatile exchange. The
Nasdaq suffered a similar plunge early this month, only to bounce
back, but analysts refrained from making any predictions about
which way the Nasdaq will head next. Some said this week's slide in
the sky-high prices of technology stocks was inevitable and
necessary to bring the markets back into balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hyperbolic performance over the past six and 12 months
clearly couldn't be sustained,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist for State Street Global Advisers, a division of State
Street Corp. ``Right now, we're getting the correction many people
felt was necessary for this market to establish a healthy
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also fell Thursday. Its decline
was limited to 38.47 points, as many old-line consumer and
industrial companies, which are bargains compared with technology
shares, held firm. The Dow closed Thursday at 10,980.25, having
fallen less than half a percent all day.
</P>
<P>
   Computer, telecommunications, and software-industry stocks have
swung wildly since the Nasdaq reached its March 10 record of
5048.62. This week, however, the Nasdaq has plunged nearly 550
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's volatility reflects concerns that the values
accorded many new companies in the technology sector are
unrealistic, given that most of them still do not produce a profit.
Analysts note that, despite this week's sharp decline, the Nasdaq
is still up nearly 10 percent so far this year _ on top of an 86
percent gain in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the wild swings in the Nasdaq is ongoing
concern that the economy is growing too fast _ and that the Federal
Reserve will be forced to raise interest rates several more times
in an attempt to slow it down.
</P>
<P>
   The government announced Thursday that the nation grew at a rate
of 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of last year, the fastest
growth rate in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems unbelievable, doesn't it?'' said Cynthia
Latta, an economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. ``Certainly, it's a
rate that isn't going to be sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   While stock markets typically drop in reaction to such news,
which may point to future interest-rate hikes by the Fed, analysts
said Thursday's stock decline was unrelated. The fourth quarter is
long forgotten, said William Cheney, chief economist for John
Hancock Financial Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the stock market is reacting to that,'' Cheney
said. ``The fourth quarter of 1999 is outside the range of the
stock market's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the Nasdaq was spurred by investors who fear that
even the premier technology stocks cannot achieve the profits
necessary to justify sky-high stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the world's biggest networking company, Cisco Systems
Inc., dived $2.4375 a share, to $73.625. The world's biggest chip
maker, Intel Corp., dropped $4.875, to $127. And the world's
biggest software company, Microsoft Corp., fell $3.8125 to $103.375
a share.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Nasdaq's slide came in the wake of another month of
record flows into mutual funds that invest in the stock market.
Investors put $39.1 billion in new money into mutual funds in
February, the Wall Street Journal reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, William Lawrence, a portfolio manager for Beacon Fiduciary
Advisors, said fund managers and other institutional investors may
be selling their tech stocks as they participate in ``window
dressing'' for customers at the end of the quarter. Institutions
often sell stocks and rebalance portfolios before shareholder
reports are mailed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be seen to have an inordinately large
position in a stock that has been falling,'' Lawrence said. Despite
a bad week, however, he said the decline was a welcome adjustment
and noted, ``the Nasdaq is still up 85 percent from last fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors are getting edgy about a market in which almost
two-thirds of Nasdaq stocks are, according to Salomon Smith Barney
equity strategist Jeffrey Warantz, down 30 percent from their
52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   Where are things headed? Thomas O'Neill, chief investment
officer for FleetBoston Financial Advisors, said that technology
stocks are, as they have done repeatedly, capable of bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill said a correction is welcome. ``What's going on now
is more healthy for the long-term than what has preceded it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
