<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.SECURITY-COUNCIL-     03-30 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.SECURITY-COUNCIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. ENVOYS SALLY HAPPILY INTO HELMS TERRITORY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT11,12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was in many ways the strangest of outings.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen foreign envoys and Richard Holbrooke, the ubiquitous
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, visited Washington Thursday
as individual sightseers _ just 14 guys and one woman, Patricia
Durrant of Jamaica. It was not, they said emphatically, an official
visit by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the Senate Foreign Relations Committee from
distributing a press packet labeled ``Visit of the United Nations
Security Council to the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't stop Sergei Lavrov, the Russian ambassador, from
preparing his wardrobe for the chance of a meeting with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am wearing a white shirt, just in case,'' said Lavrov, who,
as it turned out, did not get to meet with Clinton, who was in New
York raising money for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The leisurely beginning of the day included a Senate history
lesson, a guided tour of the Capitol and a lavish lunch in the
Russell Senate office building, all arranged by Sen. Jesse Helms,
the North Carolina Republican who heads the committee, and its
ranking Democrat, Joseph Biden of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomatic gloves came off Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At a ``round table discussion'' _ remember, this wasn't an
official hearing _ _ one ambassador after another criticized the
Foreign Relations Committee for America's ambivalent leadership and
a law that pays $926 million of the U.S. debt, but only if the
United Nations takes steps to eliminate waste, a condition many
diplomats consider unwarranted micromanaging.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's ambassador, Robert Fowler, acknowledged that the United
Nations has 8,000 bureaucrats, but chided the Congress for having
more than 30,000 employees. ``We have overlap and duplication, and
so do you,'' said Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has agreed with Congress to try to lower U.S.
payments to the United Nations, another demand that has rankled.
Member nations, including some of Washington's closest allies, were
angered that the United States was making such demands when it was
violating treaty obligations that it pay its dues on time and in
full.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats are grudgingly considering Washington's positions
because they realize the United Nations cannot effectively exist
without the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not persuaded by your arguments, but by our own
enlightened self-interest,'' said Peter van Walsum, the Dutch
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. is looking to the United States for the same thing
that the states were looking to King George and didn't get: the
right balancing between representation and taxation,'' said Sir
Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative.
</P>
<P>
   But membership is a two-way street, the diplomats reminded the
senators, who sat with the diplomats around a long rectangular
table in the committee's main hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is the only superpower, but you cannot
manage everything without the other countries of the world,'' said
Wang Yingfan, China's ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council members visited Capitol Hill to reciprocate
for a trip to New York by Helms in January, when he offered an
olive branch to diplomats, but in a mailed fist. At that meeting,
Helms asserted that Congress had the right to dictate conditions
for the payment of U.S. debts to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Helms was anything but antagonistic, playing the
courtly Southern host, and absorbing the verbal body blows that the
ambassadors flung with quiet aplomb, and not hinting at anger. ``He
said what he had to say in New York,'' said the senator's
spokesman, Marc Thiessen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the barbs, the atmosphere at Thursday's sequel
session was more diplomatic and good-humored than in the encounter
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As Thursday afternoon's 2 1-2 hour meeting was preparing to
adjourn, Fowler of Canada said Helms could make an immediate
contribution to a more efficient United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we have one of those gizmos?'' Fowler said, pointing to
the tricolor timing lights that the committee uses to alert
speakers when their allotted time is finished. ``That would
streamline Security Council meetings.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
