<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUC-NYT &LR;      03-30 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES SPENDING $2.9 BILLION TO TRAIN AND RECRUIT TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EDUC-COMPARE) 
(DW) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has been promoting
his prescriptions for education in pilgrimages to classrooms across
the country, set his presidential campaign down Thursday amid the
stacks of a middle school library here to announce a five-year,
$2.9 billion plan to improve teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncing teachers ``the whole lifeblood of the education
system,'' Bush said he would increase financing for teacher
training by $400 million annually, to $2.4 billion. He said he
would bolster a program that recruits retired military personnel to
become teachers, an idea originally championed by Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, who lost to Bush in the Republican primaries. Bush
would raise spending on the program to $30 million annually, from
$2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that teachers should be protected by law from
facing federal civil rights lawsuits for enforcing reasonable
rules, and proposed that they be allowed up to a $400 tax deduction
annually for spending their personal money on supplies. The tax
deduction would cost $150 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the five-year plan Thursday, at a forum with
educators, was the latest move by Bush to claim education as his
emblematic issue and deny his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, an
advantage on what is often seen as a Democratic preserve.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most interesting symbols of this strategy, Bush
for the second time this week even opened his remarks by
approvingly recalling an anecdote about Albert Shanker, the late
president of the American Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' unions have long been a bete noire of many
Republican politicians, who say the unions are obstacles to change.
In the 1996 presidential campaign, the Republican nominee, former
Sen. Bob Dole, often railed against the unions.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Shanker, Bush said: ``He went into a classroom and
said, `What do you think we ought to teach you to read?' And one
kid raised his hand and said, `What do the smart kids read?'
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' Bush continued, ``education excellence starts with
people knowing that every child can be a smart child. Secondly,
those of us at the table know that reforms come from the bottom up.
And therefore, we've got to align authority and responsibility at
the local level. It's impossible for the federal government to
dictate reform. It's impossible for a centralized authority to say
this is the way it's got to be, `cause you see, one size doesn't
fit all.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are pressing their education agendas, mindful
that polls show that the issue is an important one for voters. But
the two men are taking markedly different tacks. With his plan
Thursday, Bush is calling for $13.4 billion in new federal
education spending from the budget surplus over five years, far
less than Gore's plan, which amounts to $115 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush called for a five-year, $5 billion program to
combat illiteracy among children. Earlier proposals by Bush
included making $3 billion in loan guarantees available for
establishing charter schools and raising the annual contributions
parents can make to education savings accounts to $5,000 from $500.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, citing the disparity between the overall size of
the two candidates' plans, the Gore campaign called the new Bush
teacher proposal timid, saying that the vice president wants to
spend far more for teacher training and other measures. As they
have done repeatedly in recent days as Bush has presented his
education proposals, Gore aides questioned whether any new spending
was possible if Bush's tax cut plan took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has focused not on money but on the issues of control and
accountability, saying that the federal government should give
states more latitude in spending federal money while also ensuring
that the money is not wasted. He sees himself as something of a
national cheerleader for successful education policies at the state
and local level, promoting strategies but not imposing them.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the creation of more charter schools, like the one he
visited Thursday in Milwaukee, the Fritsche Middle School, and
would like states to provide money to students at poorly performing
public schools so they can attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the forum, Bush brushed aside a
question about whether voters would find Gore's education plan more
appealing because it was larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not competing on money,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush spent most of the day talking about education, he did
visit a Harley-Davidson motorcycle factory in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was given a black leather biker jacket, which he put on,
and escorted to one of the company's sizable motorcycles, where he
stood for photographs. But despite the entreaties of reporters, he
declined to climb aboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
