<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-WORST-ART-     03-30 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-WORST-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WORST PERFORMANCE BY A CAR: THE ENVELOPE, PLEASE ...  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By KEITH MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought all the lists of the best this or that of the
last 100 or 1,000 years had been compiled, think again. While the
Car of the Century has been selected (the Ford Model T, annointed
by an international panel of experts), what about the flipside: of
the tens of thousands of automobile models produced since the
1880s, which were bad enough to warrant special recognition?
</P>
<P>
   The hosts of ``Car Talk'' on National Public Radio, Tom and Ray
Magliozzi _ also known as Click and Clack, the Tappet Brothers _
invited listeners to vote for the ``worst cars of the millenium,''
vehicles that were, in their words, ``just stupid, in every
possible way.'' The results were announced this weekend on their
radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Votes were compiled on the show's Web site, www.cartalk.com. In
an interview last week, the brothers discussed the survey, the
losers-cum-winners and the selection process. As sharp-tongued on
the phone as on their show, they spoke rapidly and interchangeably;
much of the time, it was impossible to determine which Magliozzi
was talking.
</P>
<P>
   They described the chosen cars in the same salty language one
might hear in a repair shop where the owner of, say, a Chevy Vega
was getting another bit of bad news. Indeed, they characterized
some listeners as long-suffering victims bent on revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a scientific survey,'' said Ray (or was it Tom?).
``The voters are a self-selecting group of wackos, most of whom are
really aggravated by a bad experience with one of the cars, and
this is their chance to get even.'' In fact, all the finalists were
built within the last 35 years, the indignities they caused still
fresh in former owners' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hilary Swank won an Oscar for playing a woman who
lived as a man. The winner of this competition was a metallic
object with rubber tires that impersonated a car: the Yugo. ``This
was a cheap piece of junk, and built to stay that way,'' one of the
brothers said. ``The Yugo was just a dated Fiat 128 built on
worn-out equipment that Fiat sold to the Yugoslavs.'' The factory
was destroyed by Allied bombs during the Kosovo conflict, sparing
potential Yugo owners of future headaches.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yugo was the voters' choice, the Magliozzis would have
divided the top spot among three finalists: the Renault Dauphine,
the Chevrolet Chevette and a twin entry, the Dodge Aspen and
Plymouth Volare. ``At least the Yugo buyers knew they were getting
junk,'' Tom said. ``The three cars we thought were the worst
actually pretended to be real transportation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chevette, for instance, ``was a stupid design, and, just to
increase the insult to the customer, General Motors kept selling
them for a long time _ 12 years,'' one brother said. The other
added, ``Unfortunately, the engines were pretty good, which kept
the cars on the road that much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   They were no kinder to the Volare/Aspen, which hold a place in
history as the most-recalled cars ever. The Magliozzis described
them as ``cars that rusted even when they were rust-proofed,'' that
stalled in wet weather and stumbled under acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   The Dauphine, from France, ``was designed to go about 30 miles
an hour, from one end of the village to the other'' _ not for long
trips like, say, crossing Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Ray acknowledged that two finalists, the Vega and the
Ford Pinto, were among the first American attempts to make small
cars at a time of rising gas prices and surging Japanese imports.
The Pinto was sound, they said, aside from its tendency to burst
into flames when hit in the rear. It wouldn't have made their own
list.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vega, in their view, was terrible in every way.
``General Motors is the largest car corporation in the world,'' Ray
(or Tom?) said. ``And the best that it could come up with was this
car with an engine that melted and a body that rusted so badly that
the cars sometimes broke in half.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Volkswagen Bus, one Magliozzi said it was a
sentimental favorite of many people because it reminded them of the
'60s. ``It was like having your own little apartment on wheels that
you could sneak into and smoke dope,'' he said. Unfortunately, the
rear-mounted, air-cooled engines overheated to the point of
destruction. The far-forward seats essentially forced one's legs to
serve as an auxiliary front bumper.
</P>
<P>
   The only ``luxury'' car on the list was the Cadillac Cimarron.
``Buyers felt cheated,'' Tom said. ``One fellow told me he had
wanted his whole life to have a Cadillac, bought a Cimarron and
discovered he owned a Chevy Cavalier with a Cadillac badge on its
nose.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They see a common thread among the 10 cars: none took advantage
of technology available when they were built. ``A 1972 Chevrolet
Impala was a good car when it was built, and it's still a good car
today,'' Ray said. ``But a Vega, built at the same time, was a
piece of junk when it was new.''
</P>
<P>
   Car shoppers should note that a few of all these models are
still out there in the back rows of the nation's used-car lots, at
prices that might seem ridiculously low.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say, ``Caveat emptor''? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
