<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PLANETS-DISCOVERED-SF     03-30 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANETS-DISCOVERED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIND OF SMALL PLANETS FUELS HOPES FOR OTHER SUN-ORBITING WORLDS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Planet hunters searching the skies for evidence of distant solar
systems have detected two planets smaller than Jupiter or Saturn _
the most persuasive clue yet that far-off suns may indeed hold
orbiting Earth-sized worlds, perhaps much like our own.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only a few days for the two newfound planets to orbit
their parent stars, and they are so close to the suns that they are
forbiddingly hot, the astronomers who discovered them say.
</P>
<P>
   And like the 24 planets that the same team previously detected,
the new ones are most probably giant balls of gas with no solid
surface _ just as Jupiter and Saturn are in our own solar system.
</P>
<P>
   But the new ones are so much smaller than Jupiter and Saturn
that the excitement level of the astronomers has risen like a
rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The successful hunters are Geoffrey Marcy of the University of
California at Berkeley, R. Paul Butler of the Carnegie Institution
in Washington, and Steven S. Vogt of UC-Santa Cruz. Marcy and
Butler announced their discovery Wednesday at a NASA news
conference in Washington, but before Marcy left Berkeley for the
conference, he voiced his delight at the team's discovery, saying
in an interview:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tremendously exciting to see smaller and smaller planets,
because they give us the promise that there must be countless
Earths out there in the galaxy, like our own `Pale Blue Dot,' just
waiting for us to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers have been working on their extremely difficult
task for 15 years, and found their first huge ``gas giants'' the
size of Jupiter only five years ago. But Marcy and his colleagues
are convinced that discovering the two far smaller ones shows they
are on the right track toward detecting still smaller rocky ones in
the coming decade _ once new planet-seeking space-born telescopes
are operating.
</P>
<P>
   The three astronomers cannot actually see any of the planets
they have found, but they detect them _ most recently through the
eye of the giant Keck telescope on Mauna Kea in Hawaii _ by
measuring the tiny wobbles of their parent stars as the gravity of
their orbiting planets tugs at them. The light from those stars
fluctuates regularly, and by measuring the tiny changes in the
stars' velocities the team can determine the mass and speed of the
planets around them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the planets orbits every 3.02 days around an obscure star
known only as HD161141 in the constellation Monoceros, about 109
light years from Earth. The other revolves around a star called 79
Ceti, in the constellation Cetus the Whale, about 117 light-years
away. It flies in a 75-day orbit _ similar to swiftly-orbiting
Mercury's flight around our own sun. (One light-year is roughly six
trillion miles.)
</P>
<P>
   Both planets must be extremely hot, Marcy estimated _ the one in
Monoceros probably averages about 2,000 degrees Fahrenheit, while
the planet orbiting 79 Ceti is a little cooler _ about 1,500
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The newfound planets could not have been detected at all, Marcy
said, if his colleague Steve Vogt had not developed an extremely
sensitive high-tech device called a spectrometer. The team
installed the device on the Keck telescope to make it even more
precise in measuring the speed of the parent stars' wobbles.
Pinning down those velocities _ about 3 meters per second, or some
6.7 miles an hour across more than 100 light-years of space _ is an
achievement in itself, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers have been examining the light from more than
1,000 stars to find candidates for solar systems, and they have
another 1,000 to go over the next few years. The team has already
pinpointed six to 10 other stars that appear ``promising'' as
targets for more planet-hunting right now, Marcy said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's findings so far, Butler said, ``suggests that
Earth-mass planets are extremely common in our galaxy.''
</P>
<P>
   But such planets can never be found using the detection
techniques of Marcy's team, the astronomers conceded. Our own sun,
for example, wobbles under Earth's influence with a velocity of
only one-tenth of a meter per second _ far beyond the technology
available now _ so it will take direct observations by future
space-based telescopes to find any Earth-like planets, the team
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   A curious and unexplained difference between the planets of our
solar system and the gas planets detected by Marcy's team is the
nature of their orbits. In our solar system, the planets in general
revolve around the sun in nearly circular orbits, while the
newfound gas planets fly in ``eccentric'' elliptical orbits that
would alternately freeze and melt any Earth-like planets there if
they existed at all, Marcy said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings so far ``suggest that our solar system is somewhat
unusual,'' he said. And that, he said, ``may have something to do
with the fact that biology has flourished here.''
</P>
<P>
   More information and images are on the Net at:
 &UR; origins.stsci.edu/ &LR; 
 &UR; news/2000/01  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
