<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
 
TORNADO DAMAGE MAY HIT $450 million 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
and GINGER D. RICHARDSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Damage estimates from the storms that roared
through Fort Worth and south Arlington on Tuesday could soar as
high as $450 million, insurance adjusters said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Fire Department ended its ground search for
Adele Warren, 62, whose car was washed away as she left Bell
Helicopter Textron at the height of the storm. The body of Warren's
grandson, Ashlyn B. Dickens, 24, was found Wednesday morning in a
creek bed.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department spokesman Kent Worley said firefighters will fly
over the creek area Friday in helicopters provided by Bell, where
Warren had worked for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Warren was among five people killed by the storms, which spawned
two tornadoes about 30 minutes apart. Dozens suffered minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Spence, 67, and Howard D. Thornton, 52, were crushed to
death on the outskirts of downtown. Juan C. Oseguera, 19, died
Wednesday from severe head injuries suffered when a softball-size
hailstone hit him in Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-block area of downtown Fort Worth remained impassable
Thursday as workers cleared broken glass from Bank One and other
damaged high-rise buildings, and neighborhoods west of the city
center looked like a wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   Shards of glass rained from the tops of skyscrapers onto
deserted streets, and crews worked to remove uprooted trees and
overturned cars from the Linwood, Rivercrest and Monticello
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Fire Chief Larry McMillen said of downtown will
probably remain closed through the weekend. He said that eight
commercial buildings west of downtown are destroyed and that the
Cash America International building will probably have to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a massive cleanup operation under way,'' said Hugo
Malanga, director of transportation and public works for Fort
Worth. ``We're hoping that we can get the major debris cleared by
the end of the day today or early tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials are expected to continue strictly enforcing the
no-access zone Friday. Thursday, they began requiring property
owners and contractors to obtain passes for access to restricted
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The permits are available on the south end of City Hall and will
be issued only to those who provide a driver's license and/or
company identification, point of destination and their reason for
needing access to the damaged areas, city spokesman Pat Svacina
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stress that this is not for the regular workers,''
he said. ``This is not for the rank-and-file people who work
downtown. They will not be allowed into the restricted areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County has not been declared a disaster area by the
federal government, and Federal Emergency Management Agency workers
are expected to arrive sometime next week after paperwork is
completed, officials said. Gov. George W. Bush's office declared
the county a disaster area Wednesday at the request of County Judge
Tom Vandergriff.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth officials estimate local commercial damage alone at
$154 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington Mayor Elzie Odom said city staffers are having trouble
breaking out damage estimates for Arlington, because most official
agencies are seeking countywide figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a wild estimate that may or may not be close to
accurate,'' Odom said. ``They are telling me that just Arlington
may be about $28 million. But I'm reluctant to throw any number out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 Arlington homes sustained major damage, and 1,000
received light to moderate damage. Thirty-three businesses were
damaged, including Lear Corp., Buz Post Auto Body Shop, a U.S. Post
Office, the Health and Human Services Center and Bell Helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   In east Fort Worth on Thursday, firefighters, including members
of the department's dive team, combed a 2 1/2 mile stretch of creek
in a fruitless search for Warren. They were aided by volunteers,
search dogs and the Fort Worth police Mounted Patrol unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered everything we could the best way we could,'' Worley
said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who survived the storm, Thursday was a day of waiting
for insurance adjusters and city cleanup crews.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and Fort Worth city workers descended into the
heavily damaged Linwood and Monticello neighborhoods, armed with
water, axes, shovels and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents were outside, picking up trash from front lawns
and trying to patch windows with plastic, bedsheets and chunks of
plywood. As people worked in the chilly afternoon air, they
occasionally yelled to one another about their tornado experiences
or offered help.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Alvarado was driving home in his van when he saw the funnel
cloud barreling toward him from the west.
</P>
<P>
   He tore down Merrimac Street in Linwood to reach his home at 409
Foch St. and ran inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed and prayed,'' said Alvardo, who described himself as
a born-again Christian. ``This makes you believe in Christ real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are asking that sightseers avoid the area, saying the
extra traffic is hindering cleanup efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup scene was similar in south Arlington for residents
along the Embercrest Drive and Chasemore Lane, among the
hardest-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
   Although much activity surrounded what remained of the homes _
workers nailing boards or cleanup crews dragging debris to the
street _ life appeared to be stalled for many residents as they
stood around waiting for the most popular person in town: the
insurance adjuster.
</P>
<P>
   They called out to passers-by: ``Are you an insurance adjuster?
Have you seen one for Allstate? Have you seen one for State Farm?''
Spray paint on makeshift signs or garage doors spelled out the
names of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Chibli, 44, who lived at 4702 Osage Court until the
twister grabbed most of his roof, said he is frustrated that he
hasn't seen an adjuster sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're busy. Everybody is having the same problem,''
Chibli said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials also grew increasingly concerned Thursday about
scam artists, and warned residents not to pay contractors until
work is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want fly-by-night crews coming in and taking people's
money,'' Fort Worth Police Chief Ralph Mendoza said. ``Please only
deal with reputable businesses, and don't give anyone money
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate offers of help have begun flooding in.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County College and the Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce
are offering temporary office space to businesses displaced by the
storms. Lowe's, Home Depot, Payless Cashways and several other home
improvement stores are donating plywood.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take days for the city to regain some semblance
of normalcy, and months or longer before the damage is no longer
visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosmetically, we will be impacted for a while,'' Fort Worth
Mayor Kenneth Barr said. ``The downtown buildings will have plywood
on them for at least five or six months.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Deanna Boyd, Jim Fuquay and Rebeca Rodriguez
contributed to this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-COMMUNITY-A     03-30 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-COMMUNITY-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND POLICE COMMISSIONER SOFTEN TONE ON POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir have in recent days shifted on both the policy and public
relations fronts to a softer tone in an effort to ease tensions
over the death of a man who was fatally shot during a scuffle with
undercover officers who had approached him about buying drugs.
Statements made as part of this shift have included an expression
of sympathy to the family of the man, Patrick M. Dorismond, to an
examination of when police should draw their guns.
</P>
<P>
   These entreaties have not all produced the desired results: 11
Brooklyn clergy members walked out of a meeting arranged by Safir
on Thursday, including the Haitian priest who officiated at
Dorismond's funeral Saturday, which ended in a violent clash with
the police.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were disappointed that Safir would not apologize
directly for the shooting, and left just as Giuliani was arriving
at One Police Plaza to join the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the rejection, the mayor reacted in an unusually
conciliatory manner, telling reporters at an impromptu news
conference at Police Headquarters that he was still prepared to
meet with the religious leaders. In departing from what sometimes
seems like a scripted, standard defense of the police, Giuliani
acknowledged room for change within the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``No institution is perfect,'' the mayor said. The Police
Department ``is a lot better here than in most places in the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we can't improve,'' Giuliani said. ``It
doesn't mean we can't get better. It doesn't mean we can't do
things better.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenor of Giuliani's remarks shifted subtly, almost
imperceptibly, beginning Sunday, when the mayor for the first time
publicly said Dorismond's parents deserved condolences. It was 10
days after Dorismond had been shot to death. .
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, he acknowledged that the law was not entirely clear
regarding his decision to reveal Dorismond's record, including a
sealed juvenile record that Giuliani had disclosed earlier, saying
privacy rights did not extend beyond death.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the mayor's close advisers said the change in
Giuliani's public demeanor, and the steps he and Safir had taken to
ease tensions, were intentional. The shift followed criticism from
nearly all corners of the city and state, from people concerned
that the mayor's persistent attacks on Dorismond had gone too far
and merely served to exacerbate racial tension in the city.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the mayor has even dropped his repeated
references to the Rev. Al Sharpton and other persistent critics of
the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   A senior City Hall aide said that if the mayor's volume dial had
been set on ``10'' last week, it dropped to ``7'' by the end of
last weekend and was still on its way down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less of a smell of burning cordite in the city, and
everybody is on the way to calming down a bit,'' said Raymond B.
Harding, who is a close political adviser to the mayor and is the
leader of the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Safir has played a central role in the mayor's campaign to cool
tempers. The police commissioner agreed this week to allow clergy
members from the Bronx to attend police roll calls to let the
officers hear their concerns. On Wednesday, Safir gave an interview
on WLIB, a radio station with a largely black audience where
callers often criticize Giuliani. And both Safir and the mayor this
week backed a review of police department policies regarding when
it is appropriate for an officer to pull out a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond was shot March 16 outside the Wakamba Lounge, a few
blocks south of the Times Square area, during a failed drug sting.
He and an undercover officer got into an altercation and a
detective coming to officer's assistance drew his gun, which the
police have said fired accidentally after he became involved in the
scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Thursday's evening meeting with clergy members,
Safir commented Thursday that he realized tensions between the
Haitians, other minority groups and the Police Department are in
part tied up with race, a comment that brought immediate praise by
longtime critics of the police, such as Manhattan Borough President
C. Virginia Fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around the country, the complaints that we hear in
New York city are the same complaints that you hear in Louisville,
Los Angeles and Miami and in lots of other cities,'' Safir said.
``And lets face it, we are all honest. This is about race.
Something we all have to face and something we all have to talk to
each other about.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift in tone by the mayor came following polls that showed
his eroding support in his bid for the United States Senate, in
part because of his repeated attacks on Dorismond. Giuliani's aides
said Thursday that many of the mayor's advisers had been calling on
him in recent weeks to tone down his rhetoric and perhaps even give
a forthright public address on community police relations in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   But other advisers noted that if he offered a direct apology to
Dorismond's family it would be characterized as a capitulation by
the mayor to his critics. So Giuliani has decided to respond in his
own way, modifying the tone and content of his language, while
still defending his earlier actions and statements.
</P>
<P>
   Following Thursday's meeting with the clergy, which Giuliani
tried to join just as they were walking out, the mayor said he is
ready to try to resolve differences between minority communities
and the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the meeting in good faith, and I assume in good
faith,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The religious leaders made it clear that they believed an
immediate apology was welcome, but they were clear that the are
open to future talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of our negotiations hinges on his acceptable
of an apology to mark a new beginning,''said Monsignor Guy Sansari
of St. Jerome Church in Flatbush ``We said we would be happy to
meet with him again when the apology comes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
