<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN31-COX-1STLEDE     03-30 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN31-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Updates 4th graf, comments from Jackson.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Field where Al-Amin's car found may be key
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Authorities in White Hall _ the tiny Alabama town
where Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin was arrested last week _ said the
vacant field where the suspected cop killer's black Mercedes-Benz
was discovered belongs to the mother of White Hall Mayor John
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The car, considered a key piece of evidence in the shooting
death of Fulton County Deputy Ricky Kinchen and the injuring of his
partner, Aldranon English, was found in the field Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The land, off of County Road 17 in White Hall, is ``in close
proximity to Jackson's house,'' said Lowndes County Sheriff Willie
Vaughner. Jackson and Al-Amin, a former Black Panther known as H.
Rap Brown, have been acquainted for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson would not confirm the land belongs to his mother
Thursday, saying ``I have given my statements to the Fulton County
District Attorney's Office. Ask them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the discovery of a Georgia license plate behind a
small cafe in White Hall earlier this week may lead federal agents
back to friends of Al-Amin's who live in the Islamic community in
the town, Vaughner said. The license plate was originally attached
to the Mercedes. The car, according to Atlanta police, is
registered to Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe _ called the Bismillah Cafe _ and the field where the
car was uncovered, are about a mile apart, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   The friends _ two men and two women _ were detained March 20
just before Al-Amin was arrested in a wooded area in the town. FBI
Special Agent Bill Imfeld said the friends were stopped and held
overnight after a tipster told federal authorities they were seen
in a black Cadillac Seville near the spot where Al-Amin reportedly
had shot at U.S. marshal.
</P>
<P>
   The friends have denied seeing Al-Amin after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The four were held overnight at the Montgomery County Jail, but
were released the next day after police decided there was no
evidence showing they had harbored Al-Amin in White Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These friends of his are somehow associated with the cafe, and
I'm sure they'll be questioned a second time, seeing that the
license tag was found behind the restaurant,'' Vaughner said
Thursday. ``Then the Mercedes was found close by.''
</P>
<P>
   Extradition proceedings for Al-Amin could began as early as
today before Judge Lynn Bright in Montgomery District Court, where
indictment charges would be explained to him. Then his case would
move to Circuit Judge Charles Price's courtroom, where the actual
extradition hearing would occur. No date has been scheduled with
Price.
</P>
<P>
   As Al-Amin awaits extradition, the painstaking forensic
examination of his 1978 Mercedes may take several days. The results
could provide further evidence linking Al-Amin to the killing of a
Fulton County deputy, and perhaps provide evidence of a motive for
the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said there are bullet holes in the car. The first
priority will be to recover as many of the bullets that made them
as possible. The bullets will be compared to test samples fired
from the guns of Kinchen and English. If they match, then the
Mercedes was at the murder scene and one more major piece of
evidence is added to the state's case against Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Gita Smith contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
