r a BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX     03-30 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Replaces dropped word in eighth graf beginning ``Fort Worth
Fire Chief'') 
TORNADO DAMAGE MAY HIT $450 million 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
and GINGER D. RICHARDSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Damage estimates from the storms that roared
through Fort Worth and south Arlington on Tuesday could soar as
high as $450 million, insurance adjusters said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Fire Department ended its ground search for
Adele Warren, 62, whose car was washed away as she left Bell
Helicopter Textron at the height of the storm. The body of Warren's
grandson, Ashlyn B. Dickens, 24, was found Wednesday morning in a
creek bed.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department spokesman Kent Worley said firefighters will fly
over the creek area Friday in helicopters provided by Bell, where
Warren had worked for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Warren was among five people killed by the storms, which spawned
two tornadoes about 30 minutes apart. Dozens suffered minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Spence, 67, and Howard D. Thornton, 52, were crushed to
death on the outskirts of downtown. Juan C. Oseguera, 19, died
Wednesday from severe head injuries suffered when a softball-size
hailstone hit him in Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-block area of downtown Fort Worth remained impassable
Thursday as workers cleared broken glass from Bank One and other
damaged high-rise buildings, and neighborhoods west of the city
center looked like a wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   Shards of glass rained from the tops of skyscrapers onto
deserted streets, and crews worked to remove uprooted trees and
overturned cars from the Linwood, Rivercrest and Monticello
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Fire Chief Larry McMillen said most of downtown will
probably remain closed through the weekend. He said that eight
commercial buildings west of downtown are destroyed and that the
Cash America International building will probably have to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a massive cleanup operation under way,'' said Hugo
Malanga, director of transportation and public works for Fort
Worth. ``We're hoping that we can get the major debris cleared by
the end of the day today or early tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials are expected to continue strictly enforcing the
no-access zone Friday. Thursday, they began requiring property
owners and contractors to obtain passes for access to restricted
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The permits are available on the south end of City Hall and will
be issued only to those who provide a driver's license and/or
company identification, point of destination and their reason for
needing access to the damaged areas, city spokesman Pat Svacina
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stress that this is not for the regular workers,''
he said. ``This is not for the rank-and-file people who work
downtown. They will not be allowed into the restricted areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County has not been declared a disaster area by the
federal government, and Federal Emergency Management Agency workers
are expected to arrive sometime next week after paperwork is
completed, officials said. Gov. George W. Bush's office declared
the county a disaster area Wednesday at the request of County Judge
Tom Vandergriff.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth officials estimate local commercial damage alone at
$154 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington Mayor Elzie Odom said city staffers are having trouble
breaking out damage estimates for Arlington, because most official
agencies are seeking countywide figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a wild estimate that may or may not be close to
accurate,'' Odom said. ``They are telling me that just Arlington
may be about $28 million. But I'm reluctant to throw any number out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 Arlington homes sustained major damage, and 1,000
received light to moderate damage. Thirty-three businesses were
damaged, including Lear Corp., Buz Post Auto Body Shop, a U.S. Post
Office, the Health and Human Services Center and Bell Helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   In east Fort Worth on Thursday, firefighters, including members
of the department's dive team, combed a 2 1/2 mile stretch of creek
in a fruitless search for Warren. They were aided by volunteers,
search dogs and the Fort Worth police Mounted Patrol unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered everything we could the best way we could,'' Worley
said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who survived the storm, Thursday was a day of waiting
for insurance adjusters and city cleanup crews.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and Fort Worth city workers descended into the
heavily damaged Linwood and Monticello neighborhoods, armed with
water, axes, shovels and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents were outside, picking up trash from front lawns
and trying to patch windows with plastic, bedsheets and chunks of
plywood. As people worked in the chilly afternoon air, they
occasionally yelled to one another about their tornado experiences
or offered help.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Alvarado was driving home in his van when he saw the funnel
cloud barreling toward him from the west.
</P>
<P>
   He tore down Merrimac Street in Linwood to reach his home at 409
Foch St. and ran inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed and prayed,'' said Alvardo, who described himself as
a born-again Christian. ``This makes you believe in Christ real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are asking that sightseers avoid the area, saying the
extra traffic is hindering cleanup efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup scene was similar in south Arlington for residents
along the Embercrest Drive and Chasemore Lane, among the
hardest-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
   Although much activity surrounded what remained of the homes _
workers nailing boards or cleanup crews dragging debris to the
street _ life appeared to be stalled for many residents as they
stood around waiting for the most popular person in town: the
insurance adjuster.
</P>
<P>
   They called out to passers-by: ``Are you an insurance adjuster?
Have you seen one for Allstate? Have you seen one for State Farm?''
Spray paint on makeshift signs or garage doors spelled out the
names of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Chibli, 44, who lived at 4702 Osage Court until the
twister grabbed most of his roof, said he is frustrated that he
hasn't seen an adjuster sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're busy. Everybody is having the same problem,''
Chibli said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials also grew increasingly concerned Thursday about
scam artists, and warned residents not to pay contractors until
work is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want fly-by-night crews coming in and taking people's
money,'' Fort Worth Police Chief Ralph Mendoza said. ``Please only
deal with reputable businesses, and don't give anyone money
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate offers of help have begun flooding in.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County College and the Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce
are offering temporary office space to businesses displaced by the
storms. Lowe's, Home Depot, Payless Cashways and several other home
improvement stores are donating plywood.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take days for the city to regain some semblance
of normalcy, and months or longer before the damage is no longer
visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosmetically, we will be impacted for a while,'' Fort Worth
Mayor Kenneth Barr said. ``The downtown buildings will have plywood
on them for at least five or six months.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Deanna Boyd, Jim Fuquay and Rebeca Rodriguez
contributed to this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
