u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT &LR;      03-30 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA CONSIDERS BILL TO BLUNT FINANCIAL THREAT TO CIGARETTE
COMPANIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   State lawmakers in Florida may soon take up legislation intended
to reduce the financial threat to cigarette makers in a high-stakes
tobacco case that is reaching a critical phase in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Florida lawmakers, the state attorney general,
Robert A. Butterworth, offered model legislation this week that
would delay the awarding of punitive damages in any Florida lawsuit
until all compensatory damages in the action were resolved. Doing
so in the Miami case could delay a punitive judgment for years,
since compensatory damages must be considered individually and
hundreds of thousands of people are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Florida lawmakers said in interviews Thursday that it was
uncertain whether the legislation drafted by Butterworth would be
offered. But the proposal, first reported in The Los Angeles Times
Thursday, is clearly intended to affect the large class-action case
in Miami that was brought against the tobacco industry on behalf of
all Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, a six-person panel will soon decide whether the
ills of three representative smokers were caused by cigarettes. If
the jury makes such a finding regarding any one of those smokers,
it would then award punitive damages, or those meant to punish a
company, for the entire class. Though its size is unknown, the case
is estimated to cover 300,000 to 500,000 current or former smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Miami jury held that the industry had conspired
to hide the dangers of its products, setting the stage for a likely
punitive damage award.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that an award could reach tens of billions of
dollars and might lead some producers to seek bankruptcy
protection. Such a move would imperil producer payments under
recent settlements reached with states worth $246 billion over the
next two decades. Florida's share of that money is $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a number of interests, including cigarette
makers, have lobbied state lawmakers for legislation to blunt the
financial impact of the Miami case, several people involved in
those efforts said. Other groups expressing concern about the case
include financial institutions seeking to sell bonds backed by
Florida's settlement funds, those people said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Butterworth said the attorney general was
traveling and unavailable for comment. But in his letter to
lawmakers, Butterworth noted that his proposal would only codify
prevailing court decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Florida lawmakers said in interviews Thursday that they were
concerned that a huge award in the Miami lawsuit might stop the
flow of settlement payments to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said they expected that some legislation affecting
the Miami case could emerge next week, but they questioned whether
it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Rosenblatt, the chief lawyer in the class-action
lawsuit, is barred by a court order from discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Montgomery, a lawyer in Palm Beach who said that he
had consulted with Rosenblatt on the case, said that Florida law
barred the awarding of punitive damages so high that they would
force a company into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of any legislation that might blunt the effects of
the anticipated punitive damage award in the Florida case sent
tobacco stocks up sharply on Wall Street Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
