<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ELIAN-NEGOTIATE-BOS &LR;      03-30 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-NEGOTIATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS GOVERNMENT SET TO INTERVENE; FATHER PREPARES TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the father of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez took
concrete steps toward traveling to the United States to retrieve
his son, Attorney General Janet Reno insisted the US government
would be prepared to intervene if the child's current guardians
refuse to let him go.
</P>
<P>
   Peacefully extricating the boy from his Miami relatives, who
took custody of him after his arrival on US soil four months ago,
remains a tricky prospect. Even if a court orders Elian's return to
his father, as is expected, it would be politically disastrous for
the Justice Department to intervene using force, especially given
the heightened tensions surrounding his case in his newfound Miami
home.
</P>
<P>
   In part to head off such a scenario, Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, applied for a US visa Thursday, said his attorney,
Gregory B. Craig. Officials hope Gonzalez's arrival might offer a
peaceful venue for his reunion with the boy, who has become a
symbol of the hostilities between Cuba and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the wrangling with Elian's Miami relatives
will be on hold. After a second day of negotiations, federal
officials Thursday said they will wait until Tuesday before taking
any action to remove the boy from his current home.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of the continued standoff, Craig said
Elian's father was ready to fly to this country to see his son ``at
a moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The relatives in Miami do not speak for Elian. The lawyers in
Miami do not speak for Elian,'' said Craig, who was a
foreign-policy adviser to Senator Edward M. Kennedy and represented
President Clinton during his Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who has the legal and moral authority to speak
for Elian is his father,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Reno, when asked whether the federal government was prepared
to enforce the law if the boy's relatives did not agree to cede
that power to his father, said: ``You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, which began last November when Elian survived a
treacherous boat ride from Cuba that killed his mother and 10
others, was thrust back into the spotlight last week as a federal
judge in Florida upheld a ruling by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service that the boy must be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Justice Department has tried to coordinate a
plan to retrieve the boy, in preparation for a final legal ruling
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   By working out a deal with Elian's relatives ahead of time, Reno
hopes to preempt any violent outbreaks in Miami, if an appeals
court again rules Elian must go home.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans in the Miami community have indicated they would go to
great lengths to keep Elian, regardless of what the court decides,
and local law enforcement agents have essentially backed them up.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, under no circumstances would Justice Department
officials, still under fire for their handling of sieges at Waco
and Ruby Ridge, want to send armed forces to retrieve Elian and
send him home, several legal specialists and members of Congress
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they just decide to go there to the house, they are going
to face thousands upon thousands of Cubans,'' said Representative
J. Joseph Moakley, Democrat of South Boston, who has been in
contact with Elian's grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Immigration and the Justice departments have got to plan
this out. We can't have another Waco situation where people are
going to get killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative James P. McGovern, Democrat of Worcester, said
the Justice Department is in ``a very tricky spot. That's why
they're giving the family every possible option to be cooperative
and to do what's in the best interest of the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Reno, despite her insistence that the government would
carry out the full extent of the law, said she hoped Elian's
father's arrival in the United States would remove the need for
further government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   During an unusually personal news conference, Reno made it clear
she had been touched by the case, which has played out in the South
Florida region where Reno once lived and worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a community I was born in, raised in. It's a community I
love. And when it's hurting, it hurts me,'' she said. But Reno
declined to give credence to the perspective of the Cuban
protesters in Miami, who view returning Elian to the regime of
Fidel Castro as political heresy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been heartbreaking for everyone involved, but we
believe that the law is clear,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father must speak for the little boy, because the sacred
bond between parent and child must be recognized and honored, and
Elian should be reunited with his father,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials Thursday reiterated their promise to
expedite that process, speeding up the visa application for Elian's
father. Cuban officials also released a list of nearly three dozen
others hoping to come along for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the father's attorney said he had thus far submitted visa
applications only for family members, including Juan Miguel
Gonzalez's current wife, their 4-year-old son, and a favorite
cousin of Elian's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have received assurances that Juan Miguel will be able
to take custody of his son, we will also be seeking permission for
a support group of Elian's classmates, teachers, and doctors to
come to the United States to help smooth the transition,'' Craig
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the spotlight in the drama shifted to Washington, tensions in
Miami relaxed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   A second day of talks between Immigration and Naturalization
officials and lawyers for Elian's relatives in downtown Miami ended
without an agreement after about eight hours, with plans to resume
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The government said that pending the results of the next round
of negotiations, it would extend the deadline for taking action on
Elian. The deadline, which already had been extended to this
morning, now is set for 9 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That arrangement gave all sides some breathing room. But the
anxiety in Miami, and within the area's Cuban-exile population in
particular, clearly remains because of the sense that the federal
government is going to try soon _ one way or another _ to return
the youngster to his father.'
</P>
<P>
   And that is something Cuban-American activists said they will
try mightily to prevent, no matter what agreement might be reached
at the INS offices in Miami or by the State Department in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're getting ready for the worst,'' said Ileana
Bosche, one of hundreds of Cuban-Americans who shuttled into the
crowd outside the house where Elian lives with the family of his
great uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rodriguez, another of the protesters, added: ``God
willing, we won't need to have any civil disobedience or anything
like that, but we will do what we need to do . . . and it looks
like we'll have to do something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
