<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BREWERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN REGULATORS APPROVE MERGER OF 2 BIG BREWERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ga., the Netherlands, Mexico, Portugal)   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Antitrust regulators approved the $7 billion
merger of the two biggest beverage companies in Brazil Thursday,
creating the world's third-largest brewer.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Companhia Cervejaria Brahmas and Companhia
Antarctica Paulista into a company called Companhia de Bebidas das
Americas, or AmBev, was first announced last year, and came after
months of government scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the deal sent a powerful message about the potential
for other big mergers in Brazil. It represented a setback to
smaller beverage producers, who fear that AmBev could crush
competition in Brazil, Latin America's biggest economy.
</P>
<P>
   AmBev will control nearly 70 percent of Brazil's beer market,
where its Brahma, Skol and Antarctica brands are leading sellers
among the combined company's 18 beer labels. Ambev also will
control a quarter of the soft drinks industry with a product lineup
that includes 37 soft drinks and seven brands of water. Worldwide,
only Anheuser-Busch Cos. of the United States and Heineken NV of
The Netherlands are larger.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is the third-largest market worldwide for Coca-Cola after
the United States and Mexico. Coke controls about half of Brazil's
soft drinks market, in addition to owning a minority stake in
Cervejarias Kaiser, the country's third-largest brewer.
</P>
<P>
   While Kaiser and other critics had complained that the approval
of AmBev could give the company the ability to dictate beverage
prices within Brazil, the majority of regulators apparently viewed
the merger as consistent with a goal of the government's broader
economic policy _ encouraging the formation of large companies
capable of competing in markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   One of AmBev's goals is to capture 1 percent of the global soft
drinks market by exporting a beverage made with guarana, an
Amazonian berry, in a venture with PepsiCo. The company also hopes
to strengthen its presence in Latin American countries where Brahma
is already sold.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in Brazil's domestic beverage market, the federal
antitrust agency's approval of the merger was greeted with
surprise, even though several conditions were attached, like the
sale of several manufacturing facilities and one beer brand,
Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strict antitrust standpoint I thought that any merger
resulting in 70 percent market share would have trouble getting
approved,'' said John Ferencz McNaughton, a lawyer specializing in
antitrust policy at Noronha Advogados, Brazil's largest law firm.
``At the very least, the expectations were for stronger
restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible beneficiary from the approval may be Cintra, a
Portuguese brewer that is reportedly considering the purchase of
some of AmBev's factories.
</P>
<P>
   Other beverage concerns were critical.Kaiser, AmBev's main
competitor, said it is seeking a way to appeal. ``The ruling is
full of holes,'' said Humberto Pandolpho, Kaiser's president. ``It
is an insult to the Brazilian consumer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2804 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-2NDTAKE     03-30 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: reached adulthood. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would support that position and I think the vice president
would,'' Graham said. ``And the overwhelming number of people in
Miami, including in the Cuban community, would support such a
determination if they thought it was made by an appropriate
judicial body.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who said the Senate has taken the first steps toward
petitioning the majority to bring his bill to the floor, added:
``The purpose of this legislation is to try to be a channel to move
this case from an INS asylum case to a family court.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was the purpose behind Gore's statement Thursday, his
aides said. ``This was the only way to vindicate the principle,
that this should be decided in a court that deals with custody
cases,'' a top adviser said. Contrary to some suggestions, he
added, Gore's action may have the effect of calming the people of
Miami rather than stirring them up.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore said in his statement: ``Let us be clear that the real
fault in this case lies with the oppressive regime of Fidel Castro.
Elian should never have been forced to choose between freedom and
his own father. Now we must take action, here on our own shores, to
make sure that Elian's best interests are served.''
</P>
<P>
   But he definitely stirred up Washington, including some on his
own staff. ``This was not something that was discussed, chewed over
and thought out for a long time or that huge numbers of people were
consulted on,'' an adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Jake Siewert, a spokesman for Clinton, said
that Gore had alerted Clinton in advance and that the president was
not upset. ``We knew there would be times when he differed with the
president,'' Siewert said. ``This is one of those times.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said: ``We've stated in the past we don't
believe congressional action is appropriate in this situation.
There is a father who speaks for his son and has made it very clear
that he wants to be reunited with him as soon as possible, and that
is what we are trying to do. The INS has received no credible
information that any of these family members wants to stay in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, said the vice president
``clearly disagrees with the INS and the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's break with the administration is the most
dramatic of his campaign to date. Back in November, as Gore
struggled to assert his independence from the president and become
his own man, he told reporters: ``Running for president of this
country is far more important than being the best vice president I
can possibly be.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has differed from administration policy in a
number of areas. He said he would require his appointees to the
Joint Chiefs of Staff to support allowing gays to serve openly in
the military. He said he supported the use of marijuana for
medicinal purposes. And he has opposed a Clinton nominee to the
Federal Election Commission because that nominee, Bradley Smith,
opposes changing the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these matters has been a matter of national urgency,
as Elian's case has become.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
