R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee during a
visit ot the U.S. Capitol on Thursday. Looking on from left are:
Ambs. Anwarul Karim Chowdhury of Bangladesh, current president of
the Security Council; Jean Levitte of France; Wang Ying Fan of
China, Arnoldo Listre of Argentina and Amb. Agam Hasmy of Malaysia.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ATLANTA -- March 30, 2000 -- MANSION-DWELLERS-COX -- If
you're rich, especially if you're very rich, and live in the
Buckhead area of Atlanta in a house large enough to double as an
airplane hangar, there's a good chance you know Mike Adams. ``I
manage my clients' lives so they can live the kind of lifestyle
their income allows,'' says Adams, founder of MBA Management which
provides domestic staff for homes, lawn maintenance, chefs, wine
stewards, even helicopter pilots. (Phil Skinner/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- PELICANS-RELEASED -- In
another sign that spring has sprung, a group of pelicans, removed
from outdoor facilities at the Bronx Zoo before winter, are
released Thursday after spending the season in special housing.
(Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TAR HEEL, N.C. -- March 30, 2000 -- SMITHFIELD-HAM -- The
Smithfield pork processing plant in Tar Heel, NC. Smithfield Foods,
operates hog farms and slaughterhouses throughout the country,
supplying pork to the nation's biggest supermarkets and fast food
outlets like McDonald's. The company has come under intense
scrutiny from state and federal regulators who say that big
agricultural companies like Smithfield may wield too much control
over the nation's food supply, and too much pricing power in the
meatpacking industry. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- OPERA-QUIZ-KIDS -- If you
tune in Saturday afternoon to the Texaco Opera Quiz, the popular
intermission feature that is part of the live radio broadcasts of
the Metropolitan Opera, don't be surprised if the three panelists
sound rather young to be experts. They are the Texaco Quiz Kids, as
the producers of the broadcasts are calling this first-ever panel
of high school students. Their knowledge and suitability have been
tested through a series of regional competitions in the New York,
Houston, and Washington areas. Evan Diamond, one of three teenage
panelists on the Texaco Opera Quiz. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO -- March 30, 2000 -- APPLES-CHICAGO-3 -- The
Sears Tower in the Loop, background, seen from the Kinzie Street
Bridge. Reviled in the days of Al Capone and John Dillinger as a
haven for hoodlums, Chicago has been maligned for years. But no
more. Chicago enters the 21st century as a prosperous, well-
governed model for the rest of the country. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- March 30, 2000 -- APPLES-CHICAGO-2 -- In the
Carson Pirie Scott store on State Street, Louis Sullivan expressed
the revolutionary steel grid in bands of windows that became a
Chicago School trademark. Reviled in the days of Al Capone and John
Dillinger as a haven for hoodlums, Chicago was maligned for years.
But no more. Chicago enters the 21st century as a prosperous, well-
governed model for the rest of the country. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- March 30, 2000 -- APPLES-CHICAGO-1 -- In among
Chicago's shining towers stands an unparalleled collection of
modern street sculpture including Picasso's enigmatic Cor-Ten steel
beast outside the Daley Center. Reviled in the days of Al Capone
and John Dillinger as a haven for hoodlums, Chicago was maligned
for years. But no more. Chicago enters the 21st century as a
prosperous, well- governed model for the rest of the country.
(Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 30, 2000 -- JAPANESE-ART-COLLECTOR-2 --
A 10th-century Japanese cypress sculpture of a seated Shinto god
from an exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum titled,
``Masterpieces of Japanese Art From the Mary Griggs Burke
Collection.'' The exhibit will be on display at the musem through
June 25. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 30, 2000 -- JAPANESE-ART-COLLECTOR-1 --
A 17th-century Japanese screen ``Women Contemplating Floating
Fans,'' from an exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum. The work is
part of the exhibit titled, ``Masterpieces of Japanese Art From the
Mary Griggs Burke Collection'' which will be on display at the
musem through June 25. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM -- March 30, 2000 -- MIDEAST-PROTEST --
Palestinians staged marches Thursday in Israel, the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, to protest the confiscation of Arab-owned land and
Jewish settlement expansion. Near the Dome of the Rock, in the
background, Palestinians waved flags during a demonstration in
Jerusalem. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
