<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thurssday, 03/30/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- BING-MOTHERHOOD --
Elisabeth Bing, seen with a friend, led the American movement for
natural childbirth. Like so many pioneers, Bing, who fled Nazi
Germany in 1933, knows that the measure of her success is that
young women now take the advances she engendered in the obstetrical
profession for granted. ``We are not being tied down anymore,'' she
said. ``We're not lying flat on our backs with our legs in the air,
shaved like a baby. You can give birth in any position you like.
We've got it all.'' (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- NY-POLICE-COMMUNITY --
Police Commissioner Howard Safir, at center in rear of elevator
with security officers and staff members, after 11 clergy members
walked out of a meeting Thursday on the fatal police shooting of
Patrick M. Dorismond. They said they were disappointed that Safir
would not apologize directly for the shooting, and left just as
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was arriving at One Police Plaza to join the
gathering. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) HOLYOKE, Mass. -- March 30, 2000 -- DOG-TREATS-BOS
--Kara and Debbie Healy with their dog Amstel in the basement of
their grandmother's house where they first started making dog
biscuits. Although the Healy sisters are both former college
English majors who never cracked a business textbook, their
projections tell them that America's dogs will lap up some $500,000
worth of their biscuits, called ``Hi5s,'' this year. That still
makes them a minuscule pet supplier, but they impressed a local
supermarket chain so much that they added their canine niblets to
the shelves of 168 of its 202 stores. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNION CITY, N.J. -- March 30, 2000 -- NJ-SENATE-CORZINE
-- Many in New Jersey are basing their first impression of John
Corzine not on his record as an investment banker but on joking
slurs against Italian Americans, the state's largest ethnic group.
As Corzine sought to put those derogatory references and even his
apology for them behind him Thursday, Italian American leaders
expressed outrage and asked whether he had the sensitivity to serve
in public office. Corzine spoke to reporters, Thursday. (Dith
Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 2000 -- U.N.-SECURITYCOUNCIL-3
-- Members of the U.N. Security Council listen to Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, in the
Old Senate Chamber during a visit ot the U.S. Capitol on Thursday.
Looking on from clockwise from upper left: Ambs. Anwarul Karim
Chowdhury of Bangladesh, current president of the Security Council;
Jean Levitte of France; Wang Ying Fan of China, Arnoldo Listre of
Argentina and Amb. Agam Hasmy of Malaysia. (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- HEDGE-FUND -- Julian
Robertson, manager of the Tiger Fund, in his office Thursday. After
twenty years of generating superlative investment returns, buying
stocks that were undervalued and selling short those that carried
excessive valuations, Robertson is shutting down Tiger's
operations. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SARASOTA, Fla. -- March 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APR.
2 -- BBO-FREEAGENCY -- The face of free agency, as demonstrated by
the trades of Ken Griffey Jr. and Juan Gonzalez, is changing.
Griffey heads for a team portrait photo session at the Reds spring
training facility in February. (Mike Lang/Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- March 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APR. 2 -- BBN-BENITEZ -- New York Mets relief pitcher Armando
Benitez watching his team play against the Baltimore Orioles
earlier this week. Benitez has matured both emotionally and
professionally since his explosive stint with the Baltimore
Orioles. (Gary I. Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APR. 2 --
BBA-TORRE -- Most people look at Joe Torre and see the quiet,
confident manager who has led the Yankees to two consecutive world
championships. Sister Marguerite Torre, the principal of Nativity
Blessed Virgin Mary Elementary School in Queens, looks at her kid
brother and still sees the little boy she bought a baseball glove
for when he was 11 years old. Torre with her students earlier this
week. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APR. 2
-- BBA-RIVERA -- Mariano Rivera, the New York Yankees' virtually
unhittable reliever is the key to their hopes for winning a third
consecutive world championship this season. Rivera, during spring
training earlier this month. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 30, 2000 -- SCIENCE-PLAYGROUND --
Elementary school students try out the spider web, made of
reinforced-steel rope, at the Science Playground, a 30,000-square
foot park on the grounds of the New York Hall of Science in Queens,
Thursday. The park officially opens this weekend. This is the
fourth season the museum has opened the playground which lets
children have fun while learning a little physics in the process.
(Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 2000 -- CLINTON-EMAIL -- White
House counsel Beth Nolan testifies before the House Government
Reform Committee, Thursday. Nolan suggested to committee members
that a court affidavit describing the White House system for
archiving e-mail was literally true, even though it didn't disclose
that many messages were missing. In the background is Dimitri
Nionakis, left, associate counsel to the president, and White House
counsel Jim Kennedy. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 2000 -- GORE-FUTURE-CARS -- With
high gas prices serving as a backdrop, Vice President Al Gore
announced Thursday that the Big Three automakers have agreed to
mass produce vehicles with ``significant improvements'' in gas
mileage within four years. Jim Holden, right, president of
DaimlerChrysler, talks to Gore as John Rintamaki, vice president of
Ford, looks on, Thursday. Vehicles from foreground are: GM's
Precept, Ford's Prodigy and DaimlerChrysler's ESX3. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 2000 -- U.N.-SECURITYCOUNCIL-2
-- Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, facing camera, and Amb. Rihard Holbrooke,
third from right, the U.S. representative at the United Nations,
mingle with members of the U.N. Security Council in the Old Senate
Chamber on Capitol Hill, Thursday. The U.N. Security Council took
seats in the historic chamber Thursday for a greeting and a civics
lesson from Helms, the ardent critic of the world body who reminded
the visiting delegates of the Senate's ``unique role'' in U.S.
foreign policy. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
