<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DELIVERY: &LR;  Don't pity the poor Internet delivery driver who brings
your groceries on a rainy Friday night. He's probably well rewarded
for what he does, drawing a competitive salary, full benefits, a
signing bonus, yearly stipends and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   That's the hefty price a growing number of dot-com delivery
services are paying in an extremely tight labor market to deliver
their groceries, restaurant meals, videos and more on time.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; JENNIE YABROFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STOCKS: &LR;  For much of Thursday's trading session, it looked as
though the Nasdaq Stock Market might be headed for a disaster of
epic proportions. But thanks to a powerful, late rally, the net
result turned out to be merely terrible.  &UR; BY ARTHUR LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NET WORTH:  &LR;  Corporate divorces usually work out better for
shareholders than corporate marriages, but few pay off like the
breakup of Varian Associates. One year ago, in one of the more
amazing transformations in Silicon Valley history, the big old slug
of a company split itself into three little sexy ones.
 &UR; COLUMN BY KATHLEEN PENDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; POISON: &LR;  The poison runs deep in the little Mendocino County city
of Willits. A cocktail of chromium and other highly toxic chemicals
has contaminated the town's groundwater _ the result of decades of
illegal dumping and spills from a now-bankrupt hydraulics plant
adjacent to residential neighborhoods, schools and busy commercial
areas. Everyone agrees on this point.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
