<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2822 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DELIVERY--DRIVERS-SFC     03-30 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELIVERY--DRIVERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING A GREAT DEAL: DOT-COM FIRMS GIVE SCARCE DRIVERS A 
 HANDSOME PACKAGE TO DELIVER INTERNET GOODS TO E-CUSTOMERS 
 &HT;     BY JENNIE YABROFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Don't pity the poor Internet delivery driver who brings your
groceries on a rainy Friday night. He's probably well rewarded for
what he does, drawing a competitive salary, full benefits, a
signing bonus, yearly stipends and stock options.
<P>
   That's the hefty price a growing number of dot-com delivery
services are paying in an extremely tight labor market to deliver
their groceries, restaurant meals, videos and more on time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The demand for drivers is really high,'' said Gary Narducci
of EZ2Get, a restaurant delivery service that recently bought
Dine-One-One. ``We're having to constantly increase our pool as the
business grows, and it's a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   EZ2Get offers a $500 signing bonus to new employees and referral
bonuses to drivers who bring in new employees. The Dallas company
pays a base rate of $5 to $8 an hour for drivers, plus tips, and is
planning a stock option plan for all employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a (job) crunch right now, and gas prices aren't
helping,'' said Jerry Spence, a dispatcher for EZ2Get. ``It's a
great market to be in if you don't mind driving.'' EZ2Get employs
about 40 drivers for San Francisco, including students and others
who hold two jobs. Spence said some of EZ2Get's employees work two
shifts _ one for his company and another for one of its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   With more positions available than workers, drivers are jumping
from one company to another, looking for the best money and most
convenient schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Narducci said that although drivers leave to work for services
like Kozmo.com or Federal Express, some come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few competitors initially (hired) a lot of people and
offered a lot of money,'' he said. ``But the drivers would be
sitting around the warehouse with nothing to do, so (the companies)
had to scale back. It takes awhile to judge how many drivers you'll
need each night.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Kozmo.com, a movie and grocery delivery service, was
mum about providing information because it is in a pre-IPO ``quiet
period.'' It would only say its hiring has been on target.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, companies like EZ2Get have come to accept high
turnover rates as part of the cost of business.
</P>
<P>
   Other delivery services such as Foster City's Webvan concentrate
on attracting long-term employees. Starting drivers for the grocery
delivery service (which the company prefers to call couriers, or
customer service ambassadors) make $14 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Total compensation for a first-year employee at Webvan averages
more than $40,000, including bonuses, full medical coverage, a $400
stipend for a gym membership or exercise equipment, $1,500 tuition
reimbursement, stock option, and $2,000 toward a 401(k). Plus, the
lunches are free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in business over a year, and our initial 25
couriers are all still with us,'' said Bud Greby, director of
corporate affairs for Webvan. ``They have a lot of loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zaleski, who hires couriers for Webvan, said his company
hasn't had any problems hiring workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, where the unemployment rate is less than 2
percent, we've gotten 10,000 applications for our new operations.
So far, we've hired 200,'' he said. The ratio for the Bay Area
business is comparable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1 out of every 3 applicants makes it to the interview stage
at Webvan, and only 1 out of 10 is hired as a courier. Applicants
must have clean driving and criminal records and are screened for
drugs before they begin a two-week training period. The company
employs about 240 couriers for the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Employers and drivers agree the key to attracting and keeping
employees is treating the company like an Internet business that
uses drivers, instead of like a traditional delivery service doing
business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies are quickly cutting a reputation for their
generous compensation packages, which usually include stock
options, as well as their nontraditional approaches to rewarding
and motivating workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kozmo has a real dot-com attitude,'' said driver Jennifer Leo,
who previously worked for Waiters on Wheels and now drives part
time for Kozmo.com to supplement her income.
</P>
<P>
   Leo said that she sees a lot more competition for drivers than a
few years ago and that the companies that will succeed are those
that offer lots of incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make it a fun place to work _ on weekend nights (the
drivers) divide into teams and we have contest with prizes,'' she
said. ``Kozmo is paving the way for these kinds of companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to get in on the ground floor and grow with the
company also attracts employees. Randy Cervantes, who drove for
Federal Express for five years before becoming Webvan's first
courier, has been promoted three times since joining the company.
``I'm really happy to be here _ I make more money than I have in
any other delivery job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Webvan lets me have a say in things, is more open to my ideas
than other companies. If I come up with a way to improve the
process, they listen, and it might even lead to a promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cervantes also said Webvan's computerized system of calculating
how long deliveries will take means a less stressful workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Fed Ex, they didn't take into account how many packages you
had to deliver in your shift, so you had to do whatever you could
to get them all done,'' he said. ``Sometimes, it was really hard to
get it done. Webvan is better at taking into account the distance
between deliveries and the size of the orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express, which has lost drivers to Internet companies,
said it is still too early to gauge how big a threat they
represent. ``Everyone's looking to make a lot of quick cash right
now,'' said Tim Wertner, Federal Express managing director of
ground operations for the San Francisco area. ``We're staying
competitive while we see how many of the dot-coms are around in the
next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has responded to the current labor crunch by hiring
employees directly into courier positions, instead of starting them
in lower-paying jobs like package handlers.
</P>
<P>
   The starting wage for a Federal Express driver is $13.53 per
hour, which is comparable with most Internet delivery companies.
Employees receive full benefits, a pension plan and $2,000 to
$4,000 tuition remibursement for classes taken toward a college
degree. Although they aren't eligible for stock options, employees
do get the opportunity to fly free with delivery aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the chronic demand for drivers, delivery companies
depend on job fairs, employee references and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But desperate times call for desperate measures. Kozmo, for
instance, also targets college job boards and posts help wanted
signs in bike and scooter shops. (Kozmo drivers use a range of
transportation for deliveries.)
</P>
<P>
   Webvan goes so far as to hire customers and says it gets job
inquiries from people who have seen its vans.
</P>
<P>
   All delivery businesses, both high and low tech, share the same
tried-and-true method of attracting employees: classified
advertisements. ``If you want to compare companies, just look in
the classifieds under drivers,'' said EZ2Get's Narducci. ``You'll
see our ads, and the ads for all our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
