r f BC-STOCKS--DIVE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS--DIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ AVERTS TRAGEDY 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
For much of Thursday's trading session, it looked as though the
Nasdaq Stock Market might be headed for a disaster of epic
proportions. But thanks to a powerful, late rally, the net result
turned out to be merely terrible.
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, dominated by exceedingly volatile
high-technology and biotech stocks, finished the day down 186.78
points _ or 4 percent _ at 4,457.89, its fifth-largest point drop
ever.
</P>
<P>
   It has shed 590 points, or nearly 12 percent, since topping out
at 5,048.62 only three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Market experts urged investors not to worry, insisting that a
correction _ and the heart-stopping volatility that goes with it _
was natural and overdue, considering how far the Nasdaq had risen.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak on March 10, it stood 24 percent above where it was
at the end of 1999 _ a rate of gain that in retrospect clearly was
unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get extremely sharp upward moves like that, the
corrections are going to be sharp and nasty,'' said Alfred Goldman,
market strategist with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ``That's
just the way it works. The big picture is still bullish.''
</P>
<P>
   While Thursday's final tally _ the Nasdaq's third 100-plus point
drop in a row _ was bad enough, it pales by comparison with the
gore-on-the-floor carnage that prevailed up to the last half-hour
of trading.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture, the Nasdaq index was down nearly 290 points,
or more than 6 percent _ far worse than the record 229.46-point
drop it suffered on January 4.
</P>
<P>
   Then, out of the blue, bargain hunters charged in and eagerly
grabbed up a host of Nasdaq stalwarts, sending the index rebounding
by more than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   In those final 30 minutes, JDS Uniphase vaulted more than $5 to
finish at $116.25 after being down more than $8. Qualcomm also
gained more than $5 to close at $145.23, after falling a staggering
$17. Intel rebounded $2.63 to finish at $127 _ a net loss of $4.88
on the day.
</P>
<P>
   The other major market indexes also finished down yesterday,
after enduring their own, wild fluctuations. But their net losses
were relatively modest.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 20.60 points, or 1.4
percent, to 1,487.92. At one point, it was down nearly 34 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which sported a 125-point gain
at midsession and a 102-point loss later on, wound up losing 38.47
points, or 0.3 percent, at 10,980.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some froth built into the market _ it got ahead of
itself,'' said Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital
Management in San Francisco. ``Now there has been something of a
sobering-up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schlossberg stressed that there doesn't appear to be a
``change in the fundamentals'' that sent the market to its peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates have been rising, but not ``soaring,'' he noted.
``Economic growth is strong and bond yields are subdued, in part
because the inflation outlook is good.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
