<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     03-30 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INVESTORS WHO HELD ON TO VARIAN SHARES GET REWARDED 3 WAYS  &HT;    BY KATHLEEN PENDER
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate divorces usually work out better for shareholders than
corporate marriages, but few pay off like the breakup of Varian
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, in one of the more amazing transformations in
Silicon Valley history, the big old slug of a company split itself
into three little sexy ones.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the split, Varian was trading at $39. Today, shares
in the three companies combined total $146. That's a 274 percent
gain for investors who kept all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things took on a life of their own,'' says Tim Curro, a
New York hedge-fund manager, who bought Varian before the split.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1937, Varian was a Silicon Valley pioneer, but proved
better at inventing technologies than marketing them. ``The Peter
Principle started working very early at Varian,'' said Jim
McCamant, a longtime Bay Area stock analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Varian got into so many different businesses that no single
analyst could cover the company, so almost nobody did, and the
stock traded at a ``conglomerate discount.''
</P>
<P>
   After promising for years to break up the company, management
finally did on April 2, 1999. For each share of Varian Associates,
stockholders got one share in each of the spin-offs:
</P>
<P>
   Varian Medical Systems (VAR) kept the firm's hospital-equipment
business. Its stock went from an intial price of $18.31 to $44.50
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Varian Inc. (VARI), which makes high-end scientific instruments,
went from $9.19 a year ago to $41.75 yesterday. Like Varian
Medical, it remained headquartered in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Varian Semiconductor Equipment Associates (VSEA), which moved to
Gloucester, Mass., soared from $11.06 to $60.06.
</P>
<P>
   The chip-equipment business was voted ``most popular'' by Wall
Street. And Varian Inc. sells to &UR;  &LR; some sizzling markets including
biotech, oil and gas and semicoductors.
</P>
<P>
   But several investors who have owned all three say Varian
Medical is the most interesting, not just for investors, but also
for cancer patients and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Varian Medical is still the most undervalued of three
companies,'' says Geoff Barth of Investors Group, a Canadian
mutual-fund company that is the biggest holder of Varian Medical
and Varian Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Varian Medical is the leading maker of radiation oncology
equipment, which is used as an alternative to surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Varian and its biggest competitor, a division of Germany's
Siemens AG, recently introduced a new system of hardware and
software that seems far more effective at killing certain localized
tumors, with fewer side effects, than current radiation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The technology uses a massive piece of equipment called a linear
accelerator, which speeds up electrons through a tube to create a
pencil-thin beam of radiation that is targeted at the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   With older equipment, the beam can be shaped only into a
rectangle or square. Since most tumors are oddly shaped, the beam
also zaps healthy tissue. ``That restricted the dosage of radiation
to what normal tissue could tolerate, and not what the tumor
needed,'' says Steven Leibel, chairman of radiation oncology at
Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   With the new system, called intensity modulated radiation
technology, or IMRT, the beam can be shaped to fit the tumor, so
doctors can deliver more radiation to the tumor and less to
surrounding tissue.
</P>
<P>
   IMRT uses a piece of equipment called a multileaf collimator
that attaches to the lens of the linear accelerator. The MLC has as
many as 120 tungsten fingers that move in and out to change the
shape of the beam.
</P>
<P>
   The MLC is controlled by sophisticated software the doctor uses
to plan, execute and monitor the treatment. As the linear
accelerator rotates 360 degress around the patient, the fingers
keeping moving in and out at varying speeds to modulate the shape
and intensity to different parts of the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Patients still have to come in every working day for six weeks
for treatment, although Varian CEO Dick Levy says that in the
future, doctors may be able to give higher doses in fewer days.
</P>
<P>
   Although &UR;  &LR; IMRT has been used mainly for prostate cancer, it also
is being tested with tumors in the head and neck, lung, breast and
brain.
</P>
<P>
   At Memorial Sloan Kettering, 1,100 prostate cancer patients have
been treated with IMRT. Leibel said the normal radiation dosage for
prostate cases using conventional treatment is 64 to 70 Gray (units
of absorbed radiation). With IMRT, his hospital has moved the
standard dose to 81 Gray and may raise it again to 86. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By bombarding the tumor with higher doses, researchers at MSK
saw a 71 percent improvement in tumor control while reducing the
rate of complications, mainly rectal bleeding, from 10 percent to 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was chemotherapy and you got the results we did, it
would be hailed as the greatest discovery in oncology,'' says
Leibel.
</P>
<P>
   MSK is even advertising its IMRT equipment in newspapers because
people have read about it on the Internet and want to find it, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, Varian systems are in use at Stanford
University Medical Center, UCSF and the Palo Alto Medical Clinic,
and they're going in at Marin General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens systems are in use at UCSF-Mt. Zion and are going in at
Alta Bates in Berkeley, Mt. Diablo in Concord, the Tri-Valley
Clinic in Hayward, and John Muir Hospital in Walnut Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Foyles, marketing communications manager for Siemens
Oncology Care Systems in Concord, says there's not much difference
between Siemens and Varian machines, and neither company has a
patent on the core hardware. The main barriers to entry are their
huge market shares, which make it hard for newcomers to compete.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In conventional radiation equipment, Varian has about 70
percent of the U.S. market and Siemens has about 30 percent.
Worldwide, Varian has 50 percent and Siemens has 35 percent. Other
competitors include Elekta of Sweden and Mitsubishi, which operates
mainly in Asia and does not sell IMRT equipment.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Varian and Siemens each have about 25 IMRT systems in
operation, leaving plenty of room for expansion. But there are
several stumbling blocks:
</P>
<P>
   The first is cost: A top-of-the-line system sells for $2
million, although linear accelerators built since 1988 can be
upgraded for $500,000 to $1 million. ``These are big-ticket items''
and any talk about health-care cost controls could induce panic,
Curro said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's resistance to change. ``Doctors are conservative,''
Levy says, and many referring physicians have never heard of IMRT.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's training. Varian is having a hard time finding
people who can teach others to use the new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Varian's radiation oncology business accounts for 78 percent of
its revenues. But it has several other technologies in development:
</P>
<P>
   Brachytherapy. This involves feeding radioactive isotopes or
``seeds'' through a catheter into the tumor. It's invasive, but the
equipment cost is less than IMRT's, making it popular in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Digital X-rays. Varian is one of several companies working on
the medical-imaging equivalent of digital photography.
</P>
<P>
   Biosynergy. This involves using chemicals or drugs to enhance
the effect of radiation and/or desensitize healthy tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Restinosis. In about 40 percent of angioplasty cases, the artery
will clog up again. Varian is working with Cordis, a division of
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, to reduce that rate to 15 percent by using
radiation and stents, devices that prop open arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are good odds that one of these will pay off,'' Levy
says, ``but even if they don't, we see 12 to 14 percent top-line
growth and 18 to 21 percent bottom-line growth based just on our
present business.''
</P>
<P>
   Barth agrees. ``We think their cancer business alone justifies
the current stock price. But these others are home-run markets. If
they could gain first-mover status in one of them, that would be
huge, pure upside. If they were to fizzle out, I don't think the
downside is that great.''
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended September 1999, Varian Medical lost $24
million on revenues of $590 million. Excluding losses from
discontinued operations, earnings were $8.2 million (27 cents).
</P>
<P>
   In this year's first quarter, the company earned $5.2 million
(17 cents) on $141 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jay Sellick of C.L. King &AMP; Associates in New York
expects Varian to will  &LR; earn $1.55 per share this year and $1.85
next year, which means the stock is selling at 28 times this year's
expected earnings and 24 times next year's. That's higher than most
capital equipment companies but lower than medical-device
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The valuation ``clearly isn't as good as it was not too long
ago,'' Sellick says. ``But I would consider this a good one- to
two-year investment. Cancer isn't going away. And these folks have
a good reputation for innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution: Varian is a party to several environmental
lawsuits and an antitrust suit stemming from its pre-split days.
The company says it believes it has set aside sufficient reserves
for any liabilities ... but you never know. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at  &LR; kpender &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
