u k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN31-COX     03-30 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One of gardening's enduring myths: Trimming crape myrtles
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I've been thinking a lot lately about crape
myrtles. I'm writing this on a plane back to Houston after spending
nearly a week in Atlanta, where spring is in full bloom. Azalea
blossoms laden the limbs, the jasmine smells sweet, and the kudzu
is coming back to life. Two out of three ain't bad. Thank God kudzu
never made it across the Sabine River.
</P>
<P>
   All the crape myrtles have been neatly trimmed back, their ugly
spindly branches whacked away in preparation for summer's blooms,
so that what remains are thick branches and knobby outcroppings
from which the new branches will sprout. The crape myrtle is the
franchise flower of summer here in Deep East Texas, its blooms
lasting longer in the heat than anything save lantana, which grow
low to the ground and aren't nearly as impressive. A mature crape
myrtle tree in full bloom, pink or white, will bring a smile to
your face even on the worst of days.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that not all the crape myrtles in Atlanta have
been trimmed, but all were that I saw while spending my time at a
secluded conference center outside the city, in a planned community
called Peachtree City. I was trapped in an executive training
high-dollar prison camp from which there was no escaping. I spent
what little free time I had walking the grounds, trying to clear my
head of consultantese. The smell of dogwood blossoms and pine
needles rejuvenated me at key moments. First thing I noticed was
that the crape myrtles had all been pruned.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening columnist Jeff Abt has been on a lonely jihad against
pruning crape myrtles for years. Near as I can tell, at least from
observation, I am his only recent convert, though he has allies
among fellow horticulturists who already know better. He spoke
recently to a Rotary Club meeting and exhorted the nearly 200
middle-aged and older men, as well as a scattering of women, to
leave the crape myrtles alone. Pruning them has no effect
whatsoever on the quality, duration or size of their blossoms.
Leave crape myrtles alone and they grow into beautiful trees with
lovely blossoms, and he showed slides to prove his point. If you
want short crape myrtles, Jeff said, then buy a variety that
doesn't grow tall instead of whacking away at what are essentially
trees. Imagine if we went out and topped pine trees every year to
keep them to a certain height.
</P>
<P>
   I left Rotary and on my way back to the office spied a landscape
man working outside an office, flailing away on the crape myrtles,
a huge pile of limbs growing nearby. I slowed and watched him. The
pruner looked so determined, fulfilling his mission with the
certainty of a man who has done this task the same time each year
for many years: It's late February. Time to whack on the crape
myrtles. This is ingrained into our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff convinced me otherwise a few years back, the first time he
wrote a gardening column pleading with readers to not prune the
myrtles. By sad coincidence, I had spent the previous Sunday
hacking away at several huge crape myrtles growing off the back
deck of a house I had just bought. There were about eight of them,
and they were close to 20 feet tall. By the time I got through, I
had knocked them down a good five feet, had blisters on my fingers
from using the long-handled pruner, and then had to drag the limbs
out to the curb so the city would take them to the dump.
</P>
<P>
   I was feeling pretty darned manly _ job well done and all that _
until Jeff informed us in his column that pruning crape myrtles is
unnecessary, dumb and doltish. My words, not his.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never prune another crape myrtle, since I firmly believe in
the minimalist theory of lawn maintenance. But, judging from the
number of crape myrtle trees that look like multiple amputees now
that spring has arrived, Jeff's plea still falls on empty ears.
</P>
<P>
   I complimented Jeff on his talk to Rotary a few weeks ago, and
he mentioned in passing that he and some allies in this lonely
crusade were thinking about forming CRAMM: Citizens Rallying
Against Myrtle Mutilation. I don't think they're planning anything
more sinister than bumper stickers. As he explained it, this would
be the nonviolent arm of the anti-crape myrtle pruning movement. He
hinted darkly at a more militant faction, but I wasn't interested.
Shedding blood over crape myrtles is a bit out there.
</P>
<P>
   At my new house, I planted a dozen crape myrtles last fall,
spindly things that are now about four feet tall. It wasn't easy,
but I resisted the temptation to trim them back a bit as their
first spring approached, to maybe help them shoot out new branches
_ much in the way you trim rose bushes. But I looked temptation
square in the face and resisted for once, and I have been rewarded
for my efforts. All my crape myrtles have new branches coming out.
By summer, they should be delightful.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
