<SLUG> BC-BUS-TRAIN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bus driver didn't stop at crossing, feds say
 &HT;    By David Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The school bus driver in Tuesday's train-bus accident,
which killed three children and injured four, did not stop at the
unguarded rural railroad crossing, federal investigators said
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to the preliminary determination the bus driver
did not stop at the crossing prior to entering it,'' said Ken
Suydam, the National Transportation Safety Board investigator
leading the probe into the early morning wreck in Tennga, Ga., near
the Tennessee-Georgia line.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Rhonda Cloer, who was released Wednesday from Erlanger
Memorial Hospital after treatment for arm injuries and facial cuts,
has refused to be interviewed by investigators looking into the
worst train-bus crash involving Georgians since 1974. Cloer, whose
daughter was among those critically injured, referred questions to
her attorney, Suydam said.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-car CSX freight train, carrying automobiles from
Cincinnati to Tampa, Fla. _ slammed into the Murray County school
bus, tearing the passenger compartment off the chassis and dragging
it about 100 yards down the track.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer was conscious when rescue crews reached the crash site,
and according to witnesses, she said she had stopped before
entering the crossing and never saw the train.
</P>
<P>
   Suydam also said the audio portion of the videotape taken from
the bus indicated that ``several conversations were going on'' and
that the AM/FM radio was on. He said investigators could not
immediately say whether the noise was sufficient to prevent Cloer
from hearing the train whistle.
</P>
<P>
   He said Cloer was not able to see far enough down the track
because of the heavy tree growth bordering the rail bed.
</P>
<P>
   Laws in Tennessee and Georgia require a driver to put on the
bus' four-way flashing lights and come to a complete stop 15 to 50
feet before every grade crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Suydam said the engineer had sounded the train whistle at the
appropriate distance as he neared the crossing and sounded the
whistle constantly for 8 seconds before impact when the engineer
saw the bus on the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier statement, the engineer, whose name has not been
released, said he jammed the train into an emergency stop as soon
as he saw the 72-seat school bus, which was in the early part of
its route picking up children for Northwest Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the data recorder on the train indicated the
train was moving about 50 mph as it approached the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Three school buses cross the track each day at Liberty Church
Road.
</P>
<P>
   Students Kayla Silvers, 6, and Daniel Pack, 9, died Tuesday, the
day of the crash. Another student, Amber Pritchett, 9, died
Wednesday night at T.C. Thompson Children's Hospital. Three other
children remain hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Sherrill, 8, and the driver's daughter, Kayli Cloer, 5,
are in critical condition at Thompson, and relatives said Cloer has
been in a medically induced coma to control brain swelling. Jordan
Manis, 6, is in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany Gaddis, 8, was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services for Kayla and Daniel are to be held today at
Liberty Baptist Church, which is near the crossing. Services for
Amber are scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the crash site Thursday, investigators conducted tests for
five hours after a rain-delay.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB photographers rode the bus and engine through the crossing,
taking pictures at 50-yard intervals of what Cloer and the train's
conductor might have seen.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on whether Tennessee officials would
file criminal charges against Cloer.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Keeton, spokeswoman for the Tennessee Highway Patrol, said
Cloer, who had a commercial driver's license, had only one previous
violation on her driving record, a 1991 speeding ticket. The record
did not indicate whether that occurred while she was driving a bus,
Keeton said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the final NTSB report is months away, investigators
plan to provide a preliminary report Saturday that will detail
speeds, sight distances and other factors involved in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
