<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS &LR;      03-30 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS EXTENDS DEADLINE OF CUBAN BOY'S STAY IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ U.S. immigration officials extended until Tuesday the
deadline for Elian Gonzalez's stay in the United States, granting
the shipwreck survivor's attorneys another four days to fight the
boy's deportation to Cuba, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The extension was the second in as many days and came as
6-year-old Elian's father in Cuba was seeking permission to enter
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, speaking through his American attorney, said he
will enter the country once he gets the U.S. visa, and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service assures him that he will be
given custody of his son while in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The latest developments prompted presumed Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore and Republican candidate George W.
Bush to once again weigh in on the issue, with Vice President Gore
breaking ranks from the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials originally had threatened to revoke the
boy's parole Thursday unless they had written assurances from his
family that he would be surrendered to authorities once appeals are
exhausted to keep him in the United States. They later moved the
deadline to 9 a.m. Friday before agreeing Thursday to meet with the
family's attorneys again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have continued to conduct our discussions with the
government on this matter and because of scheduling difficulties we
have agreed to continue those discussions on Monday,'' Jose Garcia
Pedroza, one of six attorneys representing the family, said after
12 1/2 hours of negotiations over two days.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was placed into the custody of his great uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez, shortly after his rescue off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., by a pair of fishermen last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives and their lawyers have argued that Elian
should remain in the United States, a plea that has the outspoken
support of the city's large population of Cuban expatriates. But
the INS, citing U.S. immigration law, has decided that the boy
should be reunited with his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relatives in Miami do not speak for Elian,'' said the
father's lawyer, Gregory Craig. ``The lawyers in Miami do not speak
for Elian. The only person that has the legal and moral authority
to speak for Elian Gonzalez is his father.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling last week, U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
upheld a decision by INS Commissioner Doris Meissner to return
Elian to his father. Elian's family has appealed the ruling and a
federal appeals court in Atlanta has scheduled the case for May 11.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the father, Craig said he seeks visas for Elian's
stepmother and infant half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   Visa applications for travel from Cuba to the United States must
be submitted to the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana. The State
Department did not say how long the visa process will take but
added that it would expedite Craig's request.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling last week, U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
upheld a decision by INS Commissioner Doris Meissner to return
Elian to his father. Elian's family has appealed the ruling and a
federal appeals court in Atlanta has scheduled the case for May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who oversees INS, indicated
Thursday that she is willing to send U.S. marshals to retrieve
Elian if the Miami relatives refuse to work toward a prompt,
peaceful resolution of their dispute with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would be willing to enforce the law if peaceful
efforts fail, Reno responded, ``You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, however, did not question the relatives'
motives in fighting to keep Elian, saying that they ``love him
dearly and have cared for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a former Miami prosecutor who grew up in the city, also
made an emotional plea for calm to the city's Cuban expatriates who
have rallied in support of the family's attempt to block the
government's call that Elian be returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a community I love,'' Reno said. ``And when it's hurting,
it hurts me.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that Cuban exiles, who have fled Cuban President Fidel
Castro's regime, should have heightened respect for the U.S. rule
of law.
</P>
<P>
   On the street in front of the house in Miami's Little Havana
neighborhood where Elian has been staying with his great uncle,
dozens of demonstrators linked arms and formed two rows, according
to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, broke with the Clinton administration's view
that Elian should be summarily returned to his father under federal
immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said U.S. courts should first determine whether going back
to Cuba would be in the boy's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian Gonzalez's case is at heart a custody matter,'' Gore
said. ``It is a matter that should be decided by courts that have
the experience and expertise to resolve custody cases, with due
process and based on Elian's best interests,'' Gore said. ``It now
appears that our immigration laws may not be broad enough to allow
for such an approach in Elian's case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore endorsed pending congressional legislation that would make
Elian and his father legal immigrants, enabling them to litigate
the custody case in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he welcomed the vice president's break with the
administration and support for a custody hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he could convince the rest of the administration of the
wisdom of that approach,'' said Bush. ``I hope he'll use his
influence to encourage the president and the attorney general to
follow that approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the vice president now supports legal residency for
Elian Gonzalez,'' Bush said. ``I wish he could convince the rest of
the administration of the wisdom of that approach. The vice
president is an influential member of this administration. I hope
he'll use his influence to encourage the president and the attorney
general to follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Jan. 23 said he supported legislation in Congress to
make Gonzalez a citizen. But Bush also said citizenship would not
preclude the boy's return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be a wonderful gesture,'' Bush said on ABC's ``This
Week.'' ``I guess ... the boy could still go back to Cuba as a
citizen of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has consistently said Gonzalez should not be returned to
Cuba until his father had had a chance to spend time in the United
States ``to understand the greatness of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez has stated he would release the boy to his
father if he came to Miami to claim him. Though the great uncle
participated in Wednesday's negotiations, he did not attend
Thursday's eight-hour session. Instead, his daughter, Marisleysis,
21, joined the negotiations late Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Gutierrez, spokesman for the boy's Miami family, said
Marisleysis asked to attend the meeting, ``because (she) is the
most important person in this boy's life and she felt she needed to
be come.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother, Elizabeth Gonzalez, took the boy on an ill-fated
journey to the United States last November. Elian and two other
passengers were the only survivors of the boat trip. His mother and
10 others drowned in the journey. Before she died, she strapped
Elian to an inner tube on which he drifted for two days before
being discovered by two fisherman on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Steve Lash and Bennett Roth in Washington, and
R.G. Ratcliffe in Austin, Texas, contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
