<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONVICT-COMMENCEMENT3     03-30 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICT-COMMENCEMENT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slain cop's wife: Abu-Jamal's address `will haunt' Antioch
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOW SPRINGS, Ohio _ The widow of slain Philadelphia police
officer Daniel Faulkner told Antioch College's graduating seniors
Thursday that choosing as a commencement speaker the man convicted
of her husband's murder ``is akin to the people of Oklahoma City
having Timothy McVeigh address their graduating class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock and disgust felt by society at your decision will
haunt those who follow you at Antioch for years go come,'' Maureen
Faulkner wrote. ``Do not honor a convicted murderer by permitting
him to send you off with his banal message of `revolution' and
hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Antioch officials said Thursday they have no plans to negate the
wishes of Antioch's class of 2000, which invited radio journalist
and former Black Panther Mumia Abu-Jamal, a death-row inmate, to
speak via audiotape at its April 29 commencement.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner and fellow survivors of slain officers _ along with
active-duty and retired officers _ have deluged Antioch College
officials with more than 600 e-mails and letters protesting the
selection.
</P>
<P>
   But two college administrators said the college is not taking
sides in the international debate on Abu-Jamal's guilt or innocence
and the fairness of his trial in the 1981 slaying. Nor, they said,
is the college honoring Abu-Jamal by including his comments at
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   They said the school is respecting Abu-Jamal's free-speech
rights, as well as the wishes of its graduating seniors, who chose
Abu-Jamal and trans-gender author Leslie Feinberg over eight other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail and fax campaign represents ``five or six hundred
people trying very hard to keep one person's voice from being
heard,'' said Antioch College President Bob Devine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals on death row still have the right of free
speech,'' said Antioch Dean of Students Scott Warren, who chairs
the college's commencement committee.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said Wednesday that some correspondence amounted to
``hate mail'' clearly intended to ``intimidate and harass'' the
college. The college Thursday made available for inspection the
first 300 or so e-mails and letters it has received. A second,
similar batch is still being read and copied, college officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The letters and electronic messages virtually unanimously
criticized the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we believe in free speech, but not by a KILLER,'' wrote
Toni MacDonald, president of the northern California chapter of an
organization for survivors of police slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have someone who violated the essence of human rights by
the taking of another man's life _ especially a person in law
enforcement _ come to a place of education and deliver a
commencement speech is just not acceptable,'' wrote P.atricia Hunt,
widow of a slain California Highway Patrol officer.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement fraternal organizations and
victims-and-survivors' groups quickly e-mailed to members the word
of Antioch's selection of Abu-Jamal earlier this week and
encouraged members to express their opinion to the private college.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal's case is a lightning rod, having drawn international
attention from anti-death-penalty activists and others who believe
he was railroaded by a corrupt and racist justice system. Abu-Jamal
is black; the slain officer was white. Last month, Amnesty
International called for a new trial for Abu-Jamal, citing what the
organization called judicial bias, irregularities in the police
investigation and possible coercion of key witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter-writers consistently referred to Abu-Jamal as a
``cop-killer'' and noted that several appeals of his 1982
conviction have failed. Arnold Gordon, Philadelphia first district
attorney, said in a letter to Devine, ``From an evidentiary
standpoint, the case against Mumia Abu-Jamal was overwhelming, one
of the strongest that I have seen in 30 years as a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon wrote, ``Mr. Abu-Jamal has been portrayed by a small but
vocal group of supporters and some misguided celebrities as a
victim and a martyr, rather than the vicious, cold-blooded cop
killer that a jury found him to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some messages seemed ominous. One, from an unnamed author who
described himself as ``just a guy in Kevlar, a cop with family and
friends,'' used Devine's first name: ``When the alarm goes off,
Bob, aren't you going to wonder why they got to your neighbor's
place a little faster? Can you blame them?''
</P>
<P>
   Many letters suggested that the college would be better served
had Maureen Faulkner been invited to speak. In a phone interview
from her Southern California home Thursday, Faulkner made it clear
her voice will be heard on commencement day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to threaten, but I'm coming. I'm going to be
there, and I'm going to protest.... I'll have a picture of Danny in
my hand,'' said Faulkner, who did just that last year when students
at Evergreen State College in Olympia, Wash., invited Abu-Jamal to
speak via audiotape at commencement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last moment of my husband's life, he was looking up at
a barrel of a gun,'' Faulkner said. ``I don't want people to forget
that. I won't let people forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   One message of support came from the president of Evergreen
College, Jane Jervis, who endured similar protests last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having gone through the experience you are about to have _
namely, having Mumia Abu-Jamal as a speaker at graduation _ I want
to extend my condolences and whatever advice I or members of my
staff might offer,'' Jervis wrote to Devine.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Jervis wrote, ``our graduation ceremony was
extraordinary _ a real learning event, as graduations seldom are _
and I have never been more proud of Evergreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
