<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BING-MOTHERHOOD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE OF HELPING WOMEN HELP THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mg) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elisabeth Bing's hands are gnarled with arthritis,
and she needs help opening a display case that holds her collection
of delicate pre-Columbian and Native American fertility figurines.
</P>
<P>
   They are beautiful and shocking: A woman large of thigh and
buttocks, squatting as she gives birth. A mother with breasts
pendulous from nursing, one infant on her back and another in her
belly.
</P>
<P>
   The figurines are on display in the large carpeted studio on the
Upper West Side where Bing, at 85, continues to teach the natural
childbirth classes that were so revolutionary when she began her
crusade a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many pioneers, Bing, who fled Nazi Germany in 1933, has
gone from being a rebel to a relic, which is both the good news and
the bad. She knows that she led a movement that transformed the
obstetrical profession in the United States. And the measure of her
success is that young women now take it for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not being tied down anymore,'' Bing said. ``We're not
lying flat on our backs with our legs in the air, shaved like a
baby. You can give birth in any position you like. The father, or
anybody else, can be there. We fought for years on end for that.
And now it's commonplace. We've got it all.''
</P>
<P>
   But with all that has come a lack of regard for history. Bing
described a call from a young woman who was referred by a hospital
where the childbirth classes once scorned were now overbooked. She
was looking for an instructor. ``What are your qualifications?''
she asked Bing.
</P>
<P>
   She tells the story with a rueful laugh, seated in her
apartment, a few floors above her studio. There are books
everywhere, orchids and African violets on the sunny windowsills,
walls hung with beloved art, including reproductions by the German
artist Emil Nolde, who was ordered by the Nazis not to paint and
switched from oils to watercolor to avoid the telltale smell.
</P>
<P>
   Bing compares the ignorance of young women to that of the
post-war generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``World War II is part of my life,'' she said. ``But people see
it as so far away. That's how it works. It mostly doesn't bother
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Age has tamed her emotions, Bing said, although her eyes brim as
she describes her loneliness, after 16 years of widowhood. She
fears declining health and is grateful that her housekeeper calls
each morning to check on her. Her son, a professor of classics at
Emory University in Atlanta, is farther away than usual, on a
fellowship in Cambridge, England. He sends photos of her 5-year-old
granddaughter, who plays the cello _ as Bing does, even now with
her aching hands. But the coming weeks will be full of celebration.
She will be honored at a symposium organized by the New York
chapter of Lamaze International, an organization that Bing founded.
The chapter also intends to publish Bing's autobiography. And the
Schlesinger Library on the History of Women at Harvard University
has offered an archive for her papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is an inspiring tale that began in Berlin in 1914, when the
First World War was planting the seeds for the Second. By 1933, two
of her siblings, a dental surgeon and an architect, could not find
work because they were Jewish. Bing, for the same reason, was
thrown out of the university two days into her freshman year. With
the help of friends in London, her widowed mother arranged for the
family to flee.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Bing trained as a physical therapist. Her hospital
job involved the usual cases: broken bones, strokes, paralysis. But
each morning she went to the maternity ward, to provide exercise
for women who were not allowed out of bed for 10 days after
delivery. Around that time, a patient gave her a book by Grantly
Dick-Read, ``Childbirth Without Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed coined the term ``natural childbirth,'' and said that the
mind-body connection would ease labor. Bing longed to train with
him in the north of England. But bombs were falling and travel was
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she read about obstetrics, watched deliveries and was
horrified by what she saw. Soon Dick-Read's approach was refined by
Dr. Fernand Lamaze, a French physician who studied breathing
exercises for mothers in labor in Russia, where poverty and war had
made anesthesia a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bing settled in the United States, in 1949, she was
committed to finding doctors who would collaborate in these
techniques. In 1951 she made a niche at Mount Sinai Hospital, where
Dr. Alan Guttmacher, another pioneer in women's health, was
beginning a maternity service and welcomed her. Bing has been
teaching and lecturing since.
</P>
<P>
   But the fervor of the early days is gone; natural childbirth
classes are a routine part of the prenatal routine, not a
philosophical imperative. Bing favors six weekly classes, but
couples now want to cram the program into a few hours. And
virtually every woman who comes to her these days expects an
epidural, which blocks the sensory nerves below the waist.
</P>
<P>
   Fervent feminists once refused medication as a badge of honor.
Bing tries not to sound preachy, but she thinks the younger women
are cheating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an experience that never leaves you,'' Bing said of an
unmedicated birth. ``It needs absolute concentration; it takes up
your whole being. And you learn to use your body correctly in a
situation of stress. I'm not saying it's white or black. But these
girls are not trusting their bodies, that they can give birth by
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
