u s BC-TEN-ERICSSON31-COX     03-30 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ERICSSON31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seles takes two bites out the bagel at
 &HT;    Ericsson
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ If you were putting together a list of the
players least likely to get bageled _ tennis slang for losing a set
6-0 _ Monica Seles would be near the top.
</P>
<P>
   Since turning pro nearly 11 years ago, Seles has earned a
reputation for grunting out every single point, for fighting from
start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Bagels? She has served more of them than a Manhattan deli. But
no one had ever forced her to eat two in one sitting. Not when she
was a 14-year-old amateur playing in tour events. Not when she was
coming back after a 27-month layoff following her stabbing. Not
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the 534th match of her career, it happened.
</P>
<P>
   She lost 6-0, 6-0 to top-seed Martina Hingis in semifinals of
the Ericsson Open. The match lasted only 39 minutes. Seles, her
movement hampered by a sprained ankle, won only 22 points in the 12
games. And after she double faulted twice to end the match, hitting
a second serve into the middle of the net on the final shot, some
fans in the stadium court crowd booed and whistled.
</P>
<P>
   For Hingis, it meant a berth in the final. For Seles, it meant a
6-0, 6-1 loss to Steffi Graf in the fourth-round of the 1989
Wimbledon no longer was her worst defeat.
</P>
<P>
   She had been double-bageled. And booed.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, although understandably subdued after the defeat,
shrugged it off as just a really bad day. And as for the fans, she
seemed surprisingly forgiving. In a way, they were like her. They
came to the stadium expecting a better show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they really wanted a closer match than what happened
out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What did happen out there?
</P>
<P>
   Seles, 26, seemed to be back after a stress fracture in her
right foot kept her sidelined for five months. She won a title in
Oklahoma City earlier this month. And although she sprained her
ankle before the start of the Ericsson, she managed to win her
first four matches _ even handed out a few bagels along the way.
</P>
<P>
   She finished off a three-set match with Anna Kournikova in the
fourth round with a 6-0 set. And Wednesday, in the quarterfinals,
she needed only 22 minutes to win the first set of a 6-0, 6-3
victory against Amy Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, she predicted that playing Hingis would be
``different.'' If only she knew how different.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 minutes into the match, Seles had lost 13 of 14
points _ including 12 in a row. It didn't help that twice during
that stretch, line judges made no calls on shots by Hingis that
appeared to land past the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day. Even the calls went against her. The
first set was over in 18 minutes. Seles had won only eight points.
And Hingis was wondering if maybe she would default.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she kept playing,'' Hingis said. ``I was like, `Well,
nobody else would do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Seles was still ripping line-drive groundstrokes _ perhaps even
more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   When the match ended, Seles had hit nearly as many winners (14)
as Hingis (13). But she also had 35 unforced errors compared to
five for Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to go for more shots than I would have liked to,
because I knew I had a hard time moving sideways,'' Seles said.
``When I started doing that, I started making more errors. ...
Going against someone who is as consistent as Martina, it's not
going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final game, Hingis had three match points. When Seles hit
a forehand volley that landed near the baseline, Hingis playfully
argued with a line judge. Two double-faults later, it was over.
``I'm sure somebody else in her place wouldn't even step out on the
court,'' Hingis said. ``She just wasn't herself today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
