<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
767 FUEL TANK PARTS MAY BE SUSCEPTIBLE TO CRACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Parts in the center fuel tank structure of as many as
40 Boeing 767 widebody jets now in service may be susceptible to
cracking, The Post-Intelligencer has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect parts _ called stringers _ also may be in 16 other
767s now in various stages of production at the company's Everett,
Wash., plant, including every 767 parked on the flight line that
has not yet been delivered to a customer.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, which came to light only recently when an 8-inch
crack was found on a 767 in production, has been traced to a
shipment of improperly heat-treated parts from a Boeing supplier,
Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it does not consider this to be an immediate
safety-of-flight issue. The Federal Aviation Administration said it
is waiting for further analysis by Boeing before it determines what
should be done with planes that are already in service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplanes in service are safe to fly,'' Boeing spokeswoman
Yvonne Leach said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But this latest problem comes at an especially bad time for
Boeing. The company is scrambling to regain lost momentum after a
recent 40-day strike by its engineers and technical workers that
disrupted production lines and resulted in a number of missed
airplane deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   At this time, Boeing believes the suspect parts can be replaced
in those 767s without delaying any deliveries, Leach said. She
could not provide a breakdown of how many of the 16 767s in
production with possible suspect parts have rolled out the factory
door and are on the flight line.
</P>
<P>
   The next 767 is scheduled to be delivered Monday, she said, and
the suspect parts have already been replaced in that plane.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA was notified by Boeing of the problem last week and is
working with the company to better understand the nature and scope
of the problem, as well as to determine a corrective action plan
for planes in service, said FAA spokesman Mitch Barker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for Boeing to do an assessment of the size of
the problem, what effect this might have and what needs to be
done,'' Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second supplier problem that has complicated Boeing
production in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Production had to be slowed in early March on all but one of
Boeing's commercial models after the company discovered substandard
fasterners had been used on its assembly lines in Everett and in
Renton, Wash., since last December.
</P>
<P>
   The fasterners were made from an alloy that made them prone to
cracking.
</P>
<P>
   The latest problem involves the ``stringer'' that is used on the
767's center wing fuel tank. The 194-inch-long aluminium stringers
run the width of the center fuel tank. They carry the wing load and
serve as an attachment for the tank's metal skin.
</P>
<P>
   There are 28 stringers on top of the tank, and 28 on the
bottom.,
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 28 upper stringers are suspect, Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers have calculated that even if the two stringers failed,
the others can carry the wing load with adequate safety margins,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the issue said the fuel tank assembly for
the 767, including stringers, is shipped to Boeing from Northrop
Grumman, which is one of Boeing biggest subcontractors. Its Dallas
unit makes the 747's main fuselage and tail sections, as well as
major parts for most of Boeing's commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
   The raw material for the faulty stringers came from Alcoa, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Leach would not identify the raw-material supplier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation found that the material was heat-treated at
too high a temperature at the raw material supplier's facility,''
Leach said. Only one bad lot of parts came from that supplier,
Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   The wings of the 767 are joined to the fuselage on each side of
the center fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said a worker on the 767 production line first noticed a
8-inch long crack on one of the stringers and notified his
supervisor. That triggered an investigation that led back to the
supplier, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A P-I source gave a different account of how the crack was
discovered. This person said the crack was found during what's
known as a ``shakedown inspection.''
</P>
<P>
   This inspection is performed after machinists finish their work
on a particular area of a plane. The source said the crack resulted
from the additional drilling and riveting work that must be done
during wing installation. The crack occurred where a rivet went
through the skin into the stringer, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said Boeing does not yet know how many planes in service
are affected.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA's Barker said the number of in-service 767s with the
suspect parts is believed to be around 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good handle on the number of planes,'' he said.
Neither he nor Boeing would identify the airlines or operators of
the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the flying public should be concerned, Barker responded
that the FAA can issue an airworthiness directive requiring
operators to take immediate corrective action should it be
determined that the suspect stringers are a risk to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said Boeing has not yet come up with a corrective action
plan for those jets in service. But for those planes in production,
she said, the two suspect stringers are being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that it is time consuming to replace the two
suspect stringers on finished jets. Floor panels must be removed,
she said. But she did not know how many hours of work is involved.
</P>
<P>
   The source said any fix requires one worker to climb inside the
fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of work,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The source questioned why it took so long to discover that Alcoa
had delivered a lot of bad material to Northrop.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been building 767s at the rate of about 4 per month.
</P>
<P>
   That means the bad material could have been used in planes for
as long as a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes a year to find this problem, it indicates to me
that Boeing's quality control process is suspect,'' the source
said. ``Why should it take so long to find this.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the center fuel tank is only about a foot below
where passengers sit in the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Leach did not know when the lot of bad material was delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the FAA launched a special audit of Boeing's
quality control and manufacturing processes to determine what the
agency said was the ``root cause'' of a series of
production-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   Among those were improperly torqued tail bolts, improperly
cleaned fuel tanks and the use of an adhesive that did not meet
federal fire standards for aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   That audit was recently completed but the FAA has not yet
released the findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
