<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stankowski putts up 66
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leave it to the BellSouth Classic to revive Paul
Stankowski's game. Lost for much of the last two PGA Tour seasons,
the 1996 BellSouth champion fell back into his Atlanta area comfort
zone Thursday, taking the overnight lead at the TPC at Sugarloaf
with a 6-under-par 66.
</P>
<P>
   Stankowski squeezed more out of his round than his ball-striking
might have allowed, but after finishing 113th on the money list
last year he'll take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to steal from Tiger (Woods), but it was definitely not my
`A' game,'' he said. ``It was more like a `D' game. But it was my
`A' putting game, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite morning rain and lightning that caused a 1 hour,
55-minute delay, forcing 39 players to finish their first round
today at 7 a.m., scoring conditions became ideal during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One stroke behind Stankowski with 5-under-par 67s were Phil
Mickelson, Kenny Perry, Blaine McAllister, Frenchman Jean Van de
Velde, former U.S. Open champion Steve Jones and Jay Don Blake.
Eric Booker is at 5-under with three holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9-ranked Nick Price led a group of 11 players at 68 that
included tour rookie Gary Nicklaus and former Masters champion
Larry Mize of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is in such unbelievable condition, you can't
criticize anything,'' said Price.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval is already seven shots off the
pace, shooting a 1-over 73 that included four bogeys and three
birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Stankowski, famous for a '96 BellSouth win that pushed him into
the Masters as the tournament's final entry, birdied three of his
first four holes Thursday _ 10, 12 and 13. On the second nine, he
made birdies at 1, 2 and 6 without making a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde only entered the BellSouth because he missed the
cut at The Players Championship and didn't want to wait a week
before his first Masters appearance and become unduly restless. ``I
thought if I could manage to keep the ball in play and hit the
right section of the green, you might have a chance to roll a
couple of putts in,'' said Van de Velde. ``That is pretty much what
I did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was completely thrilled with the course. After
driving into the right fairway bunker at the fifth hole, Perry hit
a 9-iron that landed about 8 feet in front of the hole, spun back
to the front of the green and stopped. As he headed to the green,
the ball began rolling again, down into the hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Perry: ``I've never seen the ball come to rest and stop and five
minutes later roll off into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
