<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' SPIRIT IS NOT ENOUGH AGAINST BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was David against Goliath, wily veterans against willing but
inexperienced kids, a contender against a rebuilder.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the team that was expected to win _ the St. Louis
Blues _ did, but the Bruins put up a gallant fight in a 3-2
decision Thursday night at the FleetCenter. Bruins goaltender John
Grahame was sensational and kept his club in it through a very
hairy second period.
</P>
<P>
   Boston isn't mathematically eliminated from the playoffs but
with only five games remaining, it could happen as soon as Saturday
against the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a few reasons to fear the Blues. They had
lost only one of their previous 17 road games and had the best
record away from home in the league (26-9-4). They also had been
beaten Wednesday by Toronto, the first time the Blues were defeated
by a Canadian-based club this season. St. Louis came in with the
most victories (48) and points (106) in the NHL and are considered
a legitimate contender for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in the Blues' fine season has been the play of Roman
Turek, who went into the game with a 1.92 goals-against average,
.914 save percentage, and 40-14-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it was the Bruins who scored first, just 6:47 into
the game on Joe Thornton's 22d goal. Thornton, who before the game
was presented the Seventh Player Award, collected the puck from
Mikko Eloranta off the boards and backhanded a shot past Turek.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jochen Hecht tied it less than five minutes later with
his first of two goals. Former Boston College star Marty Reasoner
centered a pass that Thornton tried to intercept. The pass found
its mark, however, and Hecht backhanded a shot past Grahame at
11:16.
</P>
<P>
   Grahame often came up huge, once at 17:54 when he robbed Hecht
with his glove after Ladislav Nagy fed a pass across the crease
that Hecht tried to bang in at the right post.
</P>
<P>
   Grahame was even more impressive in the second period, during
which the Bruins were outshot, 18-7, including 10-1 at the 8:25
mark.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:16, defenseman Chris Pronger, considered a leading
candidate for the Hart Trophy as the league's MVP, had two bids.
One Grahame stopped, the other hit the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, as the Blues continued to swarm, Pronger
tested Grahame with a shot from the left point and then former
Boston University standout Scott Young had a chance at 5:36.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht broke through again on the power play at 14:34 for his
12th goal of the year. Right wing Stephane Richer teed up a slapper
that struck Grahame's glove, with the puck dropping to his skates.
With Grahame having lost sight of the puck, Don Sweeney tried to
help out by clearing it but wasn't able to and Hecht rapped it past
Grahame for the 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht's second goal was followed by some penalty trouble for the
Bruins but they survived.
</P>
<P>
   Young, however, boosted the Blues' advantage to two goals at
4:37 of the third with his 21st of the year. Boston pulled to
within 3-2 when Sergei Samsonov took a cross-ice pass from Eric
Nickulas, skated down the right circle and lifted a shot over Turek
for his 19th goal of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
