<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-AGENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT SAYS   HE'LL COMPLY   WITH LAWS   ON LICENSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Tenn., N.C., Ohio, Mich., Ind., N.J.)  (Formerly skedded as BKC-NCAA-DEMPSEY) 
 (DW) 
 By JOE DRAPE   and JUDY BATTISTA c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lawyer for Andy Miller, the professional sports agent, said
Thursday that he had contacted law enforcement authorities in
Florida and Tennessee to assure them that Miller intended to comply
with state laws governing agents.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Paul Robbins, said he had also conveyed the same
message to officials at the University of Florida and the
University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The calls came in response to an article in The New York Times
Thursday that said Miller appeared to have broken laws in both
states by repeatedly contacting prominent college basketball
players without registering as an agent in those states or alerting
the athletes' universities about the conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advised them that we have nothing but respect for the laws
in those states and we are taking steps to comply with their
licensing requirements,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Florida basketball team left for Indianapolis and the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament's Final Four
Thursday, the athletic department turned over to the university's
police department information about Andy Miller's repeated phone
calls to the Gator star Mike Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miller estimated that the agent had telephoned him about 45
times since September, and that the two spoke at least 20 times, a
university official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and Tennessee have strict laws regulating sports agents;
each requires agents to register with the state and to notify a
university when contacting an athlete. Violating these provisions
in Florida can be considered a felony. In Tennessee, it is a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miller admitted having met at least once with Andy Miller,
at a basketball game at Rutgers last December, a University of
Florida official said. He also said the agent had offered him
tickets to a professional basketball game the next night in
Orlando, Fla. Mike Miller told school officials that he declined
the offer, sparing himself a violation of NCAA rules that bar
players from receiving extra benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on a meeting with Mike Miller and our compliance staff
yesterday, we have determined no eligibility issues exist for Mike
Miller,'' Florida's athletic director, Jeremy Foley, said in a
statement. ``Because of the information reported in The New York
Times that a sports agent may have violated Florida law by
improperly contacting Mike, we have turned over information to the
police investigative authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agents routinely contact top college football and
basketball players in an effort to represent them when they turn
pro, and Miller was aggressive in his pursuit of top prospects.
Telephone records and diary entries reviewed by The Times show that
he tried to reach at least 24 players from at least 17 teams,
including Cincinnati, North Carolina and Michigan State. He placed
many telephone calls to Tony Harris of the University of Tennessee,
to Shaheen Holloway of Seton Hall and to A.J. Guyton of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Florida coaching staff and administration
have done a good job of educating us about NCAA rules,'' Mike
Miller said in a statement Thursday. ``I have not violated any NCAA
rules and my total focus is on getting ready to play North Carolina
in the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Joe Sharkey, a spokesman for the University of
Florida police department, an investigator was assigned to the case
Thursday and the police hope to determine if a crime was committed
by next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sole responsibility will be to look for any criminal
activity that this person may have done by contacting Mike Miller
or other athletes,'' Sharkey said.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Tennessee, where Harris received repeated
calls from Andy Miller, Malcolm McInnis, the school's associate
athletic director, said officials hoped to talk to three other
athletes whose names appeared in Miller's diary, although with less
frequency than Harris'.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation like this, the prudent thing to do
is check with the other athletes who might have been other targets
to see if there has been an attempt to contact them,'' McInnis
said. ``Obviously, we'd report to the state if we are aware of
somebody who violated the law.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
