r s BC-BKC-CAROLINA-FORTE-TE     03-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CAROLINA-FORTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING DUES: TAR HEELS' FORTE DOES ROOKIE STUFF AND STAR STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ As North Carolina's leading scorer, Joseph Forte
has helped carry the Tar Heels to their 15th Final Four. And that's
not the only burden the freshman has shouldered.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina program has certain traditions. Team statistics are
listed by alphabetical order, not by leading scorers. Seniors, even
walk-ons, get their picture on the cover of the media guide. And
freshmen, no matter how talented or precocious, are put in their
place. They're last in line for water breaks, last in the buffet
line and first when it comes to carrying bags.
</P>
<P>
   Before each season, North Carolina upperclassmen vote and assign
jobs to the rookies. Forte's seasonlong assignment, by unanimous
vote, was to carry the team's Green Bag. It's the trainer's bag,
the team's heaviest equipment bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bag is very heavy,'' said the 6-foot-4, 185-pound Forte.
``At times I've got my Walkman on and I'm walking out of the locker
room and the manager taps me on the shoulder and says, `Come back
and get the bag.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know about the pecking order. All the other the
little things, it's just that, humiliating. You can't knock it. It
makes you a better person. The other players saw I was confident,
and they didn't want me to be overconfident. What better way to do
that than to have me carry that bag and remind me of my place.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Tar Heels' Final Four semifinal game with Florida
on Saturday, Forte's place is at the top of the school's freshman
scoring list.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Not Phil Ford, not James Worthy, not Michael
Jordan, not Vince Carter. Forte scored 585 points, breaking Sam
Perkins' record of 550 points. He averaged 16.7 points per game to
become the first North Carolina freshman to lead the team in
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Joseph was a very good prospect,'' North Carolina
coach Bill Guthridge said. ``But I didn't know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge said that Forte has provided an ``ingredient'' the Tar
Heels needed, but in his succinct manner, he didn't elaborate. Tar
Heels senior point guard Ed Cota did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting,'' he said. ``Being able to knock down an outside
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A big-time player who makes big-time plays for us,'' North
Carolina sophomore forward Kris Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest came in the South Regional semifinal against
Tennessee. The Tar Heels trailed 64-57 with less than five minutes
to play. Faced with momentum-changing possession, Forte set a
screen near the top of the key for Cota, then stepped back and took
a flip pass from Cota. Forte's 3-pointer started a 13-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in my ear the whole game,'' Cota said. ``He told me
wasn't going to miss. All game, it was, `Ed, don't forget me. Find
me, find me.' He reminds me of myself. He wants the ball in
crunch-time situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte said his goal as a freshman was to start and win a
national championship. He didn't expect to lead the team in
scoring, but he has not been blinded by the bright lights that
focus on Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy transition,'' said the former star at
Hyattsville (Md.) DeMatha High School. ``At DeMatha we get a lot of
attention, a lot of media attention. It was easy for me to step in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly how North Carolina freshmen are supposed to
act. Sure, the school gets more than its share of high school
All-Americans. But the Tar Heel way is to be humble before you
become a star. From the first day of practice, Forte told his
teammates how good he was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the court, you might think he's a little cocky, but he's
not cocky at all, he's just got a lot of confidence,'' Cota said.
``I like being around him, because I love a person who has
confidence in himself. He might boast a little about the things he
does well. We don't pay him no mind, we just pat him on the butt
and tell him to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not like that,'' the soft-spoken Forte responded.
``I'm a good guy off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte opened the season being named MVP of the Maui Classic in
Hawaii, then was named most outstanding player of the South
Regional in Austin. After Forte scored 28 points in the South
Regional final to lead the Tar Heels past Tulsa, Guthridge was
asked if Forte would be relieved of his bag-carrying duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' he said, straight-faced. ``We might put some more
bricks in the green bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte, it would appear, can carry the load. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
