A2958 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-FIDELITY-REVIEW-     03-30 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FIDELITY-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINYL ANSWER: CUSACK HELPS `HIGH FIDELITY' FIND THE RIGHT GROOVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' begins with the end of a romance. The breakup
is not pretty to see, even if it's funny.
</P>
<P>
   As Laura, his live-in lover, walks out his door, Rob Gordon
(John Cusack) hurls self-pitying abuse at her.
</P>
<P>
   Then he informs us, in the first of his ongoing conversations
with the audience, that he may look wounded by Laura leaving, but
he's been through much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't even make the top five of my most miserable
breakups,'' Rob says. Already he sounds like a man trying to
convince himself more than his audience.
</P>
<P>
   And so Rob launches into a recap of those special girls and
women who did make his top list, starting with a classmate in
elementary school. The diverse list (two of the women played by
Catherine Zeta-Jones and Lili Taylor) includes women who broke up
with him, women he broke up with and regretted leaving, women he
dated on the rebound and women who dated him on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The further Rob gets into his hilariously pathetic
recollections, the more we, and finally he, notice the degree he
has played in his own self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity,'' directed by Stephen Frears (``Dangerous
Liaisons,'' ``The Grifters'') is a near masterpiece of comic angst.
It's an exceptionally funny, insightful romantic comedy _ but with
sting. The pain of self-recognition in the laughs makes them more
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the Nick Hornby novel about emotionally
adolescent Rob, the owner of a rundown used-record shop. Rob is
pushed to the point where he must finally embrace adulthood _ dare
we call it commitment? _ or be left behind forever.
</P>
<P>
   In its adaptation to the screen by Cusack and others, it has
been relocated from London to Chicago. (Hornby has praised the
movie for being faithful to his book's essentials.)
</P>
<P>
   Like many adolescent adults, Rob runs on obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters is what you like, not what you are like.''
</P>
<P>
   He has three likes: himself, women and music. Not much else
matters, although he has convinced himself he has depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read books like `Love in the Time of Cholera.' And I
think I've understood them,'' he says. ``They're about girls,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   For reality, he has substituted music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I listen to pop music because I was miserable? Or was I
miserable because I listened to pop music?'' Rob asks as though
there really might be a definitive answer.
</P>
<P>
   His record shop _ that's right, mostly vinyl _ specializes in
the esoteric, the cultish and arcane, as much to keep away
mainstream buyers as to attract off-beat collectors. Its
out-of-the-way location, grungy look and elitist clerks keep away
all but the music fanatics whose lives have focused down to
hoarding some narrow gully of music minutiae.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd feel guilty taking their money if I wasn't, well, one of
them,'' Rob admits.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has frequented such record shops (or used bookstores)
will fully believe Rob's two unlikely assistants, an endearingly
timid geek, played by Todd Luiso, and a verbally aggressively music
snob, Barry, played by Jack Black.
</P>
<P>
   Black, a master of comedic assault, steals most of his scenes,
and Cusack wisely stands back and lets him. When a middle-aged
businessman makes the error of wandering into the shop wanting to
buy his daughter some music Barry considers square, Barry coldly
asks if the girl is in a coma. He then orders the man out of the
shop.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Lisa Bonet and Natasha Gregson Wagner as more
of Rob's flirtations, Joan Cusack as Laura's best friend (she has a
really great small scene calling Rob names that ultimately provides
a catharsis to his self-realization) and Tim Robbins (paying back
Cusack's small role last year in Robbins' ``Cradle Will Rock'') as
guru Ian, Laura's post-Rob love interest.
</P>
<P>
   Laura is played by Iben Hjejle, and she is one of the film's few
weak links, because we can never quite figure out why Rob is so
shaken and taken by her. The script doesn't really give Hjejle
enough to work with, and she is not compelling enough to convince
us on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Frears is skilled at pinpointing the emotional frailties and
moral weaknesses of characters yet finding a humanity that makes us
care about them, even pull for them, while they mess up again and
again. He can make even the most conversation-bound scene exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by Cusack and ``The Grifters'' writing team of D.V.
DeVincentis and Steve Pink, with an additional credit to Scott
Rosenberg, who wrote an early draft, takes liberally from Hornby's
book. It's constantly scathing and comically cynical without ever
turning really ugly or bitter.
</P>
<P>
   It's Cusack who makes this film, however. He specializes in
smart but self-destructive characters we care about, and this is a
richly cutting comic version of them. Without Cusack's deft touch,
his perfect air of cynicism in which we can read an alternate human
side without having it made overt, this character would be just a
jerk or a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also benefits from a great soundtrack with music from
Bob Dylan to the Thirteenth Floor Elevators to Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   If the film has a problem, it is in taking too long to have Rob
finally grasp the essentials of what he needs to do to grow up.
That, in turn, makes the resolution seem abrupt and too little
developed. But even there, the writers have given a little shading
that reflects that in life you can never be sure of movie-perfect
endings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
``High Fidelity'' &QL; 
Starring: John Cusack, Iben Hjejle, Joan Cusack, Jack Black &QL; 
Rating: R for language and some sexuality &QL; 
Running time: 107 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B plus &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
