<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIXTH SENSE' REVEALS ITS SECRETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE SIXTH SENSE'
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   As we neared the end of a century (no, not a millennium _ not
yet), we craved more answers, more meaning, even more spirituality
in our entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a little horror film called ``The Sixth Sense'' made an
astonishing $285 million at America's box offices and racked up six
Oscar nominations.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying it's an undeserving film, just a lucky one _
and a historic case. ``The Sixth Sense'' joins ``The Exorcist'' as
the only horror movies ever nominated for Oscar's best-picture
honors.
</P>
<P>
   Almost like ``The Crying Game,'' ``The Sixth Sense'' hinges on A
Big Secret, which can't be divulged here.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that repeat viewings on video can show how
director-writer M. Night Shyamalan pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   He tells a tale of a prominent child psychologist (Bruce Willis)
encountering a boy (Haley Joel Osment) who sees and hears dead
people _ much like a former patient of Willis' who killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to redeem himself, the psychologist takes the boy as a
patient, learning painful details of his hideous visions.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``An American Werewolf in London,'' spirits appear to the
boy as the people were when they died, and since many died
violently, the visions are grisly. Seeing them is a ``gift'' he'd
rather give back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the obsessed psychologist seems to be drifting away
from his wife (Olivia Williams), drawn from home and normalcy into
the boy's bizarre world.
</P>
<P>
   Like the boy, you may be haunted by images from this film. Yet
``The Sixth Sense'' is less horrific than it is an absorbing drama,
and the performances are superb.
</P>
<P>
   Also credit Shyamalan, who gives his film new dimensions through
the cleverness of its ending, and who, like Stephen King, knows his
way around a good scary yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CRAZY IN ALABAMA'
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Antonio Banderas adores his wife, actress Melanie
Griffith. In his first directorial outing, he showcases and
photographs her lovingly, and he ensures that almost every male in
the story also worships her.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith's character is a poor woman's Thelma or Louise who, in
1965 Alabama, poisons her abusive husband, cuts off his head, puts
it in a box and heads to Hollywood with naive dreams of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   This means abandoning her seven kids to their grandmom and
stealing a car along the way. But a gal's gotta do what a gal's
gotta do, even if her hubby keeps speaking to her from his box in
the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtaposed with this odd lark of a road trip is a story back
home, as her young nephew (Lucas Black) is embroiled in a sad yet
cliched racial drama, taking the side of blacks against the town's
monstrous sheriff (rock singer Meat Loaf, now adding his original
last name of Aday).
</P>
<P>
   David Morse, Robert Wagner, Elizabeth Perkins and Paul Mazursky
are good in supporting roles, but it's Rod Steiger who steals the
show as an ornery judge.
</P>
<P>
   Though the racial drama works well, Griffith's saga does not,
starting with her allegedly forgivable crime.
</P>
<P>
   For a woman chronically abused for years, she seems happy if not
carefree, and everything comes too easily to her, from not getting
jailed to winning $32,000 in Vegas to quickly landing a role on
``Bewitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, almost every man becomes her instant guardian
angel, totally devoted to her well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its flaws, the film has many nice visual touches,
thanks to Banderas' eye. If only he were not so overcome by his
private life's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Review: C
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.95
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A TIME TO BOND &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Is Not Enough'' won't be enough for James Bond fans
May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will the latest Bond film arrive on tape and DVD that
day, but a second wave of vintage Bond movies also will make their
DVD debuts and return on VHS.
</P>
<P>
   Getting their first discs will be Sean Connery's Bond bow (``Dr.
No''), three more from Roger Moore (``Moonraker,'' ``The Man With
the Golden Gun'' and ``The Spy Who Loved Me'') and George Lazenby's
lone outing (``On Her Majesty's Secret Service'').
</P>
<P>
   All will cost a suggested $34.98 on DVD and $14.95 on tape.
Boxed sets will be $149.98 for DVD and $62.98 for VHS.
</P>
<P>
   The discs will include new documentaries, audio commentaries and
other extras.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Is Not Enough'' also will be $34.98 on DVD but will
cost an extra $5 on tape _ still low, considering this will be the
first Bond film to hit VHS at a sell-through price.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the maverick productions of ``Never Say Never
Again'' and ``Casino Royale,'' the only Bond films waiting for DVD
releases are ``From Russia With Love,'' ``You Only Live Twice,''
``Diamonds Are Forever,'' ``Octopussy,'' ``A View to a Kill'' and
``The Living Daylights.'' Look for the third and final Bond wave by
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
