<HEADLINE>
ADAM PETTY HOPES FOR CUP RACE WHILE GREAT-GRANDDAD IS ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Adam Petty says he always has thought of
great-grandfather Lee Petty, patriarch of the family's NASCAR
legacy, as the ``healthiest man around.''
</P>
<P>
   But the elder Petty, 86, has been hospitalized for treatment of
a blood aneurysm since mid-February. Great grandpa's failing health
will be another motivating factor for Adam at Texas Motor Speedway
on Friday, when he attempts to qualify for his first Winston Cup
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty serious; I'm not going to lie,'' Kyle Petty said
of his grandfather, who is hospitalized in Greensboro, N.C. ``It
could go either way. We've tried to stay away from as much of that
as we could because this is a real positive weekend for Adam. We're
trying to keep Adam shielded from this stuff as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 19-year-old Adam admittedly never has been ``real
close'' to Lee Petty, he naturally remains concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an old man, and he's been through a lot,'' Adam Petty
said Thursday. ``I always thought he was the healthiest man around
because he was always down there giving us grief at the race shop.
But he's gotten real, real weak on us. The way I look at it,
there's four generations of us still alive. He's run a Winston Cup
race, dad's run a Winston Cup race, grandpa's run a Winston Cup
race. Be neat if he could be alive when I did my first Winston Cup
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping and praying that he's going to be all right. And
we'll go see him next week in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty already is the first fourth-generation athlete in any
professional sport. If Adam does qualify for Sunday's DirecTV 500,
he and father Kyle will be able to tell Lee Petty about their first
race against one another. Lee and son Richard Petty competed
against each other in the 1959 Daytona 500, a race Lee won,
inaugurating the 2.5-mile Daytona International Speedway as
NASCAR's showcase facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something very special in our family, something that I've
grown up seeing my father and my grandfather do ever since I can
remember,'' Adam Petty said. ``Any kid wants to be just like their
father. It's something that I've always wanted to do, and I really
can't believe it's happening when I'm 19 ... trying to make my
first Winston Cup race. But if we do succeed and do make the race,
it will be very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty will need to post one of the top 36 speeds in his No.
45 Sprint Chevrolet Monte Carlo to qualify. Kyle Petty said
Sprint's promotional effort here has been considerable, adding
pressure to make the show from a business standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really break it down, it's more personal for us,'' said
Kyle Petty, the son of Richard Petty. ``Obviously, my grandfather
started this thing 50 years ago. When we look at it and say that
Adam has chosen to follow in the footsteps of what his grandfather
and his great grandfather and what I did ... that is big. And for
me personally, it's huge. Racing against my father, I always wanted
to beat him. When Adam makes this race and we go out there to race,
I hope he laps me 20 times in the first 15 laps. I'm pulling for
him. But for us as a company, Petty Enterprises, and for us
personally, this is a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Petty qualifies as a NASCAR pioneer, having competed in the
sanctioning body's inaugural season in 1949. His 55 career
victories are seventh on the all-time list, five more than compiled
by Ned Jarrett, Junior Johnson and Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's Rookie of the Year in 1959, Richard Petty retired in
1992 after winning a record 200 races and seven series
championships _ and forging a legacy as ``The King.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty has added eight Cup victories to the family total
since his first series start in August 1979 _ when he was two
months past his 19th birthday. Kyle Petty has a ready answer for
those who question whether Adam, who is in his second season of
competing in NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series, is ready to step
up to Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we do,'' Kyle Petty said. ``I'm going to use the
same line my father used ... `We have Winston Cup cars. We're in
Winston Cup racing. This is what we do. This is all we've ever
done.' So the quicker we get Adam into Winston Cup racing, the
quicker we may not have to have a Busch team or a truck team and we
can concentrate on Winston Cup racing. If Adam had not gone into
racing, we'd still have race cars and the John Andrettis and Steve
Grissoms driving for us for years to come. There doesn't
necessarily have to be a Petty driving a race car for Petty
Enterprises to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kyle said his son definitely is more focused on racing as a
career than he was coming out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I preface this by saying I'm a lot prejudiced,'' Kyle said,
``but I think he's got an incredible amount of talent at the age he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty, who qualified 13th Thursday for Saturday's
Albertson's 300 BGN race, said he selected TMS for the first of
five Cup races this year after consulting with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really the first place last year I qualified good in
the Busch car (third). Didn't race good, but qualified OK,'' Adam
Petty said. He returned with King Richard last fall to drive in a
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series event, racking up laps of experience
in a vehicle similar to a Cup car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of laps here, and I was pretty comfortable,'' said
Adam Petty, who tested his new Cup car here alongside two-time
series champion Terry Labonte on March 20-21. ``We didn't do
anything but make mock qualifying runs. We ran pretty much the same
Terry did, maybe a little bit better. Any time Terry comes to
Texas, he's on his game. So that's a pretty good gauge.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam said he is anxious to qualify so he can begin earning
respect in the Cup garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people that doubt this decision to go Winston
Cup racing right now,'' Adam Petty said. ``I'm not going to be a
star (Sunday). I know that I have no chance to win. What you do
realize is you have the opportunity. And I think if I can go out
and show Jeff Burton and Mark Martin and people like Dale Earnhardt
that I have the ability to do it, I can gain their respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, my dad's been the biggest help to me in my career.
I've got to prove that I'm not going to ride on Richard Petty's
coattails the rest of my racing career. I've got to make a name for
myself. That's what I'm trying to do.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
