<SLUG> BC-HULL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL'S ROLE AT CONVENTION UNERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a normal year, there would be little doubt that Republican
Gov. Jane Hull would lead the state's delegation to the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia, a ceremonial but coveted job
traditionally reserved for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the ordinarily innocuous matter has more than a
few politicos biting their nails. Hull badly wants to fulfill her
traditional role, but Sen. John McCain, who controls the delegates
and feuded with Hull during his bid for the White House, is hiding
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Hull is maneuvering to lead the delegation.
But McCain also could head the group himself or back someone other
than Hull, a prominent supporter of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the GOP nomination sewed up, but after McCain won
Arizona's Feb. 22 primary, he technically owns all 30 of the state'
national delegates and has shown no interest in relinquishing them
to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very definitely I would want to be the chairman,'' Hull told
``The Arizona Republic'' this week. ``If there is a strong feeling
about someone else nominating John _ you know me, I would probably
defer to them. (But) my role, obviously, the standard role of the
governor, is to be chairman of the delegation. My feeling is that's
the way we proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always have problems. Are there a lot of people out
there that hold it against me that I chaired the Bush campaign? I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for McCain had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, however, McCain announced that he has given
the Texas governor six of the delegates he won in Michigan,
allowing Gov. John Engler, a top Bush supporter, to attend the
convention as a Bush delegate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's reluctance to relinquish delegates has raised concerns
that many party activists, who tend to be Bush supporters, will be
pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and her aides are making it clear that there will be no
such contretemps in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, the 30 delegates here are committed
to John McCain unless he releases us,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Her chief of staff was unambiguous about the need to put a
tourniquet on the flow of bad blood between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not meant to be a confrontational thing. Period,''
Rick Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Arizona delegation must be elected by
delegates to the state Republican Convention on May 13, and both
McCain and Hull are eligible to run. In 1992, for instance, Gov.
Fife Symington led the delegation, although he was forced to sit it
out at the last minute by a foot injury. In 1996, he again was
expected to lead the group but stepped aside after he was indicted
on charges of bank fraud.
</P>
<P>
   For some McCain loyalists, the image of a delegation led by Hull
is, well, uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awkward,'' said Chuck Coughlin, a McCain supporter and
local lobbyist. ``She supported Governor Bush over John.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin suggested that it is Hull, rather than McCain, who
should compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody is slightly graceful about this, I'm sure there
is an amicable solution that can be worked out,'' Coughlin said.
``I guess we'll see how graceful the governor is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other scenarios that have been discussed by McCain supporters
include the possibility of state Republican Party Chairman Mike
Minnaugh announcing the McCain votes, or having more than one
person lead the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. Jon Kyl said that, ultimately, the matter of who
will lead the Arizona delegation will be decided by party activists
who are elected at the precinct level to go to the state GOP
convention in May. But, he added elliptically, the delegates likely
will be swayed by McCain's victory in the Arizona primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will certainly be informed by the fact that John McCain
won the Arizona primary, and I would think they would be somewhat
influenced by his desires,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull shows few signs of relenting. In fact, she has been
assiduously cultivating allies at the precinct level in preparation
for the state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Dunton, a former Steve Forbes supporter who is running for
convention delegate, said he expects both McCain and Hull to push
to lead the delegation. Ultimately, however, it should be the
governor's prerogative to lead the group regardless of McCain's
Arizona victory, Dunton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a (national) primary winner. She rode with the
winner,'' Dunton said. ``I would hope that we would unify and win
the election. That is the prime thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
