<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-ICAHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICAHN OFFERS PREMIUM FOR NABISCO SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By JOSEPH B. TREASTER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just 15 days after being rebuffed by the board of the Nabisco
Group Holdings Corp., Carl C. Icahn, the renowned investor,
appealed to shareholders on Thursday in a campaign to take over the
troubled maker of Oreo cookies and Ritz crackers.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the board that was widely distributed, Icahn
offered shareholders a premium of 40 percent for 100 million shares
that would give him control of the company. He offered $13 a share,
up from the stock's closing price of $9.3125 on Wednesday. Shares
of Nabisco closed Thursday at $11.75.
</P>
<P>
   And Icahn held out another carrot: Once in control, Icahn said,
he would immediately try to sell the company at what he expected
would be a ``very attractive price.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco shares, which had been trading at about $30 a year ago,
have been in decline in response to fears that as the former parent
of R.J. Reynolds, the cigarette maker, the holding company could be
liable for claims resulting from new tobacco litigation. The shares
have also suffered, analysts said, as investors shifted money from
consumer goods to technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco, whose board on March 15 adopted a shareholders rights,
or ``poison pill,'' measure designed to block Icahn, said it would
not comment until the board met and studied the proposal. In the
meantime, Nabisco urged its shareholders to sit tight. Henry A.
Sandbach, a spokesman for Nabisco, said he did not know when the
board would be meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco said on March 13 that it had been notified by Icahn, who
has been seeking control of Nabisco for five years, that he
intended to replace nine of the holding company's 12 board member
at the annual meeting scheduled for May 9. By March 13, Icahn had
increased his stake in Nabisco to 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, on March 15, the board adopted the poison pill
measure to take effect should Icahn or any other shareholder gain
10 percent of Nabisco's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn, who is known for his buyout of Trans World Airlines and
takeover attempts of the USX Corp. and Texaco Inc., is the largest
individual shareholder of Nabisco with 31 million shares. With 100
million more shares, he said, he would own 40 percent of the
company. He has recently been reported to have taken a 5 percent
stake in the Federal-Mogul Corp., a company in which Julian H.
Robertson Jr., the head of the Tiger Management hedge fund, had
held a large position.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn characterized the poison pill measure as an expression
``of contempt for stockholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, a senior analyst at Merrill Lynch who follows
Nabisco, said there was no mistaking Icahn's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to appeal to investors so that investors will put
pressure on the board,'' Goldman said. ``He's going directly to the
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco has a complicated capital structure. Nabisco Group
Holdings, the stock that Icahn says he will buy, is the holding
company that owns 80.5 percent of Nabisco Group and no other
assets. As the former parent of R.J. Reynolds, it might be liable
for damages if litigation bankrupted Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Nabisco Group Holdings has traded at a substantial
discount to the market value of its stake in Nabisco Group. That
discount was slightly over 20 percent last summer, but it grew to
58 percent last month. Even with the rise in Nabisco Group Holdings
on Thursday, the discount is still 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Icahn urged the Nabisco board to rescind its
poison pill, remove other restrictions to ownership of large blocks
of the company's shares and reschedule the annual meeting to give
him time to buy the 100 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was unclear how investors would respond to the
proposal. The $13, some analysts said, may not seem remarkably
higher than the $15 at which the stock was trading as recently as
last September. And many, investors, they said, may hold out hopes
of a turnaround in market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nabisco is a great company and they have brands that are truly
old Americana,'' Goldman said. Despite the poor performance of
Nabisco stock, Goldman said, James Kilts, the chief executive of
the operating company, has done an excellent job. ``They have very
good management,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn has criticized management, particularly for its decision
to sell the tobacco units and retain the cookie and cracker
business. He argued that shareholders would have benefited more if
the company had kept the tobacco business and sold the other units.
But company executives said Nabisco might then have been accused of
fraudulently stripping away holdings that might otherwise be used
to pay tobacco litigation claims.
</P>
<P>
   Playing to concerns about potentially heavy liabilities, Icahn
on Thursday underscored that ``the clock is ticking on tobacco
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the risks facing shareholders, he said, were that ``if and
when the current board determines to sell'' there might ``be no
buyer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
