<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APRIL IS A BANNER MONTH FOR BIRDING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Our state's reputation as a world-class vacation
destination for birdwatchers is well-established, but this month
looms especially significant.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Great Texas Birding Classic, which continues to grow
in popularity and impact, is scheduled April 7-16 over a 624-mile
stretch from Orange to Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Also cause for celebration is the completion of the Great Texas
Coastal Birding Trail _ a four-year, $1.4 million project and the
first of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MANY BENEFICIARIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Birding Classic has multiple beneficiaries:
</P>
<P>
   _ It serves as a highly competitive venue: Last year, 39 teams _
professional and amateur, including eight youth teams _ vied to see
which could count the most species (with 312 the winning number).
Contestants represented 10 states and five foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ It introduces newcomers to many of the 618 bird species
recorded in the state. Novice and advanced amateur birders, while
not involved in the competition, savor the spring migration
spectacle as millions of birds pass through on their way to
Northern summer habitats.
</P>
<P>
   _ It pours money into individual communities' tourism coffers
and the overall Texas economy. Indeed, birding generates an
estimated $155 million in annual retail sales within the state.
</P>
<P>
   _ It enhances bird conservation by linking private corporations
with competitive teams. Through corporate and local community
support and tournament entry fees, last year's event generated
$50,000 for avian habitat conservation in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   According to Texas Parks and Wildlife, the Classic's winning
teams since 1997 have directed more than $150,000 to help buy more
than 1,000 acres of emergent intertidal coastal wetlands, expand
existing bird sanctuaries, re-vegetate landscapes with native brush
valuable to migratory birds and pay back loans used to buy habitat
areas and fund long-term monitoring of high-priority migratory
birds.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Classic, sponsored by Texas Parks and Wildlife and
Texas Partners in Flight, begins April 7 with an opening ceremony
in Brownsville (5:30 p.m. at the Holiday Inn Fort Brown).
Competition starts April 9 on the lower Texas coast, moves to the
central coast April 12 and to the upper coast April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-up registration will be allowed on April 7. Call
888-892-4737 for more information, or access
www.tpwd.state.tx.us/gtbc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BIRDING TRAIL EXTENDED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 event coincides with the official opening of the Great
Texas Coastal Birding Trail's southern segment, which spotlights 88
sites along 16 loops, primarily in the lower Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   This portion of the trail extends south from near Riviera to
Brownsville, then winds along the Rio Grande to Laredo. It includes
Bentsen-Rio Grande Valley State Park, near Mission, where a $12
million World Birding Center is planned.
</P>
<P>
   A new map, produced in conjunction with the Texas Department of
Transportation, pinpoints sites in the southern segment and will be
available by April 17. Maps covering other portions of the trail
already are published. These can be obtained free at chambers of
commerce, visitors bureaus, state parks and wildlife refuges along
the trail and at Texas Travel Information Centers. They can also be
ordered by calling 888-892-4737.
</P>
<P>
   Using the three trail maps, travelers are guided by numbered,
colored symbols that correspond to 308 birding sites designated
along the trail. Maps include directions to each site, information
about birds and other wildlife commonly seen in that area, the
availability of overnight camping facilities and tourism
information.
</P>
<P>
   All the major sites in south Texas _ from the King Ranch outside
Kingsville to Sabal Palm Audubon Center and Sanctuary in
Brownsville _ are featured. And, according to Texas Parks and
Wildlife's nature tourism program director Linda Campbell, ``The
new map makes some of the lesser-known birding hot spots in the
Valley easier to find, such as state wildlife management areas and
county and city parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several south Texas communities, aware of the increased impact
on tourism, have published localized birding guides also available
free of charge. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rockport/Fulton: Call 800-242-0071.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corpus Christi: 800-678-6232.
</P>
<P>
   _ Harlingen: 800-531-7346.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brownsville: 800-626-2639.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, too, are the advances on Texas Parks and Wildlife's
Web site. Accessed from www.tpwd.state.tx.us/gtbc, pages include a
kids' guide to birdwatching; a ``birding 101'' listing of popular
sites; a calendar of migration events; a birding checklist; and
reminders on birding ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the April issue of Texas Parks and Wildlife magazine will
be designed as a birding information resource. Available at many
bookstores and supermarkets the first week of next month, the
stylish publication will include a 2000 events calendar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
