<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SPRINT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIE FINDS FERTILE GROUND FOR SPRINT CAR DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 CAR-DREAMS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Brooke Tatnell is like a lot of Sprint Car
drivers. He dreamed of one day racing with the Pennzoil World of
Outlaws and beating the likes of Steve Kinser, Sammy Swindell and
Danny Lasoski.
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell is living that dream. Only, he had to go halfway across
the world to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell, 28, is a native of Australia, from a town near Sydney,
and has been driving Sprint Cars since he was 16 years old. Now he
is running full time on the rigorous Outlaws circuit in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to make a career out of driving race cars,
particularly Sprint Cars, America is the only place you can do
it,'' Tatnell said before Thursday's first day of the Southern
Bleacher Classic at the Texas Motor Speedway dirt track. ``We have
the land mass the United States has, but we don't have the
population to make a good living in Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell's father raced Sprint Cars, which meant he was around
the sport most of his life. Tatnell follows a long line of
Australians, led by Garry Rush _ the Steve Kinser of Australian
Sprint Car racing _ who came to the United States to race the light
and powerful cars.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Car racing is one of the best attended sports in
Australia, Tatnell said, with 4,000 to 5,000 people at a race.
</P>
<P>
   He won the World Series of Sprint Cars tour in Australia this
winter after winning six out of 17 races and finishing in the top
five in all the events.
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell first ventured to the United States in 1991, when he had
his equipment shipped over, and that first year was a learning
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gained a lot of experience, learning about the business
sort of things,'' Tatnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell has raced on the Outlaws tour full time for the past two
years. After driving for himself last year, he is now driving for
Lonny Parsons in the No. 6 Casey's General Stores Maxim.
</P>
<P>
   After a seventh-place finish in the second race at Perris Motor
Speedway in Lake Perris, Calif., the team and Tatnell have
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Through five events he is not in the top 20 in points, but he
said the struggles have been good for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new team we got here and fortunately in this sport
nothing happens overnight,'' Tatnell said. ``We are trying to jell
as a team and get the right equipment that suits my driving style.
This has been a good bonding thing and really grown to work with
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatnell said that he lived in Memphis, Tenn., last year. But
since the Casey's General Stores team is based out of Des Moines,
Iowa, he now lives in a motel.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to eventually buy a motor home, but he is happy
just to be racing on the Outlaws tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done more racing in the last three years than I have in
the previous nine,'' Tatnell said. ``One year in the Outlaw deal is
five years in Australia.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
