<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: COALITION WORKS TO BE FAMILY FRIENDLY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ohio, Calif.) (mg) 
By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Efforts by marketers to generate more ``family friendly''
programming to sponsor during primetime on television networks are
accelerating, representatives of the companies involved have
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of marketers, known as the Family Friendly
Programming Forum, outlined the most recent developments, which
include a holiday movie special to run on CBS, at the annual
Television Advertising Forum on Thursday sponsored by the
Association of National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The forum drew more than 280 executives from consumer product
companies, agencies, TV networks and program syndicators, who also
heard discussions on topics like convergence, technology and
audience measurement.
</P>
<P>
   Forty members of the association are also members of the
programming coalition, which seeks to stimulate the production of
shows meant to appeal to broader, multigenerational audiences and
suitable to run from 8 p.m. to 10 p.m. (Eastern and Pacific times).
The initiative is indicative of the increasing attention being paid
to such viewers, who remain crucial to the success of mass
marketers even in an era of aiming programs and products at
narrower segments of the general population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to sit and watch TV with our families and not be
embarrassed,'' said Steve Johnston, vice president for advertising
and brand management at Nationwide Mutual Enterprises in Columbus,
Ohio. ``I've got two teen-age daughters, and there are programs I'm
embarrassed to watch with them. Maybe they're not, but I know I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the coalition are such advertising giants as
AT&AMP;T, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Coca-Cola, Ford Motors, General Motors,
Gillette, I.B.M., Kellogg, McDonald's, Procter &AMP; Gamble and
Unilever United States.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is getting some attention because of concerns
that the programs produced under its auspices may be more suitable
for viewers of the 20th century than the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the contemporary American family does not
resemble the ``nuclear'' model that prevailed during the decades
when major marketers routinely produced TV programs. And viewing
habits have substantially changed as children, teen-agers, parents
and grandparents scatter to different rooms to watch different
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be realistic; families may not be gathered around
one TV any more and they're not your traditional families,'' said
Susan Frank, executive vice president and general manager of the
Odyssey Network in Studio City, Calif., a cable channel that has
been refocused on family-oriented programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are times you can bring family members together with
content that's thought-provoking, done in a good, quality way,''
she added. ``You have to be relevant to the way people live
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Odyssey, owned by Hallmark Entertainment; the Jim Henson Co.;
and the Warner Brothers unit of Time Warner are sponsoring a
32-page advertising section about the programming coalition that
will run in the April 10 issues of the trade publications Adweek,
Brandweek and Mediaweek.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the coalition, which began in 1998 with 10
marketers, does not mean that members will shun ``dramatic
programming that touches on controversial subjects,'' said J.
Andrea Alstrup, vice president for advertising at Johnson &AMP; Johnson
in New Brunswick, N.J., who heads the programming coalition along
with Robert L. Wehling, global marketing officer at Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying everything should be sweet all the time,''
Alstrup said. ``We're saying that in the early hours of prime time,
up to 10 o'clock, there's a need for entertainment that people can
enjoy together, intergenerationally.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Johnson &AMP; Johnson is one of three members of the
programming coalition that will collaborate with CBS on the holiday
special, Alstrup said. The special is to be a two-hour movie titled
``The Flight of the Reindeer'' that is to run before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the special was coordinated by Bill Cella,
executive vice president for broadcast and programming at
McCann-Erickson North America in New York, part of McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising. The agency, a unit of the McCann-Erickson
World Group division of the Interpublic Group of Companies, works
for Johnson &AMP; Johnson and the other two marketers. Cella identified
one as Nestle USA and said the other declined to be identified at
this time.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has also agreed to broadcast the second annual presentation
of the Family Program Awards show sponsored by the programming
coalition; the broadcast has been scheduled for late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Nationwide are among 12 members of the
programming coalition that have donated $1 million to a
script-development fund that is a joint effort with the WB network,
owned by Time Warner and the Tribune Co. Eight scripts have been
developed through the fund, half of which have produced orders for
pilots or presentations for this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Alstrup said that two are ``definitely'' being considered for
the lineup for the fall 2000 season, which will be decided by WB
executives in May. One is ``Finally Home,'' featuring the actress
Melissa Gilbert, about a husband and wife who, after the deaths of
their twins, take in foster children, and the other is ``Gilmore
Girls,'' about a mother and daughter with a close relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Wonder if they are as close as the actress Angelina Jolie
was with her brother, James Haven Voight, when she won her Academy
Award on Sunday night. But that might be too family friendly even
for the folks at the Family Friendly Programming Forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
