<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO SAYS IT IS DISCUSSING INTERNET PRIVACY WITH FTC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yahoo Inc. on Thursday notified the Securities
and Exchange Commission that it was voluntarily cooperating with an
inquiry by the Federal Trade Commission into how Internet sites
gather personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo officials played down the inclusion of the information in
the annual report, stating that the company was just being
``extremely conservative in legal documents'' and that it took its
privacy policies seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But financial analysts said the disclosure underscored a larger,
and more profound, point. In deciding that the FTC inquiry was
material enough to include in an SEC filing, Yahoo has also
indicated how important the mining of demographic data on one hand
and concerns about consumer privacy on the other can be to an
Internet company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an implication that the FTC could use their disclosure
to help set industry guidelines which could impact their ability to
use that information,'' said Jordan Rohan, a media analyst with Wit
Soundview, a New York-based investment banking firm. Referring to
data gathering, he added, ``It's almost an admission that rules may
change or may become more concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure also underscored the FTC's emergence as the
primary regulator of e-commerce. In recent months, it has begun
inquiries into the Web practices of several companies, most notably
the data-gathering practices of DoubleClick Inc., and it has
wielded considerable authority over the gathering of data about
minors online.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Hunt, a Yahoo spokeswoman, said the discussions with the
FTC had ``nothing to do with advertising profiling.'' However, she
declined to elaborate on the nature of the disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   David Medine, the associate director for financial practices for
the FTC, declined to acknowledge that an inquiry was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, however, acknowledged having been contacted
by the commission after the release of a survey in February by the
nonprofit California HealthCare Foundation, which concluded that
while 19 of the top 21 health sites had privacy policies, many did
not live up to promises not to share personal information with
third parties.
</P>
<P>
   The survey included not only major health-care-only sites, like
Healtheon/WebMD, but also so-called portals like Yahoo and Excite,
which offer numerous services, including health-related content.
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Smith, an Internet security expert and one of the
researchers on the survey, said a common problem on sites was that
visitors did not know how many companies might have access to their
personal data. For example, a visitor might fill out a health care
survey on one site, but the data could be processed by a
third-party contractor, making the information more widely
available than had been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, Web sites say they are not gathering
information about individuals but are gathering general demographic
data about, for example, the nature of their subscriber base to
sell to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Rohan, from Wit Capital, said Web sites were justifiably
concerned about being able to continue gathering demographic
information. Advertisers, he said, are willing to pay substantially
more _ 7 to 10 times as much _ for the ability to direct messages
to prescreened audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's disclosure suggests that the controversy about data
gathering is hitting the mainstream, said Lanny Baker, an analyst
at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire industry's been hiding under their desks and
letting Doubleclick take it on the chin,'' Baker said. But
DoubleClick, he said, is ``not doing anything that anyone else
isn't doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
