<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-OUTLAWS-SMITHS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S GOLDEN TOUCH GIVES INNOVATIVE SMITHS A RADICAL STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Stevie Smith did not have to do much
convincing to have his father work with him on his Pennzoil World
of Outlaw team.
</P>
<P>
   That's strange considering Smith's father, Steve, spent most of
his Sprint Car career racing around their New Oxford, Pa., home.
The elder Smith rarely traveled, but now he's out on the road with
his son.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, though, wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before I quit driving, (Stevie) wanted to start his own
team,'' Steve said. ``We always wanted to go together and have our
own race team down the road. He definitely wants to be on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Smith started the team after the 1996 season and ran most
of the 1997 season without a sponsor, and his father served as the
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the 1997 season, Ingersoll-Rand signed on as a
sponsor and the team took off. In 1998, Smith led the points for
two weeks in May and led the series with 13 victories. Smith Racing
had some engine troubles midway through the season and ended fourth
in points.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stevie finished fourth again and had five victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a load off my shoulders,'' Stevie said of having his
father around. ``I don't have to do all the worrying. It's hard for
one guy to do it all, and I would like to keep it in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevie started racing Sprint Cars in his late teens in Central
Pennsylvania, while his father was already an established local
star. He later ventured onto the World of Outlaws tour in 1990, and
won the rookie of the year honors while driving for Al Hamilton,
</P>
<P>
   Stevie drove for a few other teams before starting his own team
in 1997, but he always had plans for his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie said his father ``was one of the best. Everybody kind of
expected that out of me, but I didn't know what to expect. I did my
own thing and I didn't try to outdo him and not try to be as good
as he was, but to the best I could for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevie has continued his father's tradition by building the own
equipment. The team uses a Smith chassis they designed and built
along with their own engines.
</P>
<P>
   Steve was known as one of the innovators in Sprint Car racing,
despite seldom racing outside of Sprint Car-crazed Central
Pennsylvania. Some of the sprint cars he built were radical and
were much different from the standard sprint car.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths don't have quite as radical car on the Outlaw series,
but there are a few things they do that other teams wouldn't try.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths were one of the first to use side rails on the roll
cage to provide more protection for the driver. Plus, they
experimented with a Sprint Car that used coil-over shock suspension
instead of the more common torsion bar suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't let you do much because if you come out there with
a car looking completely different, (the series officials) don't
want to argue with 40 other cars,'' Steve said. ``So, you just got
to keep up and do what you can the best you can. Out here on this
deal, you ain't going to have anything ahead of them for very
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the changing face of the Outlaw series, where teams can
buy any part they want anywhere, the Smiths still use equipment
they can call their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is part of it for me,'' Steve said. ``I have always run
my own cars and normally done my own motors. But (you feel) that
little extra if it is your stuff. That's part of the fun, but,
really, it is almost too much work for the time that we have to get
it done.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
