<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GREENSPAN-STOCKS-NYT &LR;      03-30 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED ISN'T TRYING TO CURB STOCK PRICES, SAYS GREENSPAN IN LETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, told
members of Congress in a letter made public Thursday that the
central bank's goal in raising interest rates was not to bring down
the stock market, and he reiterated his opposition to growing calls
for the Fed to make it more difficult for investors to buy stock
with borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, and chairman of the House
Banking Committee, Greenspan said the Fed ``is not `jawboning' the
stock market or targeting stock prices.'' The letter was in
response to written questions from the committee to Greenspan after
his appearance on Capitol Hill in February.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Greenspan said, the central bank is concerned that the
economy is reaching a point at which it cannot meet the sustained
high level of demand for goods and services _ and that the long
rise in the stock market, by making people feel wealthier, is
supporting that demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sharp increase in equity valuation appears to have been an
important factor behind an apparently developing imbalance,''
Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has long struggled with how monetary policy should
take account of sharp swings in asset prices. Ever since he used
the phrase ``irrational exuberance'' in discussing the stock market
in December 1996, investors have been suspicious that he is trying
to talk down the markets.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Greenspan has said that he does not know
whether stocks are overvalued _ but that in either case the wealth
being generated on Wall Street is contributing so much to the
accelerated pace of economic growth that the Fed cannot ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   To many economists and analysts, the distinction being drawn by
Greenspan _ that monetary policy does not single out stock prices,
but that the rise in stock prices will almost certainly have to be
tempered or reversed for monetary policy to be successful _ is so
fine as to be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   And as he has put the stock market at the center of the debate
over monetary policy, Greenspan has come under pressure not to drag
down the entire economy, especially with inflation so restrained,
just to put a ceiling on the stock market's rise.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Leach whether it would be better to try to rein in the
stock market not by raising interest rates but by tightening
requirements on margin lending _ buying stock with borrowed money _
Greenspan said that ``changes in such requirements have no
appreciable and predictable effect'' on stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed chairman issued a veiled warning about the rapid
rise in margin lending at a time when the markets are gyrating
wildly and technology stocks in particular are on a roller coaster
ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, he said, ``recognizes that considerable risks can be
involved in the purchase of equity on margin, especially in
volatile markets, and believes that lenders and borrowers need to
assess carefully the risks they are assuming'' in using margin
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Greenspan said in response to a question from Rep.
Ron Paul, R-Texas, the path of stock prices will be determined not
by the short-term interest rates the Fed controls, but by corporate
performance and overall interest rates in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The risks ``of investing in equities come primarily from
uncertainty about future earnings and about the longer-term
interest rates at which those future earnings should be discounted,
and not mainly from the possibility that the short-term cost of
financing stock positions could increase,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, even if our operating procedures were associated
with somewhat larger movements in short-term rates, I doubt that
investors' perceptions of equity risks would be much affected and
thus that equity prices would be significantly influenced.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
