<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2981 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-LIBBY-ASBESTOS-SPI &LR;      03-30 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBBY-ASBESTOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASBESTOS-BEARING VERMICULITE SOLD AT SEATTLE GARDEN STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vermiculite from a closed mine in Libby, Mont., where
hundreds of workers and their families died of asbestos-related
diseases is being sold in garden stores in the Puget Sound area,
the Post-Intelligencer has found.
</P>
<P>
   That product, Zonolite Chemical Packaging Vermiculite produced
by W.R. Grace &AMP; Co., was found to have alarmingly high levels of
asbestos in recent testing by the Environmental Protection Agency
and the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the EPA, sophisticated air sampling of the Zonolite
detected asbestos fibers at levels up to 80 times higher than the
exposure to workers allowed by the federal Office of Safety and
Health Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Grace said that it discontinued the product in 1992. The tracing
number on bags of Zonolite found at Chubby and Tubby, a small chain
of Seattle hardware stores, show the bags contained vermiculite
from the Grace mine in Libby. The Zonolite was packaged at a Grace
plant in Santa Ana, Calif., ``in August 1991, most likely on the
third shift,'' said William Corcoran, Grace's vice president of
public and regulatory affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran said he was surprised ``that a product discontinued
eight years ago is still available today'' and added that he had no
idea who was selling the material, but it wasn't Grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chemical packing material,'' he said, ``is not now, nor was it
ever, intended to be sold in lawn-and-garden sections of
home-improvement stores.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA investigators found the Zonolite on the top shelf of a local
garden store while they were gathering garden products for asbestos
testing. They tested the Zonolite by using it the same way that
gardeners described when they called the agency to ask if the
material was safe.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators have notified three Seattle stores where they
bought the products of the test results, but there appears to be no
effort to spread the word to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on limited sampling we've completed, we cannot make
broad determinations on what products are or are not safe, just
yet,'' said Bill Dunbar, a spokesman for EPA's regional office.
``Our testing is part of a national effort to determine what
consumer products have asbestos in them and until those studies are
complete, it would be irresponsible to take any product off the
shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that EPA is reluctant to caution the public about a
possible risk from this out-of-date product worries some in the
agency, especially those investigating possible continued asbestos
contamination near the mine at Libby and at the more than 250
operations across the country where Grace or its customers
processed Zonolite from the early 1960s to the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Mike DiCecco, general manger of Chubby and Tubby, didn't wait to
be ordered to remove the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the EPA told me that the material was contaminated with
asbestos, I ordered it taken off the shelves, I'm just not going to
take a chance that a customer buys something dangerous from us,''
DiCecco said.
</P>
<P>
   According to calls from readers who read the P-I's series on
Libby in November, Zonolite Chemical Packaging Vermiculite also was
being sold in southern and eastern Washington, Oregon, Michigan,
Missouri, Texas and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   DiCecco says he's not sure where the Zonolite he removed from
the shelves came from ``but about two years ago we bought 150 bags
from a liquidator from Tacoma. Once we saw the W.R. Grace label, we
were confident it was vermiculite because they had made it in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   A manager of another garden store in Kent, Wash., also said he
had bought it from a wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   The material, which is vermiculite ore expanded popcorn-like in
a heat process, looks identical to what gardeners use to mix with
peat and soil. Used worldwide as a packaging for chemicals, the
vermiculite not only cushions the material but also absorbs liquid
if a container should break or leak.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials may not think they have enough evidence to warn
consumers but at EPA's regional environmental testing laboratory,
across Puget Sound in Manchester, Wash., lab chemists don't want
the stuff around.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the packaging material is used for the purpose for
which it was designed, people are concerned about the hazard.
</P>
<P>
   In a large hangar-like warehouse adjacent to the area where the
testing of lawn products is being conducted, sit several barrels of
vermiculite, packaging from boxes of samples and chemicals used in
the lab. On shelves on the second floor are several large unopened
Kraft paper bags of the same type of Zonolite packaging material
which was contaminated with asbestos. They were purchased years ago
from a garden store in Port Orchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't use it any more for shipments received at the
laboratory,'' said Gerald Dodo, an EPA chemist and contract
officer. ``The coolers and boxes they use to ship samples to us are
packed with vermiculite. We just don't want people here to deal
with it because the exposure could be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``A simple painter's or dust mask isn't going to do anything to
stop asbestos fibers, so it would be better not to deal with it at
all,'' Dodo said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the EPA familiar with the test results say that OSHA
should be notified, so lab workers in other labs are aware of the
potential risk.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, according to DiCecco, signs have been posted near the
cash registers at the Chubby and Tubby stores saying ``Due to an
EPA investigation, we have pulled vermiculite off our sales
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not going to sell any of it until EPA completes its
investigation. It's not worth the risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
