<HEADLINE>
DIME BANCORP SUES SALOMON IN DISPUTE OVER HOSTILE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Doing all it can to fend off a hostile takeover bid,
Dime Bancorp is suing its former investment bankers for going to
work for its unwanted suitor, North Fork Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   Dime, which owns the Dime Savings Bank of New York, asked a
state court Wednesday to stop Salomon Smith Barney from serving as
a financial adviser to North Fork, a banking company that is
pressing Dime to accept a $1.9 billion buyout offer. North Fork,
based in Melville, rode in a few weeks ago, just as Dime's
shareholders were about to vote on a proposed purchase of Dime by
Hudson United Bancorp, based in Mahwah, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Judge Ira Gammerman declined to issue a
temporary restraining order sought by Dime and gave Salomon's
lawyers until Wednesday afternoon to explain why he should not stop
the firm from advising Dime.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Dime prevails in court, it would still have to contend
with North Fork and its other financial adviser, a smaller firm
called Sandler, O'Neill &AMP; Partners. After two postponements, Dime's
shareholders are scheduled to vote May 17 on Hudson United's
proposed $1.4 billion stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   Dime contends that Salomon Smith Barney agreed in May 1997,
while advising Dime on an acquisition, not to represent any company
on a bid for Dime without its consent.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Salomon, a unit of Citigroup, said the firm
merely pledged that it would not share any confidential information
it gathered while working for Dime.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes over conflicts of interest involving investment banks
usually center on the disclosure of confidential information, but
that is difficult to prove. In an attempt to thwart an unsolicited
takeover by Vodafone AirTouch in November, Mannesmann of Germany
filed suit in London accusing the Goldman Sachs Group of a similar
betrayal. That suit was thrown out, and Goldman continued advising
Vodafone on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Dime is arguing that Salomon is violating a
contract it signed as Dime's adviser on its purchase of the North
American Mortgage Co. in 1997. Dime contends that part of the
agreement, for which Salomon received $1.5 million in fees, was
that Salomon would refrain from working on any bid for Dime for
three years. People close to Dime said the bank was troubled by the
involvement of James Harasimowicz, a Salomon investment banker, who
worked with Dime on the North American Mortgage deal .
</P>
<P>
   Duncan King, a Salomon spokesman, said Harasimowicz, a director
at the firm, has worked on both deals but was not the lead banker
on either.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a prepared statement, King said: ``Dime is intentionally
misrepresenting the previous agreement in an effort to thwart the
transaction. The prior agreement does not preclude Salomon Smith
Barney from advising North Fork. It simply precludes our use of any
confidential information gained while advising Dime three years
ago. We are confident that we have completely respected our client
agreements.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
