<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPE, FAN SUPPORT GROW FOR WOMEN'S FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
 FOUR-GROWTH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When 63-year-old Marilyn McDonald walked off the
plane, it took her maybe a second to figure out where she was.
</P>
<P>
   Banners, posters, designated greeters all telling her that she
was in the city that's playing host to the 2000 NCAA women's Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Philadelphia, host city of this year's women's
Final Four,'' blared a representative covered in ``PWB2000''
attire, who then handed out brochures about hotels, tourist
attractions and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a women's basketball game? Since when did this
become a big deal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure wasn't like this when I started coming to these 12
years ago,'' said McDonald, a resident of Walters, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's first capital might never play host to an Olympics
or a Super Bowl, but when it throws a party, it lets everyone know
about it. Even for a sport that, until recently, was never given
this type of hype.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA women's Final Four, in its 19th year, has become an
event the Ann Meyers, C. Vivian Stringers and Jody Conradts worked
for years to build: a prime-time championship that can stand on its
own, full of fan fervor and an abundance of media coverage and
corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too often you can go somewhere and people are calling
your name and holding up signs,'' Tennessee star Tamika Catchings
said. ``You've got a lot of young athletes out there getting
excited about playing basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, yes. In 1982, it was a little different.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA sponsored its first women's basketball Final Four in
1982 in Norfolk, Va., but few took notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were the NCAAs, but I wasn't in tune so much with
the game that led to our being, you know, a member of the Final
Four,'' said Rutgers' Stringer, who coached in the first Final Four
when she was with Cheyney State University.
</P>
<P>
   The three games drew a combined 15,531 fans with the title game
on national television _ a big deal back then. But, few knew who
the players or coaches were. Remember, not all universities
embraced women's basketball. It wasn't until the late 1970s that
legislation forced Title IX equity compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My enthusiasm is exactly the same (as it was in 1982),''
Stringer said. ``but I think that when I look at this press room
and all the people that are here, this was nowhere near the size
that it was there. There has been a tremendous revolution that has
taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   People know who Tennessee coach Pat Summitt is. People know that
Connecticut is dominating the game. They know Catchings is regarded
as one of the best college players, ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably no more significant to the players who are in
the game,'' Texas coach Jody Conradt said. ``It's all about
awareness. It's about how the media views the game and its
coverage. Once we started to get fans who really started to support
the programs and the players themselves, there was a feeling that
this can be big.''
</P>
<P>
   It is big ... it's just taken awhile.
</P>
<P>
   While the men's tournament has enjoyed huge TV ratings and fan
interest for years, the women's Final Four has just recently begun
to see similar results.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 10 years of the women's Final Four, the average
three-game attendance was 19,659. Since 1992, however, the women's
event has averaged 33,536 fans, topped by the 46,582 figure in 1996
at the Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped that I would live long enough to see some of this
happen,'' said recently retired Baylor coach Sonja Hogg, who won
the NCAA's first national title with Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change, however, is the grail for all sporting
events: television.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Final Four was split between ESPN and CBS with no
day off in between. The semifinals were on ESPN before the men's
national semis. Translation: You had to know where to look and when
to look to watch the games. In 1994, the NCAA and ESPN agreed to a
seven-year contract beginning in 1996, allowing the sport to run
its own event with clear boundaries between its brothers, and for a
day off between games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA was looking for prime-time coverage and a rest day,''
ESPN spokesperson Josh Krulewitz said. ``This is a tremendous
property for us and it's been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   How successful? The 1999 title game between Duke and Purdue drew
a 4.3 rating on ESPN. That is equivalent to 3.24 million homes. It
was the second highest rating for a basketball game, men's or
women's, in the 20-year history of the network.
</P>
<P>
   The people in women's basketball aren't crazy about it, but a
sign of its progression as a big-time sporting event can be seen in
casinos, too. Oddsmakers in Las Vegas set lines on semifinals and
finals _ the only three women's games of the year where betting
odds are established.
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid the glitter of sold-out arenas and television coverage
rests some issues for the Final Four, and the tournament itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question it will continue to
grow,'' NCAA president Cedric Dempsey said. ``We're putting a lot
of money into it. It's not one of the profit sports, yet, and
neither is the tournament. The men's (tournaments) have been
profitable for some years, but it took them some time.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is guessing the timetable when the tournament will become
self-sufficient. There is talk among leaders in the sport of going
to neutral-site games in the first two rounds, which are now being
played on campus sites, but the concern is how well the games will
draw without a host school. There is also discussion of how to get
all 63 tournament games on television, equivalent to the men's
tournament. Another concern is the dominance by a few schools, such
as Tennessee and Connecticut. More parity would drive interest,
many believe.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt is also concerned that, despite the heavy media
coverage, the event it overshadowed by the men's Final Four on the
same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest disappointment is the lack of coverage
compared to the men,'' Summitt said. ``Should we move (the time)?
Are we getting the type of exposure we want? I'm not sure, but if
we don't want to compete, we should take a look at the format.''
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the Final Four from its ``why-is-this-on-TV?''
beginnings to its current ``what-time-is-it-on?'' state suggests
that all of above can happen. And it might not take long.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``I never thought it would be like this.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
