<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS: BUZZ OFF, CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, the number of toilets people have is sacred.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott joined others earlier
this week urging citizens to skip intrusive census questions, like
those about bathrooms. But even before the Mississippi Republican's
privacy push, people were wary of Census 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They say the census is too nosy, that the government doesn't
need to know whether they have a phone, their mortgage amount or
how they get to work.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials defended the 52-question survey Thursday,
saying only one question was added since the 1990 count (asking
about grandparents as caregivers) and only one in six people gets
the longer form.
</P>
<P>
   The census may not have changed in the past 10 years, but we
have. Think Caller ID, unpublished numbers, identity theft, paper
shredders and the ease of Internet information, all virtually
unheard of 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 12 percent of Arizonans have that little box alerting them
who's on the other end of the phone line and shredders were a top
Christmas gift last year. Combine that with a growing mistrust of
the government, and you get a population that's defensive about its
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in an increasingly privacy-conscious world,''
says Beth Givens, director of the Privacy Rights Clearinghouse, a
San Diego-based consumer group. ``People are concerned about the
census. They are saying, `I don't see a need for the census to know
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials say Lott and other members of Congress now
complaining about the form actually approved it.
</P>
<P>
   And the survey will help decide how to dole out $185 billion in
federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they pause and look at how the information is being used,
my guess is they will actually see its usefulness,'' says Kenneth
Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But Sylvia Allen, 53, of Heber, can't understand why the
government needs to know who in her house can't dress himself or
bathe on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally invasive. They've gone too far on some of the
questions,'' Allen says. She understands that the government needs
to count people and will fill out her form, but she might not
answer all the questions. ``Some just don't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Tilford, 34, of Phoenix, reluctantly filled out the long
form. ``It's so intrusive,'' he says. ``I feel like they threatened
me into doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't fill out the form, census officials say, are
subject to a $100 fine. But census officials admit they've never
fined anyone.
</P>
<P>
   However, they soon will call people who didn't fill out their
entire forms in order to get all questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   So far, census officials have counted the number of forms
returned (46 percent in Arizona), but not how many questions were
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt says he's unsure whether lawmakers' suggestions will
influence people.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., urged people to
answer only the first six questions, then return it with a letter
of protest.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen people called the office of Rep. John Shadegg,
R-Ariz., saying they were uncomfortable with some questions.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona congressmen say they are reassuring their
constituents, telling them to fill out the form.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't come back to haunt you in any way,'' says Keith
Rosenblum, press secretary for Republican Rep. Jim Kolbe. ``We are
a society in the Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials, by law, cannot share their information with
the Internal Revenue Service or anyone else. Although after 72
years, forms can be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep trying to tell them, it doesn't matter what they tell
us, we can't share it, not even with the president,'' says Jim
Howard, a local census office director.
</P>
<P>
   But when the president admits on television that he lied to the
American people, some don't believe government promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that people are more sensitive to privacy
issues, but it's not the individual information we're interested
in,'' Howard says. ``It's as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as people grow more concerned about their privacy, they are
revealing more about themselves, points out Professor David Sorkin
of Chicago's John Marshall Law School and an expert on privacy law.
</P>
<P>
   They are using grocery saver cards, which tell the store their
favorite ice cream and which deodorant they use. On the Internet,
they tell newspapers which stories they read and booksellers what
titles they buy.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Givens of the privacy group says people are trying to
guard their privacy more closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they don't have control of their personal
information,'' she says. ``So, they don't want to give it out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000330.0479 </DOCNO>
