<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WORKPLACE-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERGY AND LABOR CALL ATTENTION TO WORKING POOR
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (mg) 
By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On college campuses and farmers' fields, in churches
and immigration detention centers, and across a range of religious
and political beliefs, people are fasting. They do it to make a
statement, to draw attention, to make a personal kind of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Across New York state this week, more than a thousand people,
from the Roman Catholic bishop of Albany to janitors in Buffalo,
have joined in one of the country's largest fasts, this one to
protest low wages and concerns about the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Fasting, of course, has been a spiritual undertaking and
sociopolitical tool for centuries, and the lineup of famous fasters
is vast and varied: Gandhi, Cesar Chavez, Dick Gregory and, of
course, Jesus of Nazareth. But fasting, it appears, is seeing a
modest revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a definite increase in fasting,'' said Kim Bobo,
executive director of the National Interfaith Committee for Worker
Justice. ``Fasting has always been in the Christian, Jewish and
Muslim tradition, and as people of faith seek increasingly to
struggle for justice in this time of abundance, it's a natural
outgrowth that fasting would be something they do.''
</P>
<P>
   To many, the power of fasting, personal and political, feels
especially strong in New York, where many of the streets, beginning
with Wall Street and extending deep into the suburbs, seem to be
awash in money and an obsession with wealth and excess.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Howard Hubbard of Albany said New York's religious and
labor leaders initiated a 40-hour fast because they were upset that
the problems of poor workers were drawing so little attention.
Fasting, he said, is a way to make an unmistakable moral statement
when so much of the populace is preoccupied with stock options and
sybaritic consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is mesmerized these days by the soaring stock market
and how people seem to be doing so well economically, yet the gap
between the richest and the poorest is wider than it's been in
decades,'' said Bishop Hubbard, who is co-chairman of the New York
State Labor-Religion Coalition, which organized the fast.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, Brockport, Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse and New York
City, hundreds of clergy members, labor leaders, college students
and others began fasting at 8 p.m. on Wednesday. Subsisting on only
water and juice, they have prayed together and joined street
demonstrations to draw attention to a group they call ``invisible
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   These workers include janitors in Buffalo who earn $5.25 an
hour, farm workers in Sullivan County who must work 70 hours a week
and cafeteria workers at the State University of New York in Albany
who cannot afford medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorkers are fasting during the same week that six
students at Purdue University in Indiana are doing so to pressure
the university's administration to do more to ensure that apparel
bearing the Purdue name is not made in sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, six students at the University of California at
Berkeley fasted for eight days to demand more instructors for the
ethnic studies department. In 1998, half a dozen tomato pickers in
Immokalee, Fla., fasted for a month to protest low wages, while
janitors and labor leaders at the University of Southern California
shunned food to protest the university's failure to sign a union
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Kevin Irwin, a professor of theology at the Catholic
University of America who has written extensively on fasting, said
the upsurge is a healthy development, healthier, he said, than a
trendier type of fasting that he has little patience for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the fasting we're seeing now regarding social
concerns is healthier,'' Irwin said. ``It is dependent on God and
raises very important values in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who choose to fast have many role models. In the Bible,
Jesus fasted for 40 days to proclaim good news to the poor and to
give sight to the blind and health to the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi fasted to draw attention to Britain's colonialism and
harsh treatment of the Indian people. And Cesar Chavez, founder of
the United Farm Workers, held repeated fasts to make the public
focus on the low wages and miserable conditions of thousands of
farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Shaughnessy, statewide coordinator of New York's
labor-religion coalition, acknowledged that it was hard to count
how many people were participating in the fast. But he said close
to 1,500 people had told the coalition that they would participate.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition chose to make the fast 40 hours because 40 is
freighted with symbolism: the 40 days of Lent, the 40 days of rain
in the Great Flood, the Jews' 40 years in the desert, and the
40-hour workweek.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth year the coalition has held the fast. Last
year, after the participants focused on the plight of farm workers,
the State Legislature raised the minimum wage for farm workers.
This year the fast began two days after the New York State Catholic
Conference held its annual lobbying day in Albany, and it will end
at noon today.
</P>
<P>
   The participants say they want to press the New York Legislature
to raise the state minimum wage above the federal minimum of $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Hubbard said he hoped the fast would grow, and some labor
and religious leaders say they will try to spread it to other
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues may be different,'' Bishop Hubbard said, ``but the
call to reach out to those who are neediest and most vulnerable
among us is every bit as much a part of our religious mandate as it
was when Christ walked the face of the earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
