<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELDON GOES 8-FOR-9, BUT OATES REJECTS HIS PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates gave Scott Sheldon
the news he dreaded to hear Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't get sent to the minors. His spot on the team looks
fairly secure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Oates told Sheldon he couldn't pitch the ninth inning
of the Rangers' 6-1 victory against the Double-A Tulsa Drillers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chickened out,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon's calling card is his versatility, and he put that on
display by playing all eight positions in the field. He caught in
the first inning, then moved to shortstop, first base, second base,
third base, center field, right field and left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great opportunity,'' said Sheldon, who played all
four infield positions, catcher and left field for the Triple-A
Oklahoma RedHawks last season and has played short, second, third
and first in the majors. ``I thank Johnny for trying it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that would have made it perfect would have been
if he'd been able to play the ninth position. He has never pitched
in a professional game but has in alumni games at the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to pitch to one hitter in the ninth, and I chickened
out,'' Oates said. ``The rewards for doing it don't outweigh the
risks if I blow his arm out. He has a chance to make the club, and
if I blew his arm out I couldn't live with myself. If it's in
August and I need an emergency pitcher to save the bullpen, I might
use him then, but I couldn't do it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon understood the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want it to become uncomfortable for him,'' Sheldon
said. ``He worked so hard to let me play all the other positions.''
DECISIONS ALMOST DUE
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sheldon and the other players on the bubble likely will
find out Sunday whether they've made the club. Johnny Oates said he
will announce his decisions before the team works out at The
Ballpark in Arlington that day.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two exhibition games to impress the manager, Friday
night against the St. Louis Cardinals at The Ballpark and tomorrow
afternoon in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, though, said those games will carry little weight. He'll
make his decisions based on spring training as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The final roster makeup greatly depends on left-handed reliever
Mike Venafro, who has been bothered most of the spring by a finger
injury. He's scheduled to pitch the next two games, and if he shows
he's healthy, he will be on the team.
</P>
<P>
   That likely will leave the final roster spot for a utility
infielder: Sheldon or Edwin Diaz. ZIMMERMAN BEARS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Rangers were playing a team of Triple-A and
Double-A players, reliever Jeff Zimmerman treated the game as
though it meant something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to work on having a high intensity level and
not treat it as just another exhibition game,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   That's been a problem for Zimmerman this spring. He has had a
tendency to throw a couple of good pitches then lose his focus.
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished what he wanted against the Drillers, working a
1-2-3 eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to maintain my intensity,'' Zimmerman said.
RODRIGUEZ HURT
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez left the game in the first inning after
being hit on the right elbow by an inside fastball from Chuck
Smith. He is to be examined by team orthopedist Dr. John Conway,
but Rodriguez said he doesn't believe the injury is serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore, stiff, but it's OK,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays last night appeared negative but will be reviewed by
Conway on Friday. RODRIGUEZ, JONES INDUCTED
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez and Tulsa manager Bobby Jones became the charter
members of the Wall of Fame at Drillers Stadium in a pregame
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez didn't spend much time in Tulsa. He hit .274 in 50
games at the Double-A level in 1991, then was promoted to the
majors to stay on June 20 that year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is managing Tulsa for the sixth consecutive season and the
eighth year overall. He has 476 victories, the most in Tulsa
history, and guided the club to the 1998 Texas League championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Drillers plan to induct two new members each year. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ About 600 scattered single tickets, obstructed-view tickets
and standing-room tickets remain for Monday's season opener against
the Chicago White Sox. The paid attendance for Opening Day has
surpassed the regular-season record of 47,204, set July 4, 1999
against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar Lopez is the play-by-play announcer and Eleno Ornelas is
the analyst for the Rangers' Spanish radio broadcasts. All the
team's home games, beginning with Friday's exhibition against St.
Louis, are scheduled to be broadcast on KESS/1270 AM. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
