<HEADLINE>
POLL GIVES GORE AN EDGE IN NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE VOTERS
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey voters favor Vice President Al Gore over Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, 50 percent to 37 percent, primarily because
Bush's support has sagged among independents and women, according
to a Quinnipiac College poll released on Thursday. Independents
favored Bush, 43 percent to 41 percent, in a Feb. 24 Quinnipiac
poll, but now support Gore, 47 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McLean, a political science professor at Quinnipiac in
Hamden, Conn., said women now favor Gore, 54 percent to 33 percent;
last September, women were evenly divided. Only 35 percent of all
voters and 45 percent of Republicans wanted Gov. Christie Whitman
as Bush's running mate, McLean said. The poll questioned 1,177
voters from March 21 to 27 and had a margin of sampling error of
three percentage points.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ON THE CENSUS
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush said on Thursday that he understood why some
people found the long census form too nosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us need to encourage people to fill out the census,''
Bush said in Wisconsin. But, he added: ``I can understand why
people don't want to give all that information to the government.
And if I have the long form, I'm not so sure I want to either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi and other Republicans have said
those who think the long form invades their privacy should not
answer questions they see as intrusive. Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, the House Democratic leader, said that Republicans
opposed an accurate count for political purposes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLAG DEBATE IN VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   The fiery contest predicted for this year's Senate race in
Virginia is already apparent as Sen. Charles S. Robb defended his
vote against a constitutional ban on burning the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign of his Republican opponent, former Gov. George
Allen, sought to cast the incumbent Democrat as a defender of
desecration, Robb took to the Senate floor to speak passionately as
a Vietnam combat veteran who ``had men literally die in my arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending unpopular free speech as a constitutional right, he
said, ``They did not die for a piece of cloth, however sacred,''
but for ``all that our flag represents.'' The Roanoke Times
editorialized: ``The spectacle of one American _ who has never had
to defend his country's flag under fire _ waving it to attack
another _ who has _ is revolting.'' The Allen campaign denied
questioning Robb's patriotism and insisted that Allen should not be
attacked for having had a safe draft number when Robb was fighting
the war.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS BACKS PRIMARY
</P>
<P>
   In a break with his fellow state Democrats, Gov. Gray Davis of
California is asking the U.S. Supreme Court to uphold California's
open primary elections, which allow voters to cast ballots for
candidates of any party in primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party has joined with the Republican Party to
fight the open primary through the federal courts. But the governor
is convinced that the open primary system is important to his
political future _ he faces re-election in 2002 _ and that it is
sound policy, his aides said. In the 1998 primary, Davis attracted
many Republican votes, which gave him invaluable momentum heading
into the general election later that year.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Green Bay, Wis.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No public events.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
