<HEADLINE>
REFS' SURVEY HURTS, BUT NCAA BUOYED BY PROPOSED GAMBLING BAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Two days before the first Final Four of the 2000s
and NCAA president Cedric Dempsey wasn't discussing No. 8 seeds or
this NCAA Tournament's capricious twists and turns. Gambling,
again, is a major distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dempsey and other NCAA officials were in Washington
to meet with congressmen regarding legislation that would ban
betting on college sports. Also Wednesday, a University of Michigan
study was released that found that of the Division I football and
basketball game officials it surveyed, a majority said they gamble,
with some betting on sports and using bookies.
</P>
<P>
   For the NCAA, that's one up and one down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are somewhat confident that if we can get the (legislation)
to the floor for a vote, we will win that vote,'' Dempsey said
while meeting with reporters at the RCA Dome. ``We recognize that
we have strong opposition from the gaming community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan survey, which received responses from 640 out of
1,462 officials, provided another distraction from the Final Four.
Two years ago in San Antonio, the Northwestern basketball
game-fixing scandal broke two days before the national semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey, though, believes that the NCAA has been proactive when
it comes to this issue. This year, basketball officials who work
the NCAA Tournament _ plus the 10-member basketball committee that
selected and seeded the field _ underwent background checks.
Dempsey said one referee, whom he declined to name, was not
approved because of the background check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the right track,'' said Bill Saum, the NCAA's
director of Agent, Gambling and Amateurism Activities. ``We need to
remember that officials are a segment of society, and certainly
this didn't surprise us. We're very comfortable with the integrity
of the officials and the integrity of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey also discussed issues such as upcoming amateurism
legislation and college basketball issues. While most schools
oppose the elimination of summer recruiting, Dempsey said the NCAA
will propose to eliminate summer recruiting in order to improve the
``basketball culture.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Michigan State coach Tom Izzo doesn't think that his team's
second consecutive Final Four appearance provides an advantage. ``I
wish it did,'' he said. ``On the court, it doesn't help at all. Off
the court, with the nuances of handling the hotels, the practices,
all the media, it might give us a slight edge.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida coach Billy Donovan on the longer timeouts due to
television commercials: ``It certainly is an adjustment. Our
players have a tendency to want to get back on the floor a lot
sooner because they have been programmed over the year of how long
those timeouts are. In essence they're 30-second timeouts that
become 50 seconds, almost a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisconsin's Andy Kowske was a guest during an Internet chat
session hosted by CNN/Sports Illustrated. The first question he was
asked was: ``In your wildest dreams did you really believe you
would be here? Honestly.'' Kowske's answer: ``Honestly, no. We had
13 losses and to think that we'd be in the Final Four is
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Indiana player Landon Turner, who played on the
Hoosiers' 1981 national championship team before being paralyzed in
an automobile accident, has organized a Hoosier Legends Basketball
Exhibition Game that will be played Friday at Butler's Hinkle
Fieldhouse. The game's proceeds will benefit Emily Hunt, a
7-year-old paralyzed in 1996 in an amusement-park accident. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
