<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MURAKAMI WILL ALWAYS BE FIRST
</HEADLINE>
   (mg) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nearly 36 years disappeared as Alvin Jackson greeted
Masanori Murakami behind the batting cage on Thursday. The first
time they met, two curious things happened: Murakami became the
first Japanese player in the American major leagues. And the Mets
won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the winning pitcher,'' recalled Jackson, now the Mets'
bullpen coach, savoring such a rare event.
</P>
<P>
   The big news on Sept. 1, 1964, took place in the eighth inning
when the 20-year-old left-hander came out of the San Francisco
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before, I was playing in Fresno with 200-300 people,''
Murakami said Thursday night. ``The next day I played in New York
for 40,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans came out to see Willie Mays and the Giants, who had
been spirited out of New York seven years earlier, but they
happened to witness history. The odd thing is that it took three
full decades for the Nomos and the Irabus and the Yoshiis to
arrive. Now they are playing for big bucks in North America, and
the so-called major leagues sent two teams here for two official
games, the second being a 5-1 victory by the Mets in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami was here to broadcast for the NHK network, but he had
an extra duty. Just before the game, he trotted out to the mound,
wearing his old San Francisco Giants uniform, which still fits him.
He threw the ceremonial first pitch, an American custom, and later
said he hoped his own country might adopt the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Other artifacts of his are in the Baseball Hall of Fame _ his
orange Giants traveling bag, as well as a Murakami bat and glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, I brought them to Cooperstown,'' Murakami recalled in
English. Maybe one day a Japanese player will be voted into the
Cooperstown Hall of Fame. Who knows where baseball is going on this
international kick? Baseball would be lucky to capture even one
quarter of the energy of the quadrennial soccer World Cup, the
greatest sports event on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami helped put this show on the road. He told the story of
his odd voyage to America. He had been a promising young player in
the system of the Nankai Hawks, and for some progressive reason,
the team leadership decided to send him to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me over to study the language,'' he said with a
self-deprecating smile, ``but they also sent me to study baseball
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Murakami then put his odyssey into perspective: ``Before the
war, Nisei went to America to live,'' Murakami said. ``Then came
the war, and they took houses back from Japanese. People were sad
after the war. Japanese people nervous. But after 20 years, we
tried to play baseball with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball not professional wrestling. Wrestling is show.
Baseball is true.''
</P>
<P>
   With some inner wisdom, they dispatched the composed young man
to the Giants, whose classic orange-and-black-trimmed uniform had
been the model for that Japanese dynasty, the Tokyo Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a major league player when I came to San
Francisco,'' Murakami said. ``I play A ball, not Double-A ball or
Triple-A ball. But on Sept. 1, they call me up. I was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   After flying overnight from California to New York, Murakami was
handed a contract by Chub Feeney, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I don't sign,'' Murakami said. ``It was in English,
and I don't understand it, so I don't sign. Chub Feeney was all
excited. Only hours before the game. But he called in some Japanese
guy who read the contract, and he told me it was all right.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, Manager Alvin Dark sent him out there.
``Mets were ahead,'' Murakami told Jackson Thursday night. ``Ninth
inning, we scored one run. I want us to tie the score so I could
pitch ninth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson looked at him last night with 36 years of incredulity,
as if to say, ``Brother, I needed that game more than you did.''
The Mets held on. Murakami went on to pitch credibly for the Giants
in 1965, and he dreamed of being a starter, but then the Hawks
called him home.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched 18 years for Nankai, Hanshin and the Nippon Ham
Fighters, with a decent 103-82 record and a 3.64 earned run
average, mostly as a reliever. And he tried to tell people what
Mays and Marichal and Dark had taught him.
</P>
<P>
   Now he dispenses wisdom over the airwaves. On Friday he will fly
to Los Angeles and Seattle to interview Japanese players, who make
millions in the American majors. But Masanori Murakami has
something they don't. He started all this.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
