<HEADLINE>
GORDON SEARCHING FOR NEW COMBINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN, JEFF WILSON, RICK HERRIN AND JOHNNY D. BOGGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jeff Gordon's Busch Grand National
qualifying effort Thursday was nothing to celebrate, but he ate ice
cream anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's speed of 179.910 mph stood 46th after first-round
qualifying for Saturday's Albertson's 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for a different motor combination,'' said
Gordon, driver of the No. 24 Pepsi Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``We have
to find out why our speed is off. We know we are not getting down
the straightaways. We don't know if it's aerodynamics or too much
drag, or if it's under the hood with horsepower. We can't change
much on the body. The one thing we can change is the engine, so
we're going to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're searching to find a combination out there that we can
rent from someone to find out if that is our problem. We will try
to check off all the variables.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is attempting to qualify for his second BGN race of 2000.
The former three-time Winston Cup champion started 27th and
finished 18th in the Sam's Town 300 at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on
March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gordon picked his favorite new ice cream flavor as part
of a Dreyer's and Edy's Ice Cream promotion. The winning flavor,
``Jeff's Mint Chocolate Speedway,'' was submitted by Angie Athanas,
24, of Fort Lauderdale, Fla. The flavor will be available in stores
this year. PARKER HIT AND MISS
</P>
<P>
   Hank Parker had the fastest times during Busch practice Thursday
morning. However, it didn't translate to success during afternoon
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who drives the No. 53 Team Marine Chevrolet, qualified
28th at 182.278 mph after finishing the practice sessions as the
only driver to top 185 mph. Part of Parker's problem, he said, was
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the clouds were out, we were great,'' Parker said. ``Then
the sun comes out and the clouds go away, and it hurt us. The track
changed. The car was really good before, and I thought we had
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who finished second in the rookie-of-the-year points
standings last season to Tony Raines, also said he had severe
troubles with running loose. The qualifying session was especially
disappointing to Parker after his near-perfect practices. But he
anticipates his car will be ready for Saturday's Albertson's 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be good,'' said Parker, who started and finished 20th in
last season's Coca-Cola 300 at the Texas Motor Speedway. POINTS
LEADER STRUGGLES
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth, who remains devoted to running a part-time Busch
schedule even though he leads the series in points, could manage
only the 50th-best speed (178.489) Thursday in qualifying for the
Alberton's 300.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, driver of the No. 17 Visine Chevrolet on the Busch
circuit, is also the leading rookie on the Winston Cup Series and
is committed to running a full Cup schedule. WRECK UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Rich Bickle and P.J. Jones were involved in separate wrecks
during practice sessions, and David Steele tagged the wall in
qualifying. None of the drivers was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious of the accidents occurred when an oil line
broke in Jones' No. 74 BACE Motorsports Chevrolet. The car filled
with smoke, and the Monte Carlo spun in the oil in Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going that fast, and I should have been able to save
it, except there was so much smoke in the car,'' Jones said. ``I
couldn't see anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was treated and released from the Lone Star Health Infield
Care Center. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
