<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX     03-30 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN OF A SON: HULL TRAILS HIS DAD BY TWO GOALS BUT MAY HAVE
SURPASSED HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Bobby Hull morphs into a cheerleader as he
watches his son, Brett, inch closer to his goal-scoring mark of
610. Two goals, and Brett will be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I want him to break my record,'' Bobby Hull said as he
waited for Brett after the Stars' most-recent trip to Chicago. ``I
want him to get more than anybody else who has ever played because
he's better than anyone else that played.''
</P>
<P>
   Even better than Bobby?
</P>
<P>
   ``Even me,'' Bobby said, pausing before explaining his
rationale. ``I'm not sure I could've done what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   What Brett Hull has done is adapt his game because the NHL he
thrived in no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a pure goal scorer,'' said Washington forward Adam
Oates, a teammate of Hull's in St. Louis. ``The 2 1/2 years I
played with him was the best hockey I ever have had. I think the
year he scored 86 (1990-91), it was the best pure goal-scoring year
ever. I know Gretz scored 92. But the year Hull got 86, he did not
have a short-handed goal, no empty netters, no four-goal games.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest pure goal scorers doesn't score near as many
goals any more. This, they say, is progress.
</P>
<P>
   As in Wednesday against the Florida Panthers. Hull didn't score
a goal, but Stars coach Ken Hitchcock couldn't heap enough praise
on him for ``clawing and scratching and working.'' This is what it
has taken for Hull to score 22 goals, five shy of his lowest total
for a full NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   But, let's be honest. Since March 19, he has been two goals
behind dad, who ranks ninth all-time. (He has been within nine
goals since getting 600 and 601 on New Year's Eve.) And, while two
goals used to be an average night for Brett, the five games between
now and the end of the regular season might not be enough time to
score two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there is a chance it might not happen. Whatever,''
Hull says in a tone that begs you to believe he doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   But he does. If he didn't, he would've faded off into the sunset
content with the player that he was. But he didn't; he changed into
the player he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think enough people gave him credit for being a smart
hockey player, and he is, a very smart hockey player,'' Oates said.
``He knows the game, and it has changed since then, and he's
changed along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things didn't so much change as get accentuated. When you
score as many goals as Hull did, you aren't going to get as many
assists. So the idea persists that maybe you aren't a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played with some guys that were pure goal scorers but who
didn't understand the game,'' Stars forward Guy Carbonneau said.
``Talking with Brett and his dad, you can see that they understand.
People always talk about his shots and his goal-scoring ability,
but what they forget is how good he passes the puck and how well he
understands the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Hull doesn't score goals as often as he used to. He always
has one or two guys on him, which means somebody is open. He now
makes the pass. As he did against the Panthers, when he assisted on
three goals. His second assist landed so perfectly on winger Scott
Thornton's stick as he came flying toward the crease that Thornton
said he didn't have any choice but to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' Thornton admitted when asked if Hull's
play-making ability surprised him at all. ``He's a ``really'' good
passer.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is thick. Just when he's finally a couple of goals
away from the milestone he has always wanted, he starts getting
recognized for his passing. And yes, 610 is a mark he really wants
to get. This season would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau realizes that by what Hull doesn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to talk about it,'' Carbonneau said. ``I
understand. Look at Patrick Roy going after the most wins. I think
that affected him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has been affected, too. He admitted as much to his father a
couple of weeks ago. It was Brett and Bobby and Carbonneau at
lunch. They talked about a lot of things, but eventually the
conversation steered back toward hockey.
</P>
<P>
   They're different players, father and son. Bobby would come
barreling down the left wing and wind up and let it fly. Brett
would float around, getting himself in the perfect position for his
one-timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' Carbonneau said, ``is still to score goals.
They both did that really well in different days and different
games.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, things have changed. This season likely will end with
one 50-goal scorer, Florida's Pavel Bure. There could be more,
Bobby says. Probably should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not the way the game is anymore,'' he laments in a
way that if you weren't looking straight at him you'd swear you
were listening to Brett talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard adjustment for older players that were scorers,''
Hitchcock admitted. ``It's not easy making those adjustments in the
best of times, let alone when a player is set in his ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull isn't going to deny he has been known to be a little
stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hull, well, ``he makes me look flexible,'' Brett says.
</P>
<P>
   So that's what Bobby meant when he said he wasn't sure he
could've adjusted his game as Brett did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably being truthful in that sense,'' Brett Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the part about Brett being better than Bobby because
of it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering,'' Bobby Hull said. ``But then, you know,
obviously I'm his son, so he's going to say a lot of nice things.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
