<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-TEX </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE PUTTING UP HISTORIC NUMBERS IN HOME RUN TOTALS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sexiest man in America will be at The Ballpark in Arlington
this evening. Tom Cruise? Mel Gibson? Brad Pitt?
</P>
<P>
   No, no and no. We're talking Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, chicks dig the longball, and nobody does the longball
like the big St. Louis Cardinals slugger with the huge biceps and
the enormous home run totals.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and the Cardinals are in town Friday for an exhibition
game against the Rangers at 7:05 p.m. at the Ballpark in Arlington,
his first appearance in Arlington, Texas, since 1997, when he
played for the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, McGwire was simply the best slugger in the
American League. Since then, he's become the best slugger in
history. McGwire hit 70 home runs in 1998, shattering the
single-season record of 61 set by Roger Maris in 1961. He followed
that up with a relatively paltry 65 last season.
</P>
<P>
   To those who don't play the game, the numbers are unbelievable,
incredible, astounding, the adjective of your choice. Those who
play the game are even more amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to believe,'' said Rangers first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro, who was second in the American League with 47 home runs
last season. ``To hit 30 home runs is so hard, and to hit 40 is
even more so, and 50 and 60. He hit 70. That's so out of reach it's
not even funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, National League pitchers aren't laughing. McGwire
averaged a home run about every eight at-bats the past two seasons.
It wasn't a matter of would he hit another home run, but when, and
how far.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew it was just a matter of time,'' said Rangers pitcher
Darren Oliver, McGwire's teammate with the Cardinals the past two
years. ``If he hadn't hit a home run in the last three games it
didn't matter who was pitching, it was bound to happen. You knew he
was going to hit one.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only hit one, but hit one a long way. The right-handed pull
hitter holds the unofficial record for the average length of the
majestic drives he clouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hits like him, as far as he hits them,'' Oliver said.
``There was him, then there was a big separation to everyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's exploits have attracted huge crowds, even for
exhibition games. The Rangers expect a crowd of around 35,000,
about 5,000-10,000 more than they normally draw for their home
exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's raw power makes Cardinals batting practice _ which
should commence at about 5:20 p.m. Friday _ a spectacle. Even
players have been known to stop and watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What amazed me was how far he hit the ball in (batting
practice),'' Oliver said. ``That's a joke. It was almost like
somebody teeing up a golf ball and hitting it. It was amazing. When
you see it every day you'd think you got used to it, but it was
still like, `Wow.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's also a good word to describe McGwire's home run totals
the past three seasons. He warmed up with 58 in '97 _ when he split
the season between the A's and Cardinals _ obliterated Maris's
record with 70 in '98, then followed it up with 65 last year. The
'99 season proved that the '98 season wasn't an aberration, and
that McGwire might have another single-season record in his lethal
bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's capable of doing it again,'' Palmeiro said. ``I don't
think it's a once-in-a-lifetime deal. He may give it a go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that McGwire has averaged 64 homers the past three
seasons, he also might have a go at the mother of all baseball
records, Hank Aaron's 755 career homers.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has 522, 10th on the all-time list and 233 away from
Aaron. If McGwire keeps up his pace of the past three season for
the next four years, he'd break the record in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can stay healthy, he can do it,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has had periodic back problems. He was removed with
stiffness in his back in the third inning of the Cardinals' 3-1
victory over the Montreal Expos on Wednesday. This spring, he's hit
.327 with seven home runs in 52 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire won't set any records tonight. But he could have a
chance to hit the ball a long way. He doesn't always get that
chance during the regular season. Because he's a threat to swat one
over the fence every time he walks to the plate, he doesn't see
many strikes with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys pitched around him,'' Oliver said. ``You can't be dumb.
If there were guys on base, they'd take their chances with the next
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an exhibition game, though. Oliver is scheduled to start
for the Rangers, and even with men on base he said he would
probably challenge his former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exhibition game, so it's a little different,'' Oliver
said. ``I don't have to pitch him carefully. You still want to go
out there and get the guy out, but if you happen to give up
something, it doesn't count. That's the good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if McGwire does hit the longball, at least the chicks will
dig it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
