<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MINIMUM-WAGE-NYT     03-30 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MINIMUM-WAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER RAISE FOR WORKERS WHO GET TIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ State lawmakers on Thursday agreed to a law
giving waiters, bartenders and busboys a smaller minimum-wage
increase than other low-wage workers who do not get tips, despite
complaints that the move was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Without a change in the law, the minimum wage for food service
workers who also routinely earn tips would have risen on Friday to
about $3.50 an hour from $2.90.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators from both parties, in both houses of the
Legislature, reached agreement with Gov. George Pataki to cap the
wage increase for this group at $3.30. The Senate and the Assembly
passed the bill on Thursday, and the governor's office said Pataki
would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats said they voted for the bill only because Pataki,
a Republican, had signaled that if they allowed the minimum wage to
rise to about $3.50 (there was some dispute as to exactly what the
number would be), he would use his administrative powers to roll it
back to $2.90. Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, called
predictions of a rollback ``complete and total nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, and some Republicans, said they voted for it to keep
wages from rising too sharply so that small businesses would be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 121-19 in the Assembly and 58-2 in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Labor union officials were split on the bill, some believing it
was the best deal that the workers could hope for and others
arguing that the Legislature should have let the automatic increase
take effect and dared the governor to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage under federal law is $5.15 an hour, but states
are allowed to set lower minimums for certain groups of workers,
like farm laborers and food service employees. The state-mandated
minimum for most of those workers has been $4.25 since 1991, but
under a law enacted in December, it will rise on Friday to $5.15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-00 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
